A8359 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     11-02 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PHILADELPHIA _ If there were ever a situation that cried out for
Jason Garrett, this is it. Not because he's a Princeton boy and
it's a tough problem that requires Ivy League brainpower. Not
because he's got a stronger arm or a better grasp of the Cowboys'
offense than Troy Aikman. Not for any reason that has something to
do with X's and O's or football strategy drawn up on a chalkboard.
</P>
<P>
   Simply because Jason Garrett is not Troy Aikman. In other words,
survival.
</P>
<P>
   If the so-far-pretending 4-3 Cowboys are going to come out of
the bye week and make a very real run at becoming a legitimate
playoff threat through the second half of the NFL season, they will
most certainly need the talents of Aikman to carry them.
</P>
<P>
   There will be times over the coming weeks when Aikman will have
to make the thread-the-needle pass to Michael Irvin on third down.
Times when he will have to scramble away from pressuring defensive
linemen and make a bail-out pass to Billy Davis or Eric Bjornson.
Times when the Cowboys will have to rely on the strength of his
leadership and the sheer force of his will to come from behind late
in a game at home or on the road.
</P>
<P>
   There will be times when Aikman's veteran savvy alone will have
to pull the Cowboys through and keep this bounce-back season on
track to keep right on playing into January.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not the time, and this is most definitely not the
place. Not in the heat of Monday Night Football against the Eagles.
Even the 1-6 Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   It has been nearly two months since Aikman left the field at
Denver's Mile High Stadium with a broken collarbone in a 42-23 loss
to the Broncos, and it is only natural that the determined
quarterback with three Super Bowl rings in his collection would
want to get back in the lineup to start to make things happen
again. And under normal circumstances, that is exactly what you
would want him to do.
</P>
<P>
   Just not here. Not under these conditions.
</P>
<P>
   To most every other opponent in the NFL, Veterans Stadium is a
rest stop along the long road that is the 16-game regular-season
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   To the Cowboys, this is the seventh level of hell. Eagles fans
don't just get up for the Cowboys. They get down and dirty and loud
and violent.
</P>
<P>
   This is a place that on the Monday night after Halloween will be
jam-packed with banshee-screaming, glassy-eyed, chain-rattling,
bloodthirsty, howling-at-the-moon werewolves. And none of them will
be in costume. They are merely run-of-the-mill Eagles fans to whom
an encounter with the hated Cowboys means life and death. Or
something more important.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of atmosphere that can get inside the helmets of
even a lowly bunch of Eagles and turn them into flesh-eating,
bone-crunching monsters.
</P>
<P>
   This is different than any other rivalry the Cowboys have within
the NFC East. Arizona is always happy not to get run off the field
by Dallas. The Giants have a natural dislike for the Cowboys, but
the New York-Dallas thing is more like a business war between
corporate giants. Even the series with the Redskins is filled with
more of a college-type rivalry, and beneath the intensity, there is
a mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
   In Philly-Dallas, there is hatred, pure and unadulterated.
</P>
<P>
   The only time Eagles fans would not pour beer on Deion Sanders
is if he were on fire. They would rather lose to Saddam Hussein
than Dallas. They don't want to just beat the Cowboys, but also
destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the concrete-hard turf at the Vet just might be the
worst place in the world for Aikman to make his comeback. A win
here tonight over the Cowboys on ABC would make the Eagles' season.
But to drive Aikman hard to the ground and fracture him again would
finish the Cowboys and keep the Eagles warm well into winter. A
year ago, they gave him a concussion in a 13-12 win over Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett has gone 3-2 as the interim QB and done a decent enough
job to merit one more start. He shouldn't have to perform many
heroics, either. Not with the Cowboys having reinstalled the punch
in their running game. They currently rank sixth in the league in
rushing and are on pace to gain more than 2,000 yards on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   This is a task that Garrett can handle. Turn and give the ball
to Emmitt Smith. Make the short, safe passes to Irvin. Maybe get a
couple of big returns from Deion and try to get out of town with an
ugly win. More important, get out of town with Aikman still in one
piece for the second half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It's one more job that Garrett can handle _ sacrificial lamb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
