<HEADER>
A8362 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PACKERS-NINERS-HN     11-02 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PACKERS-NINERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
GREEN BAY, Wis. _ If the Green Bay Packers continue to survive on
Brett Favre's wing and Reggie White's prayer, they have a chance to
reach a third consecutive Super Bowl.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Inspired by Minnesota's first loss of the season Sunday, the
Packers pounced on San Francisco as if they were playing the NFC
Championship Game, but they turned a 16-point advantage into a
three-point deficit before Favre and White responded to a 911
desperation call.
</P>
<P>
   Favre threw his third touchdown pass and White registered the
last of his three sacks to help the Packers defeat the 49ers 36-22.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started fast, hit a sinking spell but bounced back from
some bad situations,'' Packers coach Mike Holmgren said. ``How did
I feel when we fell behind? Let me put it like this: Anger was
pushing the other emotions out of my body. Sure, I was ticked off,
but I was able to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay (6-2) pulled within one game of the Vikings in the NFC
Central. San Francisco (6-2) fell into a first-place tie with
Atlanta in the NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was going to be a big game for our
organization,'' 49ers coach Steve Mariucci said. ``It was a tough
loss, and naturally I'm disappointed. It's not easy to lose, but we
don't have time to feel sorry for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Packers extended their winning streak over the 49ers to five
games. San Francisco quarterback Steve Young dropped to 0-8 as a
starter against the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   Young was 24-of-39 for only 186 yards. He threw an interception,
lost a fumble and was sacked a career-high nine times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a surge of energy that allowed us to get off the ball
well,'' said White, who has 11 sacks in 1998 and became the first
player in league history to reach double figures 12 times in his
career. ``God gave me the strength to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key for us was keeping Steve in the pocket. We stayed in
our lanes and made sure the guys in the middle got a push. We did a
good job of getting after him, especially in the fourth quarter
when we really got revved up.''
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth time in five games, Favre threw three
interceptions and had no one to blame but himself. There were no
tipped passes at the line, no ricochets off receivers' hands and no
wrong routes. Just terrible decisions by the best quarterback in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through this before with Brett,'' Holmgren said.
``It's not good, and he knows it. But we have to take more chances,
because the running game isn't what it should be. He just needs to
eliminate the bad ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Brett and I have been through this before. We're
either going to the mountaintop together or into the Dumpster
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Packers, Favre recovered in time to help
them outscore San Francisco 17-0 in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Favre connected on 15 of 28 passes for 279 yards and three
touchdowns to go with his three interceptions. Antonio Freeman
caught seven passes for a career-high 193 yards, including
touchdowns of 80 and 62 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got the ball in my hands, it was like a Doberman was
chasing me,'' Freeman said.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Jervey, who went to the Pro Bowl last season as a
special-teams player, began this season as the Packers'
third-string running back behind Dorsey Levens, who is injured, and
Raymont Harris, who has been ineffective. Against the 49ers, Jervey
had the best game of his career, gaining 95 yards on 17 carries and
looking like Paul Hornung on an 11-yard sweep for Green Bay's last
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Three Green Bay touchdowns _ Freeman's catches and Jervey's run
_ came on the first play of a possession. That's three touchdowns
in a total of 27 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers, who are 1-2 against teams with winning records,
couldn't have gotten off to a worse start. On the first play,
Freeman got away from cornerback Marquez Pope and eluded free
safety Merton Hanks for an 80-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   On the 49ers' first series, Young was sacked by safety LeRoy
Butler and White. Then, Randy Kirk snapped the ball over punter
Reggie Roby's head and out of the end zone for a safety that made
it 9-0. Safety Pat Terrell intercepted Young moments later, and the
Packers capitalized when receiver Robert Brooks caught a 30-yard
touchdown pass to make it 16-0.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers proved they are resilient if nothing else. They scored
their first touchdown on Young's 12-yard pass to Jerry Rice. It was
the 80th time Young and Rice collaborated on a touchdown pass,
breaking the record they shared with Miami's Dan Marino and Mark
Clayton. Wade Richey's extra-point attempt was blocked.
</P>
<P>
   After Ryan Longwell kicked a 26-yard field goal for Green Bay,
Young scored on a one-yard run to pull San Francisco within 19-13
at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, Favre's second interception set up the
49ers at Green Bay's 35. Garrison Hearst carried twice, the second
for a 30-yard touchdown. Holder Ty Detmer couldn't get the ball
down for the extra point, leaving the score 19-19.
</P>
<P>
   On Green Bay's next series, strong safety Tim McDonald
intercepted Favre at the Packers' 49. The 49ers had first-and-goal
at the eight but had to settle for Richey's 20-yard field goal and
a 22-19 advantage that lasted into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers' explosion began innocently enough. Longwell tied
the score with a 45-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay's defense was at its best in the fourth quarter. It
dominated the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play of the Packers' second series in the quarter,
Freeman beat Pope off the line again and zoomed by Hanks for a
62-yard touchdown that took nine seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Young was helpless on the 49ers' next possession. Before end
Keith McKenzie drilled him for a sack, Young lost the ball, and
defensive tackle Santana Dotson recovered at the San Francisco 11.
On the next play, Jervey took off around the right side and scored
his 11-yard touchdown with 9:30 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers had three more series, but Green Bay's defense was too
good. The drives ended with two punts and a failed fourth-down
pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of losing to the Packers,'' Rice said. ``We have to
bring it (the losing streak) to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other time they could have a chance this season is in
the playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
