</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHERIFF-POLITICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHERIFF'S FUNERAL BRINGS TOGETHER POLITICAL POWERHOUSES AS ELECTION
NEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The memorial services held for Sheriff Sherman
Block also served as one of the largest political rallies in recent
history.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral Sunday at the Hollywood Bowl brought out thousands
of mourners, some of California's top politicians and numerous
candidates in Tuesday's election, including gubernatorial
candidates Democrat Lt. Gov. Gray Davis and Republican Attorney
General Dan Lungren, and Democrat U.S. Sen. Barbara Boxer, who is
in a tough fight to keep her seat.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the eulogies steered clear of politics, focusing instead
on Block's career and character. But several of the officials
sounded a call before the service for voters not to desert the man
who devoted 42 years to the Los Angeles County Sheriff's
Department. Among them was Gov. Pete Wilson, who told reporters he
would be voting for Block if he lived in the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sherman Block should be remembered for all he has given this
department, this county and this state,'' Wilson said during his
eulogy. ``Most of all, he should be remembered for what he did for
children. ... Believing that prevention was the best medication.''
</P>
<P>
   Other speakers described Block as a ``giant,'' as a ``hero,'' as
``an extraordinary man'' _ all phrases that could be used in a
political campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even former Los Angeles Police Chief Daryl F. Gates said before
the service that he would be voting for Block.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew (his rival Lee) Baca and decided to run again,'' Gates
said. ``Obviously, he knew something, and I'm going to respect
(Block's) wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   If Block's name receives more votes than Baca in Tuesday's
election, the Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors is expected
to select an interim sheriff to serve until new elections for
sheriff can be held.
</P>
<P>
   Baca, a former chief in the Sheriff's Department, attended the
ceremony but refused to discuss politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to pay my respects to a dear friend and his
family,'' Baca said, turning aside requests from television crews
for an interview. ``I have nothing else to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Block's campaign backers are urging supporters to cast their
ballots against Baca, but they tried to downplay politics Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a political funeral,'' said Joe Scott, one of Block's
campaign managers. ``But, we don't want to talk about politics
today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the wrong time to be discussing politics,'' agreed Jay
Grodin, a longtime friend and head of the Block re-election
campaign. ``There will be plenty of time for that before Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said they plan to move ahead today with the Block
campaign and challenges to comments Baca made Saturday asking for
support to keep the Board of Supervisors from appointing an interim
sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said Sunday that the Block campaign has attracted
international attention since the sheriff's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``One week ago, before he fell, this race was sub-radar,'' Scott
said. ``Since then, it's got national press. There have been
stories in The New York Times, in The Washington Post, on the
`Today' show. There's no way that would have happened otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the television cameras from every local station, as
well as CNN, to cover the funeral, Scott said Block's candidacy was
getting more attention in death than in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's understandable,'' said one official, who asked not to be
identified. ``It's not every day you have an election with a dead
candidate whose people still are running a campaign. It's just
bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan and Lungren said people had to
choose Baca or allow the Board of Supervisors to select a successor
who would serve until the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky said he would like
to look at the possibility of naming an interim sheriff who
promises not to seek election to a full term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
