<SLUG> BC-NJ-LAND-TAXES-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX INCREASES TO SAVE LAND ARE ON THE BALLOT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Ga., N.M., Gla., Ore., Ariz., Texas, N.Y., Pa.)   (See related: CAMPAIGN-RDP, CAMPAIGN-INITIATIVES,
CAMPAIGN-TURNOUT, CAMPAIGN-GOVS, CAMPAIGN-GORE, CAMPAIGN-CHURCHES,
CAMPAIGN-MASS.) 
(jw) 
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST WINDSOR, N.J. _ New Jersey voters nearly ousted Gov.
Christie Whitman last year partly because they were unhappy about
paying the highest property tax rates in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on Election Day, 50 towns and seven counties will vote on
plans to increase property taxes, and the state's voters will
consider a $1 billion statewide borrowing plan _ all to help
preserve rapidly dwindling farmland and woodlands from development.
</P>
<P>
   But there is hardly a peep of opposition, even from the state's
anti-tax groups and staunchest fiscal conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really important,'' said Sam Perilli, state chairman
of United Taxpayers of New Jersey, one of the anti-tax groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the most densely populated state in the nation, and we
are running out of space here,'' Perilli said. ``I believe that the
average New Jersey citizen understands that you got to have green
around you. People are also beginning to realize that development
is a tax liability for towns, not an asset, because you have to
build schools and hire more police officers. And that makes
property taxes go up.''
</P>
<P>
   Perilli said his support for a 2-cent property tax increase to
preserve open space in his hometown of Cedar Grove in Essex County
caused members of an anti-tax group based in Washington to call and
scold him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `What are you doing up there?' '' Perilli recalled.
``I told them to put someone on the phone who knew what they were
talking about, who knew that preserving open space saves taxpayers'
money.''
</P>
<P>
   In five other states _ Georgia, New Mexico, Florida, Oregon and
Arizona _ voters are also considering statewide ballot questions,
either borrowing plans or tax increases, to help set aside open
space. And dozens of counties and towns across the country have
similar questions on the ballot, said Phyllis Myers, president of
State Resource Strategies, a company based in Washington that
tracks state and local open-space ballot measures.
</P>
<P>
   During the last two years, Ms. Myers said, voters from Austin,
Texas, to Monroe County, Pa., have approved more than 100 local
ballot initiatives, a reflection of the increasing concern about
the effect rapid development on traffic, schools and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were grass-roots efforts that are gaining political
support because people are beginning to make the connections about
what is happening around them,'' Ms. Myers said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Suffolk County voters will be asked on Tuesday to
approve a $62 million borrowing plan to help buy land or
development rights. In addition, voters in the five towns on the
eastern end of Long Island will be asked to approve a real estate
transfer tax increase to help protect open space.
</P>
<P>
   State and local officials say voters are also beginning to
recognize that raising taxes or borrowing money to preserve open
space now can help keep down property tax rates in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are building a school a year,'' said Carole Carson, mayor
of West Windsor Township, here in Mercer County, which has grown
rapidly in the last two decades. ``If we buy the land, we don't
have to build thousands of new schools.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade alone, 2,400 new homes have risen here on
2,700 acres of what had been farms and woods, prompting local
residents to approve one of the first property tax increases
dedicated solely to open space preservation.
</P>
<P>
   The tax is now 2 cents on every $100 of assessed property value,
and voters will be asked to increase that to 7 cents. In addition,
Mercer County is seeking approval for a 2-cent increase to be used
to pay for open space purchases across the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is tremendous support for it,'' Ms. Carson said. ``This
will allow us to control development and maintain some of the
agricultural business and character.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
