<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8375 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-LAND-TAXES-2NDTAKE     11-02 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-LAND-TAXES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: and character. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Georgia, prominent business leaders, as well as
conservationists, are campaigning for a statewide ballot measure
that would increase a real estate transfer tax to create a state
fund to acquire and preserve environmentally fragile or
historically important areas. The tax increase would generate about
$32 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Williams, president of the Metro Atlanta Chamber of
Commerce, said many business leaders supported the measure because
they recognized that preserving open space would improve the
quality of life, which means it is important for economic
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a requirement for our business success,'' Williams said.
``More and more companies we talk to say that quality of life is
the No. 1 factor they consider when relocating their companies. So
open space, and recreation, is all extraordinarily important to our
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whitman tapped into growing discontent about the pace of
development when she made preserving open space and managing
suburban sprawl a top priority of her administration's second term.
Her plan to preserve 1 million acres in the coming decade _ half
the remaining open space in the state _ is considered one of the
nation's most ambitious efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide ballot measure has bipartisan support. U.S.
Senator Robert Torricelli, a Democrat, joined Mrs. Whitman this
week in campaigning in Hunterdon County to help draw attention to
the ballot question.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whitman had first recommended asking voters to approve a
4-cent increase in the state's gasoline tax to pay for the open
space program, but state lawmakers, and Perilli, balked.
Legislative leaders maintained that a gasoline tax increase should
be used for transportation purposes only, but they did agree to the
governor's next recommendation, letting voters decide whether they
wanted to borrow the money. Under the plan, the state would
dedicate $98 million annually from existing state tax revenue to
pay for the $1 billion borrowing over 30 years. The total cost is
estimated to exceed $2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1961, New Jersey voters have approved nine bond
referendums that have raised $1.39 billion to help protect more
than 400,000 acres from development. In addition, 53 towns and 13
of the state's 21 counties have floated bonds or dedicated property
tax revenue to set aside open space from development.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whitman and members of a coalition working to support the
ballot measure say they are optimistic about the ballot question's
fate. But Michael Catania, the executive director of the Nature
Conservancy of New Jersey, said he was somewhat concerned about a
low turnout, and about the effect it might have on the statewide
and local ballot measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all worry that people are just kind of disgusted and don't
want to hear about politics and government, and that could mean low
voter turnout,'' Catania said. ``Quite honestly, that is our
biggest concern. I think it will win, but we have to get people out
to vote.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
