<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOLISANO-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXECUTIVE MAY LAG IN N.Y. GOVERNOR POLLS, BUT HIS STOCK IS AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif.)   (See related: CAMPAIGN-RDP, CAMPAIGN-INITIATIVES,
CAMPAIGN-TURNOUT, CAMPAIGN-GOVS, CAMPAIGN-GORE, CAMPAIGN-CHURCHES,
CAMPAIGN-MASS.) 
(jw) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ B. Thomas Golisano, a wealthy Rochester
businessman, is spending $20 million of his fortune on a
third-party campaign for governor of New York that nobody seems to
think he can win.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he does or not, Golisano's decision to run may turn out
to have been another smart investment. During the campaign, the
stock price of Golisano's payroll processing company, Paychex Inc.,
has jumped, just as it did when he ran for governor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Forbes magazine called Golisano, Paychex's founder
and chief executive, one of the 400 wealthiest Americans, with a
net worth of about $800 million. And since Aug. 24, one week after
Golisano's campaign began advertising, Paychex stock has risen 26
percent, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index has stood
nearly unchanged. That has added about $200 million on paper to
Golisano's personal assets, far exceeding the sum he is spending on
his Independence Party candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what correlation there was between his campaign and the
price of Paychex stock, Golisano said: ``None.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had 28 consecutive quarters where earnings growth has
been over 36 percent,'' he said last week in a telephone interview,
maintaining that the stock had risen simply because the company was
a good investment.
</P>
<P>
   The stock price has climbed steadily since the company went
public in 1983, consistently beating the market. But the margins
are usually not as wide as in the last 10 weeks, when Golisano's
ads have been an unavoidable feature of newspapers and television,
stressing his role as head of Paychex and calling it one of the
best-run companies in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, Paychex stock has far outperformed not just the
broader market, but the two other big payroll processing companies,
Automatic Data Processing Inc., which gained 11 percent, and
Ceridian Corp., which remained almost unchanged. Paychex stock is
traded on Nasdaq; the two others are traded on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing about this is, when he announced to the Wall
Street investment analysts that he was running again, they viewed
it negatively because they thought he would be distracted from his
business,'' said Stephen McClellan, an analyst with Merrill Lynch
Global Securities in San Francisco. ``But New York is a pretty good
market for advertising to investors. It's not like running for
governor in Idaho.''
</P>
<P>
   If Golisano's ads have attracted investors and perhaps even new
customers to Paychex, then they have been a bargain. Television and
radio stations and newspapers charge much less for political
advertising than for commercial ads.
</P>
<P>
   Golisano says he is running because he is frustrated at the way
state government works and disappointed in Gov. George Pataki, and
even aides to his major opponents _ Pataki, a Republican, and Peter
Vallone, the Democratic speaker of the New York City Council _ say
there is no reason not to take him at his word. He may also be
looking for new challenges after 27 years at the helm of Paychex.
</P>
<P>
   When the Independence Party was founded in 1994, it would not
have attracted much attention but for Golisano's entering late in
the campaign as the party's gubernatorial nominee and spending $6.6
million of his fortune. He quickly threatened to tilt the balance
in the close race between Gov. Mario Cuomo and Pataki. The stock
price jumped about 15 percent after he began his 1994 advertising,
but then slightly fell back before Election Day.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He took 4.4 percent of the vote, enough to secure the
Independence Party a place on all state ballots for the next four
years, on the fourth line. (Lines are assigned in order of
gubernatorial vote.) This year, polls have shown Golisano
attracting close to 10 percent of the vote, according to poll
respondents.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, he said he did not want to run again, but
Independence Party officials, lacking another strong candidate,
prevailed on him to wage another campaign. They hope to make the
party a power that can tip elections and sway governments, in part
by backing candidates from the major parties or withholding that
support, as the state's Liberal and Conservative Parties have done.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Independence Party nominated three Democrats
seeking statewide office: Rep. Charles Schumer for Senate,
Comptroller H. Carl McCall for re-election, and State Sen.
Catherine Abate for attorney general. Ms. Abate lost the Democratic
primary, and while her name will appear on ballots, she is not
running in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   The Independence Party advocates fiscal conservatism, term
limits and tolerance on social issues like abortion and gay rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
