<SLUG> BC-CT-GOV-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROWLAND CAMPAIGN BEGINS AN EARLY VICTORY TOUR
</HEADLINE>
   (See related: CAMPAIGN-RDP, CAMPAIGN-INITIATIVES,
CAMPAIGN-TURNOUT, CAMPAIGN-GOVS, CAMPAIGN-GORE, CAMPAIGN-CHURCHES,
CAMPAIGN-MASS.) 
(jw) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERBURY, Conn. _ Gov. John Rowland strode triumphantly among
Republicans twirling New Year's-style noisemakers at rallies in
three packed halls Sunday, while his challenger, U.S. Rep. Barbara
Kennelly, motored across the state to thank her supporters for
their loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   In the final public splash by the two campaigns, Mrs. Kennelly,
a Democrat, worked to buck up her own team, while Rowland focused
on spreading his luster to other Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly had rented a 40-foot bus outfitted with leather
sofas and swivel chairs for Sunday's 11-stop, 14-hour schedule, and
campaign workers had painted a big banner for the side of the bus
that proclaimed her ``Better for Connecticut,'' and showed a donkey
doing a jig.
</P>
<P>
   Then she woke up Sunday morning and found that the front page of
The Hartford Courant carried a poll showing that respondents
favored Rowland over her by 57 percent to 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The news, which mirrored previous polls, did not seem to dampen
the upbeat mood of the 20 aides and relatives who packed the bus.
They clapped as patriotic marches played on the compact disk
system, and savored the memories of a much happier time as they
watched a videotape from the state Democratic Convention in July.
</P>
<P>
   At a Democratic breakfast in Derby, Mrs. Kennelly's voice broke
as she said: ``We have good times and we have bad times. But we
know who we are. We're good, and we care about our community. And I
thank you for being so nice to me this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, on the other hand, got a few days' jump on the calendar
with what his campaign promoted as ``The John Rowland Victory '98
Tour.'' He was driven from stop to stop in a behemoth motor home.
</P>
<P>
   In Manchester, Rowland warned of the consequences for other
candidates if his voters were so overconfident they stayed home.
``People say, `I wish you good luck, but you don't need it,' ''
Rowland said. ``You know what I say to that? Give me all the good
luck you have and I'll be glad to spread it around and share it
with others, or save it for another day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 0029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
