A8385 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-TOUR-CHAMPIONSHIP     11-02 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOUR-CHAMPIONSHIP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH POISE AND PRECISION, SUTTON WINS PLAYOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It has been a long road back for Hal Sutton, but on
Sunday his journey was both memorable and rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving a pressure-packed four-man battle on the back nine,
and winning with a birdie on the first hole of a sudden-death
playoff with Vijay Singh, Sutton captured the Tour Championship in
dramatic fashion, capping his most rewarding season with a
remarkable victory.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Sutton win the biggest check of his career
$720,000, but he also clinched a spot on the Presidents Cup team,
and reaffirmed that he has returned as a force in golf.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton and Singh both finished at 6 under par for the tournament
(274), one stroke ahead of Jim Furyk and Jesper Parnevik, who tied
for third place.
</P>
<P>
   They were the only four players who finished under par for the
tournament at the East Lake Golf Club, a demanding course that
brought out the best in Sutton, who at 40 years old has seen his
career reach a new zenith.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the PGA Championship in 1983, Sutton's career
slowly spiraled downhill, and in 1992, he plummeted to 185th on the
tour's money list. But through hard work, Sutton slowly put the
pieces of his swing back together, and by this year, the puzzle was
complete.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Sutton's game and poise held up under tremendous
pressure, and on the first hole of sudden death, he hit a brilliant
4-wood tee shot from 245 yards away that landed 6 feet from the
cup, setting up a birdie putt for victory. When it was over, an
emotional Sutton reflected on both the highs and the lows of his
career. The lows were difficult. But the hard times made Sunday
even more special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from feeling embarrassed to hit balls on the range to
sitting here talking about winning this tournament,'' said Sutton,
who also won the Westin Texas Open in September and finished fifth
on the 1998 money list, earning more than $1.83 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a long, hard battle,'' Sutton said. ``This is the
only way I know how to put this: When I stand on the tee and I look
down the fairway, I see the fairway. I don't see the rough. When I
was at rock bottom, all I could see was the rough. So yes, I think
I'm back. Now, I just need to sustain.''
</P>
<P>
   David Duval was the other big winner Sunday at the
regular-season tour finale, clinching the 1998 money title
($2,591,031) and the Vardon Trophy for the year's lowest-scoring
average (69.13).
</P>
<P>
   Either Duval or Mark O'Meara, who finished tied for 13th on
Sunday, will win the player-of-the-year award voted on by the
players, but no matter how that voting turns out, Duval is pleased
with his year.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point in the second round, I was last, 30th in the
field, and to buckle down and play like I know I can play makes me
feel really good,'' said Duval, who shot a 68 on Sunday to finish
tied for eighth. ``And winning the Vardon Trophy equates to playing
the best golf each week.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sutton played the best golf for four days of the Tour
Championship, shooting an even-par 70 and finding a way to win
after starting the day 1 stroke behind Singh, who led most of the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the other contenders fell by the wayside. Furyk, who
shot a 71 on Sunday, came to the 18th hole trailing Singh by 1
stroke. But Furyk made a costly bogey at the par-3 No. 18, when his
tee shot landed in the rough, followed by a chip that came up 15
feet short of the hole. Furyk missed his putt for par, and finished
at 5 under par.
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik, who shot a 68, reached the 18th needing a birdie, hit
his tee shot into the bunker, and settled for an up-and-down par.
</P>
<P>
   That left Singh and Sutton standing on the 18th tee, with Singh
holding a 1-stroke lead. Sutton hit his tee shot into the front
right bunker, but Singh got a bad break on his 3-iron tee shot,
when it landed on the green and rolled about 20 yards _ just into
the back rough. ``I thought it was pretty unlucky,'' said Singh,
who shot a 71 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vijay hit a beautiful shot,'' Sutton said. ``Until I got to
the green, I didn't realize he was over the green. As I'm walking
up, I said: `Vijay's over the green. We're in the ball game.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton followed by hitting a tremendous bunker shot that stopped
3 feet from the cup. Then Singh was faced with his difficult
downhill chip, about 15 feet from the hole, with little green to
work with. Singh hit a decent shot, but it trickled down the severe
slope, and as the crowd groaned, rolled 35 feet past the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Singh 2-putted for bogey and Sutton made his 3-footer to force
sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton teed off first and hit the shot of the tournament, a
4-wood that hit the green and settled within 6 feet of the cup.
Singh's 3-wood was about 35 feet short, and after Singh missed his
putt for birdie, Sutton calmly made the putt for victory, pumping
his fist as the crowd roared.
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   DAVID DUVAL, TIGER WOODS, JIM FURYK, JUSTIN LEONARD, PHIL
MICKELSON, DAVIS LOVE III, MARK O'MEARA, HAL SUTTON, SCOTT HOCH and
MARK CALCAVECCHIA clinched spots on the U.S. Presidents Cup team by
finishing in the top 10 in the standing. Sutton knocked out FRED
COUPLES.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
