<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INMAN TAKES SENIOR CLASSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gil Morgan, the two-time defending champion,
showed up wearing gilded colors for the stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   But co-leader Joe Inman walked away with the gold, sprinting
past Morgan and strong-finishing Lee Trevino and Brian Barnes to
win Sunday's Pacific Bell Senior Classic at Wilshire Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in Hollywood,'' said Inman (66-68-68_202), who finished a
stroke ahead of Trevino and two up on Morgan and Barnes to earn a
full exemption for next year's Senior PGA Tour and a berth in this
week's Senior Tour Championship _ both on his last chance.
</P>
<P>
   The winner, a heart-on-his-sleeve type who cried in victory and
said he wanted only to try his hardest, vaulted from 42nd on the
Senior Tour money list to 28th while joining the 31-man field in
the Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself not to back off, to be a man,'' said Inman, who
earned $165,000 to raise his first-year total to $566,402. ``I
wanted to walk off the course and be proud of my conduct and proud
of my effort.''
</P>
<P>
   He did so generally with three days of clutch putting _
especially on numerous difficult par saves _ and specifically with
three consecutive birdies on the back nine on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   That trio of birdies, coming on putts of 12-, 10- and 10-feet on
holes 14, 15 and 16, finally overtook the sizzling Trevino, who
started the day four shots behind Inman and Morgan, passed them
before starting the back nine and was on pace to break Hale Irwin's
tournament-record round of 7-under 64.
</P>
<P>
   Trevino reached 7-under for the day with a birdie on 16, only to
bogey 17 while Inman was recording his third straight birdie on 16
and taking a lead he would not lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bogey at 17 was crucial,'' said Trevino, who finished with
a 65 that equaled the best round of the tournament. ``I putted
better today _ made a lot of good putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven of them dropped for birdies, and Trevino almost made a
tournament-winning pitch for an eighth birdie on No. 16, when his
shot from behind a greenside bunker hit an inch from the cup _ only
to roll another 25 feet uphill to set up the decisive bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Inman, who finished with four birdies, kept the suspense going
even after his backside-birdie run, first by driving into the the
rough on No. 17, then hammering a putt too hard on No. 18 to leave
himself a 4-footer for the win.
</P>
<P>
   He escaped the rough with a brilliant iron shot to mid-green but
wound up in an anxious mood again after overpowering a birdie bid
from the 18th fringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe made it interesting on No. 18,'' Trevino said. ``I was
pulling for him to make that 4-footer.''
</P>
<P>
   Trevino had missed one much closer on No. 18, two-putting from
less than a foot.
</P>
<P>
   He made up for that with brilliant play Sunday, pulling Barnes
along with him and nearly into a Tour Championship berth. The big
Briton, who finished 32nd in tour earnings (31 play this week)
totaled five birdies and no bogeys and got within a stroke of the
lead before Inman's late surge.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes took the near-miss in stride, having already earned
playing privileges for next year through May by virtue of his win
in the Senior Canadian Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had enough golf this year,'' he said, ``and I knew unless
I played like a bloody idiot I was going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan wound up far from fine in terms of his tournament win
streak and his streak of sub-70 rounds at Wilshire, where he had
shot eight straight. He finished 70, offsetting three birdies with
two bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Green (69-206) finished fifth, Bobby Stroble sixth
(69-207) and four tied for seventh at 208, including broadcaster
and tour rookie Gary McCord.
</P>
<P>
   Inman wound up overwhelmed but hardly at a loss for words on the
day he won his largest check as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hung in there,'' he said. ``I got tired of saying `Great
shot, Doc' (to Dr. Gil Morgan), got my rhythm back on No. 13 and
then started making the putts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
