<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RUSTBELT (Magnitogorsk, Russia) _ Of all Russia's
problems, perhaps the most vexing lies in its Rust Belt, an
archipelago of aging industrial giants that are choking on the
bloated work forces of communities that have no other reason for
being. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-MONTENEGRO (Budva, Yugoslavia) _ Many Montenegrins,
including government officials, say they are hoping to create an
open and democratic society as an example of how all Yugoslavs
should be able to live. To achieve that, however, they are falling
back on a tradition of smuggling. By John J. O'Connor. (Graphic has
been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RIGHTS (Beijing) _ The founder of an independent research
group that was closed down by the government last week was refused
permission to leave China and had his passport confiscated. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-REBELS (Goma, Congo) _ There is not much in their resumes
to unite the leaders of the three-month-old rebellion in Congo,
except a common goal: that Laurent Kabila, who they accuse of
becoming yet another dictator, must go. By Ian Fisher. (Graphic has
been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ORLEANS-CEMETERY (New Orleans) _ Sunday was All Saints' Day,
a day to honor the dead, and in New Orleans this Roman Catholic
holiday is embraced by Protestants, Jews, everyone, it seems.
People bring food, sit in the shade and visit in the long, granite
rows of old and new crypts _ even paupers' graves. By Rick Bragg.
(Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BERKELEY-STREET-PEOPLE (Berkeley, Calif.) _ Plenty of people in
the nation's most famously liberal city want the street people who
congregate on the corners of Telegraph Avenue, the one shopping
district here mentioned in every tourist guide, swept away. By
Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-EDUC _ Spurred by fierce competition for students,
colleges and universities from Florida State to New York University
are plunging headlong into the rapidly evolving world of online
education, a world that barely existed five years ago. By Karen W.
Arenson. (Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-INITIATIVES (Seattle, Wash.) _ Exactly 100 years after
South Dakota became the first state in the union to allow direct
citizen lawmaking through a process generally known as ``initiative
and referendum,'' voters around the nation face many such measures
this week. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-TURNOUT (Charlotte, N.C.) _ In a nonpresidential
election year, with the economy humming and no national issues
inflaming passions, only committed voters _ fewer than four in 10
of whom are eligible _ are expected to vote on Tuesday. Candidates
are in a fierce struggle to insure that their core supporters vote,
or, as political professionals put it, that they ``energize their
base.'' By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-GOVS (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ In the 14-state area bounded
by the Sierra Nevadas on the West and the Missouri and Arkansas
Rivers on the East, 11 of the governors are Republicans. In two
states with Democratic governors, Colorado and Nevada, Republican
candidates approach the elections with thin leads in opinion polls.
Only Nebraska, without a gubernatorial election this fall, is
certain to have a Democratic governor next year. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE-RACE _ In a race where the victory of either Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato or Rep. Charles Schumer could well be determined by
a few percentage points at most, each party is working _ and
spending _ feverishly to get their voters to the polls. By Jonathan
P. Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HYDE (Washington) _ The role of the two teams of Rep.
Henry Hyde (investigative vs. political teams), how they work
together _ and apart _ and who will have Hyde's ear when tough
decisions have to be made on impeachment proceedings. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PARTTIME-WORKERS (Undated) _ A new class of part-timers, who put
in as many as 35 to 40 hours a week, is emerging. No one knows how
exactly many full-time part timers there are, but there is
agreement that the number is growing and that their hours are
growing. Some of these workers are happy with the arrangement, but
many others are frustrated. By Reed Abelson. (Graphic and photo has
been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-NBC-MEDIA (Undated) _ Only 18 months ago, NBC's executives
were riding a wave of prime-time success that had raised the
network to record-setting profits. But some of the edge came off
that confidence last Christmas, when Jerry Seinfeld announced that
he was stopping production on the comedy series that had led NBC to
its record profits. By Bill Carter. (Graphic has been sent to NYT
photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TIMEWARNER-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Suddenly on Wall Street, it's
the wonderful world of Time Warner. In a remarkable turnaround, the
media company that investors love best is no longer Disney. By
Geraldine Fabrikant. (Graphic has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-BIKE-FILM (New York) _ ``Vietnam: Long Time Coming,'' a
documentary about a bike ride for disabled people, premieres
Tuesday at the Times Square Sony theater and will be broadcast by
NBC in December. It marks the 25th anniversary of the Paris peace
accord. It is also the result of an unusual collaboration that
includes the makers of ``Hoop Dreams'' and the media and technology
banker Peter Kiernan of Goldman, Sachs. By Laura M. Holson. Graphic
has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ACCOUNTS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ October ended with tricks for
some agencies and treats for others, as advertisers made decisions
on accounts with total billings estimated at $210 million to $230
million. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ Of all the journalists in history,
the one most heatedly maligned by historians is James Thomson
Callender. What did he do to provoke such wrath? He broke the story
that President Thomas Jefferson ``has kept, as his concubine, one
of his own slaves'' and that ``by this wench Sally, our president
has had several children.'' By William Safire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUN-NYMARATHON-FINISHERS (New York) _ Despite its huge field and
large number of first-time runners, New York has the highest
percentage of finishers _ 96.9 in 1997 _ among the leading U.S.
marathons. A look at why, and at the mental strategies people use
to push themselves through 26.2 miles. (Photos have been sent to
NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RUN-NYMARATHON-STRAIN (New York) _ A look at the physical toll
the marathon takes, as runners struggle through the later stages,
with visits to the medical tents. What is the point when you can't
continue?
</P>
<P>
   RUN-NYMARATHON-FAMILIES (New York) _ The scene at the Family
Reunion area on Central Park West, where thousands of exhausted
runners will face one last challenge: finding their loved one.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-TURNER (Undated) _ Obituary on Clyde ``Bulldog'' Turner,
the Hall of Fame football player who was the second coach of the
New York Titans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category code)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROTHKO-ESTATE (New York) _ Remembering the Rothko estate battle,
and the fallout since. By Judith Dobrzynski. (Photo has been sent
to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SHOSTAKOVICH-DEBATE (Boston) _ Shostakovich scholars battle it
out again. By James R. Oestreich.
</P>
<P>
   ALI-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt reviews
``King of the World: Muhammad Ali and the Rise of the American
Hero,'' by David Remnick.
</P>
<P>
   TV-BECKER-REVIEW (Undated) _ Ron Wertheimer reviews ``Becker,''
a new CBS show with Ted Danson.
</P>
<P>
   FOX-CABLE-MEDIA _ The Fox Family Channel is planning two new
cable networks _ the Boyz Channel and the Girlz Channel _ raising
some questions from parents and educators of whether it is
fostering gender stereotypes among children. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
