<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-NYMARATHON-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTEBOOK: WEB SPREADS THE WORD AT A SPEED PHEIDIPPIDES NEVER
DREAMED OF
</HEADLINE>
   (See Also: RUN-NYMARATHON-WOMEN, RUN-NYMARATHON-FINISHERS,
RUN-NYMARATHON-STRAIN, RUN-NYMARATHON-FAMILIES,
RUN-NYMARATHON-FIRSTTIME, RUN-NYMARATHON-WHEELS,
RUN-NYMARATHON-ARATON-COLUMN, RUN-NYMARATHON-TV) 
(nk) 
 By GRACE LICHTENSTEIN and RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thousands of people, including many overseas, who
could not follow the New York City Marathon on Sunday on television
or radio were able to read personal messages from their friends,
relatives and loved ones sent from the course with a bit of digital
derring-do.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Road Runners Club and a Web shopping site,
stuff.com, joined forces to set up check-in sites for runners both
at the start in Staten Island and at Mile 18 on First Avenue at
96th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Runners could either fill out a brief message form on paper
beforehand and hand it to volunteers on the course, or simply slow
down and shout a message, which volunteers then relayed by cellular
phone to staffers at the Road Runners offices. There, the runners'
bib numbers were used to identify them, and their words of wonder
and woe were ``Webcast'' almost immediately on the official
marathon site, www.nycmarathon.org.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of runners took advantage of the system. Among the more
unusual messages was one from Karen Berkenfeld of New York City to
Manhattan Quilters Guild. The message: ``Going strong. Can someone
help me get this `stitch out'?''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the one from Jude Bourque of Baton Rouge, La., to
the Gang: ``Ahhhhhhh!! I need therapy!''
</P>
<P>
   Many more, however, were more upbeat, like the one from Tad
Witkowicz to ``the guys in West Boylston, Mass.'': ``Doing great,
body holding out good, thousands of people and fantastic feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Web site kept up a play-by-play account as the
race progressed and posted the finishers and times almost
immediately. By 5:30 p.m., the names, bib numbers and times of more
than 30,000 finishers were listed on line.
</P>
<P>
   Injury Report
</P>
<P>
   The hundreds of physicians, firefighters and emergency medical
technicians on hand for medical problems at the New York City
Marathon had a relatively calm day both on the course and afterward
in the medical tents in Central Park. As of 7 p.m., the New York
City Fire Department, which coordinated the on-site medical effort,
reported that 104 runners were treated and released for minor
sprains, cramps and dehydration problems. Twelve cases were
serious, ranging from a fractured femur to chest pains.
</P>
<P>
   Fine Day for a Run
</P>
<P>
   Runners were not the only marathon participants happy about
Sunday's good weather. Volunteers at the finish line in Central
Park basked in the cool, partly sunny autumnal weather, which was a
welcome contrast to last year, when they were drenched in a
rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beach day,'' exclaimed Philip Lerner of New Hyde Park,
N.Y., a volunteer for the last eight years, as the race began.
``Pass the Coppertone!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Follow-Ups
</P>
<P>
   Catching up with runners profiled in New York Times articles in
the week before the race:
</P>
<P>
   _ Jimmy Behr of Staten Island, running for the 8,628th
consecutive day, finished his 24th straight New York City Marathon
in 3:29:30. His goal had been to run 3:30 or better to qualify for
next year's Boston Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kirk Johnson, who described the emotions surrounding what
would be his first marathon in an article that appeared in the
Times on Sunday, finished in 4:27. ``I think maybe I started too
fast and fell into a hole for five or six miles, and it took me to
the end to crawl out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eyes on the Prize
</P>
<P>
   Meghan Howell said she was taught never to look over her
shoulder in a race. Had she done so in Sunday's pre-marathon high
school competition, she would have seen no one.
</P>
<P>
   Howell, a senior at Suffern High School in Rockland County,
N.Y., led from the start to win for the second straight year,
clocking 12 minutes 27 seconds on the 2.2-mile course through
Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Romaniuk captured the boys' race in 10:49.9 to complete a
sweep for Suffern. He held off the fast-closing Marc Crosswell of
Elmont (N.Y.) High School by 1.3 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt confident a mile in,'' said Romaniuk, a 10th grader.
``There was no one around me.''
</P>
<P>
   Howell burst from the pack right away and beat the second-place
finisher, Karina Acevedo of Middletown (N.Y.) High School, by 20.9
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to run away from the sound of others'
feet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Marathon Meets Halloween
</P>
<P>
   The confluence of the New York City Marathon and Halloween
produced some suitably bizarre scenes Saturday night outside Tavern
on the Green at Central Park West and 67th Street. While long
queues of runners, most in warm-up outfits, waited on line for
admission to the traditional Ronzoni pasta party inside a huge tent
on the restaurant's grounds, hordes of children and a significant
number of adults dressed as werewolves, goblins and Frankensteins
strolled on their trick-or-treat rounds. The two groups eyed each
other with undisguised interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mommy, why are those people wearing shorts?'' one diminutive
witch asked her vampire companion, pointing to a cluster of
marathoners in jackets bearing the name of a French athletic club.
(The temperature Saturday at 6 p.m. was in the high 40s.)
</P>
<P>
   Inside the tent, over a period of five hours, about 15,000
runners, many of them from outside the United States, carbo-loaded
on what Ronzoni dubbed jack o'lantern lasagne (the ingredients
included canned pumpkin), masquerade mostaccioli salad and
twist-or-treat pasta marinara. They were greeted at one point by
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and former Yankee pitcher Whitey Ford.
</P>
<P>
   A few marathoners arrived in costume, including a couple dressed
as dice in girdles of black and white Styrofoam squares, and a man
wearing a Little Red Riding Hood scarf and cape accompanied by a
woman in a wolf's mask.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Lazarowitz of Jersey City, N.J., a well-traveled
marathoner, came dressed as Minnie Mouse, complete with whiskers
and mouse ears. Among her reasons: She had run her first marathon
at Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   Most runners, however, were costumed as, well, marathoners, even
though most of the foreign visitors understood that it was, in
fact, Halloween. ``I couldn't pack my costume because my baggage
allowance didn't allow it,'' said Grant Andrea, an Australian now
living in London.
</P>
<P>
   Yasuhiro Natori, a biochemist from Japan, said he had learned
about Halloween during the two years he had lived in Boston, but
could not bring a costume on this trip because he combined it with
attending a scientific meeting in Philadelphia, ``so I had to pack
a suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mas of Lima, Peru, a veteran of two marathons in his home
country but participating in his first New York City Marathon, was
well aware of the holiday, but disdained wearing a costume. ``In
Peru,'' he said, ``that's for children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
