<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MARLBORO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VASSER FINDS THE FIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL SCHLOTTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ As teammates and friends over the past three
seasons, CART drivers Jimmy Vasser and Alex Zanardi say they have
shared expertise and exchanged ideas to make themselves and their
team better.
</P>
<P>
   Zanardi said one of his suggestions to Vasser has been to kindle
a sense of extra determination, ``a kind of fire in the eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   That fire was crackling Sunday in a final-lap shootout at the
California Speedway as Vasser blazed by Greg Moore and held off
Zanardi to win the Marlboro 500 and its season-best $1 million
prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fantastic way to finish the season,'' said Vasser,
who was able to move up to second in season points to Zanardi
thanks to the win. ``The million dollars is great, but the goal for
me coming in here was to finish second in the championship. Alex
has had the championship won for some time and it's been a goal of
our team for me to finish second.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore wound up second in the race and Zanardi third. Bobby
Rahal, making the final start of his career, finished 11th.
</P>
<P>
   Vasser's goal was just a two-mile dash away when Sunday's race
restarted with one lap left after an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Race leader Paul Tracy had spun off the track a few laps before,
leaving Greg Moore in first, Vasser second and Zanardi third when
the green starter's flag fell on lap 250. And instantly Vasser went
high and Zanardi went low to try to pass Moore on the front
straightaway.
</P>
<P>
   They were both by him in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just came out of nowhere,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was able to get one place back before the checkered flag,
beating out Zanardi for second. But Vasser was out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Vasser was in hot pursuit of the victory from the outset Sunday,
charging from his starting post on the outside of pole-winner Scott
Pruett to take the lead on the opening lap.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in an event kept close by the speed-reducing Handford Wing
device, he stayed at or near the leaders _ which at various times
included himself, Moore, Michael Andretti, Tracy and Mauricio
Gugelmin _ successfully staying out of trouble and waiting for an
expected end-of-race free-for-all.
</P>
<P>
   And as Vasser hung tough, leading 63 of the 250 laps and always
staying close, his competition slowly exited the field.
</P>
<P>
   Pruett, who won the pole with a best time of 233.748 mph, was
near the leaders through the early going. But on the 139th lap, his
car lost traction in turn 4 and hit the outside wall. Pruett was
unhurt but his race was over.
</P>
<P>
   Vasser's chief rival for second place in season points, Dario
Franchitti, had left the race in the 113th lap, his car spewing
smoke and flame as he slowed to a stop along the backstretch apron.
Franchitti, running second in the race at the time, led Vasser by
12 points (160-148) coming in.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti, who led 44 laps Sunday, went out on lap 211, as the
racing became more intense. While running second to Vasser,
Andretti's car got too low in turn 4, lost traction and spun hard
into the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get as much out of the track as possible and I
pushed it a bit too hard,'' said Andretti, who was not injured.
``It's too bad because we were really strong today.''
</P>
<P>
   With 10 laps to go, Vasser was running third and preparing to
make a late move on the leaders, Tracy and Moore.
</P>
<P>
   But a yellow flag brought out after an accident involving Bryan
Herta and Max Papis was in force for laps 241 through 245. And as
the cars restarted on lap 246, Tracy suddenly lost control,
spinning into an infield wall, leaving Moore first, Vasser second
and Zanardi third as another yellow flag came out and the race
appeared headed for a yellow-flag finish that would have made Moore
the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was speechless,'' Vasser said of Tracy's misfortune. ``But I
was hoping they would get it cleaned up quickly so I would have a
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   They did.
</P>
<P>
   And with one lap left, Vasser and Zanardi pounced.
</P>
<P>
   All weekend, drivers have said that air currents caused by use
of the Hanford Device gives cars running in packs an advantage over
cars running alone. Out in front by himself, Moore was ripe for the
picking, Vasser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these races, you don't want to be the lead car on the final
lap,'' Vasser said. ``He was a sitting duck.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the eighth of Vasser's CART career and his third
this season. And it gave his team, Target Chip Ganassi Racing, its
second straight one-two finish in the standings. Zanardi and Vasser
also finished first and second last year.
</P>
<P>
   Vasser, the 1996 CART champion, said he has enjoyed his
three-year association with Zanardi and will miss him next year
when Zanardi moves to Formula One.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned a lot from Mr. Zanardi,'' he said. ``He's been a
great teammate and a great friend. It's great to be up (on the
winner's platform) with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
