r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLLYWOOD-HOLIDAY-2ta     11-02 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-HOLIDAY-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD GEARS UP FOR END-OF-YEAR PUSH TO CAP RECORD-BREAKING
YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Hollywood's three-year hot streak shows no signs
of cooling as the movie industry scrambles to get ready for its
critical holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   The national box office remains on track to beat last year's
record by an astounding 10 percent to finish at $7 billion. That
would beat the back-to-back gains of 9 percent in 1997 and 8
percent in 1996, and certain hits like ``A Bug's Life'' and
``Stepmom'' will keep moviegoers coming during the last two months
of 1998, observers believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great year,'' declared Paul Dergarabedian,
president of industry tracker Exhibitor Relations Co. ``And I think
we're going to go out with a bang.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics may claim higher ticket prices and ``Titanic'' caused
the gain, but that's not the case. The average ticket price has
gone from $4.59 to $4.65; the first $158 million for ``Titanic''
came during the last 12 days of 1997. That means this year's
improvement has as much to do with strong performances by dozens of
films as it does with Leonardo DiCaprio.
</P>
<P>
   Dergarabedian noted this year's Friday-Sunday box office
receipts have topped their 1997 counterparts for the last 16
consecutive weekends and on 33 of the 43 weekends so far this year.
``The performance really is staggering and the bottom line is that
the product is out there,'' he said. ``You don't have 10 films get
over $100 million without people telling other people to go see
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's optimism received a major boost two weeks ago when
executives for studios and theater chains gathered in Atlantic
City, N.J., for the annual ShowEast convention. Exhibitors came
away raving about the screenings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll do better during the holiday season this year
than last year,'' said Chan Wood, head film buyer for the Los
Angeles-based Pacific Theaters chain. ``Picture for picture, this
year looks better than last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood also noted that, unlike other years, all major genres _
family, romantic comedy, science fiction, action and Academy Award
hopefuls _ have strong representation. ``And I think the scheduling
has been spread out pretty well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The final weeks of the year are crucial to studios and theater
chains. It marks one of the heaviest movie-going periods,
presumably when large groups of family members go to movies
together, and is the launch time for serious Oscar campaigning.
Last year's Thanksgiving-New Year's period generated 17 percent of
annual business, compared to 15.4 percent during the 11-week fall
period the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Early betting is that at least a half-dozen holiday-season films
will join the 10 that have topped $100 million domestically this
year. Analysts believe the following will enjoy close to slam-dunk
success:
</P>
<P>
   --Disney's ``A Bug's Life,'' the season's strongest candidate.
The computer-animated comedy is the first from Pixar Animation
since it scored a major hit in 1995 with ``Toy Story.'' Stewart
Halpern, an analyst with ING Barings Furman Selz, believes it will
match ``Toy Story's'' $192 million domestic gross.
</P>
<P>
   --Sony's ``Stepmom,'' with Julia Roberts in the title role. Buzz
has heated up since ShowEast. ``Everyone who saw it was touched,''
Wood said. ``This is a 10-hankie film.''
</P>
<P>
   --Warner Bros.' ``You've Got Mail'' with Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan
in a romantic comedy set in New York with echoes of their 1993 hit
``Sleepless in Seattle.'' ``It's good, if not better, than
`Sleepless,' '' said Dan Klusman, editor of the Independent
Marketing Edge newsletter. ``It's sort of formulaic but it works
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   --20th Century Fox's World War II drama ``The Thin Red Line,''
which will not go into wide release until next year but has emerged
as a strong Oscar candidate.
</P>
<P>
   --Universal's ``Meet Joe Black,'' with Brad Pitt as the Grim
Reaper. The buzz has been hot for months despite its running time
of nearly three hours. ``It doesn't seem long,'' Klusman said. ``I
thought it was a great story with broad appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   --Universal's comedy-drama ``Patch Adams,'' based on a true
story, with Robin Williams as a medical student with offbeat
approaches to healing. Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel
Source forecasting service, said Williams will likely receive an
Oscar nomination. ``I think this is the feel-good film of the
year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   --DreamWorks' ``Prince of Egypt'' is its second shot in the
battle to rival Disney in animation. ``We think it will cross over
into the mainstream,'' Bucksbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's distribution chief Wayne Lewellen said the outlook
for the holiday season is better this year than it was at this time
last year, when the town was holding its breath over ``Titanic.''
``I don't think there's a single big picture right now, but we're
hearing very good things about several,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (2nd take to follow)
</P>
<P>
   Except for ``A Bug's Life'' and ``Meet Joe Black,'' the season's
heavy hitters are clustered around Christmastime. That's a
substantial shift from a few years ago, when November was the hot
slot for releases, and it underscores how well the going-late
strategy worked last year for ``Titanic,'' ``Good Will Hunting,''
``Tomorrow Never Dies'' and ``As Good As It Gets.''
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen other major films also are generating strong buzz
and could do more than $50 million domestically, including
Universal's remake of ``Psycho,'' Fox's ``The Siege,'' Disney's
``Enemy of the State'' and its remake of ``Mighty Joe Young,''
Sony's sequel ``I Still Know What You Did Last Summer'' and
Paramount's ``Rugrats'' and ``Star Trek: Insurrection.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney has allocated the valuable Dec. 25 date for ``Mighty Joe
Young,'' an updated version of the 1949 film about a lovable
15-foot gorilla. It was originally slotted for mid-July, then reset
for Christmas in order to avoid competing with ``Armageddon.''
</P>
<P>
   Producer Ted Hartley, who first pitched the idea four years ago,
said test screenings have generated solid responses from children
and adults. ``Christmas is exactly the right time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several offbeat films have also generated heat, including
Gramercy's ``Elizabeth,'' Fox Searchlight's ``Waking Ned Devine,''
and PolyGram's ``Very Bad Things,'' a bleak comedy about a bachelor
party gone bad. The latter, starring Cameron Diaz in her first film
since ``There's Something About Mary,'' has received the choice
release date of Nov. 25, a day before Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love being the counterprogramming to `A Bug's Life,' '' said
producer Cindy Cowan. ``I doubt the entire family will go see this
after Thanksgiving dinner, but we will do well for people anywhere
from 18 to 30.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowan said screenings at colleges have produced exceptional
response, leading to the studio's decision to release ``Things'' at
1,500 theaters and spend $15 million on promotion. ``We figured
people would love it or be appalled by it and that it would go as a
platform release in the art houses,'' she said. ``It tested way
beyond what we expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every film will be a hit, but what's impressive is that so
many have breakout potential. ``It doesn't look like any `Titanic'
this holiday season but there are a lot of films that are going to
do over $100 million and play well into 1999,'' Bucksbaum said.
``Keep in mind that it will take five films to match `Titanic,' so
this is a really solid schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   How has the movie business kept growing at a time of spiraling
costs and brutal competition for entertainment dollars?
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, studios have become a bit more careful.
Although portrayed as havens of wild spending, the Hollywood majors
have managed to cut back slightly on the number of releases and
avoid big-ticket flops. They also have backed away from several
projects with $100 million-plus price tags, such as a fifth
``Superman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many intangibles, but I think studios are getting
more control over what's a hit,'' Dergarabedian said. ``No amount
of marketing can make up for a bad movie, but good word of mouth is
priceless on movies like `Rush Hour,' `There's Something About
Mary' and `Saving Private Ryan.' It's in the film.''
</P>
<P>
   With the average cost of making and marketing a movie now more
than $75 million, studios are playing it safer, Klusman believes.
``I think overall, you're seeing a higher quality of filmmaking
over the last year with fewer releases but better films,'' he said.
``There weren't many bombs this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, the business is no longer dominated, as it had been
since the late 1980s, by Warner Bros. and Disney. Sony was the big
winner in 1997 and Paramount has been the leader all year, thanks
to ``Titanic,'' ``The Truman Show'' and ``Deep Impact.'' With
``Rugrats'' and ``Star Trek'' still to come, it will soon join Sony
and Disney as the only studios to top $1 billion domestically in a
single year.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, studios are scheduling sensibly, avoiding
head-to-head encounters in the same genre. A key case in point came
in early summer when ``Deep Impact'' and ``Armageddon'' opened two
months apart, rather than two weeks apart.
</P>
<P>
   The only potential jam-up during the holidays is around
Thanksgiving when ``A Bug's Life,'' ``Rugrats'' and ``Babe: A Pig
in the City'' are competing. `` `A Bugs Life' is the one film
assured to be a success because of the `Toy Story' reputation and
`Rugrats' is getting a real positive buzz,'' Bucksbaum said. ``So
the `Babe' sequel may be the third wheel in that bunch although
Thanksgiving is the biggest time of the year for family films.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
