<HEADER>
A8416 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COLTS-BO     11-02 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COLTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS BACK ON TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ A wise old football sage once said that in
confusion there is profit.
</P>
<P>
   With three receivers out because of injuries, and a fourth,
Shawn Jefferson, sidelined for a bit in Sunday's game after
suffering a rib injury, the Patriots seemed doomed. But New England
discovered the talents of second-round pick Tony Simmons, whose
63-yard touchdown reception in the fourth quarter propelled the
Patriots to a 21-16 win over the Colts before 58,056 at the RCA
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   They also rediscovered the talents of their All-Pro tight end,
Ben Coates, who caught 10 passes for 109 yards. And the defense,
led by Lawyer Milloy's two late interceptions of Peyton Manning
passes, helped preserve what was a tougher victory than expected.
</P>
<P>
   The win, which was not unexpected against the 1-7 Colts,
improved the Patriots to 5-3 (their same record as last year at
this time) and ended a two-game losing streak. They also improved
to 2-2 in the AFC East and were snuggled in a four-way tie with
Buffalo, Miami, and the Jets for the division lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it would be a difficult game and it was,'' said
Patriots coach Pete Carroll. ``Ben stepped up big for us and Tony
Simmons did a terrific job. We hung in there. We needed to win it
and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots secured control with the 63-yard bomb from Drew
Bledsoe to Simmons, the rookie from Wisconsin, with 14:16 remaining
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had taken over on downs at their 37, and after a
long drive late in the third quarter resulted in an interception,
offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese decided to go for it, knowing
that Simmons had been beating cornerback Jeff Burris all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to fight Burris off and catch the ball,'' said Simmons,
who matched Coates's total of 109 receiving yards but on only four
receptions. ``It was a difficult play, but those are plays you have
to make. The ball was right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe (22 of 35 for 306 yards, with 2 TDs and the one
interception), who had problems on the long ball last week vs.
Miami, led Simmons perfectly down the right sideline with a tight
spiral. Simmons indeed fought off Burris, who was called for
interference on the play, but created enough separation to make the
catch at the 15. He took it in to give the Patriots a 21-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disappointing we couldn't close it out, but that's an
emerging team,'' Bledsoe said. ``They're going to cause a lot of
teams problems down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts almost caused them for the Patriots, driving 88 yards
on 13 plays to make it 21-16 with 3:40 left.
</P>
<P>
   The drive featured elusive running by Marshall Faulk, who had a
big 20-yard catch, and shoddy tackling by Ted Johnson, who allowed
Marcus Pollard to get out of his grasp for a 15-yard touchdown
catch.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts went for the 2-point conversion, and Faulk was stuffed
by the middle of the Patriots' line.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we look at the film, we'll see we had a chance to ice the
final 4 1/2 minutes of the game, but coming off a two-game losing
streak, right now I'm not going to be too critical,'' said
offensive tackle Bruce Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Manning threw two costly interceptions late, when it appeared he
had a chance to lead the Colts back. Nine of his 16 picks have come
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   With the Patriots leading, 14-10, the Colts took the second-half
kickoff and were forced to punt. Bledsoe then put together an
efficient drive that started at the Patriots' 9 and went to the
Colts' 11. But Bledsoe, who had thrown six passes to Coates during
the march, tried to drill one into Henry Ellard at the 5.
Cornerback Robert Blackmon stepped in front of Ellard and made the
interception, the first by Bledsoe against the Colts in six games.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, Bledsoe directed a nine-play, 80-yard
scoring drive that consumed about five minutes. Coates, who had 53
catches vs. the Colts entering the game, became the focus for
Bledsoe, hauling in a 27-yard pass to the Indy 30. Another huge
happening was a 21-yard interference call on Burris vs. Jefferson
on third and 11 at the Colts' 31. From there, Robert Edwards raced
nicely around the right corner on an 8-yard run to the 2. The drive
was completed when Bledsoe flared a pass to Coates in the far
corner of the end zone, giving the Patriots a 7-0 lead with 6:39
remaining in the first.
</P>
<P>
   According to Patriots tight end coach Carl Smith, the Colts were
in zone coverage against Coates in the first half, man-to-man in
the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why they covered me like they did,'' said Coates,
who ate up free safety Jason Belser. ``Sometimes they had two,
sometimes they had one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts didn't waste any time tying it. The coverage was
terrible, and poor tackling by Chris Canty sprung Jerome Pathon for
an 18-yard gain to the Patriots' 34. Marvin Harrison and Faulk were
wide open for catches of 10 and 11 yards, but not as alone as
Lamont Warren was on a 4-yard pass from Manning that tied the
score.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as the Patriots had trouble finding the end zone
against Miami the week before, they quickly found it again to
recapture the lead, 14-7, with 10:54 remaining in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This time the drive went 81 yards and it featured the passing
game again. Starting at his 19, Bledsoe went over the middle to
Simmons for 24 yards, and later found him on a slant for 12 yards
to the Indy 12. Bledsoe also got the veteran Ellard, who was signed
last week, in on the act, hitting him on a 15-yard pass over the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots again were aided by an interference call on Burris,
who held Simmons in the back of the end zone on a pass from the
Indy 12. With the ball placed at the 1, Edwards scored on his third
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots gave the Colts the ball back with 46 seconds left
in the half, enough time for them to set up Mike Vanderjagt's
49-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tackling was our downfall today,'' said Carroll. ``They had a
lot of small passes and large runs after the catch.''
</P>
<P>
   But while deficiencies were aplenty, the good things won out.
And now the Patriots are back to familiar territory, with the same
record they had last year at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be the steppingstone game,'' said Jefferson. ``We
needed this one to move on from here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
