MISTAKE COSTS TRACY $987,500 &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL SCHLOTTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ A million-dollar prize might have taken some
of the sting out of Paul Tracy's suspension from next year's
season-opening CART race in Miami. And Tracy was poised to earn
that big payday Sunday at the California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   But leading the $1 million Marlboro 500 with four laps to go,
Tracy tried to get a little too much speed a little too fast on a
restart and wound up spinning his car into an infield fence. And
while Jimmy Vasser fought off Greg Moore and teammate Alex Zanardi
to win the race and the big bucks, Tracy had to settle for 14th
place and $12,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my standpoint, I dropped the ball,'' Tracy said. ``I just
tried to do the restart the way I'd done the previous one and get a
good jump, and it just drove around on me. It was my mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The points: Vasser's victory and Dario Franchitti's exit with
engine trouble enabled Vasser to move past Franchitti into second
place in the season-points race, won by Zanardi. Adrian Fernandez
was fourth and Moore fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Valencia product Bryan Herta finished eighth. Glendale's Richie
Hearn was 16th.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tough day: Herta seemed to have the speed to run with the
leaders, but because of an unscheduled pit stop, he was forced to
run a lap down most of the day. He finished 15th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a flat tire running through (wreck debris),'' Herta
said. ``And it cost us a lap. I think we had a car to race with the
leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Herta went out of the race with 10 laps left when he collided
with future Team Rahal teammate Max Papis on the front
straightaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not sure what happened,'' Herta said. ``I think Max
was on the outside of me and we touched. If that's what happened,
then I guess it was my fault and I feel bad about it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Running in front: Hearn ran up front several times Sunday,
leading seven laps.
</P>
<P>
   A spin coming out of the pits late in the race didn't do any
damage to Hearn's car but cost him some places. He wound up eighth.
</P>
<P>
   __ Mr. Tenacity: When he crashed in qualifying Saturday and was
forced to begin Sunday's race at the back of the field, Adrian
Fernandez said it was no big deal. He had, after all, 500 miles to
catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Catch up he did.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez finished the race in fourth place and spent the latter
half of the race running with the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept working on the car, trying to find the right
balance,'' Fernandez said. ``Finally, toward the end of the race,
it was handling pretty good. I had to tell myself to slow down and
be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Etc.: Sunday's race was not a sellout, with the crowd
estimated at 105,000. Track officials guessed that about 160,000
attended the three-day event. . . . CART has reached an agreement
with Neil Russell Productions to make an hourlong action-adventure
television series set on the CART tour. Fall 1999 is the target
date to air the syndicated program. . . . The Lola chassis, which
fell into disrepute in recent seasons, will be run by up to four
teams in 1999, company owner Martin Birrane said Sunday. Only one
team used the Lola this year. . . . NFL great Walter Payton and his
partner Dale Coyne announced a long-term sponsorship deal has been
reached with Mexico's Herdez food company. Payton-Coyne driver
Michel Joudain of Mexico finished 12th in Sunday's race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
