<HEADLINE>
ELLARD WASTES NO TIME GETTING UP TO SPEED 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The postcareer athlete _ Lawrence Taylor excepted
_ soon learns that he must draw the curtain on the old life if he
is to be any kind of success in his new one.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Ellard had that curtain 90 percent drawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just in the process of making the transition,'' he says.
``I had put in 15 years. I had no regrets. It was nice. It was time
to move on. If it (playing one more season) wasn't meant to be, it
wasn't meant to be. I was just getting into that mode.''
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about less than a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the week this gentle man was in Orange,
Calif., coaching a 14-man high school team called Southern
California Christian. Sunday he was on the RCA Dome turf catching
three of Drew Bledsoe's passes, good for 52 yards. He was in a
winning locker room. He was once again a professional football
player. For the time being, the real world can wait.
</P>
<P>
   Catches of 15, 18, and 19 yards in an NFL game constitute a
reasonably good afternoon's work for any wide receiver. Catches of
15, 18, and 19 yards constitute a phenomenally successful
afternoon's work for someone who had practiced a mere three times
with his new team, and who was playing in his first football game
of any kind since last December. But that's why offensive
coordinator Ernie Zampese recommended the Patriots investigate
Ellard, wasn't it? Ernie Z had worked with this man in Los Angeles
and knew that if any unemployed wide receiver in the universe could
be counted on to step in and perform professionally in this
particular circumstance, it was 37-year-old Henry Ellard, a
veritable Yoda of wideouts.
</P>
<P>
   Ellard is still taking it all in. One day he is on the practice
field with his outgunned football squad when his wife, Lillian, is
having him paged. His agent, Frank Bauer, is looking for him.
Something about the Patriots needing a man to catch some passes. A
few days later he is suited up, wearing No. 17, catching real, live
passes from Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Life does have its funny little twists and turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just about ready to tell my agent that I was through,
that it was time to move onto something else,'' he admits.
</P>
<P>
   And just think if you're Bledsoe. One day you're fretting about
not having Terry Glenn, Vincent Brisby, and Troy Brown. And then
they come up with a new guy who can make it look as if the two of
you had spent the entire summer throwing footballs to each other on
the beach, kinda like Rockne and Dorais.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple fact that he can come in and play in a game after a
couple of practices is amazing,'' says Bledsoe. ``It didn't take
long to feel comfortable with him. One play in particular shows
what being a veteran can mean. His first catch was a comeback
route. You couldn't ask for a better route. I can tell you right
now I would be comfortable doing that with him against anybody in
the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Another simple fact is that only a veteran could walk in and
function in the Zampese offense, which features timing routes.
``Obviously, I'm not there yet,'' Ellard says. ``This is an offense
where you run to a spot and you turn around and the ball is there.
It will take awhile to get it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget about the cerebral aspect of all this for a minute.
Consider that Ellard hadn't been playing football at all. When the
Redskins elected to do without his services following the 1997
season, that was it. The man went home. There were no look-sees
anywhere. If the phone were to ring, he would be happy to answer
it. But he wasn't going to beg, not after 15 years of admirable NFL
service. And the phone wasn't ringing, not until the New England
Patriots got _ there is only one way to put it _ desperate.
</P>
<P>
   The only frame of reference for both his body and his mind had
come a long time ago _ 12 years, to be exact. ``I held out in LA in
'86,'' he explains. ``It lasted through September and into early
October. That was the longest I had gone without playing
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibitions? Who needs exhibitions? Two-a-days? Who needs
two-a-days? Did Henry Ellard just prove some kind of a point, or is
he a Jerry Rice-like freak of nature, as some maintain?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, what he did Sunday to help his new team was quietly
spectacular, and very much appreciated. ``What he and (rookie) Tony
Simmons are doing is helping us buy time until we get those other
guys back,'' observes offensive lineman Bruce Armstrong. ``This was
a must game for us. Of course, nobody wants to say that before the
fact. But we had to have this game. Now we have more control of our
own destiny. We've got both Buffalo games ahead of us, and next
time we'll have Miami at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellard isn't heading to the Pro Bowl. Right now all he's asking
for is to make it to the end of the season. He knows that as well
as he did Sunday, he can do better. He did, after all, drop one or
two, and he was outwrestled for a ball that turned out to be a
Robert Blackmon interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was rusty, no doubt,'' he acknowledged. ``My hands were OK,
but they'll get better. The big thing will be to get my old rhythm,
but it was fun being out there, competing again.''
</P>
<P>
   He was an immediate resource for a young'un such as Simmons, but
it doesn't stop there. ``(Strength coach) Johnny Parker gave us
some advice,'' reports eight-year vet Shawn Jefferson, occasionally
thought of as something of a sage himself, but a mere pup when
compared to Ellard. ``He said all the wide receivers should watch
Henry Ellard, and if he sneezes, we should all say, `Achoo!'''
</P>
<P>
   Achoo, gesundheit, whatever. Watching Henry Ellard catch the
ball Sunday meant one obvious thing: first down, New England.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 0129EST &QL; 
