u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MCDONOUGHCOLUMN-B     11-02 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLUTIE LEADS BILLS BACK AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ The night before, Thurman Thomas spoke to
the team, its younger players in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a game you have waited to play your whole lives,'' he
told his Buffalo Bills teammates. ``It is a privilege to play in a
game like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, the veteran of the four-time Super Bowl Bills, was right
on the money.
</P>
<P>
   In a classic shootout Sunday between two storied quarterbacks,
the Bills came from behind on the wings of some more Doug Flutie
magic to beat Dan Marino and the first-place Miami Dolphins, 30-24,
at a deafening Rich Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 79,011 was so loud that it bothered both teams,
something that usually doesn't happen in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   But it had been a few years since the once-proud Bills had
played in a home game that created such excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie vs. Marino. It doesn't get much better than that, and
neither disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie prevailed, with three touchdown passes to one for Marino.
Both players were the main men in a game that figured to be
low-scoring but suddenly erupted into a fast-break frenzy that
would have made Rick Pitino proud.
</P>
<P>
   In the second week of the season, the Dolphins had squeaked past
Buffalo, 13-7, in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   What was the difference between this game and the first one,
Miami's tough middle linebacker, Zach Thomas, was asked.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was simple. ``Him,'' said Thomas, referring to
Flutie. ``He made all the plays. In the end, he just wore us
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied at 14 at the half. Flutie threw touchdown
passes of 1 and 16 yards to tight end Jay Riemersma. Marino
connected on a 12-yard scoring pass to Orande Gadsden and set up a
1-yard scoring run by Karim Abdul-Jabbar with a 27-yard pass to
Gadsden.
</P>
<P>
   Miami seemed to put the game away early in the third period,
running off 10 straight points to go up, 24-14. Considering that
the Dolphins' No. 1-rated defense hadn't give up a touchdown in
nine periods entering the game, it looked to be over.
</P>
<P>
   But Flutie did what Flutie does. He made plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how to make plays. He gets the job done,'' said a
battered and dejected Marino.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets the crowd going,'' said Bills all-world defensive end
Bruce Smith. ``See the crowd today? They're going crazy. He makes
that happen. And then he is so creative. When he starts to
improvise, things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by those 10 points with 14 minutes to play, Flutie
said, ``We needed a spark. We had to make a play.''
</P>
<P>
   Four plays later, he did, firing a 48-yard rifle shot down the
left sideline to Eric Moulds between defenders for a touchdown,
cutting the Miami lead to 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had a one-on-one situation with Moulds,'' said
Flutie. ``And he beat his man quick, so I got the ball out there to
him. I didn't see the safety come across until the last minute. But
the ball got there before him. It looked close (to an
interception), but our bench said it wasn't that close.''
</P>
<P>
   The second Buffalo break came within two minutes. Marino had
solid pass protection most of the day, but Bills nose tackle Ted
Washington broke loose up the middle, hit Marino, and forced a
fumble. The ball was recovered by the Bills at the Miami 13. The
Bills got it to the 1, but opted for the tying field goal on fourth
down.
</P>
<P>
   Tie game. Less than 10 minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough place to play, with all of the noise,'' said
Marino. ``When they came back on us like that, they knew we had to
pass. And that made it hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino couldn't get it done. Advantage Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd bothered us, too,'' said Flutie. ``The noise was so
loud our offensive line had a hard time hearing the count.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie overcame what he had to. He passed to Andre Reed for 12
yards and Sam Gash for 14, setting up a go-ahead 36-yard field goal
by Steve Christie with 1:58 left. With 1:23 to play, and fourth
down at their 12, the Dolphins went for it and failed. Miami's
offense, which had been cooking for three periods, had minus-1 yard
in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Flutie and Buffalo gained 138 of their 313 net yards
in the final period. They tacked on a 25-yard field goal with 23
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flutie was the difference,'' said Miami's Zach Thomas. ``He is
just so smart. If we made a mistake, he took advantage of it. He
knew where to go with the football. If there was a weakness in what
we were doing on a certain play, he found it. I didn't think anyone
could move the ball on us the way they did at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug is special,'' said Gash, the former Patriot turned Bill.
``All the guys believe in him and realize how lucky we are to have
two good quarterbacks. He just goes up and makes plays. In the
huddle, he is in control. Nothing seems to bother him. All the guys
know that if we give him the chance, he will make the plays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
