<SLUG> BC-RUN-NY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAGWE BEATS CHEBET TO WIRE 
</HEADLINE>
 MARATHON-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joseph Chebet, one of the growing stable of Kenyan
distance runners on the international stage, has been at the center
of two enthralling races this year on the East Coast. He battled
Moses Tanui to the finish in the 102d Boston Marathon and raced
defender John Kagwe to the wire in Sunday's New York City Marathon
in Central Park. On each occasion, Chebet was beaten by a scant
three seconds.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the second straight year he was runner-up to Kagwe
in this race, but the margin was quite a bit larger a year ago.
Boston was all but decided when countryman Tanui turned it on with
200 meters to go, but Sunday's race saw Chebet seize the lead in
the final stretch before Kagwe had to shift gears with 100 meters
remaining to win in 2 hours 8 minutes 45 seconds. Kagwe (2:08:48)
and Tanzanian Zebedayo Bayo (2:08:51) made it a breathtaking final
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Franca Fiacconi became the first Italian to win the women's race
when she turned it on with 6 miles to go to win in a personal best
and Italian record of 2:25:17, beating Adriana Fernandez (2:26:33)
of Mexico and Tegla Loroupe (2:30:26) of Kenya, who set a world
record of 2:20:47 in Rotterdam in April. Joan Benoit Samuelson of
Freeport, Maine, who made an 11th-hour decision to run, was the
second American woman to finish (in 2:41:06), enabling her to
qualify for the US Olympic trials at the age of 41.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second-closest men's finish since the race's
inception in 1970, when it was run entirely within Central Park
before becoming an international race run through the city's five
boroughs. German Silva (fourth, 2:10:24) regrouped after making a
wrong turn in 1994 and ran down countryman Benjamin Paredes to win
by two seconds, and Alberto Salazar was the last American to win as
he edged Rodolfo Gomez by four seconds in 1982 in what is now the
third-closest finish.
</P>
<P>
   Kagwe did much of the work as the lead men's pack passed the
halfway mark in 1:04:19. He then made a decision to drop back. ``I
was giving up my energy for them,'' he said. ``I was doing the work
for them, so I got behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   Once they reached Fifth Avenue, just before turning into Central
Park for the first time with a little more than 2 miles to go,
Kagwe, Chebet, and Bayo pulled away, with Silva the last to go.
``They broke away,'' he said. ``They moved together. They held
together.'' They ran virtually three abreast out of the park and
westbound before reentering the park and heading to the finish
line.
</P>
<P>
   Bayo, who was a presence from the starting line until the final
kilometer, fell back a few strides when Chebet made his surge to
take the lead. Kagwe responded and became the first to defend since
Silva in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bayo) wasn't aware of where the finish line was,'' Kagwe said
through an interpreter. Bayo, who is just 22, refused to give up
and just lacked the finishing kick to make up his lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed in my training,'' said Kagwe. ``I've done a lot of
speed (work) and I knew I was strong. So when (Chebet) passed me, I
didn't get disturbed because I knew I could catch up with him. I
knew I could not let him go.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was another heartbreaking loss for Chebet. ``I was trying
to win,'' he said. ``I was trying to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiacconi, who had run a marathon three weeks before she finished
second in this race a year ago to Switzerland's Franziska
Rochat-Moser, had it pretty much locked up as she passed through 22
miles and opened it up to the finish in the race's second-fastest
time to Lisa Ondiecki's 2:24:40 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see a clock,'' Fiacconi said through an interpreter.
``I didn't control the pace. I knew at 30 kilometers it was my
race.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Samuelson, who phoned husband Scott Saturday night about 10:30
to let him know she was going to run, finished second among US
women to recent Tufts 10K winner Libby Hickman, who finished sixth
overall in 2:33:06. Samuelson, who won the inaugural women's
Olympic marathon in Los Angeles in 1984, now will try to make the
US team for the Sydney Games of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had planned to run Twin Cities in early October, but soccer
rules in our family,'' said the mother of two. ``By default I ended
up here in New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
