<SLUG> BC-SKATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKATING WORLD IS JUMPING 
</HEADLINE>
 AMERICA-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Elvis Stojko didn't have to do the quad here. Not in
October. Not in his first competition since the Olympics. Not with
a finicky groin. But he did. ``You're eventually going to have to
do it,'' he figured.
</P>
<P>
   A new quadrennium may have just begun, but figure skating
already has upped the ante. The International Skating Union has
said that the men may do a quadruple jump instead of a triple jump
in the short program. But the skaters understand that ``may'' soon
will mean ``must''. It will not be an option, but an obligation.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the competitive ante stayed the same. Nobody did a
triple jump until Dick Button in 1952. It was another 36 years
before Kurt Browning did the first quad. ``Now, everybody is trying
to make quads,'' said Alexei Yagudin, the Russian world champ,
after he'd outskated a brutal field at Skate America on Saturday.
``The next Olympics, the winner will make all triples and two
quads.''
</P>
<P>
   Yagudin, who landed nine triples (one more than allowed) to beat
Michael Weiss, Alexei Urmanov, and Stojko here, didn't try a quad
but he will at the European championships because he knows his top
rivals will.
</P>
<P>
   The ``optional'' quad was one of a bundle of rules changes that
took effect at Skate America, the opener of the Grand Prix season.
Pairs now must perform a throw jump in the short program, which
made for a number of unsightly sprawls here last week. And the free
dance now requires certain lifts, spins, ``twizzle'' turns, and
step sequences with specific markdowns. Just like real figure
skating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very good that we are changing,'' said France's Gwendal
Peizerat, who won the dance with partner Marina Anissina. ``We
could have gone 20 years with no changes and waited for the sport
to die. This will make it more objective in the judgment and more
interesting to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   It also will raise the stakes for the dancers, too many of whom
seem to confuse their event with a Vegas floor show. Thus is
skating evolving, and those who want to make it to Olympus in 2002
are brushing up on their Darwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young skaters, younger than me, are going to have the quad
this season,'' said Yagudin, who at 18 is the youngest world
titleist in 35 years. ``They will change the level. Everyone will
try one quad in the short program to have two quads in the long
program.''
</P>
<P>
   If you can't do the quad, you won't ever be a contender again.
That's the sobering reality for Nagano gold medalist Ilya Kulik and
former world champ Todd Eldredge, who both are sitting out the
Olympic-eligible season in what ISU president Ottavio Cinquanta
calls ``active rest''. If and when they return, they may find the
bar is beyond their leap.
</P>
<P>
   And aging ladies like Elena Butyrskaya and Nicole Bobek, who
looked woefully unprepared here last weekend, may find themselves
gobbled up by middle-schoolers they've never heard of before they
ever get to Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, my skating was not at my best,'' conceded the
26-year-old Butyrskaya, who won the women's title despite falling
on her face and her bottom and landing only three clean triples.
</P>
<P>
   There are juniors who routinely nail half a dozen triples now
and fool around with the quad for fun. Three triples these days get
you an understudy's job for Nutcracker on Ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to compete at a high level,'' said Canada's
Kris Wirtz, who won the pairs silver here with Kristy Sargeant,
``you need to have all the goods all the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 0134EST &QL; 
