<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8428 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     11-02 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN WELL-RECEIVED FOR PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; INDIANAPOLIS _ Saturday night Bruce Armstrong and Ben Coates
were holding their weekly NFL Film Festival in a hotel room at the
Omni when they saw the defense of the Indianapolis Colts allow some
unknown tight end to run wide open down the seam for a long
completion. Coates watched this act in disgust, mumbling as his
counterpart ran free on film how defenses don't give him those
opportunities anymore.
</P>
<P>
   To that, Armstrong had a counterpoint that 16 hours later would
make him appear to be the NFL's Nostradamus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reminded Ben he had some of his biggest games against the
Colts,'' Armstrong said a half-hour after Coates had another one of
them Sunday in the Patriots' 21-16 victory at the RCA Dome. ``They
just refuse to cover him. I told him that (Saturday) night, and he
finally said, `Yeah. Maybe they'll leave me open.'''
</P>
<P>
   Which they did, at least in the language of those who know Ben
Coates best.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's single-covered, he's open,'' Patriots quarterback Drew
Bledsoe remarked after throwing 10 of his 22 completions to Coates
for 109 yards and a touchdown. It was Coates's fourth double-digit
reception game and ninth 100-plus-yard game of his career. Nearly
half of those games have come against a stubborn Colts defense that
refuses to accept the simple fact that to challenge the four-time
Pro Bowl tight end with single coverage is to ensure great damage
to yourself before the day is out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't double-team me, I'm open,'' Coates said, smiling
between bites of a hot dog. ``I'm like a hungry child. You start
feeding me and I want to keep on eating.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday Coates had a 10-course meal of prime horse meat. At
various times he devoured free safety Jason Belser, cornerbacks
Jeff Burris and Monty Montgomery, outside linebackers Andre Royal
and Anthony Jordan, middle linebacker Michael Barber, and strong
safety Robert Blackmon. This continued until Coates and Bledsoe
engaged in a game of pitch-and-catch so embarassingly obvious that
even the Colts finally had to concede that reinforcements would be
necessary to keep New England's massive tight end in check.
</P>
<P>
   But before the Colts finally got around to that, Coates caught
six passes in one third-quarter drive in which he covered a total
of 68 yards worth of RCA Dome real estate before a Bledsoe pass
intended for Henry Ellard was intercepted by Blackmon at the Colts'
5. Thereafter, the Colts got the message, which meant Coates got
additional attention and no more receptions, but by that point he
had made clear once again why he has made those four straight
all-expenses-paid trips to Honolulu the first week of February for
the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best,'' Bledsoe said. ``Until somebody else comes
along or his skills diminish significantly, Ben's the best. I was
surprised when they continued singling him up, because then it's
just like playing catch. I thought they'd do more to try and take
him away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be some people who want to think Ben has slipped
because his numbers are down (from the years when he caught a
record 96 and then 84 passes at a time when New England's offense
had Coates, Bledsoe, and the punter). That's wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has he lost a step? Maybe he has, but he could lose a step or
two and he's still the best. What he does is not just based on his
being faster than his man or bigger than his man. It's based on
knowing how to get open. As his skills diminish, he'll still be
effective because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Coates's skills were on full display as he repeatedly
worked his way free against any player the Colts put on him. Early
in the first quarter, for example, he shook loose in the back of
the end zone to catch a 2-yard scoring pass behind the defense.
</P>
<P>
   That was not something terribly easy to do considering that the
play had started at the 2-yard line but in a span of 10 yards he
had done it, making the score 7-0. New England never trailed
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of catch Coates had failed to make a week
earlier against Miami, a catch that could have beaten the Dolphins.
Coates thought about that one pass that slipped off his fingertips
all week and then did something about it first chance he got this
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all our injuries, somebody had to step up and make some
plays,'' Coates said. ``I took it upon myself to do that. I'm the
oldest veteran receiver we have, so I had to do something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what the Colts would do about covering me, but
every time it seemed I was the primary receiver I seemed to be
singled, so Drew threw it to me. I hoped to hell he would. When a
guy is going to you every down, you want the ball. I want it in
these kind of situations. I thrive on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Colts died on that. Because of their stubbornness
and Coates's skills, New England's tight end accounted for more
than a third of Bledsoe's 306 passing yards and provided the safety
net his team seemed to need to win a game that turned out to be far
more of a struggle than it should have been.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game the Patriots had to win just to keep themselves
out of dire straits in the AFC East. They are now bunched up with
Buffalo, Miami, and the Jets in the kind of cluster that resembles
the coverages Coates sees more often, but at least they had
retained reasonable control of their own destiny because one game
with Miami and New York remain, as do two with Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   When those games come, Ben Coates can rest assured of one thing:
He will not again be allowed to run free up the seam of a defense
hardheadedly insisting on covering him one-on-one very often.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't get those deep seam routes against Cover-2 zones
very often anymore because the linebackers are playing with more
depth now and defenses are more aware of him in the middle,''
Bledsoe explained. ``If they'd forgotten about what happens if they
aren't, I guess he reminded them today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
