<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-SIMMONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMMONS CATCHING ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Now no one may be left from the Patriots' feared
receiving corps of a month ago, as the last and noblest of them
all, Shawn Jefferson, sat by his locker after Sunday's win over the
Colts and tried to speak without pain. But his ribs were very sore.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jefferson's eyes lit up and the words kept coming out as
the veteran spoke of rookie Tony Simmons, who just may have had a
breakthrough game against Indianapolis. Simmons caught four passes
for 109 yards, including a 63-yarder for what turned out to be the
deciding touchdown a minute into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means our receiving corps has taken a big step forward,''
said Jefferson of the depleted crew that has lost Terry Glenn, Troy
Brown, and Vincent Brisby in the last three weeks. ``I kind of knew
that Tony would be all right after that last game in Miami when he
caught that big pass. I went up to Tony before this one and I told
him, `Just concentrate on the ball.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard. Simmons was hyper and excited to be starting,
especially since he was playing only three hours from his home in
Chicago and his brother Lawson had tooled down Interstate 65 from
Chicago City to the RCA Dome. ``Tony was so excited before the
game,'' said Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Simmons was excited, Jefferson went on, ``You could
tell from his demeanor he was going to play well. He wasn't making
any mistakes in practice all week and he was poised during the
game. And then he caught a big touchdown for us when we really
needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the touchdown, the first of Simmons's career. He scooted
past defensive back Jeff Burris, even though it seemed Simmons
wasn't running that fast. ``Oh, I don't know what gear I was in,''
said Simmons. ``Once I'm in front of a guy, I just try to stay in
front of him. I just run to make sure I stay in front.''
</P>
<P>
   Which Simmons did, even though Burris was called for
interference on the play, and the rookie hauled in the pass from
Drew Bledsoe, completing the 63-yard play. ``Tony has the speed and
can run with the best of them,'' said Bledsoe. ``But he also has
strong hands and is an excellent talent.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago in Miami, Simmons had learned that pro football ``is
a very fast game,'' but his first pro appearance also made him
realize ``there's nothing to be scared of. If they hit you, they
hit you.''
</P>
<P>
   But Simmons was too fast to be hit on the TD pass, and once he
crossed the goal line he made sure to keep a firm grasp on the
ball. ``I don't spike the ball. I never spike the ball,'' he said.
``I still got this little thing from college _ I just do my little
high-knee action _ and that's it, it's all over. Then I always go
back to the team, because I wouldn't have got them without them
blocking and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons sat by his locker, his eyes still bright enough to light
the entire RCA Dome by themselves. If he was hyper before the game,
he was even more hyper as he recalled every detail of the TD and
four catches for 109 yards, not to mention drawing another
interference call on Burris that set up the Patriots with a
first-and-goal in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe tried a fade to Simmons on a second-and-8 from the
Colts' 24, but ``Burris made a good play on me,'' recalled the
rookie. ``He jumped for the ball and I tried to tap the ball up
higher, back to myself, so I could re-catch it. He was trying to
catch it, and I was trying to make sure he didn't catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   If it seemed that Simmons might have been able to catch that
fade for a TD, it made no difference as Bledsoe came back to
Simmons on the next play, hitting the rookie for a 12-yard gain on
a slant pass. ``That made me feel good,'' said Simmons, ``that Drew
had confidence in me to come right back to me. He knows that I can
make plays. I know I can make plays.'' Then came the play Burris
was penalized on.
</P>
<P>
   Speed and size are his assets, said Simmons, ``because I know I
can catch the ball. I wouldn't have made it to the NFL if I
couldn't catch the ball. I'm 6-1 and 205 pounds and most receivers
are under 6 feet, but I know I can catch the ball. What I'm most
concerned about is my route-running, because I know I can catch the
ball. And now that we have Henry Ellard, I can pick his brain about
running routes.''
</P>
<P>
   The rookie also credited Patriots defensive back Ty Law for a
chunk of his development as a receiver. He and Law face each other
in practice, ``and Ty has taught me a lot,'' said Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Tony, we battle every day,'' said Law. ``I try to help
him as much as I can. If he wants to give me credit (for his
development), fine, but if not, I just want him to keep on doing
what he's doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
