<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTE PREY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The countdown is T-minus 126 minutes, 12
seconds and counting for the Kings' offense _ which wants to blast
off, but has been in a season-long holding pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were shut out for the third time in four games on
Sunday evening when the Phoenix Coyotes defeated them 3-0 before
l2,073 at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are lacking confidence,'' said winger Craig Johnson, one of
several Kings to have good chances turned aside by Phoenix goalie
Nikolai Khabibulin. ``We have to get some ugly goals. With ugly
goals comes confidence and with confidence comes more goals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings outshot Phoenix 31-28 for the game and 13-4 in the
final period. Rob Blake had nine shots and Luc Robitaille had six,
but none went in and Los Angeles fell to 4-5-2.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille said the team, which has scored three or more goals
only three times this season, is not discouraged but is
disappointed in its performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've maybe played two or three really good games since the
beginning of the year,'' said Robitaille. ``We have to show
desperation like we showed in the third period tonight. That's the
only way to win in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles beat New Jersey 4-0 last Wednesday in the final game
of a five-game road trip, but Blake admitted that game might have
been misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a couple of breaks in New Jersey,'' he said. ``We
played well in Carolina, but we haven't been too offensive-minded
this year. You can't be afraid to make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Kings were busy missing the net or firing shots into
Khabibulin's midsection, the Coyotes made just enough plays to
improve to 5-2-1.
</P>
<P>
   They got a goal from Jyrki Lumme early in the first, one from
former King Rick Tocchet early in the second and another from
Jeremy Roenick early in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times we looked a little tentative,'' said Kings coach
Larry Robinson. ``But you have to remember that's a damn good club
over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Kings managed their first shot on goal _ 5 1/2
minutes into the the first period _ the Coyotes had already taken a
1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles had knocked the puck off Keith Tkachuk's stick, but
failed to clear. Lumme got a shot from the left circle that Kings
goalie Manny Legace stopped, but the Phoenix defenseman skated
behind the net and fired home the rebound from a steep angle 3:49
into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Legace, who came into the game with a 1.19 goals-against average
and a brilliant save percentage of .965, played another solid game.
He was beaten over the right shoulder on Tocchet's shot at 1:29 of
the second, and Roenick scored on a rebound at 2:07 of the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy I feel disappointed for is Manny Legace,'' said
Johnson of the rookie goalie, who has only one win despite allowing
only nine goals in seven games since groin injuries sidelined Jamie
Storr and Stephane Fiset . ``He has played unbelievable and I feel
like we've let him down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' power play was shutout once again, going 0-of-6
despite generating more pressure than they have in recent games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We crowded the net, went for rebounds, we were hitting skates,
sticks, but the puck went the wrong way,'' said Robitaille of a Los
Angeles power play that has generated just four goals all season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
