<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAY, PATRIOT MATES MOLDING DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ On one pass in the first half, when Patriots
cornerback Ty Law gave Colts receiver Marvin Harrison a 7-yard
cushion and he caught an easy pass from Peyton Manning, one Patriot
did not take it quietly. He was in Law's face, giving Law a piece
of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Another time in that first quarter, when Indianapolis running
back Lamont Warren escaped Patriots linebackers, especially Ted
Johnson, and caught a 4-yard TD pass, one Patriot most definitely
did not take it quietly. He was in the face of the linebackers,
giving them a piece of his mind both on the field and later on the
sideline for a blown coverage.
</P>
<P>
   That Patriot was Willie Clay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little hot,'' Clay acknowledged. ``That's because we
weren't playing the way we're capable of playing. That bothered me.
It always bothers you. That's just the way it was early. We just
weren't playing the way we're capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if New England's other safety, Lawyer Milloy,
intercepted two of Manning's passes, not to mention led the team
with 10 tackles, Clay was the soul of a defense that was hard and
soft, stingy and giving, tough and porous, all in the same game.
</P>
<P>
   Milloy would not talk to the media after Sunday's win over the
Colts (``Go talk to the other guys''), even though he did talk to
the media after a poor, for him, performance last week in Miami.
Milloy played much better Sunday and made the two crucial
interceptions late in the fourth quarter when the Colts were
threatening to steal a game the Patriots should have ended some 10
minutes earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ended up doing a pretty good job,'' said Clay, ``even
though at the end they started pricking us a little. But it was a
win, and we needed a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, though, Manning looked twice _ or maybe 10 times _ as
good as the frightened rookie quarterback who had been so lost when
the Patriots beat the Colts in Foxborough in September. Manning had
presence in that first half, he had poise, and he also had some
cooperation from a far-from-robust Patriot defense.
</P>
<P>
   Clay, though, was determined not to let the New England defense
soft-shoe into oblivion in that first half. He got into Law's face
when Harrison had wide separation and an easy catch, said Clay,
``because you got to try and get into people's heads. I was trying
to make like a coach on the field a little bit, maybe trying to do
what a coach would have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, on Warren's TD catch, Clay was upset ``at the coverage
underneath by the 'backers; that's because we made those guys
(Manning and Warren) look even better than they are.''
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, the defense once again did what it usually
does against Marshall Faulk _ hold him to few yards on the ground.
Faulk picked up 22 yards on 11 carries, and the Colts could gain
only 32 yards on 14 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk, though, did catch nine passes for 119 yards, slipping out
of the backfield as the defense had trouble tackling. On more than
a few plays, for instance, Indianapolis receivers would catch short
passes that should have gone for gains of only 4 or 5 yards, but
the receivers would stop on a dime, the defenders would go flying
past, and the 5-yard gain would turn into a 15-yard gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tackling was our downfall,'' said coach Pete Carroll. ``They
had a lot of small passes and large runs after the catch. Credit a
lot of that to single coverage, but we did miss some tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Patriots have completed their usual and dismal
Death March through October, a win to open November ``was big, very
big for us,'' said Clay. ``We needed this; now we have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, though, the defense is looking to recapture that
chemistry and attitude that propelled it to such a stout
performance last November and December. It has been lacking so far
_ the attitude that nobody can score on it _ but there is one
Patriot who will be sure to speak his mind when he sees any slack:
Willie Clay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard to stop other teams in this league,'' said Clay.
``But we got a good defense here. People sometimes talk about our
defense, but we have a really good defense. We got a lot of younger
guys playing, and those guys are doing a lot of good things, but
it's tough to come out and stop other teams completely. (Sunday) we
made plays when we had to make them.''
</P>
<P>
   And, said Clay, ``That's what won the game. That's what we got
to do all the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
