<HEADLINE>
BODGER OUT WITH BROKEN HAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Kings' injury woes continued
Sunday when veteran defenseman Doug Bodger suffered a fractured
left hand before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to know how it happened,'' Kings coach Larry
Robinson said. ``He stepped on a puck in warmups and fell
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodger played two shifts in the first period, but missed the
rest of the game and is expected to be out 4-6 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are already missing goalies Stephane Fiset (left groin
strain) and Jamie Storr (right groin strain), center Jozef Stumpel
(hip flexor, abdominal strain) and Ian Laperriere (partial torn ACL
in his left knee).
</P>
<P>
   __ No surgery required: Laperriere, who is getting close to
returning, said he decided against season-ending surgery because
``I have no pain and I feel strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for his reckless style of play, Laperriere said he won't
change upon his return.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I play I won't think about that (getting hurt again), he
said. ``If I do I'll get hurt for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might as well give it a try, if I hurt my knee again, see
you next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel said he is getting better and hopes to start skating
later this week. But the Kings' leading scorer last year said he's
probably ``a couple weeks away (from playing).''
</P>
<P>
   __ Playing time: After being scratched in eight of the season's
first 10 games, defenseman Gary Galley was in the lineup Sunday and
played nearly 22 minutes since the Kings had only five defensemen
after Bodger was forced to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Galley replaced Philippe Boucher, who was scratched for the
first time this season. Sandy Moger was the Kings' other healthy
scratch.
</P>
<P>
   __ Where have they gone?: Glenn Murray, Vladimir Tsyplakov and
Craig Johnson all continue to struggle after having career seasons
a year ago. The three players, who combined for 64 goals and 150
points in 1997-98, have combined for four goals and five points
this season.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Steve Duchesne has just one goal in 11 games after
finishing fourth in scoring among NHL defensemen (56 points) last
season with the St. Louis Blues.
</P>
<P>
   __ Still going: The Kings' penalty killing continues to sparkle.
Los Angeles, ranked No. 1 in the NHL, killed off four more
penalties to extend its streak to 43. The team has given up only
one power play goal this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 0141EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
