<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC FEELING PUNCHY 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Boston College's football season has been reduced to one
objective: Win November. After a 3-0 start in September, the Eagles
went 0-for-October for the second year in a row and now have three
games in which to redeem themselves, beginning with Saturday's home
finale against Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   But, following BC's fifth consecutive loss of the season, 35-17
against the 25th-ranked Miami Hurricanes at the Orange Bowl
Saturday night, no one in the BC locker room seemed too eager to
face the Fighting Irish.
</P>
<P>
   Would the game serve as a rallying point for the Eagles?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really tough to say,'' said quarterback Scott Mutryn, who
will be among 14 seniors who will take their final Alumni Stadium
bow Saturday. ``We were so focused on Miami that you don't think
ahead. Right now, this game's over and we've got to treat it like
that and we've got to be able to come back and watch the film and
get ready for Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to start righting this ship,'' Mutryn added.
``Right now, it's just really kind of swaying in the wind, and we
just need a stabilizing force to get it calmed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles found no safe harbor in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The manner in which their badly listing vessel went under in the
face of the Hurricanes' first-quarter gale of 21 unanswered points
no doubt resembled any of the greater maritime disasters. Miami
junior running back Edgerrin James opened the floodgates for the
'Canes when he scored on runs of 2 and 1 yards to give Miami an
early 14-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Miami quarterback Scott Covington, who completed 17 of 27 passes
for 224 yards by finding seven receivers, made it 21-0 on a 10-yard
pass to Daryl Jones with 1:56 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we came out flat in the first quarter,'' said freshman
linebacker Andy Romanowsky, who made his first career start in
place of injured sixth-year man Brian Maye (pulled right groin).
``If we got off to a better start, it might've been a different
ballgame, but it definitely stunned us.''
</P>
<P>
   James, who rushed for a career-high and conference-record 271
yards in Miami's 45-44 victory in double overtime last year at BC,
proved the real stunner when he carried 31 times for a season-high
182 yards. James overshadowed BC senior running back Mike Cloud,
who was limited to a season-low 75 yards on 20 carries, well below
the league-leading average (164.6 yards) he brought into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they kept the ball away from us,'' BC coach Tom O'Brien
said. ``So if you don't have the ball, it's tough to get the ball
to Mike Cloud. When you're behind, 21-0, it's tough to run the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last two games, it's been either feast or famine for BC's
offense. In last week's stinging 32-31 loss against Navy, the
Eagles rolled up 610 yards of total offense. Saturday night, BC
managed just 12 plays for 42 yards during Miami's first-quarter
flurry.
</P>
<P>
   All of which prompted the question: Is it time to change
helmsmen?
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was intent on staying the course with Mutryn, who
was sacked four times and completed 11 of 17 attempts for 106 yards
and a 20-yard TD to Anthony DiCosmo, O'Brien said, ``Absolutely.
There's going to be no changes. You guys always want to change
quarterbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as O'Brien is concerned, Mutryn is not the problem. ``We
didn't get control of the line of scrimmage and they had control of
the line of scrimmage,'' said the coach. ``And if you can't control
the line of scrimmage, then it's tough to run the ball, and that's
what we do best. Mutryn was running for his life half the night
back there.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win a game like this,'' he added, ``we have to hold onto
the ball like Miami did, we have to get our defense off the field,
and we have to score points.''
</P>
<P>
   If BC is unable to accomplish those objectives, then November
will be anything but smooth sailing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 0143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
