<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEBRASKA STREAK TORN ASUNDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ It was quite a run. Two and a half national
championships. Three unbeaten seasons, a field goal from a fourth
unbeaten year and national title. Three losses in five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But now that is all over for the Nebraska Cornhuskers.
Saturday's 20-16 loss to Texas took care of that. Now the Huskers
must play the role of spoiler. Losing twice in a season before
Thanksgiving will change the role of a team with high ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Nebraska lose Saturday, it lost at home, ending a
47-game winning streak in Lincoln that dated back to 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to have a streak come to an end and be a part of
it coming to an end,'' said first-year coach  &UR; Frank Solich &LR; . ``It's
been a great streak, and we don't have any choice but to come back
and get rolling again.''
</P>
<P>
   Dynasties are hard to build these days in college football. But
the Huskers were unquestionably the team of the '90s, with all due
respect to Florida State. Even with two losses this season _ and
the possibility of more to come _ Nebraska has lost only 13 games
in the past nine years. You do the math and figure out how dominant
the Huskers have been, a fact that was underscored again Sunday
when they dropped out of the Associated Press Top 10 for the first
time since 1992 (they slipped to No. 14).
</P>
<P>
   And give credit to the Nebraska fans. When it was apparent that
Texas had ended the streak, the fans in Lincoln gave the Longhorns
and running back  &UR; Ricky Williams  &LR; an ovation as they walked off the
field.
</P>
<P>
   With 150 yards Saturday, Williams is the clear front-runner in
the Heisman Trophy race.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When is a win a loss? When you are UCLA and you go all out to
beat a mediocre Stanford team. For that come-from-behind triumph,
the Bruins, who had been ranked No. 1 in the first Bowl
Championship Series rankings released last week, took a big hit in
the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins dropped from No. 2 to No. 3 in the writers' poll, and
from No. 2 to No. 4 in the coaches' poll. What that all means when
the latest BCS rankings are released Monday is that UCLA probably
will drop to third, which means they would not make the Fiesta Bowl
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   The only people happy with that will be the Rose Bowl people,
who now can dream of unbeaten UCLA vs. once-beaten Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nice to see Michigan's offense is back in gear. Minus-23 yards
against Minnesota in a 15-10 win in which a safety is a big play?
What is that all about? With games coming against once-beaten Penn
State, unbeaten Wisconsin, and unbeaten Ohio State, this still
could be a fall of discontent for the Wolverines ... Oregon State
was hoping to end its streak of 27 consecutive non-winning seasons.
But after Saturday's 20-19 loss to California, it doesn't look like
it's going to happen. With a 4-5 record, the Beavers have two games
left, with UCLA and Oregon ... If UCLA does fall out of the Fiesta
Bowl and into the Rose, Arizona could feel the pain more than
anyone. The Wildcats very well could go 10-1 and would have a
chance at a Rose Bowl berth (they're the only Pac-10 team never to
have played in the game). But if UCLA goes to the Rose, Arizona
would get squeezed into a game like the Holiday Bowl ... Just a
guess, but Florida State might be playing the best of any team in
the country right now. The Seminoles have gotten over their early
offensive slump, and quarterback  &UR; Chris Weinke &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has not
thrown an interception since he tossed six in a September loss to
North Carolina State, has been superb. But as is generally the case
with the Seminoles, who seem to stumble once a season, they are
going to need some help to get to the Fiesta Bowl ... Air Force is
the only team in Division 1-A to score at least 30 points in every
game it has played this season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's how crazy the BCS rankings are. Since strength of
schedule, the records of your opponents, and the record of your
opponents' opponents are calculated, Kansas State was hurt by
Nebraska's loss to Texas. How so? Well, the Huskers' loss was their
second of the season, and as an opponent of Kansas State (in two
weeks), every loss hurts. So even if the Wildcats beat the Huskers
for the first time in 30 years, the win will not mean as much since
Nebraska would add another loss ... Despite the signs of progress
made by Boston College in two years under  &UR; Tom O'Brien &LR; , &UR;  &LR; going
0-for-October for two straight seasons is not the way to rebuild
the program. Cheer up, Eagle fans. Northeastern is on the schedule
next Oct. 2 ... Ohio State quarterback  &UR; Joe Germaine  &LR; continues to
make a belated run at the Heisman. Germaine completed 31 of 45
passes for 351 yards and three TDs in Ohio State's rout of Indiana
Saturday. It was Germaine's fourth consecutive 300-yard passing day
... Georgia beat itself as much as Florida beat the Bulldogs.
Georgia was inside the Florida 30 four times in the final three
quarters and came away with no points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas may be 7-0, but the Hogs are doing it the hard way.
They've had to come from behind in three of their four Southeastern
Conference games this season. The Hogs have been impressive in the
second half, outscoring their opponents, 137-33 ... Oregon could be
in trouble. The Ducks were crushed by Arizona and are down to their
fourth-string running back because of injuries ... They're cheering
at Division 2 Cheyney State. Cheyney ended a 52-game winless streak
and a 39-game losing streak by crushing Mansfield, 40-13 ... Kansas
had a total of 44 yards in 45 plays in its 54-6 loss to Kansas
State, the lowest in school history ... You've got to love Virginia
quarterback  &UR; Aaron Brooks's  &LR; comments after the Cavaliers crushed
Wake Forest, 38-17. ``We just played Virginia football and they
played Wake Forest football,'' said Brooks. ``And that's saying
whatever it's saying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
