<SLUG> BC-BKW-WMNBB-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATADORS STAY LOYAL TO COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They are confused and emotionally drained, but
members of Cal State Northridge's women's basketball team remain
loyal and supportive of embattled coach Michael Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   That was the message juniors Viveca Lof and Jamilah Jones
delivered prior to practice Sunday evening, as they spoke publicly
for the first time since Abraham was arrested last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did tell us that it's not true, and I believe him,'' Jones
said. ``He said some of the things he's done in the past caught up,
but never in his past has he sold drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a death in the family. Like we lost an intricate
part of our family.''
</P>
<P>
   Abraham was arrested Tuesday after practice and indicted for
possession and conspiracy to distribute crack cocaine, FBI
officials said. Abraham is on paid administrative leave from the
school, pending resolution of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know him as a good person. He's always been good to us,''
Lof said. ``We've always been welcomed to his house and he's always
been there for us, so we don't have a reason not to believe him.
Or, at least, I don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just coaching, it's personal. It's happened to a
friend of ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Lof said team members have visited Abraham and his
family at his Northridge home.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham hasn't returned phone calls since his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wonder, but we just see the coach Mike that we know,'' Lof
said. ``I think we're finally to the stage of where we accept it
and can move on. It kind of sunk in because it was unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the day after Abraham's arrest was announced, the
women's team was picked to finish second in the preseason Big Sky
polls. Much of that had to do with Abraham, who's upgraded CSUN's
talent markedly during his first three years at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Before the arrest he said he expected the Matadors ``to be one
of the top three teams in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my third year and he's instilled a lot in us,'' Jones
said. ``He wants us to become a fighter, wants us to overcome
adversity. He doesn't want this incident to hinder us.''
</P>
<P>
   Associate athletic director Judy Brame has taken over the
head-coaching duties in Abraham's absence. At first, that move
bothered many of the players, who wanted assistants Karon Howell,
Frozena Jerro and Tara Harrington to run the team, Jones said. But
that's changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, when you first hear it, you just want to
work with what you have,'' Jones said. ``You don't want anybody
else to come in. We felt that we should have a say in it, but when
we found out how Judy really was on the court, it's been fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably all thought she was going to come in and try to
take over and run things, but that's not how she's doing things.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet to be seen is what happens to the players, particularly
those from overseas. Lof is from Sweden, Lynda Amari is French,
Daphne Verrept is from Belgium and Neda Milic hails from Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   While the other players have family in the states, Jones said
most of the players came to CSUN because of Abraham's dynamic
personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Athletic director) Paul Bubb said he asks every athlete when
they come in, `If something happened with your program, would you
still like it that you're at Northridge?' '' Jones said. ``But
that's not most of our cases. Most of us have come here because of
coach Mike, or because of the players that were here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been really tough on Neda.''
</P>
<P>
   The players will get to focus on something else when they play
an exhibition game Sunday. The regular season begins Nov. 14
against Oakland University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
