<HEADER>
A8468 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWK-RAIDERS-S     11-02 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWK-RAIDERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIDERS CAPITALIZE ON SEAHAWK TURNOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Warren Moon returned to the Seahawks' starting lineup
Sunday night. The rest of the offense continued to be AWOL.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks let a must-win game against the Oakland Raiders
slip through fumbling fingers 31-18 in a nationally televised and
sold-out game at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Moon, playing for the first time in three weeks because of two
cracked ribs, completed 29 of 39 passes for a season-best 275 yards
_ including a club-record 17 straight completions at one point. But
once again, the offense did not produce enough points to allow the
Seahawks to win a game they could not afford to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating,'' Moon said. ``You want to dominate at
home. We're not doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard-to-swallow loss, their fourth in the past five games,
left the Seahawks at 4-4. The Raiders improved to 6-2 and are one
of eight teams in the AFC with a better record than the struggling
Seahawks entering the second half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty talented, but we're not beating teams with a
winning record,'' linebacker Chad Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fact. The Seahawks four victories have come against teams
that are a combined 9-22. Their four losses have come to teams that
are 23-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some teams know how to win,'' Brown said. ``We know how to
lose to winning teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks lost this one because they turned the ball over
five times. One of Moon's rare incompletions was intercepted and
returned 74 yards for a TD by Raiders safety Albert Lewis. There
also were four lost fumbles _ three in the final 17 minutes to set
up a field goal and a TD by the Raiders after the Seahawks had cut
the lead to 21-18.
</P>
<P>
   The killer came with 11:32 left game when Raiders linebacker
Mike Morton knocked the ball from Ronnie Harris, who was returning
his first punt of the season. Kenny Shedd recovered at the Seattle
1-yard line to set up Oakland's final TD.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing about catching punts is catching the punt.
It's something I've always been pretty good at,'' said Harris, who
had a fumbled punt and a fumbled kickoff returned for TDs last
season. ``Letting your teammates down is probably the hardest part
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, the score set up by Harris' fumble came with an odd
twist in a game that was filled with strange plays. Raiders rookie
fullback Jon Ritchie fumbled on his second-down carry, but guard
Darryl Ashmore recovered the ball and scored to push the Raiders
lead to 31-18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the running back get hit and the ball came out,'' said
Ashmore, who was starting for the injured Derrick Graham. ``It was
lying on about the half-yard line. Then it was lying on Derek
Brown's lap. I picked it up and fell into the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding injury to insult, the Seahawks played most of the game
with left guard Pete Kendall at center. The switch was necessary
after starter Kevin Glover aggravated a pinched nerve in his back
on the game's first series.
</P>
<P>
   Glover was originally hurt last week in practice. Kendall
replaced Glover because backup center Chris Gray was inactive after
receiving a concussion in last week's win at San Diego, and because
rookie Jason McEndoo's only series ended when he made an errant
shotgun snap that Moon fumbled. McEndoo was signed off the practice
squad Friday because of the loss of Gray and the uncertainty over
Glover's status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously that hurt us,'' coach Dennis Erickson said of the
revolving door that the center position became. ``But that's just
an excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Raiders quarterback Donald Hollas, making his third start in
place of the injured Jeff George, needed no excuse. He completed 12
of 22 passes for 237 yards and threw TD passes to Tim Brown and
Ricky Dudley. Hollas was especially effective on third downs,
completing 5 of 7 for 121 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The layoff seemed to rejuvenate Moon, who completed each of his
16 passes in the first half to break the club record of 15 in a row
set by Jim Zorn in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Moon hit his first two passes _ a 15-yarder to Mike Pritchard
and a 25-yarder to tight end Christian Fauria _ before the
game-opening drive stalled and the Seahawks settled for a 38-yard
field goal from Todd Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Moon's hot hand, the Seahawks could muster just two TDs
_ his 1-yard pass to tight end Carlester Crumpler and a 1-yard run
by Ricky Watters on fourth-and-goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders' No. 1-ranked defense held Watters to 54 yards on 18
carries and the longest of Joey Galloway's five catches was an
8-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   Turnovers, however, were the real problem _ a bigger one than
anything the Raiders presented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we lose a game it's the turnovers that are the
problem,'' Fauria said. ``It causes problems. It was tight for a
while even with all the turnovers. But you get three or four and
that kills you.''
</P>
<P>
   The turnovers also wasted another good effort by Seattle's
defense. Despite playing without linebacker Darrin Smith, their
second-leading tackler who was sidelined with a sprained ankle, the
Seahawks held the Raiders' Napoleon Kaufman to 56 yards on 22
carries _ a 2.5-yard average, 2 yards under his season average.
</P>
<P>
   Things will get no easier for the Seahawks. They host the Kansas
City Chiefs this week, a team that has beaten them eight straight
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously bad,'' linebacker Dean Wells said. ``We know we
need 10 wins to get to the playoffs, so any time you lose at home
to an AFC opponent, it is tough to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially when you're gagging on your own turnovers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 0239EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
