<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8470 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      11-02 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWKS TAKE A HIKE WITH POOR SNAPPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The trouble was not in the throwing of strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawk quarterback Warren Moon Sunday night was a regular Roger
Clemens with the high heat, completing his first 17 passes and
generally leaving the well-regarded defense of the Oakland Raiders
dragging lumber back to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble was getting the ball back to the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The most elemental function in football, the center snap, became
an adventure that was at times no less formidable than Mount
Everest.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of thing just doesn't happen to playoff-quality teams.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, we give you the Seahawks, 4-4 at midseason, 1-3 in the AFC
West, and circling the drain.
</P>
<P>
   They need to win six of their remaining eight games to make the
playoffs and save the jobs of the coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Not with this line.
</P>
<P>
   Not with this scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Not with these mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   There are no must-wins yet, of course, but after scuffing,
31-18, an opportunity at home on national TV against the worst 5-2
team in NFL history, led by one-time kitty-furniture maker Donald
Hollas, here was coach Dennis Erickson's assessment of Sunday's
Kingdome game against Kansas City:
</P>
<P>
   ``Double do-or-die.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear exactly what that means, but it sounds important.
</P>
<P>
   Probably important enough to figure out this bad business
between the legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to make excuses, but particularly on game day, it
makes it harder,'' said Erickson of the offensive-line shuffle that
created two drive-killing muffed exchanges in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The blown snaps were only part of the five turnovers that
created the Seahawks' ghastliest loss of the season. But when the
game plan calls for more pitches than the Mariner bullpen,
interceptions are inevitable. Mistakes elsewhere can't be indulged.
</P>
<P>
   When veteran starting center Kevin Glover went down with a
pinched nerve in his back early in the first quarter, the Seahawks
on the sidelines could have been knocked over by a skinny forearm
from Raider owner Al Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The potential swoon was due to the fact that there was no
adequate backup. Regular second-stringer Chris  &UR; rr &LR; Gray was out
with a concussion from last week. The Seahawks were left with Jason
McEndoo, a rookie seventh-round draft pick from Washington State
who was signed off the practice squad only Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, that was the first time I'd played center since
high school,'' McEndoo said. ``On Friday, I had a lot of snaps,
watched film and took some notes.''
</P>
<P>
   Those notes undoubtedly intimidated the heck out of Raider
defensive tackles Russell Maryland and Darrell Russell.
</P>
<P>
   After seven plays, including a shotgun snap that escaped Moon
and killed a drive, the Seahawks opted to move over Pete Kendall
from left guard.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was ... well, let him tell you:
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I snapped was with two hands as a 9-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that wealth of experience, Kendall acquitted himself
reasonably well for the rest of the game, though he, too, messed up
a snap that meant two of the Seahawks' first four possessions were
befouled by the offensive game's starting point.
</P>
<P>
   That is a coaching blunder, pure and simple. To be caught with
so little experience at so vital a position is an oversight that
causes regimes to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Said Moon: ``I'd never worked with either of those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   So the rest of Moon's spectacular deeds for the night were
rendered almost moot. When Kendall's guard spot was filled by
seldom-used Andrew Greene, the Seahawks were a calliope short of a
full circus.
</P>
<P>
   Just mediocre when everyone was healthy, the now-makeshift line
was borderline helpless to sustain a game-long attack against the
No. 1-rated defense in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   To rely almost exclusively on the cunning of a
soon-to-be-42-year-old quarterback who had hardly practiced in a
month was not just inviting disaster, it was giving disaster a full
meal, plus an after-dinner brandy and cigar.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither team ran the ball well, the Raiders didn't need
the rushing as much because Seahawk turnovers frequently gave the
visitors a short field. The Seahawks' dependency on passing
eventually caught up to them in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a good effort by any means,'' Erickson said. ``We
need to all check and see where we are at this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we would play a lot better than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, that's pretty much how a sold-out Kingdome crowd felt,
too, not to mention football pundits around the country. But of
course, it's not up to the crowd and pundits to prepare the team.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a solid defense and greatly improved special teams, the
Seahawks have squandered the season's first half, and face a second
half with no discernible plan on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have the best talent in the league and if you can't do
squat with it, you lose,'' said Mark Collins, a Super Bowl veteran
with the New York Giants and former all-pro safety. ``I just think
we all need to look in the mirror, coaches included, and get this
thing done.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 6-2 mark, the Raiders are no more than an average
team, especially when led by a guy whose best days were spent
making scratching posts.
</P>
<P>
   If he has an inventory backlog of litter boxes, he would be wise
to leave a business card with the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
