<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DEFEAT, SEAHAWKS FIND PASSING GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Raiders came to town Sunday night hungry and ready
to take advantage of every Seahawk injury, every miscue and
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a 31-18 Seahawk defeat that will make everyone
question the direction of this .500 ballclub. Now, the Hawks will
be hard-pressed to meet expectations, let alone make an appearance
in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But in between the fumbles, in between the botched play of the
offensive line that lost veteran center Kevin Glover on the first
series and could never establish a running game, the Seahawks'
offense seemed more than ready to reclaim its identity.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in between the five turnovers that crushed any hope for
victory, you watched what Warren Moon and the passing game was
doing and you said, ``Yes, that's more like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the key to the Seahawks' running game, Ricky Watters,
caught nine passes for 68 yards _ 12 more than the 54 Watters
gained on 18 carries.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks came out passing. The game's first two plays asked
Moon to find the open man, which the veteran quarterback did, and
the Hawks were off and throwing.
</P>
<P>
   It was like the Seahawks' offense was finally ready to assert
its strength. For the first time this season, it looked like it had
a purpose, and Moon looked like the Moon of 1997, when he led the
NFL's top passing offense.
</P>
<P>
   Play No. 1 for the Hawks? Moon cranked back his Hall-of-Fame arm
and delivered a 15-yard strike to Mike Pritchard _ the same Mike
Pritchard who, like most of the offense this season, had emerged
from close games looking dazed and confused.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Sunday night, Pritchard and his fellow receivers let it
fly.
</P>
<P>
   Play No. 2 for the Hawks? Moon connected with tight end
Christian Fauria on a 25-yard completion _ letting the Raiders know
that every single eligible receiver was going to get the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``That entire opening drive was scripted,'' said Pritchard. ``We
were going to score on that drive.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first two pass completions, Moon handed off to
Watters. But then it was right back to the pass, as Joey Galloway
caught an 8-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first half, Moon was rolling. He was
15-for-15, tying Jim Zorn's franchise record for consecutive
completions. No. 15 was a beauty. It came on third-and-7, with the
Hawks at the Oakland 13.
</P>
<P>
   Moon swung a pass out to Watters, who reached down to make an
incredible catch, then trundled ahead six yards for a first down at
the Raiders' 7.
</P>
<P>
   But as good as Moon's 15th straight completion was, No. 16 was
even better. The pass that gave Moon the Seahawks' record was to
tight end Carlester Crumpler, and the big man was in the end zone.
Touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Moon said he had no idea how many completions he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I thought my rhythm was good _ as good as last season. We
got to open it up a little, and I'm the kind of quarterback who
needs to get into that kind of rhythm,'' said Moon, who ended up
completing 29 of 39 pass attempts for a season-high 275 yards.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, Moon's pass attempt to Fauria was tipped,
and the ball floated into the hands of safety Albert Lewis, who
returned the ball 74 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   After the play, coach Dennis Erickson was on the sidelines,
clapping his hands to encourage his offense, as if to say that the
play was a fluke. Even though it gave the Raiders a 21-10 lead, the
Hawks were sticking to their plan.
</P>
<P>
   The next time out, Moon led a 52-yard scoring drive on 10 plays,
connecting on all five pass attempts and then topping the drive off
with a pass to Pritchard for a two-point conversion that closed the
gap to 21-18.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the fourth quarter, the Raiders went up 24-18
but the Hawks were still looking capable of pulling off the
comeback. That's when Ronnie Harris fumbled a punt return at the
Seahawks' 5, the Raiders recovering at the 1. Two plays later, the
Raiders were in for a touchdown and the game was out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no question (down 24-18) that we could have moved
the ball. After that (fumble and Raider TD) we had to throw on
every down,'' Moon said.
</P>
<P>
   More than any of their previous losses in this rapidly
disappearing season, this defeat was a shame.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because there is no question that Moon, Pritchard and the
rest want the remainder of the season to continue in this newly
established passing fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This suits our personality,'' Pritchard said. ``We're
playmakers. We're not the kind of two-tight-end, smash-mouth
offense. We're a team that can make the short passes, make the
medium passes and then go for the big play. We can control the game
with our passing, especially our short passing, and then take our
shots long. That's just as effective as using the running back.''
</P>
<P>
   It can be. It should have been, except for the five turnovers
that will make it tough to remember that Moon and his passing crew
were back to feeling good again.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
