<HEADLINE>
BIG-PLAY DEFENSE KEEPS OAKLAND ON WINNING TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ At this point last year, the Oakland Raiders had only
one more win left in them and several more deflating defeats,
including one against New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Shaw, then the Saints' defensive backs coach, was present
for that debacle. The Raiders were 2-6 before that game en route to
a 4-12 finish, but they were playing at home against a team that's
usually a pushover. Instead, the Saints won, 13-10, with turnovers
playing an important role.
</P>
<P>
   That Saints unit didn't get much attention, but it ranked sixth
in the NFL in pass defense in '97 and earned Shaw a promotion to
defensive coordinator in '98 _ with the Raiders. Now, under Shaw
and new head coach Jon Gruden, the Raiders have the best defense in
football.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks got to that defense a bit Sunday. In fact, Hawks
quarterback Warren Moon set a team record with 17 consecutive
completions. But the Raiders made the big plays, forcing five
turnovers to the Seahawks' one. That, more than anything, gave
Oakland the 31-18 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing, getting here after a 4-12 season, is that they
needed an attitude change,'' Shaw said. ``You're going to have good
X's and O's, everybody has that. But when you're 4-12, guys have to
want to change, to play hard and go for the ball. X's and O's don't
play. People play, and that's why they needed an attitude change.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders showed that new attitude immediately, when safety
Anthony Newman ripped the helmet off receiver Mike Pritchard. The
play had gone for 15 yards, but the message seemed clear: these
were not going to be your '97 Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's defense had allowed an average of 12 points in the
Raiders' past four games, all of which resulted in wins for 6-2
Oakland. Entering Sunday night's game, the Raiders had allowed only
249.6 yards per game, the best figure in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's doing their job, and it's like one group, one
heartbeat,'' said rookie cornerback Charles Woodson, who was busy
winning the Heisman Trophy for Michigan while the Raiders struggled
last year. ``Everybody's getting to the ball, hitting, making
plays. It's a lot of fun when you know you're No. 1 and people are
coming at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Added defensive tackle Darrell Russell: ``To know everyone has
the same mind-set as you, it doesn't get any better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders are looking like the Raiders again, and Russell
talked afterward about how much he enjoys playing for ``the team
you love to hate.'' One way this team is like its bad-boy
predecessors is in penalties: the Raiders entered Sunday's play
with 100 more penalty yards than their opponents, and penalties
twice hurt them Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Both times, however, the talent of the Raiders' defense made up
for the mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the first half, as Seahawk receiver Christian Fauria
rolled around on the NFL logo at the 30-yard line after a 16-yard
reception, Raiders safety Albert Lewis came roaring in from the
blind side with a hit.
</P>
<P>
   That earned an unnecessary roughness call, turning it into a
31-yard play for the Hawks and bringing a mock cheer from Fauria,
who raised his arms while sprawled on his back. Five plays later,
the Seahawks had a touchdown and a 10-7 lead. The next quarter,
though, Lewis returned an interception 74 yards for a touchdown of
his own.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the third, Marquis Walker's facemask penalty turned a
third-and-7 into a third-and-2 for the Hawks. But Russell then
sacked Warren Moon, causing a fumble that the Raiders recovered.
That play turned into an Oakland field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Walker would atone for his penalty by picking up Joey Galloway's
fumble in the fourth quarter. But that play belonged on Woodson's
highlight reel. The Seahawks completed only one pass to Woodson's
side all day, and attempted only one other pass his way before the
final drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy that doesn't feel pressure,'' Lewis said. ``He
believes in the skills he has, and rightfully so.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Woodson doesn't feel pressure because he's part of a unit
that specializes in taking pressure off. With starting quarterback
Jeff George out with a groin injury, the Raiders are forced to be
somewhat more conservative offensively. They can pull it off,
George said, because of the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you don't turn the ball over, if you have a defense
like we have, you're going to always have a chance to win,'' George
said. ``That's stressed: don't turn the ball over, and we'll take
our chances with our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a winning formula last night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
