<SLUG> BC-FBC-UW-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNARLING BEGINS FOR UW, OREGON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The fur and the feathers were not yet flying Sunday
night in Eugene and Seattle. Perhaps the Saturday losses incurred
by Oregon and Washington in their pursuit of upper-level bowl games
dulled the rancor.
</P>
<P>
   If form holds, however, there will be enough barbs thrown soon
to wire a fence from here to the state line in advance of
Saturday's ABC-televised UW-UO game at 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has become a rivalry,'' said Oregon coach Mike Bellotti,
``where maybe it wasn't for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's always been a rivalry, it just hasn't been one so
punctuated recently by Duck victories. Oregon has won three of the
past four and the Huskies will go to Eugene Saturday as a bigger
underdog _ 6{ points on Sunday night's early line _ than they have
been since they were a 10-point 'dog to the Ducks in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we can catch them sleeping,'' said UW linebacker Marques
Hairston. ``They have to put their pads on and we have to put our
pads on, and whoever plays best wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1928-31 _ when Enoch Bagshaw and James Phelan were
coaching the Huskies _ have the Ducks won four games from the
Huskies in a five-year period. The perception has developed that
Oregon has taken the game more seriously than Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all perception, somebody else's thing,'' Jim Lambright,
the UW coach, said before Sunday night's short practice. ``It's
definitely not coming from our field.''
</P>
<P>
   Lending to the notion have been some crackling comments from
Duck players in recent years. Former wide receiver Pat Johnson _
whose touchdown catch beat Washington last year _ talked about
learning to hate the Huskies, and ex-running back Saladin
McCullough accused Lambright of ``bragging,'' apparently a
reference to Lambright's 1995 comments detailing why Washington
should be picked for the Cotton Bowl ahead of the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, two days after Oregon's 31-28 victory, Lambright
said, ``I have a hard time with hatred in a rival game. I will
never get into it, and I know it's being coached. So right away,
you probably give up a lever as far as getting your team ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellotti, asked Sunday night if he and Lambright had discussed
the issue since last year, said, ``No, I didn't talk to him about
it. He says a lot of things I don't go back and talk to him about.
We take this rivalry very seriously, but I don't teach hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambright said Sunday night, ``You try to teach a classy
approach to the game and that same way of playing it. But at the
same time, you also have to let your players know about the emotion
that's going to be there. You play a fine line.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambright said cornerback Jermaine Smith might return this week,
a boon for a Husky secondary that has been burned for 748 yards
passing by freshman quarterbacks in the past two games. While
Washington hopes to have back fullback Pat Conniff, Oregon running
back Herman Ho-Ching, who missed the 38-3 loss at Arizona and five
games before it with a knee injury, could play pending workouts
later this week.
</P>
<P>
   A key interference call against UW rover Nigel Burton, which
would have stopped a fourth-quarter USC drive with the Trojans
ahead, 14-10, ``was as questionable as I thought at the time,''
Lambright said. The play negated an interception and USC scored to
continue toward a 33-10 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Washington offensive coordinator Scott Linehan left Sunday for
Eastern Washington to be with his seriously ill father. Offensive
line coach Steve Morton will direct the offense until Linehan
returns.
</P>
</TEXT>
