   &UR; NON-FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1.TUESDAYS WITH MORRIE, by Mitch Albom.
</P>
<P>
   (Doubleday, $19.95.) A sportswriter tells of
</P>
<P>
   his weekly visits to his old college mentor,
</P>
<P>
   who was near death's door.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE DEATH OF OUTRAGE, by William J. Bennett. (Free Press,
</P>
<P>
   $20.) A former secretary of education takes a critical view
</P>
<P>
   of the Clinton presidency. (b).
</P>
<P>
   3. THE TEN COMMANDMENTS, by Laura Schlesinger and Stewart
</P>
<P>
   Vogel. (Cliff Street/HarperCollins, $24.) The radio
</P>
<P>
   psychologist and a rabbi discuss the significance of the
</P>
<P>
   Ten Commandments in contemporary life.
</P>
<P>
   4. DAVE BARRY TURNS 50, by Dave Barry. (Crown, $22.)
</P>
<P>
   The humorist's observations about reaching the half-century
</P>
<P>
   mark.
</P>
<P>
   5. LINDBERGH, by A. Scott Berg. (Putnam, $30.) The
</P>
<P>
   checkered life of Charles A. Lindbergh.
</P>
<P>
   6. THE PROFESSOR AND THE MADMAN, by Simon Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperCollins, $22.) How an American who was a certified
</P>
<P>
   lunatic and a murderer helped James Murray compile the
</P>
<P>
   Oxford English Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   7. PURE DRIVEL, by Steve Martin. (Hyperion, $19.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Humor pieces by the actor, comedian and writer.
</P>
<P>
   8. JUST JACKIE, by Edward Klein. (Ballantine, $25.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The life of Jacqueline Onassis from the assassination of
</P>
<P>
   President Kennedy to her death, 31 years later.
</P>
<P>
   9. WORKING WITH EMOTIONAL INTELLIGENCE, by Daniel Goleman.
</P>
<P>
   (Bantam, $25.95.) The attributes that enable people to become
</P>
<P>
   leaders in their fields.
</P>
<P>
   10. HIGH CRIMES AND MISDEMEANORS, by Ann H. Coulter.
</P>
<P>
   (Regnery, $24.95.) A lawyer states the case for the
</P>
<P>
   impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   11.(x) A PIRATE LOOKS AT FIFTY, by Jimmy Buffett. (Random
</P>
<P>
   House, $24.95.) While traveling from the Florida Keys
</P>
<P>
   to the Amazon, the singer-songwriter reflects on his
</P>
<P>
   half-century of life.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking the
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   13. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Scribner, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   An Irish-American writer recalls his childhood amid the
</P>
<P>
   miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) ...AND THE HORSE HE RODE IN ON, by James Carville.
</P>
<P>
   (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $14.95.) A critical account of Kenneth
</P>
<P>
   Starr and his investigation.
</P>
<P>
   15. HIS BRIGHT LIGHT, by Danielle Steel. (Delacorte,
</P>
<P>
   $25.) The novelist recalls the life of her son Nick
</P>
<P>
   Traina, who suffered from manic depression and died at
</P>
<P>
   19.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) CONVERSATIONS WITH GOD: Book 1, by Neale Donald Walsch.
</P>
<P>
   (Putnam, $19.95.) The author addresses questions
</P>
<P>
   of life and love, good and evil, guilt and sin. (b).
</P>
