<HEADER>
A8677 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-NOVEMBER-KAN &LR;      11-02 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-NOVEMBER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T WE JUST SKIP NOVEMBER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   November starts out all wrong and then goes downhill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The very first day of the month is a bummer because it's All
Saints Day, which serves no higher purpose than to remind us of our
imperfections. Where is the self-esteem movement when we need it? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And all this happens in a misnamed month. The name November
comes from the Latin word for nine, (ital)nove,(end-ital) which
gets applied to the 11th month. Someone can't count too well, and
it's not me. September is the ninth month, but it's already named
for the Latin word for seven, (ital)septem.(end-ital) Which proves
the world is full of goofy stuff that most of us accept without
thinking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, now that I'm already sidetracked here, I may as well
complain a little about the whole concept of months, which is
outdated and in need of a complete overhaul. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Months are based on the length of time the moon takes to revolve
once around the Earth. This is called a synodic month. Remember
that. You might need to know that some day, along with how to find
the square root of a number and the gestation period of an
elephant. Although maybe not. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But synodic isn't the only type of month. Oh, no. You've also
got your sidereal month, your tropical month and your draconic (or
nodical) month (you could look them up). And probably you've got
several other kinds of months that the encyclopedia from which I
steal information so I can look smart couldn't bear to describe to
confused devils like me. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you add up the time between what scientists (and worse) call
``lunations'' _ that is, the time between, say, successive new
moons _ you end up with a year that, though 12 months long, lasts
only 354 days. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's a year that doesn't work out right with your solar-based
year, although if you ask me it's weirdly intriguing that 12 months
calculated by one celestial body would wind up almost equaling 12
months calculated by a wholly different celestial body. I'm sure it
involves some sort of conspiracy, but I've had it up to here with
conspiracies at the moment and have no desire to dig into this one,
no matter who promises to fund the study. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By now I'm so deflected from my original (and quite brilliant)
point about what a doofus month November is that I may not be able
to right this ship. But I'm going to try. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The whole thrust of November is wrong, at least here in the
Northern Hemisphere where I've spent my alleged life. The days get
shorter, the nights longer and the temperatures colder. What's the
sense of any of that? If I were a month and that's the best I could
do, I'd retire _ 401(k) or no 401(k). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   November is also woefully short of major holidays. You've got
Thanksgiving, of course, and I'm all for keeping that, as long as
someone else has to carve the turkey. But name me another good
November holiday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No doubt folks in South Dakota are pretty excited each Nov. 2
about celebrating the anniversary of their state joining the union
in 1889. But it's hard to stir up much interest in that once you
get outside of Yankton. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK, Nov. 2 is Admission Day for North Dakota, too, but
tell me when you last saw any TV network devote much time to the
annual North Dakota Admission Day parade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is true that there are a few good birthdays to celebrate in
November _ especially Nov. 30, when Mark Twain, Winston Churchill,
Jonathan Swift and Dick Clark all were born. But you counter that
with Nov. 9, the late Spiro T. Agnew's birthday, and it all seems
to come to naught. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So I say we skip November, head right for the December holidays
and try to explain why a month named for the Latin word for 10,
(ital)decem(edd-ital) is 12th. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
