<HEADER>
A8685 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN04-COX     11-02 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Topsy-turvy world of presidential lawsuits
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has come to this: An old friend from their high school days
is suing President Clinton for slander because he has said he
didn't have sex with her. That's ``didn't,'' as in ``did not.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers are pleading with the judge either to throw
the suit out like a noisy drunk or at least to revisit the Supreme
Court's ruling that presidents are no better than any other working
stiff and can be sued at will.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, civil suits had to be put off until after the
president left office, which pretty much filtered out the publicity
hounds and political snipers. But last year, the Supreme Court,
establishing that it had lost all contact with reality, and
unanimously at that, held that suits against a president would be
no worse than a small bother.
</P>
<P>
   The small bother of Paula Jones's suit, used to walk the
president into a trap, has now brought Clinton into the impeachment
dock and face to face with the political equivalent of the death
penalty because he was slippin' around on Hillary and told this
little white lie about it. (Oh, all right: this BIG white lie.)
</P>
<P>
   The president's problems are compounded by Kenneth Starr's
successful effort to disarm him in order to attack him the more
freely. Starr won a court ruling that the president can't use White
House counsels in his defense and must hire private lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Starr gets $40 million-plus of your money and mine to go after
Clinton while Clinton has to pauper himself in his defense. Clinton
must by now have run up enough billable hours to capitalize a
fair-sized country. Whenever and however he leaves the White House,
he'll leave worse than broke.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we may ponder the curious claim by Dolly Kyle
Browning that for a president to say he never had sex with her _ at
least for this president to say he never had sex with her _ when
she insists he did amounts to slander. After all, what's Browning?
Chopped liver?
</P>
<P>
   Since folklore now holds that Clinton is one of those guys who
chases every skirt, then, yes, by a goofy syllogism of sorts, it
could be argued that for him to let one pass unpestered amounts to
actionable disdain. What's a poor girl to make of herself and what
will others think of her if she's the only maid left standing at a
bed-a-thon? Oh, the shame of it! And how do you make a career move
out of innocence anyway?
</P>
<P>
   The Browning suit extends the rationale of the Jones suit. Jones
is suing, she says, to clear her name, but Clinton is the only
person in the whole nutty business who has been insisting her name
is unsullied _ that nothing untoward passed between them. It was
the right-wing political buddies of her own later handlers who
dragged Jones's name into play.
</P>
<P>
   If Jones, for vindication, and egged on by her real detractors,
can sue the one man who is insisting she is a good girl, then
Browning has a darned sensible point.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's review and see if we've got all this straight: a
fallen woman is one whose sexual adventures want for willing
corroboration and a cad is a fellow who kisses and tries not to
tell.
</P>
<P>
   Yep. Sounds about right, here in Wonderland.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
