<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8754 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN03-COX     11-02 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Building dispute surrounds course Bobby Jones made famous
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last week, thousands of golf fans poured into Atlanta
to watch the PGA Tour Championship at the historic East Lake Golf
Club. At the tournament, which wrapped up Sunday, they strolled
along sun-baked zoysia fairways and stood in the dappled shade of
tall oaks dropping golden leaves. It was beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   But East Lake Golf Club is not only one of the finest places in
the world to play and watch golf. It might also be one of the best
locations for contemplating the meaning of money. Wealth and
poverty surround the course; their juxtaposition give the
neighborhood a fascinating history and an inspiring future.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the century, East Lake was the home course of the
legendary Bobby Jones. Three years ago, the course and club
buildings were brought back to their former splendor through the
efforts of local developer and philanthropist Tom Cousins. With the
wealthy again enjoying the course, just 10 minutes east of
downtown, ``East Lake'' is now emblazed on cotton golf shirts
selling for $100.
</P>
<P>
   But for decades, the East Lake name also conjured up images that
had nothing to do with clipped greens and Bermuda roughs. Crime,
violence, drug dealing and despair overshadowed the leafy beauty of
the old neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   When Cousins set out to restore the East Lake Golf Club, he
understood that it would be immoral and shortsighted to try to wall
off the problems surrounding the course. East Lake would get its
good name back only if the whole area became a decent place to
live, work and recreate.
</P>
<P>
   With courage and vision, Cousins created the East Lake Community
Foundation, a charitable group, to spearhead a complex program of
true urban renewal. Working closely with the Atlanta Housing
Authority, the foundation has pushed to replace crime-infested,
failed public housing, called East Lake Meadows, with attractive,
mixed-income housing called the Villages of East Lake. Because the
new housing includes working people who are paying rent, the poorer
residents can see examples of success.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the efforts of AHA and Cousins, longtime homeowners
in the area are seeing property values shoot up. Young people who
thought they'd never get a decent job are making good money as
caddies. Older people are sitting on their front porches again as
the drug dealers move away.
</P>
<P>
   Cousins not only is helping the neighborhood, he is teaching
other affluent people a valuable lesson: Being wealthy is a lot
more fun when you don't have to hide in your house and fear for
your safety. By wisely spreading around a little cash, you can help
create a richer society where urban amenities are safe to use,
property values are secure and future workers have access to good
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, a small group that lives in the last of the
decaying East Lake Meadows housing is fighting the effort to
temporarily relocate them. They need to move into other public
housing while their old apartments are razed to make way for new
ones. They filed suit last week to stop the East Lake redevelopment
until AHA meets their demand to build new housing before taking
down the old.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Bill Campbell has promised to try to help settle this
dispute quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Something the last residents of East Lake Meadows need to
realize is that creating wealth is a process of risks and rewards.
They will have to give up the housing they know in the hope that
the new will be better.
</P>
<P>
   Cousins, a millionaire, knows this. He has risked millions of
his own dollars to improve, not only the golf course, but the
community around it. Everyone involved has to do their part, but
they all stand to gain.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax is a member of The Atlanta Constitution editorial
board.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
