<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web's the place for the politically astute
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Election Day is here, but there's still time to bone
up on the candidates and the issues on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   All 435 U.S. representatives are up for re-election, and the
outcome of campaigns across the country could impact the makeup of
the House, now Republican-controlled. AllPolitics
(http://www.allpolitics.com or http://www.cnn.com/election/1998),
Time Warner's online political arm, handles election chores with
help from CNN, Time magazine, Congressional Quarterly, The
Associated Press and Reuters. CNN's AllPolitics.com takes an
in-depth look at the election. CNN has devoted more than a thousand
Web pages to election coverage, with analysis of key races. There's
also a wealth of background information and candidate profiles
courtesy of Congressional Quarterly. On election night,
AllPolitics.com will offer up-to-the-minute election returns and
exit polling.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Woelfel, vice president and editor in chief of CNN
Interactive, promises the election night online coverage will be
timely and comprehensive. ``We're drawing upon nearly three years
of covering politics exclusively for the Web. Not only do we have
the best resources, but also we have the most experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Election night is tailor-made for this medium and for AOL,''
said Barry Schuler, president of AOL Interactive Services.
``Instead of sitting in front of the television or listening to the
radio for hours waiting for the race you care about to be
mentioned, you can go online, and with a few clicks, you have the
results you want.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL's live coverage begins at 7 p.m. and will continue into the
early morning hours. AOL members will also have a chance to talk
politics live online with guests John Kennedy Jr., Republican
strategist Mary Matalin and ABC News analysts and reporters at
remote locations on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ABCNews.com has created a special area of its site called
``Political Nation'' (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .abcnews.com/sections/us
</P>
<P>
   /politicalnation/politicalnation
</P>
<P>
   .html). The site highlights key races around the country. ABC
News has also taken the liberty of handicapping most of the races.
</P>
<P>
   When all the political rhetoric and mumbo-jumbo gets to be a bit
too much, you can always try ``Politically Incorrect'' (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .abc.com/pi/index.html) for a little comic relief. You can check
out host Bill Maher's one-liners, vote on question of the day,
indulge in politically themed games or post your two cents in the
area of the same name. Surprisingly, the postings on the ``PI''
site aren't the usual all-caps Web ranting, but some interesting
comments from political junkies who also appreciate good political
satire.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
