A8760 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-MEDIA03-COX     11-02 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magazine provides sneak preview of 'Quake' update
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents don't much care for it, but that hasn't stopped
``Quake'' from being a hit with male children of all ages. Now the
third version of the gory shoot-'em-up is set for release, and the
November issue of PC Gamer has a sneak preview. The preview
includes 13 pages of inside information and screen shots from the
game. This version of ``Quake'' promises to be controversial.
Publisher id Software decided to try something new and focus on
just the DeathMatch part of the game. This version also will
emphasize multiplayer gaming over the Internet, says the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Online is going Hollywood. ``You've Got Mail,'' a new film
starring Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan, is about a couple that romance
each other through cyberspace. Learn all about this new movie in
the November issue of Yahoo! Internet Life. The magazine features
an interview with Hanks about the movie. Says Hanks, now hooked on
cyberspace, ``I'd throw my phone away if I could. E-mail is a much
better way of communicating.''
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   PurpleMoon has released the latest title in its series about a
middle school girl and her friends. This one is called ``Rockett's
Adventure Maker'' and once again stars eighth-grader Rockett
Movado. In this title, kids create their own characters and place
them in a story. Kids choose from five body types, 25 faces, eight
skin tones and 30 hairstyles. There are also 32 backgrounds, 60
props and 14 speech and thought bubbles from which kids can create
adventures for their characters. ``Adventure Maker'' retails for
$29.95 and is available for both Windows and PowerPC Macs.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   In this time of financial turmoil, it's more important than ever
to investigate stocks before buying. That's especially true of
initial public offerings, or IPOs, which were among the hottest
sectors of the market until lately. There's no better place to
research an IPO than on the Net. Begin your research at Hoover's
IPO Central, a site dedicated to in-depth research of companies
going public. It holds, for example, thousands of profiles of IPO
companies, both past and present. There's also a primer on how to
judge an IPO. You'll find the site at http://www.ipocentral.com.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
