<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's time to start over with a lean, mean Net browser
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Not too many years ago, a good friend gave me one of
those fancy Swiss Army knives. It was a marvel (probably still is,
but it's lost in the clutter now, or perhaps has escaped back to
Switzerland).
</P>
<P>
   It contained a magnifying glass, two different kinds of
screwdrivers, a small saw, three or four knife blades, a fingernail
clipper, scissors, a hole punch and even a toothpick. All of them
worked, after a fashion, and none of them worked very well. If you
really needed a screwdriver or scissors, it was nothing like having
the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I download a new version of Netscape Communicator or
Microsoft Internet Explorer _ the two most popular programs for
browsing the World Wide Web _ I think of that knife. The
competition has gotten so heated between the two Web browsers that
each tries hard to outdo the other by loading in new features.
There are so many I truly can't remember what all of them do. And
since I don't use them, I never get reminded.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I can zip through the menus of Netscape Communicator and
find a way to design a Web page from scratch, or read postings in
the newsgroups, or send e-mail, join a chat group on the Net or
fire up AOL's Instant Messager to locate a friend online and send a
message. It's the same with Internet Explorer. Each time one
browser adds a new feature, the other duplicates that feature and
adds two additional ones.
</P>
<P>
   But all I want to do is browse the Web. That, after all, is why
I have the Web browser in the first place. When I want to send
e-mail, I use a program made to do that (in my case, Eudora Pro)
much better than a Web browser. When I want to browse the
newsgroups, I fire up NewsXpress. Dedicated programs truly do a
better job than a Swiss Army knife program.
</P>
<P>
   At first, all this feature-packing seems harmless. After all, in
the screwy world of Internet commerce, both Microsoft and Netscape
give these products away. You can download either program
(Netscape: http://home.netscape.com or Explorer:
http://www.microsoft.com) directly from the Internet without paying
a cent.
</P>
<P>
   But when you do, you'll find out one of the many reasons I wish
these companies would get out of the Swiss Army knife business and
back into the honorable business of creating a way to browse the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'm spoiled by the high-speed T1 data line I use at work
when connecting to the Internet. It's like driving on the Autobahn
on a day when the traffic is light. But when I get home and use my
56k bps analog modem and the telephone lines, downloads crawl. And
both Internet Explorer and Netscape are huge. To give you a notion,
the full version of Netscape Communicator is more than 14
megabytes. That's bigger than the first hard drive I owned, back in
the dark ages.
</P>
<P>
   Since you fight both relatively slow download speeds and heavy
traffic at these sites, the download often gets painfully slow,
with speeds dipping well below the rated speed of most modems. I've
literally seen downloads that took hours.
</P>
<P>
   And if your Internet connection is at all shaky, you could have
the painful experience of waiting an hour or so for the download to
finish and _ at the last minute _ losing the connection. You have
to start all over again.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I wish Microsoft and Netscape would do. Start all
over again and build a browser that is lean and mean.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
