<SLUG> BC-TECHTOOLS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Language tutor CDs lose a lot in translation
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Surely all of us, at one time or another, have wondered how it
would be to have our consciousness transplanted into that of
another, to see and understand from the viewpoint of someone else.
</P>
<P>
   My encounters with software conceived and whelped in France lead
me to believe that entering the mind of a Gallic software designer
would be like walking into a carnival funhouse for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   What got me into this train of thought is a product called Tell
Me More from Auralog, which is at once the most creative and the
most useless language tutor I have ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Tell Me More is a voice-recognition program that comes in
several languages; I looked at the Spanish version. It comes with
the mandatory headset (microphone and earphones), a couple of
manuals which are of only occasional help, and three CD-ROMs.
</P>
<P>
   The program provides almost every approach to language
comprehension you can imagine. The main screen is a scene full of
hotspots (remember Microsoft Bob?) leading you to to these various
approaches. Click on the notebook and you get the exercises. Among
the possible exercises are word associations, word order, filling
in the blanks in sentences, Hangman, a chance to take dictation,
associating words with pictures, and a crossword.
</P>
<P>
   All these are in Spanish. In other words, in filling in the
blanks, you get a sentence in Spanish and a set of words in
Spanish, from which you must choose the proper word to complete the
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Kinda tough if you don't know Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you go to the glossary and the grammar book. The
glossary is straightfoward and useful; it gives you a translation
of a Spanish word and a pronunciation of it. The grammar book, on
the other hand, is useless. For example, it attempts to demonstrate
the proper use of the word ``esta'' by using it in a series of
sentences _ none of which is translated.
</P>
<P>
   For further frustration, you can click on dialogue, which takes
you to a picture and a set of sentences. Another sentence is spoken
to you. You are supposed to select and utter the proper response.
</P>
<P>
   In some of these sections you can right-click on a word and get
some options such as a translation or pronunciation. The procedure
is, however, slow and cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   What is utterly lacking in Tell Me More is any kind of cohesion
and direction. There is no step-by-step plan for learning, no sense
of ``Do this lesson and it will prepare you for that one.'' You
apparently are expected simply to jump off into the deep end and
sink or swim.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't know a good many Spanish words already, you'd
better take a life preserver with you.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear to me _ si, claro _ the French do not think the same
way I do. At least not the folks at 12 avenue Jean Bart, in Voisins
le Bretonneux.
</P>
<P>
   While we are on the subject of voice recognition, I took a look
at IBM's latest version, ViaVoice Executive 98. It terms of its
breadth, it is much improved. But in the critical area _ how well
it recognized my voice _ I can see no significant improvement. Once
again, I must conclude the time of the voice-recognition program
has not yet arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
