<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emission waiver lets drivers off the hook
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I recently attended a public hearing held by the
Georgia Environmental Protection Division. The turnout was small _
a handful of auto industry representatives and state bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   We in the auto repair industry weren't required to be there. We
didn't go because the subject matter was especially spectacular.
The agenda item we had come to hear and object to was the extension
of the $200 waiver limit for vehicles failing the metro area's
emission test _ and continuing to contribute to the deterioration
of Atlanta's air quality.
</P>
<P>
   The waiver limit means cars that fail the state's emission test
can be granted a waiver _ and permission to get new tags for two
years _ if the owner spends at least $200 fixing the car and it
shows some improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the limit _ meaning the owner has to spend more money on
the car before it is granted a waiver _ will be better for everyone
in the long run. Let me explain.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone failing an emissions inspection must attempt to have
their vehicle repaired to comply with specific emissions standards.
After repairs are made, the car must show an improvement in the
emission of certain gases without adversely affecting the other
tailpipe readings. If the customer has spent more than $200 in
emission-related repairs and the vehicle's tailpipe readings meet
the above criteria, the vehicle may qualify for a waiver even
though it actually fails the test.
</P>
<P>
   This waiver enables the owner to register the vehicle, and it
will not need to be retested for another two years.
</P>
<P>
   When the new state testing program started in October 1996, the
$200 limit was put in place for the first two years only. This
arrangement was intended to give the public, time to adjust to the
test and to begin bringing vehicles into compliance. The emissions
standards would get stricter, as would the testing procedure for
older vehicles. They had to.
</P>
<P>
   The old emissions program, with its $50 repair limit, had
virtually no effect on improving Atlanta's air quality. In fact,
according to the Environmental Protection Division statistics, 1998
was one of the worst years for ground level ozone. The metro area
was in compliance with federal standards on 22 days. While the
weather and other variables can increase or decrease the problem,
the one constant factor has been the steady increase in pollution
from cars.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the automotive repair industry realized that the
current system was flawed by the constraints placed upon them. A
primary issue was the public perception that $200 in repairs would
``get them a sticker.''
</P>
<P>
   It was common knowledge that a large percentage of the cars on
the road were in despicable states of repair that $200 would not
begin to fix. The public also discovered this as it bounced back
and forth between retests and repairs with the costs escalating
each time.
</P>
<P>
   However, the $200 figure stuck in their minds, and any repairs
costing more began to fuel tempers. The repair industry has been
eager for the ceiling to be raised so it could get down to the
business of fixing cars without having to haggle over an
unrealistic price limit.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners have invested thousands of dollars in equipment
to meet the needs of the program. While early concerns that there
wouldn't be enough test lanes were quickly dispelled, a new element
has begun to emerge: a shortage of mechanics with the skills to
repair emissions failures.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 26 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, is an automotive instructor and an ASE master automobile
technician/L-1. Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Or send
comments online to nora(AT)admin2.dekalb.tec.ga.us or
2wrenchs(AT)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
