<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8779 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREIG-COLUMN03-COX     11-02 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREIG-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leather jackets can be preserved
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have a leather letter jacket with patches and pins I want
to display. I don't want it hanging in a closet or stuffed in a
box. Where can I find tips on preserving this precious memory? _ E.
Dever
</P>
<P>
   A: A framer can build a shadow box and mount it _ literally sew
the jacket to the backing. Or you can purchase a Plexiglas case
from Lin Terry at (732) 370-5252 and hang the jacket inside the
case. That is the advice of Stars, the high-end memorabilia giant
of Aspen, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Stars recently handled a Jan. 1, 1784, document signed by George
Washington, which sold for a cool $25,000. On a more pedestrian
level, Stars has a ``Saving Private Ryan'' poster signed by Steven
Spielberg, et al. _ a mere $795. Q: Assuming it ever gets cold
enough to use the fireplace, how can I be sure any wood I order is
free of oak wilt? Any vendor you call will swear up and down their
wood is ``clean.'' _ Georgia Reed
</P>
<P>
   A: You can't be sure. Burning wood with oak wilt does not spread
the disease. However, transporting and storing infected firewood
could contaminate other trees. To be safe, never buy red oak
firewood. Purchase mesquite, pecan or elm.
</P>
<P>
   Barring that, only well-seasoned wood should be purchased. This
wood is light-weight. The ends are split; bark may be loose.
</P>
<P>
   The advice of Texas Forest Service's Jim Rooni is to burn all
wood by the middle of February and cover all unseasoned wood with
clear plastic, tucked under the pile. If you cut wood suspected of
having oak wilt, allow the logs to dry in the sun for an entire
summer before moving them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I need your help! I am seeing two guys _ 23 and 17 years of
age. I am only 15. I really like the 23-year-old, but my mom
disapproves of him. I was friends with him for more than a year,
but I am scared. He wants to take our friendship a step forward.
The 17-year-old is the one I like to hang around with, but we had
an intimate relationship when we knew each other for only a few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The older guy asked me to choose between the two of them. What
should I do? _ K.H.
</P>
<P>
   A: You asked me, I think, because you suspect the answer will be
similar to your mom's. I won't disappoint. The 23-year-old guy is
too old for you. I can barely sanction seeing the 17-year-old.
Trust your mom. She loves you.
</P>
<P>
   Licensed marriage and family therapist Annie Drake says, ``The
only people who can slow down a teen-ager's world are parents.'' If
confused, she advises, ``Say no.''
</P>
<P>
   Age differences are particularly acute now. Fifteen is young _
you are not driving or voting and cannot join the Army. When you
are 45 and the older man is 53, no problem. But those eight years
represent light years in maturity during the teen years.
</P>
<P>
   Drake also noted two ways for parents to say ``no'': ``No, I
love you too much to let you do that,'' and, ``No, not now.''
</P>
<P>
   Looks like for you it is ``No, not now.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: My mother is in a nursing home. My father and I have a
general durable power of attorney. My mother's Medicaid application
for nursing home payment was denied and now is going through an
appeals process. In the meantime the bill must be paid or she will
be discharged for nonpayment (decision made by a DHS hearing
officer).
</P>
<P>
   The nursing home administrator demands payment from me and has
threatened to file a lien against my home and my father's for any
unpaid bill. Do I have a legal obligation to pay my mother's bill
with my resources?
</P>
<P>
   Also, can a nursing home discharge a patient to the home of a
family member who is not the spouse or legal guardian?
</P>
<P>
   _N.S.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Federal law prohibits a Medicaid-certified nursing home
from requiring a third party to guarantee payment as a condition of
admission,'' says attorney H. Clyde Farrell. If you signed a
contract agreeing to be responsible for your mother's bills, it may
be invalid (the moral obligation is another question).
</P>
<P>
   Your home is your homestead, and you need not worry about the
nursing home or anyone else putting a lien on it. Your father's
obligations to your mother's bills do not include his home. After
the death of your parents, the estate may need the proceeds of the
sale of the house to settle bills, which may include nursing home
bills.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney experienced in the growing field of elder law,
Christine Larson adds that the discharge of a patient can only be
to a spouse or legal guardian. When the well-being of a person age
60 or more is in jeopardy, contact Adult Protective Services at
(800) 252-5400.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Reel Women is a nonprofit organization formed to promote the
education and networking of women filmmakers. We need a computer
and reasonable office space to facilitate film production and
administration. The computer should be a 200 Pentium at least,
Windows 95, with 32 mgs of RAM, a sound card and a video card. We
are also looking for a 15-inch (or larger) monitor, a CD-ROM drive
and a laser printer. _ Susan Kirr
</P>
<P>
   A: Readers, think of this as an opportunity to get into the
movie business. Call Kirr at 512-263-7586 if you can help.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I get my white pants dyed khaki? _ P.M.F.
</P>
<P>
   A: Grab the familiar RIT dye and hit the washing machine. Or you
can tea-dye the pants (send me a stamped, self-addressed envelope
for the recipe).
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(AT)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
Because of the number of inquiries, Jane cannot respond to every
request.
</P>
