<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Who says the American voters are not fools?
 &HT;    For release Nov. 4, 1998
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere along each just-concluded campaign, candidates _
usually one on the receiving end of a hard, low hit by his or her
opponent _ will notify the electorate through the media that the
American people are not fools and will see through the opposition's
bluster.
</P>
<P>
   I have no doubt that almost all of us can see through the
word-twisting and planted innuendoes of today's American politics,
but I'm not quite certain of the claim about us not being a nation
of fools.
</P>
<P>
   This concern is based upon what I am seeing and reading about us
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The people who appear on the Jerry Springer show, both
participants and audience, are an example. Who are they and why do
they act in the manner they do? Are they the ones who elected
people to Congress, to City Hall, or to the bench? And what about
those millions who watch that low-level stupidity; what does it say
about them?
</P>
<P>
   So successful has been the Springer show that copycats have
bloomed all over the morning and late afternoon TV tube.
</P>
<P>
   Who are those people who dress up in bizarre getups at televised
football games, seeking mainly to appear coast-to-coast? ``Did you
see when the camera panned to the end zone? The guy in the gorilla
mask, with `Jets' written in green across his belly? That was me!''
</P>
<P>
   How nice.
</P>
<P>
   Who are those people who go to professional wrestling matches,
screaming vulgarities at the beefy actors in the ring? Or pay the
cost of closed-circuit telecasts of those events? Why are they
imitating our Hollywood perception of mobs in the Roman Coliseum?
And who is that 45-year-old lady who, at a safe distance, is
taunting the 250-pound wrestler?
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting to note that with every documented charge
against Bill Clinton by Ken Starr, Clinton's popularity rises in
the polls, and Starr's sags. I'm not one interested in continuing
this Clinton inquisition, but I'm also not one to think more of him
today than I did yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   How many spend their days and nights glued to music videos, and
never read a book, a magazine, a newspaper; never watch a public
service telecast?
</P>
<P>
   If this is not a nation of fools, then who are those people and
how many of them are there?
</P>
<P>
   From one end of the country to the other, political candidates
have drummed into our heads awful things about the other guy.
Professional advisers tell the candidates that if you throw enough
of that into the air, some of it is going to stick. The
professionals do that based on experience, the experience that
while not all Americans are fools, a good number of us are. Perhaps
a greater number than we would like to think.
</P>
<P>
   It clearly would be unconstitutional to require citizens to take
a Rorschach test before being eligible to vote, but I certainly
would like to know who among us believes that wrestling is
unrehearsed or that the warring women on Jerry Springer's stage,
those booing and cheering in the audience and those at home _ their
eyes glued to the spectacle _ are considered part of that broad
generic observation that says that the voters of America are not
fools.
</P>
<P>
   We are not talking about the stoic portrait of a Middle American
caste, pitchfork in hand, solemn wife at his side. They exist out
there, but are shrinking at the same rate as their farms. We're not
talking about the old Silent Majority, either; they evolved into
the Christian Right. They are identifiable and with goals.
</P>
<P>
   But those others, those many who read tabloid newspapers, follow
movie stars' lives far more closely than the actions of their
elected representatives, watch morning TV mayhem and actually
believe the horribly distorted claims made in political races _
they're the ones who worry me.
</P>
<P>
   How many of them are out there? Are they the deciding force in
the course of this nation? Heaven help us if they are.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
