<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once you add the necessities, G3 is a better buy than iMac
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No question about it. The iMac is one sharp-looking
computer. But is it a good buy? I'd argue not. A better investment
would be any of Apple Computer's G3 desktop models.
</P>
<P>
   Now, before you start flaming me with e-mail charges of
betrayal, let me explain. I consider the iMac a good, if not great,
computer. It works reasonably well, has a brilliantly sharp screen
and, of course, there's that striking bondi translucent body.
</P>
<P>
   But a computer is a lot more than looks. It needs to work out of
the box with existing software and devices like printers. It is
here the iMac falls short. In addition, the iMac really costs more
than its listed price. Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   For starters, there's no internal floppy drive. Apple Computer's
Steve Jobs doesn't think you need or want one. But I doubt few of
you can get by without a floppy drive. How better to save and carry
all those little files you create day in and out?
</P>
<P>
   That means you'll have to buy a floppy, and there's only one
available that works with the iMac. It's called the Imation
SuperDisk and sells for about $150. Adding an Imation drive raises
the price of the iMac to $1,450.
</P>
<P>
   And there's more
</P>
<P>
   That's still a good price _ but wait, you're not done yet. The
iMac's 32 megabytes of internal memory, or RAM, is inadequate to
run most of today's multimedia games, supposedly one of this
computer's strengths. You'll need to at least double the iMac's
RAM, which adds another $100 to $200 to the price.
</P>
<P>
   Don't close your wallet yet, especially if you'd like to print
anything from the iMac. It uses a new standard for connecting
peripheral devices, and your old printer won't work. That means you
either have to buy a new printer, for $270, or a special device
that will connect the iMac to old printers. Those devices range in
price from $40 to $100.
</P>
<P>
   In total, the iMac is not as inexpensive as Apple Computer would
have you believe. Its true price runs between $1,700 and $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   For that, you might as well buy a G3 desktop or PowerBook. Both
of them cost about the same and come with everything you need right
out of the box.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
