<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What a difference 30 years makes
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Pop songs are like time machines. Take the
Supremes' hit Love Child, which topped the charts 30 years ago.
It's one of those pop songs that, to put it kindly, remind you that
1968 was a very, very long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's about a woman born to an unmarried mother and determined
not to let the same thing happen to a child of her own:
</P>
<P>
   No child of mine'll be bearing/ The name of shame I've been
wearing...
</P>
<P>
   It's hard for Janice Benson, a lead teacher Dunbar High School's
day care center, to imagine Love Child becoming a hit today. The
kids she works with just couldn't identify. The lyrics seem quaint
as a lace doily:
</P>
<P>
   This love we're contemplating
</P>
<P>
   Is worth the pain of waiting
</P>
<P>
   We'll only end up hating
</P>
<P>
   This child we may be creating
</P>
<P>
   Love child, never meant to be
</P>
<P>
   Love child, scorned by
</P>
<P>
   society
</P>
<P>
   Love child, always second best
</P>
<P>
   Love child, different from the rest
</P>
<P>
   Teen pregnancy doesn't carry the stigma that it did when Benson,
51, was a teen-ager. Yes, maybe that's one of the reasons there are
more teen pregnancies today. But would it be better for teen-agers
_ and their children _ if we returned to the days of the stigma?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it would be great if kids felt peer pressure not to have
sex. But do we want teen mothers to drop out of school? Do we want
their babies to feel ``never quite as good''?
</P>
<P>
   Benson was 15 and unmarried when she became pregnant. Her high
school kicked her out. She was forced to leave her baby daughter
home with her mother while attending high school 43 miles away and
living with her grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had made a mistake,'' Benson says, ``but I felt I
could still do what I wanted with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother told her, ``Janice, this isn't the end of your life.
You can do it; you're gonna do it.''
</P>
<P>
   And she did. She graduated from Sinclair Community College and
has been a child care provider for 30 years. She has raised six
good kids.
</P>
<P>
   Benson made it in spite of the disgrace she was made to feel.
Now she's working in an environment where teen mothers are treated
much more compassionately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through it, so I understand where these teen moms are
coming from,'' Benson says. ``And my heart just goes out to these
babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar's nursery started as a laboratory in the school's
vocational education program in the early '70s, serving children in
the community. It is still a classroom and laboratory, ``only now
we take care of our students' children,'' says director Mary
Molnar.
</P>
<P>
   Currently 25 inmates and toddlers are in the nursery, and their
mothers can see them between classes and at lunch. Student mothers
arrive by bus at 7 a.m., bogged down with babies, pumpkin seats,
book bags and diaper bags. The babies aren't admitted into the
nursery after 7:30 a.m.; they can only stay while their parents are
in school.
</P>
<P>
   Molnar, 52, remembers how pregancies were handled when she was
in high school: Girls came down with some vague ``illness,'' were
sent to live with an aunt, and came home, miraculously recovered _
and without the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the nursery were not here, there would still be
pregnancies, but there would be more dropouts,'' Molnar says.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar principal Leon Love concurs: ``We're being more realistic
than when I was in school. We're enabling them to continue their
education so they become productive citizens instead of being on
welfare rolls.''
</P>
<P>
   Typhanie Wagner, a 17-year-old senior, said the availability of
day care didn't have anything to do with her getting pregnant; that
was an accident. But finding child care for 5-month-old Donte had
everything to do with her decision to stay in school. Being
responsible for Donte has made her more serious about her studies.
``I've got to make a life for me and him,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she discourages her friends from following her path.
``It's a burden,'' she tells them. ``You don't get to be a
teen-ager. You have to make sure your baby has everything first.''
</P>
<P>
   Brianna Ware, 17, a vocational student, says that working in the
nursery has provided an example of what not to do. ``It's helping
me to know I don't want to have kids right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner doesn't mind setting that kind of example. Just don't
take it out on her son. He's nobody's ``love child,'' nobody's
``second best.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These babies didn't do anything,'' she says, ``it was the male
and the female. ``
</P>
<P>
   Yes, 1968 was a very, very long time ago. Look around, and
you'll see lots of changes, good and bad, in the messages we send
about teen-agers and sex.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar's day care center is one of the good ones.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
