<SLUG> BC-SHARP-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jaguar strives for feel of elegance with new S-Type
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the words of the president of Jaguar Cars North America, Mike
Dale, there are two reasons people purchase automobiles. The first
is for basic transportation; the second is a perception that a
certain vehicle adds something to the quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   Noting there are a number of vehicles that provide fine basic
transportation, he explained that it was Jaguar's purpose to add
much more, but specifically to add elegance to the lifestyle of
Jaguar drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Building on this concept, Jaguar introduced at this month's
Birmingham, England, motor show the new S-Type. Inspired but not
limited by the popular Mark II S-Type models of the 1960s, the
all-new S-Type captures the traditional proportion and stance of a
sporty, European sedan.
</P>
<P>
   The S-Type's elliptical vertical-bar grille is perhaps its
strongest visual link to its Jaguar lineage. This grille has been a
symbol of the marque since the introduction of the XK120 sports
cars. The tradition of elegant Jaguar interiors also continues with
the new S-Type.
</P>
<P>
   The S-Type also has a host of more sporty and technical features
than typically found in current Jags. Beginning with the power
plants, the S-Type will be available with a 240-horsepower V-6 or a
281-hp V-8.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguar intends to compete with cars from BMW and Mercedes-Benz
by focusing technology toward customer convenience. An industry
first will be voice-activated controls for a telephone and audio
and climate controls.
</P>
<P>
   The S-Type will offer a dynamic stability control system, an
integrated navigation system and a satellite-based emergency
messaging system. A rear-bumper-mounted sensor system alerts the
driver to rear obstacles. Rain-sensitive wipers automatically
adjust blade frequency. Dual-zone climate controls and an in-dash
six-disc CD changer highlight creature comforts.
</P>
<P>
   The S-Type will be built in Jaguar's new Castle Bromwich
manufacturing plant, part of Ford Motor Co.'s investment. Outgoing
Ford Chief Executive Officer Alex Trotman once said that it was not
the elephant's (Ford) intention to stand on the toes of the cat
(Jaguar), but rather to protect it so as to enable it to run.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 model year S-Type is expected to arrive in showrooms in
the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp is a training consultant to auto manufacturers. Her
column is written for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. Write her
in care of Wheels, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689,
Atlanta, GA 30302. Or send comments online to
sharpdriver(at)worldnet.att.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
