A8789 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANATEES-WATER03-COX     11-02 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANATEES-WATER03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Resolution for warm manatee habitat being sought
 &HT;    By Sally D. Swartz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ A plan to create solar-heated underwater
showers for the Moore's Creek manatees is making waves between
manatee-lovers and environmental agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The gentle sea cows have visited the creek each winter for
years, basking in the warm water discharged from a nearby Fort
Pierce Utilities Authority power plant.
</P>
<P>
   But the plant, operating less often under a new agreement to
pool power with other utilities, is generating less warm water.
</P>
<P>
   So Liberta Scotto, director of the Manatee Observation and
Education Center, built in 1996 at the mouth of the creek, proposed
the showers as a two-year experiment.
</P>
<P>
   The Waterfront Council offered $5,000 toward the $45,000
project, and, along with St. Lucie County Conservation Alliance,
backed Scotto's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine it as like the showers in gym class,'' the Waterfront
Council's John Parry said. ``There would be a long pipe underwater
with 12 to 20 nozzles blowing warm water. Each manatee would have
its own warm water shower.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental agencies have had mixed reactions.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Environmental Protection's water facilities
administrator OK'd the plan as long as chlorine isn't used to clean
the underwater plumbing and water temperatures are monitored.
</P>
<P>
   David W. Arnold, head of the DEP's bureau of protected species
in Tallahassee, is opposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want folks to think we're cold-hearted about the
plight of the manatees,'' Arnold said. ``I wish we could do
research at a number of different power plants for a number of
years so we could feel comfortable in making the best choice _ get
rid of all warm water discharges, maintain them, or let nature take
its course.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Turner, with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, thought the
plan had merits but considers it ``premature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've formed a group to look at the warm-water issue in a
broad way. It could be good, it could be bad. We recommended she
defer it.''
</P>
<P>
   Scotto said she'd redesign the experiment if the agencies would
tell her what's wrong with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't like the idea of heating the water,'' said
Waterfront Council member Jeanne Hearn. ``But we aren't doing any
more by heating it than the utility did by shutting it off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All I was trying to do was get the study up and running, to
see the impact of solar-heated water on our visiting manatees,''
Scotto said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the agencies have the authority to enforcing a ban on
the showers is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd have to decide if it was actually harming the animals,''
Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Manatee Center stands to lose human visitors if
the manatees look for warmer water elsewhere. The center, which
draws 50,000 manatee-watchers during the winter season, will
continue as an environmental education center. But the manatees are
its major attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer manatees showed up last winter when less warm water flowed
into Moore's Creek, Scotto said. But the water everywhere was
warmer last year because of El Nino, so the manatees may have felt
less need to visit Moore's Creek.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Valade, wildlife biologist with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service in Jacksonville, said studies of manatee travel patterns,
using radio tag tracking identifying manatees by their scars where
large groups are gathered, indicate they're individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some go to the same site every year, knowing they can feed and
keep warm there. Others move to three or four warm water sites
throughout the winter. Some stay at one site two or three years and
then move on,'' Valade said.
</P>
<P>
   So predicting what will happen at Moore's Creek, with or without
the showers, is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Elie Boudreaux, director of the Fort Pierce Utilities Authority,
doubts the showers would make much difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of heat they would provide is minuscule,''
Boudreaux said.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't convinced the manatees have a problem. Runoff from the
land keeps Moore's Creek slightly warmer than surrounding waters
anyway, Boudreaux said.
</P>
<P>
   And the utility operates the plant based on its own needs and
those of a Vero Beach plant. During cold weather in this area, the
plant definitely would be operating. It also could operate, for
example, if a cold snap hits Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   In north Florida, some power plants agree to provide warm water
for manatees even if they aren't generating.
</P>
<P>
   Scotto's discouraged about the prospects for her experiment.
``Everyone's sitting on the fence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She plans to concentrate on other projects _ the center's new
butterfly garden, aquariums, 3-dimensional mural. And its gift shop
with 600 manatee items.
</P>
<P>
   Sally D. Swartz writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
