<HEADER>
A8815 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-$ADV06-N     11-02 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-$ADV06-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSE NOW HOW TO BEHAVE
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Dr. Joy Browne, a licensed psychologist, has joined the New
York Times Syndicate to give your readers the warm, friendly _ and
professional _ advice that she supplies to 9 million listeners in
the United States and Canada through the WOR Radio Network. Her
weekly Q&AMP;A column, ``Dr.Joy,'' will answer readers' questions about
personal relationships that are key in having happy and productive
lives.) 
 FOR USE FRI., NOV. 6, OR ANYTIME THEREAFTER. 
 By DR. JOY BROWNE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUESTION: Here I am at age 28 with a boyfriend who says I
shouldn't get mad at him when he hollers because he grew up in a
family where everybody screamed at each other. He says his family
is more dysfunctional than mine. _ Hollywood, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: Jeez! Dueling dysfunctions? I don't think you want to
go there and I definitely don't. Everybody's family _ and I do mean
everybody's _ is dysfunctional. I'm not sure where this national
obsession with blame began, but it's past time to put the
family-as-doomed-destiny thing to rest. We choose how we behave. If
you're unhappy about your boyfriend's behavior, talk with him about
it. Don't let him duck the issue by invoking the Ghost of Family
Past. The dysfunctional family blues are a variation of ``Woe is
me.'' Let's all repeat together: ``I'm in charge of my own life.
I'm responsible. I can function.''
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: I feel guilty all the time. I don't spend enough time
with my kids. My wife complains that I'm cold and indifferent. My
mother, recently widowed, needs me. I'm in the really competitive
field of sales, so my free time is limited, but I try to get in a
couple of workouts each week because my dad had a bad ticker. I
can't please anyone, and when I find some time for myself, I feel
even worse. What should I do? _ Wheeling, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: First, take a deep breath here and relax. Guilt is
feeling good about feeling bad, and it's a colossal waste of time.
You've got a lot on your plate. Feeling tired and under the gun all
the time doesn't help anyone. Adding a huge dollop of guilt will
only sap more time and energy.
</P>
<P>
   Sort through your priorities and get better at scheduling. If
you block out specific time to spend with your kids and schedule
private time for you and your wife to keep the spark alive, your
loved ones won't feel they have to beg for your attention. Make
sure you budget some time for yourself _ even if that means going
grocery shopping after work without the kids.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: I'm afraid to let anyone get close to me because I've
been hurt too often. I know the right person will be patient. But
at 44, I've sure kissed a lot of frogs while looking for that
handsome, understanding prince. I'm really a good person. Why am I
still alone? _ Fort Pierce, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: Everyone over 16 feels at some point that someone's
done 'em wrong and they're probably right. But this is the time to
take some emotional risks, not wallow in self-pity. I'm not
suggesting you march down to the harbor and pick up the first
sailor you meet. I am suggesting that it's time to get out of your
own way.
</P>
<P>
   Try the ``life is a daring risk or it's nothing at all''
blueprint for a month or two. Come out of your shell a bit. This
may mean taking tango lessons or flirting at the bus stop or
knocking that chip off your shoulder. You're making all those
inattentive men the bad guys. If you're a bristly ball of anger,
everyone will stay away.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: My boyfriend and I have been living together for a
year, and I want to get married. I work for him because he's trying
to get his business off the ground. We're living in his house,
which I'm helping to fix up. I love him, but I'm upset because but
every time I bring up the ``m'' word, he changes the subject. _
Stockton, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: You write ``welcome'' on your forehead and then you're
surprised when he steps on your face. Your boyfriend isn't
exploiting you. YOU are exploiting you.
</P>
<P>
   If you want your boyfriend to marry you, set a deadline and tell
him about it. If he refuses, move out and get on with your life. No
tears or cajolery. And don't even think about ``accidentally''
getting pregnant. If he wants to spend the rest of his life with
you, give him the opportunity to sort it out. If not, volunteer
with Habitat for Humanity to fix up someone else's home.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: My parents divorced 16 years ago when I was 3. I
always thought Dad abandoned us. I've recently gotten in touch with
him and he says Mom and her parents said they'd sic the law on him
if he didn't clear out. I don't know who's telling the truth and
who's lying. _ Salem, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: A long time ago somebody said there are three sides to
every story: my side, your side and the truth. I think this person
was overly optimistic. Most of us can figure out several
``sensible'' versions to support our perspective.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to worry if one of your folks is lying. They
could both be telling the truth -- THEIR version of the truth. If
you look for your own version and leave them to do the same, you
can save a whole lot of wear and tear on your head, heart and
internal organs.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   For information on subscribing to Dr. Joy, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Dr. Joy Browne, c/o The New York Times
Syndication Sales Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, NY 10168.
Questions of general interest will be answered in this weekly
column. Dr. Joy regrets that unpublished letters cannot be answered
individually.
</P>
