<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Nov. 2, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GOVERNOR (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Republican Attorney
General Dan Lungren and Democratic Lt. Gov. Gray Davis vying for
the state's governorship Tuesday have little to fight over but the
tired ghosts of their own pasts, with no controversial ballot
initiative shadowing the race. The result has been one of the most
conventional gubernatorial campaigns in recent memory. By ROBERT
SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-SENATE (San Francisco) _ In a volatile race with momentum
see-sawing between the candidates, incumbent Democrat Barbara Boxer
and Republican challenger Matt Fong are in a dead heat in the
campaign for U.S. Senate, according to a poll by The San Francisco
Examiner and station KTVU. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   FLUORIDE (Mountain View, Calif.) _ While most Americans have
fluoridated water coming out of their taps, just 17 percent of
Californians do, placing the state 47th in the nation in rates of
fluoridation. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAIMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-BECKER (Undated) _ Are you ready for another Archie Bunker?
That's exactly what the producers of ``Becker'' are hoping because
this Ted Danson vehicle is all about being politically incorrect.
And that's a good thing, really. TV has become so safe and devoid
of sharp edges that it's boring beyond its normal level. By TIM
GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-DEATH (New York) _ Susan Minot wanted to imagine the
process of slowly dying. And so she began her fourth book and her
third novel, ``Evening,'' told from the point of view of a woman
dying of ovarian cancer, consumed by pain and memories, including a
once &UR; - &LR; repressed recollection of what seems now to have been the
most important weekend in her life _ an eventful wedding 40 years
earlier at which she'd fallen hopelessly in love. By JOAN SMITH.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BRANSON (Branson, Mo.) _ If the King of Rock 'n' Roll were
alive, he would have his own theater in Branson, musical capital of
the nation. People flock here at a rate of some 5.5 million a year.
A market survey puts Branson in the top 20 destination cities,
right up there with Orlando, Las Vegas and Myrtle Beach, S.C. By
JULIE COOPER
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BARGE (Undated) _ The River Explorer is a daring and
innovative venture that offers an unusual perspective of America's
inland waterways from two connected barges propelled by a
3,000-horsepower towboat. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ I did a double take the first time I
saw the message in a hotel bathroom in British Columbia several
years back. It read: ``Please rehang towels for use a second day;
only towels left on the floor or in the tub will be replaced.''
Working together to protect our environment is a win-win situation
for the traveler and those in the industry. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Summer phlox grows well in a
well-draining soil. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Green Bay, Wis.) _ It was the obvious question, and
Tim McDonald gave what seems to be the obvious answer. The San
Francisco 49ers are squat for their last five against the Green Bay
Packers, so what's the grand truth to be gleaned? ``That we'd
better not lose six in a row,'' he said with a helpless smile. By
RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A duck hunt with San Francisco
Giants manager Dusty Baker is the grand prize in a drawing for
junior hunters who sign up as a member with the California
Waterfowl Association. Phone: (916) 648-1406. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Someone recently suggested that
it would be a good idea to require candidates for public office to
participate in debates. The idea certainly is tempting but, alas,
would likely violate the First Amendment. Freedom of speech also
includes the freedom not to speak. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Election campaigns are
instructive, but rarely in the ways that the politicians intend.
This year, if anything, the campaigns seem more burdened with
absurdities. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   HEAVY-TRUCKS (San Antonio) _ One of the reasons cited for
keeping Mexican trucks out of the United States is the fear that
overweight trucks would create safety problems and damage U.S.
highways. What few people know, though, is Texas allows thousands
of trucks daily to operate over the weight limits by issuing
special permits that cost a fraction of the damage caused to roads
and bridges. By DAVID HENDRICKS.
</P>
