<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, November 3, 1998 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The best part of taking 74
eighth_graders to the zoo is bringing all 74 of them back. The boss
is kind of picky about coming out even, I remind myself as I watch
the buses load. Four teachers, eight parent chaperones, four
coolers filled with bottled water, fruit, cookies, and enough ham
and cheese sandwiches to feed the economy section of a 747. I guess
we're ready to go. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Pop songs are like time
machines. Take the Supremes' hit ``Love Child,'' which topped the
charts 30 years ago. It's one of those pop songs that, to put it
kindly, remind you that 1968 was a very, very long time ago. It's
about a woman born to an unmarried mother and determined not to let
the same thing happen to a child of her own. It's hard for Janice
Benson to imagine ``Love Child'' becoming a hit today. The kids she
works with just couldn't identify. The lyrics seem quaint as a lace
doily. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
