</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8839 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-LOCK03-COX     11-02 3078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-LOCK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Analyst says 'hold' Saf T Lok because of SEC probe
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's rare when a gathering in the White
House Rose Garden makes investors dizzy for a small-cap stock.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what happened a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Saf T Lok, a small gun-lock manufacturer based in West
Palm Beach, had fallen to a dismal 37 cents a share in late
September of last year. The company had lost $733,790 in the first
nine months of the year on disappointing sales, according to
filings with the Securities and Exchange Commission, and was facing
delisting by the Nasdaq Stock Market. Then President Clinton
stepped into the Rose Garden on Thursday, Oct. 9, 1997, with eight
major gun manufacturers. He extracted their pledge to put locks on
every gun sold, launching Saf T Lok's second life.
</P>
<P>
   In two days, Saf T Lok's share price soared 11-fold. In four
days, it cut a financing deal that assured its place on Nasdaq and
gave it capital for the future.
</P>
<P>
   It was the company's highest point. Before and since, Saf T Lok,
10 years old next year, has stumbled. In the past two years alone,
it has dumped two chief executives. It's also fighting two
shareholder lawsuits that allege it hyped its stock and has
depended on offshore investments to keep it afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Saf T Lok officials have not returned repeated phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The company's problems worsened in July when the SEC launched an
informal investigation into the company's accounting practices and
a shareholder filed suit, claiming he and other shareholders were
misled by the company. A second shareholder's suit was filed in
August. The suits are pending, and attorneys have asked to combine
them into a single suit, said Neil Zola, an attorney for
shareholder Joseph Yud. The SEC's inquiry is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Saf T Lok Chief Executive Frank Brooks defended his company in
September at its annual meeting of shareholders. Saf T Lok has nine
patents to its credit after nine years in operation, and finally is
ready to start marketing its locks, Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a shareholder, too. I'd like to get these out to the
market just like you,'' Brooks told shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's stock has fallen to just over $1 a share from
more than $5, and for a reason, said analyst Cheryl Bostater of
Chatfield Dean &AMP; Co., a stockbrokerage in Greenwood Village, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Bostater has recommended that investors ``hold'' Saf T Lok
because of the SEC's informal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always a major distraction, at the very least, and I'm
not sure what's going to come from it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Saf T Lok touts its locks as superior to other gun safety
devices, such as trigger locks and lock boxes, because the latter
need keys. The Saf T Lok, incorporated into a handgun's grip, works
by depressing three small plungers, each keyed to a number in a
combination. A gun can be unlocked the dark.
</P>
<P>
   A locked gun can't be fired, but when it is needed _ say, when
there's a burglar in the house _ it can be released quickly for
use, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   The company doesn't conceal its giant-size obstacle to posting a
profit. The retail price of the gun lock is $90. Adding that to the
average gun cost, and the typical gun owner ``has to be seriously
motivated about gun safety ... to add 30 percent onto the price of
the gun'' to use a Saf T Lok, the company said in SEC documents.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Miller, chairman of the Coalition of New Jersey
Sportsmen, issued a warning letter to his group's members about Saf
T Lok in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company says they're the only lock that can be used on a
loaded gun. That goes against one of the prime safety premises:
You'd never put a trigger lock on a loaded gun. It's a good way to
shoot yourself (accidentally),'' Miller said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Saf T Lok, started in 1989, was a private company looking for
capital until Feb. 13, 1996, when it bought publicly traded RGB
Computer &AMP; Video of Riviera Beach in a stock deal. RGB had been
losing money, selling video-editing systems tied to the antiquated
Commodore computer system.
</P>
<P>
   Within a month, the new company found itself in controversy. The
Wall Street Journal reported that government agencies and companies
that supposedly had endorsed the company's locks _ the Secret
Service among them _ denied they had done so. The company blamed it
on casual statements made to its public relations firm, which in
turn repeated the ``endorsements'' in promotional pamphlets. The
stock fell by $2.25 a share to $5.63.
</P>
<P>
   In less than two months, RGB soon was on the rise again. An
investment newsletter _ one that doesn't demand or accept
reimbursement for stock recommendations _ touted the new gun lock.
The stock then hit a high of $19 in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The company soon changed its name to Saf T Lok, and executives
demonstrated the lock at the company's first meeting for
shareholders after the RGB deal. Shareholders were giddy about the
rise in the stock price, even though the company had sold only 500
locks.
</P>
<P>
   But Saf T Lok couldn't stay away from trouble. In November 1996,
Brooks hired and fired a new chief executive, Lisa Broderick, or
she quit on her own, depending on whom you believe, bringing on
more controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The company said in a news release that Broderick left after
only eight days because of ``differences with the company,'' but
Brooks told Bloomberg News he fired her because she didn't come up
with $7 million she promised to invest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw her out the door,'' he said. He later backpedaled,
saying she left on her own.
</P>
<P>
   Broderick sent a scathing resignation letter to Brooks two days
before the announcement of her leaving. In the letter, which was
submitted in Broderick's suit against Saf T Lok, she complained
that five of the company's 12 employees were family members and ``3
to 4 additional employees were apparently incompetent.'' She also
described Saf T Lok as ``a technically bankrupt, deeply troubled
company.'' Broderick's attorney would not comment when contacted.
</P>
<P>
   The suit by Broderick and her husband was filed in Martin County
Circuit Court, claiming libel, slander and loss of consortium. The
suit is awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving, Broderick had suggested seeking investors in
Italy, using the SEC's Regulation S, Brooks said, according to the
lawsuit. He was opposed to it, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   But in the next year, that's what Brooks did. Regulation S stock
usually is sold offshore at a discount, and the deals require less
disclosure to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Garden factor
</P>
<P>
   From April to November last year, the company sold almost 1.7
million shares of stock in four so-called Reg S sales to offshore
investors, bringing in more than $3 million, SEC documents show.
</P>
<P>
   The final sale last November followed Clinton's Rose Garden
meeting. It required Saf T Lok to hire as business consultant New
York-based A.B. &AMP; Associates and Las Vegas-based Marketing Direct
Concepts as its public relations firm, and that they be paid from
the proceeds, SEC documents show.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing firm went right to work in mid-January of this
year, issuing six news releases about Saf T Lok in 16 working days.
The releases covered the company's new chief executive, John
Gardner, testifying before the New York City Council on the need
for gun safety legislation, about an order for $560,000 in gun
locks from a new national distributor, United Safety Action, and
about patents the company had earned for its locks.
</P>
<P>
   New York-based United Safety Action is run by Arthur Braun of
Monsey, N.Y. In February of this year, Saf T Lok announced Braun
had agreed to buy $20 million in gun locks over two years, and
would join Saf T Lok in a $5 million advertising campaign,
according to a company news release.
</P>
<P>
   About nine months later, Braun says he is just finishing work on
the advertising campaign and an agency is negotiating with national
magazines to place the ads. He expected the ads to start running
``in the next couple of months.'' He was unsure how much they would
cost.
</P>
<P>
   But back in February, before the company made the Braun
announcement, it was blind-sided by two news releases from a New
York-based stock trading company, Quantum Group Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   A trader at Quantum, Steve Ehlers, said in a release that it was
his opinion that Saf T Lok was ``being hyped up to unrealistic
levels that are unsustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehlers was critical of the company's deal with offshore
investors because it funneled $2 million in ``incentives'' to
consultants. He questioned the sale of 665,000 shares of Saf T Lok
stock by executives. Some investors see the sale of stock by
executives as a sign of impending trouble for a company.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Quantum statement, Saf T Lok stock nearly had doubled
in value in the short time after the company's new marketing firm
had begun firing off news releases. After each release, its stock
would creep upward. Then came Quantum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quantum believes this is a pump-and-dump scheme,'' Quantum's
release said. ``The company's aggressive focus on the price of the
stock is very alarming.''
</P>
<P>
   A ``pump-and-dump scheme'' is when a company seeks to inflate
the price of its stock so insiders can then sell their shares at a
higher profit.
</P>
<P>
   Quantum acknowledged that it was a short seller of the stock,
however, betting that it would drop in value.
</P>
<P>
   Insider trading
</P>
<P>
   There was heavy insider selling at Saf T Lok, records show.
After Clinton's announcement, the company's stock price jumped
nearly 600 percent, and a rash of insider selling began.
</P>
<P>
   Before the president's statement on Oct. 9 last year, the last
time an insider sold stock was July 30, records show. But on the
day of the announcement, Brooks sold 69,000 shares for a total
$204,240. By the end of the month, Brooks had shed 179,000 shares
for a total $697,700. Gardner sold 200,000 shares for a total
$515,300. Brooks' son, Jeffrey, a vice president, had unloaded
48,000 shares taking in $152,160, Chief Engineer Eugene Horanoff
had sold 47,000 shares for $163,665, and Director William Schmidt
had sold 34,300 shares for $156,505. Brooks and his son, and
Schmidt, still own shares in the company as of Aug. 10 this year.
</P>
<P>
   1.5 million shares sold
</P>
<P>
   Following the sales, Saf T Lok stock began dropping _ until Oct.
22, when the company announced that former U.S. Sen. Dennis
DeConcini, D.-Ariz. and former U.S. Rep. James Stanton, D-Ohio, had
signed on as directors. The announcement boosted the stock price
for two days before it began to falter again. Each holds 255,000
shares of Saf T Lok stock, according to the company's proxy, dated
Aug. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are getting us in places we wouldn't have been able to go
to,'' Brooks said at the annual stockholders meeting. ``They're
earning their keep.''
</P>
<P>
   According to CDA/Investnet, a research firm in Fort Lauderdale,
insiders of Saf T Lok have sold 1.5 million shares since Saf T Lok
bought RGB less than two years ago, with the largest chunk sold by
Brooks, the founder. He sold more than 570,000 shares. He holds
almost 11 percent of the company's stock, according to Saf T Lok's
proxy statement.
</P>
<P>
   Saf T Lok is not without support from some analysts. Howard
Stillman, a New York broker, and Craig Woodward of Woodward Trading
in Atlanta have endorsed the company based on increasing awareness
of the need for gun safety. This year, Stillman predicted a $20 to
$40 share price within 12 to 24 months; Woodward gave a target
price of $30 a share in 12 months and $12 to $15 in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   The stock has not risen above $5.22 a share in the past year,
and its average was $2.77.
</P>
<P>
   Ehlers, the short-seller at Quantum, and Stillman and Woodward
could not be reached for comment. None is certified as an analyst
with the Association for Investment Management and Research, an
industry group that tests prospective analysts and then registers
those who pass those tests. Neither is Bostater, the Chatfield Dean
&AMP; Co. analyst who recommends a ``hold'' on Saf T Lok stock.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts don't have to be certified, but the designation is
sought by mainstream investment houses. All are securities brokers,
according to the National Association of Securities Dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Bostater projected a target price of $10 a share in the next 12
to 24 months. She based her projection on the company's recent
orders with two distributors. But that was before Saf T Lok's
announcement in July that it is under an SEC informal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's waiting to see some progress from Saf T Lok before
issuing a new target price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't feel comfortable putting out another target with
management still up in the air, and the SEC is still a concern,''
she said. ``Part of it, too, is seeing a track record of results.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's latest troubles began July 21, when trading of Saf
T Lok on the Nasdaq Stock Market was halted for part of the day on
news that it might restate its first-quarter results. It also said
the SEC had launched the informal inquiry. In an informal
investigation, the SEC requests that the company submit documents
voluntarily. In a formal inquiry, the SEC can subpoena documents.
</P>
<P>
   Saf T Lok's auditors, Goldberg Persches &AMP; Co., had expressed
concern about the value of warrants to buy 2 million shares of
company stock for $5 a share, according to SEC documents. The
warrants were issued in February to United Safety Action as part of
its deal to distribute products for Saf T Lok, according to
documents filed with the SEC. The stock was trading for as much as
$5.21 a share in February. As of Aug. 10, United Safety Action
owned 1 million shares of Saf T Lok, or 7.3 percent of the company,
according to Saf T Lok's proxy.
</P>
<P>
   The company hired an appraiser to help auditors decide how to
value the warrants and ultimately decided that it wouldn't have to
restate its results.
</P>
<P>
   Then the shareholder lawsuits began. Law firms in Fort
Lauderdale and New York filed against the company. It accused the
company of lying to investors in a May 26 news release on a deal
with Semiconductor Laser International Corp. to co-develop ``an
optical laser-driven fingerprint locking mechanism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see we are being set up by this,'' Brooks told
shareholders at this year's annual meeting. ``We feel confident we
didn't break any laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward issued his $30-a-share projection the day after the
laser deal was announced. The company's stock rose $1.25 a share on
17 million shares traded. For comparison, IBM's average trading
volume is less than 4 million shares a day on 972 million shares
outstanding as of the end of the third quarter of 1997. Saf T Lok
had almost 7 million shares outstanding at the end of that same
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Deal too costly
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said he later canceled the laser deal because it would
have cost the company $2 million to $3 million in research and
development, and fired Chief Executive Gardner after 14 months on
the job. But the lawsuit accuses Saf T Lok management of knowing
the laser deal would never have resulted in a product breakthrough,
and that Woodward's projection was overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Semiconductor Laser) had no experience with fingerprint
recognition and did not have the capability to actually carry out
the proposed development of the technology,'' the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   Early last month, Gardner filed his own suit against Saf T Lok
and Brooks, saying he was libeled and fired without cause, and was
not allowed to exchange options for nearly 1 million shares of
stock. Gardner would not comment when reached.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, the company got a big break when one of its
distributors, Endzone USA, signed Sports Authority to a gun lock
order valued at $35,000. But Bostater is still unsure what to make
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely good news. But it's impossible to tell how
successful sales are on the retail level at this point,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At Saf T Lok's annual meeting of shareholders in September,
Brooks said the company finally is in a position to sell its
products. It has been slowed by lack of cash and bad timing. It had
spent all its money to develop the Saf T Lok when it realized that
half the market had handguns with magazines _ cartridges that hold
bullets and can be installed quickly. Saf T Lok's product was not
developed for such guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stopped our marketing effort to work on the new lock. We
had to raise more money and develop a new product,'' Brooks said at
the shareholders meeting. ``We were broke and struggling. The only
thing we could do is go for a Reg S (overseas financing plan).''
</P>
<P>
   It raised $2 million, got $1 million up-front from a New
York-based distributor and developed a marketing strategy. ``The
strategy is for them to fill the pipeline for the residential
market and Saf T Lok to go after law enforcement,'' Brooks said at
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The company has delivered its first shipments of 25,000 locks to
the distributor and has moved into a larger building in the
Northpoint Corporate Park in West Palm Beach, where it employs 30
to 35 people to assemble the locks.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, his son Jeffrey who is also a director of the company,
and Steve Eccher, Saf T Lok's vice president of marketing, have
been meeting with police departments and sheriff's offices to hawk
their product. One department in Illinois has made it mandatory for
officers to use gun locks when off duty. Last month, the company
gave locks to Palm Beach County sheriff's deputies to try out. But
it takes time for police chiefs and sheriffs to get approval to
spend money on equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The route we're taking in law enforcement is a real long-term
route,'' Brooks said at the shareholders meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks also told shareholders he believes the company will do
better than the dismal financial showing of last year, when it lost
$5.3 million on $15,926 in sales. If the company can produce sales,
its stock price will rise, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every company has these things happen,'' Brooks, who owns 1.49
million shares of the company's stock as of Aug. 10, told
shareholders. ``People want to know if we're hyping the stock, if
we're doing something wrong. We're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Saf T Lock stock closed Friday at $1.34 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Pounds writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
