<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ ATLANTA _ I recently attended a public hearing
held by the Georgia Environmental Protection Division. The turnout
was small _ a handful of auto industry representatives and state
bureaucrats. We in the auto repair industry weren't required to be
there. We didn't go because the subject matter was especially
spectacular. The agenda item we had come to hear and object to was
the extension of the $200 waiver limit for vehicles failing the
metro Atlanta area's emission test _ and continuing to contribute
to the deterioration of Atlanta's air quality. The waiver limit
means cars that fail the state's emission test can be granted a
waiver _ and permission to get new tags for two years _ if the
owner spends at least $200 fixing the car and it shows some
improvement. (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ Surely all of us, at one time or a have
wondered how it would be to have our consciousness transplanted
into that of another, to see and understand from the viewpoint of
someone else. My encounters with software conceived and whelped in
France lead me to believe that entering the mind of a Gallic
software designer would be like walking into a carnival funhouse
for the first time. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Every time I download a new version of Netscape
Communicator or Microsoft Internet Explorer _ the two most popular
programs for browsing the World Wide Web _ I am reminded of a
multi-function of a Swiss Army knife. The competition has gotten so
heated between the two Web browsers that each tries hard to outdo
the other by loading in new features. There are so many I truly
can't remember what all of them do. And since I don't use them, I
never get reminded. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ Parents don't much care for it, but that hasn't
stopped ``Quake'' from being a hit with male children of all ages.
Now the third version of the gory shoot-'em-up is set for release,
and the November issue of PC Gamer has a sneak preview. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ No question about it. The iMac is one
sharp-looking computer. But is it a good buy? I'd argue not. A
better investment would be any of Apple Computer's G3 desktop
models. Now, before you start flaming me with e-mail charges of
betrayal, let me explain. I consider the iMac a good, if not great,
computer. It works reasonably well, has a brilliantly sharp screen
and, of course, there's that striking bondi translucent body. But a
computer is a lot more than looks.(Haddad , Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ Election Day is here, but there's still time to bone
up on the candidates and the issues on the Web. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ A cellular phone without a battery is like a
doughnut without its hole. Maybe that's overstating things a bit,
but batteries are crucial. In the name of making batteries that
last longer, Duracell recently rolled out its Ultra line of
refillable alkaline battery packs. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
