<HEADER>
A8847 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN03-COX     11-02 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MAKING TRACKS ACROSS EUROPE: The gamble of Monte Carlo
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (EDITOR'S NOTE: Joe Murray has been traveling around Western
Europe by train. This is one in a series of stories.)
</P>
<P>
   MONTE CARLO TO MILAN _ Everyone knows Monaco's real-life fairy
tale of love and romance, movie queen marries prince.
</P>
<P>
   I know another one. I met her by chance on the train between
Monte Carlo and Milan.
</P>
<P>
   Close your eyes and it's as if you were listening to Greta
Garbo. Such is Kathleen's Swedish accent.
</P>
<P>
   Open your eyes and you won't want to close them again. Such is
Kathleen's beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Tall and willowy, with blondish brown hair, blue eyes and lovely
features, she's the kind of young woman you'd think would be a
fashion model. You'd think right.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen became a model at age 16 in Sweden after being spotted
on the street by a woman whose job it was to be on the lookout for
girls with the right kind of looks.
</P>
<P>
   That in itself was a fairy tale of sorts, how she toured much of
the world _ Europe, America and Asia _ with the fashion runway as
her stage.
</P>
<P>
   But that part of the story is only prologue. Besides, it wasn't
so glamorous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' Kathleen said, frowning a beautiful frown. ``In
the evening it was fun, and it was fun when you traveled. But the
work is very stressful, and it is dull.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was that she came to Monte Carlo, for a fashion show, and
that's where her husband-to-be saw her for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   After just one week, they became as one. They've been married
for six months. She is 25. He is 32. And it is paradise, such is
life as a newlywed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, to hear Kathleen tell it, this is paradise in paradise,
such is life in Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call it the Doll City,'' Kathleen said, ``because
everything is so pretty, so clean and so nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it is really nice to live in Monaco. You have people from
all over the world here, and all of them living in good harmony
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Really nice, but really expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The smallest apartment costs more than $1,250 a month to rent,
she said. To go out to eat, it is a minimum of $100 per person.
</P>
<P>
   But, yes, it's really nice, especially if your husband's family
has substantial investments in real estate. Imagine the value of
real estate in the doll-like principality of Monaco, only 368 acres
in size.
</P>
<P>
   Nice, too, to know the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie, the daughter of Prince Rainier and the late Princess
Grace, is a friend of Kathleen's husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is the one with the new baby,'' Kathleen said. ``She is
very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Without being asked, Kathleen adds:
</P>
<P>
   ``Her sister Caroline is very snobby.''
</P>
<P>
   But never mind that. ``We like the place,'' she said. ``It is
really calm, it is secure to walk around anywhere. You can go out
at midnight with all the gold and diamonds you have, and nothing
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   People are people everywhere. But in Monaco, it seems that the
police are something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing will happen to you in Monaco because we have lots of
police and security cameras everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   A police state, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no,'' Kathleen said, shaking her pretty head. ``All the
security, all the police, is because they don't want any bad
persons to come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no bad people here. The tourists who come to Monaco,
they don't have any problems, unless they do something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is very bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they have to leave immediately,'' Kathleen said, sadly.
``And they can never come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that I think about it, maybe this wasn't a fairy tale after
all. Perhaps it's more on the proportion of an epic poem.
</P>
<P>
   Paradise Lost, as it were.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
