   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Ayers Rock, or ``Uluru'' as it's called in Appalachian, is the
world's largest single stone monolith, rising 1,143 feet above
Australia's seemingly endless desert plain. It is as much a symbol
of the continent as Mt. Fuji is of Japan. It's also as steep a
climb as Masada in Israel, the Grand Canyon in the United States or
the Great Wall in China.
</P>
<P>
   Ayers Rock must exude some primal force that draws tourists from
faraway places, who view the sun rising and setting over it, walk
the six miles around its base and, in some cases, climb to its top.
</P>
<P>
   Among those attracted to this geologic wonder was Dennis
Cavagnaro, a veteran traveler from Oakland, Calif. Like many mature
travelers, he is a little overweight. Despite two hip replacements,
he refused to go quietly into his 60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't easy!'' Cavagnaro said. ``The reward of the climb is
the sense of achievement and the spectacular 360-degree view.''
</P>
<P>
   It's best to climb Ayers Rock early in the morning before the
direct, unfiltered sunlight makes it unbearably hot. An early start
also allows the breeze to keep away flies and other biting insects.
</P>
<P>
   The climbers in Cavagnaro's tour group piled out of bed in
pitch-black darkness so that they wouldn't miss the sunrise over
the rock. They had to travel 11 miles from the comfortable resort
at Yulara Village outside Uluru National Park, an Aboriginal
National Park leased to the Commonwealth of Australia. To enter the
park you must show your prepaid entrance ticket ($10) at the ranger
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't the first or last group to reach the western tip of
Uluru's base,'' Cavagnaro said. ``We could see a thin line of hardy
climbers already creeping vertically up the only approved trail.''
</P>
<P>
   The trail's only identifying mark is a low steel chain. Since
there are no other natural features on the rock, the climbers, at a
distance, could easily have passed for ants.
</P>
<P>
   At the base of the trail is a sign that explains how the
Aboriginal owners have given permission for people to climb the
rock, but the natives prefer that people don't. A sign also warns
climbers of the dangers: At least 26 climbers have perished on the
rock since 1965 _ 20 from heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the climb requires picking the most efficient
path through 200 yards of huge broken boulders. These have earned
the derisive name ``Chicken Rocks.'' It is here that many initially
intrepid climbers decide it's best to simply explore Uluru's base.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Chicken Rocks,'' there's another 200 yards of bare
surface sandstone which rises at about a 45-degree incline.
Cavagnaro says it's imperative that a climber's footwear have
``grip,'' because that's the only thing that can keep a person from
slipping back down the mountainside _ especially if it's windy.
</P>
<P>
   A steel chain was Cavagnaro's lifesaver. It was supported by
stanchions placed about every five yards. The stanchion is
suspended only two feet off the rock's surface. The low height
isn't a problem since climbers are already bent forward trying to
pull themselves up. The chain also affords some security for
resting and catching your breath.
</P>
<P>
   Rest stops proved to be heartbreaking, Cavagnaro says. He felt
as though he wasn't getting any closer to the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only measure of gain was to look back and see my progress
from the bottom, which looked smaller and smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   Depressions in the rock showed signs of occasional rainwater.
Cavagnaro was surprised by Uluru's scarred and striated surface _
it was much rougher than pictures had lead him to believe.
 &UR; 'OVER THE HILL' _ TO THE TOP &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cavagnaro's persistence finally paid off when, over a rolling
``hill,'' he saw the marker monument at the summit. The climb had
taken him an hour and a half.
</P>
<P>
   A younger climber, Sherry, had run to the top in 45 minutes. And
she paid the price. ``My thighs are screaming at me,'' she later
complained.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry had brought a pair of ballet slippers, donned them and
pirouetted on the peak. The climbers all posed for pictures before
beginning the descent.
</P>
<P>
   Cavagnaro's calves and thigh muscles, which had valiantly
carried him to the top, now were trembling, begging him to find the
slightest excuse to stop. He tried a variety of psychological and
physical tricks to compensate.
</P>
<P>
   Descending with his back to the rock, Cavagnaro enjoyed the
breathtaking, wide-angled vista before him. Letting go of the first
link of chain, he found it a bit frightening to negotiate the last
400 to 500 yards. All the muscles in his body were tight, his hips
were aching and he feared he would fall.
</P>
<P>
   At the base, his troupe of climbers all piled into a van and
headed back to their luxurious digs, Sailes in the Desert Hotel at
the Ayers Rock Resort. Their reward: a cooling plunge in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk just a bit taller these days,'' Cavagnaro now says. ``I
had met my self-imposed challenge. I was validated in my own eyes.
My next goal is to climb the mountain I consider to be one of the
ultimates _ Mt. Sinai, Jebel Sirbal.''
</P>
<P>
   A visa is required to enter Australia. Visitors should consider
staying a few extra days and renting a four-wheel-drive vehicle.
Alice Springs and a stop at the Frontier Camel Farm _ complete with
a camel ride along the Todd River _ make for a remarkable trip.
</P>
<P>
   All Ayers Rock tourist facilities are located at Ayers Rock
Resort, P.O. Box 10, Yulara, NT 0872, Australia; phone 562737 or
fax 562270.
 &UR; ----- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
</P>
<P>
   The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
