A8965 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     11-02 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ANTI-CLINTON TACK: WHAT IS THE GOP THINKING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hang on, folks. The negative, disgusting, sleazier-than-sleazy
election campaign of 1998 is almost over.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will end the misery on Tuesday when they go to the polls
and elect whichever candidates seemed most believable _ or least
offensive. Some might even be tempted to toss darts at the ballot
and just hope that fate can make a good decision.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how they go about it, conscientious voters will do
their best to fulfill their responsibility as citizens of the
greatest nation on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Less conscientious voters might use the gut-wrenching nastiness
of the campaign as an excuse to duck responsibility and stay away
from the polls, a course of nonaction that would certainly be
understandable but definitely not commendable.
</P>
<P>
   Voters need to vote. If you think the political process is
horrendous now, wait till you see what happens when right-minded
citizens stop voting.
</P>
<P>
   The experts are predicting one of the lowest turnouts of all
time, sad to say, which might explain why the Republican Party is
trying to motivate its base with a last-minute, $10 million
advertising campaign that urges voters to register their
disapproval of President Clinton by electing Republican candidates
to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   GOP strategists are denying that the purpose of the ads is to
turn the election into a referendum on Clinton. But what other
purpose could there be for an ad that demands: ``Reward Bill
Clinton. Or vote Republican''?
</P>
<P>
   The campaign reportedly was devised by House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, who knows a heck of a lot more about political strategy
than I do. But I can't help but wonder why Gingrich thinks it's a
good idea to fish for votes by attacking a president who has a job
approval rating of 68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And another thing, as long as I'm wondering: Why are Republicans
in Congress pushing so hard to impeach a president when polls say
that more than 70 percent of Americans don't want him impeached?
</P>
<P>
   It seems to me that all those folks who oppose impeachment might
just go out and vote Democratic in the expectation that more
Democrats in Congress would mean less likelihood of impeachment
proceedings against the Democratic president.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the GOP's anti-Clinton blitz, many pundits were
insisting that the election could have a major impact on Clinton's
future.
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans make big gains in the House and Senate, the
experts say, GOP leaders will interpret the election results as a
green light to charge ahead with impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if Republicans don't increase their grip on
Congress or they lose significant numbers of seats to the
Democrats, well, Gingrich and his cohorts would have to rethink
their impeachment strategy.
</P>
<P>
   That's a fairly tricky theory when you consider that most
congressional elections are decided on the basis of local issues.
If a congressional election is a referendum on anything, it's most
often a referendum on the quality of constituent service provided
by the incumbent officeholder.
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing that Gingrich knows full well that those
anti-Clinton ads won't make a major difference in most
congressional races. The ads are apparently designed to inflame
confirmed Clinton-haters and boost voter turnout in areas where
Republicans have an edge to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   If the strategy is effective, Republicans will have a rationale
for pursuing impeachment even if the election fails to provide a
clear-cut mandate for going after Clinton. They could just point
out that Republicans won big in districts where the anti-Clinton
ads were seen, meaning that the pro-impeachment crowd prevailed in
the so-called referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Republicans need any cover. As long as they retain
a majority in the House of Representatives, they have the power to
impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
   And if Republican leaders aren't deterred by polls suggesting
that nearly three-fourths of Americans oppose impeachment, there's
no reason to expect that a little thing like an election will make
them back off.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
