<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8969 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-02 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACING THE BLAME FOR TODAY'S POLITICAL CIRCUS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Election campaigns are instructive, but rarely in
the ways that the politicians intend. This year, if anything, the
campaigns seem more burdened with absurdities.
</P>
<P>
   The worst is how otherwise apparently intelligent people espouse
nonsense and non sequiturs when they run for office. They use
certain so-called hot-button issues to establish their credentials
and arouse a phlegmatic electorate. One of the sure-fire ones is to
ban the burning of flags.
</P>
<P>
   It gives the politicians from both major parties the chance to
wrap themselves in the flag. Of course, burning is the prescribed
way to dispose of worn or torn flags. So it is not the burning
itself that these politicians want to ban, it is the desecration of
the flag, a hallowed symbol.
</P>
<P>
   But the banners are selective in just what they consider
desecration. They do not oppose the commercial exploitation of the
flag. They voice no opposition to those who make swim suits and
underwear, shirts, pillow cases, and jeans patches from the flag.
They say not a word against car lots using the flag to sell their
products or doughnut emporia flying humongous flags in an effort to
suck in more customers.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not desecration at all that these pols are against, but
only one aspect of it, the political demonstration of burning the
flag, usually engaged in by hippies and other marginal outcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if the symbol of the American flag stands for anything, it
stands for free speech, even for toleration of the most obnoxious
sort.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these same super patriots support a ban on flag burning
paradoxically want the people (including the flag-burners?) to be
able to arm themselves against the possibility of their government
becoming oppressive.
</P>
<P>
   They say that's what the Second Amendment to the Constitution
provides. Well, not exactly; it provides for an armed militia. But
even reading the Constitution the way the gun aficionados would,
their reasoning falls short of landfall.
</P>
<P>
   There's no way in the world for the owner of a handgun to face
off against the forces of government. For this you would require
missiles, nuclear warheads, cannon, tanks, machine guns and other
heavy weaponry that have never enjoyed sanction even under the most
expansive reading of the Second Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the matter of bountiful campaign contributions and
the special favors that so often appear to be attached to them.
Normally sober men and women actually claim that there is no
connection between the donation of massive amounts of the dollars
and the beneficial government largess that is showered on to the
donors. It is merely a coincidence of political philosophies, or,
if you believe in miracles, it is a miracle. It is a game
candidates of both parties play, trotting out identical platitudes
to validate a system that reeks of favoritism on its better days,
and of corruption on its worst.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates say they are doing nothing illegal. The pity is they
are right, and in making this alibi have put their finger on the
problem. But it's not only fund-raising from interest parties that
is undermining the integrity of the political system. Under the
rules, individuals can give limitless funds to their own
candidacies, which endows a handful of people in this nation more
than equal rights.
</P>
<P>
   If we allow them this power to dominate the process, then we
might as well go all the way and set up a new standard for voting.
</P>
<P>
   We can abandon entirely the foolish notion of one man, one vote,
and assign the number of votes according to how much money each
person owns. Someone with a million dollars would get, say, 10
votes, and another with $20 million would get 200 votes. It seems
only equitable, given what we already countenance.
</P>
<P>
   This campaign season we've had the pleasure of being showered
with attack ads, as candidates spend millions in order to get a job
paying thousands.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, negative ads are considered by the specialists as
more beneficial than not someone in a contentious election battle.
</P>
<P>
   The question facing the electorate, which should be asked by
each voter while looking in the mirror, is why such transparently
low-down campaigning wins their hearts and minds.
</P>
<P>
   There is an old saying that we should heed: ``We have met the
enemy and he is us.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
