<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAVY-TRUCKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBLE STANDARD IN TEXAS TRUCKING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ One of the reasons cited for keeping Mexican
trucks out of the United States is the fear that overweight trucks
would create safety problems and damage U.S. highways.
</P>
<P>
   For that and other political reasons, provisions in the North
American Free Trade Agreement that would start cross-border
trucking remain delayed indefinitely, even though Mexican trucks
would be subjected to the same rules and regulations for U.S.
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   What few people know, though, is Texas allows thousands of
trucks daily to operate over the weight limits by issuing special
permits that cost a fraction of the damage caused to roads and
bridges.
</P>
<P>
   The permits are called ``2060 permits,'' after the Texas
legislative bill number in 1989 that created the program.
</P>
<P>
   In the fiscal year ended Aug. 31, 14,530 permits were issued by
the Texas Department of Transportation, raising revenues of $3.43
million, almost all of which goes to counties for road and bridge
repair reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 state DOT study, however, estimated that overweight
trucks cause $450 million in damage to state roads and bridges each
year.
</P>
<P>
   The state's gross weight limit is 80,000 pounds, counting both
the truck and its freight. The permit allows a 5 percent increase
in gross weight and up to a 10 percent increase on each axle's
weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, for every 10 percent increase in axle loading above
the legal limit, there is 50 percent more damage (caused to
roads),'' said Ray Barnhart, an Austin transportation consultant
who headed the Federal Highway Administration from 1981 to 1988
during the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   The permit is for the 137,000 miles of county roads and the
77,000-mile state road system only. Federal highway funding would
be threatened if the 2060 permits allowed overweight trucks on the
state's 3,400-mile interstate highway system.
</P>
<P>
   Most state and county roads are built to handle 10,000 to 15,000
pounds. But under 2060 permits, trucks legally can be 84,000
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The state's bridges are a further concern. Inspected every 18
months, the bridges often have signs limiting weights to 10,000
pounds or 15,000 pounds. Yet, 84,000-pound trucks cross them
legally with 2060 permits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It defies engineering principles,'' Barnhart said. ``I think
this is criminal. One of these days you'll have a major tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts concur that damage is being done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean the bridges will fall down. But there is not
the degree of safety that is expected,'' said Rob Harrison,
associate director at the University of Texas at Austin's Center
for Transportation Research. ``And bridges are expensive to fix.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some part of the bridge's life is extracted every time a heavy
load goes over it,'' added Jose Weissmann, engineering professor at
the University of Texas at San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bridge would need replacement sooner than expected'' when
heavy loads are allowed, said Weissmann, a former associate at the
Center for Transportation Research, part of the University of Texas
at Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The base fee for 2060 permits, which are good for one year in
any 20-county area, is $75, plus a $5 administration fee.
</P>
<P>
   Fees to operate in additional 20-county areas are $125 each,
ranging up to a $2,080 cap to operate statewide, said Monty
Chamberlain, spokesman for the state DOT motor carrier division.
</P>
<P>
   Barnhart said the reimbursement to counties for repairs, based
on a formula that considers the miles of roads in each county,
comes to less than $9 per mile statewide. Repair costs typically
range from $10,000 to $50,000 per mile, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most onerous piece of highway legislation I've
ever seen,'' Barnhart said. ``And it threatens the safety and lives
of every motorist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The 2060 fees are not based on science, but on political
clout,'' said Barnhart, who has criticized the 2060 permit in
testimony before Texas legislative committees.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful trucking lobby is a difficult barrier to change,
Barnhart said, adding he is not aware of any plans to change state
law in the upcoming 1999 legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trucking companies naturally want to increase
productivity'' with heavier loads, Weissmann said. ``They like this
permit and, like anyone, they go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that the 2060 permits rarely involve NAFTA
trade that is concentrated on the interstate highways. Most 2060
permits are for transporting specialized loads _ oil-drilling
equipment, timber logs, gravel and agricultural roads _ over
intrastate routes.
</P>
<P>
   But if Texas trucks are allowed to carry road-damaging loads
with a low-cost permit, international trucks will get permits, too,
whenever the NAFTA provisions are enacted for non-interstate
highway transport.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, 2060 permits are a problem. They ought to be phased out
in favor of lower axle limits, bridge-use restrictions and new,
better corridors to accommodate deliveries. And more weighing
stations should be built to enforce limits.
</P>
<P>
   Those can be goals as Texas receives higher levels of federal
highway funding the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, dangerous and heavy loads will be getting a
free ride in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Hendricks writes for the San Antonio Express-News, P.O.
Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
