u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-OBSERVER-BOS &LR;      11-02 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-OBSERVER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOGISTICAL NIGHTMARE FOR SECURITY FORCE IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Clenching his eyes tight and furrowing
his brow, Mans Nyberg used a thumb and forefinger to massage the
bridge of his nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the flu,'' he said nasally. ``I'm sick, and we haven't
even started yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Nyberg, chief spokesman for the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, or OSCE, was among the first of the
Vienna-based group to come here to Kosovo to begin laying the
groundwork for the arrival of 2,000 international observers to
verify an uneasy truce.
</P>
<P>
   Nyberg admits that it is a logistical nightmare, and says the
observers probably will not be at work here before the end of
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're setting up a headquarters, looking for office space
around Kosovo,'' he said. ``We need 1,000 vehicles. We need to find
accommodation for 2,000 people.''
</P>
<P>
   But as any visitor to Kosovo will attest, the Serbian province
is not exactly suited for an onslaught of visitors. There are few
hotels, and most of them are clustered in Pristina, the provincial
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The observers, however, need to be in the rural countryside,
where most of the fighting took place and where the potential for
trouble recurring is greatest, but where amenities are lacking.
</P>
<P>
   In the countryside, the vast majority of people whose rights and
personal safety the observers are supposed to protect do not even
know they are coming.
</P>
<P>
   In central Kosovo, where the worst fighting took place, an
Albanian farmer stood outside his home, which had been destroyed by
Serb forces, and asked, ``What is OSCE?''
</P>
<P>
   The OSCE is a coalition of 54 countries, including the United
States and nearly all of the European countries, that seeks to
prevent conflict and nurture Western-style democracy in former
Eastern Bloc nations. Yugoslavia left the group in 1992 when the
Bosnian war exploded.
</P>
<P>
   The group was widely criticized for its oversight of the Bosnian
elections in September. When it said it would give preliminary
election results, then at the last minute announced it would not do
so, many accused OSCE of withholding the results because they
showed that Western-backed moderates had lost ground to hardline
nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring the situation in Kosovo gives OSCE a chance to redeem
itself. It seems determined not to fumble that chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, gave permission to
OSCE to enter Kosovo as part of the deal brokered by the US special
envoy Richard Holbrooke. The observers are charged with verifying
that Milosevic complies with the United Nations resolutions that
call for the demilitarization of Kosovo, cutting troops and police
there back to the levels they were at nine months ago, when
fighting broke out.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps an even more important part of the OSCE mission is
to give ethnic Albanians who fled the fighting the confidence to
return to their homes before winter sets in. Up to 300,000 people,
most of them Albanians, fled their homes because of the fighting.
Many are returning to uninhabitable homes destroyed by Serb
shelling.
</P>
<P>
   Nyberg and Norwegian General Bjorn Nygard, OSCE's chief of
staff, believe the group will be able to accomplish both parts of
its mission.
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, international observation here was handled by the
Kosovo Diplomatic Observer Mission, or K-DOM, a group of 51
Americans, 26 Europeans, 10 Russians, and one Canadian. They will
be absorbed into the OSCE team.
</P>
<P>
   At the insistence of NATO, part of the deal calls for the
monitors to be shadowed by a so-called extraction force of some
2,000 soldiers in nearby Macedonia. The idea is that the extraction
force would be called in to rescue observers if either Serb forces
or Albanian separatists decide to take any of them hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the observers believe their credibility rests in part
on their being unarmed, Nyberg admitted that many observers are
uneasy about a stealth military force being set up to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shadows of NATO pressure,'' he said, dismissively, of the
extraction force idea. ``The issue of the security of our members
is over-inflated. If the (Serbian) army stays away, in barracks,
there will be no problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if OSCE would report any provocation or show of force by
the Albanian rebels of the Kosovo Liberation Army, Nyberg said,
``The KLA is not a party to the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, Adem Demaci, the liberation army's political
representative, ``gave the KLA's support for OSCE's mission. The
KLA have promised to show restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Nyberg set off to find office space and medication
for his flu, unaware that as difficult it would be to find the
former, it would be virtually impossible to find the latter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 1328EST &QL; 
