r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-DEATH-HNS     11-02 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-DEATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EVENING' EXPLORES THE DARKNESS OF DYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOAN SMITH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Susan Minot wanted to imagine the process of slowly
dying. She had recently endured the death of a friend, from
leukemia, and of her grandmother, ``who took to her bed and, two
months later, simply died.''
</P>
<P>
   And so she began her fourth book and her third novel,
``Evening,'' told from the point of view of a woman dying of
ovarian cancer, consumed by pain and memories, including a
once-repressed recollection of what seems now to have been the most
important weekend in her life _ an eventful wedding 40 years
earlier at which she'd fallen hopelessly in love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most writers have something under their skins they've just got
to get out,'' Minot said over coffee at a small cafe near her
studio in the West Village, her hands fluttering eloquently over
her bare arms. ``It isn't a lovely feeling. I watched both of these
people, who were very close to me, go through this terrible ordeal
of pain and drugs and hospitals and disorientation, this kind of
drifting off, this horrendous isolation. That, you could say, was
the thing under my skin. I just can't forget about it, so one of my
ways of dealing with it is to try to imagine what it must have been
like for them.''
</P>
<P>
   But writing about a dying woman also was ``a way of exploring
what really matters.'' When death is imminent, what are the things
most likely to occupy the final moments of consciousness? And for
Minot, the moment of falling in love, especially if love is
frustrated, is ``the center of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   She has written about its messy power in her short stories,
including her 1989 collection ``Lust''; in her much-admired 1992
novel ``Folly'' about a sheltered upper-class Boston woman's single
secret romantic indiscretion; and in the screenplay she wrote for
the great Italian filmmaker Bernardo Bertolucci's ``Stealing
Beauty,'' in which a 19-year-old American girl travels to Tuscany
hoping to find her real father and to finally sleep with the boy
she fell in love with when she was 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beginning of love is so full of hope,'' she said, ``so
full of the possibility of the fulfillment of everything you ever
wanted. It is a lovely, drugged, unreal feeling that is absolutely
crucial to the experience of life.''
</P>
<P>
   And Minot, who has a near-perfect ear, writes about it so
beautifully. Page through ``Evening,'' published by Knopf this
month to admiring reviews, and read a passage at random: ``She
heard soft paws crossing the floor above her. A blur passed by the
window, a cloud of fidgeting butterflies. She smelled sea water,
she smelled burnt sugar. Someone was baking a cake. The sound of
fingernails scraped the wainscoting behind the bamboo bookshelf.
She scanned the shelves of her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the publication in 1986, when she was only 30, of
``Monkeys,'' a semi-autobiographical novel about an Irish Catholic
family of seven children growing up on the coast of Massachusetts,
she has enjoyed widespread admiration, not just for her sensitive
renderings of her characters' inner lives and relationships, but
for prose as fluid as music.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sounds of words,'' she sighed. ``They're the tools,
they're what you use to tell your story. You can literally make
them sing. I've always thought that if you really could sing your
material it would be lovely.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet singing, she said, is one of the few arts she has never
explored.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time I could not decide whether to concentrate on
painting or writing,'' she said. ``When I was in graduate school
studying writing at Columbia (where she earned a Masters of Fine
Arts degree in 1983), I used to go upstairs one floor to study
film, then downstairs one floor for painting classes. They all
cross-pollinate one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why a friend who was interviewing Bernardo Bertolucci
for the New Yorker sent him to Minot when he needed a writer for a
film he was making about a young American virgin. ``I am in love
with film,'' she said. ``I've seen as many movies as I've read
books, and he is the master.''
</P>
<P>
   After directing his epics, ``The Last Emperor'' and ``The Little
Buddha,'' Bertolucci ``wanted to do something small.'' The idea was
sketchy, ``a girl on a mission to lose her virginity.'' And if
Minot wasn't crazy about the concept, she found Bertolucci ``very
open to what I had to say. He admitted that he had no idea what it
was like to be a young American woman and he wanted my ideas. So
I'd write something, he'd go over it, and we ended up
collaborating. Yet the way he works is absolutely his own, in that
he'd use the qualities of an actress, in this case Liv Tyler, to
develop the character I'd written in a certain direction. It was
very much his way of telling the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing fiction, she said, is ``deeply, deeply lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it so hard to do that I do it intensely so it doesn't
drag out forever. I've driven myself crazy, but it's good to know
what that is like, too, and at a certain point in every book you
have to put yourself through it or you won't go deep enough to come
up with something worth telling. What I like best is when I come up
with something and have no idea where it came from. It doesn't
sound like me. It's a surprise. Those are the things you search
for, the things that make you stop and say, `Now that, just maybe,
is kind of interesting.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
