<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN WE BE BOTH FIT AND FAT?
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   One of the most striking images in ``Fat'' on ``Frontline'' is
that of triathlete Dave Alexander, in peak physical condition at 5
feet 8 inches and 250 pounds. A veteran of 264 triathlons,
Alexander embodies what the program's producer, Antony Thomas,
calls a ``revolutionary'' notion: It's possible to be both fit and
fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frontline'' interviews a Dallas reasearcher whose long-term
studies of fitness levels in 25,000 people found that men who were
fat but fit had no increased mortality rate. Professor Steven Blair
thinks that since people come in so many different shapes and
sizes, applying a predetermined ``ideal'' weight to an individual
is faulty logic.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the program, which airs this week on PBS, will be no
news at all for those who closely follow the fortunes of fat. But
it's an interesting overview of the state of a subject close to the
hearts, so to speak, of many Americans. A lot closer to some hearts
than others. ``Frontline'' reminds us that 39 million Americans are
obese, defined as 20 percent above the medically determined
``ideal'' weight.
</P>
<P>
   Experts interviewed by ``Frontline'' say scientists are finding
increasing evidence of genetic susceptibility to obesity. Some
people can't help gaining weight, caught as they are in what one
expert calls the ``fat trap'' of the American diet and our
increasingly sedentary way of life. And obesity is becoming a
serious problem in other parts of the world, as we export our
fast-food, leisure-centered lifestyle to other countries.
</P>
<P>
   It may be easier than ever to become fat, but it's never been
harder to be fat. ``You see our society does not accept very well
the obese individual,'' one doctor tells ``Frontline.'' ``They are
being treated today as the modern moral equivalent of lepers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn McAffee, a 500-pound woman, is shown talking to
pharmaceutical employees about her weight struggle and about
anti-fat prejudice. ``If you are a super-size person, you are a
target,'' she says. ``I've personally had experiences where people
try to run me down in cars, laughing at me.''
</P>
<P>
   In another segment, elementary school students are handed
photographs of four children and asked to pick the one they would
least like as a friend. The most rejected photo by far is of a fat
child. The students interviewed are candid about why they wouldn't
want to befriend him. ``Because he's fat,'' one after another says.
The teacher asks what they think fat people are like. ``Lazy,''
says one little boy.
</P>
<P>
   Fat (and formerly fat) people can be just as hard on themselves.
When ``Frontline'' interviews patients who have undergone risky and
painful stomach bypass surgery to lose weight, they eagerly revile
their old selves. ``I was pitiful,'' says one. ``I looked like a
blimp,'' says another.
</P>
<P>
   Anorexia and bulimia are the other side of obesity. The program
visits a British clinic where children as young as 6 are treated
for eating disorders. A very slim teenager says that when she looks
in the mirror, she sees ``a fat person _ a person who I just don't
like because it kind of repulses me.''
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment and fashion industries, and the media, are as
usual blamed for holding up an unrealistic ideal of slimness that
fosters eating disorders. Vidal Sassoon denies the connection,
saying he has seen very few models that he would consider anorexic.
``Frontline,'' meanwhile, shows footage of stick-thin models behind
the scenes of his latest fashion show. But can all models be
anorexic? If some people are genetically programmed to be fat,
surely there must be some who are genetically programmed to be
skeletal. Is this an example of anti-thin bias? Can there even be
such a thing in our culture?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
