<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9055 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      11-02 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-YIELD FUND IS TOO RISKY FOR 80-YEAR-OLDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My brother and I are in our 80s and have been conservative
investors in value-related stocks and municipal bonds for many
years. We're having a difference of opinion on a particular fund
we've held for five years: Alliance North American Government
Income Trust, Class B. My brother believes we have benefited from
the fund's high yield, currently more than 12 percent, since all
our dividends have been reinvested. We invested $57,408 in 1993 and
1994 and our position is now worth $72,000. It seems like rates
such as this would be a haven for investors seeking a high rate of
return, but high income is no longer one of our objectives. Safety
is. High yields carry resulting risks. I am reluctant to be exposed
to unneeded risks. Am I overly concerned?
</P>
<P>
   A.Z., Canton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There's no question that this is a high-risk fund, and the
real returns on the fund are nowhere near as good as those yield
figures make it seem.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years the fund's average annual return has
been 5.63 percent, according to the latest report from Morningstar
Mutual Funds. The reason is that the generous income levels are
offset by erosions in net asset value.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in 1992 with a $10 net asset value, the B shares
entered this week at $7.43, and the fund's year-to-date total
return has been 0.8 percent. That's a pretty far cry from 12
percent plus, from my point of view.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, by charter, must invest 65 percent of its portfolio in
investment-grade government securities of the United States,
Canada, and Mexico. The remainder may be invested in Central and
South American government securities.
</P>
<P>
   I'm with you all the way: This is not the fund for investors who
consider themselves conservative. Sure, the 29.57 percent gain of
1995 and the 23.05 percent for 1996 were spectacular, especially
for a bond fund, but don't forget the shuddering 30.80 percent loss
of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The best and highest use of this fund is as a short-term holding
for a speculative investor. I see little prospect that it will
deliver good returns to the long-term holder. (Note: Compare that
5.63 percent five-year average annual total return to the 7.42
percent for boring old Vanguard GNMA fund.)
</P>
<P>
   But there's one final factor, and since you have been municipal
bond investors, I'll bet this will be the final clincher for your
brother. That's taxes. When it comes to tax efficiency, this fund
has very little to offer.
</P>
<P>
   If you hold this fund in a taxable account, you see large
distributions adding up on your form 1040, while your real returns
may be more modest _ or negative.
</P>
<P>
   You write that your investments were made during 1993 and 1994,
so let's use the Jan. 1, 1994 market price for the shares as a
benchmark _ $10.31. If you were to sell, you would probably be able
to report a capital loss of $2.75 to $3 for each of the shares you
initially purchased. (The figure would vary for the additional
shares you bought through reinvestment of distributions, but you
would probably see a loss there as well.)
</P>
<P>
   So not only would a sale get you out of this high-risk holding,
but it would generate a significant capital loss, which could be
used to reduce your tax liabilities or to offset any gain you might
generate elsewhere in your portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My siblings and I have set up a trust fund for our mother.
Our ages range from 36 to 56. My mother is almost 80, and the trust
will dissolve upon her death. The trust now holds four mutual
funds: $44,063 in Chesapeake, $77,871 in PIMCo Institutional
Capital Appreciation, $49,887 in PIMCo. Institutional Micro Cap,
and $20,734 in Harbor International. We want to be aggressive and
achieve maximum growth, but we believe we might be too heavily
positioned in small-technology companies. The trust lost 25 percent
of its value since April, most of it since mid-July. Our mother
receives $900 a month from the trust. My preference would be to
invest 30 percent in a Standard &AMP; Poor's Index fund, 30 percent in
a growth and income fund, 30 percent in a small-company fund, and
10 percent in an overseas fund. All funds would need to be rated
five stars by Morningstar. How do you suggest we position ourselves
for the next five years in the current market?
</P>
<P>
   C.M., North Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If it were up to me, I'd invest the entire portfolio in
fixed-income securities, which would allow the trust to generate
the $900 monthly income check with no invasion of principal _ this
would require generating a yield of only 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the realignment you suggest would be a more
conservative course than the current one, but I think it's still
too aggressive. After all, is the purpose of this trust to play the
market for capital gains or to support your mother?
</P>
<P>
   Even with the change you suggest, it's entirely possible that a
couple of tough market years, plus the steady sequence of
withdrawals, could substantially deplete the trust.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely, for example, that the portfolio you suggest could
yield more than 1 percent to 2 percent in dividends, and probably
closer to the former.
</P>
<P>
   So you would be effectively gambling that short-term market
gains will be sufficient to support the sequence of withdrawals.
Since I have a dim view of the short-term prospects for the market,
I think you're making a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Fixed-income funds are boring, perhaps, but there are some
purposes, such as this one, for which they're perfect.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
