<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-CLINTON ADS BACKFIRE ON GINGRICH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORRANCE, Calif. _ There has to be a reason why Republican pols
from New York to this middle-class nerve center south of Los
Angeles are telling their national leaders to keep those three
anti-Clinton ads out of their races.
</P>
<P>
   There has to be a reason why the ads are showing up only in a
tiny number of TV markets with nothing even close to the trumpeted
$10 million behind them.
</P>
<P>
   There has to be a reason why the fourth, and nastiest,
commercial was withheld going into the final weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And there is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gosh, if I had the money, I'd put 'em up here myself,'' said
underdog Democrat Janice Hahn, running for this modestly
conservative congressional seat. ``We're talking about the right
things, and this last-minute silliness only reminds people that
this Congress is obsessed with Clinton and not with them.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of an odd national campaign, Newt Gingrich has put
the politics of impeachment ahead of substance, preferring to
communicate with fellow right-wingers as opposed to the country.
</P>
<P>
   Politics aside, what the speaker has done with his last,
over-hyped batch of watered-down campaign commercials is to remind
one and all that throwing President Clinton out of office is a
matter of votes, not evidence. The idea of some solemn,
constitutional process in which bipartisanship and national
consensus dominate is rejected. Instead, Republicans who have
Clinton in their sights are simply going to try to impeach him _ as
quickly as possible. The goal is not to persuade, it is to win.
</P>
<P>
   That makes the first victim of Gingrich's latest stunt any
pretense of judiciousness in the House Judiciary Committee's
``inquiry.'' The public is correct: This thing is almost entirely
partisan.
</P>
<P>
   The other victims are national Republican interests, as distinct
from House Republican and Gingrich interests _ once again.
California's GOP attorney general, Dan Lungren, who is in the final
stages of blowing his chance to be governor, said the other evening
between sparsely attended events that he traces his campaign's
slide to the House vote to formally launch its inquiry and to the
backlash he says that vote created.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Lieutenant Governor Gray Davis, whose gubernatorial
campaign right now is truly on fire, would differ, but Lungren has
a point, and it is made a lot more forcefully by veteran state
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gingrich never thinks beyond himself,'' one of them told me.
``He didn't need that vote at that time. Look at what's happened
since, nothing. It was only done to position people politically on
the assumption that Clinton was the issue. Well he wasn't then, and
he isn't now.''
</P>
<P>
   Said another California Republican, close to the candidacy of
state Treasurer Matt Fong against Senator Barbara Boxer: ``Maybe,
with very careful targeting, there might be a few House seats
Gingrich could tip with this stuff. But the cost to the rest of us
from backlash is high, and as always that doesn't concern him. It's
just like two years ago, when his ads about the congressional
campaign pulled the plug on poor Bob Dole.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong stuff, but one need look no further than California's
36th Congressional District, a middle-class microcosm of upward
mobility from wacky Venice south to more working class San Pedro.
Once a defense industry hub, it is today more of a New Economy area
_ fiscally conservative but more live-and-let-live culturally,
almost equally divided between the parties. Won by the same 6 point
margin both times by Clinton, but also won handily both times by
outgoing Republican Governor Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The district was redesigned after the 1990 census to be
Republican, but it was won three times by a deft Democratic
centrist, Jane Harman, who is vacating it after losing her
self-financed bid to become the nominee for governor.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, it should have been a slam-dunk for GOP state
legislator Steve Kuykendall, a mortgage banker from affluent Rancho
Palos Verdes. But it isn't, and both sides attribute the race's
tightness and volatility to the impeachment backlash.
</P>
<P>
   Janice Hahn says that's only the beginning, that a tighter race
has brought her more attention and her opponent more scrutiny. Her
main argument down the stretch, she told me at a fund-raiser last
week, is that a Congress fixated on Clinton is not fixated on the
education, health care, and retirement security issues on which
voters are fixated.
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize the closeness of the race, House Democratic leader
Dick Gephardt chose Hahn _ a true scion of a famous family, whose
dad was the legendary Los Angeles County supervisor Kenneth Hahn
and whose brother Jimmy is the city attorney _ to be his
``Candidate from the Real World'' at a press conference mocking the
Gingrich ads.
</P>
<P>
   And to further emphasize it, the Kuykendall camp was terrified
that those commercials might end up on LA television screens. As it
turned out, the ads were confined to a longshot right-winger's
effort to unseat Representative Lois Capps in Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Kuykendall's camp says he remains confident, and off the
demographics alone he should be. But the fact this is a horserace
on the final weekend is the perfect metaphor for the national
campaign _ a golden Republican opportunity in peril. And the blame,
his fellow Republicans agree, belongs on Gingrich's shoulders for
putting too much politics into an issue which only works when it
has none.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
