<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-FUTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWAITING THE SECOND REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGORY MOORE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Even to an observer of just a few days, this island
nation, forbidden to most Americans, presents striking
contradictions: a rich history all but obscured by grinding poverty
and crumbling infrastructure, a touted revolution slowly
compromised by a bifurcated economy that has created a privileged
class in what was to be a classless society.
</P>
<P>
   On a nearly one-hour ride from Jose Marti Airport to the
well-appointed Melia Cohiba Hotel along the beachfront Malecon
boulevard, the sense that Cuba is in trouble is inescapable. You
see it in the faces of the people, staring blankly from glassless
windows and darkened doorways.
</P>
<P>
   As ubiquitous images of the revolutionary hero Che Guevara stare
from billboards and buildings, the desire for change is palpable.
Many of the 12 million inhabitants here seem to be just biding
their time until the second revolution, one that can bring them
into the 21st century of decent housing, prosperity, freedom _ and
perhaps even satellite dishes and cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it seems to an American visitor _ part of a 32-member
delegation of journalists from the American Society of Newspaper
Editors who arrived in the country on a fact-finding mission 11
days ago. The Cuba we saw on our four-day stay, a stay carefully
choreographed by a watchful government, is a Cuba most of the
population rarely glimpses up close.
</P>
<P>
   Ours was a privileged view. We were ferried about in an
air-conditioned bus. We were accompanied constantly by Cuban
officials whose task it was to accommodate us. And we met with
Fidel Castro himself, something the few regular Cubans I spoke to
had ever done.
</P>
<P>
   We saw only fleeting, unofficial glimpses of the poverty that
grips many on the island. Our carefully orchestrated meetings were
scheduled nearly back-to-back so we had no time to roam. They were
aimed at illuminating the accomplishments of the 39 years since
Castro stormed Cuba, spreading the communist revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Cuba has much to be proud of.
</P>
<P>
   Officials boast that Cuba has no organized crime, and a low
overall crime rate. They note that few, if any, criminals have
guns. Theft, they admit, is a big problem, with prostitution a
growing aggravation. And yes, there is talk of a mounting drug
problem, though the Minister of Justice Roberto Diaz Sotolongo
denied it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cuba has many measures of its success: It has a minuscule
infant mortality rate of 7.2 per thousand, an illiteracy rate of
only 2 percent, a home ownership rate of 85 percent and a free
health care system that inoculates 95 percent of its children
against 12 diseases and which developed a vaccine that virtually
eliminated meningitis, a big killer.
</P>
<P>
   Concepcion Campa Huergo, a physician and president of the Carlos
Finlay Institute and the only ranking woman we met in the
government, said the institute is working on a vaccine for cholera
and hepatitis. And US officals here said the Cubans are consumed
with finding the cure for AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   But the confidence of the government seems sadly disconnected
from the hopes and dreams of the people.
</P>
<P>
   As we traveled through the narrow streets amid the crumbling
Spanish-style architecture, even on a weekday many people seemed to
have nothing to do. Yet the government claims an unemployment rate
of under 7 percent. Scrawny dogs roamed the roads and markets
looking for scraps. No doubt there are some Cubans who enjoy a
comfortable existence, but they appear to be outnumbered by their
countrymen living on the margins.
</P>
<P>
   A typical Cuban home is said to be sparsely furnished,
containing only a refrigerator (almost always an aging Philco), a
television (probably color), a battered sofa, and a beloved pet the
family can barely afford to feed. Despite the high rate of home
ownership, Cubans I spoke with said the average young person has
little hope of owning a home anytime soon unless they inherit it.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the Soviet Union, once Cuba's great
benefactor, pumped nearly $5 billion into the country each year for
sugar exports and other goods. But with the Soviet Union's breakup
seven years ago, that aid is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Now Cuba is on its own, hunting for new markets, trying to
rebuild its confidence _ and to survive. In a revealing meeting,
Ricardo Alarcon, president of the National Assembly and a possible
successor to Castro, said the first few years after Soviet aid
dried up were difficult ``not only economically, but ... on a
psychological level. ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``To wake up one day and realize you are alone. That created in
many Cubans uncertainty _ `What are we now?' ... From that moment
to this year, the mood has drastically changed,'' he said. ``I
don't think anyone in Cuba is uncertain about our destiny. The mood
now is more optimistic, more constructive.''
</P>
<P>
   But to survive, the only communist government in the Western
Hemisphere has had to swallow a bitter pill. It's called
capitalism, although no one uses that word.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, the country has been in what Economic Minister Jose
Luis Rodriguez calls ``the special period,'' one in which Cuba has
opened itself to billions in foreign investment and joint ventures
with international enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   And since 1993, the nation has authorized the circulation of
foreign currencies, most notably dollars, and the creation of
private businesses. The most profitable entrepreneurs are taxi
drivers, plumbers, carpenters, and restaurateurs who are limited to
seating 12 people at any one time.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for this freedom to pursue dollars and experiment
with a market economy, these enterprises pay taxes to the state, as
much as 1,000 Cuban pesos a month, regardless of what they take in.
That is roughly equivalent to $50, a significant amount by Cuban
domestic standards.
</P>
<P>
   These entrepreneurs have to work hard to attract dollars, since
Americans are banned from the country under terms of the
controversial 36-year-old US embargo constantly denounced by the
Cuban government. But somehow, dollars still permeate the economy.
For some, they are far easier to come by than pesos.
</P>
<P>
   And the growing dollar economy has had the effect of creating
two Cubas: one, in which people who get dollars (legally or
illegally) eat better, buy better goods, and enjoy greater status.
The other, ruled by the peso, is poorer, far less privileged, and
more dissatisified.
</P>
<P>
   All of those who work for the state _ be they doctors, lawyers,
police officers, or teachers _ are paid in pesos, about 350 a
month, or $17 at current rates. While there are some perks,
including cars, inexpensive housing, free medical care, and
educational benefits, state workers are acutely aware that others
doing ``less important'' work are being paid in dollars, with all
the buying power that brings.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, some professionals have quit their state jobs
and started driving taxis to earn dollars, officials acknowledged.
Allowing this dual economy to exist, Castro told us, is ``very
painful.'' He added: ``We would have preferred never to establish
these differences.''
</P>
<P>
   In this land of contradictions is yet another: There are places
_ including the island's most elegant establishments _ where Cubans
are apparently not allowed to go, an insidious form of apartheid
that government officials are reluctant to acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   But walk into the large hotels along the Malecon and in the
tourist mecca, Varadero, where foreigners lavishly spend their
currencies, and one can see uniformed workers, some with earpieces,
ready to stop any Cuban who might try to enter the lobbies. Why?
Perhaps out of fear that just the sight of such opulence and
consumption might incite insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   Castro's ministers defend the accelerated effort to bolster
tourism, saying this is the only way to attract the foreign capital
needed to rebuild this nation. This year, Cuba expects to have 1
million visitors, mostly Canadians, but Germans and Spaniards, too.
By the year 2000, Cuba hopes to double that number, and by 2010, to
have 7 million visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dire straits Cuba finds itself in, there are some
steps toward capitalism the country is simply not willing to take.
One of those is resurrecting gambling casinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not interested in gambling,'' said Tourism Minister
Osmany Cienfuegos. ``Some other countries in Latin America are
thinking about this. But for Cuba, gambling has a very special
meaning. Gambling in Cuba brings vices. For the people it has a
very psychological meaning in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   While the burgeoning tourist trade and other changes may bring
some stability, it comes at a cost.
</P>
<P>
   On my last night in Havana, I spoke with a young man of about 21
who waited tables in a restaurant. In perfect English he told me
his dream is to be a teacher. But he said he makes more money
waiting tables than he can ever make standing in front of a high
school class.
</P>
<P>
   He believes in many of the ideals of the revolution, but wants
to own a home, own a car, and have a family. And he wonders how can
he do that on 250 to 350 pesos a month.
</P>
<P>
   It's a question many Cubans are asking as they appear to
patiently await the second revolution, the one that will inevitably
come after Fidel Castro leaves the scene.
</P>
<P>
   And then maybe, just maybe, Cuba can seize the 21st century and
its promise of a better life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
