<SLUG> BC-CASTRO-INPERSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDEL CASTRO IS EVER THE TIRELESS REVOLUTIONARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGORY L. MOORE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Fidel Castro is a striking figure. Ramrod straight and
over 6 feet tall, he is, at 72, fit and trim. Meeting with a group
of US journalists here eight days ago, he promised to talk for as
long as we wanted. Six intense hours later _ with only a 10-minute
break _ he finished.
</P>
<P>
   He was nothing like the beard-stroking pontificator that is
often portrayed. Instead, wearing his trademark fatigues, he was
charismatic, curious, passionate, a lover of books, and a lively
debater.
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation with our delegation from the American Society
of Newspaper Editors, Castro answered 15 questions, sometimes
making long speeches before coming back to the point. He complained
about the press, denied he has accumulated personal wealth, talked
about baseball, and speculated about Cuba's future without him.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet Union may have crumbled, he said, but Cuba remains
committed to the principles of its revolution. Evidence of its
success lies in the fact that most people have jobs, own their own
homes, and all have access to free health care and free education,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He lambasted the United States for its longstanding embargo
against the island. He called it an act of war and a violation of
Cubans' human rights. ``It has caused enormous pain for nearly 40
years,'' he said, speaking through an interpreter. ``But the
revolution proves that if you have a little and you distribute it
equally, you can make miracles happen.''
</P>
<P>
   On American newspapers' desire to operate in Cuba in the same
way that Cable News Network already does, Castro was discouraging.
It's acceptable, he said, for American reporters to visit Cuba for
special events like the pope's visit last January, but not on a
permanent basis, not yet. What would make him change his mind? ``If
I were certain objective reporters would come to Cuba and not be
biased beforehand.''
</P>
<P>
   He praised the success of Cuban Major League Baseball players,
but bristled at a suggestion that he had dispatched them to the
United States. ``We did not send them,'' he thundered. ``You stole
them. If you have to compete against $6 million vs. 3,000 pesos,
you cannot win.'' He said, half-jokingly, that maybe a couple of
Cuban teams could join the Major Leagues to show just how good they
are.
</P>
<P>
   Castro became most animated about a Forbes magazine report
suggesting he had accumulated $1.5 billion in personal wealth,
demanding, ``What right do they have to write such slander?'' He
said he owns no property and recently donated 17,500 gifts
accumulated from his many travels. Along with some books, he said,
he kept the black $30 Seiko watch on his wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself a revolutionary,'' he said. ``I do not need
a bank account anywhere. I have made a decision to die in my trench
with honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about retirement, he scoffed. ``Do you think one has the
right to retire in the midst of such a struggle the country faces?
There is only one reason to be here at my age. Duty and
responsibility. As long as I have the necessary energy to do what
is imposed on me, I will remain.''
</P>
<P>
   And after he is gone, what happens?
</P>
<P>
   ``People consider without reason that my absence could alter the
course of events,'' he said. ``The day I am no longer here nothing
is going to happen and possibly things will be even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted, the editors eventually ran out of questions. Castro
moved to a downstairs lobby to shake hands and pose for photos for
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving with his entourage, the revolutionary leader slipped
into a sparkling black Mercedes-Benz, and was whisked away.
</P>
</TEXT>
