<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVES ENTITLED TO OUR PRAYERS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One is the image of our warmest fantasies: her tufts of
strawberry-blond hair, her plump cheeks, and full-bodied wail.
</P>
<P>
   The other is the embodiment of our worst nightmares: her violent
conception, her shrunken limbs, and fragile lungs.
</P>
<P>
   In an old industrial city, a young woman goes into labor in the
nursing home bed where for three years she has lain comatose and
vulnerable to an as-yet-unidentified predator. The 2-pound
premature infant she delivers clings to life in a hospital's
neonatal intensive care unit.
</P>
<P>
   In a wealthy Boston suburb, the sound of a car door is our only
link to the mother who left her robust newborn on the steps of a
modern castle, complete with turret and fairy godmother. All 7
pounds, 6 ounces of health and possibility settles into the home of
one of scores of families clamoring to adopt her.
</P>
<P>
   Two births. Two babies. One difficult, confusing week in the
annals of maternity.
</P>
<P>
   By the simple act of conferring a name on the baby left on a
Newton doorstep, we will a promising future for Baby Julia. By
withholding as much from the baby born to an unconscious rape
victim, we betray our lack of hope for Baby Girl. We try not to
think too much about their mothers, one oblivious to her
motherhood, the other apparently too frightened to acknowledge
hers.
</P>
<P>
   We know nothing of the circumstances of Baby Julia's conception
and birth, yet we spin a story line that suits our need for happy
endings. We imagine a young mother with a face out of a Walker
Evans photograph and a heart out of a Bing Crosby movie canvassing
a Newton neighborhood to select the perfect home for her princess.
She sees the lights of the stone castle. Fade to the fairy
godmother fetching her morning newspapers and discovering the
irresistible foundling.
</P>
<P>
   We edit out the terror and desperation this newly-minted mom
must have felt as she wrapped her daughter, umbilical cord still
attached, in a small, bloody towel. Where did she deliver this
baby? In a back seat, in the predawn chill of an October morning?
Did she drive herself to the house where she left her child? Was
she alone? Did the contractions take her by surprise? Had her
pregnancy advanced just as unacknowledged and undetected as the
pregnancy of the comatose woman in the nursing home?
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, we know too much about the circumstances of Baby
Girl's conception and birth. The most we can muster for her future
is a prayer that if she survives _ she is in critical condition at
Floating Hospital for Children at the New England Medical Center in
Boston _ she will not emerge as damaged as the mother who bore her,
a 24-year-old woman rendered silent and defenseless after an
apparent drug overdose in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   While Massachusetts courts pondered the fate of these two
babies, a judge in New Jersey sentenced a young woman for killing
her newborn son at her senior prom. Melissa Drexler had admitted
giving birth to a healthy boy in a bathroom stall during the prom
last year. She wrapped him in a plastic bag and placed him in a
trash can before returning to the dance.
</P>
<P>
   Was Drexler uncaring or unbalanced? Was her crime a symbol of
our culture's indifference to human life or a case study of our
ignorance of the mind's capacity for denial?
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the prosecution and defense drew different
portraits of the tearful young woman in the dock. Drexler's friends
had written to the court on her behalf, noted prosecutor Elaine
Leschot, but it was her job to speak for a discarded baby. ``The
friend of the baby in this courtroom is me,'' Leschot said.
``Somebody has to say, `We will protect the helpless.'''
</P>
<P>
   She was right, of course. But so was Steven Secare, the defense
lawyer, who reminded the court how many countries consider
psychiatric treatment rather than imprisonment the proper response
to such cases.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of both the mother's distress and the baby's death,
Judge John A. Ricciardi tried to walk a middle course. He would
leave it to others to explain how a teenage girl could deliver a
baby before the salad course and continue partying through dessert.
``What the law is concerned with is that a life has been taken,''
he said before sentencing Drexler to 15 years in prison. ``The
victim here has as much right to life as any one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Drexler will be eligible for parole after two years and 11
months. She is not ``a monster,'' the judge declared. ``She's
entitled to our understanding, to our compassion, and, indeed, our
prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   No less so than Baby Julia and Baby Girl and the mothers who
bore them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
