<HEADER>
A9069 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-BECKER-1STLD-WRITE     11-02 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BECKER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACERBIC SITCOM SHOWS PROMISE BUT NEEDS DOCTORING 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: SUBS 5thgraf, The problem, to identify network)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ready for another Archie Bunker? That's exactly what the
producers of ``Becker'' are hoping because this Ted Danson vehicle
is all about being politically incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a good thing, really. Television has become so safe
and devoid of sharp edges that it's boring beyond its normal level.
Producers are so afraid that jokes will step on someone's feelings
that bland wins every time.
</P>
<P>
   But let's not start thinking that just because Danson's
character is acerbic and angry he's as funny or as important as
Bunker. First off, there's very little racial humor in the pilot of
``Becker'' and that was the catalyst to ``All in the Family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Becker'' is a sitcom we're going to have to see a lot more of
to truly pass judgment. That's because the pilot is half annoying,
half encouraging. It's funny in a lot of places but predictable and
trite in others.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is in the attitude. Dave Hackel, the executive
producer, creator and writer of the pilot for CBS, wants to take
his Howard Beale-like anger at the world and give it a forum. Up on
that soap box steps Dr. John Becker, who has a compassionate
practice in the Bronx but lives his life as one unholy (literally)
curmudgeon.
</P>
<P>
   He's fed up with everything. He goes on an assortment of rants _
most of which are dated or seem patently orchestrated. About talk
shows, Becker says: ``It's like America stepped in something and
it's scraping off its shoe right over my TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything can set him off: ``White trash is the only natural
resource this country will never run out of.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is spared. ``If you shut your mouth, it stops the words
from falling out like that,'' he tells Linda (Shawnee Smith), his
spacey nurse's aide.
</P>
<P>
   He yells out the window to his neighbor, who is playing loud
ethnic music: ``Hey, foreign guy! Turn it off or I call
immigration.'' He rants about bicyclists, car salesmen, Jesus (``I
think he fell asleep at the wheel'') and to Jake, the blind
newsstand operator who works out of Becker's favorite bar: ``Just
because you're blind doesn't mean you've got a sixth sense. It just
means you're blind.''
</P>
<P>
   Now most of this stuff is pretty funny. It would be funnier if
it seemed more natural, not just following a scene created to set
up another rant. But give Danson credit, he's funny as Mr. Bitter
and it's a role he could make his second-biggest if ``Becker''
rounds into shape. There's a load of potential here, but the kinks
need to be hammered out quickly.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of the problem with being grumpy is that as an
unlikable character, most people will turn the channel if you have
nothing else to offer. Archie Bunker was tolerable not only because
he was funny, but because it was clear he was a big softy under the
blowhard exterior.
</P>
<P>
   But the producers go overboard with Danson. Sensing that need,
the producers have him fall for a 7-year-old patient who contracted
HIV and is losing the battle.
</P>
<P>
   The surrounding cast may help. No-nonsense head nurse Margaret
(wonderfully fleshed out by Hattie Winston) cuts him down a lot.
And Reggie (Terry Farrell), the female bartender/owner of his
favorite hangout, looks to be some kind of love interest down the
line.
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping ``Becker'' gets that far down the line. The world
of television needs a caustic hero we can love and hate. Make the
soap box less apparent and cut the sap, and ``Becker'' may be the
tonic TV needs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
