u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-02 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST IDEALS IN SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most recent launch of Discovery was one of those moments
when Americans everywhere stopped whatever they were doing and
stared at their television sets. Many watched CNN, which hired
legendary anchorman Walter Cronkite for the occasion of John
Glenn's triumphant return to space. Cronkite had been the voice of
Glenn's first mission in 1962. Glenn was then an authentic American
hero.
</P>
<P>
   So much has changed in 36 years. As Discovery disappeared out of
camera range and through the sky last Thursday, Cronkite spoke of
the majesty of space travel. Had he expanded his commentary, he
might also have mentioned the breath-taking cynicism that made this
particular mission possible.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's return to space was hardly heroic. It was instead the
story of one of the most tawdry political tradeoffs in recent
memory.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was straightforward. Glenn got to fly on the space
shuttle in return for his unceasing efforts to derail the Thompson
Committee hearings concerning the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign
finance scandals. Lest anyone forget, those scandals involved vast
amounts of Asian money finding its way into the campaign accounts
of the presidents reelection campaign and the Democratic National
Committee, two ledgers that meet the definition of the phrase
``distinction without a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those monies came from operatives with direct ties to
the government of the People's Republic of China. Other of those
funds came through the mysterious John Huang, whose access to the
White House and top-secret intelligence data remains the subject of
a criminal investigation by the US Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn was explicit with the White House about what he expected
in return. USA TODAY columnist Walter Shapiro, in a recent column
for Slate magazine, chronicled the chain of events: ``On July 6,
1997, the Sunday before the Thompson hearings began, Glenn used his
appearance on `Meet the Press' to publicly lobby for his
last-hurrah launch into space. He was followed on the broadcast by
NASA administrator Daniel Goldin, who purred, `I want to tell you
John is an outstanding astronaut and a great American. He has a
burning desire to go back into space. And we're giving it very
serious consideration, and we'll see where this goes.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where this went,'' Shapiro wrote, ``was toward a month of
nonstop obstructive tactics by Glenn patently designed to block any
serious examination of Clinton's ... campaign fund-raising abuses.
(I) attended every day of the hearings and this was one time when
Glenn was anything but an American hero.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Glenn deny, of course, that any such deal
was struck. And one supposes that they are, as the Wall Street
Journal Editorial Page noted, ``legally accurate'' in this regard.
No one has knowledge that they talked face-to-face about it. But
you would have had to have been born yesterday to believe that what
happened Thursday, five days before the midterm elections that may
decide whether or not President Clinton is impeached by the House
of Representatives, was a coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn is 77 years old. The oldest man ever to travel in space,
astronaut Story Musgrave, did so at the age of 61. At age 67, NASA
informed him he was too old for space travel.
</P>
<P>
   NASA maintains that Glenn's purpose on this mission is to allow
the agency to study the effects of aging in space. Given that the
medical data on Musgrave is much more complete (and therefore more
pertinent to the supposed medical inquiry), NASA would have been
much better off sending Musgrave instead of Glenn. But Musgrave
never threw sand into the gears of an inquiry into the president's
corrupt campaign practices, so he was cast aside to make room for
someone who had.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons to vote straight Republican on Tuesday is to
send a clear message to Washington that this kind of conduct is
unacceptable. Corrupting the space program for the benefit of a
favorite son who has done the president's bidding is sleazy by any
measure. The fact that it is no less sleazy than many other public
actions taken by the Clinton administration is but another reason
to punish the president's party at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's ride on the space shuttle was described in this
newspaper Friday as a ``journey of the national spirit.'' It would
have been better described as a metaphor for heroism in the age of
Clinton. Had Glenn investigated the Clinton campaign's fund-raising
abuses without fear or favor and cooperated fully with Senator
Thompson and his staff, then he would never have been on the launch
pad Thursday. His obstruction of a serious inquiry into corrupt
practices is what qualified him for the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton now taints even those agencies of government that
represent our highest aspirations. For years, the space program was
emblematic of America's greatness: our willingness to reach for the
stars. Today, the Discovery still flies in perfect orbit, guided by
the programmers of perfect software, piloted by the best men and
women the nation has to offer. But it is diminished by the
sleaziness for which Clinton stands. The heroism of 36 years ago is
not heroism today.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
