   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ELECTIONS _ Newt Gingrich faces minimum challenge himself, but
all 435 U.S. House seats, 34 U.S. Senate seats and governorships in
36 states are on Tuesday's ballots. If the Republicans don't gain
more than a few seats, conservatives may ask questions about the
budget compromise and the impeachment fuss? (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GLENN _ HOUSTON _ Daily update on Sen. John Glenn and the
shuttle mission. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES _ CLEWISTON, Fla. _ The U.S. Army Corps takes its
South Florida replumbing project out for public comment to
Clewiston, home of U.S. Sugar and a company town. Expect a
capacity-plus crowd. (King, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   FLAVOTE _ Seven to eight million voters will head to the polls
today to elect a new governor and decide the shape of Florida's
cabinet and whether to change the constitution for the first time
in 30 years. (Elmore, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   TRIPLE-EXTRADITE _ Harry Lee Johnson, charged in four murders in
Atlanta, is being extradited to Georgia today.
(Pendered/Longa/Croft, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Police mug from Memphis is not being released at request of
Atlanta police. The AJC is trying for a live shot of Johnson's
arrival in Atlanta and if they are successful photos will be posted
in a folder that has been created on the National folder on the
server.
</P>
<P>
   BARNES&AMP;NOBLE _ Cobb County Solicitor Barry Morgan decides not to
prosecute the Barnes &AMP; Nobles bookstore chain for selling two
coffee table books featuring nudes of young children that some say
is kidie porn. (Payne, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FREEH-RUDOLPH _ FBI Director Louis Freeh is expected to be in
Andrews, N.C., Monday as agents double their efforts in the hunt
for Eric Rudolph. It also marks the opening of deer season, and it
is hoped a hunter will stumble on the fugitive. (Scruggs, Atlanta
Jurnal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MANATEES-WATER _ FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ A plan to create
solar-heated underwater showers for the Moore's Creek manatees is
making waves between manatee-lovers and environmental agencies. The
gentle sea cows have visited the creek each winter for years,
basking in the warm water discharged from a nearby Fort Pierce
Utilities Authority power plant. But the plant, operating less
often under a new agreement to pool power with other utilities, is
generating less warm water. So Liberta Scotto, director of the
Manatee Observation and Education Center, built in 1996 at the
mouth of the creek, proposed the showers as a two-year experiment.
(Swartz, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
