<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9095 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      11-02 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTIONS LIKELY TO OUTLINE CLINTON'S FATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ In ways that the principals in Washington can
neither now imagine nor deny, the pace, intensity, reach, rhythm,
and very likely even the outcome of the presidential impeachment
drama will be incontrovertibly altered by Tuesday's elections in
places like this.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the unusual circumstances and unprecedented stakes of
this year's midterm elections are apparent here in central Florida,
where the four critical elements of this year's contests are
dramatically underlined in one congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in the city neighborhoods, military bases, tourist
attractions, retirement enclaves, orange groves, and bass-fishing
centers scattered between Jacksonville and Orlando, is the American
political landscape writ large: A strong economy. Few competitive
races. The near certainty that a Republican will win a
gubernatorial race. And a whiff of scandal pervading everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election has to be watched closely in the White House,''
said Michael Birkner, a Gettysburg College historian. ``Mr.
Clinton's 1999 will be deeply affected by the results of the 1998
elections.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is seldom mentioned on the stump as
congressional candidates race from shopping malls and autumn fairs
to political forums and downtown rallies. But though his name does
not appear on a single ballot anywhere in the country, his fate in
the White House and perhaps in history may be sealed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   No House Judiciary Committee member who returns to the capital
for this month's impeachment hearings will be unmarked by Tuesday's
results. Some lawmakers who are likely to cast votes on an
impeachment resolution on the House floor in December will have
been repudiated by the voters back home in November. Some of the
jurors in any Senate trial of the president next year will be
chosen this week.
</P>
<P>
   The partisan anger over impeachment that has coursed quietly but
unmistakably beneath the midterm campaigns boiled over with an
exchange of late-hour television advertisements. Even if voters
ultimately make their choices on the basis of candidates' views on
taxes and trade, education and the environment rather than on the
president's conduct, the elections are an important marker in the
sex scandal that has engulfed Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The election results could add fuel to the drive to impeach the
president, or they could persuade lawmakers to find a less severe
resolution to the episode, such as a congressional reprimand or
censure.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee approval of three resolutions of
impeachment against Richard M. Nixon in 1974 came three months
before midterm elections, before the voters had rendered their
verdicts. The votes on any resolutions of impeachment against
Clinton will probably come only weeks after the 1998 midterm
elections, after the voters' verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, when President Clinton first won the White House,
Florida was the most competitive political state in the nation,
with close contests in 21 of the state's 23 congressional
districts. This year, with Jeb Bush almost certain to win the
governor's office in Tallahassee, 18 of Florida's House members are
unopposed, and analysts agree that only one of the 23 races is
remotely competitive.
</P>
<P>
   And in that one race, where Democratic Representative Corinne
Brown is being challenged by onetime local NAACP president Bill
Randall, a cloud of scandal hangs over the battle. Brown is facing
charges of financial irregularities and questions about how her
daughter acquired a $50,000 Lexus, while Randall is facing
questions about fathering a son out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   Here in this classic battleground _ Clinton lost the area by
100,000 votes in 1992, only to win it by 300,000 votes four years
later _ as elsewhere around the country, peculiar local factors
provide the leitmotif of the election. Not since 1982, when
Democrats successfully transformed midterm elections into a broad
debate over the future of Social Security, have off-year elections
been conducted on national themes.
</P>
<P>
   This year, despite the backdrop of scandal and a $10 million
infusion of Republican ads reminding voters about the president's
conduct and his misleading statements, there is little evidence
that the election is a referendum on Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Though a Wall Street Journal/NBC News Poll conducted last week
showed that voters, 47 percent to 25 percent, are less likely to
support a candidate who favors impeachment, the polltakers who
conducted the survey minimize the impact of impeachment on
Tuesday's races.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at it upside down and inside out and you see zero
impact of impeachment, zero referendum on Bill Clinton,'' said
Peter D. Hart, a Democratic pollster.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans don't disagree. William McInturff, a GOP consultant,
compared the Clinton scandals to a baked Alaska dessert. ``There
are flames everywhere, but they burn off and disappear. The
alcohol's kind of gone but there are traces left. Now this looks
like a very normal offterm election. It's very remarkable how
little Clinton's in the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's fate is very much tied to the election. There are
as many scenarios as there are outcomes to the contests.
</P>
<P>
   In the unlikely event of a Democratic takeover of the House, for
example, the Republicans might re-think their drive to impeach the
president in the last few weeks of their control of the chamber _
or they could rush to complete it before their power ebbs.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republicans, who now hold a 22-seat advantage in the
House, tighten their hold, they could feel more emboldened to act
against the president. If their margin, the smallest majority since
1954, diminishes even further, they could feel more restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The size of a Republican majority will tell us a lot about
what happens to him,'' said Austin Ranney, a political scientist at
the University of California at Berkeley. ``And the way the
elections are interpreted could cause a backlash against the
Republicans, not the president, and it may open the way toward a
resolution of this different from impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   For months the public has felt that the course of the
presidential sex scandal was out of their hands. Tuesday, the
public regains control. And its verdict will almost certainly shape
the verdict on the president's conduct _ and shape the politics of
the remainder of the century and the beginning of the presidential
campaign of the year 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 1353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
