<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9104 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-DOCTOR-BOS &LR;      11-02 1770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-DOCTOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL COMMUNITY'S RESPONSE TO DOCTOR'S KILLING   IS MUTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would have sent a powerful message: hundreds of doctors, in
white lab coats, standing as one at the funeral of Dr. Barnett
Slepian. But there was no long white line mourning the New York
obstetrician murdered nine days ago for practicing medicine.
</P>
<P>
   When a police officer is killed in the line of duty, law
enforcement mourns as one. When a firefighter dies doing his job,
the funeral is attended by scores of colleagues from around the
country. When writer Salman Rushdie was targeted for death in 1989
by the ayatollah, authors picketed the Iranian mission to the
United Nations and called for the withdrawal of their books from
any store that chose not to sell Rushdie's novel.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of Slepian's murder, the response from the
medical establishment has been muted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is everybody?'' asks Dr. Richard Hausknecht, a New York
physician who helped establish the first legal abortion clinic in
New York City in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is a bright, capable, and highly trained ob-gyn
performing his life's work; he provided prenatal care, he delivered
babies, provided contraception and safe, legal abortions. And he
was brutally killed before his family's eyes. Just think of those
kids in the kitchen with their daddy. But there is silence from the
elected House and Senate and the medical establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, where three doctors who perform abortions have been
wounded by a sniper in the past four years, the response from the
medical establishment has been outrage _ and action. On Monday, the
day of Slepian's funeral, the Canadian Medical Association
announced a $250,000 reward for information leading to the arrest
of the individuals involved in the Canadian shootings. Law
enforcement officials believe one person may be responsible for the
three Canadian shootings and Slepian's assassination. The
association is trying to get its regional organizations to up the
reward to $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physicians in this country banded together to help each
other,'' said Marc Perreault, of the Canadian Medical Association.
``The more money offered, the more information might come in, and
we will not tolerate violence of any kind against doctors, and we
just saw this as the best way to protect physicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Canadian organization's US counterpart _ the
300,000-member American Medical Association _ has offered a more
tepid response. On Monday it issued a statement expressing shock
and sorrow at Slepian's death and noted that ``violence is never an
acceptable response to resolving the philosphical, moral, and
religious differences we may share as a people.''
</P>
<P>
   Randolph Smoak, chairman of the AMA board of trustees, said in
an interview Thursday that the AMA would also meet tomorrow with
Attorney General Janet Reno and the FBI to express concern over the
violence, and get information on how health care workers can better
protect themselves. But on Friday, a spokesman for Reno said the
attorney general will be on vacation all week, and had no meeting
scheduled with the AMA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local medical society (in New York) has a very strong
expression against this useless killing, and we have shown
responsiveness,'' said Smoak. ``I'm not sure what you can expect to
hope for, except that law enforcement can bring the killers to
justice and you protect yourself as best as you can.'' There are no
immediate plans, he said, for the AMA to offer reward money or to
organize any formal demonstration against the violence.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists
called for all groups in the abortion debate to speak against
violence, an increase in state and federal intervention, and
increased physician training in abortion _ in all, a much stronger
response than the AMA's.
</P>
<P>
   While several doctors from around the country have volunteered
to go to Buffalo to work in Slepian's place until a permanent
replacement can be found, such expressions appear isolated and not
anything close to an expression of medical solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the medical community as a whole, in every single
community, not to be out condemning this horrific act is
astonishing,'' said Kate Michelman, president of the National
Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League. ``All doctors
should be out there, but ACOG are the only ones,'' she said,
referring to the American College of Obstetricians and
Gynecologists.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie J. Regan, a history professor at the Univerity of
Illinois and author of ``When Abortion Was a Crime: Medicine, and
the Law in the United States, 1867-1973,'' said the lack of a
unified voice is shocking but not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is shocking to me because Dr. Slepian as well as other
physicians assassinated and attacked are members of the medical
profession,'' Regan said. ``If this could happen to one portion of
the profession, it could happen to any other if their procedures
become politicized.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is not surprising, she said, because the AMA has always
viewed abortion with suspicion. Consider that the AMA and Boston
physician Horatio Shorter were in the vanguard in making abortion
illegal in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   That opposition, say Regan and Carole Joffe, author of ``Doctors
of Conscience: The Struggle to Provide Abortion Before and After
Roe v. Wade,'' led to the push to criminalize the procedure in the
late 1800s _ not on moral grounds but in an effort to set
professional standards and drive out midwives and others who had
not received the same training.
</P>
<P>
   Much more recently, in 1997, the AMA endorsed legislation that
would ban late-term abortion, a procedure referred to by abortion
foes as ``partial birth abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is safe to say that some abortion providers feel
disappointed in the mainstream medical community,'' said Stephanie
Mueller, communications director for the National Abortion
Federation, an organization of abortion providers that works almost
like a mini-AMA.
</P>
<P>
   Michelman is more blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organized medical profession has allowed the antichoice
zealots to demonize the medical service of abortion. They have
isolated the doctors and health care professionals who perform
abortions, as if it is some untouchable service. But this is a
medical service that (more than 1 million) women need and receive
every year.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, however, it was the strong demand for abortion
that accounts for some of its isolation from the rest of medicine.
Only 10 percent of abortions are performed in hospitals. The vast
majority are done in clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it is so safe, and can be done without general
anesthesia, abortion providers really pioneered the freestanding
outpatient surgery clinics,'' said Joffe.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a downside: This not only made it easier for
antiabortionists to target and picket clinics, it also ``made it
easier for organized medicine to not face the reality that abortion
is a medical procedure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That disassociation comes with other costs for those doctors who
perform abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond the terror campaign ... people who have made abortion
provision a center point of their career have had promotions
denied, privileges at hospitals canceled, and partners will say
they should receive less remuneration because they bring a stigma
to the practice,'' said Joffe.
</P>
<P>
   And in medical schools, most students don't have to learn how to
do abortions if they don't want to, unlike other widely used
procedures. In fact, students frequently have to make a great
effort _ such as taking elective classes when they are already
working more than 80 hours a week _ to learn the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might come up in an ethics class, but students don't learn
about the procedure, how it is done, how to manage complications,
or how to talk to a patient about an unplanned pregnancy,'' said
Patricia Anderson, executive director of Medical Students for
Choice, a California-based group that is advocating for instruction
on abortion and has 100 chapters in medical schools around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   A study published in 1995 found that only 12 percent of all
ob-gyn residency programs required training in abortion, and there
is nothing to indicate the numbers have gone up appreciably since
then.
</P>
<P>
   After that study, the Accreditation Council for Graduate Medical
Education ruled that to be accredited, all ob-gyn residency
programs should require abortion training. But Congress did an
end-run around that rule, saying that schools that did not provide
the training _ and thus failed to win accreditation _ would still
get federal money. So far, no program has lost its accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   The net effect, said Anderson, is ``Students ... are getting a
strong message: Abortion is not a medical issue.''
</P>
<P>
   More training, abortion rights supporters say, would mean more
doctors able to perform abortions, thereby making it harder for key
individuals to be targeted by abortion foes. It would also mean
more doctors in other fields who would speak out against
antiabortion violence.
</P>
<P>
   Medical Students for Choice was formed after Dr. David Gunn was
killed outside a Pensacola, Fla., clinic on March 10, 1993 _ the
first person to be killed in abortion-related violence. Although
that murder shocked the nation, the murder of Slepian on Oct. 23
resonates in a different, and perhaps more powerful, way.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is because Slepian was murdered in his own home by a
sniper's bullet that blasted through the kitchen window. Or perhaps
it's because his sons and wife watched his life ebb away as the
sniper fled. Or perhaps because so many of his patients _ many
holding the hands of the children he delivered into the world _
came to his funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, some, like Jodi Magee, executive director
of Physicians for Reproductive Choice and Health, believe that
Slepian's murder ``is a watershed moment for us in the physician
community. There is an image of him as a fuller person and doctor
... that is galvanizing doctors who are saying this is
unacceptable. The statement by ACOG is an example of this.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the AMA does indeed arrange a meeting with the nation's
top law enforcement officials, it may signal a new urgency.
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, almost too much for some to hope that Slepian's
murder will be the rallying cry for a move to bring abortion back
into the medical mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to believe that,'' said Michelman, ``but I don't
know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
