<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9110 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SETI-BOS &LR;      11-02 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SETI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYBODY'S INVITED TO LISTEN IN TO SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the most powerful computers on Earth have been built
specifically to scan radio waves picked up by huge radiotelescope
dishes in search of some sign of a signal from intelligent beings
on another world _ a task that has been likened to searching for a
needle in a cosmic haystack.
</P>
<P>
   But now, scientists involved in SETI _ the Search for
Extra-Terrestrial Intelligence _ have their eyes on another
computer: Yours.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, lots of yourses. The plan is to enlist at least
100,000 volunteers to help analyze radiotelescope data with their
own ordinary desktop (or even laptop) PCs.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is at once disarmingly simple and amazingly
powerful: Divide up that huge haystack into lots of tiny bundles of
hay, and send each bundle to an individual. Instead of looking for
a needle in a giant haystack, many thousands of individuals can
search through their small bundles _ a much more manageable task.
</P>
<P>
   It's called distributed computing, and it's an idea that may
someday be applied to a variety of tasks in science and other
fields. It has already been used, for example, to help crack a
computer code. But this application comes with an unusually grand
potential payoff. Some volunteer who signs up for the project might
someday be credited with what many scientists and philosophers
believe could be the most important and transformative discovery in
human history. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Like the lottery, it's one of those low-probability but
high-impact outcomes. Only in this case, the whole world would be
changed, instead of one lucky person's bank account. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The project has been in the works for three years, but just
two weeks ago it got the funding needed to bring it to reality.
Grants of $50,000 each from the Planetary Society, a nonprofit
space advocacy group, and from Paramount Pictures, which hopes to
use the project as a promotional tie-in for its December release of
another ``Star Trek'' movie, will pay for perfecting the computer
software that will be sent free of charge to all who sign up.
</P>
<P>
   Already, more than the desired 100,000 people have signed up,
although not all may end up participating. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``It brings a new level of personal involvement'' to
exploration, said Louis Friedman, executive director of the
Planetary Society. It used to be that the only way ordinary
citizens could play a role in projects such as planetary
exploration or the search for extraterrestrials was by contributing
money, he said, but distributed computing allows hands-on
involvement, which could someday also be applied to analyzing data
from robotic exploration of other planets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be so elitist and esoteric, only a few people could
work on it,'' Friedman said. ``The number of SETI researchers in
the world now is about 20. Now it will be more than 100,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The program won't tie up the volunteers' computers; it will only
work during moments when the computer is switched on but sitting
idle. In fact, it's just the world's most sophisticated screen
saver.
</P>
<P>
   Like any other screen saver, it is designed to load
automatically after the computer has been unused for a few minutes
(as with all screen savers, the exact interval can be set by the
user). It then begins processing a chunk of data from the world's
largest radiotelescope dish, the Arecibo observatory in Puerto
Rico, downloaded earlier over the Internet. Each chunk of data will
consist of 250 kilobytes, or a quarter of a megabyte, and the
program itself will take up about 10 megabytes on the user's hard
drive _ comparable to many application programs today, and less
than most videogames.
</P>
<P>
   As the program crunches the data, the screen will show exactly
what it's doing, with colored graphs showing the peaks of intensity
as it scans through hundreds of radio frequency channels, looking
for strong peaks of transmission that stand out from the background
noise.
</P>
<P>
   When the analysis of that data is complete _ typically, it
should take a week or two of idle moments, but can vary
considerably, depending on how long the computer is left on _ that
chunk is sent back to a central computer at the University of
California, Berkeley, where the project will be run. At the same
time, a new packet of data is downloaded. All this happens
automatically whenever the computer user logs onto the internet,
and does not interfere with other activity.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the entire search operates in a ``piggyback'' mode. The
Arecibo telescope, the most powerful of its kind, is in use
virtually full time for astronomical projects, but a group of
Berkeley astronomers came up with an ingenious plan for using the
telescope for the SETI project without interfering with its primary
work. They simply attached a second radio receiver to the back end
of the receiving platform suspended high above the 1,000-foot dish.
</P>
<P>
   This secondary receiver points in a random direction, controlled
by the primary researchers observing plans. But that's fine with
the SETI astronomers, because they have no idea where to look
anyway. Over the course of a year, their random observations cover
virtually all of the sky that's visible from Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The software, which will be sent free to volunteers, won't be
ready until April, although a few copies will be sent out for
testing in December.
</P>
<P>
   In full swing, the project is expected to increase by about
tenfold the power to detect faint signals, said project scientist
Daniel Werthimer of Berkeley. It will also make it possible to look
for more subtle kinds of signals &UR;  &LR; than past searches.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that nobody's done before is look for
pulsing signals. It's very hard. Nobody's been able to do that
before because it's so computationally intensive,'' Werthimer said
in a telephone interview from Arecibo last week. ``We'd like to
look for as many patterns and frequencies as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The searches now in operation _ the SETI Institute's Project
Phoenix, the Planetary Society funded BETA project at a
radiotelescope in Harvard, Mass., and Berkeley's SERENDIP project
at Arecibo, among others _ use different strategies and are looking
for different types of signals, since nobody really knows what an
alien civilization might be sending.
</P>
<P>
   ``In SETI, we should try as many things as possible,'' Werthimer
said. ``A hundred years ago, we might have said smoke signals were
the thing to look for.''
</P>
<P>
   In the future, new technologies may suggest completely different
ways of sending signals across the vast distances between the
stars. While most searches have concentrated in radio waves, one
team is gearing up for a search for laser pulses from other stars
instead.
</P>
<P>
   If a promising signal does get discovered in one of the packets
of data sent out by the new project, which is titled SETI(AT)home,
the person whose computer found it won't know about it right away.
Intriguing signals are found all the time _ and usually turn out to
be airplanes or satellites or other terrestrial interference.
</P>
<P>
   The project leaders don't want to get people all excited about
such false alarms, so any ``hits'' will be sent back to Berkeley
for further analysis and testing.
</P>
<P>
   But whoever finds that first signal will get credit. The data
will be labelled with the finder's identity, and if a signal does
prove to be real after weeks of followup, he or she will be
notified.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person that did it will find out and become famous,''
Werthimer said, ``but they won't know right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with a home or office computer who wants to join the
project can sign up on line, or by calling the Planetary Society.
The SETI(AT)home software will be available in versions for PC, and
eventually Macintosh and Unix-based computers.
</P>
<P>
   To sign up online, connect to one of these sites:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; http://www.planetary.org/
</P>
<P>
   http://setiathome.ssl.berkeley.edu/
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Museum of Science features SETI research in its 40th
anniversary planetarium program, ``Quest for Contact,'' which
premieres Friday. The program features Jill Tarter, director of the
SETI Institute's Project Phoenix search, who was the inspiration
for the Jodie Foster character in the movie ``Contact.'' She will
be available outside the planetarium Thursday from 2 to 3 p.m. to
answer questions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
