<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9119 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTH-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      11-02 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HAS A MINOR ROLE IN THE SOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ In the South, where President Clinton was rejected
in most states in 1996, the White House scandal is not a
significant factor in this year's campaign, and the Democratic
Party has a chance to hold its own in major races.
</P>
<P>
   While political analysts in Washington are debating the wisdom
of a Republican Party decision to use the issue in an eleventh-hour
advertising offensive, contests in Dixie appear to be turning on
other matters.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama and South Carolina, incumbent Republican governors
are struggling for survival in the face of Democratic initiatives
to create state lotteries to finance education programs. Thinly
veiled racial themes are being used by GOP candidates in Georgia
and Arkansas, and personalities are very much in play in other
races around the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``If history is any guide, next Tuesday's election is about
local issues,'' said Doug Sosnick, one of Clinton's chief political
advisers on the White House staff.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign winds up, it appears that the embattled
Democratic Party could escape with a standoff in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jeb Bush is favored to win the governor's office that
had been held by a Democrat in Florida, Republican Governor Fob
James of Alabama is trailing in polls going into the final weekend.
And in closely contested Senate races, Republican Senator Launch
Faircloth is involved in a desperate fight to keep his seat in
North Carolina, while Senator Ernest F. Hollings, a Democrat, holds
a slight lead in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Republican pollster Whit Ayres believes that the
Clinton factor could hold down Democratic turnout in some cases,
but most of the statewide races are expected to be determined by
other issues.
</P>
<P>
   _Alabama: Republican Senator Richard Shelby is breezing to an
easy reelection, but James has become the most vulnerable GOP
incumbent in the South. Lieutenant Governor Don Siegelman, the
Democratic gubernatorial candidate, leads James 49-43 in the latest
published poll. Siegelman's advantage is attributed to his proposal
to institute a state lottery to fund college scholarships for
Alabama students, a concept that worked for outgoing Georgia
Governor Zell Miller. James is hurt by weakness in his own party.
Elements of the Republican business establishment tried
unsuccessfully to take out James in the GOP primary earlier this
year when they backed Winton Blount. ``A lot of Blount supporters
have come to Siegelman,'' said Giles Perkins, executive director of
the Alabama Democratic Party. ``We believe the race will be very
tight and come down to whether the voters of Alabama want a new
education program or not.''
</P>
<P>
   _Arkansas: Republican Governor Mike Huckabee is far in front of
his Democratic challenger, but Blanche L. Lincoln, a former
Democratic congresswoman, holds an equally commanding lead in state
polls over Republican Fay Boozman in the race for a Senate seat
being given up by retiring Democratic Senator Dale Bumpers.
Boozman, who hurt himself with remarks about a ``protective
shield,'' caused by adrenaline fueled by fear, that keeps rape
victims from getting pregnant. has drawn criticism for an ad
attacking Lincoln for supporting ``foreign aid to Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   _Florida: Jeb Bush is expected to join his brother, Texas
Governor George W. Bush, in the ranks of the nation's governors by
defeating Democrat Buddy MacKay. Bush, who is reaching out to an
erstwhile Democratic constituency with a moderate approach, has
held a comfortable lead all year. MacKay is hobbled by an
internecine struggle within the state Democratic Party growing out
of the ouster of a black legislative leader. Nevertheless,
Democratic Senator Bob Graham has a 30-point polling lead over his
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   _Georgia: With the popular Miller not a candidate for
reelection, Republican businessman Guy Millner and Democratic state
Representative Roy Barnes are locked in a nip-and-tuck race for the
governor's office. Rather than linking Barnes to the president,
Millner has tied him to prominent black politicians, primarily the
mayor of Atlanta, Bill Campbell. Senator Paul Coverdell, a
Republican, is expected to win reelection easily.
</P>
<P>
   _Louisiana: In the last reliable Democratic bastion left in the
South, Senator John Breaux is a heavy favorite over a weak
Republican adversary.
</P>
<P>
   _North Carolina: The Clinton issue is most visible in the Senate
race here, where Faircloth accuses John Edwards, the Democratic
candidate, of serving as a Clinton acolyte and supporting the
president's tobacco tax hike. Edwards, who is tied with Faircloth
in polls, responded with a new ad this week: ``Lauch Faircloth
keeps hitting John Edwards with Bill Clinton. But it's Lauch
Faircloth who has voted with Bill Clinton over 200 times. Is Lauch
a liberal?''
</P>
<P>
   _South Carolina: Former State House minority leader Jim Hughes,
a Democrat, is waging a strong campaign to unseat Governor David
Beasley. Hughes is an advocate of a state lottery to fund
education; Beasley antagonized members of his conservative base
last year by trying to take down the Confederate battle flag from
atop the state capitol. The local issues have turned the governor's
race into a neck-and-neck stretch run. Hollings, a Democratic
incumbent with an irascible style, did not help his cause by
inviting his opponent, Representative Bob Inglis, to ``kiss my
fanny.'' But the five-term senator hangs on to a lead in statewide
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   _Tennessee: Governor Don Sundquist, swept into office by a
Republican tide in 1994, is believed to be well ahead of John Jay
Hooker, a Democratic populist.
</P>
<P>
   _Texas: The governor's race is expected to be a warm-up for
incumbent George Bush as he prepares for a run at the Republican
presidential nomination. Bush has held an overwhelming lead all
year over Land Commissioner Gary Mauro and has no need to use
Clinton as a cudgel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
