<HEADER>
A9123 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-GOVERNOR-BOS &LR;      11-02 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GOVERNOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUCH HANGS IN THE BALANCE IN GOVERNOR RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ No one has jumped into the Charles River just to make a
point. No one has fallen off a stage after giving a speech. And no
one has resorted to Yiddish curse words.
</P>
<P>
   While the 1998 run for governor has been relatively low on
theatrics that have been mainstays of other campaigns, it has still
been a tense, largely negative, battle that remains a close contest
as voters prepare to cast their ballots Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Paul Cellucci is the no-new-taxes candidate,
promising to steer the Commonwealth safely through whatever
economic times lie ahead. Democrat Scott Harshbarger is the social
activist, hoping to take advantage of the state's strong financial
picture to expand health care, improve education, and better-train
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Massachusetts election that really does matter,''
said Elizabeth A. Sherman, director of the Center for Women in
Politics and Public Policy at the University of Massachusetts. ``It
is more of a turning point than people realize.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from setting a tone and an agenda for the state, the next
governor will grapple with whatever economic downturn may arise,
will appoint at least three judges to the seven-member Supreme
Judicial Court, and will oversee the redrawing of the state's
congressional lines. On education, the governor will help determine
whether state spending for public schools continues after funding
for the Education Reform Act of 1993 expires.
</P>
<P>
   But these are not always the issues that voters hear about.
Debates between the two men have been nasty, with each candidate
trying to talk over the other, interrupting, and name calling.
``That's a lie'' or ``Tell the truth'' has been a common refrain
from Harshbarger to Cellucci. ``Scott, you can't handle the
truth,'' Cellucci sneered back at the last matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, they have made such a mess of their
presentations in the context of these debates, it makes it hard for
thoughtful voters to make up their minds,'' said Michael Cudahy, an
independent media consultant who was once active in Republican
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Voters who did not tune out were treated to a diet of death
penalty, taxes, welfare, and teacher testing by Cellucci, the
acting governor. And Cellucci's agenda largely overwhelmed Attorney
General Harshbarger's attempts to talk about crumbling schools and
health insurance for children.
</P>
<P>
   Bird-dogging it all has been Cellucci's estimated $700,000 in
personal debt. First in the Republican primary, and now in the
general election campaign, Cellucci's opponents have questioned how
he accumulated so much red ink and whether he can be trusted to
hold the state's purse strings, and have been unsatisfied by his
accounting of his finances.
</P>
<P>
   Even the heretofore unspoken rumor of gambling as a possible
explanation for Cellucci's debt entered the campaign give and take.
</P>
<P>
   To that, Cellucci vehemently denied any problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things are totally false, there's no truth to them,
there's nothing there, and believe me, they've searched,'' he said.
Cellucci described himself as a ``casual fan'' of horse racing and
denied that he had ever lost hundreds of thousands of dollars at
the track.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci also tried to turn the issue around against
Harshbarger, accusing him of attacking Cellucci's family. Jan
Cellucci, the acting governor's wife, spoke out for the first time
during the race. She said Harshbarger and his supporters had gone
too far, and she said he ought to apologize. Harshbarger refused to
yield, calling Cellucci's tactic ``sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Argeo Paul Cellucci, 50, was born in Marlborough and raised in
Hudson. He has spent the bulk of his adult life in politics,
beginning with the Board of Selectmen in Hudson, moving on to the
state House of Representatives, the state Senate, and then the
lieutenant governor's office. It was former governor William F.
Weld's resignation in the summer of 1997 that led to Cellucci's
elevation to the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Luther Scott Harshbarger, 56, was born in New Haven and raised
in Pennsylvania Furnace, Pa., a small farming town. He has spent
his career as a public servant working on criminal justice issues,
running the Middlesex district attorney's office and then the
attorney general's office. It was US Representative Joseph P.
Kennedy II's decision to drop out of the governor's race in the
summer of 1997 that catapulted Harshbarger to the head of the
Democratic pack.
</P>
<P>
   In person, both men are mild mannered and would never be
considered larger-than-life. Cellucci is a State House insider,
close to Democrats and Republicans. Harshbarger is an outsider
within his own party _ unpopular for some of his
political-corruption prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways there are more similarities between the two men
than differences. There is a dogged quality to each of their
personalities and to each of their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The race began on primary night in mid-September with Cellucci
immediately going after Harshbarger, describing him as a risk to
the state's economic security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our state cannot afford to return to the failed policies of
the late 1980s,'' Cellucci said in his victory speech at the Park
Plaza hotel in Boston. ``The state cannot afford Scott Harshbarger
as governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the last seven weeks, Cellucci has portrayed
Harshbarger as someone who would raise taxes, increase spending,
and hurt the economy. In television advertising, Cellucci mocked
Harshbarger for having the wrong priorities, portraying him as a
dilettante attorney general more interested in suing a toothpaste
manufacturer than prosecuting crime.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger, on the other hand, launched his general election
campaign with a victory speech aimed at the Democrats who had made
him their standard bearer, rather than to a wider audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor's agenda is my agenda,'' he said, mentioning every
social program and issue under the sun that he hoped to address and
fix as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger's campaign has been more about attacking Cellucci
for failing working families than about his own plans for the
corner office.
</P>
<P>
   On the minimum wage, Harshbarger derided Cellucci for opposing
an increase every year until he began running for governor. On
health care, Harshbarger scolded Cellucci for vetoing legislation
that would have increased the tobacco tax to pay for covering
uninsured children. And on education, Harshbarger ridiculed
Cellucci for promising to hire 4,000 teachers, and then not funding
the positions.
</P>
<P>
   Though the candidates have tried to stick to their scripts, the
animosity between them became apparent. While they have hurled
insults at each other inside the debate halls and on the campaign
trail, their sign-wielding supporters have gotten into fistfights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know when I've ever seen a campaign that has
degenerated into so much personal insult and affrontery,'' Sherman
said. ``It's just palpable. They can't help themselves. They are
true enemies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
