<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9124 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAHN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      11-02 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAHN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE-WHEELING MEMORIES OF THE MACHINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If the threatened Y2K computer catastrophe crashes
everyone's computer, I'd be the only one in this joint who could
produce Election Day copy _ on my 50-year-old Royal Standard
typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you'd never see it because everything down line is
online. The whole bleeding process of turning computer terminal
words into printed words is controlled by computers. No more
typewriters. No more linotype machines. None of the older presses
that printed off cast-metal cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   And if all our newfangled voting and computerized
ballot-counting systems crashed in a Y2K catastrophe, we would be
cast back into the era of paper or punch-out ballots. I'd be able
to once again wear my large lapel pin that declares:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm From Chicago ... Two Ballots, Please!''
</P>
<P>
   The local precinct people here never thought that was very
funny. I'm not sure they had even the foggiest idea why that might
be amusing. But for anyone growed-up on Chicago machine politics,
it kindles a kind of uncivilized civic nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   Machine politics doesn't refer to computerized voting or the
vintage voting machines, although they were an integral part of the
larger political machine. It was not uncommon to see a local
precinct worker, sometimes called a ``ward heeler,'' step behind
the voting machine privacy curtain to ``assist'' a bewildered
voter.
</P>
<P>
   The most magnificent of all machines ever invented by man was
the good ol' Chicago political machine. It was the closest we've
ever come to true perpetual motion because it ran on an endless
supply of greed, power and control, and was well-oiled by legions
who were, of course, vested in the machine system.
</P>
<P>
   That it developed from a street science to an art form under
former Mayor Richard J. Daley was in part a result of the man's
political acumen and partly a natural evolution. The so-called
Daley (read that, Democratic) Machine was a more refined version of
the machine that for years ran the Republican-controlled areas
generally referred to as ``Downstate.'' And it was thus in so many
other states where Democratic politics naturally attached to the
working class and poor folks in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   If you heard truly strange stories about Chicago machine
politics, chances are they were true. Leftover Halloween ghosts had
a habit of coming out of the grave to vote _ at least once. Names
of dead people remained on voter registration lists longer than
names remain on today's computerized mailing lists.
</P>
<P>
   Not only had these mysterious voters long passed into precincts
on the other side (which is not to be confused with voting
Republican), but many of them officially resided in vacant lots,
demolished buildings and yes, even cemeteries. Just an address, any
address, was needed. No one much checked out these things.
</P>
<P>
   And the really live _ sometimes, barely _ voters who stumbled
into the precinct polling places, such as local barber shops, hair
salons, American Legion halls, school auditoriums and even church
basements, oftentimes were derelicts or unfortunates who'd taken 13
steps on a 12-step program.
</P>
<P>
   For doing their civic duty, they were rewarded with a small
stipend, sometimes as small as a half-pint of ``musky'' _
muscatel-fortified wine. Lord only knows how many Chicago votes
were lubricated with a few ounces of cheap beverage, especially in
the days when local public houses were officially closed during
voting hours.
</P>
<P>
   There were election judges, of course, reportedly trained by the
Cook County Clerk and apportioned to polling places on a formula
ensuring representation from both sides. Alas, dozens of precincts
could not secure even one registered Republican to serve, and only
the higher calling of civic duty compelled some Democrats to
volunteer as Republican precinct election judges.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the polls closed and the taverns opened, the long,
drawn-out process of vote-counting was where machine politics
proved itself. Voting results from numerous so-called key precincts
seemed to disappear into the night, held back, some charged, to be
played as a trump card against the opposition's strong gains in
other areas.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, this strategy was also used by the Downstate
Republicans, where election judges explained that they'd taken
ballot boxes home with them to keep them secure. So secure were
some of those Downstate returns that they didn't surface for days.
</P>
<P>
   Which was too late, in many cases, to sway results of a national
election in which all those Chicago ballots were bounced, bobbled
and counted. Some, they say, were counted several times, in the
interest of, say, accuracy. That would be Democratic accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the infamous words of one icon of Chicago Democratic
politics that ``Chicago ain't ready for reform!'' things have moved
closer to the surface. Or maybe just deeper, and less obvious than
the years in which the current mayor's father ran the machine.
</P>
<P>
   If circumstances would allow, I'd vote today _ and at least
twice _ for anyone who promised to work 110 percent to fix the
Social Security mess and the predicted Y2K computer catastrophe.
And against anyone even slightly involved in perpetuating the
impeachment machine in Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
