<HEADLINE>
BRACE YOURSELF: HERE COMES TV'S SWEEPS PERIOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As of this writing, Roseanne was staging the public spectacle of
trying to snag escorts for her three single, twentysomething
daughters. Her ``Date My Daughters'' contest is being conducted
from the pulpit of her new talker, and so far the only criteria is
being Jewish and mentally stable, although standing upright, being
unmarried and clear of criminal activity would rank high on my
list.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Roseanne drill some poor audience member the other day
(he finally asked his girlfriend to stand after it was apparent
Rosie wouldn't let him be) clearly shows that the outspoken one has
fallen in line with the ratings-at-all-cost hustlers she used to
dismiss as spineless parasites.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeps can do that to you. November isn't as crucial (and
therefore as out-and-out silly) as May _ but the ``above-average''
offerings designed to help local stations pull higher ratings and
earn fatter checks from advertisers are still uneven, and often
empty and trashy as well.
</P>
<P>
   The general rule in my household is to steer clear of sitcoms
and approach dramas with some trepidation, even steady offerings
like ABC's ``The Practice.'' That law drama on Nov. 15 begins a
three-episode story line featuring, well, Tony Danza, as a
street-smart (it's a stretch!) lawyer who fancies himself a ``man
of the people.'' (On second thought, Danza spouting David E.
Kelleyisms should prove rather intriguing.)
</P>
<P>
   On cue, Chris Carter delivers the new season of ``The X-Files,''
(Nov. 8) supplanting ``NYPD Blue'' as the drama series so arrogant
it must arrive oh-so-fashionably late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   As for the movies, miniseries and specials, well, read the
warning labels. Productions this month will star Christopher Reeve,
Whoopi Goldberg and Sidney Poitier, but one sure shot might be Ken
Burns' examination of architect Frank Lloyd Wright (Nov. 10-11) on
PBS.
</P>
<P>
   The networks will also trot out high-priced theatrical buys: Fox
has ``The Lost World: Jurassic Park'' (Nov. 1), ABC delivers ``The
Birdcage'' (Nov. 12) and NBC presents ``Twister'' (Nov. 15), all
edited for TV and filled with pesky commercials. (Just go rent the
things.)
</P>
<P>
   What you won't see is NBC's version of Shakespeare's ``The
Tempest.'' After losing its shirt on another literary barn-burner,
``Crime and Punishment,'' the network decided to stick the Peter
Fonda production in the December schedule, where it can do the
least damage. (You can also kiss goodbye any future productions of
that nature.)
</P>
<P>
   At least ``David &AMP; Lisa'' (Sunday, ABC), about a psychiatrist
(Poitier) and the troubled teens he helps, had a graceful pace and
literary feel.
</P>
<P>
   And continuing in that literary vein, we do have an Alex Haley
project. CBS is quite high on ``Mama Flora's Family'' (Nov. 8 and
10), though each Haley-inspired project since ``Roots: The Next
Generation'' has dipped in quality. Even ``Mama Flora'' sounds
calculated. It stars Cicely Tyson as a woman of modest means who
survives three generations and pulls a ``Touched by an Angel'' on
her family members: She instills the importance of God and family
in their lives. There's even a cameo by Della Reese.
</P>
<P>
   If that's not enough, catch Reese's ``Touched'' sidekick, Roma
Downey, along with another in-house star, Moira Kelly (''To Have
and to Hold'') in the network's ``Monday After the Miracle'' (Nov.
15). This one's about the relationship between the grown-up Helen
Keller and her teacher, Annie Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   The most-discussed movie, the ABC remake of the Alfred Hitchcock
suspense thriller ``Rear Window,'' (Nov. 22) even appears
manipulative. For Reeve, who takes over the role played by Jimmy
Stewart, this is the first major acting job since that riding
accident. Producers are promising to put his character, a
quadriplegic, in much more jeopardy than was the case in
Hitchcock's version of the Cornell Woolrich story about a man
convinced that his neighbor is a murderer.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers will probably tune in just to see Reeve, a journeyman
actor who now commands far more attention than he did before his
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Noth returns for more of the same, reprising his role as
Detective Mike Logan from ``Law &AMP; Order,'' in a murder mystery that
also stars his ``L&AMP;O'' buddies Jerry Orbach, Benjamin Bratt, Sam
Waterston and S. Epatha Merkerson.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg appears in ``A Knight in Camelot'' (Nov. 8), about a
20th-century scientist accidentally flung back in time to
sixth-century England. If you've seen ``A Connecticut Yankee in
King Arthur's Court,'' you've got the general idea.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of cable movies look promising: HBO's ``Winchell,'' with
Stanley Tucci as the legendary journalist (Nov. 21), and ``A
Soldier's Sweetheart,'' with Kiefer Sutherland in a Vietnam-related
drama slated for Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most anticipated happening of sweeps is in series
TV, where Fred Savage (''Wonder Years'') joins his kid brother in a
Nov. 6 episode of ABC's ``Boy Meets World.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that would be the 90-minute installment of ``NYPD
Blue'' set for Nov. 24. Jimmy Smits exits the 15th Precinct after
four seasons, opening the doors for a Dec. 1 debut of Rick
Schroder.
</P>
<P>
   No word yet on Smits' post-''Blue'' plans.
</P>
<P>
   Is he Jewish? Roseanne might still have an opening.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
