</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FUNDING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLUSH TIMES FOR BIOMEDICAL RESEARCHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A windfall of federal dollars is about to land on Massachusetts'
formidable biomedical research enterprise, fueling an unprecedented
spending spree on everything from Alzheimer's to asthma, confocal
laser microscopy machines to clinical trials, aspiring young
scientists to new buildings for them to work in.
</P>
<P>
   How big is the boon? Here's one way to gauge:
</P>
<P>
   Roll together the $80 million that Congress just appropriated
for more than 15 new rail transportation projects from Springfield
to Cape Cod; the $50 million extra voted for the Boston Harbor
cleanup; the additional $20 million for the Big Dig; and $14
million for nine national parks in the Bay State.
</P>
<P>
   The grand total of $164 million earmarked for all these
tax-funded blessings is still $10 million short of the new money
the National Institutes of Health is expected to funnel to
Massachusetts hospitals and universities in the coming year,
swelling the state's total NIH revenue stream to more than $1.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The extra $174 million far exceeds the entire current annual
federal take of Massachusetts General or Brigham and Women's
hospitals. It's more than the combined yearly federal research
outlays for Dana Farber Cancer Institute, Children's Hospital, and
Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a boost like this creates a tremendous opportunity for
Harvard, for the people of Boston, for technology companies, for
the general welfare of society _ a tremendous opportunity,'' exults
Dr. Joseph Martin, dean of Harvard Medical School. ``It's the
largest increase, both by percentage and by amount, we have ever
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's increase comes on top of already flush times for
medical research. ``This is not the first good year,'' notes NIH
director Harold Varmus. ``The last three years we've had 6 or 7
percent increases when inflation was only 2.5 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Some local research institutions have managed to do considerably
better than that. ``In the past year we've seen a 20 percent
increase in our overall grant income through recruitment of a lot
of good people,'' reports Aram Chobanian, dean of Boston University
Medical School. ``Since 1991, we've risen from 41st to 20th among
all US medical schools in federal funding.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospects are even brighter. The 1999 windfall is supposed
to be just a down payment on a breathtaking new era of federal
investment in medical research.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston-based lobbying effort has quietly been building
bipartisan support for nothing less than a doubling of the NIH
budget over the next five years, from $13.6 billion in 1998 to
$26.4 billion in 2003. Massachusetts institutions historically reap
10 percent of NIH ``extramural'' funds _ the 78 percent of the
budget that the agency spends outside its Bethesda campus.
</P>
<P>
   Since there are no guarantees that the 1999 bonanza will be
repeated in the next four budget cycles, deans and department
chairmen and disease-funding advocates plan to keep pushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress just doesn't write five-year contracts, so we have to
keep the pressure on,'' says Arthur Ullian, an energetic
59-year-old Boston real estate developer rendered paraplegic by a
1991 bicycle accident, who has become a spearhead of the ambitious
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Their success so far has surprised even Ullian and his unusual
cast of co-conspirators, who include scientists such as cancer
researchers Dr. Judah Folkman of Children's Hospital and Eric
Lander of MIT, mutual-fund guru Peter Lynch, biotech entrepreneur
Henri Termeer, liberal Sen. Edward M. Kennedy and conservative Sen.
Connie Mack of Florida, quadraplegic movie star Christopher Reeve,
and Boston University student Travis Roy, paralyzed from an
accident during his first college hockey game.
</P>
<P>
   The winning argument, Ullian says, was a canny combination of
hard-headed economics and unabashed emotion. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``We had Travis Roy testify from his wheelchair,'' Ullian
recalls. ``He said, `I know we can cure this thing if we put our
minds to it. I just want to hug my mother.' The senators just
crumbled. There was silence. Then each of the 12 senators started
talking about their own experience with illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the conspicuous involvement of spinal cord-injured
advocates such as Ullian, Reeve, and Roy, it's not surprising that
regrowth of damage nerved cells stands to gain new prominence from
the congressional largesse.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be a large increase in effort on spinal cord
regeneration,'' says Dr. Gerald Fischbach, director of the National
Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke, which will reap
what Fischbach calls an ``unexpectedly large'' $124 million, or 16
percent, budget increase. ``I believe there is a wonderful
opportunity. We now know there are factors that inhibit and enhance
nerve regeneration.''
</P>
<P>
   However, one of the remarkable departures in the recent NIH
funding saga is that advocates of the disease-by-disease approach
have put aside their usual rivalries, at least temporarily, in
favor of a rising-tide-lifts-all-boats strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality has always been that pitting one disease against
another is an artificial juxtaposition,'' says Daniel Zingale,
executive director of AIDS Action. ```AIDS research benefits
Alzheimer's, and cancer research benefits AIDS. I think that
resonated with the Congress.'' (AIDS research, at $1.7 billion the
largest NIH category except for cancer, will gain 12.1 percent _
enabling an expected, and overdue, emphasis on developing AIDS
vaccines.)
</P>
<P>
   The result of an across-the-board budget increase is a
cornucopia of new opportunities that has NIH officials and their
advisers working overtime on spending plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the question is: What are we going to do with the money?''
says Dr. Valentin Fuster, president of the American Heart
Association. ``The National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute has
come up with three priorities: the role of inflammation in
atherosclerosis, the interaction of genes and environment, and how
we can make new blood vessels and heart tissue grow.''
</P>
<P>
   On NIH director Varmus' list of priorities are ``genomics'' _
the translation of new genetic knowledge into targeted therapies _
and stepped-up human trials of new drugs against cancer, arthritis,
neuromuscular diseases, drug abuse, and alternative medicines, such
as a study of the putative antidepressant herb St. John's Wort that
the NIH already has under way. (The overall budget for alternative
medicine research has jumped from $20 million to $50 million, and
the area has won new status as a research center with grant-making
authority.)
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most critical payoffs, research administrators said,
are not in such sexy areas as spinal cord regeneration, AIDS
vaccines, or breast cancer therapies, but rather in general growth
of the nation's medical research infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, NIH-funded researchers can expect to get grants
that come closer to covering the actual costs of their projects &UR; , &LR; 
instead of the 90 percent that has become standard practice. ``Full
funding will mean scientists can spend more time doing the science
and less looking for money,'' says Dr. John T. Potts, MGH's
director of research.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, NIH will foster training of physicians to do
clinical research. ``There was a appalling 30 percent decline in
the number of physicians who were first-time applicants for NIH
grants between 1994 and 1996,'' says Dr. David Nathan, president of
Dana Farber Cancer Institute. ``If you extrapolate that, there
won't be any physician investigators by the year 2003.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most fundamentally, the new money will improve the
prospects that good proposals will get funded. In recent years, NIH
has been able to fund fewer than a third of projects deemed worthy
after rigorous review.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important impact of all this is sort of a spiritual
one,'' says Dr. Eugene Braunwald, vice president for research at
Partners Healthcare. ``In the last 10 years, some of our
outstanding fellows and residents and graduate students have not
really even considered a career in biomedical research. By
augmenting research funding, we'll have a tremendous effect,
particularly in Boston where we have such superb young minds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
