<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-$ADV03-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY CLUES TO THE ELECTION NIGHT TREND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Tuesday, Nov. 3, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Face it, it's going to be a long night for the
politically crazed. But for normal people with jobs to get to,
there's still a way to get a sense of the election results without
joining the junkies after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   On television, the trick is to take the right clues from the
statewide races where the polls close first, and from a
representative sampling of usually under-covered House races. It is
more than possible to get the drift before the big ones out here
check in after 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, is my cheat sheet:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; 6 O'CLOCK &QC; 
 &LR;  _Kentucky is traditionally a decent barometer of national trends,
but this year it is an off-year gem. The Senate seat opened by
Democrat Wendell Ford's retirement is must-carry for each party and
is a very tight race between two congressmen, one a GOP Hall of
Fame pitcher (Jim Bunning), the other an early 1960s captain of one
of Adolph Rupp's famous UK basketball teams (Scotty Baesler).
</P>
<P>
   And that race has opened up two of the country's closest 32
incumbent-less House races, for Bunning's 4th District seat in the
east and Baesler's 6th District in central Kentucky. In addition,
the 3d District, which includes Louisville, presents a good example
(in Republican Anne Northrup) of an incumbent who should win but
who has been pressed. If you watch on cable, House results are
constantly scrolled across the bottom of your TV.
</P>
<P>
   _Indiana is almost as good, with three House seats likely to
provide quick clues to the national trend. In the
Indianapolis-centered 10th District, Democratic freshman Julia
Carson is like Northrup _ favored but pressed.
</P>
<P>
   But to the south, along the Ohio River are two much closer
races. In the southwestern 8th, New Right Republican John
Hostettler is again in a tight one. And right next door in the 9th,
from which veteran Democrat Lee Hamilton is retiring, the race is
also close and one the GOP badly needs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; 7 O'CLOCK &QC; 
 &LR;  _The clues at this hour will be about the Deep South. In Florida,
Jeb Bush is favored to be elected governor on his second try.
Barring a gigantic upset, the real issue here is how quickly the
networks call it, and how close Lieutenant Governor Buddy MacKay
makes it, an early hint about the intensity of Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   _Georgia is another state where the GOP has a decent shot at
picking up a governor's office. But here the race between
businessman Guy Millner and legislative leader Roy Barnes has been
very close and polluted by race-baiting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; 7:30 P.M. &QC; 
 &LR;  _North Carolina ia a doozie this year. Not only is the critical
Senate fight between GOP Senator Lauch Faircloth and wealthy lawyer
John Edwards a nail-biter, but three of the mercurial state's 12
House districts (all currently Democratic) are in play as well.
Faircloth's campaign will provide a clue to sentiment about the
president because he has used a ``Clinton Clone'' motif to tar his
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   In the 2d District around Raleigh, freshman Bob Etheridge has an
anti-Clinton-advertising opponent; and Representative Mel Watt, who
is on the Judiciary Committee, has been pushed in the 12th to
Etheridge's west. Perhaps the Republicans best chance at a pickup
is in the textile-oriented 8th, from which 12-termer Bill Hefner is
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   _Ohio will also provide early clues. In the governor's race,
former Democratic Attorney General Lee Fisher has trailed Bob Taft
all fall, but he has hung around. The result and the margin will
hint at Democratic turnout because this race has seen a major
investment of labor union resources on Fisher's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Two House races here are also critical. In the 1st District
around Cincinnati, a Gingrich Revolutionary, Representative Steve
Chabot, has had to work to keep a seat that has a large percentage
of potential black voters. And in the 6th to the southeast,
Democratic Representative Ted Strickland is having another close
race, this time with Lieutenant Governor Nancy Hollister.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; AFTER 8 O'CLOCK &QC; 
 &LR;  This is when the deluge starts. On TV, the key Senate and
governor races are easy to follow, but the House races are tougher.
If you follow on cable, some order is possible by watching for
results in the following 12 races:
</P>
<P>
   _Nonstunners. As with Representatives Northrup and Carson above,
look for the numbers on two Democrats: Frank Pallone Jr. in New
Jersey's 6th District and Jerry Costello in Illinois' rural 12th;
and two Republicans: freshman Heather Wilson in New Mexico's 1st
and Dick Baker in Louisiana's Baton Rouge-based 6th.
</P>
<P>
   _Weak Incumbents. Two embattled Democrats' fates will be
revealing: Jay Johnson out of Wisconsin's 8th District and Lane
Evans downstate in Illinois' 17th District. The same goes for two
Republicans: Bill Redmond in New Mexico's 3d and Vince Snowbarger
in Kansas's 3d District.
</P>
<P>
   _Open Seats. These provide the best chances for party shifts,
and here are four critical ones: the fights for Colorado's 2d
District, from which Democrat David Scaggs is retiring; eastern
Pennsylvania's 15th, which is losing a rare pro-impeachment
Democrat, Paul McHale; Idaho's 2d District, which Republican Mike
Crapo is leaving for the Senate; and Mississippi's 4th, where GOP
Representative Mike Parker is moving on for a possible run for
governor next year.
</P>
<P>
   _Impeachment. Those much-publicized anti-Clinton TV ads were
spread around more than two dozen House districts in the final
days. If I had to pick one place to gauge their impact early, it
would be the 5th District in up-country South Carolina, represented
by a veteran Democrat, John Spratt.
</P>
<P>
   In all, there are 24 House races referred to here. If you hit
the hay before midnight and the GOP hasn't won 15 of them, it's in
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   So enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
