<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL PUTS BOXER, FONG IN A DEAD HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a volatile race with momentum see-sawing
between the candidates, incumbent Sen. Barbara Boxer and her
Republican challenger, state Treasurer Matt Fong, appear to be in a
statistical dead heat heading into Tuesday's election.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer is favored over Fong by 45 percent to 43 percent _ a
statistically insignificant edge given the poll's margin of error
of plus or minus 3.5 percentage points, according to a poll
commissioned by the San Francisco Examiner and KTVU-TV.
</P>
<P>
   The tight race reflected by the poll contrasts with a survey
released last week that showed Boxer had surged to a 9-percentage
point lead based primarily on a barrage of negative television
advertising against her opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner/KTVU poll raised new caution flags for Boxer,
including the voters' continued negative impression of her. Voters
in the Central Valley, a key swing area in statewide elections,
support Fong by 11 percentage points over the Democratic incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   The changing numbers point to a campaign to be decided on which
candidate can best get their voters to the polls, said Del Ali, of
Mason-Dixon Political/Media Research in Columbia, Md., which
conducted the poll for the Examiner and KTVU.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing she (Boxer) has going for her is Gray Davis,'' Ali
said, referring to the Democratic gubernatorial nominee who leads
in recent surveys. ``It could be that he wins by such a wide
margin, and enough Democrats come out to the polls that they carry
her over the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing is, there could be ticket-splitting, with
Davis voters going over to Fong.''
</P>
<P>
   The statewide telephone survey of 809 likely voters was
conducted Oct. 26-28. All those surveyed were registered voters who
said they regularly vote in elections. The poll showed 12 percent
still undecided about the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also revealed several obstacles for Fong:
</P>
<P>
   _ Women, who have fueled Democratic victories in statewide
elections, overwhelmingly support Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Independents, the fastest growing group of voters, back Boxer
by 51 percent to 41 percent with 8 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   _ Boxer is a favorite among voters in the San Francisco area,
besting her opponent 57 percent to 36 percent. And, in a reversal
from an Examiner/KTVU poll two weeks ago, she is favored 44 percent
to 41 percent in the Los Angeles area, a traditional Democratic
stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   But she trails Fong in the Central Valley, in Northern
California and in the San Diego area.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer campaign manager Rose Kapolczynski said the campaign's
nightly internal polling showed the senator favored by 5 to 7
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   At a Friday fund-raiser in San Francisco with first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton, Boxer said she always had close races and expected
this one to be no different. She said four out of the past five
California senate races were won by a candidate, including herself,
who got less than 50 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a two- to five-point race, I've said that all
along,'' Boxer said. ``It all depends on who gets out to vote. That
is really the big issue. Our own internal polls show us winning in
every single group, including men. So we're happy about that. But I
still believe these races are always tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer has outspent her opponent 2-1 on commercials in the past
month. The commercials, which attack Fong on issues like gun
control, abortion, the environment and health care, are aimed at
undermining his image as a moderate.
</P>
<P>
   The Fong campaign is using advertising to hammer Boxer's
positions on taxes and crime.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has replaced a campaign commercial featuring Fong's
mother, March Fong Eu, the former secretary of state, with one
using newspaper clips accusing Boxer of being a ``liberal and
ineffective'' senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've spent a great deal of time since the beginning of the
campaign listing off his (Fong's) positions on issues like
education, crime, the environment,'' Fong spokesman Steve Schmidt
said. ``That part of the campaign has ended. We will now remind
voters why they so dislike Barbara Boxer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
