<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9145 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-CIA-BOS &LR;      11-02 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS RAISED ABOUT THE CIA'S ROLE IN THE MIDEAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The new Israeli-Palestinian peace accord avoids any
mention of one major development: an increase in the power _ and
the profile _ of the CIA.
</P>
<P>
   CIA officials say the agency will do nothing more than monitor
the peace process, as it has done several times in the Mideast. But
former officials and analysts say the agency has never assumed such
a public assignment in so turbulent a region. Even some of those
who support the CIA's offer to help the peace process concede that
the secretive agency is not prepared for the scrutiny and
complaints it will receive.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters and critics alike warn that officers will have
trouble balancing two conflicting roles: serving as mediators while
remaining Washington's objective eyes and ears in the region.
</P>
<P>
   R. James Woolsey, a former director of central intelligence,
backs the agency's new, high-profile venture, provided CIA officers
have strict limits on their monitoring roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they report back to the US government, there's no
problem,'' Woolsey said. ``What gets dicey is if they have to
assess what the Palestinians are doing and then report directly to
Israel officials. That gets them betwixt and between.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the plan for CIA involvement has drawn the
support of several left-leaning groups such as Americans for Peace
Now while drawing criticism from the right.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama Republican Richard C. Shelby, who heads the Senate
Intelligence Committee, says the CIA is in danger of overstepping
its authority. Appearing on the Fox television network Oct. 25 he
said, ``What is the role of the CIA? Is it to be an arbitrator? Is
it to be bodyguards? I think not.''
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence specialists say the CIA's involvement in the region
is nothing new. They say the CIA has long maintained contacts with
Israeli security agencies as well as Yasser Arafat and his inner
circle, even when the Palestinians were fighting Israel. In the
aftermath of the 1973 Yom Kippur war, US intelligence agencies kept
track of Israeli troop withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-page agreement signed on Oct. 23 speaks vaguely of the
American government's attendance at biweekly meetings to ``review
the steps being taken to eliminate terrorist cells and the support
structure that plans, finances, supplies and abets terror.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be done by a ``US-Palestinian committee.'' In
addition, a ``high ranking US-Palestinian-Israeli committee'' will
meet at least twice a week ``to assess current threats'' and
coordinate anti-terrorism strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: CIA officials will be actively involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CIA is the right choice and they have a good working
relationship with both Israelis and Palestinians,'' said Richard
Shultz, an international security expert at the Fletcher School of
Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University.
</P>
<P>
   But Shultz said the agency runs a risk whenever it crosses over
from covert to overt policy-making as it monitors the peace
process. ``What if the CIA issues a status report saying things are
not going well? Does the administration lean on the CIA to say,
`What can you say that's positive?'''
</P>
<P>
   That's not merely a hypothetical issue. Historians say that
during the 1980s, President Reagan's intelligence director, William
Casey, became convinced that Mexico was close to having a
revolution. Casey ordered a National Intelligence Estimate _ a
weighty report that offers the best intelligence from the Central
Intelligence Agency, Defense Intelligence Agency, and other spy
services. When they concluded that Mexico would not have
revolution, Casey ignored the expertise and ordered that the final
report to be more pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Woolsey, the former CIA director, said the CIA can avoid such
problems by reporting impartially to Washington, even when the news
is bad. ``If some deputy assistant secretary says, `You're too
negative, can't you take the adjectives out?' they can tell 'em to
go peddle their papers,'' Woolsey said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, most members of Congress have been cautious about
speaking out against the CIA's commitment in the region. Senator
John F. Kerry, the Massachusetts Democrat who sits on the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, said it is difficult to tell whether
the agency is taking on a new task or simply getting more publicity
than usual. Either way, Kerry said, ``I am prepared to see the CIA
play this role because our interest in furthering the cause of
peace in the Middle East is overriding.''
</P>
<P>
   But others warn that the CIA is entering a foreign policy
minefield. Joe Stork, who directs Mideast programs for Human Rights
Watch, the nonprofit group, found it ironic that the peace accord
became public just as news reports emerged about the agency's close
relationship with an oppressive military government in Honduras in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the CIA's record of complicity with abusive governments
and security forces elsewhere in the world, we're concerned about
the role they're playing in this peace agreement,'' Stork said.
``Maybe it's a reformed CIA, but it begs questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Stork sees other potential problems in the document signed at
the White House. At one point, it exhorts the Palestinians to take
``all measures necessary'' to prevent terrorism. Later, the
document says human rights should be honored ``without derogating
from the above'' promise to quash terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be read to say, `Security first, human rights
second,''' Stork said. Yet at Americans for Peace Now, spokesman
Lewis Roth said, ``We're very supportive of the strong American
role in the peace process, and certainly the CIA as an agency
representing the United States in the region seems to have
developed enough trust from the Israelis and the Palestinians so
that it can play a bridging role.''
</P>
<P>
   A former member of the Palestinian delegation to the early peace
talks says the CIA's involvement could spell political problems for
the Palestinians. ``It's not likely to be something that's going to
endear Yasser Arafat to his critics _ this will be seen as the
Palestinian Authority operating at the behest of the US agency
that's close to Israel,'' Khalidi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
