<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE KEEPS ITS UNIQUE WARES OPEN TO ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ From its early days as an outpost, when the educator
Asa Mercer recruited East Coast women to come West to marry its
lovelorn lumberjacks and thus keep them at their saws, Seattle has
boasted an admirable authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Unpretentious and honest, it's a city that delights in its
location in one of the country's most stunning areas, a city
confident enough in itself that it unconsciously starts trends
rather than unwittingly following them.
</P>
<P>
   One of its best traditions is Pike Place Market, the farmers'
and artisans' bazaar that thrives in a narrow perch between I-5 to
the west and the city's steep eastward rise. The market is a mecca
where tourists and locals, young and old, indigent and well-heeled,
rub shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Public markets, of course, are famous as great people mixers.
It's no mistake that when George Bernard Shaw's Professor Henry
Higgins goes afoot to study his city's various dialects, the venue
he chooses is London's Covent Garden, then a busy
fruit-and-vegetable market.
</P>
<P>
   But Pike Place, now in its 91st year, does more than just
provide a common meeting place. It also grounds the city in its
unique identity.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Quincy Market in Boston, anchored by the same assemblage
of upscale retailers and souvenir shops that one might find in
Baltimore or Houston, San Francisco or Chicago, Pike Place market
brings together a distinctive collection of local farmers,
artisans, and craftsfolk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings a little soul to the city,'' said Russell Hartwig,
who was tending a jewelry stall there on a recent Sunday morning.
``Things are made here, more or less by the person you are buying
from. It isn't the same mass-produced stuff shipped in overseas
from ill-paid slaves. There is individuality, creativity, to what
you see.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity for small artists and entrepreneurs to display
and sell in a low-cost stall or booth lets a thousand creative
personalities bloom, said Beverly Plansky, who sells
custom-designed silver jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make a living as an artist selling your wares without
having to deal with the corporate world,'' she said. That, she
says, allows artists to support themselves at prices the public can
afford.
</P>
<P>
   As a spinoff, Plansky said, the market crowds support nearby
restaurants, which number in the dozens.
</P>
<P>
   Hartwig himself is a good example of the possibilities Pike
Place Market allows. A cook at a fraternity house during the
college year, he spends the summer selling the hand-blown glass
jewelry his longtime girlfriend makes.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunities for low-cost craft capitalism lead to an
astounding array of things for sale. In a walk of several blocks,
the market offers local watercolors, etchings, and photographs,
hand-crafted jewelry, leather work, native art, carved goods,
homemade toys, pottery, and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   To say nothing of the cornucopia of local produce. Hungry? How
about some succulent peaches at $1 a pound? A mouth-watering
cluster of grapes? Looking for salad stuff? Try the green peppers,
or the beefsteak tomatoes. This is prime produce, fresh from the
farm.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the several markets where fishmongers peddle
Pacific seafood, the deli full of kosher delights, the stalls with
jams and jellies, baked goods, and flavored honeys. All against the
backdrop of flower stalls that paint the crowded market in the
colors of the Northwest in bloom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the best way to gain a perspective on what Pike
Place Market does for Seattle is a Sunday morning walk from the
Pioneer Square area to Pike Place. Pioneer Square is perhaps the
more famous Seattle locale, its tower a landmark. By day it boasts
a wide variety of galleries, shops, and restaurants, as well as the
Elliott Bay Book Co., one of the nation's finest bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Even a fine summer Sunday morning, however, finds its streets
more or less deserted, as they will be until commercial doors start
to open later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the field to the large population of street folk and
wanderers for whom Seattle serves as home base. At such a time,
it's easy to see how the Seattle-coined Skid Road, for the street
down which felled logs were skidded to the bay, morphed from
logging lexicon to take on down-and-out connotations. Even in the
bright of day, the vagrants sprawled in doorways and sidewalks,
begging or raising a morning bottle, give the area a gothic feel.
</P>
<P>
   But a mile away, Pike Place Market has already drawn a crowd of
hundreds into the city. To be sure, the street people have a place
here, too. But they don't predominate in quite the same way. Even
tiny Victor Steinbrueck Park, a bay overlook a block north of the
market where drifters, alcoholics, and addicts abound, is made safe
by the crowds drawn to Pike Place.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, is part of the magic of the marketplace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
