<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-ADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS UNLEASHES $25 MILLION AD CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bloodhound didn't pass muster with focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Sherpa? As an advertising pitchman, the Sherpa didn't have
enough staying power to suit Lycos Inc., the Internet search
service.
</P>
<P>
   So a $25 million ad campaign that has just hit the airwaves
introduces a new company pitchman: a black Labrador retriever named
Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   With the dog cast as ``your personal Internet guide,'' TV ads
with a ``Go get it'' tagline aim to convince viewers that the
Waltham, Mass. company's search services can retrieve data from the
Internet as quickly and easily as a Lab can fetch a stick.
</P>
<P>
   In one spot, the dog is a shown pictures of a frogman's flippers
and an antique yellow sports car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lycos, go get it!'' a voice-over says, and in a flash the dog
returns with the requested article. ``Unleash the new Lycos, and
the Internet is at your command,'' the voice-over notes.
</P>
<P>
   In a final scene, the dog is shown a photo of a model in a
fashion magazine. Lycos dashes off, and the next thing that viewers
hear is the sultry voice of an unseen woman, saying, ``Hi, I'm
Claudia.''
</P>
<P>
   Created by New York ad agency Bozell Worldwide, the ads are the
latest salvo in a fierce battle that has such Lycos rivals as Snap,
Yahoo, Excite, and Infoseek all trying to convince personal
computer users that their portals and search engines are the ideal
gateway to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A lot is riding on consumers' choices. Each Internet entry point
is packed with banner advertising. The more consumers who pass
through one of these gateways, or portals, the more the company can
charge advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   In looking to set itself apart, Lycos has experimented with
several metaphors in its marketing and advertising, said Jan Robert
Horsfall, the company's vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   According to Horsfall, the name Lycos derives from a Latin word
for a special kind of spider. Most spiders use their webs to trap
prey, but a Lycos spider leaves its web to hunt.
</P>
<P>
   But spiders don't make for swell advertising images. So an
earlier ad campaign starred a Sherpa mountain guide.
</P>
<P>
   Sherpas evoke dangerous situations, and while that was
appropriate at a time when many PC users were fearful of getting
lost on the World Wide Web, most no longer regard the Internet as
treacherous terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what they demand now from a search service is speed,
convenience, and friendliness _ not exactly traits one immediately
associates with mountain guides, Horsfall said.
</P>
<P>
   So Lycos auditioned a bloodhound to replace the Sherpa, but
focus-group testing revealed that speed and friendliness were not
the bloodhound's forte. Lycos opted for a Lab to plug its newly
streamlined search service.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Labrador retriever is a great symbol of approachability and
friendliness,'' said Horsfall, adding: ``This is one dog you want
to walk up to and pet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
