<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BELOVED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NARRATIVE'S PULL: REREADING `BELOVED' ON FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its murderous reds and bleak Midwestern snows, its manifest
acceptance of ghostly witnesses, Jonathan Demme's ``Beloved''
manages to capture the central and specific tragedy of Toni
Morrison's mythic novel. What it doesn't do, and probably should
not, is evoke the sweeping, multilayered lyricism of a great work
of fiction. The passion and earnest fidelity that Oprah Winfrey
(who both produced and stars in the movie) and director Demme
brought to this project have their imprint all over the film, from
the starkly emotional performances of Winfrey and Thandie Newton to
the literal translation of text-to-script. And certainly much of
the power of the movie owes its debt to that intensity of intent.
But in daring to comprehend the legacy of grief and violence left
by American slavery, Morrison's ``Beloved'' triumphs over those
agonies of history with the rhapsodic pull of narrative. Dense with
allusion and shifting time and narrators, Morrison's ``Beloved'' is
wed to a sonorous, Faulknerian prose, and it suggests that the pure
act of telling a story can supersede its evil: If a dead child can
reappear to love a mother out of her mind, so, too, can a cri de
coeur from an old woman take on the magical force of a eulogy
recited in starlight. No visual medium can fully encompass that,
any more than a poem can deliver the colors of the canvas it seeks
to describe.
</P>
<P>
   The story line of both novel and film may be familiar ground by
now. Sethe, a former slave, lives with her daughter Denver in a
house in Ohio; the sorrow of the past has also taken up residence,
in the form of a ghost girl named Beloved. The year is 1873; 18
years before, Sethe _ pregnant with her fourth child _ escaped from
Sweet Home, the Kentucky plantation where she was born. Her
children had been sent ahead to her mother-in-law, Baby Suggs, a
freed slave living in Ohio. With the aid of a white girl who helped
her give birth in a boat near the Ohio River, Sethe made her way to
blessed freedom _ blessed at least for 28 days, until terror, not
content with owning yesterday, showed its face again and took the
future as well.
</P>
<P>
   Now an old friend from Sweet Home has ventured to knock on the
door of 124 Bluestone Road, the house near Cincinnati where Sethe
and Denver try to endure. Beat back by a pulsing scarlet light that
awaits him over the threshold (a garishly creepy Halloween effect
in the movie), Paul D at first recoils, until Sethe reassures him:
``Not evil, just sad.'' Full of his own silent memories of the path
he walked out of slavery, Paul D comes carrying a modicum of hope;
what he hadn't bargained on was the broken-child spirit whose
misery rules 124 with spectral tyranny. Throwing furniture along
with her infantile rages, the girl finally appears in the flesh _ a
beautiful young woman who walks out of the water to Sethe's door,
making guttural noises and, when asked her name, spelling out the
word on a nearby tombstone: B-e-l-o-v-e-d. And there's way too much
angry yearning behind that beauty to suggest that this will be a
wholly sweet reunion.
</P>
<P>
   By taking the dramatic risk of making Beloved the girl a
blatantly otherworldly character, Demme's ``Beloved'' handles well
the insistent fact of her, and attempts to suggest the mythic
undertow of the novel: that memory is as alive as you or me; that
reality as we know it is merely the summation of truth we cannot
see; that, in Denver's words, ``death is a skipped meal'' compared
to some kinds of loss. For ``Beloved'' is also a story about the
cost of attachment _ the price you pay for loving thick, whether
it's Sethe's maternal devotion, Denver's need for her sister, or
Paul D's red, red heart, hidden within the sheath of memory. Beyond
the tragic particulars of Sethe's story and the demonic history it
represents is a quieter, more ineffable notion _ that Beloved's
reappearance, to each of these people, only serves to remind them
of what they no longer possess.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took my milk.'' Those four monosyllables come hurled out
of Sethe's history like stones off a cliff, and they testify to the
unthinkable iniquities she has already suffered. Part of Sethe's
tale of ``rememory,'' the words form one of several refrains in the
novel of such resonant restraint that they begin to seem like a
poetry of oppression: the choruses of black men and women and
children strangled by slavery. (``Those white things have taken all
I had or dreamed,'' said Baby Suggs before she died.) Some of this
litany appears in Baby Suggs's holy soliloquies in the forest,
where she preaches to a woodland congregation. ``Cry,'' she tells
them, ``for the living and the dead. Just cry.''
</P>
<P>
   As mesmerizing as this exhortation is in the hands of Beah
Richards, who plays Baby Suggs in the film, it's only the first
half of her speech in the novel, which continues on to a fierce,
heartbroken crescendo. ``And O my people, out yonder, hear me, they
do not love your neck unnoosed and straight. So love your neck; put
a hand on it, grace it, stroke it and hold it up.'' Filled with the
unconquerable weapon of language, Morrison's ``Beloved'' never
pulls its punches on the evils of slavery. And though the film may
seem unstoppably brutal, it actually leaves out (or abbreviates)
some of the worst moments in the novel _ including the story behind
that gravestone, which taught Beloved her name and for which Sethe
paid with blood and soul.
</P>
<P>
   More important, much of the background of Sethe's loved ones has
disappeared: Denver's early deafness, supplanted by a phobic
refusal to leave the house; the life at Sweet Home Sethe shared
with Paul D and her husband, Halle; Paul D's subsequent horrors on
a Georgia prison farm; Baby Suggs's giving up on grace toward the
end of her life. These offstage stories may not seem essential to
Sethe's central agony, but they are. They enhance the pain of it,
explain the sickening inhumanities that led her to her own act of
outrage, and together paint an even bleaker picture than the film
allows. Such omissions are rarely surprising in the translation of
novels into film, where time and bearable endings reign supreme. To
his credit, Demme has transformed much of Morrison's incantatory
narrative into dialogue, a risk that preserves a certain chronology
of fact.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said shortly after the publication of ``Beloved,'' in
1987, that the original idea for her novel came from a news story
she'd discovered about a tragedy similar to ``Sethe's rough
choice,'' as Baby Suggs calls it. Certainly what Demme has brought
through loud and clear is Sethe's slow descent into madness: numbed
by a sorrow too great to bear, then seduced and reawakened by this
wild child who emerges from her amniotic grave, heading for love
and resolution. This fixed nexus of ``Beloved'' probably begged to
be filmed, with its unequivocal dramatic possibilities and
day-by-day battle with the past. Harder to elucidate are the more
far-flung nuances of the novel: the intangible burdens of slavery,
from the survivor's guilt of future generations to the cauterized
hopes of an entire community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beloved'' the novel is wider and sadder in all directions than
any screen adaptation could ever be, though that inevitability of
literature shouldn't have stopped it from being made. Mass
culture's formulas alone will guarantee legions of moviegoers who
might never have gone near Morrison's demanding narrative. And the
daring performance of Newton's Beloved suggests the radical
sensuality of the novel, as well as the child's own mutable
necessity to each of these characters: their eventual belief that,
in Morrison's words, ``other than what they themselves were
thinking, she hadn't said anything at all.'' Like its girl-spirit's
watery birthplace, the mythic voices of ``Beloved'' _ its wrestling
with evil, its resplendent chords of memory _ are far deeper than
anything you can see, either in a darkened theater or the light of
everyday life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
