<HEADLINE>
IRISH-AMERICAN STORIES AND STEREOTYPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN DEZELL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Actor and director Edward Burns has said he made his 1994 film
``The Brothers McMullen'' because he didn't see any movies about
Irish Catholics when he was growing up.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Americans born during or after the Vietnam War, Burns,
30, is too young to have watched Jimmy Cagney, Spencer Tracy, or
Bing Crosby movies, even on late-night TV.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish-American ethnic story was presumed to have ended when
John F. Kennedy was elected president. The Irish had suburbanized.
Assimilated. They were indistinguishable from WASPS, save for their
Catholicism and peculiar fondness for green beer and shamrocks
around St. Patrick's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   Now the American Irish are back. Big time. With their Hibernian
cousins across the Atlantic on the up and up, they've become a
pop-culture commodity. Witness the current television season, with
three TV shows about Irish-American families and a third _
``Turks,'' set in Chicago _ slated for a midseason premiere.
</P>
<P>
   The shows are about as true-to-life as Father O'Malley was in
1944. They also date to that previous era _ or notions of the era.
Each one is a jaw-dropping parade of anachronisms and stereotypes.
Fox's ``Costello,'' set in a South Boston bar (where else?), was
canceled after four episodes. CBS's ``To Have and Hold,'' about the
newlywed McGrails of Dorchester, draws its dramatic tension from
his family: three cops and a fireman, all of whom drink too much
(of course), and a mother with a brogue who breaks plates over a
son's head, then makes the sign of the cross.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ``Trinity,'' about a family in New York's Hell's Kitchen,
presents a broader range of Irish caricature. The siblings in this
show are a priest, a policeman, a labor-union representative, an
alcoholic, and a successful sister whose emotional life is a mess.
As Mike Flaherty wrote in Entertainment Weekly, ``Allusion is also
made to a brother who overdosed at the age of 15 (what was he, a
leprechaun?).''
</P>
<P>
   No one seems to have noticed in Hollywood, but the American
Irish are overwhelmingly middle- and upper-middle-class, and still
Irish, as Burns showed in ``The Brothers McMullen,'' which takes
place largely on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church is at the center of far fewer lives. But
humor, self-deprecation, a predilection for the tragic, and
emotional reticence remain fundamental. Burns's movie opens in a
graveyard, with a recently widowed mother breaking a silence she's
kept for 30 years. The McMullen brothers show their affection by
insulting one another.
</P>
<P>
   The American Irish have long suffered by comparison to the
legendary tale tellers of their ancestral land. (And any involved
in this season's Irish TV shows deserve to suffer.) It would be
premature to say there's a renaissance in Irish-American writing in
the making. But Burns is one of a handful of writers who've
recently started retelling Irish-American tales.
</P>
<P>
   James Carroll won a National Book Award for his memoir ``An
American Requiem.'' Alice McDermott's ``Charming Billy,'' set among
the Irish milieu that was the backdrop of her well-regarded ``At
Weddings and Wakes,'' was nominated for this year's award. Comedian
Colin Quinn, of ``Saturday Night Live,'' recently staged a one-man
autobiographical drama, ``An Irish Wake,'' and is writing a memoir.
And Frank McCourt was born in New York, the setting of much of
``'Tis,'' the sequel to ``Angela's Ashes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
