<SLUG> BC-IRISH-MCDONAGH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYWRIGHT MCDONAGH CROSSES THE BORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN DEZELL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arguably the hottest cultural commodity to come out of Ireland
in the past year are the plays of 28-year-old Anglo-Irish Martin
McDonagh. Four of them ran simultaneously in London's West End
during the summer of 1997. Last winter in New York, the Joseph Papp
Public Theatre staged ``The Cripple of Inishmaan,'' and the
Atlantic Theatre Company brought over the Druid Theatre production
of ``Beauty Queen of Leenane,'' which transferred to Broadway,
where it won four Tony awards.
</P>
<P>
   Dark, disturbing, and hilariously funny, McDonagh's plays are
postmodern hybrids of Irish theatrical tradition and American pop
culture, and hijinks handling of the cliches of both. Sitting in
farmhouse kitchens that could be sets in any Irish bog drama,
characters in McDonagh's Leenane Trilogy fulminate about lumps in
porridge and about the details of American sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   Pictureseque villages are lawless places, where Americans who
come looking for the nearby settings they saw in John Ford's movie
``The Quiet Man'' can get lost for years. Family ties strangle. The
church is a fleeting, pathetic presence in the persona of an
alcoholic, depressed, but well-intentioned priest in ``The Lonesome
West.''
</P>
<P>
   Father Walsh (or is it Welsh? he's so inconsequential no one in
the play can remember) is treated with some sympathy, perhaps
because he is in such a state of despair. ``Ah, there be a lot
worse priests than you, Father, I'm sure,'' another character tries
to reassure him. ``You're a terror for the drink and you have
doubts about Catholicism. Apart from that, you're a fine priest.
Number one, you don't go abusing poor gasurs, so, sure, doesn't
that give you a head start over half the priests in Ireland?''
</P>
<P>
   McDonagh turns the Irish traditions of family, faith, and
fatherland upside down and inside out. But he treats them more
adroitly than any number of older, more earnestly iconoclastic
writers. Dealing deftly with cultural bogeymen appears to be a
point of pride with young Irish writers. ``There is nothing more
tedious than Irish writers banging on about the oppression of
Catholicism,'' novelist Patrich McCabe said in an interview last
year. McDonagh, McCabe, and many of their contemporaries view the
world through prisms that are neither ground with tedious identity
politics nor clouded with the specter of political correctness.
Which may explain their appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``McDonagh is the first playwright of the 21st century,'' said
American Repertory Theatre director and drama critic Robert
Brustein. ``He's the best Irish playwright since Synge; he may be
better than Synge. He has the Irish control of language and poetry,
but you expect that. He is very funny and dark. Yet he has a way of
evoking both human failure and virtue that is powerful and
universal. No one writing today can touch him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
