</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-ARTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVERDANCE OVERSHADOWS IRISH EXPLOSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN DEZELL 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Riverdance,'' the exuberant, seemingly ubiquitous Irish dance
extravaganza, bowed out of the Wang Theatre this weekend, after
selling out the cavernous performance hall during most of its third
Boston run in less than two years. It has played to nearly 5
million people on three continents since its 1994 debut as an
extended commercial in a Eurovision song contest _ notwithstanding
competition from Michael Flatley's frantic-tapping, air-boxing,
Eire-satz spinoff, `Lord of the Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Razzle-dazzle stage shows with Irish roots have become a
worldwide symbol of Celtic chic in the late '90s: a time when
everything green-tinged has turned red hot. Frank McCourt's
``Angela's Ashes'' recently entered its third year on the New York
Times bestseller list, where it has overlapped at various points
with Thomas Cahill's ``How the Irish Saved Civilization,'' Nuala
O'Faolain's ``Are You Somebody: The Accidental Memoir of a Dublin
Woman,'' and ``A Monk Swimming,'' by Malachy McCourt, Frank's
brother.
</P>
<P>
   The Druid Theatre's production of Martin McDonagh's mordantly
funny ``Beauty Queen of Leenane,'' which won four Tony Awards this
year, is selling out on Broadway. From U2 and the Cranberries
through Black 47 and Cherish the Ladies, a wide variety of Irish
music has been simultaneously popular. Irish authors are pulling
down record advances, cashing in on the international success of
novelists like Roddy Doyle (``Paddy Clark Ha Ha Ha,'' ``The
Commitments'') and Patrick McCabe (``The Butcher Boy''). Doyle and
McCabe have written screenplays based on their books for an Irish
film industry that is flourishing, thanks to the ascendance of Jim
Sheridan (``My Left Foot,'' ``In the Name of the Father'') and Neil
Jordan (``The Crying Game,'' ``Michael Collins,'' ``The Butcher
Boy'').
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Riverdance,'' with its upbeat muddle of folk art,
multi-culti fuzziness, and feel-good American showbiz, is by no
means emblematic of the artistic efforts coming out of Ireland and
Irish America right now, many of which are dark, edgy, and keenly
rendered. Contemporary Irish literature, film, and theater are
brimming with bleak, blackly humorous explorations of centers that
cannot hold: the impoverished family in ``Angela's Ashes''; the
brutally indifferent church and village society of ``The Butcher
Boy''; McDonagh's post-romantic west of Ireland, where simple
country folk scorn themselves and their surroundings, and act on
murderous impulses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a counter-melody to the Celtic Tiger's'' success in the
international economy, said Declan Kiberd, the literature professor
at University College Dublin who wrote ``Inventing Ireland.'' The
popular explosion of brooding social portraiture and tragi-comedy
is taking place in the midst of unprecedented peace, secularism,
and prosperity in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Irish live with paradox,'' Kiberd pointed out. ``There is
an Irish condition, having to do with colonial history, in which
there are two versions of reality: official and unofficial. People
don't see pagan and Christian as opposed, or past and future. So
while it was once a cliche that the Irish were obsessed with the
past, now they are interested in having power over the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in any decade in Ireland you get an incredibly high number
of quality writers and novelists and playwrights,'' he added. ``The
question is, why is there so much current interest in the US and
Britain?''
</P>
<P>
   The melodies and counter-melodies of Irish arts, literature, and
entertainment are playing extraordinarily well in the United
States, to the surprise of some observers. ``When I was growing up
in the Bronx, the kids who took step-dancing classes were the ones
who couldn't run fast enough,'' said Peter Quinn, a novelist and
speechwriter who has written extensively about Ireland and Irish
America. These days, there are waiting lists for Irish dance
classes, and Americans flock to traditional Irish music festivals.
Quinn attributes the surge of interest to the receding influence of
the Catholic Church. Through the mid-1960s, ``our whole emotional
life was involved with the church,'' he said. ``There was
tremendous psychic energy drawn into the church. And now a lot of
creativity, a lot of the best minds, are going into secular
pursuits.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Quinn said, ``Irish culture has always been kind of
marginal and out of the mainstream, and that appeals to a lot of
people now. We're living in the decline of the culture of the
superego, of the great European cultures. Irish culture is an id
culture. It's passionate, and dark, it is an exploration of human
failure. Survival. And now people are exploring that marginal
experience'' in music, movies, books, and plays.
</P>
<P>
   Some have found the explorations poignant and revealing. When
Boston's Sugan Theatre staged Tom Murphy's harrowing play
``Famine,'' it quickly became clear to Sugan artistic director
Carmel O'Reilly that ``this was a story that had not been told.''
The company mounted the production in 1995, two years before
commemorations marking the 150th anniversary of the worst year of
the Irish Famine raised awareness of the catastrophe that drove
more than 1 million people out of Ireland to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``People came in droves'' to the Sugan show, said O'Reilly.
``They came up from Rhode Island, from as far away as New Jersey.
The response was tremendous; we got cards and letters from Irish
Americans who didn't really know what they'd come out of, thanking
us. Knowing something about what had happened was a spiritual
experience for some people. A way of reconnecting with this
immigrant experience that left a lot of people rootless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got negative reactions, too,'' O'Reilly continued. ``There
were people who were bitterly angry that we had shown the Irish
that way _ poor and dirty and drunken, reduced to stealing turf.
There is a shame about that, a feeling that Irish Americans spent
all these years building them-selves up, and we shouldn't be
telling people about that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The declasse part of the Irish experience was never spoken of
until recently,'' said the director Jim Sheridan, who ran the Irish
Arts Center in New York in the 1980s before he began making hit
movies with Daniel Day-Lewis. ``The origin of `Angela's Ashes' was
a play that Frank and Malachy McCourt did, `A Couple of
Blackguards.' It ran for years, and no one paid attention. That
wasn't a legitimate field. Until the influx of the immigrants in
the 1980s, Irish-American audiences were very conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now there's a distance. There's been a shift of wealth,
and Irish culture is for sale. There hasn't been much to buy
besides Waterford in the Aer Lingus catalog. Now you can go to
`Riverdance.' You can look at `Angela's Ashes' or `My Left Foot.'
And you can say `Look at how far we've come.'''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Ireland that today's senaithe, or storytellers, are
revealing to the world ``is history,'' noted Kiberd. McCourt's
1940s Limerick and the Cold War backdrop of ``The Butcher Boy'' are
long gone. The implacable politics of ``In the Name of the Father''
at this point appear to be contained. Even some of Doyle's
present-day tales are dated: The title characters of ``The
Commitments'' formed their anachronistic soul band in a late-'80s
Dublin overrun with drug use and unemployment. Dublin today is a
cosmopolitan capital of the fastest-growing economy in the European
Union, bustling with trilling cell phones, traffic noise, tourists,
and men and women in designer suits closing deals over large cups
of cappuccino.
</P>
<P>
   Remote, religious Ireland _ like the mythical land of mist,
musicmakers, and senaithe _ has all but disappeared. But it is the
remoteness, religion, and myth that have gone missing. The
musicmaking and the storytelling are thriving _ along with
moviemaking and the visual arts _ because Ireland, for all its
seismic social changes, remains a place where those things matter.
</P>
<P>
   Irish residents who earn their livings in the creative arts have
been exempt from paying income tax since 1969. The poet and Nobel
laureate Seamus Heaney is a celebrity in Dublin. The Irish press
covered multiple angles of the Druid Theatre's Broadway success
last spring, and fans at home were grumbling for weeks after the
Tonys that McDonagh, who lost out to ``Art'' in the best play
category, was robbed.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the world, it is its ``remarkable adaptability''
and ``open-endedness'' that have kept Irish culture vital and made
it ``universal,'' according to Adele Dalsimer, cofounder of Boston
College's Irish Studies program. Traditional Irish music, for
example, traveled to Appalachia, returned to Ireland in the form of
country-Western, mixed it up with rock 'n' roll, and has recently
grown the offshoot of Celtic rock. ``Riverdance'' would never have
existed were it not for the Broadway musical, and, as the Irish
journalist Fintan O'Toole has pointed out, Broadway wouldn't be
what it became without the original song-and-dance man, George M.
Cohan, whose father, a son of famine immigrants, was a famous
traditional Irish dancer.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish arts tide shows few signs of slowing. Critically
acclaimed in London and Dublin, Conor McPherson's ``The Weir'' is
reportedly on its way to Broadway early next year. McPherson is the
other hot 28-year-old Irish playwright (along with Martin McDonagh
_ see accompanying story), and wrote the screenplay for this year's
successful independent film ``I Went Down.'' ART is doing
McDonagh's ``The Cripple of Inishmaan,'' and the Huntington is
producing Sebastian Barry's ``The Steward of Christendom'' this
season. Meanwhile, the screen version of veteran playwright Brian
Friel's ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' is due out in November. Another
spate of Irish memoirs _ including one by Peter Sheridan, the
director's brother, and the sequel to ``Angela's Ashes'' _ is
expected out next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the economy, it feeds on itself,'' said Ciaran
O'Reilly, producing director of the Irish Repertory Theatre in
Manhattan. ``Maybe it's happening by virtue of great art and talent
that's suddenly being embraced. Maybe it's just coming into Irish
Americans' consciousness for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or maybe it's just hip.''
</P>
</TEXT>
