<SLUG> BC-ANIMAL-BALLOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVEN STATES TO VOTE ON ANIMAL ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Anticockfighting ballot questions in Arizona and Missouri are
among eight animal-related issues facing voters in seven states
Tuesday, continuing a trend of taking control of such decisions
away from elected lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Including the votes in Arizona and Missouri, six of the ballot
questions are supported by animal-rights activists:
</P>
<P>
   _In Alaska, voters will decide whether to ban the practice of
wolf snaring, used primarily for predator control and fur sales.
</P>
<P>
   _California voters will be asked whether to ban the sale of
horses for human consumption, and whether to outlaw the use of
certain traps and poisons.
</P>
<P>
   _Ohio voters will be asked whether to ban target shooting and
restore protections for mourning doves.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in two other states will face ballot questions supported
by pro-hunting groups:
</P>
<P>
   _In Minnesota, voters will be asked whether to approve a
constitutional amendment affirming that hunting and trapping are
valued elements of the state's heritage ``that shall be forever
preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   _Utah voters will decide whether to enact a constitutional
amendment requiring all animal-protection initiatives to be
approved by two-thirds of voters to take effect, rather than the
current majority.
</P>
<P>
   The use of ballot questions on animal-rights issues has gained
significant ground since 1990, when California voters outlawed
mountain lion hunting, said Wayne Pacelle, senior vice president of
the Humane Society of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, voters have approved 10 of the 12 animal-protection
questions put before them, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
