<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9169 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARIZ-COCKFIGHTING-BOS     11-02 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZ-COCKFIGHTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURE OF BLOOD SPORT AT STAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Two tough birds slash and peck in a feather-flying
brawl that ends with one triumphant and the other defeated, maybe
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   That's cockfighting, but it also happens to be a pretty fair
description of the battle going on between Belton Hodges and Ken
White over the future of the blood sport, and just maybe, the
future of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The two men are opposing leaders in a campaign to decide whether
to outlaw cockfighting in the state. Polls indicate that ballot
questions making cockfighting a felony will probably pass Tuesday
here and in Missouri, limiting the legal range of the sport to
Oklahoma, Louisiana, and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Though cockfighting is the immediate focus, the face-off between
Hodges and White is about more than that. It is a contest that
exposes fault lines in a longstanding conflict over whose Arizona
this is, with Hodges and White representing the competing forces _
natives versus transplants, rural dwellers versus urbanites _ that
are redefining this rapidly growing state.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges, 78, a Phoenix native from a long line of cockfighters,
says he is protecting the state's heritage, preserving a besieged
western culture built on individual freedoms and upholding a
common-sense view of the proper place of animals, fowl, and vermin:
well below humans on the evolutionary scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been invaded and become a heavily urbanized state, by
people raised in the major cities of the East,'' said Hodges,
former president of a national cockfighting group. ``They've
forgotten the fact that a large group of people lived here together
before they arrived. And we cherish our manners and our customs. If
they don't like fighting cocks, they can go play golf or whatever
it is they like to do.''
</P>
<P>
   White, 45, a Brooklyn native who arrived here three years ago
from San Francisco, says he is working to eliminate an ugly vestige
of the past, one that considers cruelty to animals to be
entertainment and desensitizes adults and children to acts of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think what the West was, in its entirety, is what
anybody needs the West to be today,'' said White, executive
director of the Arizona Humane Society. ``We don't need to settle
squabbles with a shootout, we don't need to force people to marry
at the point of a shotgun. The West has a heritage that is rich,
but there are some things we need to make sure never happen again,
and cockfighting is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The backdrop of the cockfighting conflict is the explosive
growth Arizona has experienced in recent years. Flooded by retirees
and warm-weather seekers, the state's population has nearly tripled
since 1970 to 4.6 million people. It is the second-fastest growing
state in the nation, after Nevada, and Phoenix has emerged as the
nation's sixth-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been real social upheaval. As a small community grows
into a larger city, the old-time residents clearly have significant
changes in their lives, and change can be wrenching,'' said Tom
Rex, research manager at the Center for Business Research at
Arizona State University. ``Cockfighting is a good example of what
this state used to be like, but isn't anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, cockfighting is a pretty straightforward
activity. Three men _ participants are nearly all male _ enter an
enclosed dirt ring, two with prized gamecocks in their arms and one
to serve as referee.
</P>
<P>
   The knee-high birds, their multicolored feathers glowing with a
lustrous sheen, are fitted with knifelike spikes, or gaffs,
sharpened at the tip. The gaffs are placed over bone spurs that
grow from roosters' ankles and are the birds' most potent weapon in
the wild. Cockfighters say the metal blades are necessary to
equalize fights between birds whose natural spurs grow to different
lengths; opponents say the purpose is to guarantee the bouts will
be bloody.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the fight, wagers are made and the handlers coo at
their birds, holding them close to their intended foe. At the
referee's signal, the handlers drop the birds and step back to
watch them fight, often until one is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Cockfighting is out of season right now, Hodges said, as the
birds go through a molting period. But underground videos of fights
show bloody contests in which gamecocks lunge at each other, wings
flapping, leaping over each other's backs, and making
lightning-quick cuts and gouges. Men in jeans and camouflage pants
urge the birds on, in one case rubbing a downed bird's face in the
dirt to encourage it to fight on; the bird was soon tossed in a
losers' barrel brimming with carcasses.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 45 cockfighting venues in Arizona, from
backyard pits ringed with chicken wire to perhaps a half-dozen
larger, barnlike structures, most on the California border.
Anywhere from 15,000 to 50,000 fights take place a year, depending
on which side is doing the estimating.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three attempts to outlaw cockfighting have failed in the
Arizona Legislature since the 1950s, killed by lawmakers who were
enthusiasts or at least sympathetic to the pleas of a small but
vocal pro-cockfighting lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Anticockfighting forces, under the umbrella of a Tucson group
called Citizens Against Cockfighting, came to understand that
legislatures change more slowly than the general population in a
place like this. This year's ballot question is the first time the
issue has been put directly to voters, and independent polls show
overwhelmingly support for making cockfighting a felony punishable
by up to two years in prison and a $150,000 fine; attending a
cockfight would be a misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Similar support is seen in Missouri, where cockfighting had been
outlawed for more than 100 years, until a 1985 state Supreme Court
decision struck down the law as unconstitutionally vague. Since
then, repeated attempts to outlaw the blood sport have failed in
the Missouri Legislature, said Barbara Gray, campaign manager of
Missourians Against Cockfighting.
</P>
<P>
   If the Arizona and Missouri cockfighting bans are approved, ``we
will immediately focus our attention on a ballot initiative in
Oklahoma ... to eliminate this gruesome and nasty blood sport
nationwide,'' said Wayne Pacelle, senior vice president of the
Humane Society of the United States. New Mexico and Louisiana do
not allow ballot initiatives, he said, so efforts in those states
will continue in legislative chambers.
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, Hodges is still raising fighting birds behind
his tidy red-brick ranch house in south Phoenix, a home brimming
with cockfighting paraphernalia and memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   A retired railroad engineer with a silver pompadour and a pinch
of Skoal tobacco in his mouth, Hodges talks about his birds with a
mix of admiration and disdain. He revels in what he considers their
take-no-prisoners courage against overwhelming odds, then derides
them as ``just chickens, not dogs or cats.'' He says he does not
name them _ though there is one retired fighter called ``Pretty
Boy'' _ and says their only purpose in life is to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges is well aware of the polls showing Arizona residents are
against cockfighting, and he is perplexed. ``Watching what nature
intended, watching two birds fight, is a felonious offense? It's
one of my rights they're taking away.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain the appeal, Hodges and fellow cockfighters talk
about the pride of purifying bloodlines, the two years it takes to
raise birds from the egg to the ring, and the pure pleasure of
winning.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty miles away, at the Arizona Humane Society, White scoffs
at Hodges' rationale.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do this in nature? I don't think they would ingest
steroids, strap stilettos to their ankles, confine themselves to
wooden pens, and ask human beings to wager on who was going to die
first,'' says White, a trim man wearing stylish glasses, deck shoes
without socks and a red polo shirt with the Humane Society logo.
``This kind of thing is at the core of societal violence and it's
not just about Belton's life choices.''
</P>
<P>
   White, does, however, acknowledge a certain sympathy for Hodges.
``To be his age and see his world change that dramatically is
sad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 1423EST &QL; 
