u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-02 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN DEBATES OK, BUT TV ADS CRUCIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Someone _ I don't remember who _ recently suggested
that it would be a good idea to require candidates for public
office to participate in debates.
</P>
<P>
   The idea would be to promote an alternative to the programmed
television commercials that now dominate most major political
campaigns _ those campaigns that are successful anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The idea certainly is tempting but, alas, would likely violate
the First Amendment. Freedom of speech also includes the freedom
not to speak, and the last time I checked the First Amendment also
applied to political candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The debate issue predictably surfaces in every political season.
Challengers and other candidates with more energy than campaign
dollars will typically demand to debate better-known or
better-financed opponents, who often will dance around the
invitation and come up with repeated scheduling conflicts or other
excuses to avoid a head-to-head encounter.
</P>
<P>
   There were only three major televised debates featuring
statewide candidates this fall. Gov. George W. Bush, after much
prodding, debated his Democratic challenger, Garry Mauro, in El
Paso, Texas, a couple of weeks ago. Democrat John Sharp and
Republican Rick Perry, the candidates for lieutenant governor,
debated, also in El Paso, a few weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   And, last week, Democrat Jim Mattox and Republican John Cornyn
butted heads in Dallas in their attorney general's race. Candidates
who doubt their abilities to think quickly or speak coherently and
convincingly in a spontaneous exchange are reluctant to debate
their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Many front-runners, particularly those whose leads in the polls
are as wide as Bush's, also believe, with some justification, that
debates and other joint appearances with their opponents can do
little more than benefit their opponents. A televised debate
obviously gives an underdog more public exposure and, front-runners
fear, more credibility in the eyes of the voters. Front-runners
also fear, perhaps more than anything else, that they will commit a
major gaffe or blunder that could embarrass them before the voters,
damage their own credibility and make them more vulnerable to their
opponents' attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, nevertheless, continued what has become something of a
tradition of gubernatorial debates in Texas and finally agreed to
one debate with Mauro. And from all indications, it hasn't affected
the likely outcome of the gubernatorial race. It actually was one
of the duller events of the political season. Bush didn't make any
major mistakes, Mauro didn't come close to scoring a knockdown
punch and both candidates' rhetoric was largely uninspiring.
</P>
<P>
   But the mere fact that the televised debate was held was
important to the political process because it afforded voters who
made the effort to watch it _ either live or on taped replays _ an
opportunity to see the two candidates field questions about
important issues from an impartial moderator and challenge each
other's answers. In so doing, Bush and Mauro clearly outlined some
important differences.
</P>
<P>
   The liveliest televised debate of the fall was clearly last
week's shootout between Mattox and Cornyn, who eagerly displayed
their sharp political and philosophical differences in the attorney
general's race. As political debaters exchange charges and
countercharges, there, of course, is no guarantee that what they
are saying about themselves and each other is true.
</P>
<P>
   Lies can as easily be uttered by candidates during a debate as
they can be presented in political advertising. But the important
difference in a debate is that an opponent can immediately fire
back to challenge a statement that he or she believes is _ or knows
to be _ untrue. Debates, candidate forums, chamber of commerce
speeches, courthouse tours, endorsements by interest groups and
newspapers and, to be sure, party affiliation all play roles in
helping voters decide how to cast their ballots.
</P>
<P>
   But television advertising _ with all its exaggerations,
misrepresentations and downright lies _ will remain a dominant
factor in determining the outcome of major statewide races in
Texas. Sharp, for example, who has been criticizing Perry for
avoiding recent joint appearances in the lieutenant governor's
race, is, nevertheless, banking heavily on TV ads, some of which
have been blasted by Perry as unfair and inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't completely ignore the commercials. I paid $6.7 million
for them,'' Sharp told a Houston business group last week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
