<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9173 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-LENNON-BOS &LR;      11-02 1680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LENNON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTHOLOGY SHOWS ALL SIDES OF JOHN LENNON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Whether singing about working-class heroes or whatever gets
you through the night, John Lennon was rock's most genuine, most
ardent, most shoot-from-the-hip star. He was the creative fuel of
the Beatles, but it was in his post-Beatles solo career that his
true personality emerged. He wore many hats _ as peace activist,
house-husband, primal-scream advocate, black-humored satirist, FBI
antagonist, mind-games analyst, impish wastrel, and, almost without
fail, musical seer.
</P>
<P>
   All of these boldly unapologetic stances are celebrated in a
new, four-CD boxed set, ``The John Lennon Anthology,'' due out
Tuesday (it's expected to retail for $70-$75). It collects close to
100 previously unreleased Lennon nuggets, from stunning homemade
acoustic recordings to studio outtakes, live tracks, and highly
personal family conversations with wife Yoko Ono and son Sean.
</P>
<P>
   Together they paint a picture of a burningly complex yet
winsomely funny artist whose influence on rock 'n' roll was
unsurpassed. In his colorful, vigorously candid way, Lennon paved
the way for Kurt Cobain, Billy Corgan, and many other rock
iconoclasts.
</P>
<P>
   Like the three ``Beatles Anthology'' volumes that preceded it,
the new Lennon anthology takes the listener behind the scenes,
showing songs as they progress from demo to studio tapes, providing
studio banter (some hilarious exchanges with producer Phil Spector)
and giving a diarylike expression of Lennon's innermost thoughts,
from romantic to cynical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted this to embody a total picture of John,'' says
executive producer Ono, during a recent phone interview from her
home in the Dakota apartment building in Manhattan, where she lived
with Lennon until he was murdered by a crazed fan while entering
the building in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to include just the proper stuff about John,''
she added. ``Some of it is not that proper, because his black humor
was a little bit too sharp, but that was John. I didn't want to
censor it. I just wanted to show him as he was. The brilliant self
that he was.''
</P>
<P>
   She succeeded admirably _ and maybe, finally, this will help
Ono's image with some of those stuck-in-cement die-hards who still
scorn her as the ``Dragon Lady'' who broke up the Beatles. She has
treated Lennon's catalog with dignity for many years _ and this new
project is the most intimate, and arguably the most creative, boxed
set in the history of the genre.
</P>
<P>
   The timing also feels right. For many Lennon lovers, it has
taken years of healing to get to the point of being able to hear
his songs again without dissolving into regret. And this is the
right time, because it's also encouraging to revisit the music of
an artist who wasn't mimicking trends, as so often happens with
today's ``rock stars,'' but was creating his own.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Premiere of ``Hero''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The cultural significance of the new box jumps out from the
start. It opens with the first-ever take (a solo acoustic version)
of ``Working Class Hero'' from 1970. Like a minstrel of the
apocalypse, Lennon snarls the famous lines: ``As soon as you're
born, they make you feel small/By giving you no time instead of it
all/ &QC; 
Until the pain is so big you feel nothing at all.'' And then a
verse that still gives chills: ``When they've tortured you and
scared you for 20-odd years/Then they expect you to pick a
career/But you can't really function, you're so full of fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The song didn't sit well with the authoritiies, but neither did
a lot of Lennon tunes. Next up is ``God,'' in which he questions
religious icons and concludes ``I just believe in me, Yoko and me _
that's reality.'' More reality comes in a mesmerizing home tape of
``I Found Out,'' in which, atop his muddy solo electric guitar, he
sings, ``There ain't no guru who can look through your eyes.'' And
that's not to overlook ``I Don't Want to Be a Soldier,'' with its
tense line, ``I don't want to die.'' Vietnam, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   And this is just on the first CD, which also includes the first
take of his idealistic anthem, ``Imagine,'' done with harmonium, as
Spector is heard in the background admonishing some guests: ``Can
you be very quiet in the kitchen, please?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first take of `Imagine' was very powerful,'' says Ono, who
was there. ``It's like John was singing without knowing that it
would have such an incredible influence on the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine all the people living for today .../Imagine all the
people living life in peace,'' Lennon sings in the forceful, and
yet heartfelt, tone that he brought to everything he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``John didn't record something unless it really came from his
heart,'' Ono says. ``Somebody once said that the truth is a very
precious thing and you have to take it in small dosages. John
thought it was important to have a piece of truth told in every
song he did. He didn't want to just give something generic.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Lennon anthology so extraordinary is hearing
Lennon's voice front and center on the home tapes, before it often
got mixed down in the studio. His messages are thus even more bold,
as if he's singing right in the same room with the listener.
</P>
<P>
   There are home recordings from throughout his solo career,
climaxing with songs that ended up on 1980's ``Double Fantasy''
album. One is ``Watching the Wheels,'' his poetic ode to
house-husbandry, done hypnotically on acoustic guitar. He thumbs
his nose at the corporate rec-ord industry by singing that he's
``no longer riding on the merry-go-round/I just had to let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the serious philosophical songs that emerge
from the home tapes. Lennon's wry, satirical bent is illuminated in
three spontaneous parodies of Bob Dylan. Lennon affects Dylan's
pinched, nasal voice in ``Serve Yourself'' (a spoof of ``You Gotta
Serve Somebody''), singing, ``You've got to serve yourself, lads,
there ain't no room service here! .../You got to save yourself and
that's all there is to it.''
</P>
<P>
   He takes another poke at Dylan by mock-singing ``Knockin' on
Heaven's Door'' and then doing an untitled, spontaneous talking
blues about Vietnam, this time imitating the dour side of Dylan's
voice: ``The official Soviet newspaper said the temple members had
protested the mindless war in Vietnam and were persecuted and were
finally forced to seek refuge in another country. Wow, it sounds
like a ballad to me!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Off-the-cuff genius
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``These things just came out,'' says Ono. ``It wasn't like John
was laboring or finding words in a dictionary or anything. It just
came out of his head. It was incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Another spontaneous creation was the country twang of ``Life
Begins at 40,'' a home tape of Lennon on guitar and rhythm box.
``We'd like to welcome you to the Dakota Country-and-Western
Club,'' he says, sounding like Hank Williams. ``Life begins at 40,
age is just a state of mind .../And if that don't work, I'll jerk
around until my next birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   This song, in particular, sounds as though Lennon had drunk a
beer or two or three before devising it. ``Sometimes he had one too
many beers, and you can hear it,'' admits Ono. ``But he was still
there as a singer and a musician. He was still spot on.''
</P>
<P>
   The sensitive-father side of Lennon also comes out in some of
the home tapes. There's one called ``Loud,'' in which son Sean is
banging away on an electric guitar. ``I like it very loud,'' says
Sean. ``Well, that's how I like it too,'' says Dad. Another has
Sean asking where he was before he was born. ``You were still in
the sky,'' says John. When Sean wonders what he landed on when he
came down from the sky, John adds, ``A little cardboard box with a
little blanket in it _ like they bring the groceries in, but it was
you instead of the groceries.''
</P>
<P>
   Lennon's unique wit fills this boxed set, but so do his bold
political pronouncements, as heard in a live version of ``Attica
State,'' condemning the suffocating conditions that led to the
prison riots there. Further highlights are two versions of the
provocative ``Woman Is the Nigger of the World,'' which show Lennon
to be ahead of his time in supporting female empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   The least revelatory part of the box concerns sessions for his
``Rock 'n' Roll'' album in 1974. That came during a time when he
and Ono had broken up for nearly a year and a half and he was
partying heavily with rock buddies like Harry Nilsson and Keith
Moon in Los Angeles. The album has cover versions of classics such
as Little Richard's ``Rip It Up'' and Buddy Holly's ``Peggy Sue,''
but this was just a limbo period before Lennon reunited with Ono
and rekindled his creativity.
</P>
<P>
   The new anthology is chronologically arranged _ and the CDs are
titled according to different eras: ``Ascot,'' ``New York City,''
``The Lost Weekend,'' and ``Dakota.'' But after all of Lennon's
many moods and stances, it's compelling to see how positive he was
before his death. He never became the ``90-year-old guru'' that he
jokingly predicted he'd become in studio banter with Spector, but
he was definitely at peace with himself.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Grow Old With Me,'' he sings, ``Grow old with me, our best
is yet to be.'' In the poignant ``Beautiful Boy,'' he sings of
Sean: ``I can hardly wait to see you come of age.'' And in the
eerie ``Borrowed Time,'' represented by another home tape on
acoustic guitar, he sings, ``Now I'm older, the more that I see,
the less that I know for sure .../But the future is brighter.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ono, compiling this box (with the help of chief engineer Rob
Stevens) was a labor of love filled with tears. ``Oh, I was crying
most of the time or was choked up because he's no longer here _ you
know that feeling,'' she says. ``But it was a revelation to be
reminded of what an incredible talent he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'd listen to how brilliant he was, I felt like my
personal emotion just disappeared. And, as artist to artist, I just
felt like saying `Bravo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 1424EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9176 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-BARGE-2TAKES-H     11-02 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BARGE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE A CRUISE ABOARD A BARGE, SEE THE WORLD ALONG THE RIVERBANKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's play word association.
</P>
<P>
   We start with a ``vessel.'' We place it in the ``water.'' We put
198 ``passengers'' aboard and provide them with comfortable
``accommodations.'' We hire ``service'' personnel to cater to their
essential needs and individual whims. And we develop an
``itinerary'' that includes multiple ``ports.''
</P>
<P>
   What do we call this experience? A ``cruise,'' right?
</P>
<P>
   Not aboard the River Explorer, a daring and innovative venture
that offers an unusual perspective of America's inland waterways _
and their significant role in history and modern-day commerce _
from two connected barges propelled by a 3,000-horsepower towboat.
</P>
<P>
   Whoa, now. Fess up. You grimaced upon reading that last
paragraph, didn't you?
</P>
<P>
   Barges? Towboat? Immense, flat river barges _ not those
intimate, similarly named passenger boats that ply European canals
_ are designed to carry coal, grain, oil products, lumber and other
materials, aren't they? Not humans. Especially not humans on
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Don't dare make that suggestion to Eddie Conrad, chairman and
chief visionary of New Orleans-based RiverBarge Excursion Lines.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad already has defied the odds by achieving success for nine
years with ``RV barging'' on America's rivers. Five weeks ago, his
longtime dream became reality with the debut of the River Explorer,
billed as a ``floating community'' on explorations of four to 10
days on the Mississippi, Ohio, Missouri and Cumberland rivers and
on the Intracoastal Waterway in Texas and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural season includes six winter sailings between
Galveston, Texas, and New Orleans, La., one timed to showcase Mardi
Gras celebrations at each extreme and en route. Also scheduled is
one excursion in each direction between Galveston and Port Isabel,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It's a safe wager that you've neither seen nor imagined anything
quite like the River Explorer, constructed in Jennings, La. Its
three components _ the LaSalle and DeSoto barges and Miss Nari
towboat _ stretch for 730 feet, comparable in length to many large
cruise ships, but have a maximum width of 54 feet and rise only 50
feet above the water.
</P>
<P>
   Its on-board tone is as distinctive as its appearance. Unlike
most passenger vessels _ including steamboats operated by Delta
Queen and other companies _ the River Explorer schedules few
organized activities. ``We try to minimize herding,'' Conrad says.
``Herding works well for cattle but not for people.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no casino. Not even bingo. There are no lavish
song-and-dance revues. No magicians. No art auctions. No
napkin-folding demonstrations. No ``fluffy drink specials featuring
flaming flamingos,'' the line says. No pool games. No pool.
</P>
<P>
   While his approach may befuddle devoted cruisers, Conrad says
proudly, ``You won't find the word `cruise' anywhere in our
brochure or advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   The star attraction is clearly the river.
</P>
<P>
   Limited musical entertainment focuses on river lore.
Storytelling sessions detail legendary characters and their
exploits. Frequent commentary piped throughout the vessel relates
how rivers fostered industry and helped communities grow and
prosper, how they provided the impetus for the founding of New
Orleans, Memphis, St. Louis, Cincinnati and many other towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exploring these rivers provides people an opportunity to find
their heritage,'' Conrad suggests. ``People talked a few
generations ago of traveling to Ireland or England or other parts
of the world to trace their roots. But our roots are here in the
heartland.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the River Explorer represents America's first ``hotel
barge'' enterprise, Conrad is quick to remind that passenger
barging was a favored mode of transportation in the nation's
infancy, indeed that George Washington arrived for his inauguration
on a barge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barging evolved as the best and safest means to move people,
and it remains the safest way to travel on the river,'' says
Conrad. ``And with our shallow draft (drawing only 6 feet of
water), we can access more ports. That's important, because we're
trying not to offer canned itineraries. We want flexibility. We
want every excursion to stand on its own. Part of the appeal is
that there is always a certain amount of uncertainty and adventure
along the river.''
</P>
<P>
   Traveling at about 7 mph, it's a comfortable adventure. Diverse
sights _ a snowy white egret, a rusty freighter or an elegant
antebellum home high on a bluff _ are easily observed through
picture windows in staterooms, along corridors and in public areas.
Sunsets are spectacular when viewed from the vast open-air Sky
Deck.
</P>
<P>
   And if the River Explorer eschews traditional cruise enticements
too eagerly in some respects _ some travelers do enjoy organized or
disorganized fun, especially when paying $200-$300 per day _
oceangoing lines should take note of its passenger-friendly
amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Among these: bathtubs, refrigerators, coffee-makers and
televisions with VCRs in every stateroom; ice machines conveniently
placed in corridors; complimentary soft drinks, lemonade, tea and
coffee available by self-service at any hour; a prohibition against
tipping; and a basic fare that includes all land excursions and
port charges.
</P>
<P>
   Another nice touch: Binoculars are provided for every passenger,
with the request only that they be left in the stateroom upon
departure.
</P>
<P>
   A casual, family-style ambience prevails throughout. All 99
staterooms are identical except that upper-level cabins feature
small balconies beyond their ample 200-square-foot dimensions. No
one wears coats and ties or evening dresses. Passengers dine in the
Galley _ a large and comfortable room _ when and with whom they
please. And they are encouraged to raid the refrigerator day or
night for sandwiches, sweets or surprises, or to dip into a
``perpetual cookie jar'' in the main lobby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Passengers, officers and crew members mingle easily. The captain
answers to Kenny. The bargemaster _ no cruise director here _ is
introduced as Rock, his assistant as Sonny. The all-American crew
is designated as BargeMates, and each member performs various
duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't hire people as waiters, bartenders, housekeepers,
busboys and dishwashers,'' Conrad says. ``People have an
opportunity to rotate. We don't like titles. Teamwork is the only
way you can get barges up and down the river, and this is no
exception. Our captains come down from the bridge to help sort
luggage. And they don't wear uniforms with gold bars.''
</P>
<P>
   RiverBarge Excursions Line president Jeff Krida, a former
president of Delta Queen Steamboat Co., elaborates: ``Our main
emphasis in hiring is to find people whose mamas and daddies raised
them right.''
</P>
<P>
   While this idealistic approach is laudable, drawbacks quickly
become evident in its implementation. During an early-October
sailing between New Orleans and Vicksburg, Miss., some passengers
expressed confusion about the on-board chain of command and whom to
consult for specific requests or concerns. Service was consistently
provided with a smile _ ``We're told never to ignore a passenger's
request,'' one beaming BargeMate said _ but efficiency was erratic.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, start-ups in any service-oriented travel venture
are difficult; even long-existing companies refer to early sailings
on new ships as ``shakedown cruises,'' and most experienced
passengers avoid them. Imagine the challenge of starting from
scratch, using employees who, with few exceptions, have never been
to sea. Or to river.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the venture's potential seems almost unlimited,
especially if the vessel's vast space is used to maximum advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The two custom-built barges, named for famed river explorers,
consist of two interior decks each with a joint open upper deck
that includes a lounge, a jogging track and two hot tubs. Elevators
access all areas (but because of the vessel's length, expect to do
considerable walking).
</P>
<P>
   All staterooms are on the aft LaSalle barge. Twin beds are
easily converted into a ``super queen'' _ only about 3 inches
narrower than a king _ and, unlike on many cruise ships, aren't
lodged against a wall. Individual air-conditioning units allow
passengers to set temperatures to their liking. Television
reception includes ESPN, CNN, HBO and other cable outlets (but not
local channels). Bathrooms are spacious. Storage room is ample but
not extravagant.
</P>
<P>
   Among public rooms _ all on the forward DeSoto barge _ the
second-floor Pilot House at the front of the vessel is especially
inviting. Though the River Explorer's controls are elsewhere, this
room is a re-creation of a working pilot's station with radar,
charts and other instruments used by river pilots. Passengers gaze
through huge windows and listen to communications between the barge
and other vessels.
</P>
<P>
   On the same deck, a large lobby is ideal for relaxation and
river viewing. Nearby, a library/card room is notable both for its
classy decor and the care devoted to selecting books (many with a
maritime theme) and videos available on an honor system. Dozens
more seats are positioned beside windows in corridors.
</P>
<P>
   One significant oversight likely to be addressed soon,
considering the potential revenue to the line: No cocktail service
is offered anywhere on this deck. (Bars are on the lower floor and
the Sky Deck.)
</P>
<P>
   Dominating the lower level is the Galley, designed to seat about
230 passengers _ well above the vessel's capacity _ and never
crowded, given the flexible dining hours.
</P>
<P>
   Self-service buffets are featured at breakfast (with staples
including bacon, sausages, grits, fruit, cereals, made-to-order
omelets and pancakes, waffles or French toast) and lunch (a choice
of two or three hot entrees, a carving station, a salad bar with
exquisite dressings, innovative soups and cold cuts).
</P>
<P>
   Dinner menus change nightly. Passengers are offered soup or
salad and one of three entrees, including a Blue Plate Special that
reflects regional cuisine and on most evenings a dish suitable for
vegetarians.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights on our October excursion included Cornish game hen,
veal piccata and a roast pork loin. While some passengers expressed
disappointment at the sparsity of beef, lamb and lobster, most were
delighted by seafood gumbo, Louisiana crab cakes, red beans and
rice, fried-shrimp po-boys and ratatouille.
</P>
<P>
   Extending the emphasis on an educational experience, the line's
chefs might enhance appreciation by printing descriptions _ even
brief histories _ of signature dishes. One passenger from Iowa was
aghast at the ``foreign material'' in her rice (it was a delectable
chicken-and-sausage jambalaya); another from California asked
whether the ``sauce'' could be removed from her crawfish touffe.
</P>
<P>
   Also advisable is more frequent use of a grill on the open deck
for hamburgers, hot dogs and barbecue as lunch-hour alternatives
when weather permits.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprague showroom, arguably the vessel's most beautiful room,
encompasses both DeSoto interior decks with its cozy balcony
overlooking the main seating area. Named after one of the most
famous stern-wheelers on the Mississippi River, this is the perfect
venue for music and dancing, even for small-scale theatrical
productions. It also can be used for meetings and lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, during the October sailing, the Sprague was underused. A
Dixieland band played as part of pre-departure christening
festivities in New Orleans, then disembarked. A solo performance by
songwriter/musician Tom Hook _ billed as ``the Riverman'' _ was
well-received.
</P>
<P>
   But the only after-dinner ``entertainment'' on back-to-back
evenings consisted of storytelling sessions focusing on the
historical Mississippi ports Natchez and Vicksburg. While enjoyable
and enlightening, these seem better suited to mornings or
midafternoons. Even the Sprague's grand player piano was mostly
silent during this excursion, though RiverBarge officials promised
regular use _ with dancing encouraged _ on subsequent trips.
</P>
<P>
   Considerable thought has gone into the land packages, all
offered as part of the basic fare. At ports where some distances
are involved (visiting battlefields in Vicksburg and diverse sites
in Memphis, for instance), group bus tours are scheduled. Free
shuttle vans are provided where appropriate. In Natchez, a more
compact destination, passengers are issued a set of coupons they
can use at their leisure to board convenient trolleys and access
antebellum homes and other landmarks. A 30-minute horse-and-buggy
tour is included.
</P>
<P>
   So is this first U.S. hotel barge destined for success, the
forerunner of a trend?
</P>
<P>
   Early reaction is positive: Several trips are sold out, some as
group charters. A millennium excursion is fully booked 14 months in
advance. Conrad already talks of launching a second vessel within
two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't fit now into the locking systems of the upper
Mississippi, Tennessee, Tombigbee and Arkansas rivers,'' he says,
``so our next barge will be only 600 feet long and hold 156
guests.''
</P>
<P>
   With few exceptions, passengers on the October cruise were
retirees. Conrad envisions senior citizens as his primary clientele
but also hopes to lure teachers and families with children when
school isn't in session (though most kids would require more
diversions).
</P>
<P>
   It's not an inexpensive vacation: Brochure prices, based on
double occupancy, range from $740 per person for a three-night
excursion in a lower-level stateroom to $2,335 per person for
accommodations with a balcony on some eight-night trips. Those
rates do compare favorably with Delta Queen brochure prices, and
the inclusion of land tours and service charges makes them more
palatable.
</P>
<P>
   The main long-term challenge likely lies in sustaining the river
as the main lure. ``We're trying to tell a story within a certain
outline,'' Conrad says.
</P>
<P>
   Time will tell whether passenger reaction dictates that the
outline also call for a dance band, bingo and fruity drinks with
``flaming flamingos.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, just call this the anti-cruise. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
