<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NIGHT-TALK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRIENDSHIP, IN BLACK AND WHITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
NIGHT TALK 
By Elizabeth Cox 
St. Martin's, 288 pp., $13.95 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Evie and Janey Louise grew up as friends, best friends in that
precious, almost holy way only girls of a certain age can be
friends. When they found each other, they were not quite little
girls, not yet teenagers hinting of young womanhood. Life could
still seem fresh and simple, though each already bore tender,
similar scars. Both were fatherless: Janey Louise's daddy was dead
and gone; Evie's just up and gone.
</P>
<P>
   So each filled the painful spaces in the other's life,
especially at night when they would lie in Evie's room and share
secrets as intimate as an embrace. Dreams, fears, all the things
that could busy a child's mind, unfolded in the hush of their
nights like a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was a friendship often consigned to the shadows, so much
so the girls were warned not to tell anyone they even slept in the
same room _ Evie was white, Janey Louise was black, and they lived
in segregated, small-town Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Cox's uneven, yet involving ``Night Talk'' is
certainly about the resilience of Evie and Janey Louise's
friendship through four tumultuous decades. But at its core, it is
a novel about the insidious nature of the great American dilemma,
and how perceptions of race and racism can infringe on and even
threaten the most intimate relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The novel bounces between the 1950s and 1970s, when Volusia,
Janey Louise's mother, is dying of cancer. The slow decline of this
once-mighty woman beckons Evie and Janey Louise (now called Jane)
back to their hometown, the fictional Mercy, Ga., and allows Evie,
who narrates the story, to reminisce about their tinderbox
relationship. As they return home, Evie and Jane have been
estranged for three years, their friendship left ragged by the
socio-political upheavals of the 1960s and 1970s. Says Evie, ``The
politics ... pulled us apart. Her friends told her not to trust me,
and mine were wary of us.'' It's a sad admission.
</P>
<P>
   The book begins in 1949 as Evie's father, August, a research
biologist handcuffed by domestic life, abandons his family. On that
night, Jane and Volusia moved in with Agnes Bell, and her children,
Evie and Tucker. Volusia has been the Bells' housekeeper for two
years, so no one looks askance at her residence with a white
family.
</P>
<P>
   These are the years before the landmark Brown v. Board of
Education decision, before Rosa Parks refused to surrender her seat
on a Montogomery, Ala., bus. Mercy is a typical well-mannered,
God-fearing Southern town where Negroes are expected to know their
place or suffer the brutal consequences.
</P>
<P>
   As children, those realities constantly intrude on Evie and
Jane, and this is where Cox excels in capturing the small, but
soul-stifling indignities of racism. When the girls venture down to
the new, grand department store, a woman points at Jane, and scolds
Evie, ``You know good and well you're not supposed to bring her in
here,'' before Jane runs out the door. At the movies, Jane, forced
to sit in the segregated section, sneaks down from the balcony to
sit with Evie. She crawls under the seats, soiling and ripping her
dress, to get a better view of her favorite star, Rita Hayworth.
</P>
<P>
   Jane endures these outrages quietly, and perhaps because of
this, Evie, as a child, does not consider how damaging these
incidents are to her friend. Racism begins in the gut, then settles
deeply into the bones, becoming a daily part of life, which Evie
accepts as the natural order of things. Even when Evie writes to
her father after seeing a photograph of Jane's daddy, she describes
him as ``a handsome man, even though he is colored.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox handles these sections with certainty and sincerity. But the
book later suffers wobbly moments, especially after one of the
friends is arrested for murder the day of Volusia's funeral. It's a
dramatic device to push the women to overlook their differences,
but it's too much like a daytime soap opera, with life-altering
revelations delivered in long-sealed envelopes. Another problem is
Volusia, who seems as if plucked from 1930s central casting. Less a
character than a symbol, she's the quintessential hat-making,
home-cooking, storytelling, long-suffering negress, like Louise
Beavers in ``Imitation of Life,'' but with a dash more sass and
bite. And the shifts between the past and present, sometimes within
the same chapter, are at times confusing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cox is an graceful writer who confronts a difficult
issue, and handles it with pathos and recognition. There may always
be things white people will never truly understand, and hard, hurt
places where black people will never permit them to go. Yet for
those willing, there is much to savor and learn from all that is
sweet and sustaining between us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
