<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9180 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-02 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVE THE EARTH WHILE TRAVELING IT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I did a double take the first time I saw the message in a hotel
bathroom in British Columbia several years back.
</P>
<P>
   It read: ``Please rehang towels for use a second day; only
towels left on the floor or in the tub will be replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever the skeptic, I turned to the co-pilot and said, ``These
people are just trying to save money on housekeeping and
towel-washing.''
</P>
<P>
   And I was right. Well, half-right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working together to protect our environment is a win-win
situation for the traveler and those in the industry,'' says
Patricia Griffin, founder and president of the Houston-based
`Green' Hotels Association, whose worldwide membership has grown to
150 properties in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin's mandate is to appeal to the ecological conscience of
hoteliers and their guests. Implementing water-saving measures,
using energy-saving techniques and reducing solid waste can indeed
stretch the budget of a hotel or any other travel-service provider.
Beyond that, Griffin says, these programs help ``save our planet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taking steps &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The concept is growing in scope and popularity. Many hotels now
ask guests to consider using towels and bed linens more than once.
Liquid soap and shampoo dispensers replace paper-wrapped bars and
miniature bottles. Recycling bins stand adjacent to trash cans.
Strategically placed reminders encourage guests to avoid excessive
use of electricity. Drinking water often is served by request only
in hotels and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   On the new River Explorer barge, every passenger is provided a
mug and encouraged (though not required) to carry and use it
throughout the vessel in an effort to reduce paper waste. Crew
members will gladly wash the mug at any time or place.
</P>
<P>
   In stark contrast to most traditional cruise ships, which
heavily promote twice-daily replacement of towels and washcloths as
part of routine ``pampering,'' towels and linens aboard the River
Explorer are changed every other day unless a passenger requests
more frequent service.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, too, that most travelers at sea would embrace _ or
at least accept _ environment-protection measures just as they do
on land. We relish being pampered while on vacation or at the end
of a long business day, but we try not to leave our common-sense
values at home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some hesitation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Griffin concedes that innkeepers were sensitive when first
approached with ideas such as placing towel- and sheet-changing
request cards in rooms. ``Hotel managers feared insulting even one
guest,'' Griffin says. ``Now some hotels estimate that 70 to 90
percent of their guests participate (in agreeing to reuse towels
and linens).
</P>
<P>
   ``Most travelers recognize the importance of helping preserve
the environment. Very few people go to a hotel because of the hotel
itself; they go because of a beach or the water or a park _ because
of the beauty of a destination. A hotel's efforts can help protect
this for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by public response, some hotels and other establishments
have expanded their ``green'' programs. Griffin cites a Toronto
hotel that recycles stained tablecloths into napkins, chef's aprons
and neckties. A Wisconsin bed-and-breakfast installed a blue tile
floor made from recycled automobile windshields. Other hotels make
cloth laundry bags from retired sheets. A Florida hotel bought a
mulcher to chop up its garden clippings and create its own mulch.
(The mulcher paid for itself in three months).
</P>
<P>
   Reducing paper use is a common objective: Coins or chips are
gaining popularity as an alternative to paper receipts for car
parking and coat checking. Restaurants, banquet facilities and even
some room-service operations are eschewing individual packets and
instead using pourers for sugar, pitchers for cream and small
serving dishes for butter, jellies and other condiments.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin's association also promotes (and sells to hotels) a
toilet-tank fill diverter that saves } of a gallon of water per
flush, is invisible to the guest, doesn't affect the flush and
costs less than $1.
</P>
<P>
   Even with so much progress in the industry, Griffin says, the
traveling public must stand at the forefront of
environmental-protection efforts.
</P>
<P>
   So what can we do? Among initiatives Griffin recommends:
</P>
<P>
   Spend travel dollars with businesses interested in protecting
destinations. Encourage the adoption and expansion of ``green''
programs. Express your support by writing a note or speaking
directly to the management of a hotel, tour company, cruise line or
airline.
</P>
<P>
   Use hotel vans, buses and local transit systems to reduce
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Use electronic ticketing for air travel to reduce paper use.
</P>
<P>
   At visitor centers, take only brochures or maps necessary for
planning or enjoying a trip. Return others to the brochure stand.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid disposable cameras. And buy rolls of film with 36 shots
rather than 12 or 24; it helps reduce packaging waste and is
cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Use zippable plastic bags for cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of buying small toothpaste tubes, squeeze some
toothpaste into a clean contact-lens case or contact-lens cleaning
capsule. These also are handy for carrying salves or pills (but
make sure you mark them appropriately).
</P>
<P>
   Reduce the amount of water you use for bathing or showering in
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Leave unused bottles of amenities in hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   For additional suggestions or information about the `Green'
Hotels Association, which has members in 39 states, Canada, Mexico,
the Caribbean, Central and South America and Europe, access
www.greenhotels.com on the Internet; call 713-789-8889; fax
713-789-9786; or write to P.O. Box 420212, Houston, Texas
77242-0212. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
