<HEADER>
A9183 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-02 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER PHLOX GROWS WELL IN A WELL-DRAINING SOIL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I bought a `Robert Poore' phlox. How do I care for it?
</P>
<P>
   I have a ``Dracaena marginata'' that grew tall and spindly
indoors. I moved it outdoors last spring, and it has put on several
shoots near the bottom. Can I cut off the top and root it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The phlox you have is a summer-flowering perennial, ``Phlox
paniculata'' `Robert Poore.' Summer phlox are taller than the
spring-flowering Louisiana phlox and are generally in the 3- to
5-foot range. However, I've read that `Robert Poore' can grow even
taller.
</P>
<P>
   The fragrant flowers of summer phlox come in large, dome-shaped
clusters. Your variety is a bright pink, and there are also white,
lavender, rose and red varieties. Some have a contrasting eye.
</P>
<P>
   Summer phlox likes sun or partial sun and an organically
enriched, well-draining soil. Powdery mildew can be a problem with
some varieties, so it's wise to provide good air circulation by not
crowding plants. `Robert Poore' is touted as disease-resistant.
</P>
<P>
   You can remove the top of a leggy dracaena cane, treat the cut
end with a rooting hormone and plant in a well-draining potting
compost. You also can cut 2- to 3-inch pieces of stem and root them
similarly. Cuttings will root more quickly in a humid atmosphere,
but do not overwater the soil. Ideal temperature is 70-75 degrees.
Keep in bright, but not direct, sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Q: I would like information on planting potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   A: You can plant potatoes two weeks before to two weeks after
the average last freeze date, Feb. 14. Or you can plant 12 to 14
weeks before the average date of our first frost, Dec. 11. Potatoes
need to mature in a cool soil.
</P>
<P>
   If you find seed potatoes in time for fall planting, plant 3 to
4 inches deep in a compost-enriched, slightly acidic soil. When you
see about 6 inches of top growth, rake the soil over the plant,
leaving only an inch of growth exposed. Repeat this process weeks
later when you again see 6 inches of growth. Harvest time varies,
from 85 to more than 100 days.
</P>
<P>
   Since grocery-store potatoes have been treated to prevent
sprouting while in storage, they usually don't sprout in the
ground. You can buy seed potatoes from catalogs or save small
potatoes from spring crops, a common practice because locating seed
potatoes in time for fall planting can be difficult. Sometimes,
however, spring potatoes don't sprout due to a natural dormancy.
One way to break this dormancy is to harvest the spring potatoes
and store in an area where temperatures are in the 50-degree range
up to a month before fall planting time. Then keep the potatoes at
normal temperatures until you're ready to plant.
</P>
<P>
   Plant the small seed potatoes whole.
</P>
<P>
   Harvest time varies from 75 to more than 100 days. Usually the
plants begin to yellow when it's time to harvest the tubers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am always looking for new plants, especially hummingbird
plants. What can you tell me about ``Zauschneria californica'' and
``Z. cana?'' Common name is California fuchsia, but it is not a
true fuchsia.
</P>
<P>
   Many books that list hummingbird plants accent flowers for more
northern and eastern areas and often omit some of the great ones we
can grow. I'm thinking of three clerodendrums, shrimp plant,
hamelia and ``Odontonema strictum.''
</P>
<P>
   A: I have read that the California fuchsia, or hummingbird
flower, is a summer-fall bloomer with trumpet-shaped orange to red
flowers that attract the small birds. There are white and pink
forms. The plants spread by underground stems as they colonize.
</P>
<P>
   I have not seen this plant here nor ``Z. cana,'' which is denser
and has more silver in its leaves. But the other plants you mention
occasionally are available in the Houston area. They are excellent
garden choices to draw butterflies and hummingbirds.
</P>
<P>
   We've mentioned each at various times in this column. The
clerodendrums are underused here. Your list included ``C.
speciossisimum,'' ``C. paniculatum'' and ``C. fragrans,'' and I
would like to add ``C. ugandense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``C. speciossisimum,'' or Java glorybower, has 12- to 18-inch
pyramidal flower clusters of intense red blooms and large, velvety
leaves. This old-fashioned, easy plant can grow more than 10 feet
tall. It tolerates pruning if you want a shorter shrub. Protect
with mulch in winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``C. paniculatum,'' or pagoda glorybower, matures to 4 to 5
feet, has rounded or oval foliage to 16 inches long and 12-inch
pyramidal clusters of small scarlet blooms. Protect in winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``C. fragrens pleniflorum'' is a shrub that spreads by suckers,
is up to 8 feet tall and has 10-inch leaves and clusters of double,
pale pink blooms. The fragrant flowers resemble those of a florist
hydrangea. ``C. bungei'' has the same, oval leaves with toothed
edges, dark green on top, rusty beneath and clusters of rosy-red
blooms. The latter is the familiar, old-fashioned shrub known as
cashmere bouquet.
</P>
<P>
   ``C. ugandense,'' or blue butterfly bush, is a leggy shrub that
accepts pruning to encourage bushier growth. It has glossy, 4-inch
leaves and beautiful 1-inch blooms with one violet-blue petal and
four pale blue petals for many months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Firespike (Odontonema) is a shade-tolerant perennial that
produces spikes of waxy, deep-red blooms in fall. This plant is
easy to grow and is more readily available now. Hamelia and shrimp
plant are even easier to locate.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, more books are being written for our growing area.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've had a blue skyflower bush (``Duranta plumeri'') in my
garden for two years. The bush is very healthy, but it has never
bloomed. Any advice?
</P>
<P>
   A: If your plant is getting a good amount of sun, I imagine it
will bloom eventually. Sometimes plants are a little on the
obstinate side about flowering and just take their time. Since it
is healthy and growing, hold off on any nitrogen, as it may have
been growing at the expense of flowering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duranta plumeri'' is synonymous with ``Duranta repens.''
Common names include golden dewdrop (because of the small golden
berries that follow the blue blooms) and blue skyflower. These
graceful shrubs have arching branches. Protect during hard freezes
with a heavy layer of mulch. Prune any dead wood in early spring
before new growth begins.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: My bougainvillea survived last winter because the weather was
so mild, so now it is huge. It is outgrowing the trellis. Do I
prune it back? At what time of the year? Will trimming encourage it
to bloom?
</P>
<P>
   A: Since your plant has made it through a winter or two, it may
be root-hardy if planted in the ground. A heavy blanket of mulch
will help protect it in cold weather. You can prune bougainvillea
to shape or direct the growth during the growing season. You also
can prune after flowering. You might nip branches that are in the
way now, but any heavy pruning will encourage growth that will be
more vulnerable should we have an early frost. So try to live with
the plant pretty much as it is now, then prune hard early next
spring when we're out of danger of a freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Should top growth be damaged during a freeze, leave all or at
least a good deal of dead wood until we're out of the danger of
frost. This protects live or green wood farther down the branch and
closer to the base of the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Those gardeners with container-grown bougainvillea sometimes
prune long stems for easier storage in a garage or sheltered area
in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Use a high-potash fertilizer, such as a hibiscus fertilizer, to
encourage color. A tablespoon every three to four weeks is
adequate. A tablespoon of Epsom salts when you fertilize also is
beneficial. Stop fertilizing during late fall and winter. Water
only when you see a slight wilt.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Some bougainvillea varieties bloom best in fall when
nights are long and days are short.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
