<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9189 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-DOCTOR-ART-BOS &LR;      11-02 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-DOCTOR-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS DOCTOR KEEPS MUSICIANS IN TUNE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES-RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The idea that professional athletes and dancers should
have doctors who specialize in injuries common to their vocation is
not exactly radical. Athletes use their muscles to the extreme,
often leading to painful conditions that most people, thankfully,
never experience.
</P>
<P>
   But what about musicians, such as the classical pianist who
practices etudes and arpeggios up to 15 hours a day, or the rock
guitarist running pentatonic scales six hours in a row? Besides the
damage to these players' social lives, couldn't there also be a
nearly athletic muscular strain born of such continuous physical
demands?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael E. Charness, associate chief of neurology at Brigham
and Women's Hospital and associate professor of neurology at
Harvard University Medical School, believes the answer is yes.
</P>
<P>
   Charness, director of Brigham and Women's ``performing arts
clinic,'' is one of a handful of doctors in that narrow medical
specialty. In addition to the Wednesday clinic at the hospital, he
also runs a musicians-only clinic on Saturdays at the New England
Conservatory. Only one other local doctor shares Charness's beat:
Fred Hochberg at Massachusetts General Hospital, who also
specializes in brain tumors.
</P>
<P>
   Charness, a classical pianist, said, ``I've seen a lot of
musicians who go to doctors with their problems, just to be told
it's all in their head. Or they are told to stop playing their
instrument. You can't tell musicians that.''
</P>
<P>
   Charness's patients _ Boston Symphony Orchestra musicians,
Boston Pops players, and Berklee College professors among them _
say he understands them. Many of them will not talk about their
injuries on the record because, they say, being an injured musician
is taboo in competitive musical circles, where the credo ``no pain
no gain'' dominates, and any weakness is ammunition for your
challengers.
</P>
<P>
   But Conservatory graduate Karen Choo, a 24-year-old vioinist
with ulnar nerve problems, was happy to share her thoughts on the
doctor at a recent post-operative appointment. She makes her
living, for the time being, as an economist.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first when I got the pain, I thought it was just because
... my technique wasn't strong anymore,'' she said as she exercised
her fingers with a rubber band ``gymnasium.'' ``I felt relieved to
know that it was actually a physical problem, and to know that
there was something I could do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charness should know. He's had the same operation Choo had, for
musical injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to practicing medicine and being a research
scientist in the field of fetal alcohol syndrome, Charness has
played piano since he was 9. He's married to a professional flute
player, and their three children are all musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a neurologist, I'm a scientist, I'm a dad, I'm a
musician,'' Charness says with a smile. ``I feel privileged to be
all of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from McGill University and Johns Hopkins
University Medical School, Charness did his first residency at
Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Then he took his second residency at the University of
California at San Francisco. While working there, friends told him
he had to meet a flutist named Deborah Nathan, from New York City,
who they thought was a perfect match for him. Not only did she
share his passion for classical music, they said, but the fact that
her father, David G. Nathan, was a noted doctor _ and now president
of Dana-Farber Cancer Institute _ was a plus.
</P>
<P>
   Charness flew to New York to meet this person, and within seven
hours, the two were engaged. The moment of knowing came, he says,
when they played Mozart sonatas together. ``She auditioned me,'' he
jokes. ``I passed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was a great guy right away,'' said Deborah Charness,
who now performs with several local groups and teaches out of her
home studio in Newton. ``But the problem for me as a professional
musician would have been marrying an amateur musician. If he was
not good, and wanted to come home and play with me, it would have
been unbearable. But Michael was very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Charness said he struggled to keep up with his
wife-to-be. Six weeks after they met, they performed publicly
together, at the Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   And all the extra practicing was taking a toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began to have trouble playing,'' Charness says. ``I'd had a
little bit already, but it got worse. I was developing a problem
with coordination in my hands, first one, then the other. If I
wasn't a musician, I would never have known that I had a problem at
all, because it was not immediately apparent. I began to pay a lot
of attention to it. I was very interested in the fact that a person
could be so disabled, and yet appear normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Charness shared his concerns with a friend and violinist who
also was a doctor. He told Charness the problem was a pinched nerve
in the elbow, and suggested surgery to decompress the ulnar nerve
(funny bone). In August of 1984, Charness, who was then doing a
postgraduate fellowship in science at UC-San Francisco, had the
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was done in an hour, with local anesthesia, and I went back
to work the next day,'' he says. ``I improved gradually.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of Charness's improvement spread by word of mouth among his
musician friends, he says. And one by one, they began to come to
him with their particular pains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was seeing them as patients, but it wasn't like it is now. I
would see them in the back of the science lab, after-hours. When I
started looking at these problems, I didn't have any more expertise
than anyone else. But I did know that you could have very important
problems as a musician without having a lot wrong with you in
obvious ways.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 Charness relocated to Boston, where he had been hired as
chief of neurology at the Veterans Administration Hospital in West
Roxbury, a post he still holds.
</P>
<P>
   And in Boston, as in California, musician friends soon began to
seek his advice. In the insular world of classical musicians, word
spread quickly, and patients began to come here from Europe,
Canada, and across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Charness's practice at the Brigham is full, and limited _
to musicians only. His patients have constant access to him via
e-mail, which he checks continuously on his laptop, responding
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   And there's plenty of work. So much work, in fact, that he has
been able to keep a team of physical therapists and surgeons quite
happy with his referrals. Regina Campbell, owner and clinician at
Performing Arts Physical and Occupational Therapy, said her
business has grown substantially because of Charness's patients,
and that 95 percent of her patients are musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Dr. Charness's musicianship has allowed him to
interface with musicians in a special way,'' said Campbell. ``He
understands them. He knows what they're talking about, knows the
instruments, the posture, the technique. He knows what it's like to
play too much, and he knows how to fix it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
