<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9191 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-MATISSE-BOS &LR;      11-02 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MATISSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DARK DAYS OF A PAINTER OF BRILLIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Henri Matisse, painter of warmth and light, was born near the
bleak beet fields of northern France, not far from the Belgian
border, in the same region that had produced Vincent Van Gogh. We
think of them as opposites, of Van Gogh as the quintessential
tortured soul, of Matisse as transmitter of joy and voluptuousness.
Their lives must surely have been equally opposed, no?
</P>
<P>
   No. In her majestic biography that tracks Matisse from his birth
in 1869 to 1908, by which time he'd painted ``The Joy of Life,''
one of the key works of a career that stretched until his death in
1954, Hilary Spurling spins a tale of poverty, rejection, and
despair. Thank goodness, it's also a tale of determination: Without
that, Matisse might have bowed to parental pressure and remained a
law clerk in a provincial town. Or he might have stuck with an
early and somewhat successful formula, one that led to a friend
calling him ``a delicate painter, master of the arts of grey.'' The
style for which Matisse would become famous pitted pink against
orange, blue against green; his high-key colors sing. If ever there
were a painter not ultimately identified with gray, it was Henri
Matisse.
</P>
<P>
   A sickly youth, he was a 20-year-old lying in a hospital bed
when his mother brought him a paint box to pass the time. ``From
the moment I held the box of colors in my hand, I knew this was my
life,'' he later said.
</P>
<P>
   The rest is history _ but one skimpily recorded until Spurling
came along. There's no shortage of books on Matisse, of course, one
of the most picked-over painters of all time, but most are art
historical or straight hagiography. Spurling sets out to offer an
exhaustive look at the minutiae of the first half of Matisse's life
and place him in the context of a world in political as well as
artistic tumult. As Matisse arrived on the scene, Impressionism's
revolution had already ripped apart the French art world, which had
been as tightly ruled by an entrenched bureaucracy as the
government itself.
</P>
<P>
   It was a political scandal, the ``Humbert Affair'' _ worse than
Watergate and Monica rolled into one _ that almost killed Matisse's
career early on. The Humberts, at the zenith of financial and
political power in France, were also found to be at the center of a
world-class scam that rocked the nation and threatened its banking
system. And the Humberts' chief lieutenants were Matisse's in-laws,
on whom Matisse and his devoted wife had depended utterly.
</P>
<P>
   What little work Matisse was able to produce during that
1902-'03 crisis, when he was primarily involved in damage control _
dealing with lawyers, jailers and an intrusive press _ has been
labelled his ``dark period,'' a retreat to the somber palette of
Flemish painting. ``Matisse scholars have put the change down to
native prudence, failure of nerve, an innately bourgeois instinct
to retrench,'' Spurling writes. She argues convincingly that
Matisse didn't merely get cold feet, that the shift was the result
of cataclysm in his personal life and extreme financial hardship.
Suddenly, he was the sole support of a wife, three young children,
and his in-laws, who were found innocent of any wrongdoing in the
Humbert mess but were ruined nonetheless. During this period,
Matisse had to paint what collectors would buy. The Humbert affair,
which the authorities covered up for the better part of a century,
also explains Matisse's reputation for being cold-hearted and
mean-spirited, Spurling contends: It made him secretive and wary of
others.
</P>
<P>
   The minute he could, Matisse stopped painting for the market.
The dealer Ambroise Vollard wanted him to paint more of the same.
Matisse even had more of the same _ which he deliberately
destroyed, although ``the hands of the butcher and the baker were
outstretched waiting for the money,'' he later recalled. He set his
wife and daughter to scrubbing and scraping the offending canvases,
which were too expensive to destroy, canvases on which he'd paint
his authentic work.
</P>
<P>
   By pawning his wife's emerald ring _ with her permission _ he
scraped together the cash to buy Cezanne's ``Three Bathers,'' a
painting he felt he had to confront on a daily basis. Spurling
writes that ``Matisse absorbed Cezanne _ as he said Cezanne himself
had absorbed Poussin _ into his bloodstream at so deep a level
that, though the underlying relationship is unmistakable, it is
hard to pinpoint any specific visual resemblance.''
</P>
<P>
   What he learned from contemplating his Cezanne each morning was
at least as important as what he got from the various academies and
ateliers where he studied. One of the book's dominant themes is the
struggle to find a mentor, a master sufficiently secure not to
demand that his pupils ape his style. Gustave Moreau, Symbolist and
recluse, came closest for Matisse, who also spent long days copying
masters including Chardin in the Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more fascinating aspects of Spurling's book is its
descriptions of the interactions among painters, their
conversations on canvas and off, which put paid to the stereotype
of the artist working in isolation. Spurling tells you more than
you may want to know about artists unknown to all but scholars, but
manages to interest you in how Matisse finally pulled away from the
pack. By the time the book ends, painting in Paris is basically a
two-man race between Matisse and Picasso. A dialogue and also a
duel, Spurling calls it, describing how the two goaded each other
on, competing, for instance, in assimilating the African art that
deeply affected them both.
</P>
<P>
   Matisse was consumed by color that had a life of its own, and
ridiculed by most for paintings like the portrait of his
long-suffering wife with a green stripe down the middle of her
face. For his dazzling color he was labelled ``Fauve'' _ ``wild
beast.'' But after more than a decade of public contempt,
perceptive people came around. Spurling's sentence ``The buyers
were two Americans, a brother and sister, Leo and Gertrude Stein,''
makes you want to stand up and cheer. Sarah Stein, a Stein by
marriage, was an even greater supporter: She converted the
legendary art historian Bernard Berenson to Matisse's cause, and
convinced her friends back home in San Francisco to buy Matisses,
too, which accounts for that city's wealth of work by the artist.
Sergei Ivanovich Shchukin, the Russian textile magnate, became
another great Matisse collector, but his canvases ``spent the
central decades of the 20th century shut up in a Soviet cellar,''
Spurling writes. (She avoids the current debate over their fate in
Russia, where the government now proudly flaunts them, refusing
restitution to the Shchukin heirs.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Unknown Matisse'' does just what Volume 1 of a biography
should do _ it makes you eager for Volume 2, which, according to
Spurling's publisher, is years down the road. But this lengthy
first installment leaves Matisse at a good moment in his career,
finally able to provide a proper home for the children he'd had to
parcel out to relatives better able to care for them, finally
supported by a loyal little band of collectors. Spurling makes you
feel confident about Matisse's future _ the way Matisse, just shy
of 40, was starting to feel about himself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Christine Temin writes about art and dance for the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
