<P>
   &UR; PET NAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Bernie was invited to his friend's home for dinner. Morris, the
host, preceded every request to his wife by endearing terms,
calling her Honey, My Love, Darling, Sweetheart, Pumpkin, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie looked at Morris and remarked, `That is really nice, that
after all these years that you have been married, you keep calling
your wife those pet names.`
</P>
<P>
   Morris hung his head and whispered,` To tell the truth, I forgot
her name three years ago.`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERFECT HEARING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An elderly gentleman had serious hearing problems for a number
of years. He went to the doctor and the doctor was able to have him
fitted for a set of hearing aids that allowed the gentleman to hear
100%.
</P>
<P>
   The elderly gentleman went back in a month to the doctor and the
doctor said, `Your hearing is perfect. Your family must be really
pleased that you can hear again.`
</P>
<P>
   The gentleman replied, `Oh, I haven't told my family yet. I just
sit around and listen to the conversations. I've changed my will
three times!`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   To study the effects of weightlessness, why send John Glenn into
space? Wouldn't sitting around listening to Senate speeches do just
as well?
</P>
<P>
   _ (Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   My friend Julie Morganstern gave me a 6-inch-high chubby ceramic
Chinese ``lucky cat'' for my birthday. It came with printed
instructions to put the cat in my shop window or at the entrance to
my house. Since I work out of my 30th-floor apartment, I decided to
glue the cat outside my door.
</P>
<P>
   It has since been a conversation starter, eliciting such
questions as ``Why do you have a cat outside your entry instead of
a mezuza?'' My answer: ``Because I'm not Jewish.'' (Of course, I'm
not Chinese either, but never mind.)
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I opened the door to get the Sunday paper and found a
2-inch-high miniature clone of my lucky cat sitting alongside the
original. I laughed out loud for at least five minutes. The next
Sunday, another clone appeared. I've asked several people if they
are responsible for my cat having kittens, and none of them seem to
know anything about it. To date, I've received four little kittens
that have added a tremendous amount of delight and charm to my
life.
</P>
<P>
   Looks like my lucky cat really does bring good fortune. I wonder
what will be outside my door today.
</P>
<P>
   _ MARILYNN FRANCES LUNDY
</P>
<P>
   Four-year-old Rebecca was told by her mother, Sharon Edelstein,
that she would get hurt if she continued bouncing on her bed. ``I
won't get hurt,'' Rebecca said, and continued bouncing. Her mother
repeated the warning and added that she might also break the bed.
``No, I won't,'' Rebecca insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother gave up. ``Fine,'' she said. ``Do it. You'll have to
live with the consequences.'' Rebecca immediately stopped bouncing.
``I don't want to go and live with them, Mommy,'' she said. ``I
don't even know the Consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after her 90th birthday, Lillian Susskind asked her
daughter, Henny Weiss, to accompany her to her favorite store to
replenish her wardrobe. Cane in hand, she cheerfully selected and
tried on several outfits. When the time came to pay, she placed her
cane on the counter, freeing her hands to find the correct amount
of cash.
</P>
<P>
   Elated by her fabulous bargains, she took her shopping bags and
marched proudly toward the exit, forgetting her cane. An astonished
cashier, cane in hand, ran after her, shouting ``Madam, this is
Loehmann's, not Lourdes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fifth Avenue bus was headed downtown when a gray-haired
woman got on with a young man in his late teens, possibly her
grandson. He hesitated a moment, apparently uncertain about the
correct procedure of swiping his Metrocard, and she set him
straight.
</P>
<P>
   He then started to take one of the seats in the front, when she
reminded him that those seats were reserved for the elderly.
``Well, you are one,'' he said. ``Don't be silly,'' she replied as
she guided him toward the back of the bus. ``I'm only 76.''
</P>
<P>
   _ SAMI I. SAID
</P>
<P>
   Mary M. Wheelwright was recently reminded of a hobby she had as
a little girl growing up in Manhattan. She went through a stage of
being entranced by what she considered the fascinating and exotic
names of taxi drivers. She would read them, write them down and
carefully save them.
</P>
<P>
   After a year or so, beaming with pride, she presented the list
to her parents. She couldn't understand why they looked at each
other and seemed to be having a hard time stifling laughter. They
didn't enlighten her until some years later. Her list was titled
``Taxi Drivers I Have Had.'' As Ms. Wheelwright says, ``Ah
innocence!''
</P>
<P>
   A young supermarket clerk was stocking shelves as Liz Miller
wandered in vain, looking for peanuts. ``Where are the nuts?'' she
finally asked. ``Up and down every aisle, lady,'' he replied. ``Up
and down every aisle.''
</P>
<P>
   I went to the bank last week to deposit a check into my savings
account and noticed that the bank was having a promotion. If you
opened a savings account with $500 or more, the bank would give you
a limited-edition Yankee baseball. My husband and brother are
die-hard fans, so I thought this would be a great gift for one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   I told the teller I did not want to open a new account, but I
would like a baseball. She sent me to customer service, where I
asked to speak to the manager. I was told I'd have to open a new
account to get a baseball.
</P>
<P>
   I was then sent to another customer representative who went into
the office of a vice president to consult. He obviously told her
the same thing the manager told me.
</P>
<P>
   I said, fine, close the account I have now (which I've had for
more than 20 years) and open a new one. I also told her that there
were three customers waiting to open new accounts, and that I could
not believe that she was going to waste 20 or 30 minutes on
paperwork and get no new money. She had to do it that way, she
said. The vice president had instructed her, and that was that.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes later I walked out of the bank with my new
account and Yankee baseball. Maybe next week I'll go back for the
Yankee cap promotion.
</P>
<P>
   _ SAUNDRA JACKSON
</P>
<P>
   Jamie deRoy lives on an upper floor of a building undergoing
repairs to the facade. Recently, she stepped out of the shower and,
naked, walked into her bedroom where her cat was sitting at the
open window. She began opening a clothes drawer when she heard a
man say, ``You are so cute.''
</P>
<P>
   She turned around to find that one of the repair men was working
outside her window. What was the appropriate reaction, she wondered
_ shock or disappointment? He was talking to her cat.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have a cell phone, what's the next best thing?
Tracey Zabar saw a little girl reach into a shopping bag, pull out
a wedge of cheese, hold it to her ear and start chatting.
</P>
<P>
   Carmel Quinn, who some years ago was a fixture on Arthur
Godfrey's television and radio programs, was browsing with a friend
at a Barnes &AMP; Noble bookstore when a woman approached her. ``Excuse
me,'' the woman said, ``I couldn't help hearing you speaking to
your friend. You sound just like Carmel Quinn, and you look like
her, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am Carmel Quinn,'' Ms. Quinn replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no,'' the woman replied. ``You can't be. I'd know her if I
saw her.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'LATE NIGHT WITH CONAN O'BRIEN' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, President Clinton said that the Mideast peace
accord with Arafat and Netanyahu has helped him with his own
personal growth. The President went on to say, 'It's the first time
I've ever been part of a non-sexual threesome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier tonight, Frank Gifford took calls for one hour on
'Larry King Live.' Unfortunately, most of the calls were from
Kathie Lee trying to make sure Frank was really there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA is making final preparations to the Space Shuttle for
John Glenn's historic return to space. Today, they put a bumper
sticker on the shuttle that says, 'Ask me about my
grandchildren.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a recent interview, Woody Allen said that Mia Farrow is an
unfit mother to her adopted children. Woody went on to say, 'As far
as I know, she's not interested in dating any of them.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night in an interview, Frank Gifford said his
extra-marital affair was the most stupid thing he ever got involved
with. Which coincidentally is the same toast he made at his
wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a recent interview, David Duchovny said he likes
pornography. You can read the entire interview in this month's
issue of 'Alien Jugs.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, Hillary Clinton attended a luncheon with 125 gay
and lesbian activists. Hillary said, 'It was fantastic. It's the
first time I've been in a room full of people who haven't had sex
with my husband.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, the FAA announced that due to possible side
effects, pilots should not take Viagra before flying. The FAA said
passengers should be concerned if the pilot comes on the intercom
and says, 'We'll be flying at an altitude of 35,000 feet, six
inches.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today in Cape Canaveral, Fla., the Space Shuttle Discovery
blasted off, taking John Glenn on his historic return to space.
There was one glitch -- when the countdown got to T minus 20, Glenn
yelled out 'Bingo!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``John Glenn went back into space today and just before he left,
he said it's really exciting achieving weightlessness. Which
coincidentally is the same thing Calista Flockhart says.'' ``Before
John Glenn's historic launch in 1962, NASA said to him 'Godspeed
John Glenn.' They struggled with what to say this time but finally
they came up with 'Hang onto your ass, grandpa, here we go.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
