<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9212 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUTU-PINOCHET-RIGHTS-     11-02 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUTU-PINOCHET-RIGHTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE CAN THANK PINOCHET FOR THIS ... BUT NOTHING MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JORGE G. CASTANEDA  
 c.1998 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Augusto Pinochet soon may be back in Chile, or free on bail in
London, having frustrated the efforts of Spanish and subsequently
French, Swiss and Swedish magistrates and citizens, as well as the
wishes of most of his countrymen, who according to recent polls
want to see the dictator tried somewhere, anywhere, for his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But his arrest will still have served a purpose, beyond warming
the hearts of the thousands of friends, relatives and colleagues of
his victims _ men and women who have waited nearly a quarter of a
century for justice and solace.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its ethical and legal implications, the dictator's
detention will have revealed many of the contradictions and deeper
truths about how societies move from authoritarian to democratic
rule, and how they settle scores with a past that never should have
existed.
</P>
<P>
   Both in general and in specific reference to Chile, Pinochet's
predicament raises far more questions than answers _ questions that
years ago should have been asked in Chile and Latin America, and in
countries as dissimilar as Mexico and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called transitions to democracy in Latin America during
the 1980s, in eastern Europe in the late '80s and early '90s, as
well as in Asia and Africa, all rested on a few basic premises that
at the time seemed self-evident. Dictatorships do not just fade
away; military rulers do not simply walk into the sun when they get
bored or tired. Achieving their departure and the overall
dismantling of their regimes, as of one-party systems, implied
providing them with a way out: a safe departure, to a safe haven,
for a safe future.
</P>
<P>
   On some occasions, the political golden handshake of explicit
amnesty or tacitly letting bygones be bygones was accompanied by a
willingness to know, if not to punish. Truth Commissions, Never
Again Commissions, White Books and the like were created and
supported.
</P>
<P>
   But the implicit understanding always was that the personal and
financial integrity of the dictators remain protected and that
details of their policies _ economic in some cases, geopolitical in
others _ be preserved by their democratic successors. In Chile, in
Argentina, in Uruguay, in a certain sense initially in Nicaragua
with Somoza, in South Korea, South Africa and even in some cases in
eastern Europe, this was the deal _ formal and institutionalized in
some cases, de facto in others _ that made democracy possible. It
seemed a small price to pay, a pill not too bitter to swallow, a
necessary and sufficient condition for moving on.
</P>
<P>
   But too many questions simply went unanswered. Who made the
deals? Who did the political leaders truly represent and were those
people ever truly consulted? How freely did the leaders and the led
consent to the deals and how well informed about them were the
countries' most interested parties, that is, the citizens?
</P>
<P>
   Would the arrangement withstand international and historical
scrutiny, particularly of a passionate and critical nature? How
would skeptical or frankly adverse local minorities react? Would
they be able to compromise on the understandings reached by others?
Would those agreements resist the test of time, further
investigations and new revelations? Today's situation in at least
two other countries illustrates the many pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   By now, South Africa's Truth and Amnesty Commission has released
its findings _ albeit, in the absence of all of the nation's
political parties while in the presence of tensions and discomfort
between two old friends and heroes who are true role models for
transitions everywhere: Nelson Mandela and Desmond Tutu.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reasons for today's disenchantment with the
commission's report, its very existence and premises, one fact
clearly stands out. The idea that inspired its creation and work
was that the spirit of national reconciliation guiding the shift
from apartheid to majority rule in South Africa should also prevail
in dealing with the country's past. But this is no longer as
relevant or widespread as when the commission was set up.
</P>
<P>
   What then seemed fair, prudent and tolerant, today appears
callous and cynical; what today is deemed unacceptable and
insensitive then felt cautious and moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was better to demur in asking too many questions back
when Mandela was freed, when negotiations with the white minority
were in full swing and hanging by a thread, when civil war or a
mass exodus by the white community seemed imminent. Perhaps then
was the time to formulate those doubts, rather than now, when
resentment and discontent have set in.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly for Mexico. The country is painfully, desperately,
slowly proceeding with its move toward democratic rule, and while
settling scores with the past is certainly not the most pressing
task, it is one of the most delicate ones. From the student
massacre in Tlatelocolo in 1968 to the localized ``dirty war'' of
the 1970s to the electoral fraud of the 1980s and the corruption of
the 1990s, the PRI has a great deal to answer for.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe, sincerely, that the best solution is to bury the
past, the dead and the bank accounts and move forward. Others think
that some degree of accountability and punishment is indispensable
to ensure that impunity cease being a leitmotif of Mexican
political life.
</P>
<P>
   But no one really knows the cost of each option: whether
forgiving and forgetting is possible, or if burrowing into the past
is unavoidable. The Chilean precedent confounds everyone willing to
think the matter through.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Chile has left its friends and its people perplexed,
perhaps undeservedly. For the past decade, the conventional wisdom
about the country was simple. Moderation and sensibility had
prevailed, national reconciliation had been achieved, successful
economic policies had been pursued. The past decades of
revolutionary turmoil and bloody repression had come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Today we know that while Chile is a more prosperous nation than
before, it is as unequal in wealth and income distribution as ever,
and the polarization of its society is as acute as 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For the country's left, and center, and sympathizers and allies,
as well as for much of international public opinion, Pinochet is
the personification of evil: The man with the dark glasses is as
bad as they come. Yet for a large minority of the population, he is
still the saviour of a nation threatened by heathen communism and
inflationary socialism.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably preferable for Chileans to have uncovered this,
and for the rest of the world to begin to grasp that dealing with
the past is a very complicated matter, and that easy solutions, as
brisk and painless as they may seem, generally do not work.
</P>
<P>
   We can thank the dictator for this, but for nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jorge G. Castaneda, Latin America's leading political
scientist, is the author of the best-selling ``Companero: The Life
and Death of Che Guevara.'' Castaneda lives in New York and Mexico
City and teaches at New York University.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
