<HEADLINE>
WHY THE WOMEN ARE FADING AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By GAIL COLLINS  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    I covered Connecticut state government in the 1970s, and I can
still remember how wonderful the women were. I'm not really
thinking about Ella Grasso, the first
woman-elected-in-her-own-right governor. Grasso still seemed more
like a traditional pol with an extra X chromosome.
 &HT;    The women I really admired were the state legislators, those
battle-scarred survivors of charter-revision and zoning boards who
waded diligently through important but utterly unglamorous issues
like special education and ambulance regulation. They seemed
miraculously devoid of ego.
 &HT;    Next to them, the men looked like squalling children (albeit
children who had all the real political power). I couldn't wait
until the women moved up, so they could run the whole country the
way they ran the subcommittee on inland wetlands.
 &HT;    It didn't quite work out that way. Connecticut never got another
female governor, and Rep. Barbara Kennelly, who is running this
year, trails by stomach-churning margins in the polls. There are
exactly two female elected governors in the country, Christie Todd
Whitman of New Jersey and Jeanne Shaheen of New Hampshire. (A
third, Jane Dee Hull, was elected secretary of state in Arizona and
moved up when Gov. Fife Symington was convicted of fraud.)
 &HT;    New York, which gave us a generation of female political
superstars, has turned into the hellmouth of women in politics. Liz
Holtzman, Bess Myerson, Carol Bellamy, Geraldine Ferraro, Karen
Burstein and Ruth Messinger all crashed and burned. The lucky ones
found jobs in the nonprofit world; the less fortunate wound up
sharing a defendant's table with Sukhreet Gabel's mom.
 &HT;    Just a few years ago, women had good reason to expect a steady
and inevitable progression toward gender parity in politics. In
1992, they scored an unprecedented number of victories in the
national elections, and there was genuine anticipation that some
top women would be on the presidential short list by 1996 _ or
certainly 2000.
 &HT;    But instead, the big names have almost all faded away. Ferraro's
1984 vice-presidential nomination was a high point for the women's
movement, but also the last good day in Ferraro's political career.
Ann Richards of Texas is out of politics. Whitman, once mentioned
as a likely vice-presidential nominee, had a close call last year
against a relatively weak male challenger.
 &HT;    There are nine women in the Senate, and the three freshmen up
for re-election this year - Barbara Boxer, Carol Moseley-Braun and
Patty Murray _ are all in trouble. The one given the best odds is
Murray, of Washington, who is running against another woman.
 &HT;    One reason that women are having trouble winning the top
political offices is that those are the jobs men want to keep. The
offices most accessible to women are those too cheap to be
interesting to male pols. New Hampshire, for instance, not only has
a female governor but also a legislature that's more than 30
percent female. This achievement may have something to do with the
fact that the job pays $100 a year.
 &HT;    The number of women in Congress keeps inching up, but there is
no House woman within a mile of a real leadership role. People who
remember watching Holtzman and Barbara Jordan hold forth during the
House Judiciary impeachment hearings on Richard Nixon may notice
that 20 years later the only woman in the majority party on
Judiciary is Sonny Bono's widow.
 &HT;    ``It almost looks like it could be the end of the last century,
except no one's taken our right to vote away,'' says Pat Schroeder,
the former representative.
 &HT;    Where did all that momentum go, and why? Was the Year of the
Woman just that _ one year? Every political loss is an individual
story, but if you look around, it's easy to come up with reasons
why women seem to be hitting a glass ceiling.
 The Mommy Detour  
 &HT;    Women in politics get a slow start; a study once found that male
legislators were on average 20 years younger, though the gap has
since narrowed. ``Men decide to run in two hours after someone in
the law firm says, 'You've got to run,''' says Cathy Allen, a
political consultant in Olympia, Wash. ``The average woman takes
two years to decide. She'll wait until she has the perfect campaign
manager, the right 17 endorsements, until she's gotten down to a
perfect size 10 and the kids are out of school.''
 &HT;    Mixing child rearing and Congress is tough, since constituents
themselves tend to be big babies, demanding lots of attention and
refusing to make allowances for anyone else's needs. Only one of
the four women who have given birth while in the House has stayed
on.
 &HT;    Reps. Enid Greene Waldholtz of Utah and Susan Molinari of New
York became poster people for Republican family values when in 1995
and 1996, respectively, they gave birth to daughters, but before
the babies were walking, their mothers were out of office.
 &HT;    Molinari, who was married to another House member, grew strapped
for time and money and quit. Greene Waldholtz fell into disgrace
when her husband turned out to be a con man who had illegally
financed his wife's campaign with money obtained from her father.
 Guilt by Association (With Men)  
 &HT;    A current theory holds that a woman stands an excellent chance
of making a presidential ticket in 2000 since both parties will be
looking for candidates who are guaranteed never to be caught with
an intern underneath the telephone table.
 &HT;    But the Greene Waldholtz saga is a reminder that neither gender
is immune to the pitfalls of misplaced love. (During a weepy
five-hour news conference, she denounced her husband and claimed
she knew little about the finances of her campaign and her
household, and didn't even have the access codes to the family
answering machine.)
 &HT;    Moseley-Braun of Illinois is perhaps the most endangered
incumbent senator this year, mainly because of political baggage
stemming from her association with Kgosie Matthews, her former
fiance and campaign manager.
 &HT;    Matthews has been accused of everything from misuse of campaign
funds to sexual harassment to breaking immigration laws. A former
lobbyist for Nigeria, he was presumably also the genius behind
Moseley-Braun's decision to meet with the brutal Nigerian dictator
Gen. Sani Abacha, a gaffe that has become a serious campaign issue.
 It's the Fund-Raising, Stupid  
 &HT;    The issues that women gravitate toward in politics _ day care,
education, child protection _ do not attract a lot of big donors.
Women, the champions of the neighborhood fund-raiser, would
undoubtedly benefit from a campaign-finance system in which
candidates got matching funds and were prohibited from taking huge
donations.
 &HT;    But campaign finance reform keeps receding, and some contrarians
say that Emily's List is one of the reasons. That's near-heresy:
Emily's List, a political action committee that ``bundles''
donations from backers interested in promoting Democratic women in
politics, has done more than any group to put women's campaigns on
an equal financial level with men's.
 &HT;    Still, nearly any discussion of campaign finance reform
inevitably raises the question of what such reform would do to
Emily. Bill Curry, a former adviser to President Clinton, says that
at one White House meeting, Ann Lewis, a Clinton campaign official,
laced into Curry as a ``chauvinist'' for pressing reform. ``The
Emily's List group did more to slow Clinton down on campaign
finance reform than anyone,'' Curry says.
 Left on the Left  
 &HT;    One of the most interesting factoids gleaned from a generation's
worth of survey research on women in politics is that while men
