generally get into the game because they want to help.
 &HT;    ``Most women begin with community concerns, not ambition,'' says
Harriet Woods, the former president of the National Women's
Political Caucus. That impulse to help is in keeping with what
pollsters find about women voters _ they're more likely to support
social spending and activist government.
 &HT;    But perhaps as a result, while the nation in general is trending
toward the right, female candidates tend to be seen as left of
their party's center. Boxer, struggling in California to keep her
Senate seat, is viewed as more liberal than her state's voters, and
Whitman has never been able to win over the right wing that
dominates the Republican Party's organizational base.
 &HT;    Support for abortion rights, usually a plus in general
elections, often hurts Republicans in their primaries. The abortion
issue has always been a rallying point for the women-in-politics
movement, but it's also a problem. Some of the staunchest
abortion-rights advocates will admit that the issue sometimes
overshadows everything else, giving the public the idea that women
are one-note candidates.
 &HT;    ``There's this perception that women's groups are focused
entirely on choice,'' says Ruth Messinger, the recent New York
mayoral candidate. ``It's hard to get voters to understand that a
higher percentage of women means more day care and better HMOs.''
 Time to Play Rough  
 &HT;    Lately, female candidates have been hammering away at the
mom-who-cares theme so hard that it almost trivializes the jobs
they're seeking. Blanche Lambert Lincoln, a former Arkansas
congresswoman who left office after having twins but is now running
for the Senate _ broadcasts commercials that show her balancing the
family checkbook.
 &HT;    Patty Murray won her Senate seat in 1992 as a ``mom in tennis
shoes''; this year, she is being marketed as a ``quietly
effective'' person who used to teach school. Stressing women's
unthreatening, nurturing side makes for good spin, but we may have
gone overboard in idealizing the nonaggressive worker bees.
 &HT;    Politics is still a struggle for power, and anybody who wants
change has to be willing to wrestle money or privilege away from
whoever has it. The point of gender equality isn't to raise women's
self-esteem, or even to pack the Education Committee with people
who love children _ the Education Committee already loves children.
 &HT;    The point is that once women hit a critical mass, large numbers
will lap over into places such as Commerce and Finance, injecting
big-bucks, hard-muscle deliberations with a larger version of
what's important in the world.
 &HT;     c.1998 The New York Times Magazine  
