<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9278 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIEF-LITERATURE-TEX     11-02 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIEF-LITERATURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK OF POEMS, ESSAYS, FICTION ARTICULATE CHAOTIC FEELINGS OF LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by GRIEF-EXCERPTS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've never forgotten the day my brother died. I was 10, and he
was 17. It was the middle of summer, I remember, because it is
impossible to forget a Mississippi summer: hot and indelible like
pain.
</P>
<P>
   Not the sort of pain I knew as a child, but the kind that comes
from grief, the kind I saw in my mother's hot tears, heard in her
wailing that seemed to tumble up from a place so deep inside it
would take a thousand hands to rescue.
</P>
<P>
   That was my first experience with death. Then, before I turned
25, I lost both my mother and father, and the only grandmother I
ever knew. When I was 28, I miscarried my first child.
</P>
<P>
   Neither death nor grief is a stranger to me. And neither are the
words and experiences shared in the soon-to-be-released ``A Broken
Heart Still Beats: After Your Child Dies,'' (Hazelden) a
compilation of excerpts from poems, works of fiction and essays
that articulate the chaos of feelings that comes with such a loss.
</P>
<P>
   The editors, Mary Semel and Anne McCracken, came up with the
idea of the book as they separately, yet simultaneously, found in
literature comfort from the deaths of their own children _ a
comfort that far exceeded anything they had found in traditional
self-help books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started off doing this for ourselves with no thought that
it was a book,'' said McCracken in a telephone interview from her
home in Baltimore. ``After our sons died, Mary and I both had
emotions we couldn't put words to, questions we couldn't frame and
so we independently turned to literature to deal with our grief.''
</P>
<P>
   McCracken, 49, a former journalist, and Semel, 54, a
psychotherapist, were introduced through mutual friends. Before
long, the two began exchanging the literary finds that they found
comforting.
</P>
<P>
   Some two years later, the mothers decided that if it was ``so
helpful to us to find these well-known writers who could put our
feelings into words, it could help other bereaved parents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that anything helps,'' Semel said, ``when you
find some gifted person to put what you're feeling into the right
words, I think there is a kind of catharsis ... solace knowing
others have endured the same pain.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Semel's son Alexander, they called him Allie, was three weeks
short of his 17th birthday when he was killed in an accident.
McCracken's son Jake was only 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life was completely changed when my son was killed,'' Semel
said. ``It was like a bomb dropped on my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Semel and McCracken's book takes parents through the stages of
grief and the coping and healing process that follows the death of
one's child. The excerpted works, accompanied by personal and
poignant memoirs by the editors, came from proven authors who had,
as McCraken says, ``hiked this territory before us, explored it
thoroughly and come back with nuggets of gold.'' The writers _ from
Robert Frost to William Shakespeare, from W.E.B. Du Bois to Anne
Tyler _ validated the mothers' feelings of despair and also their
desire to hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Broken Heart,'' scheduled to be in bookstores across the
country Nov. 14, will do just that for other grieving parents, the
editors believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the strength of the book is that most grief books have
the authoritative voice of one person _ a minister, a rabbi, a
therapist, one family, one death,'' McCracken said. ``This offers a
chorus of voices.''
</P>
<P>
   Including their own.
</P>
<P>
   McCracken recalls, for instance, losing her son as she and her
two young children were ending a visit with her mother in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had had a lovely 10-day visit,'' she remembered. ``We were
about a mile down the road, and a man in the opposing lane had a
seizure, blacked out at the wheel and came straight into my car.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Jake and his 2-year-old sister were in the back seat.
McCracken was critically injured. Her son died some 45 minutes
later from his injuries. It was August 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later, she said: ``It's a permanent wound. You don't
get over (it). You go on with your life. You fashion a new kind of
life with this big hole in it.''
</P>
<P>
   But for those who will come after Semel and McCracken, for those
who know the pain of this ultimate loss, there is, at least, ``A
Broken Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Said McCracken: ``Even if you don't read it from cover to cover,
there is that sense that you are not alone.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
