<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9287 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRANSON-2TAKES-HNS &LR;      11-02 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRANSON-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI'S MUSIC MECCA IS FUN AND FRIENDLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE COOPER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRANSON, Mo. _ If the King of Rock 'n' Roll were alive, he would
have his own theater in Branson.
</P>
<P>
   The bright neon marquee would light up E-L-V-I-S and the music
would play from speakers designed to look like teddy bears and
hound dogs (animals also for sale as Beanie Babies in the Elvis
``Love Me Tender'' Gift Shop).
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Marie and the grandkids would do a few numbers in the first
half of the show, which would be produced by ex-wife Priscilla.
</P>
<P>
   The hits would flow from a nine-piece band, the buses would stop
here and the ``All Shook Up'' crowd would cheer for more _ then
line up for autographs (or sweaty scarves) as the King waved
farewell.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis would fit right in, along with Mel Tillis, Andy Williams,
Bobby Vinton, Mo Bandy, Jim Stafford, the Osmond Brothers, Mickey
Gilley, Charley Pride, Box Car Willie, the Lennon Sisters, Shoji
Tabuchi and Yakov Smirnoff.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Elvis impersonators can be found in this southern
Missouri mecca for music lovers, and Presleys' Country Jubilee (no
relation) is one of the longest-running shows on 76 Country
Boulevard (state Highway 76).
</P>
<P>
   People flock to Branson, a town of some 3,700, at a rate of some
5.5 million a year. The town's traffic problem was once legendary;
but since 1990, $100 million has been invested to open up roads,
taking the burden of bumper-to-bumper off Highway 76.
</P>
<P>
   A tourism market survey by Virginia-based D.K. Shifflet puts
Branson in the top 20 destination cities in the United States,
right up there with San Antonio, Orlando, Las Vegas and Myrtle
Beach, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   While senior citizens make up the bulk of autumn and winter
tourism, especially on bus tours, families flock to Branson in the
spring and summer. The median age for a Branson tourist is 49.2,
compared to 40.9 in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The town has been dubbed ``Las Vegas without the gambling and
drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Add ``and with lower prices'' to that. Branson's show ticket
prices average $22, compared to tickets for big shows in Las Vegas
that can reach $75 to $90.
</P>
<P>
   When you aren't in a theater, there's still a lot to do:
miniature golf, Ripley's Believe It or Not, Silver Dollar City, go
carts, the scenic railway, a winery, golf, shopping, camping,
fishing and water sports on lakes Taneycomo and Table Rock. Nearby
Springfield, Mo., is, after all, the national headquarters of Bass
Pro Shops.
</P>
<P>
   Lake living attracts the big fish and the big names.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Williams was the first non-country entertainer to build a
theater in Branson in 1991, followed quickly by the Osmond Brothers
in 1992 and the Lennon Sisters, who joined the Lawrence Welk
Champagne Theater in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But the man who really packs 'em in is Shoji Tabuchi.
</P>
<P>
   Who?
</P>
<P>
   A Japanese wonder on the violin with a bowl haircut and
disarming, gee-whiz attitude, Tabuchi performs to an often sold-out
crowd from a lavish theater where even the extravagant bathrooms
attract the tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Tabuchi, who moved to the United States 30 years ago, mixes
country, laser lights, ancient Japanese taiko drums and the talents
of his teen-age daughter, Christina.
</P>
<P>
   In heavily accented English, Tabuchi introduces his songs and
steps nimbly as he plays ``In the Mood'' or ``Orange Blossom
Special.''
</P>
<P>
   Branson is a friendly place. No wonder the show-biz types are
putting down roots here. Residents say it isn't unusual to run into
a celebrity at Wal-Mart. Hard to imagine ``Mr. Vegas'' Wayne Newton
in the express line.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Clark was the first big name to have a theater, but it was
owned by someone else. Today the Platters do a $36 dinner show at
the Roy Clark Celebrity Theater.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from his Moon River Theater, Williams
talked about the town and his reasons for building here.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother, Don, was here with Ray Stevens. He was Ray's
manager ... and he asked me to come down (to Branson),'' Williams
said. ``He said, `I think people would come see you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Williams decided to take a chance and open his own theater,
against the advice of his friends, agent and lawyer. Without ever
playing Branson, Williams jumped right in and built a $12 million
theater, a beautiful building with a rough stone exterior and the
``Moon River'' meandering by.
</P>
<P>
   It's right across the street from Bobby Vinton's Blue Velvet
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   At the Blue Velvet, Vinton shares the stage with the Glenn
Miller Orchestra _ no original members, but the sound is true. So
even if you aren't a big Vinton fan, the show offers Big Band
sounds and you can get up and dance.
</P>
<P>
   Vinton belts out such hits as ``Roses are Red'' and ``Blue
Velvet,'' and a newer country song ``Not Enough Roses in Texas''
while exhorting the crowd to shout ``Ho Ho'' after every number.
</P>
<P>
   The color blue and the flower the rose are thematic in the
theater. The lobby is blue, as are the curtains.
</P>
<P>
   And if a lady wants to spend $3.75 on a rose, she can present it
to Vinton and get a kiss in return. (There were no takers during
our show.)
</P>
<P>
   This is high-energy stuff; even Vinton's mother (of
indeterminate age) takes the stage in a short, tight black dress
and does some high kicks singing ``When You're Smiling.'' Besides
Mama, three of Vinton's five children are on stage.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Family is the theme throughout Branson _ family shows, family
members and family prices, and many shows are free for children
younger than 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Presleys pioneered the family show concept back in 1963,
when Lloyd Presley and son, Gary, stopped taking their show on the
road and opened their own theater. In 1967, they moved the show and
became the first to build on Highway 76. Theirs wasn't the first
Branson show _ that honor goes to the Baldknobbers Hillbilly
Jamboree, which began in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Gary Presley's role as ``Herkimer,'' complete with
sparkling overalls, missing teeth and floppy hat, keeps audiences
laughing. His son, Eric, plays clown, too, with ``Cecil.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the jokes are chestnuts, but the crowd of 1,600 loves
them. (On stage, Cecil is dressed as a baby in a carriage. Emcee
says to Herkimer, ``Is he spoiled?'' Herkimer replies, ``No, he
always smells that way.'')
</P>
<P>
   The musical entertainment is top-notch. Current hits, gospel and
old favorites share the stage; the finale is a patriotic ``Proud to
Be an American.'' We saw nine Presleys on stage in a cast of 22,
playing to a full house on a Saturday night. They ranged from
8-year-old Sarah to 74-year-old Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting and greeting every bus, the Presleys talked
business upstairs in their offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had any hit songs of our own, but we get to do
everyone else's,'' Gary Presley muses. When he isn't doing
Herkimer, he plays guitar and brother, Steve, plays the drums.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neat thing about Branson is the variety, (and) everyone
works real hard putting on a good show,'' Steve Presley adds.
</P>
<P>
   Show changes in the last 30 years? More sequins and better
lighting, the Presleys say.
</P>
<P>
   When Tillis signed on in 1990, ``He went back to Nashville and
said, `Guys, you gotta come to Branson,''' says Steve Presley.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Tillis is in his third Branson location and has been
packing in the crowds, thanks to appearances by his daughter, Pam.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone can make it here; Willie Nelson is a case in point.
</P>
<P>
   ``His manager called me up and said, `Why can't we draw 1,500 a
night? We draw 15,000 at a concert,''' Steve Presley says. Nelson,
he says, was doing a three-hour concert while the Branson crowds
want variety.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Williams says, ``People wanted to see Willie Nelson do some
tap dancing and tell some jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of TV variety shows, Williams believes he knows his
Branson audience. His show mixes Broadway, movie themes, film
clips, dancing penguins, an audience Q&AMP;A, acrobats, singers and the
orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   This show is not a nostalgic review of hits. The 69-year-old
singer does newer songs, some made famous by Mariah Carey, Sting
and Bryan Adams. His wonderful voice fills the theater, and the
production numbers, such as ``Circle of Life'' from ``The Lion
King,'' are vibrant and dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   If country is what you want, you'll find it here. There are the
barbecue restaurants along Highway 76, Dolly Parton's Dixie
Stampede where you eat chicken with your hands and watch a rodeo
dinner show, a ride on the Showboat Branson Belle, or a seat at the
Shepard of Hills outdoor drama about life in turn-of-the-century
Ozarks.
</P>
<P>
   Branson has been called a land cruise _ with entertainment and
buffets from one end of town to the other.
</P>
<P>
   Bus tours bring visitors from around the country and Branson
loves its bus tours. The buses get VIP parking and the riders get
special group seating.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainers take time on stage to announce the tours and where
they are from. About 65 percent of Branson business comes from
organized tours, says Cindy Merry, a Branson publicist.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Yakov's American Pavilion, Russian comedian Yakov
Smirnoff jokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know who offered to teach me English? Shoji Tabuchi _ and
he learned it from Mel Tillis.''
</P>
<P>
   Smirnoff takes time to meet and greet all 13 buses in his
parking lot after a full-house Saturday morning show. He also signs
autographs by the exit door and poses cheerfully with fans for
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The bearded comedian _ remembered for his line ``What a
country!'' _ makes the audience part of his show, encouraging jokes
and bringing tourists on stage.
</P>
<P>
   If Branson is the home of American patriotism _ where most every
show in town does gospel or ends with ``God Bless America'' _
Smirnoff is the leader of the band.
</P>
<P>
   His show, ``From Red to Redneck,'' is topical _ from Clinton
jokes (and clean ones at that) to life in these United States
(always punctuated with his new trademark line, ``I'll bet you
never looked at it like that'') to funny asides about life in
Branson (``My middle name is now Bubba'').
</P>
<P>
   He credits Willie Nelson with pointing him toward the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asked to do Farm Aid with Willie, performing in front of
40,000 farmers, and I thought they'd look at me (like I was) from
another planet,'' he says. Smirnoff was a hit and Nelson said he
should consider doing his act in Branson.
</P>
<P>
   With a wife and two young children, Smirnoff is enjoying life in
the family-friendly Ozarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who travel to this destination have a certain
mindset,'' Smirnoff says. The former Los Angeles resident says he
finds the routine of two shows a day in Branson more conducive to
family life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people should come to Branson and see how America
ought to be,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: The airport at Springfield, Mo., is about 40
miles from Branson. Allow an hour's drive-time from the airport to
Branson.
</P>
<P>
   On the bus: A number of companies do bus tours to Branson, which
include hotel and show tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: Ticket prices range from $12 for the Frederick's
Waltzing Waters Show (a grand pianist), to $33 for Andy Williams'
Christmas Show. Dinner shows, such as the Dixie Stampede and the
Roy Clark Celebrity Theater, are in the mid-$30s.
</P>
<P>
   Most shows in Branson go dark by Dec. 19 and re-open in March.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: contact the Branson/Lakes Area Chamber of
Commerce, P.O. Box 1897, Branson, MO 65615; 800-214-3661 or
417-334-4136.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web at www.branson.com. Find the Branson Getaway Guide at
www.bransonworld.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
