<HEADLINE>
N.H. SPECTATORS PAY TRIBUTE TO COURAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for Green Bay and all others needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ The draw was septuagenarian &UR;  &LR; John Glenn's return
to space, but another astronaut was on the minds of a captive,
capacity audience reclining in tilted armchairs inside the
planetarium here.
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of Christa McAuliffe, the Concord High School teacher
who perished in the Challenger explosion in 1986, literally
surrounded 100 people watching the liftoff of the space shuttle
Discovery. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous,'' said Jack Bentz, a great-grandfather who
watched the launch projected on the 40-foot dome of the planetarium
named for McAuliffe. ``I felt that something was going to happen.
But when we saw they were safe, I let out a big sigh.''
</P>
<P>
   But while McAuliffe's fate was on the minds of everyone here,
the memory of her courage and inspiration was stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Auger, 26, of Pembroke, brought her 7-year-old son to
the planetarium to witness history and to honor McAuliffe's
accomplishments as the first US civilian to be selected for space
travel.
</P>
<P>
   Auger recalled watching the Challenger explosion live on
television, but not being aware that the tragedy would be so
historic.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, she knows. So, bearing witness to Glenn's flight
in the city where McAuliffe taught social studies had special
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about Christa,'' Auger said.
</P>
<P>
   As her son paid rapt attention to simulated displays in a
shuttle mockup, Auger described how he had sat ``mesmerized'' by
the ``fire'' that thrust the shuttle skyward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice for him to see this, especially in a place like
this,'' Auger said.
</P>
<P>
   Planetarium director Jeanne Gerulskis decided only this week to
invite the public to a CNN broadcast of the launch.
</P>
<P>
   The planetarium had been deluged by so many calls asking whether
a special event was planned that Gerulskis decided to throw open
the doors free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the callers, Gerulskis said, ``I didn't know if anyone
would come.''
</P>
<P>
   The seats were quickly taken, and an overflow crowd watched the
launch from other venues in the planetarium complex.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the small dome, applause echoed off the curved walls as
Discovery hurtled toward space 19 minutes behind schedule. Until
that point, the planetarium had been eerily quiet as spectators
from infants to 80-year-olds were bathed in images of blue Florida
skies.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast was the first showing of a shuttle launch in the
planetarium, which opened in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, shuttle liftoffs had been carried by small TV
monitors in the complex.
</P>
<P>
   Gerulskis said she hoped that Glenn's journey will rekindle an
interest in the space program that has declined dramatically since
McAuliffe and six crewmates died over the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Vetter, the planetarium's development director, believes
such a resurgence is possible _ even though the scientific basis
for many shuttle missions does not grab the public's interest.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's turnout bolsters that thinking, she said, and helps
reaffirm the planetarium's forward-looking mission instead of
dwelling on past tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Vetter said, the planetarium showed videos of
the Challenger explosion. Now, it was time to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christa would have wanted us to move forward,'' Vetter said.
``Instead of showing Christa's story, we're showing Christa's
vision.''
</P>
<P>
   That vision may have been glimpsed by Melissa Cappucci, a
9-year-old from Concord.
</P>
<P>
   As she left the planetarium with her mother and younger brother,
Melissa talked excitedly of watching her first launch.
</P>
<P>
   She also talked of a new-found goal: ``I would like to walk on
the moon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
