<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9335 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MOM-ESSAY-2TAKES-     11-02 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MOM-ESSAY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLORING THE SCIENCE OF BLAMING MOM FOR EVERYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Alice Dreger is a professor of science and technology at Michigan
State University.)  
(The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By ALICE DREGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This summer I suffered a miscarriage. Although I had no
particular reason to worry that I might miscarry, it probably
featured more prominently as a possibility in my mind than it would
for most women.
</P>
<P>
   I study the history of the biomedical treatment of development
anomalies for a living, and so I knew going into my pregnancy about
the many ways human development can go fatally wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to ease my concerns about future pregnancies, my husband,
a physician, declared it simply a case of what his colleagues call
PPP _ pretty poor protoplasm. It made sense. I tried to believe it.
I should have been able to believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Why, just that week I had been working on an article about
genetic anomalies. When infants have birth defects, well-meaning
doctors often quiz parents, especially mothers, about their habits,
medications, family history and so on. This conveys to parents an
inadvertent message of blame.
</P>
<P>
   About a month later my friend Libby, who studies women's
experiences of pregnancy and birthing, came home from a long trip
to England. ``Out with it,'' she said. ``Tell me all the ways
you're blaming yourself.'' So I started to list the 14 or so ``my
fault'' explanations I had come up with, topping the list with my
personal favorite: A few days before the miscarriage, I
accidentally slammed my fingers in the garage door and a searing
pain went through my whole body. That's when it must have happened.
</P>
<P>
   Libby nodded at each explanation, and even offered a few more.
She had heard it all. Inhaling a sudden blast of jet exhaust. Too
much sexual activity.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, when we had come up with every explanation we could,
Libby said, ``You know, you'll never know why, and it probably
wasn't anything you did.'' I had to agree with her. After all, I'm
a science-minded person. The ``genetic bad luck'' explanation made
sense to me.
</P>
<P>
   I had to agree that, if slamming one's fingers in a garage door
really caused miscarriages, garage door sales would be up and
abortion clinic attendance down. So when Libby absolved me of the
explanations, I felt relief. And then I felt powerless.
</P>
<P>
   I sensed the presence of a kindred spirit lurking behind the
news reports of Judith Rich Harris' new book, ``The Nurture
Assumption: Why Children Turn Out the Way They Do.'' Ms. Harris,
who has two daughters, clearly approached this work from a personal
point of view. She had raised her daughters in roughly the same way
by her account, and yet they had turned out tremendously different.
</P>
<P>
   After much research and thinking, Ms. Harris has concluded, as
her subtitle _ ``Parents Matter Less Than You Think and Peers
Matter More'' _ indicates, that parental influence may not matter
as much as peers' influence. Interviews with her betray the same
combination of feelings I felt after my talk with Libby: relief and
powerlessness.
</P>
<P>
   This strikes me as the trope of middle-class motherhood for the
1990s. Mothers are much less likely to slow down for their
pregnancies, much more likely to continue their careers as their
children develop pre- and postnatally.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us are quite willing to make the in-vogue motherhood
trade-off: a lot less perceived power in terms of our nurturing
abilities in exchange for a lot less guilt. We are happy to be able
to accept the possibility that our children will be fine if we get
them into a good day-care facility. Working mothers I talk with
like Ms. Harris' theory.
</P>
<P>
   But giving up the idea of motherly power takes away some of
motherhood's wonder. After my miscarriage, an older woman said to
me, ``You're so lucky to be living in an age when people won't
blame you for your miscarriage.'' I agreed, but I also thought,
``You were so lucky to think you could control what happened to
your baby.''
</P>
<P>
   A hundred years ago, medical men thought pregnant women had a
lot more power, and they worried about what would happen if that
power were redirected away from motherhood and gentle femininity
and toward careers and political concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Not unusual was the kind of book by C.J. Bayer, published in
1897: ``Maternal Impressions: A Study of Child Life Before and
After Birth, and Their Effect Upon Individual Life and Character.''
Bayer argued in favor of a theory popular for centuries, the belief
that the ``mother's mental influence'' _ her thoughts, desires and
fantasies _ could dispose a gestating child to turn out deformed,
physically or morally.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Bayer used as an example the Pomeroy case in Boston, where ``a
boy aged 14 enticed two children about 3 years old, into a church
and killed them in his insane desire to see blood flow,'' he wrote.
``At the trial, his mother testified that she often went to the
slaughterhouse to see her husband butcher, and it always pleased
her to see blood flowing. ... This was preceding the birth of this
boy,'' the murderer.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer could explain just about every ``abnormal'' child this
way. He anxiously advised prospective mothers to read at once his
chapters on ``Mothers' Longings'' and on epilepsy. (It doesn't seem
to have occurred to Bayer that his book might, by his logic, result
in an epidemic of problem children.)
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, this maternal impression theory held sway.
Mothers were warned not to desire or eat too many cherries, lest
their children come out with cherry-colored birth marks. Conjoined
twins, better known as Siamese twins, were banned from display in
Paris because the government feared it would cause a rash of such
births.
</P>
<P>
   My miscarriage would have been a cinch to explain under this
theory. After all, I was thinking and writing about genetic
anomalies when I miscarried: maternal impressions, pretty poor
protoplasm. During the next pregnancy, I should perhaps follow
Bayer's recommendation: Sit quietly, ``use judgment, and do not
brood over any particular idea.'' In other words, give up being a
teacher, writer, thinker. Not surprisingly, Bayer didn't believe
women should work outside the home and he didn't even want them to
socialize much during their pregnancies. (Parties have a way of
inducing wild desires.)
</P>
<P>
   One sort of picture, in Bayer's utopia, teams of socially
responsible citizens fanning out across the land to distract
pregnant mothers.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, I'll take the world of the stuff-just-happens
PPP theory, which lets me keep working. And if I should get lucky
with the next batch of protoplasm and have a child, and then, after
all, turn out to be a neglectful mother, and my child blames me?
Back to the science well for one more hit of guilt alleviation.
</P>
<P>
   A new gene theory, published in September, suggests that good
maternal behavior has a genetic basis, and that a mother's father
gives her those genes _ assuming the mother's mother doesn't shut
out his contribution. So this theory would allow me, in an
equal-opportunity twist, to blame my father for failing to endow me
with good maternal behavior. Or should I blame my mother for
shutting out his contribution?
</P>
<P>
   To say that middle-class mothers are generally shifting in the
direction of the guiltless-but-powerless self-image is not to say
that people have stopped worrying about how much power mothers
have. A new law in South Dakota subjects women who drink during
pregnancy to severe penalties. Clearly heavy drinking during
pregnancy leads to dangers like fetal alcohol syndrome. But where
are we going when we start to police mothers' prenatal power? Will
we return slowly to a time of blatant negative eugenics, in which
mothers' and fathers' genetic powers are policed, too? Would women
with no nurturing gene have to take parenting classes before having
children?
</P>
<P>
   I would feel less inclined to believe that we're on a slippery
slope toward genetically policed pregnancies if the discovery of
the ``gene of the week'' didn't always seem to carry an encoded
instruction about genetic guilt _ who should be blamed for passing
on or not passing on the featured gene.
</P>
<P>
   I am left with two questions and two tentative answers. First,
will there ever be a way to enjoy maternal power without suffering
maternal guilt? Probably not, because power is supposed to come
with responsibility, and responsibility entails guilt when
something goes wrong. Genetics only makes this formula more
evident.
</P>
<P>
   Second, how often is a theory accepted and disseminated
primarily because it fits our social and personal needs? In other
words, are perfectly viable theories sometimes aborted or neglected
not because they have inherent problems with evidence or logical
coherence, but because we just do not want them? When our desired
relationships to our physical offspring are threatened, I would
have to answer yes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
