<HEADLINE>
`DOTCOMS' GIVE WOLFE EARLY BOOST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (e and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Wolfe's new novel, ``A Man in Full,'' won't be on bookstore
shelves until Nov. 6, but it is already a marketing phenomenon,
racking up thousands of advance orders on the ``dotcoms,'' the
book-selling Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   And publishing industry watchers predict that with a 1.2-million
copy launch, it will debut at No. 1 on the first-possible New York
Times best-seller list _ probably that of Nov. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect it will be No. 1,'' said Daisy Maryles, executive
editor of Publisher's Weekly, the trade magazine. ``People wait for
a Tom Wolfe. He doesn't write every year.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, the unreleased ``A Man in Full'' was No. 2 in
sales at Amazon.com, the Seattle-based virtual bookstore, edged out
only by the latest Oprah Winfry book club selection, ``Midwives,''
by Vermonter Chris Bohjalian.
</P>
<P>
   While Amazon.com refuses to give out sales figures on individual
titles, public relations director Bill Curry said ``it's not
unusual to see a book go to No. 1 on our bestseller list before the
book is in the stores.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Amazon.com sales are being rung up without heavy
promotion _ other than the 40 percent discount it gives to all the
``selected featured titles,'' shipping not included. On Friday,
Curry noted, the Wolfe book was not being promoted on either of its
high-profile sites, its Homepage or its Daily Scoop.
</P>
<P>
   But, Curry added, the hourly updating of its sales ranking acts
like an instant bestseller list, letting readers know ``what's
going on in the world right now, not last week or a month ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly heavy advance sales have been registered on Amazon.com
for other blockbuster novels earlier this year _ John Grisham's
``Street Lawyer,'' Tom Clancy's ``Rainbow Six,'' and Stephen King's
``Bag of Bones.''
</P>
<P>
   As one indication of the widespread early interest in ``A Man in
Full,'' publisher Farrar, Straus and Giroux has moved the
publication date up from Nov. 12 to Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things broke faster than they thought,'' said Maryles
_ among them the novel being chosen as a finalist for the 1998
National Book Awards, a Time magazine cover story for its Nov. 2
issue, and jump-the-gun reviews in nationally circulated papers
such as the New York Times and Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   In the industry, a 1.2 million-copy launch is big, but not
monumental. This year, Grisham's ``Street Lawyer'' had a 2.8
million first printing, Clancy's ``Rainbow Six'' 2 million, and
King's ``Bag of Bones'' 1.31 million.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of all the buzz and hype is a 742-page novel _ the
kind that reviewers will inevitably call ``sprawling'' _ set in
Atlanta. It involves an aging real estate developer facing the loss
of his 28,000-acre plantation when his business ventures go sour.
Just as Wolfe's 1987 bestseller, ``Bonfire of the Vanities,'' was
set in motion by a racial incident, ``A Man in Full'' takes off
when a local black football hero is accused of raping the daughter
of a prominent white businessman.
</P>
<P>
   The National Book Award nomination came as a surprise to many
editors and reviewers because review copies did not become
available until several days after the finalists were announced
Oct. 14. The aggressive prepublication marketing of ``A Man in
Full'' is feeding off the nomination, as well as the Time cover.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com's ``book detail page'' notice states that the book
``is not yet available. You may still order this title. We will
ship it when it is released by the publisher.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Brown, vice president of marketing at Farrar, Straus,
said that under its agreements with distributors, ``all the dotcoms
will begin fulfilling their advance orders on the same day we let
the bookstores put it on sale.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
