<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-EYE-LASER-ART-words(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASERS MAY SOON BE USED TO THREAT FARSIGHTEDNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (af)  
 By ANNE EISENBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sharon McCormack of White Salmon, Wash., loved windsurfing the
Columbia River Gorge, but she had a problem on the big jumps: Her
contact lenses washed out. ``Or I got dust under a lens,'' she
said. ``That's incredibly painful.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCormack solved the problem by having laser surgery to
correct her nearsightedness. More than 400,000 laser vision
procedures will be done this year, industry sources say, most of
them for nearsightedness, or myopia, like Ms. McCormack's. But next
year, farsighted surfers and others may be having laser surgery,
too.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the Ophthalmic Devices Panel of the Food and Drug
Administration recommended approval of a laser to treat
farsightedness, or hyperopia.
</P>
<P>
   Final approval by the agency is expected by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that Americans will be treated for farsightedness
with lasers next year,'' said Dr. Scott MacRae, associate professor
of ophthalmology at the Casey Eye Institute at the Oregon Health
Sciences University in Portland. MacRae has also served on the FDA
Ophthalmic Devices Panel.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two lasers used to treat myopia and myopia with astigmatism
are approved by the federal agency. The basic procedures,
photorefractive keratotomy (PRK) and laser in-situ keratomileusis
(Lasik), remove tiny bits of the cornea to flatten it so light
focuses more precisely on the retina. PRK shapes the cornea's
surface; Lasik, a mid-corneal method, vaporizes or ablates the
middle of the cornea rather than the front to improve focus.
</P>
<P>
   Farsightedness, however, is more difficult to correct, MacRae
said. In the new procedure, a laser will be used to sculpture the
area in the periphery of the cornea, in effect, making the center
steeper and bringing the focus from behind the retina to the
retina.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're doing for the nearsighted is a crewcut to the
cornea,'' MacRae said. ``For the farsighted, you have the trickier
job of steepening the cornea.''
</P>
<P>
   A variation of farsightedness that the new procedures will not
treat is presbyopia, the gradual, age-related condition of suddenly
fuzzy print and the necessity of reading glasses. ``About the time
you turn 40, the eyes start to lose their capability to focus
sharply for near vision,'' said Dr. Jeffrey Weaver, director of the
Clinical Care Center at the American Optometric Association in St.
Louis. ``These new laser procedures won't affect presbyopia,
because the condition is not due to the cornea. It comes about as
the lens loses its ability to accommodate or focus sharply for near
vision, a loss of elasticity that is inevitable as we age.''
</P>
<P>
   The new laser methods to treat farsightedness are expected to
cost at least $4,000 and probably will not be covered by most
insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver cautions that any laser treatment should be approached
thoughtfully. ``PRK and Lasik for myopia have been very
successful,'' he said. ``People are usually quite happy with the
outcomes, unlike older surgeries like radial keratotomy.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how successful a procedure, though, risks remain.
``Surgeons doing Lasik actually slice off the front surface of the
eye, flip it back, do the laser procedure, and then return the flap
to its place,'' Weaver said. ``There's always the small possibility
that the flap may become dislodged. You have to weigh the risk
against how much you want to get rid of your glasses or contact
lenses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
