<P>
   &UR; THE SAME BRANDY IN THREE DIFFERENT BOTTLES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,300 words) Includes a color slide of Brandy with Jennifer Love
Hewitt in a scene from ``I Still Know What You Did Last Summer.'' &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN SPELLING &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Brandy Norwood _ known professionally simply as Brandy _ is a
one-girl entertainment conglomerate: Star of UPN's hit sitcom
``Moesha,'' star of the recently released album ``Never Say
Never,'' co-star of ``I Still Know What You Did Last Summer,''
opening Nov. 13. And, believe it or not, she's still only 19.
Brandy talks with New York-based free-lance writer Ian Spelling
about the new film, co-star Jennifer Love Hewitt, why it took her
four years to follow up her multiplatinum debut album ``Brandy''
and why she's having trouble finding a boyfriend. (slugged:
BC-BRANDY-IN-I-STILL-KNOW-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF, priority code w,
category code e) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHE'S STRAIGHT, HE'S GAY, THE RATINGS ARE BOFFO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,300 words) Includes a color slide of Debra Messing and Eric
McCormack in a scene from ``Will &AMP; Grace.'' &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; From Canadian TV Guide &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The most remarkable thing about NBC's new sitcom, ``Will &AMP;
Grace,'' is not that it's been a ratings hit in a year when most
new shows have collapsed, or even that it's holding its own against
formidable competition from ``Ally McBeal'' and ``Monday Night
Football.'' It's that there's been virtually no controversy over a
show whose two main characters _ roommates, no less _ are a
straight woman and a gay man. Stars Eric McCormack and Debra
Messing talk with Canadian TV Guide editor-in-chief Christopher
Loudon about the series, why they think viewers have accepted the
gay Will when they resisted a lesbian character on last year's
``Ellen,'' when and if the show will explore such dicey topics as
dating and gay sex, and why they feel the show can best serve the
gay community by being funny. (slugged:
BC-WILL-&AMP;-GRACE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF, priority code w, category code
e) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMRYN MANHEIM: THE NEXT BIG THING, AND PROUD OF IT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,400 words) Includes a color slide of Camryn Manheim in a scene
from ``The Practice.'' &QL; 
 &UR; By CINDY PEARLMAN &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; World rights except Chicago &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't call her ``big-boned.'' Don't call her ``amply
proportioned.'' Camryn Manheim is fat, and she doesn't mind saying
so. And why should she, since the only thing about her bigger than
her size is her talent? Fresh from winning an Emmy for her role in
``The Practice'' and already on multiplex screens in Todd Solondz's
controversial ``Happiness,'' Manheim talks with Chicago-based
free-lance writer Cindy Pearlman about the new movie, the series,
her Emmy win, the diet-pills episode that almost killed her and
why, at 37, she's finally comfortable with who and what she is.
(slugged: BC-CAMRYN-MANHEIM-IN-THE-PRACTICE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF,
priority code w, category code e) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEBE NEUWIRTH'S LATEST BRUSH WITH GENIUS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,400 words) Includes a black-and-white slide of Bebe Neuwirth
with Judy Davis in a scene from ``Celebrity.'' &QL; 
 &UR; By JEANNE WOLF and SHEP MORGAN &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Bebe Neuwirth has two Emmy Awards from ``Cheers'' and a Tony
apiece for ``Sweet Charity'' and ``Chicago,'' but all anyone wants
to ask her about is a scene in Woody Allen's new film,
``Celebrity,'' opening nationwide Nov. 20, in which she utilizes a
banana in giving Judy Davis a lesson in oral-sex technique.
Neuwirth talks with Hollywood-based free-lance writers Jeanne Wolf
and Shep Morgan about the new film, her memories of ``Cheers,'' how
she enjoyed working with the idiosyncratic Allen and why she
herself is both comfortable and uncomfortable with her own fame.
(slugged: BC-BEBE-NEUWIRTH-IN-CELEBRITY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF,
priority code w, category code e) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACE VALUE: DEATH WARMED OVER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By RICARDO CASTANEDA &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In this new cartoon feature from The New York Times Syndicate,
artist Ricardo Castaneda offers an intriguing take on Brad Pitt as
Death in his new film, ``Meet Joe Black.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEXT WEEK IN STARBEAT: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cameron Diaz tells Cindy Pearlman about her new film, ``Very Bad
Things.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Reeve tells Ian Spelling about his new television
movie, a remake of the Hitchcock classic ``Rear Window.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Norton discusses his controversial new film, the skinhead
thriller ``American History X,'' in an interview with Jeanne Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong action star Sammo Hung talks about his hit new series,
``Martial Law,'' in an interview with Andrew Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   And in a Face Value special, cartoonist Vance Lehmkuhl offers
his offbeat take on Cameron Diaz in ``Very Bad Things.''
