<HEADER>
A9424 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRANDY-IN-I-STILL-KNO     11-02 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRANDY-IN-I-STILL-KNOW-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SAME BRANDY IN THREE DIFFERENT BOTTLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Brandy with Jennifer Love Hewitt in a
scene from ``I Still Know What You Did Last Summer.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's all about self-expression for Brandy Norwood.
 &HT;    ``I feel that I'm definitely expressing myself when I sing,''
says the multitalented 19-year-old, who uses the single name Brandy
professionally. ``With acting, I'm not really expressing myself _
I'm expressing myself through another character. Singing is all me.
It's all about the way I feel about life.''
 &HT;    Nevertheless, she says, ``If somebody put a gun to my head and
said I could only sing or act, I'd act. First of all, I could play
a singer, and second I could do the soundtracks for my movies.''
 &HT;    She may express herself as a singer, and she does have a new hit
album, ``Never Say Never,'' but Brandy has a lot more to offer.
Last year, she co-starred with Whitney Houston and Whoopi Goldberg
in a high-rated television-film version of Rodgers &AMP; Hammerstein's
``Cinderella,'' and she's a household name as the star of the
popular television show, ``Moesha.''
 &HT;    Rounding out the triple-threat lineup is a movie career. Her
first feature, ``I Still Know What You Did Last Summer,'' slashes
into theaters nationwide on Nov. 13.
 &HT;    No one will confuse ``I Still Know'' with the lighthearted fun
of ``Moesha,'' or for that matter with ``Cinderella.'' Brandy's
character, Karla, and her college roommate Julie (Jennifer Love
Hewitt) get chased around the Bahamas by the same killer fisherman
who tried to take a hook to Julie in ``I Know What You Did Last
Summer'' (1997).
 &HT;    ``It was very different from anything else I'd done, because
there was a lot of physical work I had to do,'' Brandy says by
cellular phone from Los Angeles. ``Karla's a kickboxer, and I had
to have this tough-girl attitude, and I also had to have this sexy,
sassy type of image that I'm not used to.
 &HT;    ``I'm more used to being like Moesha or Cinderella or Brandy,''
she says. ``Karla is a really different kind of girl. If I met a
girl like her, I'd want to be her friend because she's so cool.
She's not corny, but she's down to earth. She loves her best friend
and she protects her.''
 &HT;    On the set, Brandy and Hewitt hit it off, which makes perfect
sense. They're both young and beautiful, they're both
actress/singers with hit television shows and they both know the
ups and downs of life as a teen idol.
 &HT;    ``When Love and I meet up, we're always goofing around,'' Brandy
says. ``Once or twice we talked about the pressures of having to be
role models. People look up to us and expect us to be such good
girls, so squeaky clean, and sometimes we want to be able to make
mistakes.''
 &HT;    With ``I Still Know'' ready for release, it's back to ``Moesha''
for Brandy. The sitcom, now in its fourth season, is the fledging
UPN network's highest-rated series.
 &HT;    ``Everybody's getting along, having a good time,'' Brandy says.
``I'm really happy that I'm still doing TV, because at one point I
wanted to just go on and sing.
 &HT;    ``I'd like to do the show until the writers can't come up with
anything else,'' she says cheerfully. ``I don't want to put a time
limit on it, because I just might get what I ask for, and I might
not want that.
 &HT;    ``I change my mind every other week,'' she adds, ``so it's
better if I just keep working and do it until they can't write for
Moesha anymore.''
 &HT;    Beyond the film and the series, there's ``Never Say Never,'' an
Atlantic Records release that is her first album since 1994's
multiplatinum disk, ``Brandy.'' Released in June, ``Never''
features the hit single ``The Boy Is Mine,'' a duet with her fellow
single-named pop sensation, Monica.
 &HT;    She let four years pass between albums, Brandy says, for the
simplest and oldest of reasons: fear of the sophomore jinx.
 &HT;    ``I was so used to acting and everybody was so used to seeing me
on TV that I was scared to come back out with a new album,'' she
says.
 &HT;    ``Everybody says that the second album is what really counts,''
she adds. ``You can have one hit album, but when you come back you
will not do as well as you did the first time. So that's the test,
the second album.
 &HT;    ``To come back so strong, to have people like Monica and Mase
work on it with me, to have producers like Rodney Jerkins and David
Foster, to have the record company behind me, was great,'' the
young star says. ``So I'm blessed.''
 &HT;    When ``Moesha'' finishes production for the season, probably in
April, Brandy hopes to squeeze in a short concert tour in support
of ``Never Say Never.'' She's already at work on ``Double
Platinum,'' a television movie whose mother-daughter storyline
pairs two generations of pop stardom: Diana Ross and Brandy. And
then there's the seemingly inevitable ``I Still Know III,''
assuming that the current sequel merit another follow-up and should
a script meet with all the right approvals.
 &HT;    Away from the glare of the spotlight, Brandy lives with her
parents in Los Angeles. She hangs out with friends whenever
possible and, since ending a relationship with Boyz II Men singer
Wanya Morris, has kept her eyes open for boyfriend prospects.
 &HT;    ``Do you have anybody you could hook me up with?'' she asks
playfully.
 &HT;    She's kidding, but it's a complicated subject. A 19-year-old
with her own television show, movie deal and record contract can't
just mingle at a party. It's one of a great many teen-age things
that Brandy has had to deal with.
 &HT;    ``I really don't feel like I've missed anything,'' she says.
``Sometimes my social life gets a little crammed and I can't do it
like I want to do it. But it doesn't matter, because I bring my
social life into what I do, into whatever I'm working on.
 &HT;    ``I hated junior high school and high school, because nobody
liked me,'' she adds. ``So I'm glad something took me out of that.
I didn't think those days would ever end. I thought I'd go through
the torture, get out of high school, go to college and all of that.
 &HT;    ``But I always had the dream that I was going to be something,
that I'd be someone.''
 &HT;    If millions of albums sold, starring roles in television shows
and feature films, and countless adoring fans a somebody make,
Brandy has definitely accomplished that goal.
 &HT;    ``I'm somebody people look up to,'' she says. ``That's a key
thing, that I'm appreciated.
 &HT;    ``I feel that people appreciate me and really take what I do
seriously,'' the actress says. ``That's why I take what I do so
seriously _ I know there are a lot of people depending on me and
counting on me to do the right thing.
 &HT;    ``I want to do this for a long time,'' Brandy says. ``Then
again, I want to have a family. I'll have to take a break, do that
and come back.
 &HT;    ``I want to come in and out of this business, if the business
will let me.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
