<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9425 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILL-&AMP;-GRACE-STARBEAT     11-02 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILL-&AMP;-GRACE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE'S STRAIGHT, HE'S GAY, THE RATINGS ARE BOFFO 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Debra Messing and Eric McCormack in a
scene from ``Will &AMP; Grace.'' 
 By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON  
 c.1998 Canadian TV Guide  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The revolution was indeed televised, but hardly anyone noticed.
</P>
<P>
   This past September, NBC launched ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' an
unorthodox sitcom about two best friends/roommates who happen to be
a gay man and a straight woman _ and nobody raised an eyebrow.
</P>
<P>
   No advertiser boycotts, no hassles with network censors, no
fire-and-brimstone condemnation from fundamentalist preachers.
Nothing but rave reviews and millions of viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite the show's initial success _ it's already crushed
one Monday-night competitor, ``The Brian Benben Show,'' and is
holding its own against formidable opponents ``Ally McBeal'' and
``Monday Night Football'' _ producers David Kohan and Max Mutchnick
remain caught in a dilemma: If it's perceived that they're
soft-pedaling their character's gayness, gay advocates will scream
foul. If the show becomes preachy or overtly political, its
hard-won audience might flip back to ``Ally'' or football.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest episode in a decades-old debate: Is television's
responsibility simply to entertain or also to inform and educate?
</P>
<P>
   Eric McCormack, the Toronto-born actor who plays Will _ and who,
for the record, is straight _ thinks the answer is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why push the envelope if it's going to put you off the air in
six episodes?'' he says. ``It makes no sense. Our producers very
much want the show to be around for a long time. They want the gay
audience to love it, they want the straight audience to love it,
they want the old and the young to love it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody asks, `When are we going to see two men kiss? When
are we going to see two men in bed?' And the answer is, when it's
time. Not time for the network, but time for Will.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that's bothered me in all of the critical
reaction was how people responded to Will having just ended a
relationship as `convenient' _ like the writers were hiding behind
it,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is about Will and Grace. So of course it's
convenient,'' the actor says. ``It's actually brilliant _ a
brilliant way to explore this friendship for a while and get them
to the point where the audience is saying, `Gee, I want them to
both start dating nice people _ when are they both gonna find a
nice fella?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually we will break barriers,'' he promises, ``and we
will surprise people. But we're not going to do it overnight,
because I don't think anybody wants that immediately. They want to
love the characters first.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuddled next to McCormack on his dressing-room couch, co-star
Debra Messing nods in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the smartest way to launch the show,'' she says. ``You
can't root for the characters until you know them, and it was so
clever to have both of us out of relationships, so the audience
could fall in love with our friendship and make an investment in
these characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, accusations continue to fly that the series is ducking
the hard ones. Will is a successful, self-employed lawyer, so
there's little risk of workplace discrimination. And to date the
show has been populated only with characters who embrace Will's
lifestyle _ he hasn't had to deal with homophobia or aggressively
defend his way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, anything the audience might perceive as
stereotypically gay behavior has been deflected onto Will's best
friend, Jack (Sean Hayes), who's much more the standard ``flaming''
gay.
</P>
<P>
   McCormack doesn't see Jack as an evasion, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``A stereotype is dangerous when it stands alone, when it is the
only example of what's shown, when the gay community is represented
solely by one character who's limp-wristed and lisping,'' he says.
``But by having a Will, we earn a Jack.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of flamboyant characters like Jack in the gay
community,'' he adds. ``They're not ashamed of themselves, nor
should they be. But if that's the only thing you see, the rest of
the community says, `There's more to us than that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tendency to think of all gay people as Jacks,'' the
actor says. ``If gay people are also like Will, well, then it could
be your brother or your dad or your son. That's something very
scary to the average person, that a really terrific lawyer and a
really terrific friend could also be gay. And those people need to
learn that they shouldn't be so scared.''
</P>
<P>
   But the main point, McCormack says _ wary of the controversy
that enveloped ABC's ``Ellen'' last year after the title character
``came out'' as a lesbian and the series became heavily gay-themed
_ is that ``Will &AMP; Grace'' will continue to stress entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it will be is a show with lots of good-looking guys,'' he
says with a laugh, ``because all four of the main characters want
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   And it really is a four-person show, despite its two-person
title. McCormack and Messing already have a relaxed, innately
humorous chemistry, and Hayes has flashed Emmy potential with his
unbridled yet poignantly sympathetic portrayal of Jack. The series'
fourth star, Megan Mullavy as Grace's well-connected but hopelessly
inept assistant Karen, is emerging as the best scene-stealer since
``Cybill's'' Christine Baranski.
</P>
<P>
   Most valuable of all, McCormack says, is the creative guidance
of Kohan and Mutchnick, who rival ``Seinfeld's'' Larry David and
Jerry Seinfeld in their ability to craft a quartet of characters
who are as believable as they are lovable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max and David are the voices of these characters,'' McCormack
says. ``Recently someone asked Max what qualified the two of them
to write this show, and he said, `Well, I'm a gay man, and Dave's a
straight woman.'''
</P>
<P>
   Messing laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there wasn't one gay person on the creative staff, I'd be
concerned,'' McCormack adds. ``But there's Max, who's gay, and
David, who's not. Together they really are Will and Grace. They've
created this landmark television relationship that's so new and so
rich and ground-breaking _ but funny first.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the two of them around, I know I don't have to question a
single thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The series has already started to take ``baby steps'' toward
dealing more directly with gay issues, McCormack adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Halloween episode,'' he says, ``Will's biggest client,
Harlan, asks Will and Grace to baby-sit his two children without a
second thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we filmed it,'' the actor says, ``I didn't think anything
of it. Then afterward Max said to me, `Do you know what an
important statement this is? That a conservative Texan would
automatically trust a gay man with his kids?'
</P>
<P>
   ``So we may not be sending out powerful political messages, but
you can't dismiss what we're doing as fluff, either.''
</P>
<P>
   For Messing, the show's impact has already been proven _ not by
big ratings, but by a single piece of fan mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most moving thing that's happened so far,'' the actress
says, ``is that I got a letter from this 18-year-old guy in
Arizona, who said, `I just came out three months ago, and my
mother's pretty OK with it, but my best friend won't speak to me
anymore, and I really wish I had a Grace in my life.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That, to me, was truly amazing. That's really great.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Loudon is the editor-in-chief of Canadian TV
Guide, based in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
