<HEADER>
A9426 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMRYN-MANHEIM-IN-THE     11-02 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMRYN-MANHEIM-IN-THE-PRACTICE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMRYN MANHEIM: THE NEXT BIG THING, AND PROUD OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Camryn Manheim in a scene from ``The
Practice.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Rosie O'Donnell isn't noted for subtlety.
 &HT;    The day after Camryn Manheim won a Best Supporting Actress Emmy
for her role on ABC's ``The Practice,'' a bouquet of flowers from
the morning maven arrived in Manheim's dressing room.
 &HT;    ``Rosie wrote, `Fat Girls Rule!''' Manheim whoops.
 &HT;    In this case, bigger is better, and Manheim doesn't mind talking
about it. She doesn't call herself ``big-boned'' or ``amply
proportioned'' or any other euphemism _ but what else would you
expect from a woman who once wrote and starred in a one-woman show
called ``Wake Up! I'm Fat''?
 &HT;    Manheim is the anti-Ally McBeal, and she's reveling in it.
During an interview in her dressing room she gets a call from her
publicist, announcing that People wants her for an upcoming cover.
 &HT;    ``All right!'' Manheim screams into the receiver. ``This is just
so cool!''
 &HT;    Television's new big star is even on the big screen nowadays,
appearing in Todd Solondz's controversial new film ``Happiness'' as
an enigmatic loner.
 &HT;    ``It's really the darkest role I've ever done,'' she says, ``but
I loved the script. Todd is a brilliant director, and I thought it
would be fun to explore someone who is really messed up.''
 &HT;    When she won the Emmy, the 37-year-old dedicated her award to
``all the fat girls out there.'' And she wasn't kidding.
 &HT;    ``I am the girl who was told she would never make it in
Hollywood,'' she says, her voice cracking. ``I was told that there
was no place for fat girls.''
 &HT;    Manheim laughs.
 &HT;    ``I guess it's a good thing that I've always been someone who
can't accept no for an answer,'' she says.
 &HT;    Believe it or not, Manheim says, she didn't get teased as a
child. And why should she? She was a thin little girl, she says.
Popular. Accepted. Happy. It was her sister who was overweight.
 &HT;    ``When I was 13, we swapped,'' she says. ``She got thin and I
got fat.''
 &HT;    The catalyst was the family's move to Los Angeles, she says.
 &HT;    ``I overate because we moved from the East Coast to California,
where people shopped for groceries in bikinis,'' she says. ``It was
all about being skinny in L.A. That freaked me out. I think to
prevent having to show off my body, I built up my own defense
system.''
 &HT;    Her parents weren't supportive, she admits.
 &HT;    ``They claimed it was for my own benefit,'' she recalls. ``They
didn't want my life to be hard. But it wounded me greatly to think
I wasn't lovable just the way I was. It became a cruel circle of
`We love you _ lose weight,' and me saying, `If you love me, leave
me alone.'''
 &HT;    High school was a nightmare, the actress adds.
 &HT;    ``Every teen girl magazine told me my body was not desirable and
it was ugly,'' Manheim says. ``At age 37, the fact that I have any
self-worth is a miracle.''
 &HT;    She tried to lose weight many times, but always failed.
 &HT;    ``The only diet program that ever worked for me was
amphetamines,'' she adds. ``I lost about 20 pounds very quickly.''
 &HT;    She also almost overdosed on the pills.
 &HT;    ``Finally I said, `Enough is enough,''' she recalls. ``I wasn't
going to risk my health to wear size-eight jeans. It just wasn't
worth the cost.
 &HT;    ``I figured I had two choices when it came to Hollywood,''
Manheim says. ``I could conform and be the standard of beauty, or I
could do some real soul-searching and say, `Love yourself and your
talent, no matter what size you are.'''
 &HT;    In Hollywood she has experienced size discrimination, she says,
but she doesn't have horror stories.
 &HT;    ``Once I would get a part, it wouldn't be a case of makeup
artists talking about hiding my double chin,'' she says. ``I'm a
big girl. I am what I am. There is no way to hide it.
 &HT;    ``If a movie or TV show wants me, then they get all of me. I
have nothing to hide.''
 &HT;    Working days as an interpreter for the deaf, Manheim began
making the rounds to audition, and began to snag an occasional
television role.
 &HT;    ``I spent the early part of my acting career playing the best
friend of the pretty girl, because casting agents decided I was
sexually undesirable at this weight, but I was also
non-threatening,'' she says. ``I think the line I've uttered more
than anyone else in this business is, `Really? Then what
happened?'''
 &HT;    She got away from best-friend roles in a short stint on ``All My
Children.''
 &HT;    ``I was the prison warden,'' she says. ``I was always made up to
look about 10 years older and matronly. Drab clothes, no makeup. I
was told that I was lucky to get these roles.''
 &HT;    Finally the lack of opportunities for major parts led Manheim to
write ``Wake Up! I'm Fat,'' the hit Off-Broadway show which she is
now expanding into a book. In turn, the show led to an audition for
``The Practice,'' and a surprise.
 &HT;    Attorney Ellenor Frutt isn't a best-friend role, the actress
found. She wears makeup, dresses beautifully and even has a sex
life.
 &HT;    ``That was a real breakthrough,'' Manheim says. ``For years, in
Hollywood no one wanted to see a big woman kiss somebody. The
attitude was that big women aren't sexy and men don't love them.
I'm trying my best to destroy that myth.''
 &HT;    Which leads to her biggest ambition for Ellenor.
 &HT;    ``I'd love to sleep with Dylan McDermott's character on the
show,'' she says with a devilish smile. ``Hell, he has slept with
everyone else in that law office. I figure I'm next.
 &HT;    ``I'd also love to have a serious, passionate love affair with a
sex symbol in a film,'' she says. ``That would be ground-breaking.
I wish Hollywood would think about me with Tom Cruise or Kevin
Costner. I think real women would especially be jazzed to see it.''
 &HT;    In real life the tabloids have linked Manheim with actor/dancer
Gregory Hines, with whom she is co-starring in an independent film
called ``The Tick Code,'' but she won't comment. She'd rather talk
about motorcycling.
 &HT;    ``There is just something so liberating about getting on your
bike and hitting the open road,'' Manheim says. ``You have the wind
in your hair and your cares seem to dissolve. Motorcycles are my
favorite thing in the world.''
 &HT;    When she heard she'd been nominated for an Emmy, she turned to
her Harley to settle down.
 &HT;    ``I cried like a baby when I heard the news,'' she recalls. ``To
calm myself down, I went for a ride.''
 &HT;    And the ride hasn't stopped since. On Emmy night, she could
hardly believe she'd won.
 &HT;    ``My date had to nudge me and say, `It's you,''' she says,
laughing. ``It just didn't seem right. It seemed like it was a
mistake.''
 &HT;    Since then a flood of offers has come in, including movies,
television shows and commercials. Don't look for her to turn up
hawking Slim Fact, however.
 &HT;    ``I will not sell out and hawk some diet product. I will not be
a hypocrite,'' she insists. ``I'm healthy _ I get checkups. I see
no reason to lose weight to conform to society's standard of
beauty.''
 &HT;    The only thing she wants now is one more award.
 &HT;    ``I have a dream where I go up to accept my Oscar and someone in
the audience stops me for a moment,'' she says. ``I say to her,
`Oh, my beautiful dress? I got it at Lane Bryant.'''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
