<HEADER>
A9427 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEBE-NEUWIRTH-IN-CELE     11-02 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEBE-NEUWIRTH-IN-CELEBRITY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEBE NEUWIRTH'S LATEST BRUSH WITH GENIUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a black-and-white slide of Bebe Neuwirth with Judy Davis
in a scene from ``Celebrity.'' 
 By JEANNE WOLF and SHEP MORGAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Bebe Neuwirth is a star of stage and screen _ she won a 1996
Tony Award as a singing murderess in ``Chicago'' and a couple of
Emmys as Dr. Lilith Sternin on ``Cheers.'' She's worked with some
of the biggest names in show business, from Bob Fosse and Michael
Bennett in the 1970s to Woody Allen in the 1990s.
 &HT;    But all anyone asks her about nowadays is that banana.
 &HT;    In Allen's new film ``Celebrity,'' opening nationwide on Nov.
20, Neuwirth plays a prostitute who, in her most noteworthy scene,
teaches a well-bred divorcee (Judy Davis) how to perform oral sex
using ... well, a tree-grown prop.
 &HT;    ``When we first shot it we used fake bananas,'' she recalls,
``but that just didn't seem to work, so we eventually went for the
real thing. I mean, real bananas.''
 &HT;    The scene may seem risque, but Neuwirth says she never hesitated
to take the role.
 &HT;    ``I'm a big fan of Woody Allen,'' she says. ``It read funny on
the page, two women standing there with bananas in their mouths. I
completely trusted Woody to fit it brilliantly into the movie, and
I think he did, because he has a great sense of comic timing.''
 &HT;    After seven years on ``Cheers,'' Neuwirth knows something about
comic timing.
 &HT;    ``You can't think it's funny when you're doing it,'' she says.
``Whether it's dry humor or slapstick, it has to be completely
truthful and real. So I didn't find it hard to keep a straight face
with a banana in my mouth.
 &HT;    ``Thank goodness I didn't laugh,'' she adds, ``because it could
have easily become obscene instead of just outrageous. As it is, I
think it turned out hysterical but not raunchy.''
 &HT;    Actors line up to work with the highly respected Allen, but many
are also disconcerted by his reluctance to let them see the full
script or, for that matter, to give them detailed direction on a
given character or scene. Neuwirth has no complaints, however.
 &HT;    ``I thought he was very specific,'' she says. ``I've worked with
directors who talk in these theoretical concepts and then put you
in front of the camera and you're thinking, `What in the hell did
they mean?' I felt I always knew exactly what Woody wanted from me,
and he made me feel like I could give it to him.
 &HT;    ``I know some people are disturbed that Woody hardly ever gives
them the whole script,'' she adds with a chuckle, ``but it didn't
bother me. I was perfectly happy just getting my scenes, and I
didn't worry about how they were going to fit into the film.''
 &HT;    Neuwirth, a self-described ``nice Jewish girl from New Jersey,''
grew up in Princeton as the daughter of a mathematician and a
painter. After seeing a performance of ``The Nutcracker'' while
still in elementary school, she set her heart on being a ballerina.
 &HT;    By her teens, Broadway had replaced the ballet stage in her
dreams, inspired by a trip to New York to see a performance of
``Pippin,'' directed by Fosse, the innovative choreographer. At 19
she won an understudy role in a touring company of ``A Chorus
Line,'' and a year later she was dancing in the New York
production, staged by Bennett.
 &HT;    ``I like to perform _ I've been on stage since I was 7, and I
think of the theater as my home,'' she says. ``More than anything,
I love to dance on stage.
 &HT;    ``But I sort of feel like the vaudevillian I played in
`Chicago,''' she adds. ``You want me to dance? I'll dance. You want
me to sing? I'll sing. You want me to act? I'll act. Performing is
what keeps me going.''
 &HT;    After ``A Chorus Line,'' Neuwirth starred in two shows for her
idol, Fosse: ``Dancin''' (1982) and a revival of ``Sweet Charity''
(1985), for which she won the first of her two Tonys.
 &HT;    ``I started out working with geniuses,'' she says. ``I didn't
realize it until later when, all of sudden, I was being directed by
people who weren't geniuses. I went, `Wait a minute! This is
getting tough.'
 &HT;    ``But it made me work harder to develop my craft,'' the actress
says. ``I guess, in a way, I was sort of compensating for their
lack of brilliance.''
 &HT;    Neuwirth feels that working with Woody Allen put her back in
touch with genius.
 &HT;    ``It's a quality that's hard to define,'' she says. ``They have
a clarity of vision and the ability to make it happen with a
certain creative spark. Also, every creative detail gets addressed,
nothing is sloughed over. In the end, it becomes their particular
take on the truth.''
 &HT;    In ``Celebrity,'' Allen takes on a subject that every performer
has some ideas about _ the pluses and minuses of fame.
 &HT;    ``I've never thought of myself as a celebrity,'' Neuwirth says.
``However, I can't deny that I have some notoriety from Broadway
and television, and it's not all bad _ sometimes, a little
recognition can be quite good.
 &HT;    ``But in the film Woody shows the effect on two very different
people,'' she says. ``Kenneth Branagh plays a guy who's desperately
trying to claw his way into the limelight and ends up a failure.
His ex-wife, played by Judy Davis, becomes a celebrity almost by
accident _ her fame is just luck. I think that's fascinating and
thought-provoking.
 &HT;    ``Actually, I think Bob Fosse's perspective on fame in `Chicago'
was equally on the money,'' Neuwirth adds. ``Bob was a great
romantic, but also a great cynic. When he made `Chicago' into a
musical in 1975, I think it was his answer to the Watergate
hearings. You know, his take was, `It's all a circus, kid, a
three-ring circus.' It's a very telling send-up of celebrity.''
 &HT;    Audience awareness of the current round of Washington scandals
may lend an extra zip to Neuwirth's banana scene _ which was shot
long before Monica Lewinsky was a household name _ but Neuwirth
would rather it just went away.
 &HT;    ``People may find more to laugh at when they watch that scene,''
she says, ``but I find everything that's gone on with the
revelations of the president's sex life disgusting. I'm totally
disgusted. I try not even to think about it.
 &HT;    ``Woody Allen's movies become classics, but what happened
between Clinton and Lewinsky will be forgotten.''
 &HT;    If Neuwirth is remembered by future generations, chances are it
will be as Lilith in reruns of ``Cheers.''
 &HT;    ``I just hope people will look at me on their TV and say, `Wow,
she was funny, she did a good job. I think she's a pretty good
actress,''' she says. ``I think `Cheers' was a great showcase for
me, and I don't have a regret about doing it. I certainly was never
worried about getting typecast as a psychiatrist!''
 &HT;    Whatever may be said about her role in ``Celebrity'' or future
endeavors, Neuwirth won't be listening. She avoids reviews, and
hesitates even to do interviews.
 &HT;    ``I'm always uncomfortable with the fact that what someone else
may write might not reflect what I'm trying to say,'' she says.
``Anytime you give an interview, you're giving people permission to
make judgments about you. That's a very difficult and vulnerable
position to be in. I find it nerve-wracking.
 &HT;    ``I'm really a very sensitive person,'' Neuwirth continues.
``I've learned not to read anything that's written about me,
because I don't want to lose that sensitivity.
 &HT;    ``I don't think it's a particularly good thing to build up an
armor as to how you're portrayed. That's not healthy. It can chip
away at your compassion.''
 c.1998 Pentacom Productions  
