<HEADER>
A9432 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV08-NY     11-02 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE E-LANCER EATS A BAGELWICH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Nov. 8)  
 (Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.)  
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How are new words created? What's the logic behind neologisms?
How can you, working at home, coin your own words for fun and
profit?
</P>
<P>
   Here is how you can amaze your friends and dismay your
derogators by displaying your hidden ingenuity. The secret: knowing
your combining forms.
</P>
<P>
   Take  &UR; -ware &LR; . This started out in the Sanskrit  &UR; vasna &LR; ,
``price,'' and came to mean, in English, things of value _
``goods.'' We used this combining form for articles made of clay
( &UR; earthenware &LR; ) or a range of tools ( &UR; hardware &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1960, as computers came on the scene, we had the need
for a word to describe the programming needed to go with the
hardware. Coinage:  &UR; software &LR; , the opposite of ``hard'' with the
combining form  &UR; -ware &LR; . That was only the beginning: If a company
promises new software and doesn't meet its deadline, the nonproduct
is derided as  &UR; vaporware &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Last month, in a harangue against gloom-and-doom economists
wringing their hands about a global crisis, I had the need for a
name for what ailed them. What's the combining form for an ailment?
Often it's  &UR; -itis &LR; , as in  &UR; sinusitis &LR; . So I blazed away at those
afflicted with  &UR; global crisis-itis &LR; . Strictly a nonce coinage, but
it fit the moment's vituperative need.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring 1998 issue of American Speech, A Quarterly of
Linguistic Usage, Adrienne Lehrer of the University of Arizona has
an article about ``Scapes, Holics and Thons: The Semantics of
English Combining Forms.'' She describes how ``source words'' like
 &UR; Watergate &LR;  get splintered, with a portion becoming a combining
form, from Carter's  &UR; Billygate &LR;  to Reagan's  &UR; Irangate &LR;  to Clinton's
 &UR; Monicagate &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In the same way  &UR; alcoholic &LR;  spawned  &UR; workaholic &LR;  and
 &UR; chocoholic &LR; , as  &UR; -holic &LR;  became a combining form meaning ``hooked
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Take a familiar word like  &UR; sandwich &LR; , a culinary creation named
after the fourth Earl of Sandwich in 1762. Say you are a bagel
baker and you want to use your product instead of bread to purvey
smoked salmon and cream cheese. You put up a sign:  &UR; bagelwich &LR; .
Everyone instantly knows you are pushing a sandwich made on a
bagel.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, a Francophile competitor puts up his own
sign,  &UR; croissantwich &LR; , and your customers desert you, mouths fixed
for croissants stuffed with the filling of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   Same with  &UR; hamburger &LR; , originally chopped meat enjoyed by
residents of Hamburg, Germany. Using the  &UR; -burger &LR;  combining form,
we come up with  &UR; cheeseburger &LR;  and now  &UR; veggieburger &LR; , with a score
of variations in between. You get the meaning instantly with no
explanation needed, even if you've never seen or heard the word
before.
</P>
<P>
   Quick: What is a  &UR; turkeyfurter &LR; ? (It could be wurst: Would you
like to wash one down with a  &UR; vodkatini &LR; ? You need no help to make
the leap to these neologisms based on  &UR; frankfurter &LR;  and  &UR; martini &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jargonauts &LR;  (a play on  &UR; Argonauts &LR;  and an example of the
 &UR; -nauts &LR;  combiner used by  &UR; Reaganauts &LR; ) like to use  &UR; -speak &LR;  as
their combiner. The source word is George Orwell's  &UR; newspeak &LR; , and
it spawned everything from my  &UR; Haigspeak &LR;  (Al Haig's ``Snakecheck
that'' and shades-of-gray  &UR; nuancal &LR; ) to the San Fernando Valley
girls'  &UR; Valspeak &LR;  (``grody to the max'').
</P>
<P>
   Let's leave behind the  &UR; -holics &LR;  and  &UR; -thons &LR; . (Just as a
 &UR; television marathon &LR;  blends to  &UR; telethon &LR; , an unending stream of
faxes becomes a  &UR; faxathon &LR; .) We can also skip the  &UR; -scapes &LR; .
( &UR; Landscape &LR; , the source word, led to coinages of  &UR; seascape &LR; ,
 &UR; moonscape &LR; ,  &UR; cityscape &LR;  and  &UR; Xeriscape &LR; , ``parks created with
little need for water.'')
</P>
<P>
   Turn to the fifth letter of the Roman alphabet for the combining
form now most in vogue: I've been keeping a fair weather eye on the
letter  &UR; E &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``More of us will work as  &UR; e-lancers &LR; ,'' said Snigdha Prakash,
an NPR reporter, in the course of an interview, defining the term
as ``free agents who are electronically linked to other soloists
for specific projects, and move on when the work is done.'' These
are the unaffiliated employed (``drifters,'' we used to call them),
and the term is a rhyming play on  &UR; freelancer &LR; , originally a
mercenary soldier of the Middle Ages, now often a middle-aged
soloist.
</P>
<P>
   When  &UR; electronic mail &LR; , coined in 1977, was shortened five years
later to  &UR; e-mail &LR; , it became the combining form of the Information
Age, muscling aside its competition on the prefix menu,  &UR; cyber- &LR; 
(from the Greek  &UR; kybernan &LR; , ``to govern'').
</P>
<P>
   Now we have  &UR; e-text &LR;  published in an  &UR; e-zine &LR;  (often shortened
and pronounced ``zeen''). You can buy an airline  &UR; e-ticket &LR;  with
 &UR; e-money &LR;  or  &UR; e-bucks &LR;  (terms that have bankrupted  &UR; cybercash &LR; ),
unless you want to use  &UR; e-credit &LR; , a form of Internet dealing known
as  &UR; e-commerce &LR;  or  &UR; e-tailing &LR; . That last is a play on  &UR; retailing &LR; 
and, as in  &UR; e-lancer &LR; , the letter  &UR; E &LR;  does not stand only for
``electronic.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wayne Glowka, an editor of the Among the New Words section
of American Speech, reports that  &UR; e-gifts &LR;  of  &UR; e-bouquets &LR;  are
often given by members of the  &UR; e-generation &LR; . (Want to subscribe?
Send $35 to Duke University Press, Box 90660, Durham, N.C.
27708-0660. Sorry, I don't know how to do it electronically.)
</P>
<P>
   All of this, plus generations of new terms as yet uncoined, will
be sneered at as  &UR; e-speak &LR; , a product _ just think of it _ of two
combining forms, which I have just coined this instant unless some
 &UR; e-reader &LR;  of my  &UR; e-text &LR;  beat me to it.
</P>
<P>
   NOBODY'S PERFECT
</P>
<P>
   In a smirking swipe at the use of ``what  &UR; is &LR;  is'' by the only
president we have, a language maven noted that  &UR; has there been &LR;  was
in the past perfect tense.
</P>
<P>
   As Lise Nazarenko, a lecturer in English at the University of
Vienna, noted: `` &UR; Has there been &LR;  is not in the  &UR; past &LR;  perfect
tense, but rather in the  &UR; present &LR;  perfect tense. Past perfect
would be  &UR; had there been &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Perfect &LR; , in its most familiar sense, means ``flawless''; in an
earlier sense, it meant ``complete.'' That sense of ``finished'' is
what we use in grammar: a verb form expressing an action that is
complete at the time of speaking or at the time spoken of. And
since  &UR; has &LR;  is present and  &UR; had &LR;  is past, `` &UR; has &LR;  there been'' is,
as the entire Gotcha! Gang has gleefully pointed out, in the
 &UR; present perfect &LR;  tense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 1637EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
