<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9443 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-PRIVACY-NYT &LR;      11-02 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-PRIVACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVER ELUSIVE, PRIVACY SLIPS FROM GRASP OF PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ABIGAIL ZUGER, M.D.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On my desk at the hospital sits a computer terminal I use to
check my patients' blood tests and X-ray results. I could also,
were I so inclined, use it to browse through the blood tests and
X-rays of thousands of complete strangers, tracking biopsy results,
guessing at life expectancies and generally shattering every known
code of medical privacy and confidentiality to smithereens without
ever leaving my chair.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that no activity could tempt me less is actually not
very important. My very ordinary access code and password into an
ordinary hospital computer network are just one more indication
that medical privacy as we once understood it has become a thing of
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, medical records were almost as sacrosanct as
the body itself, as carefully shielded by the medical chart as the
body's various bulges are shielded by clothes. Generally, only
people permitted to breach one defense and see you in a state of
undress could breach the other and read through your medical
records.
</P>
<P>
   Now, your personal medical history has acquired a frenetic life
of its own. It zooms by fax and modem farther and farther away from
your person, far from your medical chart and your medical
caretakers, far from anyone likely to recognize your face or greet
you by name, let alone rejoice at your good health or grieve at
news of illness.
</P>
<P>
   It routinely lands on the desks of insurers, but sometimes
wanders even farther afield. Last winter, a national chain of
drugstores was caught selling names of customers with specific
illnesses to pharmaceutical companies for use in targeted drug
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the federal government contemplated assigning every
citizen an electronic code to summarize his or her medical health,
much as a credit report summarizes financial health, and presumably
just as easy for interested parties to inspect.
</P>
<P>
   The drugstores hastily called off their deal at the first sign
of public outrage, and the government said it has shelved its plans
until legislation to protect patients' privacy is enacted. But many
experts glumly predict that privacy legislation will only lock the
barn door after a long-departed horse. The computer on my desk says
they are probably right.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one consolation in this chilly new world of
exposed medical records: Objective violations of medical privacy
and our subjective experience of them are often two quite different
things.
</P>
<P>
   True privacy, that all-important cloak that allows a person to
proceed with dignity through the many indignities of illness, is a
remarkably complex and elusive entity, a real will-o'-the-wisp,
often found where least expected and almost impossible to
legislate.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the long, slow revolution in hospital design that has
filled our hospitals with two- and four-bed semiprivate rooms in
place of large open wards that once routinely housed all but the
wealthiest patients.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was an obvious violation of privacy to abolish, it
was one of those big, noisy wards, lined with dozens of beds
separated only by the occasional curtain. The head nurse at the
front desk could see every detail of every patient's hospital
course _ and so could every patient's 35 roommates, all their
visitors, and the workers who mopped the floor.
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out that privacy is not so easy to create or bisect
_ the semiprivacy we have today is often less than none at all. In
a two-bed room, each roommate is the other's only universe. There
is no avoiding the other's illness, visitors, night terrors or idle
ears.
</P>
<P>
   A survey taken in Britain two years ago found that more than
three times as many patients in a large ward felt they could have a
private conversation with their doctors than patients in smaller
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The patrons of stores with large communal dressing rooms know
this paradox well: Trying on a bathing suit in a room with 30
strangers similarly engaged is a far more private experience than
sharing a dressing room for two would be.
</P>
<P>
   One of my patients was placed in a sunny four-bed room several
years ago to recover from pneumonia. His roommates were pleasant,
quiet and solicitous; even their visitors were kind to him. For the
next two weeks, I would visit him and find an empty bed.
</P>
<P>
   The congenial roommates would point me to the noisy, crowded
lounge at the end of the hall where my patient was spending his
days, happily anonymous. ``No privacy back there,'' he would
explain, hoisting up his shirt to be examined.
</P>
<P>
   As our medical records fly hither and yon, legislation may
ultimately help protect us from incurring financial harm from their
travels. But for that terrible feeling of being naked in front of
millions of curious spectators, the only remedy may be to remember
that most of the millions are not all that curious _ and that most
of them now are naked themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
