<HEADLINE>
VITAL SIGNS: SHORT TAKES ON HEALTH AND FITNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Should pediatricians charge patients for telephone advice? _
John O'Neil
</P>
<P>
   Pediatricians should re-evaluate the expertise dispensed by
phone. In the old system, that expense was bundled in with other
charges, a hidden charge in fee for service. Now we are in an
insurance environment where that is impossible and are essentially
giving away expertise. The doctor-patient relationship has changed.
In the old days, the people who called in the middle of the night
were with me for long periods. Now you get a call at 1 a.m. saying
my kid just woke up and is crying. Those patients are usually only
with you for a year or two, because insurance plans change so much.
The insurance companies are going around saying, ``We provide
24-hour care.'' What they provide is us. _ Dr. Kurt Metzl,
Professor, University of Missouri-Kansas City; pediatrician.
</P>
<P>
   I'm very sympathetic, but I do not think it would work. It is
impractical, it is bad marketing and it potentially could be
harmful for patients who depend on it. It is true, the practice of
medicine today is no longer one of long-running relationships with
families. However, the danger here is that you want to encourage
people to call so you can make the decision of whether what you are
listening to is potentially serious. You do not want to put a
roadblock in the way of those calls, and money is always a
roadblock. Secondly, you offer this service as a way of encouraging
patients to use your services. The more you can convince patients
that you care, the more successful the pediatric practice will be.
</P>
<P>
   _Dr. Edwin J. Saltzman, Lecturer at University of Miami School
of Medicine; retired pediatrician.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Teens Nix Heels &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Heels are out, athletic shoes are in, at least among teen-age
girls. And orthopedic researchers believe that this trend may
explain why young women have fewer foot problems than their older
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 672 girls ages 10 to 18 conducted by Dr. Carol Frey,
director of the Orthopedic Foot and Ankle Center at Los Angeles
Orthopedic Hospital, found that 68 percent wore sneakers or
athletic shoes most often and only 4 percent wore heels. Only 13
percent complained of foot pain and 9 percent reported foot
deformities, compared with 80 percent and 76 percent reported by
women ages 20 to 60 in a previous study. Both problems, said Dr.
Frey, are associated with shoes that fit poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby boomers' daughters will have fewer foot disorders than
their mothers later on in life if they continue to wear comfortable
shoes that fit the foot properly,'' Dr. Frey said. ``Bunions,
hammertoes, corns, calluses _ all of these are secondary to narrow,
ill-fitting shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most teen-age girls have not had to shove their feet
into uncomfortable shoes for hours on end to comply with workplace
dress standards, which may help explain their problem-free feet.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frey said that if the girls followed in the footsteps of
older women and chose heels, foot problems would follow. ``It takes
decades of wearing heels to get deformities,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the girls switch to the ill-fitting styles, over time,''
she added, ``they will also be subject to foot deformities.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; That's Reality &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a busy drugstore in midtown Manhattan last week,
where a display case boasted 29 different types of condom, one
brand was conspicuously absent from the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you sell Reality?'' a customer asked uncomfortably, and
watched as a sales clerk extracted a box of three from the depths
of a low shelf well hidden behind the counter.
</P>
<P>
   Reality, available in the United States since 1993, is the first
and only ``female condom'' on the market.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in the words of its manufacturer, ``a soft, loose-fitting
plastic pouch that lines the vagina.''
</P>
<P>
   A flexible ring holds the inner, closed end in place against a
woman's cervix, and another, larger ring, which protrudes from her
body, forms the outer opening.
</P>
<P>
   Generously lubricated by the manufacturer, the whole thing is
quite wet and slippery.
</P>
<P>
   In America, the female condom never really caught on.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not popular,'' said Kris Kim, a spokeswoman for
Planned Parenthood of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kim said that although a few women like the condom, birth
control counselors report that many clients are put off by its
looks, by squeamishness about inserting it, by irritation from the
rings and by its reputed tendency to squeak. Those who do use it
complain that they have trouble finding it in drugstores.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the most recent year for which data were available,
only 12,000 of the 38.7 million American women who used birth
control said the female condom was their primary method, according
to the National Survey of Family Growth, conducted by the National
Center for Health Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   But Reality is finding an important niche overseas. Like the
male condom, it protects against sexually transmitted diseases,
including AIDS. But the female condom is the only means of
protection that a woman can fully control.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, it has been embraced by the U.N. AIDS programs
and other international groups, which have been helping to provide
millions of female condoms to Zimbabwe, South Africa, Uganda and
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
   Reality is manufactured by Female Health Co., in Chicago, a
small firm without much of an advertising budget, according to O.B.
Parrish, the company's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   But he said sales, most of them overseas, had more than doubled
in the past year, to 7.4 million by the end of September from 3.3
million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of on the threshold of commercializing,'' Parrish
said. ``One of the things we feel good about is that this product
actually saves some lives.''
</P>
<P>
   _Denise Grady
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Is Finding Fitness Just a Blade Away? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An infomercial for Bodyblade, a 4-foot by 1.75-inch blade with a
rubber hand grip at the center, hit the airways earlier this year,
its makers hoping to follow in the lucrative footsteps of fitness
products like ab rollers and butt blasters. The infomercial, which
claimed that Bodyblade offered ``a complete and total body workout
in as little as six minutes a day,'' enticed fitness buffs to snap
up 100,000 of the $99 gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   But the American Council on Exercise, a watchdog for the fitness
industry, disputed Bodyblade's claims. A product review, published
in ACE Fitness Matters, states that performing the suggested Super
Six routine _ a set of six, one-minute exercises _ offers little
fitness benefit. The review, conducted by biomechanists at
California State University, Northridge, said the limited movement
required for most of the exercises did little to improve
flexibility or strength and that no exercise device could bring
about significant weight loss or increases in cardiovascular
endurance if used for only six minutes a day. The reviewers also
said that using Bodyblade regularly might result in overuse
injuries of the shoulders and wrists.
</P>
<P>
   Council reviewers addressed their comments to infomercial
claims; they did not test the product, which requires users to grip
the center of the oblong object with one or both hands and wave it
back and forth to create resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Hymanson, the inventor of Bodyblade and president of its
distribution company, said council reviewers misinterpreted the
video. ``We never say that using the blade for six minutes will
help you lose weight or increase endurance,'' he said, ``We clearly
state it will help you strengthen, tone and sculpt your muscles.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Cotton, the council's chief exercise physiologist,
disagreed and said that lifting weights is a more natural way to
strengthen muscles than the pulsating action of the blade.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ Liz Neporent &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
