r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-SPRING-SPI &LR;      11-02 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SPRING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION DESIGNERS AIM TO HAVE WOMEN BARING MORE THAN THEIR SOULS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hip-riding skirts, bare bellies and carpenter pants
are just a few of the things to look forward to next spring.
</P>
<P>
   That's what designers here are showing this week as they present
spring '99 collections to retailers and fashion media.
</P>
<P>
   Why designers assume that women want to bare more than their
souls when daylight hours lengthen and trees turn green is
something of a mystery. Don't these creative people know that women
need coverage when they go to work, drive a carpool or volunteer
for a favorite cause?
</P>
<P>
   Even Carolina Herrera, who can usually be counted on for
tasteful clothing, seems to have lost her bearings. Her latest line
focuses on hip-hanging skirts and simple shell or tank tops that
never quite connect, leaving flashes of bare skin.
</P>
<P>
   It's cute on models with very flat, nicely tanned tummies. Women
of a certain age, however, might pause or pass.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera's leather tops in pale pink or lilac were pretty. But
are they practical? She is also fond of fish-tail skirts _ skirts
that forced models into mincing steps.
</P>
<P>
   Another trademark of her collection is a cowl neckline draping
either the front or back of a dress. When that collar is lined with
a contrasting satin _ lavender on a dove-gray dress, for example _
it's stunning.
</P>
<P>
   For several seasons now, designers have focused on late-day
apparel, from cocktail dresses to ballgowns. Dresses, suits,
sportswear and other everyday styles are in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   Han Feng, a designer who emigrated from China 13 years ago, does
create some sporty looking apparel _ pants and jackets in gingham,
for example. But the gingham pattern is on silk taffeta, making it
impractical for daily wear.
</P>
<P>
   She showed her collection informally in a dingy building on West
39th Street. Against the patched plaster walls and peeled paint
floors, her ethereal silks looked very fragile.
</P>
<P>
   Han Feng is known for her textures. For spring '99, that means
pleats so small they look like a ribbed fabric, or silk chiffon
embroidered with elastic thread for a puckered texture. She
frequently mixes fabrics _ a bias-cut dress with a satin top and
matte jersey skirt, for example. ``Women can wear bras with
these,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   Bras are a scarce commodity in this garment district. The many
halter tops being shown often leave sides of the chest with very
little coverage. Or, tops are simply so sheer, they show all. And
models never wear bras on the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the clothes being shown are accessory-free except for
shoes _ shoes that seem to be giving models nothing but trouble.
High-heeled mules _ that means only the toes are covered, there's
no ``back'' to the shoe _ tangled with fish-tail skirts at Herrera.
</P>
<P>
   At the Susan Lazar show, models wore slippers by Jacques Levine
that resembled those old-fashioned leather wedgies by Daniel Green.
The footwear reduced some to shuffling down the runway.
</P>
<P>
   This is actually the second showing of spring '99 fashions. A
few designers presented their wares in mid-September, so they could
show before the unveilings in Milan, Paris and London. (American
designers are sometimes accused of copying the Europeans and they
wanted to prove that isn't so.)
</P>
<P>
   Beginning next February, New York designers will show their fall
collections together, about six weeks earlier than usual.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
