<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9492 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-JEFFERSON-SUB-BOS     11-02 1527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-JEFFERSON-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN SCIENCE CONFIRMS JEFFERSON RUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Corrects reference to presidential term in third graf.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many historians have long held it unthinkable, but new DNA
evidence suggests it is almost certain that Thomas Jefferson, that
icon of American idealism, fathered at least one child with his
slave, Sally Hemings, even as he opposed ``race mixing'' and
believed blacks to be inferior.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic test results released last week strongly support
persistent but often-dismissed rumors that the third US president
had a long-lasting liaison with Hemings, during which six children
were born, of whom four lived to adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists said the DNA evidence ``seems to seal the case'' that
Jefferson fathered the mulatto slave's last child, Eston Hemings
Jefferson, born in 1808 during the last year of his second term as
president.
</P>
<P>
   If so, their liaison likely endured for at least 20 years, if it
began, as Hemings's son Madison said in an 1827 newspaper
interview, in 1788 when Jefferson and Hemings were in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said that Jefferson appears not to have been the
father of Hemings's first child, born in 1790, Thomas Woodson
(whose name comes from a later owner). But the evidence could not
rule out Jefferson's paternity, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Confirmation of the 196-year-old rumor is the most dramatic
application so far of new DNA methods that use the Y, or male,
chromosome to trace male lineages. The Jefferson project, headed by
Dr. Eugene Foster, a retired pathologist at the University of
Virginia in Charlottesville, Va., compared tell-tale patterns on
the Y chromosome of present-day descendants of the Jefferson family
with those of descendants of Thomas Woodson and of Eston Hemings
Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   The results were published by the scientific journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Foster, the report is authored by two British
genetic specialists, M.A. Jobling of the University of Leicester
and C. Tyler-Smith of the University of Oxford, and others.
</P>
<P>
   The testing was undertaken in an effort to settle the debate
over the most potent character issue involving Jefferson, an
enigmatic and extraordinarily private president.
</P>
<P>
   Annette Gordon-Reed, a black law professor at New York
University Law School and author of the 1997 book, ``Thomas
Jefferson and Sally Hemings: An American Controversy,'' has argued
that traditional, mainly white Jefferson historians dismissed the
rumor and ignored the evidence of black oral history on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a powerful incentive to turn aside anything to
suggest that the story might be true,'' Gordon-Reed said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Some also believed that Jefferson ``was too cerebral to be
interested in sex,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Those historians include Mount Holyoke College professor Joseph
Ellis, who was quoted earlier this year as saying, ``I believe his
deepest sensual urges were directed at buildings, rather than at
women.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon-Reed called the findings ``quite gratifying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that no matter what was said in my book it would never
be resolved based on what was (previously) known,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes as a number of revisionist scholars emphasize
the disconcerting racist beliefs and other weaknesses of Jefferson,
a slave owner who declared in the Declaration of Independence that
``all men are created equal.''
</P>
<P>
   Historian Ellis and geneticist Eric Lander at the Whitehead
Institute in Cambridge, Mass. coauthored a commentary accompanying
the report in Nature. They said the new revelation adds ``a
dimension of hypocrisy'' and ``only deepens the paradoxes'' in
Jefferson's life.
</P>
<P>
   While never freeing the bulk of his slaves, Jefferson freed the
children of Sally Hemings, two informally by helping them escape
and the the other two formally. Eston, in particular, was said to
closely resemble Jefferson, contributing to the rumor of the
president's paternity, but this was countered by others who
attributed parentage to one or the other of two Jefferson nephews.
</P>
<P>
   For the testing project, Foster gathered blood samples from 19
men, including several descendants of Jefferson's paternal uncle,
as Jefferson himself had no surviving sons.
</P>
<P>
   The testing found that a specific pattern of genetic markers on
the Y chromosome of those Jeffersonian descendants exactly matched
the marker pattern on the Y chromosome carried by a male descendant
of Eston Hemings Jefferson. The genetic fingerprint is rare, the
scientists said, leaving only about a 1 percent probability that
they matched by chance.
</P>
<P>
   All males carry a Y chromosome that has been passed down through
their father's lineage, changing little from one generation to
another. (The two X chromosomes of a female, by contrast, can be
shuffled between paternal and maternal lineages). However, only in
the past two years have scientists found enough variable genetic
markers on the Y chromosome to match a distinctive pattern with a
particular male lineage.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, who was born in 1743, married in 1772, but his wife,
Martha, died in 1782 after bearing six children. Only two of them,
both girls, survived to adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   In 1774, Sally Hemings, who was Martha's half-sister, came to
Jefferson as property bequeathed to him. She was one of about 150
slaves kept by Jefferson at Monticello, his estate outside
Charlottesville. Sally was described by a slave, Isaac Jefferson,
as ``mighty near white ... very handsome, long straight hair down
her back.''
</P>
<P>
   The affair is said to have begun when Jefferson, serving as
ambassador to France, brought Hemings to Paris in 1787 to care for
his daughter. Madison Hemings said specifically that his mother
became Jefferson's concubine at that time. Sally Hemings returned
with him to Monticello in 1789, and records show that Jefferson was
at Monticello during the times when all the children would have
been conceived.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor of their affair first became public when a former
Jefferson ally who turned against him publicized it in a newspaper
article in 1802, but the report was deemed politically motivated
and untrustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the rumor persisted. In 1974, historian Fawn M. Brodie was
the first modern writer to give strong credence to the affair. Her
best-selling book, ``Jefferson: An Intimate History,'' stirred a
controversy that has lasted until now.
</P>
<P>
   Lander, the Whitehead Institute geneticist, pointed out that the
one child known from the DNA findings to be Jefferson's was born in
1808 _ six years after he had been accused of the liaison with his
slave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inconceivable that he didn't have a relationship before''
the damning newspaper article ``and then started one after'' it had
been published, said Lander.
</P>
<P>
   The Jefferson-Hemings question has been a popular topic for the
past few years among tourists visiting Monticello, and the guides
who lead tours around the historic site ``range from true believers
to absolute deniers,'' said Cinder Stanton, senior research
historian at Monticello. ``There's no party line,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   As for herself, Stanton, who has studied Jefferson's life for 30
years while at Monticello, said her position has recently changed.
Initially skeptical that he would engage in such an exploitative
relationship with a slave, Stanton said she became more or less
persuaded following a recent oral history project that involved
interviews with 20 descendants of Sally Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearing that story over and over again moved me from thinking
it was improbable to thinking it was probable,'' she said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Lander and Ellis note that the DNA findings reveal nothing about
the character of the relationship, whether it was ``a tale of lust
and rape'' or mutual affection or ``something in between.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon-Reed, the NYU law school historian, said, ``I came away
feeling that we have no way of knowing, except that they had
children together over a 20-year period and they were named after
people who were important to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Eston, for example, was named for Jefferson's favorite cousin,
Thomas Eston Randolph; Madison, in honor of Dolley Madison, wife of
President James Madison; Beverley (a son) and Harriet for members
of the Randolph family to whom Jefferson was related.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Allgor, assistant professor of history at Simmons
College agrees. If the affair were mainly about power and lust, she
says, ``Jefferson could have moved on'' to other, younger women.
</P>
<P>
   Allgor believes that the impact of the report will be felt
widely, ``because it was so easy for so long to think of Jefferson
not as a human being but an embodiment of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, the new understanding that Jefferson's
descendants include people who are white, black, and intermediate
in color ``challenges our racial categories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what an American family looks like _ not dark people
down in the small house and white, First Family of Virginia people
up in the big house,'' Allgor said. ``An American family looks like
everybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
