<HEADER>
A9522 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-PEACE-1103-CO     11-02 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-PEACE-1103-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRISH PEACE PROCESS STALLS OVER DISARMAMENT OF IRA
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Northern Ireland peace process showed signs of
stalling Monday in the aftermath of an weekend shooting death in
north Belfast and a deepening stalemate over disarming paramilitary
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Bertie Ahern, the prime minister of the Republic of Ireland,
arrived in Belfast Monday seeking to spur progress toward
disarmament. It was not clear by the end of the day if he had made
much progress.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting came on the day an important deadline in the
process was missed because of the impasse over weapons
decommissioning. The new Northern Ireland assembly was scheduled to
have its cabinet in place by Saturday to begin assuming control
over most of the province's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   However, the protracted dispute over disarming has prevented the
appointment of key government ministers from Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Protestant leaders have refused to allow the appointment of
cabinet ministers from Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish
Republican Army, until progress is made toward disarmament. The IRA
has declared a cease-fire in its decades-old war to force Britain
to relinquish control over Northern Ireland, but the predominantly
Catholic group still maintains a huge stockpile of weapons and
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   David Trimble, an advocate of Northern Ireland remaining a part
of Britain and the assembly's first minister, insists that the IRA
surrender its weapons before Sinn Fein can be allowed to assume its
cabinet positions.
</P>
<P>
   But Sinn Fein says the Good Friday agreement mediated by the
United States does not require disarming before the cabinet is
formed. Sinn Fein also says it cannot persuade the IRA to give up
its weapons until its members are seated in the provincial
government.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern is searching for a compromise in the cabinet issue. He
also is trying to create a North-South Ministerial Council, which
would boost the Irish Republic's influence in the north. Some
Protestant leaders want Ahern to pressure Sinn Fein into getting
the IRA to begin turning in its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings Monday on the surface were unpromising, with the
leaders of the two sides trading verbal jabs between sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Ulster Unionist deputy leader John Taylor said Sinn Fein leader
Gerry Adams was ``becoming a joke'' because of his assertion that
the Good Friday accord does not require IRA disarmament as a
condition to Sinn Fein's participation in the new government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time Mr. Adams begins to deliver on his side of the
agreement,'' he said, adding that the requirement is explicit in
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Adams accused Trimble of pursuing a ``deliberate, go-slow''
policy and was unjustified in excluding Sinn Fein members from the
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Even though most of attention has been given to disarming the
IRA, Saturday's killing has been attributed to a small Protestant
paramilitary group, the Red Hand Defenders.
</P>
<P>
   The group has claimed responsibility for killing Brian Service.
The 35-year-old construction worker was shot in the head several
times in a Catholic area of North Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   While there are fears that the killing could spark reprisals,
Adams pledged to use his influence to urge the IRA not to break its
15-month cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   John Hume, who shared this year's Nobel Peace Prize with
Trimble, called the rift over scrapping arms a ``silly
distraction'' standing in the way of peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decommissioning is a silly distraction ... on the part of
those who are raising it,'' Hume, who was on a private visit to
Denmark, told Reuters News Service. He further noted that the April
peace agreement committed all sides to total disarmament within two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come to leave the past behind and build a new
future together. If we are going to draw up our past, all we are
doing is preserving the problem,'' said Hume, leader of Northern
Ireland's biggest Catholic party. ``A huge majority of people want
the agreement fully implemented as soon as possible and that is
what we should all be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
