<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Tuesday, November 3, 1998,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   FORTUNE _ Fortune magazine has named Austin and the surrounding
area the best city for business in North America. We check with
other cities who have received similar designations in recent years
to see what kind of an impact a No. 1 ranking has on a city. (Omar,
Austin American-Statesman). 15. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   AIRTRAN _ ATLANTA _ Checking to see if there are any
developments in the aftermath of an incident involving a
Dallas-bound AirTran flight, which was forced to return to Atlanta
after an hydraulic warning light came on. The National
Transportation Safety Board is investigating the Sunday incident.
(Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEBUILDERS _ Atlanta-based Beazer Homes has agreed to buy
Washington, D.C.'s fourth largest home building company for $100
million, perhaps another sign that the market has peaked. (Harte,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GUN-LOCK _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Shares of Saf T Lok, a small
gun-lock manufacturer based in West Palm Beach, had fallen to a
dismal 37 cents a share in late September of last year. The company
had lost $733,790 in the first nine months of the year on
disappointing sales, according to filings with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, and was facing delisting by the Nasdaq Stock
Market. Then President Clinton stepped into the Rose Garden on
Thursday, Oct. 9, 1997, with eight major gun manufacturers. He
extracted their pledge to put locks on every gun sold, launching
Saf T Lok's second life. In two days, Saf T Lok's share price
soared 11-fold. In four days, it cut a financing deal that assured
its place on Nasdaq and gave it capital for the future. It was the
company's highest point. Before and since, Saf T Lok, 10 years old
next year, has stumbled. An in-depth story. (Pounds, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Earlier in the century, East Lake was
the home course of the legendary Bobby Jones. Three years ago, the
course and club buildings were brought back to their former
splendor through the efforts of Atlanta developer and
philanthropist Tom Cousins. With the wealthy again enjoying the
course, just 10 minutes east of downtown, ``East Lake'' is now
emblazed on cotton golf shirts selling for $100. But for decades,
the East Lake name also conjured up images that had nothing to do
with clipped greens and Bermuda roughs. Crime, violence, drug
dealing and despair overshadowed the leafy beauty of the old
neighborhood. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (k, f) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ In the words of the president of Jaguar Cars
North America, Mike Dale, there are two reasons people purchase
automobiles. The first is for basic transportation; the second is a
perception that a certain vehicle adds something to the quality of
life. (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ ATLANTA _ I recently attended a public hearing
held by the Georgia Environmental Protection Division. The turnout
was small _ a handful of auto industry representatives and state
bureaucrats. We in the auto repair industry weren't required to be
there. We didn't go because the subject matter was especially
spectacular. The agenda item we had come to hear and object to was
the extension of the $200 waiver limit for vehicles failing the
metro Atlanta area's emission test _ and continuing to contribute
to the deterioration of Atlanta's air quality. The waiver limit
means cars that fail the state's emission test can be granted a
waiver _ and permission to get new tags for two years _ if the
owner spends at least $200 fixing the car and it shows some
improvement. (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ Surely all of us, at one time or another, have
wondered how it would be to have our consciousness transplanted
into that of another, to see and understand from the viewpoint of
someone else. My encounters with software conceived and whelped in
France lead me to believe that entering the mind of a Gallic
software designer would be like walking into a carnival funhouse
for the first time. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Every time I download a new version of Netscape
Communicator or Microsoft Internet Explorer _ the two most popular
programs for browsing the World Wide Web _ I am reminded of a
multi-function of a Swiss Army knife. The competition has gotten so
heated between the two Web browsers that each tries hard to outdo
the other by loading in new features. There are so many I truly
can't remember what all of them do. And since I don't use them, I
never get reminded. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ Parents don't much care for it, but that hasn't
stopped ``Quake'' from being a hit with male children of all ages.
Now the third version of the gory shoot-'em-up is set for release,
and the November issue of PC Gamer has a sneak preview. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ No question about it. The iMac is one
sharp-looking computer. But is it a good buy? I'd argue not. A
better investment would be any of Apple Computer's G3 desktop
models. Now, before you start flaming me with e-mail charges of
betrayal, let me explain. I consider the iMac a good, if not great,
computer. It works reasonably well, has a brilliantly sharp screen
and, of course, there's that striking bondi translucent body. But a
computer is a lot more than looks.(Haddad , Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ Election Day is here, but there's still time to bone
up on the candidates and the issues on the Web. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ A cellular phone without a battery is like a
doughnut without its hole. Maybe that's overstating things a bit,
but batteries are crucial. In the name of making batteries that
last longer, Duracell recently rolled out its Ultra line of
refillable alkaline battery packs. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
