<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9600 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-02 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM AND SALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thomas Jefferson's place in American history is
secure, no matter what his sex life was.
</P>
<P>
   Trust me on this. We may be momentarily distracted from his
inspired leadership shaping our democratic principles, but we'll
get back to it eventually.
</P>
<P>
   The public is in a short-term uproar over the scientific finding
that our third president, the revered visionary who drafted the
Declaration of Independence, fathered at least one child with his
slave Sally Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the great Jefferson was made of mortal clay after
all. But that's okay. He still earned his reputation 200 years ago
as a heroic figure to whom we all owe the freedoms we now take for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   The awesome Jefferson monument on Washington's Tidal Basin will
remain, as will his face on Mount Rushmore.
</P>
<P>
   Some historians are having a tough time with this revelation,
forced to revise their automatic rejection of circumstantial
evidence that long suggested a lengthy affair between the widowed
Jefferson and Hemings, an illegitimate child of his father-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Hemings was his late wife Martha's half-sister and may have
resembled her. She was Jefferson's daughter's companion and lived
in his household. At the age of 14, she accompanied his daughter to
France, where he was U.S. minister. She was pregnant when she
returned with the family at 17. She bore seven children at
Monticello, all during periods of Jefferson's presence there.
</P>
<P>
   The advocates of a four-decade Jefferson monkhood clearly did
not know their man. In retrospect it is odd that they were
convinced a genius of such voracious intellectual appetites would
not have physical ones as well.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some angry conspiracy-minded political commentators
profess to see sinister implications in the timing of the expose,
coming at the onset of impeachment proceedings against President
Clinton over his own illicit affair.
</P>
<P>
   Since the DNA match between descendants of Hemings and
Jefferson's uncle is reported in this week's issue of the British
journal Nature, however, there seems no basis to claim it as all a
liberal pro-Clinton plot. The research has been in the works the
past two years. No matter when the news broke, it would coincide
with some Clinton sex problem.
</P>
<P>
   The conservatives' concern is that Clinton's affair with Monica
Lewinsky will now be dismissed as normal presidential behavior, not
a rare and impeachable offense. Jefferson, after all, also
dismissed reports about his secret relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Jefferson had no choice because miscegenation was
illegal, even though widely practiced by Southern slave-owners. He
was re-elected in a landslide despite the Hemings rumors of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Ellis, a noted Jeffersonian scholar, says, ``The dominant
effect of this news will be to make Clinton's sins seem less
aberrant and more palatable.''
</P>
<P>
   What a stretch. Clinton's place in history is not secure, unlike
Jefferson's. And Clinton is a married man, unlike Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Clinton write the Declaration of Independence, make the
Louisiana purchase, found the University of Virginia or collect a
personal library so exceptional that it became the nucleus of the
Library of Congress. Clinton gets no pass on Jefferson's
200-year-old coattails.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever history is re-examined, however, actions taken in a
long-ago context can be misinterpreted in the light of modern
sensibilities. The early analyses point out that Jefferson owned
600 slaves during his lifetime, held a ``great aversion'' to racial
mixing and could make a scholarly defense of human equality while
ignoring the reality around him.
</P>
<P>
   This is not fair to Jefferson. He, like George Washington and
other plantation owners who kept slaves, was a product of a time
when the Southern agrarian economy was largely dependent on slave
labor. Jefferson also suffered from the typical white male view of
the era that women were intellectually inferior.
</P>
<P>
   In writings collected in ``The Jeffersonian Cyclopedia,'' he
repeatedly agonizes over slavery, despairing that it would never be
abolished in his lifetime but hoping that it would be ended in the
future. And he tried to do what he could about it.
</P>
<P>
   As Virginia's governor in 1778, he pushed through the state
legislature a measure to outlaw the importing of slaves into the
state. ``This stopped the increase of evil ... leaving to future
efforts its final eradication,'' he wrote in his autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   In 1784, as chairman of a congressional committee planning the
governance of the new western territories, he pushed for a ban on
slavery in the pioneering states. The measure lost by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The love of justice and the love of country plead equally the
cause of these people (slaves),'' Jefferson wrote in 1814, during
his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   But his notions of female intelligence were deplorable, if
commonplace. ``Our good ladies, I trust, have been too wise to
wrinkle their foreheads with politics,'' he wrote to a friend.
``They are contented to soothe and calm the minds of their husbands
returning ruffled from political debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. Nobody's perfect, even Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what President John Kennedy said is still true. Toasting
Spanish cellist Pablo Casals at a glamorous White House dinner,
Kennedy joked, ``This is the most brilliant assemblage here since
Thomas Jefferson dined alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson was the closest thing to a Renaissance man ever to
occupy the White House, a philosophical and practical genius who
was adept at the violin, architectural design, gardening, the
culinary arts, Greek and Latin, diplomacy and political policy. He
even introduced ice cream to America.
</P>
<P>
   Historians who are having trouble adapting the human Jefferson
to their idealized version may resent the demythification of
important historical figures and events. But history is not static,
any more than life itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
