<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Nov. 8)  
 
 CRUISING IRISH WATERS  
 LAYOVER IN HONG KONG  
 WATTS TOWERS  
 
 (af)  
 By PAUL FREIREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Several years ago I read about the charter of boats on rivers
in Ireland. One route went from Dublin west; the other went from
northeast to southwest, near the River Shannon. Can you provide
details? _ Leo J. Jordan, Wanaque, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. The route that runs west of Dublin is the Grand Canal, a
commercial link to Shannon plied for many years by horse-drawn
barges. These days vacationers are found on the route, which runs
basically east-west, as well as on its spurs, which run pretty much
north (as far as Beleek) and south (to St. Mullin).
</P>
<P>
   There are three tiers of prices for boat rentals. In 1998, the
highest rates were in effect from July 4 to Aug. 21 and the lowest
rates from before April 24 and after Sept. 12. The vessels have two
to nine berths. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to navigate the 81 miles of the Grand Canal, which
has 36 locks, a good spot to start is Tullamore, an hour's train
ride from Dublin. Vessels suited for the Grand Canal are top-heavy
and cannot be taken into lakes, but they can, for instance, travel
down the Barrow Navigation, a spur of the canal. On the way, one
can stop at Kilkenny and see Kilkenny Castle, parts of which date
from the 13th century.
</P>
<P>
   The route you mention near the River Shannon is probably the
Shannon-Erne Link. It was reopened in 1994 after more than a
century of disuse, having yielded to the steam train. It runs for
37 miles from Ballyconnell to Leitrim and has 16 locks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on going very far in a single day. On the Grand
Canal, the Barrow Navigation and the Shannon-Erne Waterway, for
example, the speed limit is less than 4 mph. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is the 1998 range of rates for a four-berth vessel for a
week, calculated at 66 pence to the dollar. The 1999 rates have not
been set yet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Athlone Cruisers, (353-902) 72892, fax (353-902) 74386. Captain
class, $530 to $954. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carrick Craft, (353-78) 20236, fax (353-78) 21336. Kerry class,
$603 to $996. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celtic Canal Cruisers, (353-506) 21861, fax (353-506) 51266.
Celtic Princess, $750 to $1.053. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Derg Line Cruisers, (353-61) 376364, fax (353-61) 376205.
Birchwood 320, $803 to $1,212. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Emerald Star Line, (353-1) 679-8166, fax (353-1) 679-8165.
Village Star, $833 to $1,288.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Castle Line, (353-1) 660-0964, fax (353-1) 668-9091.
Freeman 24, $591 to $914.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Line Cruisers, (353-509) 51112, fax (353-509) 51632.
Silver Swan, which sleeps four to six, $682 to $1,091. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tara Cruisers, (353-78) 20736, fax (353-78) 21284. The smallest
boat, a 36-footer for six, is $495 to $1,811.
</P>
<P>
   More details are available from the Irish Tourist Board, 345
Park Avenue, New York, N.Y. 10154; (212) 418-0800. For an
informative Web site, try www.heritageireland.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q. We will be arriving in Hong Kong at 5:55 a.m. on the way to
Hanoi at 5:25 p.m. the same day. Are there ``day rooms'' at the
airport where one may shower and sleep after a long flight? _
Richard G. Topazian, Farmington, Conn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Depending on your stamina and interests, you can catch not
only 40 winks but also a tour of Hong Kong during your half day
there.
</P>
<P>
   All the hotels listed here have a 6 p.m. checkout for day rooms
and all tack on 13 percent for government tax and service charge.
Rates are calculated at $7.80 (Hong Kong) to the United States
dollar. Here, in the order of check-in time, are some
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   6 a.m. The Regal Kowloon, 71 Mody Road, Tsimshatsui East,
Kowloon; (852) 2722-1818, fax (852) 2369-6950. Rate: $51.60.
</P>
<P>
   6 a.m. The Windsor, 39-43A Kimberley Road, Tsimshatsui, Kowloon;
(852) 2739-5665, fax (852) 2311-5101. Rate: $55.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10 a.m. The Prince, Hong Kong, Harbour City, Canton Road,
Tsimshatsui, Kowloon; (852) 2113-1888, fax (852) 2113-0066. Rate:
$126. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Noon. Sheraton Hong Kong Hotel and Towers, 20 Nathan Road,
Tsimshatsui, Kowloon; (852) 2369-1111, fax (852) 2739-8707. Rate:
$161.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another option may be the Regal Airport Hotel, which expects
to open next month and to charge $78 to $116. Information: (800)
222-8888.
</P>
<P>
   The ride from the airport into town on a train known as the
Airport Express takes 25 minutes. Assuming round trip and same-day
return, the fare is $19 to Hong Kong Station and $17 to Kowloon. A
taxi costs about $45 to the Central district on Hong Kong Island
and $37 to Kowloon. Travel time is about 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If the idea of a city tour appeals, take the Airport Express to
Kowloon Station, where you can catch the Transit Bus Tour. For
$15.50, you get to and from the airport and also to the Wong Sai
Sin Taoist Temple, Hong Kong's largest temple; the Kowloon Walled
City Park, and the New World Center, a shopping mall in
Tsimshatsui.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't get off _ and you can do so at any stop _ the tour
takes 90 minutes; if you get off, say, at the temple, you should _
given the bus schedule _ allot three hours. The charge includes a
guidebook and a taped commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm interested in seeing Simon Rodia's Watts Towers in Los
Angeles but understand they are only open to group tours. _ Ann
Clothier, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Actually, you don't have to be part of a group to see the
towers, which are now being restored. And actually, they won't
reopen until midyear 2000, according to Virginia Kazor, historic
site curator for the Los Angeles Cultural Affairs Department. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the towers, which rise as high as 99 feet and
are a National Historic Site, can be seen from the adjoining Watts
Towers Arts Center _ although there is scaffolding at the site.
</P>
<P>
   The towers consist of nine major sculptures of structural steel
and were built between 1921 and 1954 by Simon Rodia, a tile setter
and construction worker who once lived on the site. Embedded in the
sculptures are bits of glass from such sources as 7-Up and milk of
magnesia bottles as well as seashells, rocks, ceramic tile and
pottery.
</P>
<P>
   The art center, which sponsors classes, exhibitions and
lectures, is at 1727 East 107th Street. The hours are Tuesday to
Saturday from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. and Sunday from noon to 4 p.m. For
information, call (213) 847-4646.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the best way to get there is to drive, taking the
Wilmington Avenue exit off the Anderson Freeway or the Century
Boulevard exit off the Harbor Freeway. Parking at the center is
free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
