<SLUG> BC-ESPY-BRIBERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TO EXAMINE PART OF ESPY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court agreed Monday to consider
reinstating the conviction of Sun-Diamond Growers of California on
charges the cooperative of nut and fruit growers gave $5,900 in
illegal gifts to former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy.
</P>
<P>
   The court said it would hear independent counsel Donald C.
Smaltz's argument that the cooperative could be convicted even
without proof the gifts were intended to influence Espy's official
acts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Pleasanton-based company was convicted of giving
illegal gifts to Espy, including tickets to the 1993 U.S. Open
tennis tournament, luggage and a crystal bowl. The cooperative was
fined $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, the court told jurors that prosecutors did not
have to prove that the gifts led Espy to grant the cooperative
favors. Instead, the jurors were told they could convict
Sun-Diamond if the company gave things of value to Espy merely to
``keep him happy,'' even if the company did not intend the gifts to
relate in any way to an official act.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this year, the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia ruled the jury wrongly convicted Sun-Diamond,
saying that prosecutors did need to prove that the gifts were
intended to influence Espy's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz is asking the Supreme Court to overturn that decision and
rule that prosecutors are not required to prove that Espy did
anything in return for the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Monday, Espy began the second month of his trial on 38
corruption charges. Espy, a former Mississippi congressman who
headed the Agriculture Department from January 1993 until December
1994, is accused of accepting gifts from people and businesses he
was supposed to be regulating as agriculture secretary and then
attempting to cover up his actions when authorities began an
investigation. Those businesses included Sun-Diamond and Tyson Food
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Espy has pleaded innocent to all charges.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law permits a public official to receive gifts out of
friendship and goodwill, so long as they aren't meant as a reward
for past or future acts.
</P>
<P>
   Espy's federal corruption case is the culmination of Smaltz's
four-year, $17.4 million investigation of the secretary and
companies, lobbyists, friends and family associated with Espy's
tenure as agriculture secretary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Douglas, a former vice president of Sun-Diamond, spent a
fourth day on the witness stand Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew I worked for Sun-Diamond,'' Douglas said of his old
friend Espy. But Espy still wanted Douglas' advice as he moved into
the top Agriculture Department job, and did not seem bothered by
the possibility their relationship could seem inappropriate,
Douglas testified.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas said he promised his friend he wouldn't put him in an
ethically awkward position by lobbying him on issues of specific
interest to Sun-Diamond, but the two did talk about more general
issues affecting Sun-Diamond.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not give any favoritism to Sun-Diamond,'' Douglas
testified.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Douglas testified that Espy asked him to lie to the
FBI as the investigation began in 1994. It was the most direct
allegation of wrongdoing since testimony began Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But Douglas, who admitted to a variety of crimes under
questioning by Smaltz, also said prosecutors badgered him into
cooperating.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a possibility of four separate trials, nearly 60 years in
prison and with legal bills of about $100,000, Douglas pleaded
guilty in a related case and became Smaltz's ``puppet,'' he said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they wanted Mike, and by giving them Mike I could get
off the hook,'' Douglas testified.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Espy's former chief of staff, Ronald H.
Blackley, was sentenced to a 27-month prison term for lying about
$22,000 he received from two Mississippi individuals who obtained
large government farming subsidies.
</P>
</TEXT>
