<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPREME-COURT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TO DECIDE WHETHER CLINTON VIOLATED AIR FORCE MAJOR'S
RIGHT AGAINST DOUBLE JEOPARDY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday agreed to decide if the
constitutional rights of an Air Force major infected with the AIDS
virus were violated when President Clinton tried to drum him out of
the military following his court-martial in Texas for having
unprotected sex in violation of orders from a superior officer.
</P>
<P>
   The justices also will hear Houston-based Compaq Computer
Corp.'s defense of a court's order that a patent be awarded to the
company, despite the federal government's objection. In addition,
the high court will decide whether an agricultural cooperative
violated federal anti-bribery law when it gave then-Agriculture
Secretary Mike Espy tickets to sporting events, treated him to
meals and bought him gifts.
</P>
<P>
   In the military case, James T. Goldsmith argues that Clinton
violated the major's constitutional right against ``double
jeopardy,'' being punished twice for the same offense, when the
president tried to discharge him for the same acts that led a
military court at Lackland Air Force Base to imprison him and
withhold his pay. Goldsmith also says Clinton has no constitutional
authority to throw him out of the military because the law
permitting presidential discharge took effect after his
court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, appealing a lower court decision in
Goldsmith's favor, tells the high court that the constitutional
prohibition on double jeopardy does not apply because a military
discharge is not a second punishment but an administrative action.
</P>
<P>
   Solicitor General Seth Waxman, the president's chief lawyer
before the justices, added that a military discharge is not a
criminal proceeding. Therefore, the constitutional prohibition on
using new criminal laws to punish old acts does not apply.
</P>
<P>
   After Goldsmith was diagnosed with HIV, the virus that causes
AIDS, his superior officer ordered him to inform sexual partners of
his illness and to use condoms during intercourse to prevent
spreading the disease. However, Goldsmith later had unprotected sex
with two women without telling them he was HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   He was court-martialed and sentenced on March 4, 1994, for
willfully disobeying his superior officer's order and for two
counts of assault with a means likely to produce death or grievous
bodily harm. Goldsmith was sentenced to six years in the U.S.
Disciplinary Barracks at Fort Leavenworth, Kan., and $2,500 was
ordered to be withheld from his pay each month for the six years.
</P>
<P>
   A federal law enacted Feb. 10, 1996, enables the president to
discharge military officers who have been court-martialed and
sentenced to more than six months in prison. When Clinton moved to
discharge him in December 1996, Goldsmith appealed to the U.S.
Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruled the president's effort to discharge
Goldsmith was an unconstitutional second punishment for the same
offenses. The court also ruled that Clinton was barred from
removing Goldsmith from the military based on the 1996 law because
it was enacted after the major had committed his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Compaq case, the company urges the justices to uphold the
U.S. Court for the Federal Circuit's decision ordering the
government to issue a patent for a high-tech method of improving
security in computer systems. The U.S. government argues that the
court violated the Administrative Procedure Act by failing to defer
to the U.S. Patent Office's expertise in determining what
inventions are worthy of patents.
</P>
<P>
   The bribery case involves independent counsel Donald Smaltz's
effort to reinstate the graft conviction of Sun-Diamond Growers of
California, which the U.S. District Court in Washington, D.C.,
found had illegally treated Espy to 1993 U.S. Open Tennis
Tournament tickets, $2,427 worth of luggage, $665 in meals and $524
for a framed print and a crystal bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia
overturned the conviction, ruling that the anti-bribery law
requires that gifts be given to a government official not merely
because of his position but because of a specific act he has or
will perform as a result of receiving the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has not decided when it will hear the cases.
The justices are expected to render their decisions by July. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
