<HEADLINE>
HARRY TRUMAN'S ELECTION IN 1948 AN INSPIRATION TO UNDERDOGS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   ... the segregationist.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   There were other issues, such as agriculture. Truman, a former
farmer, needed little prompting. In Dexter, Iowa, that September,
Truman told farmers that the Republicans had ``stuck a pitchfork in
the farmer's back.''
</P>
<P>
   Truman had hit his stride. On Oct. 30, when he delivered an
especially emotional speech in St. Louis, he set his prepared text
aside.
</P>
<P>
   But it was too late, many correspondents believed.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 16 years of Democratic rule of the White House, the
voters want a change,'' Duke Shoop, a Star and Times Washington
correspondent, wrote on Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Elmo Roper, meanwhile, had stopped making surveys in
September. (break here)President confident (begin text here)At dawn
on Nov. 3, 1948, Truman arrived at the Hotel Muehlebach, his Kansas
City, Mo., campaign headquarters, knowing he had won.
</P>
<P>
   His escape to the Elms, however mysterious, did have precedent.
Sixteen years earlier, disappointed that he had not been Boss Tom
Pendergast's choice for governor, Truman also had booked a room at
the resort.
</P>
<P>
   First to shake his hand at the Muehlebach was Kansas City lawyer
Lyman Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was utterly unchanged,'' said Field.
</P>
<P>
   Truman's serenity in the face of apparent defeat had impressed
many. Elsey's own glimpse of it occurred in mid-October, as the
Truman train crossed Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president asked me to write down a list of the states,''
Elsey said. ``He knew the number of electoral votes that went with
each, and he predicted how each state would go.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were through he said, `What's the total?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `You've got 340.' Actually, he was overconfident,
because he only got 303. But he was absolutely convinced he was
going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by the civil rights issue, Truman carried all 13 of the
country's biggest cities. He also won five farm states that
Franklin Roosevelt had lost in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Truman's upset was stunning in part because polls had convinced
many people that he had no chance. Publications like the Chicago
Tribune, which published an early election edition bearing the
headline ``Dewey Defeats Truman,'' depended upon old advance polls
instead of the exit polls that are common today, said Frank
Mitchell, a University of Southern California historian.
</P>
<P>
   But another factor contributing to the general amazement,
Mitchell said, was ``a campaign of deliberate bias on the part of
the news media.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially brazen, Mitchell said recently from Santa Monica,
Calif., was the Time-Life-Fortune empire of Henry Luce.
</P>
<P>
   The ``acres of empty seats'' that Life had described in Omaha,
for instance, didn't explain how about 160,000 city residents had
seen Truman during a parade earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   And since Time magazine carried such clout with the Washington
press corps, many correspondents discounted the large crowds Truman
continued to attract, Mitchell added.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Kelly can vouch for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them told me, `They like him, but they are not going to
vote for him,' '' said Kelly. ``Just the blindness of the press was
interesting. They didn't see what was going on right in front of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Truman was handed the ``Dewey Defeats Truman'' edition of the
Chicago Tribune during a train stop in St. Louis two days after the
election.
</P>
<P>
   He held up the newspaper for photographers, and smiled. (break
here)Country rebounded (begin text here)In retrospect, the election
should not have surprised anyone, argues Herb Parmet, author of a
recent George Bush biography.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy had been restored by 1948,'' said Parmet of
Hillsdale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truman also had the support of people early in the Cold War in
how he responded promptly to the Berlin blockade. All things being
equal, you've got a president who had the country back in shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the glory of 1948 was ephemeral.''
</P>
<P>
   The Korean War, plus Truman's break with Gen. Douglas MacArthur,
later diminished the president's status. Truman didn't run for
re-election in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Truman's 1948 campaign has left its legacy. The term
``whistlestop'' has entered the language as the definition of a
hard-hitting grass-roots campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Republican nominee Bush invoked Truman in 1988 when he was 17
points behind Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis, Parmet said. Bush
won.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Bush invoked Truman again. But Democratic
challenger Bill Clinton praised him, too. Bush, it soon was
learned, had not voted for Truman in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what's so screwy,'' political comedian Mark Russell later
sang, ``he voted for Dewey.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1948 election ultimately emphasized the importance of
voting. Days after the election, Kelly spoke at Boston University,
where he had taken a job as a journalism professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people came up to me and said, `I voted for Truman but I
didn't think anybody else did,' &UR; '' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly was substituting that day for pollster Elmo Roper, who was
to have delivered a speech titled ``Why Dewey Won.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently he had gotten ill,'' Kelly said. (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
