<HEADLINE>
LABOR'S VOICE WILL BE HEARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even before the votes are counted in Tuesday's elections, it is
apparent that organized labor's role in many of these contests is
likely to influence the fate of some candidates on either side of
labor's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   On the national level, a key ballot referendum this past June in
California called Proposition 226, which was sponsored by
conservative Republicans and aimed at weakening labor's political
strengthy by making it virtually impossible for organized labor in
the state to participate in any election.
</P>
<P>
   But because labor was able to explain the referendum and its
true intent to workers across the state, the referendum went down
to a surprising defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the referendum crushed, it helped the Democratic
candidate for governor, Gray Davis, who had labor's support, to
upset his millionaire Democratic opponent in the June primary,
Davis is currently leading in his bid to become California's next
governor. If Davis wins Tuesday, the Democrats will have one of
their own at the state's helm during the presidential election in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Other important labor issues that will be impacted by the
outcome of Tuesday's national elections include the GOP's effort to
do away with overtime after working 40 hours in a week, and the
party's offorts to further erode the powers of the Occupational
Safety and Health Administration. If the GOP wins more seats in
Congress, these anti-labor issues could prevail.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, there's no doubt that organized labor has
played an influential role in the gubernatorial race. The
Democratic candidate, Atty. Gen. Scott Harshbarger, made it clear
early on that he wanted labor's support. He won the endorsement of
the 400,000-member state AFL-CIO and 30 large individual unions.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he wins or loses Tuesday, Harshbarger, as well as his
GOP opponent Acting Gov. Paul Cellucci, know that a key reason why
the race has been as close as it has been in the weeks leading up
to this election was largely due to labor's active support of
Harshbarger's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   In the Massachusetts congressional elections, labor's support
was the key reason that two Democrats defeated two GOP incumbents
in the 1996 election. Tuesday, these two Democrats -- John Tierney
(6th District) and James McGovern (3rd District) --are currently
leading their GOP opponents largely because of labor's support.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a test of labor's strength in these elections can be
measured by the response from candidates on the other side of
labor's support. For example, the national GOP campaign committee
last week released a political ad which suggested that Tierney
voted with the ``corrupt'' Teamsters ``union bosses,'' on the
government financing of the Teamsters election.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, what Tierney voted for was what both Democrats and
Republicans supported when the government paid for the Teamsters
elections two years ago. In essence, it appears to be a last-minute
desparate GOP strategy that is so misleading that all but one local
television station has refused to run this ad.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the carelessness of this GOP ad is apparent since the
overall attack on the Teamsters includes &UR;  &LR; by inference a local that
backs the GOP gubernatorial candidate, Paul Cellucci. Another
Teamster local which was credited with exposing the campaign
violations in last year's Teamsters elections is supporting
Democratic gubernatorial hopeful Scott Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Also in this year's Democratic primaries, more labor-endorsed
candidates won than lost, including Lt. Gov. candidate Warren
Tolman, Norfolk District Attorney candidate William Keating, and
several state senatorial and state representative races across the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Kathy Casavant, Massachusetts AFL-CIO
Secretary-Treasurer, the first woman to hold this labor post, said
it best: ``Without labor's presence in the election process, it is
hard to say whether the candidates would have paid as close
attention to important issues such as education and health care and
economic security that affects the three million folks who work and
live in Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, after Tuesday's votes are tallied, there will be
political anaylsts who will give their perspective on whether labor
won or lost overall in this election.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike candidates who may not have fared well and decide to
disappear from the political arena, organized labor, as they have
already vowed, will be back at work on Wednesday, looking toward
the next election.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Jordan is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
