<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILEANS-REMEMBER-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET'S FATE ATTRACTS SPECIAL INTEREST AMONG SOME KC AREA
RESIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (KANSAS CITY, MO.) _ ... (break here)`War for survival' (begin
text here)After Pinochet took power, Cruz continued distributing
opposition pamphlets, with help from the Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning on his way to work, Cruz saw how Santiago had
changed. Bodies were piled on the streets, riddled with bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz believes soldiers left them to intimidate opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep never came easily. The rustle of leaves on the sidewalk,
car doors slamming, reminded Cruz that the secret police could take
him away at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 4, 1974, Cruz and his wife, Alicia, awoke after midnight
to the sound of doors flying open. In the shadows, Cruz saw a dozen
soldiers pointing rifles at his head.
</P>
<P>
   They bound him with wire, threw him into the back of a truck and
covered him with straw. His captors drove him to a prison a few
blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was over,'' Cruz recalled. ``I thought that I
didn't deserve death but if they thought I did, then I'd have to
accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times each day, guards demanded information about Cruz's
colleagues. He refused each time, prompting them to shake his body
with electricity or pummel his head.
</P>
<P>
   At least four agencies shared in the torturing. The way Cruz
remembers it, they had a rivalry to see who was the bloodiest.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, he survived. At one point, he was thrown into a cell
with a veterinarian. Cruz's head was one big wound. The skin on the
veterinarian's wrists had been nearly scraped away. The vet advised
that they urinate on each other's wounds _ the only way to
sterilize them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day was our own little war for survival,'' Cruz said.
``We thought that if we could survive the torture, that meant we
were winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz was transferred to the Puchuncavi concentration camp. He
was released and made his way to Kansas City in April 1977 with
help from the same agency that brought Ramirez over.
</P>
<P>
   The memories from the camp remain vivid.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, a Spanish priest was held in a nearby cell. For
three days, the man was beaten after refusing to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speak because it is against my beliefs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, he repeated the reply.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Cruz learned that the priest had promised his colleagues
he would hold out for at least three days. That way, they'd have
time to move to safety. On the fourth day, the priest spoke. Two
hours later, he died.
</P>
<P>
   His phrase still echoes in Cruz's mind:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speak because it is against my beliefs.'' (break
here)`We should never forget' (begin text here)Luis Ramirez was
waiting at Kansas City's airport when Cruz's family arrived. Jewish
Family &AMP; Children Services, a Kansas City agency, had sponsored
both families.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz couldn't remember Ramirez's name, but he hadn't forgotten
his face from Puchuncavi. Ramirez was standing in the terminal with
a small Chilean flag and a sign that read, in Spanish: ``Welcome to
Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It meant a lot to me to see him there,'' Cruz said.
</P>
<P>
   Life has changed over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz, 61, and Ramirez, 52, live in comfortable homes just miles
apart. They don't shudder when a car drives by anymore. A knock on
the door means welcoming a friend, not fearing an enemy.
</P>
<P>
   But their experiences have taken their toll. Because of the
torture, Silvia Ramirez cannot have children. Both families left
relatives behind.
</P>
<P>
   They look on sadly as Chile wrestles with Pinochet's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Many Pinochet supporters say bringing the general to justice
will only cause instability. His following remains strong and many
credit Pinochet with fighting communism and strengthening the
economy. The Chilean government has resisted Pinochet's extradition
and trial. Chilean natives in Kansas City have not reached a
consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez says he understands why some want to forget the past so
the nation can heal. But he cannot agree, especially when he sees
history repeating itself in Bosnia and other places.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can forget that I was tortured. I can forget that there were
nights when I would lie awake, not knowing if I was going to
live,'' Ramirez said. ``I can forget that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But somebody is responsible for that. This isn't a Chilean
problem, it's a problem for humanity,'' he said. ``If they permit
butchers like this to be free, then there is a possibility that
this will continue to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that we need to forget,'' he added, ``but there are
some things that we should never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
