<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9710 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     11-02 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAVING BLANKS IN YOUR RESUME A BAD STRATEGY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, CA 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Question: I changed careers and will soon graduate
from a technical school. On my resume, the career counselor said to
emphasize my recent training, list only a few of my previous jobs
in general terms, and write a statement saying that I am energetic,
a team player and so forth. She said the details can be provided
when I fill out an application blank. How does this sound to you?
B.L. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Answer: It sounds like the career counselor is missing a few
details. By definition, a resume provides a summary of your work
experience, not just an overview of recent education, a few
selected jobs and a self-serving statement that could easily be
interpreted as wishful thinking. Besides, a well-written chronology
of your previous jobs and responsibilities is a far more credible
indicator of your energy and team orientation.
</P>
<P>
   When employers see vague resumes, the typical interpretation is
that important information is being intentionally withheld. The
typical result is that the resume ends up in the ``thanks, but no
thanks'' pile. So much for that opportunity to fill in the details
on the application blank.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to keep in mind that a resume is a sales tool
that should entice the reader to get in touch with you. A clear,
thorough and professional-looking resume can do just that. You are
making a productive career change, and this is no time to be
shortchanged by a counterproductive resume.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a teacher at a small, nonprofit school. The director
hired her daughter five years ago and treats her with great
favoritism. Some very good teachers have been fired or not hired
back because the daughter has a problem getting along with them.
What can those of us who have walked on eggs around this daughter
do to change this situation? The board of the school has many
parents who see the problem and want to fix it. M.H.
</P>
<P>
   A: If the board members are aware of a serious problem but have
taken no action to deal with it, then they are a serious problem,
too. Either they do not know or do not want to know what is going
on, or they are aware of what is happening and either cannot or
will not do anything about it. In any of these cases, the board is
acting in the role of follower rather than leader. And by doing so,
they are condoning the questionable practices that are forcing so
many people to walk on eggs.
</P>
<P>
   To attempt to unscramble this mess, you and your fellow teachers
as a group should meet initially with the favored daughter and, if
necessary, with the director to discuss the situation and see if
there is a basis to resolve it among yourselves.
</P>
<P>
   If you are still forced to do the egg-walk, you and your
colleagues should meet with the board. Give it specific examples of
the practices that are undermining the school's mission and
objectives, along with some suggestions to correct the matter. If
nothing changes after you have spoken to the board, then accept the
fact that the board has spoken. It is up to you to decide what to
do with what you have heard.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I did an excellent job on a project and I expected some
appreciation from my manager. When I met with him afterward, all he
did was complain about minor matters that had nothing to do with
the project. This was upsetting, but I didn't say anything at the
time. Now I want to discuss it. How should I do it? J.E.
</P>
<P>
   A: While the issue of how to do this is important, the issue of
when to do it is even more important. The best time to have this
type of discussion is as close to the incident as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, since the incident is still bothering you, there
are some key pointers to remember. First, it is easy to make the
mistake of directly telling your manager that you would have
appreciated some thanks for your excellent work. This type of
approach can easily elicit a degrading comment about your being
overly needy or a few hollow words of appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   A better strategy is to meet with him and ask for some feedback
on your project. If you did an excellent job, this is a way to get
some meaningful thanks without having to beg. And if your manager
felt that your work was not so excellent, this approach allows him
to give you some guidance to improve your performance in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it is best to approach him with questions rather
than answers. By doing so, you are more likely to generate
solutions rather than problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
