<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV08-975&AMP;DD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL BRIEFS: TRAVEL NEWS ABOUT GERMANY, PUERTO RICO, GREAT
BRITAIN AND WASHINGTON, D.C. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Nov. 8)  
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The year 2000 will draw almost half a million visitors to the
small Bavarian village of Oberammergau for the Passion Play, which
will be performed from May to October. Every 10 years, the
production, which begins with Christ's arrival in Jerusalem and
ends with the Resurrection and Transfiguration, is held outdoors in
the Alpine village. This production faithfully follows a tradition
of more than 350 years, though the play itself has been revised in
recent years to eliminate anti-Semitic stereotypes. In 1633, the
town elders vowed to perform the Passion if God spared the village
from a plague.
</P>
<P>
   The cast, choir and orchestra will be made up of more than 2,000
of the village's 5,200 residents. The costumes, set design and
organization are also exclusively in the hands of residents who
have either been born in Oberammergau or have lived there at least
20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The play takes place in the outdoor village theater, which has
sheltered seating for about 4,700 people. Although the stage is
uncovered, performances are not postponed for rain. Each
performance is scheduled to start between 9 and 9:30 a.m. and end
at approximately 5:30 p.m., with a three-hour lunch break. Tickets
are $65 and $97; $211 and $340 with one night's stay; $262 and $482
for two nights (including a booking fee). Pre-booked tickets are
expected to be sold out by early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For tickets and more information, contact the Geschaftsstell der
Passionsspiele 2000, 9A Eugen-Papst Strasse, 82487 Oberammergau,
Germany; telephone (49-8822) 92310, fax (49-8822) 923190, or
www.oberammergau.de/passione.htm.
</P>
<P>
   _ MARINA BARTL &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Coming to a Hotel Near You: Golden Door
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago, the Golden Door Spa started toning the bodies
of affluent women in Southern California and went on to become a
top name in luxury health and fitness. Now, the spa is doing the
stretching. It was recently acquired by Grand Bay Hotels and
Resorts _ operated by Patriot American Hospitality _ which plans to
open a Golden Door Spa for both men and women in each of its
resorts and hotels. It starts with Las Casitas Village in Puerto
Rico on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Bay expects to open another Golden Door this winter in the
new Grand Bay Hotel, Toronto. Grand Bay is also planning hotels
with Golden Doors in Philadelphia, Chicago and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Door's founder, Deborah Szekely, based her spa on the
Honjin inns of Japan, stressing personalized service and
therapeutic treatments like massage and baths. The spa, in
Escondido, Calif., became known for its healthful cuisine and
weeklong fitness programs limited to 39 guests _ women only, except
for two sessions a year.
</P>
<P>
   At Las Casitas Village, the 25,000-square-foot spa will be open
to men and women. It has 24 treatment rooms, a movement studio,
exercise classes, a fitness-assessment area and a tearoom. The spa
is free for Las Casitas guests, but there will be charges for such
treatments as aromatherapy massages ($95 for 50 minutes), an
anti-oxidant pineapple polish ($99 for 50 minutes, $150 for 80
minutes) and an ambrosia facial ($99 and $150).
</P>
<P>
   The resort, which opens in mid-November after a month's delay
caused partly by Hurricane Georges, has 90 one-, two- and
three-bedroom casitas with full kitchens and balconies on a
300-foot bluff in Fajardo, on Puerto Rico's northeast coast.
Nightly rates range from $435 to $2,290.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Bay's existing properties, which will also get Golden
Doors, are the Grand Bay Hotel Coconut Grove, Miami; The Boulders,
Carefree, Ariz.; the Lodge at Ventana Canyon, Tucson, Ariz.; the
Peaks, Telluride, Colo.; and Carmel Valley Ranch, Carmel, Calif.
Call (888) 472-6229 for reservations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ray Cormier &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Armor, Wooden Horses at Tower of London
</P>
<P>
   The White Tower, the part of the Tower of London complex
containing the Royal Armories' collection of armor and armaments of
Britain's kings and queens, will reopen Friday following a
three-year renovation. For the first time in 30 years, the White
Tower will now be devoted exclusively to the display of the
collection historically connected to the tower.
</P>
<P>
   Nine galleries on the four floors of the 90-foot White Tower
have been designed to help visitors understand the tower's history,
dating back to 1080 when William the Conqueror started work on the
fortress.
</P>
<P>
   An introduction gallery will use computer imagery to show how
the White Tower has changed in design and function over the
centuries. Besides having been a royal palace, a prison for royalty
and the aristocracy (including Anne Boleyn and Sir Walter Raleigh)
and the place where both ceremonial and practical armor and
weaponry were kept, the tower housed the Royal Observatory in 1675
and was a repository for gunpowder in the 17th century. In
addition, the chapel was periodically used to store state records.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Armories' collection of Tudor and Stuart armor, in
another gallery, includes Charles I's gilt armor as well as highly
decorated pieces made for various princes.
</P>
<P>
   Other exhibits include Henry VIII's tournament armor, and
weapons and instruments of torture including an executioner's axe
and the block used at the last public beheading in 1747.
</P>
<P>
   Also on display are 12 life-size 17th-century wooden horses not
seen since the end of the 19th century. Known as The Line of Kings,
the exhibit shows surviving pieces depicting the good monarchs of
England that were carved by some of the country's finest craftsmen
including Grinling Gibbons, England's great 17th-century
woodcarver, whose work is currently on exhibition at the Victoria
and Albert until Jan 24.
</P>
<P>
   The museum will be included in the Tower complex admission,
which is $16.25; children under 16, $10.75. Information: (800)
806-7187.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Treasures From Ancient Edo in Washington
</P>
<P>
   Japan, 1615-1868: For the first time in centuries, the country
was united under the Tokugawa shoguns, who governed during a period
of unprecedented peace and prosperity from their new capital, Edo,
which grew into the world's largest city in the 18th century and is
now Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Art flourished, too. Now nearly 300 painted scrolls, screens,
costumes, ceremonial armor, sculpture, ceramics, lacquerware and
woodblock prints from this rich period, drawn from 75 public and
private Japanese collections, will be on view from Sunday to Feb.
15 at the National Gallery of Art in Washington. ``Edo: Art in
Japan 1615-1868'' is the first comprehensive survey in the United
States of Edo period art. Many pieces are National Treasures that
have never before left Japan. Some are sensitive to light, and will
be rotated, between Jan. 6 and 12.
</P>
<P>
   To establish the tone of high style and buoyant spirits
characteristic of Edo art, the exhibition will open with a display
of gold lacquerware, embroidered and painted kimonos and a section
of colorful gold-leaf screens that define the period's esthetics.
One screen, Sakai Hoitsu's ``Spring and Autumn Maples,'' has never
before been exhibited, even in Japan. Next come samurai rooms,
showing the peaceful arts created for the warrior class; a work
section, with images of urban and rural occupations; a religion
area, with works illustrating Buddhist and Shinto beliefs; a travel
and landscape area, focusing on paintings of beautiful sites, and
entertainment galleries, with works depicting fashionable actors,
sumo wrestlers and geisha as well as bold costumes.
</P>
<P>
   To complete the picture of daily life during the Edo period, the
National Gallery has scheduled a free performing-arts festival in
and around the museum throughout November. Festival dancers will
perform a lion dance, firemen-acrobats will present a traditional
fire-safety ceremony, and actors will explain Kabuki and other
traditional performing arts.
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery, Fourth Street and Constitution Avenue,
N.W., is open daily. Admission is free, but passes for the
exhibition will be required on weekends, holidays, the Friday after
Thanksgiving and the week following Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Advance passes can be obtained at the National Gallery (no fee)
or at Ticketmaster locations ($2 per pass). Passes may be obtained
from Ticketmaster, (800) 551-7328, outside the Washington area, for
$2.75 per pass and $1.25 per order. A limited number of same-day
passes will be available at the Gallery's East Building on a
first-come, first-served basis; (202) 737-4215 or www.nga.gov.
</P>
<P>
   _ Judith H. Dobrzynski &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
