r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILEANS-REMEMBER-2TA     11-02 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILEANS-REMEMBER-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET'S FATE ATTRACTS SPECIAL INTEREST AMONG SOME KC AREA
RESIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (KANSAS CITY, MO.) _ Marco Cruz and Luis Ramirez shared a dream.
Both men _ one a construction worker, the other an educator _
wanted social justice for Chile.
</P>
<P>
   They shared a nightmare, too.
</P>
<P>
   Both were tortured in the 1970s for opposing the dictatorship of
Augusto Pinochet. Cruz was dragged from his bedroom at gunpoint,
Ramirez was hauled out of his classroom.
</P>
<P>
   For months, both men were beaten, shocked with electricity and
threatened with death. They crossed paths in the Puchuncavi
concentration camp, near the town of Quintero, in 1976. They
arrived in Kansas City, Mo., months later.
</P>
<P>
   Their hopes for justice were raised this month when Pinochet was
arrested in Britain on Oct. 16 and charged with genocide, torture
and terrorism. But last week, a British court ruled that Pinochet
had diplomatic immunity. Prosecutors will present an appeal this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights officials estimate that about 3,000 people died
during Pinochet's 17-year reign. Amnesty International says ``the
human rights violations _ which include thousands of cases of
torture, extrajudicial execution and `disappearances' _ constitute
crimes against humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on those days, Cruz closes his eyes and speaks
softly. He is angry, but his voice does not rise. He describes
guards mocking their captives. He recounts the pleas for mercy that
torturers ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all that, how does Pinochet have the right to ask for
mercy on humanitarian grounds?'' wonders Cruz, who lives in Kansas
City, Mo. ``It's not just for what happened to us. It's not just
the killing, not just the disappearances. It's the suffering of an
entire country for 17 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz said Pinochet killed more than his loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   He killed a nation's hopes.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1970 and the new president, Salvador Allende,
entered office with promises of creating a socialist utopia. Cruz
and Ramirez, strangers at the time, took the ideals to heart. Both
campaigned for Allende.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the nation's elite and military eyed the changes
nervously. So did the Nixon White House. Some thought the
starry-eyed Allende, who professed himself a Marxist, would land
Chile in the Soviet camp.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz had followed his father into the construction business. He
hoped Allende would improve not just salaries but working
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez designed the curriculum for the Chilean equivalent of a
community college. He hoped Allende would expand education to all.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 22, 1973, both men learned that Pinochet had led a
bloody coup, backed by the CIA, that left Allende dead and the
nation in military hands. Soldiers were filling the streets. On
opposite sides of the capital city of Santiago, they eyed the
future uneasily.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go from being a free man with hope to a man living in
fear, seeing who's watching you, who's passing in front of your
house,'' said Ramirez, who lives in Prairie Village, Kan. ``Just
like that, our lives changed.''
(break here)`Do what it takes to live' (begin text here)The coup
instantly made targets of Ramirez and his wife, Silvia. Ramirez had
been part of Allende's educational bureaucracy and a union
organizer.
</P>
<P>
   The Ramirezes moved from Santiago and started teaching at a high
school in a small town. They worked quietly there for several
months.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon in March 1975, some men came to Ramirez's
classroom door.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to talk to you,'' a voice intoned.
</P>
<P>
   Panicked students rushed next door to tell Silvia Ramirez her
husband was being taken away. She looked out just in time to see
it.
</P>
<P>
   Someone apparently had revealed Luis Ramirez's name during
torture. Soldiers brought him to a vacant country mansion called
Villa Grimaldi, where prisoners were kept in metal closets to the
sound of constant screaming.
</P>
<P>
   One day, Ramirez was stunned to see that two of his captors were
former students. The young men, through pained eyes, recognized
their teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The men taught Ramirez a different sort of lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They taught me how to survive a torture, how to stay alive,''
Ramirez said. ``I learned that you have to do what it takes to
live.''
</P>
<P>
   They told him which torturers were incompetent. And they advised
Ramirez to be a sissy. Scream once the electrical shocks start. The
more unfazed you seem, the more the guards will increase the
voltage.
</P>
<P>
   Silvia Ramirez also was tortured. While Luis Ramirez was
confined, she protested with other spouses, a movement that drew
international attention. In May 1976, under pressure from the
United States, Chile freed Ramirez and other prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez was taken directly from the Puchuncavi concentration
camp to the airport. An old black-and-white photo shows his blank
stare as he climbed the stairs into the jet. A government agent
followed.
</P>
<P>
   The family ended up in Kansas City when a local social-service
agency sponsored their trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to rebuild the lives we had,'' Silvia
Ramirez said. (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
