<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GOVERNOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS LEARN LITTLE FROM BIG SPENDERS IN CALIFORNIA RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When state Republican Party Chairman Michael
Schroeder heard about a new initiative that would ban bilingual
education in public schools, he implored its authors to keep the
potentially divisive issue off this year's. They complied.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with Republican Attorney General Dan Lungren trailing
Democratic Lt. Gov. Gray Davis in the polls, the GOP might look
fondly to the days of wedge-issue politics.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. Pete Wilson _ who is barred bar law from seeking
a third term _ sensed the mood of middle-class white voters in
1994, and successfully rode Proposition 187, the anti-immigration
initiative, to a huge second-term victory over Democrat Kathleen
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, in contrast, Lungren and Davis are left to
fight over nothing but the tired ghosts of their own pasts, with no
controversial ballot initiative shadowing the race. The result has
been one of the most conventional gubernatorial campaigns in recent
memory.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Lungren, each with a long history of public service,
presented a campaign between a moderate and a conservative, between
the status quo and change.
</P>
<P>
   ``In comparison to past elections, there are no hugely divisive
propositions on the ballot,'' said Ann Crigler, director of the
Jesse Unruh School of Politics at the University of Southern
California. ``And at this point, we're in kind of a period of
recouping our sense of normalcy, or at least trying not to
antagonize groups.''
</P>
<P>
   When the bills are finally counted, the four major candidates
for California governor are expected to have spent a record $110
million on the campaign this year, mostly on television
advertising. What did voters learn about financier Al Checchi and
Rep. Jane Harman, who challenged Davis in the Democratic primary,
and Lungren?
</P>
<P>
   Not much, according to analysts and partisan observers.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Checchi's 90-page ``Checchi Plan'' and a few largely
ignored policy addresses from Davis and Lungren, voters have
received more of a history lesson than a blueprint for change in
the most diverse, most populous, richest and, in some ways, most
troubled state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was not one issue on the ballot drowning out what the
candidates were trying to say, and it presented a unique
opportunity to talk about the future of this state into the next
millennium,'' said Mark Petracca, a political scientist at the
University of California at Irvine. ``And yet it didn't happen.
This was a real missed opportunity by both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps because of the times, Californians got a race from
the 20th century, not for the 21st. Voters believe _ by a margin of
2-to-1 _ that the state is headed in the right direction, according
to a poll by the San Francisco-based Public Policy Institute of
California. An even larger number _ 73 percent _ told pollsters
they expected the state's economy to either stay the same or get
better.
</P>
<P>
   Without a wedge issue, a faltering economy or runaway crime,
Lungren took his campaign to the days when then-Gov. Jerry Brown
was denounced as too liberal and Republican governors began a reign
that lasted another 16 years. Although Lungren was seeking to
continue Republican rule, he became the challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren returned Californians to a time when the liberal
moonbeam governor jetted to Africa with rock stars and left people
like Davis, his former chief of staff, in charge. He invoked the
spirit of Ronald Reagan and then ridiculed Brown, former state
Supreme Court Chief Justice Rose Bird and liberal state lawmaker
Tom Hayden.
</P>
<P>
   After all that energy spent attacking Jerry Brown, Lungren must
have flinched when he read a recent Los Angeles Times poll showing
voters thought more highly of Brown, now the mayor-elect of
Oakland, than they did of him.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren kept looking backward. His campaign theme alleged that
Davis was not tough enough in supporting the state's ``three
strikes'' law _ an issue from three years ago. Lungren also
questions Davis' commitment to the death penalty, which the Supreme
Court made legal again more than two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren rode that horse from June to November, but voters ended
up thinking both candidates would handle crime in about the same
tough manner.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Davis' campaign was vintage Wilson. Davis became the
incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   He took one look at the polls and discovered what voters wanted
to hear about _ education. He attacked his opponent with wedge
issues of his own _ abortion and assault weapons. He stayed on
message, and didn't get into specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Garry South, the Davis campaign manager, said when voters are
asked in focus groups and polls which candidate has the most
experience to be governor, they picked Davis by a 2-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an election,'' South said, ``that I think by and large
is going to benefit incumbents. And even though this is an open
seat, Gray Davis is the closest thing you have to an incumbent in
this election.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
