<HEADER>
A9735 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHN-MELLENCAMP-LADN     11-02 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHN-MELLENCAMP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELLENCAMP REMAINS A VOICE OF A VANISHED ERA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BY FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Fashion is dead, the supermodels thing is over,
and there are no more rock stars. I hope you enjoyed it 'cause it's
all gone now.''
</P>
<P>
   To be honest, the only person complaining about it seems to be
heartland rocker John Mellencamp, who spoke those words the other
day.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he's still plugging away. Mellencamp's self-titled
new album, his first for Columbia Records after 22 years with
PolyGram, reveals a return to the rootsy, guitar-driven rock that
made him famous after a techno-enhanced detour two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock 'n' roll isn't the music that matters anymore,''
Mellencamp, 47, said. ``It's just another genre today. When I was a
kid, rock music examined the country, reported the condition the
nation was in, told us who we were, told us everything. Those days
are over. The boomers have grown up and they're a passive audience.
The record stores we all flocked to are in bankruptcy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly true that rock has lost ground to sales leaders
like rap and pop over the last five years. In this week's top 10,
for example, seven songs are rap or r&AMP;b-derived.
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp says this cheerfully, his positive, accepting
attitude also reflected in the new record, which was strongly
influenced by a series of changes in his life _ his happy marriage
to his wife, Elaine, with whom he's raising two young sons; the
physical, emotional and spiritual rehabilitation from a heart
attack that forced an abrupt end to a relentless rock 'n' roll
lifestyle; the softening of a grinding tour schedule; and the
dissolution of his long relationship with his former label.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, when PolyGram signed me, it was a case of,
`We don't care if we don't make money on the first few records,'''
the Seymour, Ind.-born Mellencamp said. ``That thinking is extinct
now. If a label doesn't make money on an act right away, they're
gone. If I came along today, I doubt I'd be signed at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp's run on the charts began with 1982's ``American
Fool.'' In addition to his 36 gold, platinum and multiplatinum
awards from 1982-97, he has been nominated for 11 Grammys and
racked up seven top 10 albums and 10 top 10 singles with titles
like ``Pink Houses,'' ``Small Town,'' ``R.O.C.K. in the U.S.A.,''
``Hurts So Good'' and ``Jack &AMP; Diane.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Mellencamp supporters such as Bryon Jordan, a
29-year-old software engineer from Columbus, Ohio, insist the
singer-songwriter's best days are far from behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``John still has something to say,'' says Jordan, who runs a
Mellencamp mailing list on the Internet for roughly 800 members
around the world. ``If he didn't, I don't think he'd bother putting
out music, since he could probably do anything he wants at this
point. He's still very important to the fans who've remained with
him all these years. Almost the entire `Human Wheels' album still
amazes me today, five years after it came out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock radio veteran Jim Ladd says ``Your Life Is Now,'' the first
single from Mellencamp's new record, ``is one of the best things
he's ever written. I love it. It's really a great song.''
</P>
<P>
   Ladd, heard locally at 6 p.m. on KLOS-FM (95.5), said Mellencamp
continues to be relevant in today's music scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has a lot to say,'' the DJ said.
</P>
<P>
   Long a fixture in the nation's stadiums, the former John Cougar
won't tour behind the new album until next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that's really the best time to go out,'' Mellencamp
explained. ``I enjoy performing outdoors the most. I spent so many
years in the arenas doing 120 shows a year. I may go back sometime,
but these days I prefer the venues where the suns shines and you're
not in some cavernous gymnasium with lockers and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp continues to pursue his hobby as a painter.
``Mellencamp: Painting and Reflections,'' a book showcasing 75 of
his works, has just been published by HarperCollins. Profits are
earmarked for music education in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good cause,'' Mellencamp said from his home in
Bloomington, Ind. ``How can kids learn anything about music if
they're not exposed to it?''
</P>
<P>
   Equally, how can a new generation know anything about Mellencamp
if he's not on radio or MTV? The singer-painter isn't optimistic
about the state of the music business in late '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``To these kids, I'm Dean Martin,'' he said. ``You're going to
see groups come and go like Matchbox 20 until there's another
generation that's energetic and motivated enough to change the
world like we did. I defy you to tell me the last time someone in
their 40s raced to a record store because they just had to have a
certain record. It just doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp takes a dig at the politics of today's youth on the
new album's hard-rocking ``Fruit Trader'': ``Ain't got no
morals/Ain't got no politics/Ain't got no particular point of
view/What I've got is plenty of time on my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   With luck, Mellencamp, too, will have plenty of time on his
hands. After suffering a major heart attack and close call with
death in late 1994, the singer spent a year recovering but refuses
to quit smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was bulletproof for years,'' he said. ``When
something like that happens, it really messes with your head to
hear you've got coronary heart disease. But stop smoking? Let's not
get crazy here now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
