<SLUG> BC-FASHIONSHOW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Little known fashion designer starting to turn some heads
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although designer Susan Lazar is far from being a
household name. She does, however, have enough clout in the
industry to be among the designers staging lavish, spring/summer
'99 runway shows this week in massive tents at Bryant Park.
</P>
<P>
   In order to continue her progression toward fashion phenom, it
was important for Lazar to show a solid collection on Monday. And
solid it was. Besides restricting herself almost exclusively to
clothes in pale pastel, cream and gray shades, Lazar also rendered
almost all of her looks in solids.
</P>
<P>
   This continues a trend in bucking trends among designers
worldwide. When the first wave of New York designers showed their
warm-weather collections in September, it appeared as if floral
prints and bold colors would be requisite inclusions in stylish
womens' wardrobes. Since then, British, Italian, French and, now,
more New York designers have declared that that ain't necessarily
so.
</P>
<P>
   The only prints Lazar showed were subtle ones: some of her
chiffon, ribbon strap sundresses and sleeveless tops were in
marbelized shades of lime green and fuscia. Mainly, she focused on
clothes in form-fitting silhouettes.
</P>
<P>
   Her skirt and dress hems grazed the knees. And she showed pants
in both wide-leg and ankle-hugging styles. Tops were cropped to
expose a bit of tummy, and her beltless pants swiveled on the hips.
</P>
<P>
   Every designer has tried to create revealing clothes, and Lazar
did her part by cutting ovular vents into the sides of tops and
making dresses with deep, plunging armholes.
</P>
<P>
   When the shapely, athletic-looking Lazar emerged from backstage
to accept applause wearing hip-hugging slacks and a skintight
sweater, it was immediately apparent that she's someone who
identifies with women who are proud of their bodies and appreciate
simplistic clothes that show off their physiques.
</P>
<P>
   In the show staged immediately after Lazar's, Carolina Herrera
showed a bevy of beautiful, body-conscious looks as well. She too
showed hippy, beltless slacks, clingy dresses and tops that flashed
a bit of navel.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of lavender lining peeked out from folds of her wrap-style
skirts and dresses. And she deftly combined colors like
bronze-and-fuscia or beige-and-lilac in sweater-skirt ensembles.
Most striking of all were Herrera's leather halters, jackets,
dresses and shirts shaded pink, baby blue and lilac.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera also had serious fun with her eveningwear styles.
Relying on variations on the tuxedo to convey the formal concept,
she cut the satin-lapeled jackets to look like jackets with the
sleeves rolled to the bicep, or paired them with slinky skirts. Her
ballgowns were tweeked as well: her wrapped satin skirts had
slouchy pockets and were worn with clubby, embroidered T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera didn't come far enough down the runway to show what kind
of shape her 50-something body's in. The rousing applause she
received after her show came by virtue of her body of work.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
