A9744 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN03-COX     11-02 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Expectations' from society shouldn't dictate a girl's choices
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The square in Dahlonega, Georgia seemed as good a place as any
to bring it up. Sunday was sunny and beautiful, but life is not
always blue skies. It is a grim business, and it was time they knew
it.
</P>
<P>
   Our daughter Alex and I had gone to Dahlonega for the day with
friends, who don't wish to be dragged into this nasty dispute but
look upon it with bemused wonder. He is a writer and translator,
she an engineer, and their daughter is a schoolmate of Alex's.
</P>
<P>
   On the drive up, Alex, Negin and I played time-killing games in
the back seat, with Negin's mother joining in from the sidelines
when the pickings seemed easy. I enjoy games in which you take a
word _ ``Elizabeth,'' for example _ and find in it as many other
words as you can. Both girls are 8 years old, and I dispatched them
with impressive ease.
</P>
<P>
   They fared somewhat better in the number games, which is why, as
we sat eating ice cream cones on the square, I decided the subject
could be put off no longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alex,'' I said, ``what do you want to be when you grow up?'' I
might have added, ``You haven't much more time, you know.'' But she
knows that when my tone takes on a certain gravity, we are into one
of my Life Is Serious lectures again.
</P>
<P>
   Both had ordered cones of mint chocolate chip, one with a squirt
of whipped cream on top. Licking pensively, Alex said: ``I'm going
to be either a teacher or a dancer. Haven't decided. But when we're
finished here, can we ride the ponies?''
</P>
<P>
   I was greatly troubled, of course. What father wouldn't be?
</P>
<P>
   Her friend hadn't even given it that much thought. ``I don't
know,'' Negin said, insouciant in the way only a child is allowed
to be.
</P>
<P>
   Already 8 years old and neither girl had any apparent interest
in soil mechanics _ a field in which women are severely
``underpresented'' _ or chemical engineering or physics. Very sad.
</P>
<P>
   I mention all this because of a column I wrote two weeks ago
about an ad campaign sponsored by the Women's College Coalition.
The ads call on parents to interest their daughters in science and
technology at an early age _ while they're still in the crib, for
all one knows. The implied point of the ads is clear: Women are not
proportionally represented in certain fields. Therefore, they are
being held back (maybe even oppressed!). It is the only possible
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The ads were less than explicit about exactly who was holding
them back, but a stream of e-mails from readers (some of them, I
should say) has cleared up all confusion. ``Society'' is holding
them back. Given a free choice, girls would go into engineering and
the sciences in the same numbers as boys. If only they had that
choice.
</P>
<P>
   The gist of the column, in so many words, was that maybe girls
aren't as interested as we think they must be. Nature and nurture
obviously interpenetrate, and none of us is equipped to say where
the one leaves off and the other takes over. But try telling some
people that.
</P>
<P>
   From Southern Polytechnic State University (a school I had never
heard of) came the quite remarkable ruminations of someone named A.
Bowdoin Van Riper. Best that we let this gentlemen speak in his own
words:
</P>
<P>
   ``Feminism, from Mary Wollstonecraft on down, has always been
about opportunity. Arguing that girls today have as much
`opportunity' to study science and technology as boys do is as
specious as arguing that, in the Jim Crow era, Southern blacks had
as much `opportunity' to vote as Southern whites.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there is a contention that requires no response. And it's a
good thing: What could one say?
</P>
<P>
   But something sticks in my mind. The mother of Alex's friend was
telling me later, ``You know, when Negin said she didn't know what
she wanted to be when she grew up, that made me feel good. I'm glad
she doesn't.'' I hadn't thought about it in that way, but here was
an accomplished woman saying she was happy to see her daughter a
child still. There was time for her to enjoy many things, and find
out which way her heart pulled her.
</P>
<P>
   What is contemptible is the idea that she _ or any child _ must
conform to someone else's expectations. ``I am a female in a
traditionally white male profession (forestry),'' Kate Robie wrote
me, ``and I am weary of the notion that something is `wrong'
because the demographics of our profession don't match the
demographics of society.''
</P>
<P>
   For this reader, the greater problem is the images of
``successful'' women we get from advertising and popular culture _
``hip, stylish and sexy rather than bright and capable.'' No
argument, although parallel images of boys are also propagated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing,'' as Robie says, ``is that we do away
with institutional barriers to women and minorities. If we are
barrier-free and certain groups are still under-represented, well,
gee, I guess different people like different things. So what?''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the square in Dahlonega, under the bluest sky of the
fall, it was hard to imagine why some people worry about the things
they do. Maybe their lives really are that grim.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
