<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Updike: Wolfe's novel `not literature'
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this week's issue of The New Yorker ($3), one literary
heavyweight _ John Updike _ weighs in on another _ Tom Wolfe _
declaring ``A Man in Full'' to be ``entertainment, not
literature.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 25 years ago, Updike writes, ``Wolfe chastised his
writing contemporaries with ignoring most of the American reality,
the brawling socioeconomic and power-crazed vastness of it,
concerning themselves instead with trivial introspective exercises.
`A Man in Full' is a brave, flamboyant effort to practice what he
preached.''
</P>
<P>
   The novel surrounds the reader like the modern equivalent of the
Cyclorama, Updike says, with detailed descriptions of Atlanta,
Oakland, Calif., and the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much local information, so many well-lighted settings, so
much news do not quite knit into a novel powered by the human
spirit as it gropes and struggles for focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Updike praises Wolfe's muscular prose and ambitious scope, but
concludes that the novel, like ``a movie desperate to recoup its
bankers' investment,'' tries too hard to please us.
</P>
<P>
   Updike's review is entertaining enough, but in this issue
there's more great writing for the literary-minded. In an
insightful essay on the books Ernest Hemingway never wanted us to
read, Joan Didion questions the decision to publish an unfinished
novel next year _ a novel that the author obviously thought was not
ready for publication. And Michael Knight has written a delightful
short story about a blonde, parrots and football in Elbow, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   X MARKS THE SPOT: Editors are constantly looking for ways to
repackage their magazines to appeal to different target groups.
That's why the November issue of Men's Health ($2.95) has different
cover lines for subscribers and newsstand customers. Newsstand
issues featured a cover line that reads, ``Put More X in Your
Sex,'' while the cover sent to subscribers and advertisers reads,
``Natural sex boosters'' and ``No more backaches.'' Editor Michael
Lafavore, who wrote the cover lines, explains that newsstand buyers
tend to be younger and more impulsive. The article, by the way, is
about herbal supplements that may help your sex drive.
</P>
<P>
   FOUNDING FATHER: Speaking of sex, if you're interested in more
details about Thomas Jefferson's intimate life, take a look at U.S.
News &AMP; World Report ($2.95). The magazine, which revealed the DNA
results indicating Jefferson fathered several children by his slave
Sally Hemings, includes a detailed account of how professor Eugene
A. Foster conducted his research.
</P>
<P>
   ALANIS AGAIN: Three years after her smash hit album, ``Jagged
Little Pill,'' Alanis Morissette is back with a new album and a new
look: nude. Entertainment Weekly ($2.95) talks with the 24-year-old
rock star about her CD and her controversial video. Also of note:
The cast of ``The Big Chill'' tells all on the 15th anniversary of
the film.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEWSWEEKLIES: Time's ($2.95) first installment of a
multipart series on corporate welfare offers some startling facts
for the average American. While Congress has reduced welfare for
individuals and families, big business continues to cash in to the
tune of $125 billion a year. This costs every working adult the
equivalent of two weekly paychecks a year. According to Time
reporters Donald Barlett and James B. Steele, ``It has turned
politicians into bribery specialists and smart business people into
con artists.'' Elsewhere, Time reports that the supermodel is dead,
replaced by anonymous, gangly teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek ($2.95) lists the tech cities that are challenging
Silicon Valley. Among the hottest: Austin, Texas; Boise, Idaho; and
Tel Aviv, Israel.
</P>
<P>
   NEW LOOK: The content is as conservative as ever, but National
Review ($3.50) has a new ``reader-friendly'' design. Featured on
the cover of the Nov. 9 issue is a series of articles on what went
wrong with the global market, and an insightful handicapping of
Republican presidential hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
