<P>
   HURRICANE-DEATHS (Chinandega, Nicaragua) _ Overwhelmed by death
and chaos, Central American officials estimate that more than 7,000
people have died in floods and mudslides triggered by Hurricane
Mitch. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   ELN-RDP (Undated) _ The final day of campaigning: The polls, the
stakes, the key races. After a campaign season distinguished more
by President Clinton's tribulations than by any raging national
issues, Americans will trickle, if not stream, to the polls on
Tuesday in a mid-term election that will inevitably be interpreted
as a referendum on the fate of the president. By Richard L. Berke.
With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ELN-NONVOTERS (Ottawa, Ill.) _ In the town where the
Lincoln-Douglas debates took place in 1858, Dirk Johnson talks with
those people who say they won't vote _ they're disaffected, they
feel their vote doesn't make any difference, they're disgusted with
their own parties. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TRIAL (Undated) _ Developments at the Microsoft trial.
Bill Gates, confronted with memos he wrote or received, denies in
videotaped testimony played in court that the software giant set
out to undermine competitors to gain a competitive edge. By Steven
Lohr and Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-RECRUITING (Waldorf, Md.) _ The armed forces face a
crisis in recruiting. The Navy fell 10 percent short of its goal
this year. Congress last week poured money into more recruiters and
new ads, but many believe the military faces a much deeper problem:
It just doesn't loom large in the lives of young people and their
families. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-BOOM (Boston) _ Boston, of course, would never do
anything so utterly uncouth as to boom. But consider: Big cranes
are in such demand here these days that builders have been looking
for them as far West as the Mississippi. Architects are in short
supply. Downtown commercial real estate has the lowest vacancy rate
in the country and the highest average rental rates, topping even
San Francisco and Manhattan. Many aging northern cities are booming
these days, say urban experts _ at least, compared to the decay of
past decades. By Carey Goldberg. 2,300 words. With graphic.
</P>
</TEXT>
