<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HDTV-SIDEBAR1R-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURRENT TV SETS HEADED FOR OBSOLENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES &UR;  &LR; _ You may not know it, but the television set you
watch tonight is obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it'll work fine for the next several years. But the Federal
Communications Commission wants to toss analog television sets _
the kind you've been watching for probably your entire life _ onto
the ash heap of history.
</P>
<P>
   To help force the issue, the FCC gave the television industry,
and TV watchers, eight years to go digital. In 2006, the FCC said
wants to turn off the transmitters sending signals that current TV
sets understand.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's a total fantasy,'' said Josh Bernoff, a principal
analyst for Forrester Research who follows digital television
issues. ``No one in the industry believes that.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because most industry observers think that consumers,
people like you, aren't going to be rushing out to buy
astronomically expensive high-definition television sets any time
soon, especially when there isn't much to watch.
</P>
<P>
   It's something of a chicken-and-egg problem: HDTV prices won't
drop until consumers start buying lots of them. Consumers won't buy
lots of TVs until prices drop and there's lots of cool programming
to watch. Broadcasters won't create lots of cool programming until
there are lots of HDTVs in people's homes. See ya in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Sony can get the cost of those receivers down where the
consumer can walk in and buy a set for $500,'' broadcasters will
create the high-definition programming that will draw more
customers in, said Dan Corsini, general manager and vice president
of KCAL-TV (Channel 9). &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LONG ROAD AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   Some analyst see the problems facing HDTV as similar to the
difficulties that plagued color TV. First introduced in 1954, it
took until the '60s for both the technical and programming bugs to
be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Bernoff and the Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association
both estimate that less than half the country will have digital TV
sets by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really think Congress can ask broadcasters to turn off
their signals when more than half the homes aren't digital, you're
pretty naive, Bernoff said. ``It's just a means of putting the
pressure on, that's all. The end of analog is more likely to be
2015.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, today's kickoff of the digital television age brings
some tempting hints of the era to come.
</P>
<P>
   Already, companies such as Thomson Consumer Electronics, which
owns RCA and the upscale ProScan lines, are making the transition.
Thomson just announced it will spend $20 million to convert its
picture tube plant in Indiana to digital production.
</P>
<P>
   And Microsoft is extremely interested in television's digital
revolution, according to company executives. Microsoft already owns
WebTV _ which inexpensively and simply allows Internet Web sites to
be displayed on a television set _ and has bundled a WebTV-like
video player in Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also wants to provide the software that will run the
coming generation of digital set-top converter boxes. Microsoft's
marketplace muscle and ability to create or buy genre-spanning
technologies may hasten digital
</P>
<P>
   TV's spread.
</P>
<P>
   MAGIC BOX?
</P>
<P>
   The set-top box, once just a simple device to get cable channels
to a television, may in fact become the entertainment center of the
future _ and both quickly and cheaply, Bernoff said.
</P>
<P>
   That machine _ probably costing as little as $150 by 2001 _
could not only bring in HDTV signals but also connect to the
Internet, the home computer and cable provider, play DVD movies and
games, and give access to ``ancillary and supplementary services''
the FCC envisioned in ordering the digital conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Those additional services would be tucked into the spare
bandwidth on broadcasters' frequency and could include such things
as extra channels, CD-quality audio, sports information, computer
software, phone directories, stock-market updates and interactive
educational materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, a broadcaster could transmit a news program
consisting of four separate SDTV programs for local news, national
news, weather and sports, while interrupting that programming with
a single high-definition TV commercial with embedded data about the
product,'' the FCC order says.
</P>
<P>
   The first network program to take advantage of these
possibilities will air next week on PBS, though it won't be shown
here because KCET's digital transmitter isn't running yet.
</P>
<P>
   PBS' Frank Lloyd Wright documentary isn't in high-definition,
but it will include several hundred megabytes of
computer-accessible information about his life and work, including
virtual walk-throughs of his most famous buildings, said PBS
spokeswoman Dara Goldberg. PBS hopes to use such an approach in
many of its programs in the hope that schools in particular will be
able to take advantage of the additional broadcast information to
flesh out students' understanding of subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Sports and educational programs, both of which are
information-heavy, are perfect for such enhanced programming,
observers said. But the best stuff probably hasn't been imagined
yet. For that, stay tuned. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
