<HEADER>
A9774 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLAIR-SCHROEDER-BOS &LR;      11-02 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLAIR-SCHROEDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHROEDER MEETS BLAIR, PLEDGES NEW ERA OF COOPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In his first official trip abroad, Gerhard Schroeder,
the newly elected German chancellor, met with his political soul
mate, British Prime Minister Tony Blair, and promised a new era of
cooperation between Britain and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders engaged in a mutual admiration society at 10
Downing St. during talks on improving relations between their
governments, European integration, the introduction in January of a
single European currency, and the crises in Kosovo and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Just a week before Remembrance Day, when Britons honor those who
were killed fighting Germans in the two world wars, Blair and
Schroeder were a study in harmony. Schroeder even refrained from
criticizing Britain's reluctance to participate in the launch of
the single currency. He diplomatically described Britain's
reservations about monetary union as a ``clever approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair and Schroeder faced the media in The Durbar Court on King
Charles Street, just a few hundred feet from where Winston
Churchill and his Cabinet plotted strategy to defeat the Nazis
during World War II. But if Churchill had nothing good to say about
Hitler, Blair had nothing bad to say about Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   The only hint of the historic hostilities between the two
countries was a red poppy that Blair wore on his lapel in honor of
British war veterans. Many Britons wear poppies in anticipation of
Remembrance Day.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the left-of-center leaders agreed that their biggest
challenge is to foster competitive, market-based economies while
providing a social welfare system for the less fortunate. They
announced the formation of a task force to recommend ``practical
policies'' to nurture the ``Third Way,'' the term used to describe
the increasing pragmatism of formerly ideological-driven leftist
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Both men rose to power by moving their traditionally left-wing
parties toward the center to end lengthy conservative regimes. In
Blair's case, his Labor Party ended an 18-year reign by the
Conservatives, while Schroeder ousted Helmut Kohl, Europe's most
enduring leader, after 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders downplayed the significance when, in the first
days of his administration, Schroeder declined a Blair invitation
extended to him and French premier Lionel Jospin to visit Blair at
the Labor Party conference immediately after Schroeder's Social
Democrats won the German election in September. He visited France
instead, causing many to conclude that Schroeder was more concerned
about easing French fears about a weakened Franco-German
relationship than encouraging a closer Anglo-German axis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cooperation isn't aimed against anyone,'' said Schroeder.
Blair added, ``There's enough room for all sorts of relationships
in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men refused to be drawn into the controversy surrounding
the legal battle to extradite former Chilean dictator Augusto
Pinochet from London to Spain to face charges that he tortured and
killed political opponents during his 17-year regime.
</P>
<P>
   And they voiced strong support for American mediation efforts in
the Middle East and continued pressure on Iraq. Schroeder stressed
that forcing Iraq to comply with weapons monitoring was not ``about
a conflict between Iraq and the United States,'' but of
international concern.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl focused on building the Franco-German axis, in part because
he saw that the British were unenthusiastic about greater European
integration. In contrast, Schroeder's aides say he wants to help
Blair bring Britain deeper into the European Union so that London
can join Paris and Bonn in taking a leadership role.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperation between Germany and Britain ``is excellent,''
Schroeder insisted, ``but we can improve on that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 1848EST &QL; 
