A9778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURSTON-THEATER-REVIE     11-02 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURSTON-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ZORA NEALE HURSTON': REDISCOVERING A WRITER THROUGH HER OWN
WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
 (fb) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At first, the claims of the stooped over, clearly
down-and-out old woman in the bus station seem ludicrous. She sets
down her cheap suitcase and declares, ``I was the queen of the
Harlem Renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was. This is Elizabeth Van Dyke as the title character
in ``Zora Neale Hurston: A Theatrical Biography,'' Laurence
Holder's 1990 one-act play now in revival at the American Place
Theater. The production is both a disappointment and a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   When Van Dyke is reciting Hurston's words, she sometimes seems
on fire with feeling and the sheer joy of storytelling. In between,
narrating and acting out the outline of her character's life, she
is much less compelling. Her co-star in this two-actor production,
Joseph Edward, is appealing in multiple roles as all the men in
Hurston's life (including the poet Langston Hughes and the novelist
Richard Wright, who accused her of minstrelsy). But he, too, is at
his best when performing what seem to be Hughes' or Wright's own
words rather than the playwright's.
</P>
<P>
   The life story in question is a sad one. Hurston was a
preacher's daughter from Eatonville, Fla. (``the first town built
and governed by Negroes''), who left home at 14 to work as a maid
for an operetta troupe. With the money she earned, she attended
Howard University. Then it was on to Barnard College in New York,
where she found a Park Avenue patron (an arrangement that Hughes
compared to slavery) and became a prolific folklorist, novelist,
playwright and journalist in the 1920's, a particularly glorious
time for the arts in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   But she was a little too outspoken for some people's tastes,
perhaps ahead of her time in terms of Afrocentricity and black
pride, and her career foundered, as did her marriages. The final
straw was a false criminal accusation of the sexual abuse of a
child. Hurston died, forgotten, in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation of ``Zora Neale Hurston,'' directed by Wynn
Handman, is the overflowing talent of its subject. Devotees will
relish it; readers unfamiliar with her work are likely to be drawn
to it.
</P>
<P>
   Her tale about the balance of power between men and women, taken
from ``Mules and Men,'' a 1935 story collection, is folklore at its
most powerful. In it, Adam asks God for more strength than his
wife, ``so he could whoop her and make her mind.'' To even things
up, Eve asks God for certain keys: to the kitchen, to the bedroom,
to the cradle. Then the Devil, who made her do it, gives one more
piece of advice: ``Now don't go bragging about the keys.'' And from
there, things go downhill for the human race.
</P>
<P>
   Hurston was a wise woman.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ZORA NEALE HURSTON: A THEATRICAL BIOGRAPHY'
</P>
<P>
   By Laurence Holder; directed by Wynn Handman; production design,
Ryan E. McMahon; production stage manager, Wendy Ouellette.
Presented by the American Place Theater, Handman, artistic
director; Carl H. Jaynes, general manager; in association with the
National Black Touring Circuit, Woodie King Jr., producer. At 111
W. 46th St., Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   With: Elizabeth Van Dyke (Zora Neale Hurston) and Joseph Edward
(Herbert Sheen, Langston Hughes, Alain Locke and Richard Wright).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 1849EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
