A9780 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELN-MASS-EIGHTH-BOS &LR;      11-02 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-MASS-EIGHTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPUANO SEES EIGHTH DISTRICT RACE AS WIDE OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (p and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Looking for an alternative to the governor's race?
There's always the 8th Congressional District race, with a
Democrat, a Republican, an Independent, and a candidate from the
Socialist Workers Party on the ballot vying to succeed Joseph P.
Kennedy II.
</P>
<P>
   Well, so maybe it's not a barn-burner. Somerville Mayor Michael
Capuano, the Democratic nominee, is by most accounts nearly assured
a victory in one of the most heavily Democratic congressional
districts in the country. The real battle was back on Sept. 15,
when Capuano edged out nine other Democrats in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   But anything could happen. Capuano faces opposition from J.
Philip Hyde, a Republican who ran for the seat two years ago,
against Kennedy; Independent Anthony Schinella, who ran for Boston
City Council last year; and Andrea Morell.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who is an advocate of ``time-sizing,'' or paying people
for a 40-hour work week but having them work a 30-hour week,
coupled with better use of technology in the workplace, said he
garnered more votes in his 1996 race against Kennedy than Capuano
received in the Sept. 15 primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything can happen,'' Hyde said. ``I'm more Democratic than
the Democrat. Here we've got a machine Democrat against a reform
Republican. And I think black voters might be looking for an
alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Schinella said his candidacy was an effort to talk about
``issues a lot of people I know think are important,'' such as the
future of Social Security, NAFTA, military spending, campaign
finance reform, and corporate welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea how we're going to do. I think people might be
surprised, with the low turnout, and the Democratic nominee closing
up shop on Sept. 16,'' said Schinella. ``We've been actively
campaigning. For me, a victory would be anything over 5 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Schinella said he was disappointed by the lack of coverage of
the 8th District race after the Democratic primary. ``This is not
about viability,'' he said. ``A lot of people talk about opening up
the process, talking about issues. We ran that type of race from
day one, and we were ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Capuano is taking nothing for granted, though he
said ``if this isn't a safe Democratic seat, I don't know what is.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we know we won with 25 percent. So we've been reaching
out, to all the people in the last race who couldn't vote for us.
We respect that. But it's my job to reach out to them and say, I
represent 100 percent of the people in this district,'' the
five-term Somerville mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Capuano said the feedback has been good. ``In the primary, very
few people went out to vote against anybody. People went out to
vote for their candidates. That makes it easy to build bridges.
I've seen very little animosity. It's been very cordial.''
</P>
<P>
   Would he like to collect a certain number of votes to be sent to
Washington with a mandate? Capuano says no. ``I just want to get
one more vote than the other guy,'' he said. ``Unless I get 100
percent of the vote. That's one heck of a mandate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 1850EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TITANIC-TV-REVIEW-NYT     11-02 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TITANIC-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL EFFECTS AT SEA AND ELSEWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've been wondering how the vaunted special effects of
``Titanic'' were produced, Tuesday night's ``Nova'' should satisfy
your curiosity. As one of the assembled whizzes observes, ``The art
of visual effects is the art of what you can get away with.''
</P>
<P>
   And given the advent of supercomputers, movie makers these days
can get away with almost anything.
</P>
<P>
   The hour reminds us of Cecil B. DeMille's parting of the Red Sea
(a couple of slabs of Jell-O), the 18-inch-tall King Kong who
terrorized New York City and the three-foot-high flying house that
swirled through ``The Wizard of Oz.'' All relied on the brain to
process what the eye thought it saw.
</P>
<P>
   Most attention is given to ``Titanic,'' whose 11 Academy Awards
included one for best visual effects. There was the 700-foot model
of a ship that could not sail, and the 45-foot model that could.
</P>
<P>
   See how illusions of disaster were created by little ships
sitting in a bathtub while actors did their stuff on a studio set.
To the audience's eye, the movements look all of a piece.
</P>
<P>
   Using images shifted around by computer, an action movie like
``The X-Files'' agitated the screen with what seems to be an
exploding skyscraper. And ``Jurassic Park'' turned out dinosaurs
that seemed as real as the actors they swept past.
</P>
<P>
   What looked like hundreds of humans going down with the Titanic
were digital creations whose movements were performed by fewer than
20 live actors.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the narrator's promise of a totally computer-generated
cinema is within reach or much to be desired you can decide, but
unlike the usual secrets of magic tricks, these revelations of how
they fool us enhance the effects. It's a high-tech hour of show and
tell. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NOVA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Special Effects, Titanic and Beyond  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Tuesday night &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 8) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written by Bill Lattanzi and Susanne Simpson; Susanne Simpson,
senior producer; Bill Lattanzi, producer; Kelly Tyler, co-producer.
A Nova production by the WGBH/Boston Science Unit in association
with the BBC and Sveriges Television.
</P>
<P>
   Special effects also figure in Wednesday night's close-up of the
making of an award-winning episode of NBC's ``Homicide: Life on the
Street,'' known in the trade as ``the best show viewers aren't
watching.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``Titanic'' went in for big effects, ``Subway,'' which was
originally broadcast last December, met the squeezed-in challenges
of a 40-minute drama about a man trapped in a Baltimore subway car.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds less like a crowd-pleaser than a critic-pleaser,
such is the boast of the program, which is not known for equaling
the ratings of rivals like ABC's ``20/20'' and CBS's ``Nash
Bridges.'' Tuesday night's report probes the pressures of turning
out a series that is grittier than the usual commercial fare yet
has managed to survive for six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   It's a testy collaboration between corporate managers trying to
hold onto an audience, and producers, writers, directors and
photographers trying to stretch the limits of the police-drama
formula. Tuesday night's example suggests that all parties are
remarkably accommodating.
</P>
<P>
   This peek at how the elements of ``Subway'' were put together is
followed by the complete show that viewers saw when it was
originally broadcast, except that this time around they are spared
the commercials. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anatomy of a Homicide
</P>
<P>
   Life on the Street
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Wednesday night at 9 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 1856EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
