<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9826 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT02-COX     11-02 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A RELUCTANT GATES COMES TO COURT _ ON TAPE
 &HT;    660&AMP;insert. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Appearing Monday in videotaped testimony as a
hostile government witness, Microsoft chairman Bill Gates
repeatedly denied knowing of key internal documents that seemingly
implicated him in the company's bid to use its Windows monopoly to
divide markets and crush competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Halting from time to time the showing of the tape, Justice
Department lead prosecutor David Boies contrasted Gates's memory
lapses and vague replies in his 20-hour August deposition with
sharply worded directives to key executives that ordered them to do
whatever it took for Microsoft's Internet Explorer browser to
dominate personal computer desktops.
</P>
<P>
   The constantly argumentative and frequently forgetful Gates
shown on a 10-foot courtroom screen bore scant resemblance to his
public image, that of an enthusiastic super-salesman with a $60
billion personal fortune who over 23 years saw Microsoft crowned as
king of the software jungle.
</P>
<P>
   On the tape, Gates, seated in a large leather chair and sipping
from a soft drink can, rocked back and forth whenever he was irked
by Boies's polite but insistent questions. By turns evasive and
defiant, Gates often would hesitate and scratch the back of his
head before giving a snappish reply.
</P>
<P>
   The hour-long excerpt played in the landmark antitrust case
focused largely on Gates's role in August 1997 in striking a broad
deal with Apple Computer, then on the financial ropes, as well as
on a key 1995 meeting between Microsoft and Netscape executives,
then and now fierce competitors in the browser wars.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors sought to use the Gates tape to buttress charges by
their next live witness, Apple senior vice president Avadis
Tevanian, who has accused Microsoft of using its dominance in
computer applications and operating systems to force Apple to dance
to Microsoft's tune.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft lawyers spent much of the morning session in a bench
conference with U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson in a
vain bid to keep the trust-busters from releasing the Gates
excerpts played in court to the nation's TV screens.
</P>
<P>
   Denouncing the government's tactics, Microsoft lawyer William
Neukom, said: ``The government is resorting to an edited videotape
instead of actually calling Bill Gates as a witness. This is ...a
gimmick to get snippets in the headlines rather than get at the
facts pertinent to this lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft branded the playing of the tapes a personal attack on
Gates and an attempt to shift the focus from ``some very serious
hits over the last few weeks'' directed at the antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly an attempt to sensationalize the case and
distract people's attention from the weakness of the government's
case,'' Microsoft spokesman Mark Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the exchanges in the deposition was one based on an
Aug. 21, 1997, memo that purportedly quoted Gates as giving
marching orders with respect to Apple's use of Microsoft browsing
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill's top priority is for us to get the browser in the
October OS (operating system) release from Apple. We should do
whatever it takes to make this happen. If we are getting shut out,
we should escalate to Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   The internal memo, based on ``conversations with billg last
nite(cq),'' also said: ``Bill was clear that his goal here is to
keep Apple and Sun (Microsystems, a Microsoft competitor,) split.
He doesn't care that much about being aligned with Apple, he just
wants them split from other potential allies.''
</P>
<P>
   On the tape, Boies asked Gates: ``Do you recall conveying to
your executive staff in or about August of 1997 that your top
priority was to get Microsoft's browser in the October OS release
from Apple?''
</P>
<P>
   Gates: ``No, I don't recall that.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on, Boies asked Gates whether he recalled telling the same
key staffers that ``your whole goal with respect to Apple related
to (Sun's) Java's runtime (technology) was to keep Apple and Sun
split?
</P>
<P>
   Gates: ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies also cited several e-mails in which Gates hears of threats
to halt work on an updated version of Microsoft's Office business
software for Macintosh computers unless Apple toed the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The threat to cancel Mac Office 97 is certainly the strongest
bargaining point we have, as doing so will do a great deal of harm
to Apple immediately. I also believe that Apple is taking this
threat pretty seriously,'' one Microsoft executive wrote to Gates
in a June 27, 1997, missive.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another message to Gates, dated Feb. 13, 1998, said: ``Mac
Office is the perfect club to use on them.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Boies asked Gates whether he recalled being told about
the bargaining chip plan, Gates said evasively: ``Well, I know that
Apple would prefer that we have a more updated version of Mac
Office, that that would be a positive thing for them.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
