<HEADER>
A9833 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATH-OF-A-SALESMAN-R     11-02 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-OF-A-SALESMAN-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEATH OF A SALESMAN': A DARK NEW PRODUCTION ILLUMINATES WILLY
LOMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The darkness is always waiting for Willy Loman. It
laps away at the edges of even his sunniest memories. It clouds his
vision to the point that he cannot trust himself to drive. It keeps
pulling him back, with gravitational force, whenever hopes, however
small, are rekindled. The darkness terrifies Willy. You can sense
that in the lost, panicked expression that abruptly takes over his
face. But there is never any doubt that he is going to surrender to
it.
</P>
<P>
   Darkness is the primary element of the director Robert Falls'
exquisitely reimagined staging of Arthur Miller's ``Death of a
Salesman,'' which stars Brian Dennehy and Elizabeth Franz in the
performances of their careers and runs at the Goodman Theater here
through Nov. 7. The sad Brooklyn household in Miller's benchmark
study of an American loser seems more fragile than ever, and its
individual characters even lonelier.
</P>
<P>
   The production's set and lighting designers, Mark Wendland and
Michael Philippi respectively, have created a sense of engulfing
night that evokes William Styron's notion of emotional depression
as ``darkness visible.'' Many of the evening's individual scenes
are presented in wan pools of light that stake only tentative
claims against the blue-tinged shadows behind them. Moreover,
nothing seems fixed. Entire rooms glide into and out of focus,
creating sudden gulfs between people who an instant before were
standing side by side.
</P>
<P>
   When Dennehy's Willy famously declares that he is feeling ``kind
of temporary'' about himself, you understand him not as a
sympathetic outsider but as someone who sees what Willy sees.
Miller had once considered titling this, his greatest play,
``Inside His Head.'' Falls' production comes closer than any I have
witnessed in taking us into just that place.
</P>
<P>
   In February, it will have been 50 years since ``Death of a
Salesman'' first opened on Broadway, with its immortal cry for
attention for the failures in a country that worships success.
Though Miller's own reputation may have fluctuated in the
succeeding years, the place of ``Salesman'' as a dramatic
masterpiece has remained secure. Yet to return to it is always to
discover how much richer and bigger the play is than you remembered
it.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, to revisit ``Salesman,'' and particularly this
``Salesman,'' is to realize that the work doesn't match its popular
perception as a naturalistic social drama. As recent Miller
scholarship has suggested again and again, the play's images and
rhythms have the patterns of poetry, as well as that discipline's
reach for the small detail that sets off ever-widening echoes. Take
another look at the opening stage directions for the play, which
describe the setting as having the air of ``a dream rising out of
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller has said that Willy is best understood as ``a figure in a
poem.'' In a notebook entry about ``Salesman,'' he wrote, ``Life is
formless. ... Its interconnections are concealed by lapses of time,
by events occurring in separated places, by the hiatus of memory.''
</P>
<P>
   The description might be a blueprint for Falls' interpretation.
The first words spoken in the play, those of Willy's wife, Linda
(Franz), calling her husband's name, are surreally amplified, as
though emerging from another dimension. This idea is underscored by
the framing of Ms. Franz in a dusky, diagonal shaft of light, while
Dennehy stands below her, salesman's sample case in hand.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is of a sensation that sometimes surfaces in dreams,
of returning home and discovering you don't really know where you
are. Throughout the evening, Wendland's miraculously fluid settings
keep shifting. Your sense of something as basic as the location of
the Lomans' kitchen is consistently sabotaged. The only rules of
geography belong to the mind of Willy, a man for whom nothing feels
certain or fixed.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds forbiddingly abstract, rest assured that the
actors here keep you grounded in a heartbreaking emotional reality.
Those whose last exposure to Willy came with Dustin Hoffman's
memorably scrappy bantamweight of 1984 will be shocked at first by
the presence of Dennehy, a man of truly monumental proportions that
make Lee J. Cobb, who created the role, look puny. Yet it is clear
from the first instant that this Willy not only doesn't know his
own strength, he is also incapable of using it.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The production plays hauntingly on the contrast between
Dennehy's imposing frame and the sad, scared gestures of a sickly
child. When Willy shields his face with his hands, palms outward,
during an argument with his son Biff (Kevin Anderson), the effect
is devastating in a way it wouldn't be with a physically slighter
actor. The image of a big man made small perfectly embodies the
argument for ``Salesman'' as a bona fide tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Dennehy's stunningly disciplined performance is also sure to set
off tremors in anyone who has known depression or lived with
someone who suffers from it. When Linda says, ``A terrible thing is
happening to him,'' it doesn't seem like hyperbole. Just watch how
he works himself up to a pitch of confident bluster and then
deflates in a single instant, as though forced to remember that
life has never kept its promises.
</P>
<P>
   Gestures of assurance turn into signs of defeat and
disorientation for Willy: an angrily raised fist is abruptly turned
toward his own face; a wagging finger is brought nervously to his
lips. Such moments match the governing rhythms of Falls'
production, in which every self-contained vignette, even those
showing Willy's memories of happier times, slides into sourness.
</P>
<P>
   In Franz's superb portrait of Linda, which finds the aggression
in a traditionally passive character, Willy's wife is the sole
defense against his slide into the abyss, a one-woman rescue squad
destined to fail. She keeps talking quietly to her husband, her
head nodding in gentle affirmation, in a litany of supportive
statements and domestic reminders, with startling glimmers of a
physicality that suggests a warm and enduring sexual relationship.
When she sings soothingly to him in bed at the end of the first
act, you realize that in effect that's what she's been doing all
along.
</P>
<P>
   You also see the raw fear in her eyes when Willie's mind starts
to wander. Linda's anger at the callousness of Willy's sons, Biff
and Happy (Ted Koch), isn't just the defensiveness of a loyal,
protective wife. There's the self-interest here, too, of a woman
staving off threats to the only world she knows.
</P>
<P>
   As Biff, Anderson brings extraordinary conviction to the idea of
a man struggling not to become his father and losing the battle.
(Though the actors look nothing alike, there are moments when
Dennehy's face seems to loom from beneath Anderson's.) This actor
is irritatingly unfocused when playing the football hero Biff of
the flashbacks. But he is so strong is his big confrontational
scenes with Dennehy that you forgive his weaknesses and even his
inappropriate folk-singer hair.
</P>
<P>
   Koch's Happy is just about perfect, a self-deluding, aging boy
who is fast reaching the twilight of his sexual attractiveness.
Howard Witt, as Willy's patient, wisecracking neighbor, nicely
blends his character's brusqueness and compassion. Allen Hamilton
is fine as the rich and pontificating Ben, Willy's Horatio
Alger-ish brother, and the subjective framework of this production
makes the character's symbolical weight seem less strained.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the smaller roles come close to cartoonishness, and,
in a play that flows so naturally between the real and the surreal,
the memory scenes have an unexpectedly awkward quality. For the
most part, Falls maintains a remarkable balance between poetic
abstraction and domestic specificity, but there are moments,
especially toward the end, where the staging could be tighter.
</P>
<P>
   These are small objections, however, about a production that
achieves something rare and splendid in the theater: an
interpretation that rejuvenates a familiar classic without ever
betraying its soul. Playgoers whose memories of ``Death of a
Salesman'' are tainted by the ennui of high school English classes
are sure to be shocked by the ways this version disturbs and stirs.
</P>
<P>
   The production, rumor has it, is bound for New York next year.
It is hard to imagine a better way to celebrate the 50th
anniversary of a play that, so unlike its hero, seems only to grow
larger with age.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
