<HEADER>
A9837 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-AIKMAN-TE     11-02 1623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-AIKMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN WANTS TO PLAY FIVE MORE YEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Once and for all, allow Troy Aikman to set the
record ``straight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard the stuff about me supposedly being gay, and it's
tough to take,'' he says of the inaccurate-yet-persistent rumors
recycling in Metroplex comedy clubs and office cubicles. ``It
bothers me not only because it's not true, but it also goes against
my beliefs. You'd like to have a thick skin and let it roll off
you, but it's hurtful. I hate to have to defend myself on something
like that, but it's just plain wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   With his heterosexuality secure and his collarbone all but
healed, the Cowboys' silver-and-blue-chip quarterback was to make
his prime-time return Monday night as confident and as appreciative
as ever about his life, love and longevity.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a tumultuous year in which he has endured a cancerous
mole, his parents' separation, a strained relationship with former
coach Barry Switzer, a fire in his new house and the cracked
clavicle, Aikman said he is determined to win a fourth Super Bowl,
inspired to play another five years and rejuvenated, in part, by
his recent status as a one-woman man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say we're very steady,'' he said of his girlfriend.
``It's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Said long-snapper and close friend Dale Hellestrae, ``He's as
happy as he's been in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so fabulous is his health. Despite wearing extra ``channel''
cushioning in his left shoulder pad, Aikman and the 4-3 Cowboys
realize another awkward fall like the one Sept. 13 against the
Denver Broncos will likely end his season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is risk,'' said trainer Jim Maurer. ``But he's not going
to re-break it unless he falls on it the same way again. If that
happens, in all likelihood, he's done for the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there will be fewer seven-step drops, rare rollouts and
strong suggestions to not kamikaze interception returners, there
are few concessions to the game plan. In typical rawhide-tough
fashion, Aikman said only ``subconsciously'' will he protect his
left arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I \Rsay anything\S it will be a general thing in passing,''
said coach Chan Gailey. ``He's been down this road before. He knows
what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this isn't Troy's first rodeo. But what if it's
his last?
</P>
<P>
   Troy Kenneth Aikman _ the man owner Jerry Jones calls ``the most
important person in our organization'' _ is sneaking up on 32
years, 30,000 yards passing and 1,000 MRIs. A wide-ranging
appreciation of Aikman's career and a peak at his mental and
physical state as he returns onto the field and closer to Canton:
</P>
<P>
   The Injuries
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Frankensteinian scars, technicolor bruises and
cranky back, Aikman said his warranty is safe because the parts
aren't yet wearing out.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he wears more padding than John Glenn, sometimes walks
like Quasimoto and can't come close to touching his toes, but 252
career sacks behind an offensive line that used to be made up of
guys now waiting tables will do that. He still remembers his first
broken bone (left arm as a 10-year-old linebacker in Cerritos,
Calif.), almost all of the 40 stitches in his chin (''Now I've got
a turbo-strap'') and scratching his cornea by wearing his contacts
in the wrong eye during Super Bowl XXVIII.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a day goes by that I'm not reminded I had back surgery,''
said Aikman, who underwent surgery to repair a herniated disk in
June 1993. ``Some mornings it's tight and just never loosens up.
It's the scariest because it's the only thing that won't fix
itself. Other than that, I feel pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that 11-sack mauling against the Eagles in '89, his leg
bending like an accordion against the Redskins in 1991 and that hit
by the Cardinals' Anthony Bell in '89 that sent blood spewing out
his left ear, Aikman said he feels good enough to play out this
contract (through 2001) and another.
</P>
<P>
   Before the collarbone, he had made 58 consecutive starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I feel as good as when I was in my 20s because
the hits have taken their toll,'' said Aikman. ``But I take much
better care of myself. I run four to five times a week, something I
never did early on. I used to think 10 \Rseasons\S was the magic
number, but I'm so encouraged by guys like John Elway, Dan Marino
and Warren Moon. They're still growing strong, and I've got six or
seven years on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Maurer: ``He's probably not as beaten up as you think.
There's nothing physically to limit him from playing another five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Style
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, a self-proclaimed ``grunt,'' is as slow as the last day
of school and as mobile as a mailbox. Few passers in NFL history,
however, have combined his zip and precision.
</P>
<P>
   A flop at the Improv, No. 8's 15-yard post is unchallenged and
he has the unique ability to consistently launch lasers through a
window as small as the drive-thru at Wendy's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our `oomph','' said receiver Michael Irvin. ``There's no
one who's ever played this game that I'd rather be catching balls
from. No one.''
</P>
<P>
   With piercing blue eyes, rugged good looks and a jerky-tough
mentality, the guy friends and teammates call ``8-ball,'' ``T-Roy''
or just ``Roy'' is as big (6-foot-4, 220 pounds) and precise
(third-most accurate passer in NFL history at 62 percent) as Big
Ben.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career playing with receivers who disappeared
faster than David Copperfield assistants, Aikman painted his
self-image and grabbed 42 Cowboys passing records by standing
patiently in the pocket and picking apart secondaries like a
vegetarian sorting through beef stew.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he needs is time \Rto throw,\S'' said Irvin. ``He's got
everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Maturity
</P>
<P>
   Like he has done since he was 2, Aikman still eats Lucky Charms
for breakfast. He has, however, done some serious growing up in his
10 years with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do quite the running around like we used to do, and
he's cut out the junk food,'' says long-time close friend Doug
Kline. ``He's grown up, but his ego hasn't. He's still a Mr.
Humble, but a darn strong, driven one.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, he was a guy taking a swing at an obnoxious fan in
1989 and leaving the Pro Bowl at halftime in '92. Now, he has the
ability to overcome the loss of close friends and former teammates
like Kevin Gogan and Jay Novacek and who last off-season
optimistically dealt with seemingly negative news involving his
family, residence and health.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been anything but a tough year,'' he says. ``Each was an
isolated incident. Instead of feeling sorry for myself, I was able
to see the positives. Like the fact that no one was injured in the
fire and we caught the cancer early. There's been some tough things
to deal with, but football is still fun and exciting. It's a
different type of feeling without some of those guys around, but
I'm a different person now, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fish Bowl
</P>
<P>
   The Aikmaniacs are still out there, but the object of their
obsession has learned to play their game. He's prepared to sign
autographs anywhere, anytime. He doesn't like signing a guy's
receipt at the gas station or a woman's underwear at a restaurant,
but it comes with the territory of being the highest-paid player on
the world's most popular team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never be completely comfortable,'' said Aikman. ``But
there is a misconception that I can't leave my house, and that's
just not true. I'm not a prisoner of whatever celebrity I may
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman realizes the same popularity that pushes fans to approach
him has also produced more money than Sultan of Brunai, appearances
on everything from Oprah to ``People'''s list of the 50 Most
Beautiful, and the seven fireplaces in the new house he hopes to
move back into next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do look forward to the days when I can have a private
life,'' he said. ``But I also know I'll miss not playing. I talked
to Dan \RMarino\S and he told me that when you're done, you're
done. It's simple, but it really made me think and I'm trying to
soak things in a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Future
</P>
<P>
   Aikman's immediate sights are accomplishing something of
unprecedented biblical proportion: two resurrections.
</P>
<P>
   One from 1-15; the other from Switzerland. The first took a 1-15
disaster to three Super Bowls in four years earlier this decade.
This one is about rebuilding a winner and an image from a team that
plunged to 6-10 last year under Switzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be very disappointed if we don't get a fourth
Super Bowl,'' he said. ``Because we've got the core players to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And when he's done playing? Marriage? Kids? Ownership? For now
he's content with his down-to-earth girlfriend, who has no links to
Hollywood stardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've enjoyed playing too much to just walk away altogether,''
he said. ``I don't think I have the patience to coach, but I'd like
to be involved in some part of ownership. It could really be
rewarding if it's a meaningful position.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legacy
</P>
<P>
   Three Super Bowls. Super Bowl MVP. 11-2 in the playoffs. 88-56
record as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a kid who practiced crossing his T's and A's because
he thought his baseball autograph would someday be worth something
and who took up football in the eighth grade only because his
Marlboro-Man tough dad, Ken, signed him up without asking.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it all ended today my career would be a success, yes,''
Aikman said. ``The Super Bowls are something to be proud of; I've
got the respect of my teammates and have pretty much established
myself. I don't dwell on the end because I'm not too worried about
it. It's not like I'm going to have to start selling shoes when
football is over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
