<HEADER>
A9838 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SARAZEN-COX     11-02 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SARAZEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Calcavecchia looks for good things at Sarazen World OpenBy Glenn
Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASELTON, Ga. _ There hasn't been a pin that he doesn't aim
for. There isn't a power fade in his bag that can't clear a fairway
bunker. There isn't a moment that Mark Calcavecchia spends on the
golf course when he isn't the aggressor.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why there's only one major championship _ the 1989
British Open _ in his biographical sketch. Maybe it doesn't suit
his nature to be patient. If par is a good score, Calcavecchia
might find himself thinking, then maybe this isn't my kind of golf
course or tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to places where I feel good,'' Calcavecchia says. ``Maybe
that's why I wouldn't consider myself a U.S. Open specialist, by
any means. That's probably my least favorite tournament on the
planet. I disagree with what they try to do there, and that
probably hasn't helped my attitude going in there. I'm sure I'm
always going to play in it if I'm eligible, but if I wasn't, I
don't know if I'd even try to qualify.''
</P>
<P>
   The complete antithesis is this week's Sarazen World Open at the
Legends Course at Chateau Elan, an event that Calcavecchia clearly
enjoys nearly as much as his old bowling ball _ even more this year
after a forgettable 29th-place finish just down the road at the
Tour Championship. In five years of competing in the Sarazen,
Calcavecchia has earned enough to purchase a decent-sized Caribbean
island. The $360,000 Calcavecchia secured last year with a
three-shot win over England's Lee Westwood pushed his career total
to $593,525. Only two-time winner Frank Nobilo of New Zealand (
$741,500) has feasted more on Don Panoz's property.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely been a good place for me,'' Calcavecchia said
about the Sarazen, which will fade away after this year, pushed off
the schedule by a 1999 World Golf Championship event. ``It's one of
those courses that the more you play it, the more comfortable you
are. Like, for instance, some of those little uphill holes. You've
got 135 yards, but it might be a 7-iron. It's tough to force
yourself to take enough club.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was no problem for Calcavecchia, whose week began
with an unreal 62 in unbelievably wretched weather. With his back
in spasm on Sunday, his 10-shot lead had evaporated to two. But
with a 40-foot birdie putt on the 18th, Calcavecchia secured the
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew one way or another I was going to finish,''
Calcavecchia said. ``Thank God I got off to a great start. I guess
that's what big leads are for.''
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia's 1998 season has mirrored last year's Sarazen, but
without the back pain. He built up a financial surplus in the
spring with a win at the Honda, a tie for fourth at Bay Hill and a
fourth at The Players Championship _ earning $604,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good three weeks, for sure; that's really been the
basis of my whole season,'' he said. ``If I had played bad those
three weeks, I'd really consider my season a complete disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia is disappointed about the demise of the Sarazen,
and not merely from a financial standpoint. From the start, he has
been one of the tournament's staunchest allies, giving it a
credibility boost and urging other PGA Tour stars to attend. He had
earned the chance to accept the trophy from the 96-year old Sarazen
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every year the tournament has seemed to get a little
more important,'' Calcavecchia said. ``I mean, it's the Gene
Sarazen World Open. I have always thought that's pretty neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
