<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEBUILDERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mega-deal for two builders announced
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two of America's top 10 home builders are using
strategic acquisitions to boost earnings and market share in a
slowdown that both acknowledge has begun.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with industry observers, as long as debt does not
get out of hand in what analyst Steve Percoco of Lark Research
calls ``a spotty market.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Beazer Homes announced Monday its agreement to buy
Trafalgar House Property of Washington, D.C., from its Norwegian
owner for about $100 million. The transaction, expected to close in
December, gives Beazer entry into a blooming market and control of
the fourth-largest builder in northern Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Although the deal does not include Trafalgar's South Riding, a
planned community in Loudon, Va., Beazer will gain about 4,000 lots
in northern Virginia, Maryland and New Jersey, said David Weiss,
vice president and chief financial officer. It will also be able to
buy choice lots and build in South Riding, which is being sold
separately to a consortium of buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Beazer will pay cash _ from its renegotiated revolving
credit line and from its own coffers _ for Trafalgar, the price was
discounted because the owner was motivated to sell, Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   Trafalgar's estimated revenue this year is $210 million on 1,000
homes sold.
</P>
<P>
   Beazer Homes' fiscal year ended in September, and results will
be released next week. However, through the first nine months, the
company reported $612 million in sales. The Trafalgar purchase will
take it to the billion-dollar range.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a strategic opportunity for them that makes a lot of
sense,'' said Percoco. ``It broadens their base, (and does so) with
an established name and good reputation like Trafalgar's. . . . My
concern is not the strategy, it is the leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks ago, Beazer announced a far smaller acquisition,
Snow Construction, of Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, Columbia, Md.-based Ryland Group was
acquiring Regency Communities of Tampa, enhancing its market share
in a prime retirement market.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase price and details were not divulged when the
company announced the acquisition Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But, like the Beazer transaction in northern Virginia, Ryland's
purchase was designed to position the company to continue to do
business in a slowdown, said spokeswoman Anne Madison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fiscal year is the calendar year. During November and
December, Regency will add 90 closings to our balance sheet. It
will add 350 more in 1999. It will take our Florida division from
325 homes a year to 750 or 800 homes a year, making that one of our
largest divisions,'' Madison said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regency builds in north Tampa,'' noted analyst Percoco, adding
territory to Ryland's existing Tampa base, ``and enables them to
save some money on overhead.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Harte writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
