<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-COACHES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baylor hired as Braves batting coach as changes announced
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Braves formally announced the hiring of
hitting coach Don Baylor on Monday afternoon, but they hardly
stopped there. In a sweeping set of moves, almost all of the Braves
coaching staff was rearranged, as the organization seeks to
revitalize a component of the club that might have gone stale.
</P>
<P>
   Gone from Atlanta are hitting coach Clarence Jones, replaced by
Baylor after 11 seasons on the staff, and bench coach Jim
Beauchamp. Both have been offered minor league coaching positions.
Third-base coach Bobby Dews has been transferred to the bullpen in
a swap with bullpen coach Ned Yost, who takes Dews' spot in the
third-base box.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, former Brave second baseman Glenn Hubbard, most
recently a coach with the Class A Macon Braves, has been promoted
to become the first-base coach, and nine-year first base coach Pat
Corrales moves to the dugout to become Bobby Cox's bench coach.
Only pitching coach Leo Mazzone and strength and conditioning coach
Frank Fultz were unaffected by the moves.
</P>
<P>
   The transactions turned over what had been the most stable
coaching staff in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at it as an attempt to invigorate our environment and
freshen the spirit,'' said general manager John Schuerholz, who
informed Jones and Beauchamp of the changes in Monday meetings.
``Even though those guys did great jobs for us, sometimes there are
changes that are needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz had said the day after the Braves were eliminated
from the NLCS that he did not foresee any staff changes, but he and
Cox already had started begun toying with ideas. Once Baylor became
available, the notion of revamping the whole staff gained momentum.
With the exception of Dews who was brought in after Jimy Williams
departed in 1996, Cox's staff had remained unchanged since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that longevity stemmed from Cox's loyalty to those
coaches, even while critics suggested the team was overdue for some
new, younger blood. Beauchamp is 59, Dews is 60 and Jones turns 57
on Saturday. Nevertheless, such wholesale change was not all Cox's
idea originally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who initiates it,'' Schuerholz said. ``It
matters that there's an agreement, which is what we have. Bobby and
I talked about it, and we thought it was the thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor's charge is to sharpen an offense that just scored a
franchise record 826 runs last year (5.1 per game). He undoubtedly
will be the highest-paid coach in baseball next year, drawing
$600,000 from the Colorado Rockies for the final year of his
managerial contract.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, who was the 1995 National League manager of the year,
already had a reputation as a hitting coach. In two seasons with
Baylor overseeing Milwaukee's offense in 1990-91, the Brewers' team
average went from .259 to .271. In the 1992 season in St. Louis,
the Cardinals added seven points to their club average before
Baylor was hired away to manage the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Braves ranked in the top four in the league in
runs, homers (second with 215) and average (fourth at .272), the
club fought streakiness and inconsistency up and down the order.
The team struck out more than 1,000 times for the third year in a
row, after doing so just once in the previous 30 years. Baylor's
most interesting client should be Andruw Jones, who is still a few
strides short of offensive stardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy is we're going to have to work the pitchers and
not make outs early in the count,'' Baylor said from his California
home. ``Make the pitcher make the mistake and think about driving
in runs. That's the bottom line. You have extra runs to work with.
You have an excellent pitching staff, so the hitters will have do
their duty too hit the ball the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor will be reunited with two of his favorite ex-Rockies in
shortstop Walt Weiss and first baseman Andres Galarraga, whose
career Baylor revitalized beginning in St. Louis in 1992. Galarraga
posted eague-leading seasons in average (.370 in 1993), homers (47
in 1996) and RBIs (150 in 1996, 140 in 1997) in Colorado, the first
baseman thought he had strained his relationship with his former
manager by leaving for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never about personality between Cat and (me),'' Baylor
said. ``We had gone through so many different things to finally get
him hitting the way he is today. There were a lot of blood, sweat
and tears to get him straightened out. You hated to lose a player
like Andres off your club. He was a clubhouse leader. But our
relationship was never in jeopardy, on my part.''
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard, the staff newcomer, will be back in an Atlanta uniform
for the first time since 1987, his last of 10 seasons with the
Braves before he completed his playing career with Oakland in
1988-89. He rejoined the Braves organization the following year and
has since logged minor-league coaching stops in Bradenton, Macon
and Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
