A9841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SETTLER-THEATER-REVIE     11-02 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SETTLER-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE OLD SETTLER': AN OLDER WOMAN CHOOSES AN UNLIKELY LOVE OVER
LONELINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (Production notes at end of the review)  
 (fb) 
By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Why do fools fall in love? ``The Old Settler,'' John
Henry Redwood's lonely-hearts comedy set in the Harlem of the early
1940's, addresses the question through a pair of romantic dunces:
an old fool, desperate for affection and eager to believe in anyone
who can supply it, and a younger one, unschooled in affairs of the
heart and a terrible judge of when they might be practical.
</P>
<P>
   Redwood plays matchmaker to these lovelorn naifs, prompting a
tender chain of events that inevitably teaches each of them
invaluable lessons. The older fool, Elizabeth Borny (played by
Leslie Uggams), an unmarried housemaid, is past her prime and thus
considered pitiable; the younger by more than two decades, Husband
Witherspoon (Godfrey L. Simmons Jr.), is a weak-willed rube fresh
from the rural South who nonetheless finds himself a prize to be
fought over.
</P>
<P>
   For this gentle comic equation to add up, for the story to have
any urgency, it's more important to understand the minuses in the
relationship than the pluses. What's poignant in ``The Old
Settler,'' which opened last week at Primary Stages, is that
community tyranny can propel a woman of Elizabeth's grace into the
arms of such a guileless suitor. The utter absurdity of their
romance has more to do with sociology than age; their courtship
must seem outrageous because it's an outrage that a substantial
person like Elizabeth would feel compelled to settle for only half
a mate.
</P>
<P>
   This was precisely the quality communicated by ``The Old
Settler'' the first time I saw it, at the McCarter Theater in
Princeton, N.J., in a charming production directed by Walter Dallas
with all the right overemphases. McCarter's Elizabeth and Husband
were a patently ridiculous pair; the Husband of Tico Wells was so
callow, so out of place in cosmopolitan, wartime Harlem, that your
heart instantly melted for the Elizabeth of Brenda Pressley, whose
vulnerability was so nakedly on display.
</P>
<P>
   While the new ``Old Settler'' retains the play's warm atmosphere
and humor, and can also count in its corner agile supporting
performances by Lynda Gravatt and Rosalyn Coleman, the Primary
Stages incarnation, directed by Harold Scott, renders it an
altogether slighter work. Not that it harbors any great claim to
profundity; the play owes more to Neil Simon than, for instance,
August Wilson. It's a pleasant, genteel comedy that aspires neither
to lyrical flight nor penetrating insight.
</P>
<P>
   But it is character-rich, and when played to the hilt, it can
seem more than the sum of its parts. And this is where the serious
disappointment creeps in. The couple at its core now is flavorless.
Simmons and Uggams are capable actors who nevertheless do not make
an interesting pair. Cast against type _ that is to say,
considerably more worldly (in his case) and glamorous (in hers)
than the characters they play _ the actors turn an odd coupling
into a fairly conventional liaison. The gap between them is not so
wide. The romance loses its asymmetry and thus its essence.
</P>
<P>
   The social milieu of Redwood's Harlem is the hierarchy of
domestics _``kitchen mechanics'' they call themselves _ who travel
to daily, or live in sporadically, the houses of white families.
The story unfolds in an apartment shared by two of them: Elizabeth
and her younger, tougher sister, Quilly (Gravatt), who take in
Husband as a boarder. He has come to New York after his mother's
death in pursuit of a hometown sweetheart, Lou Bessie (Coleman),
who left South Carolina for the brighter lights.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Bessie, played by the delightful Coleman with all the bite
and effervescence of overcarbonated ginger ale, has little use for
anything about Husband but his inheritance. So he turns for comfort
to the needy Elizabeth, who is scoffed at behind her back as ``an
old settler,'' a woman who has reached middle age with no
marriageable prospects. Over the protests of the mistrustful
Quilly, to whom Redwood awards all the choicest ripostes _ ``You
look like Uncle Ben before he started cookin' rice,'' she says to
Husband when he arrives home one night in a bright orange zoot suit
_ Elizabeth takes the dangerous plunge, consenting when he proposes
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman's and Gravatt's steady hands notwithstanding, the
production is a bit of an anesthetic. It leaves you feeling
pain-free, when a little vicarious heartache is what you are after.
Scott's direction is stolid and his pacing leisurely, which proves
a skillful ploy only in a lovely scene in Act II in which Uggams,
sitting by the window in the designer Bob Phillips' realistic
rendering of Elizabeth's immaculate flat, waits silently in the
fading moonlight for Husband to return and take her away.
</P>
<P>
   The moment is one of Uggams' most fetching _ she also rises to
the occasion when called on to break into song _ but these are
isolated instances in a play that never delivers on its promise of
pathos, never raises goose bumps. ``I understand about eating alone
and being alone,'' the radiant Uggams declares, in a way that leads
you to think she's just saying that.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE OLD SETTLER'
</P>
<P>
   By John Henry Redwood; directed by Harold Scott; sets by Bob
Phillips; costumes by Debra Stein; lighting by Frances Aronson;
sound by Jim van Bergen; production manager, Tina Fallo/Tor Ekeland
for Crux; stage manager, Peter Lomuscio. Presented by Primary
Stages, Casey Childs, artistic director, in association with Eric
Krebs and Anne Strickland Squadron. At 354 W. 45th St., Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   With: Leslie Uggams (Elizabeth Borny), Lynda Gravatt (Quilly
McGrath), Godfrey L. Simmons Jr. (Husband Witherspoon) and Rosalyn
Coleman (Lou Bessie Preston).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 1914EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
