<HEADER>
A9854 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILITARY-RECRUITING-A     11-02 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-RECRUITING-ART-2TAKES(1,250)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG PEOPLE CHOOSING FUN OVER BEING ALL THEY CAN BE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALDORF, Md. _ Christopher Thompson was a prime target for the
two older men roaming the St. Charles Towne Center mall Monday,
dressed in identical black uniforms. He was young. He looked fit.
He was in the mall in the middle of the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play sports?'' Thompson was asked by way of introduction.
More importantly, Keith L. Dixon wondered, had Thompson ever
considered enlisting in the U.S. Navy?
</P>
<P>
   Petty Officer Dixon and his fellow recruiter got little more
than a shrug from Thompson, 19, a response all too familiar these
days.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting young men and women into the nation's all-volunteer
military has never been easy, but the military now faces a crisis
in recruiting that has been building for some time and, many
commanders fear, could get worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has just announced that the Army and the Navy have
each failed to reach their goals in signing up new recruits for the
fiscal year that just ended. It was the first time since the draft
ended in 1973 that the Navy had fallen short, and it did so
disastrously, enlisting 12 percent fewer recruits than its stated
goal of 55,300.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon attributes its recruiting difficulties to many
things. The economy is thriving. The unemployment rate is at its
lowest level since the days of the draft. Young people are more
likely than ever to go straight to college after graduating from
high school _ nearly 70 percent now, compared to less than half
just a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   But many officials believe the armed services face a deeper
problem and one more difficult to overcome: The military, simply
put, no longer looms very large in young people's lives and
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people are into just having fun,'' said Thompson, who
recently moved to Maryland from Charlotte, N.C. ``And there's so
much fun to have.''
</P>
<P>
   The sharp draw down of personnel that followed the end of the
Cold War _ and the collapse of the nation's only overarching enemy
_ has left the military as small as it has been since right after
World War II. With 1.4 million soldiers, sailors, airmen and
marines on active duty, the military is 40 percent the size it was
at the peak of the Vietnam War in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   That has meant a steady decline in the number of veterans in the
population, and in the number of those the recruiters call
``influencers,'' the relatives, friends, teachers or others with
military service who often inspire young people to sign up.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's generation _ the teen-agers and 20-somethings born
after 1973 _ is the first whose fathers never had to face
conscription.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember, when I was a little kid growing up, all I
heard about was the military service of my parents,'' said Adm.
Barbara E. McGann, the Navy's two-star commander in charge of
recruiting. ``Both my parents served. And you do grow up hearing
these stories and being curious about what military service would
be all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean that's gone forever,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty in recruiting has led to shortages of enlisted
personnel in the field, raising concerns in some quarters about
what is called the ``readiness'' of the armed forces to fight _ and
win _ a war.
</P>
<P>
   Since Navy recruits almost always go straight to sea after basic
training, the Navy's shortfall has contributed disproportionately
to shortages of enlisted sailors in the fleet. Navy ships, on
average, are now setting sail with only 90 percent of a full crew.
</P>
<P>
   The Army missed its goal to recruit 72,600 new soldiers overall
by only 1 percent, but it fell far shorter in enlisting recruits
for harder-to-fill specialities, including armor and artillery
crews.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force and Marines, both smaller forces with more
specialized appeals, met their recruiting goals for the last fiscal
year; the Air Force, though, met their goal only after speeding up
the starting dates of those who signed up but decided to wait to
enter the service.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is scrambling to address the shortfalls. The $1.1
billion that Congress approved for military ``readiness'' two weeks
ago included $113 million to help boost recruiting, including an
increase in enlistment bonuses for areas hit hardest by the
recruiting woes.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of recruiting has risen steadily. Without the infusion
of new money, it now costs, on average, $7,187 per recruit,
including advertising dollars, enlistment bonuses and money for
college. At the end of the Cold War in 1989, each recruit cost
$5,460, in dollars adjusted for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy and the Army have hired new recruiters (700 and 600
more, respectively), and they have flooded television with new
advertising they hope will reach today's youth.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-October, the Army began broadcasting new commercials.
They replace the current gauzy testimonials of soldiers who say
they have made something of themselves with jolting ads that mix
staccato Nike-like images and pulsating music. ``Are you ready to
make real noise?'' one of them asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still `Be all that you can be,' but we took the
experience the Army can offer and packaged it in a more
contemporary fashion,'' said Lt. Col. James P. Sullivan, the Army's
chief of marketing and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   In a few weeks, the Navy will broadcast its first
``infomercial'' on cable, touting the rewards of Navy life in a
medium more often used to sell beauty products and financial
investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This generation watches cable late into the evening,'' McGann
said.
</P>
<P>
   The admiral and other Pentagon officials express optimism that a
redoubled effort _ with new ads and more recruiters _ will fix any
serious recruiting problems before they endanger the services.
</P>
<P>
   But others argue that recruiting will thrive only when more
chronic problems are addressed. In a memo sent to every Army
general on Oct. 7, the Army's Chief of Staff, Gen. Dennis J.
Reimer, warned that the perceived gap between civilian and military
pay and benefits and the high pace of Army operations would
continue to hurt recruiting until the situation is addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Reimer's memo cited the lament of an Army recruiting sergeant in
Ohio, who summarized the problem like this: ``We are asking today's
youth to leave home, deploy at a moment's notice and give his life
for his country for the same pay as a fry cook.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes recruiters like Petty Officer Dixon more
important than ever. He works out of a small office in a boxy brick
building here in Waldorf, a small town about 25 miles southeast of
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   An 18-year veteran, Dixon has spent the last two and a half
years trying to sell prospective recruits on the experience,
training and education that the Navy offers.
</P>
<P>
   He scours the high schools and recreation centers, but he also
improvises. He once left his business card in each sneaker in the
mall's shoe store and, surprising even himself, received a call
from a prospect, who a week later was on his way to the Great Lakes
Naval Training Center, the Navy's boot camp north of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, he has been the second best recruiter in
a region that stretches from northern Virginia to New Jersey, but
it was always a struggle, he said. A lot of kids simply do not
think the military has much to offer them; the ones that do often
have a close friend or relative who steers them toward service.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real lack of interest,'' he said, cheerful
nonetheless, as he cruised the mall, which, he explained, is
crawling with prospects. ``And I see it get weaker and weaker every
year.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the Navy is a victim of its own success.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other services, the Navy has increased the quality of
its recruits by requiring a high school diploma and above-average
scores on aptitude tests. The Navy also turns down anyone with
physical or mental defects, or a history of drug use. Those
standards, the Navy estimates, eliminate two-thirds of the pool;
more often than not those are the ones who volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people who walk into the office have something
wrong with them,'' said Petty Officer Benny J. Granillo, a 10-year
veteran who works most days out of the Lexington Park office.
</P>
<P>
   That is why recruiters rely more on contacts they cultivate.
During their trip to the mall, for example, Dixon and Granillo each
went to the mall to check up on prospects, like Patricia
Overstreet, 19, who signed up to be a medical corpsman but wanted
to wait until after Christmas to start.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mall has a ban on soliciting, they approach prospects
like Thompson indirectly. In this case, they chatted a bit about
basketball and high school, learning along the way that Thompson
was waiting for his girlfriend to get off from her job at the
sporting goods store. Dixon invited him to join a pick-up
basketball game on Saturday. ``No strings attached,'' he said,
handing him a card.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Thompson, Dixon asked, ``Do you know what the
problem with that guy is?''
</P>
<P>
   He and Granillo answered in tandem, ``The girlfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be interested, but the girlfriend won't want him to
leave,'' Dixon explained. Then he made a note to himself to drop by
the store every now and then and see how the relationship was
going.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
