<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: POP ART GOES TO CHINA; EIFFEL TOWER IS CLOSED;
CARAVAGGIO PAINTING AT BOSTON COLLEGE; NEW HAT FOR PLACIDO DOMINGO
AT THE LOS ANGELES OPERA
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pop Art to China
</P>
<P>
   Pop Art goes to China beginning on Sunday, when the Smithsonian
Institution's Arthur M. Sackler Gallery in Washington opens ``Roy
Lichtenstein: Landscapes in the Chinese Style.'' The exhibition
includes six examples of the Chinese art that inspired
Lichtenstein. He used his signature dots to create craggy,
fog-shrouded mountains, winding rivers, lakes and even a seascape _
images that echo the classic subjects of Chinese landscapes. The
exhibition continues until Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Sightless
</P>
<P>
   The Eiffel Tower remained closed Monday, the fourth day of a
strike by French workers demanding an increase in staff members.
The press office for the tower, where 35,000 visitors had been
expected over the All Saints Day holiday weekend and 8,000 on
Monday, declined to predict when the attraction would reopen.
</P>
<P>
   Art History
</P>
<P>
   For 200 years, Caravaggio's masterpiece ``The Taking of Christ''
(1602) was considered missing. Then, in 1993, it was rediscovered
in Dublin in the dining room of a Jesuit community residence.
Cleaned and restored, the painting is on indefinite loan to the
National Gallery of Ireland. But from Feb. 1 through May 24, the
work will make its first appearance in the Western Hemisphere at
the McMullen Museum of Art at Boston College. It will be the
centerpiece of the exhibition ``Saints and Sinners: Caravaggio and
the Baroque Image,'' which will introduce Americans to the
masterpiece and provide an interdisciplinary study of Italian
religious art from 1580 to 1680.
</P>
<P>
   Another Hat
</P>
<P>
   Placido Domingo will become the artistic director and co-manager
of the Los Angeles Opera in 2000, while continuing as the artistic
director of the Washington Opera. Domingo, who is already the
artistic adviser and principal guest conductor for the Los Angeles
Opera, will replace Peter Hemmings, the company's general director,
who is to retire in June 2000. Domingo will share oversight of the
Los Angeles Opera with a manager to be named. ``Peter Hemmings did
a great job,'' Domingo said, ``and the company is inherently very
healthy. But now it is time to think of how to proceed into the
next millennium.'' Domingo said he would continue his singing and
conducting career. One of the Three Tenors, he is singing in the
Washington Opera's production of ``Fedora.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
