<HEADLINE>
NEBRASKA FAN TRACKS HEISMAN RACE ON HIS SITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a touch of irony, the only known homemade Web site that
tracks the Heisman Trophy race this season belongs to a Nebraska
football fan.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wingert of Sioux City, Iowa, might be a diehard Cornhuskers
fan, but it doesn't seem to get in his way of ranking college
football's best players at his Heisman Watch page
(www.geocities.com/Colosseum/Pressbox/4188/heisman.html).
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it must pain Wingert to see Texas running back
Ricky Williams rank No. 1 among his top 15 selections. Williams,
after all, rushed for 150 yards to help the Longhorns hand
Wingert's favorite team a 20-16 home loss on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than stick a Hook 'em Horns sign in Wingert's face,
Longhorns fans should applaud him for seeing his online project
through. Outside of a few sites that tout their author's favorites,
the Heisman race is tracked rather poorly on the Internet, with
only the College Football Hall of Fame's official site
(collegefootball.org) and CBS SportsLine making anything out of it.
</P>
<P>
   It should also be pointed out that Wingert started his site in a
season in which no Cornhuskers player has been mentioned as a
legitimate candidate. (Wingert listed Nebraska quarterback Bobby
Newcombe as a preseason dark-horse candidate in a section on his
site, but let the guy be a Nebraska fan, for Pete's sake.)
</P>
<P>
   Wingert, who already has an impressive site devoted to the
Cornhuskers, started his Heisman section after discussing Heisman
hopefuls with some online friends. A search on the Net yielded only
big-media sites, ``so I decided I would start up my own,'' Wingert
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wingert came up with an enterprising site.
</P>
<P>
   On his site, Wingert tinkers with the order of his top 15
players based on their weekly performances. He also has developed a
section for each player, a fans poll (he resets the results at the
first of each month to keep the voters honest), a message board and
a list of past Heisman winners. Most of the candidates also are
linked to official sites touting their candidacy for the trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Wingert's effort on free GeoCities Web space rivals that of
resource-rich CBS SportsLine
(www.sportsline.com/u/football/college/heisman), which uses senior
writer Dennis Dodd's weekly analysis as its Heisman presence.
</P>
<P>
   When the Heisman is awarded next month, it's a good bet that
Wingert won't be at the Downtown Athletic Club in lower Manhattan
to witness the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   That's a shame because Wingert does a first-class job on this
new media known as the Internet in promoting the Heisman Trophy.
 &LR; subheds:Say Ricky, you're so fine
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Williams leads other Heisman candidates in the number of
fan pages on the Web. A few of the known pages that follow
Williams:
</P>
<P>
   Ricky's Heisman Page
(www.geocities.com/Colosseum/Midfield/2640/GAR.HTM): Lots of
bandwidth-eating images, but a nice game-by-game table that tracks
Williams' yardage.
</P>
<P>
   Williams for Heisman
(lonestar.texas.net/~tvf/rickywilliams4heismanhomepage.htm): Long
address, yet lots of research.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Bob's Williams Page
(www.primechoice.com/texas/rickywilliams.html): Clearinghouse of
links to Williams articles.
 &LR; subheds:Chat highlights
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: Chicago Bears quarterback Erik Kramer, 7 tonight on
NFL.com's Quarterback Club chat series (www.nfl.com/qbclub) ... San
Francisco 49ers defensive end Chris Doleman, 8 p.m. Thursday,
Players Chat (www.nflplayers.com) ... golf legend Jack Nicklaus, 7
tonight, CBS SportsLine.
</P>
<P>
   On America Online: Detroit Lions QB Scott Mitchell at 8 tonight
on AOL QB Club Chat (keyword: Sports Live) ... Indianapolis Colts
QB Peyton Manning, 7 p.m. tomorrow, AOL QB Club Chat.
 &LR; subheds:At the polls
</P>
<P>
   Former Rangers pitcher Kevin Brown's worth as a free agent? In
ESPN.com polls, 40.5 percent of 21,037 respondents say he deserves
the biggest contract of the remaining free agents; 54.8 percent of
8,371 voters say he deserves an average annual salary of $13
million to $14 million ... Of 27,320 respondents in a CNN/SI.com
poll, 56 percent (15,167) voted that they couldn't care less about
the NBA lockout.
</P>
</TEXT>
