<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9865 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELN-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-02 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. NEWSPAPERS SWAP BLOWS OVER CANDIDATE'S LINK TO GAY CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (p, a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just one week before Election Day, The (Manchester) Union Leader
dropped a bombshell _ or what some would call a stink bomb _ into
the middle of a hard-fought New Hampshire state Senate contest.
</P>
<P>
   Reinforcing its reputation as the Granite State's bastion of
conservatism, the Oct. 27 Union Leader ran a story linking
Democratic candidate Rick Trombly to a gay club that holds monthly
``leather nights.'' A day later, a Union Leader editorial claimed
Trombly's sexual identity wasn't the relevant issue. But it implied
that he did not have the ``sound moral and family values'' for
public office and emphasized the point by sprinkling in such
phrases as ``rubber orgy'' and ``quaint homosexual fetishes.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows whether The Union Leader will influence today's
state Senate voting. But in outing Trombly _ a respected former
House Democratic leader challenging a Republican incumbent _ it has
brought accusations of an ideological smear, resurrected the
chronic journalistic dilemma about the relevance of a public
figure's private life, and triggered a newspaper war between The
Union Leader and the Concord Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bilious spirit of (the late &UR;  &LR; publisher) William Loeb still
haunts the newsroom of The Union Leader,'' declared an indignant
Oct. 29 Monitor editorial. ``The paper's scurvy attack on Senate
candidate Rick Trombly was a reminder of its bad old days _ and
fresh cause for shame, not satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released after The Union Leader story, Trombly
asked voters to ``reject gutter politics.'' In some quarters, the
episode seemed to exemplify The Union Leader's take-no-prisoners
approach to politics. With Democratic governor Jeanne Shaheen
favored to win reelection, there is speculation that Democrats
could make inroads into the GOP's 15-9 edge in the state Senate.
Trombly is widely viewed as having launched a serious challenge to
Republican Amy Patenaude.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had done polling to show this as a winnable race,'' says a
Democratic Party spokesman, Jon Paone. ``There's no level The Union
Leader will not sink to to push its political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they ... try to throw their weight around in the
political arena,'' says Clark Hubbard, a University of New
Hampshire political science professor, noting that demographic
changes are moderating the state's conservative politics and
reducing the ranks of ``Union &UR;  &LR; Leader stalwarts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think if this was a candidate who shared The
Union Leader's political philosphy, they would not have done
this,'' says Concord Monitor editor Mike Pride.
</P>
<P>
   Union Leader editor Joseph McQuade rejects charges that his
paper dredged up dirt on Trombly to bury a political foe. ``In the
immortal words of Dave Puddy from `Seinfeld,''' he says, ```That's
bogus, man.''' The Union Leader's Oct. 27 story was generated when
the paper discovered Trombly's home phone number on the gay club's
Web site and found a source who said Trombly is the group's
president, before later recanting. Trombly told the paper that he
is a lawyer for the club, but not a member. And he said his sexual
identity is not relevant to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found in the public interest the nature of this club and
the nature of Mr. Trombly's relationship to it,'' says McQuade.
``The guy is running for fairly high public office in the state of
New Hampshire. ... I'd feel the same if this was swinging singles
of the heterosexual variety.''
</P>
<P>
   While declining to criticize The Union Leader, New Hampshire
Republican Party chairman Steve Duprey calls Trombly a friend and
says ``his sexuality isn't an issue. ... Absent some clear and
compelling connection (with his public duties), someone's private
life should be just that.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the state's media has kept The Union Leader's story at
arm's length. According to the Associated Press bureau chief for
northern New England, Larry Laughlin, the wire service initially
picked up the story because ``it couldn't be ignored.'' But it has
run nothing in recent days ``in view of the fact that it was a
highly inflammatory story that was coming out shortly before an
election.''
</P>
<P>
   The (Nashua, N.H.) Telegraph briefly mentioned the controversy
in a political column Nov. 1. But editor George Geers says the
Trombly race is not in the paper's circulation area and ``there was
a sense it was a cheap shot by The Union Leader.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed to us to be a questionable story,'' adds Thomas
Kearney, executive editor of The Keene (N.H.) Sentinel. ``It's just
another example of the chute news organizations have been sliding
down for decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than The Union Leader, the one outlet to hop on the
controversy was the considerably more liberal Monitor. On Oct. 28,
it reacted to The Union Leader's story with a piece highlighting
Trombly's accusations of ``gutter politics.'' It ran a story
explaining why the Monitor, which had also received a tip about
Trombly and the Minotaurs, declined to pursue that lead. And in
addition to its scathing anti-Union Leader editorial, the Monitor
published two Sunday columns critical of its rival's ethics.
</P>
<P>
   One, authored by Pride, said The Union Leader had ``crossed the
line into character assassination in its effort to defeat Rick
Trombly.'' When asked why it had given so much ink to a story it
found so vile, Pride replied that ``once a story is out there, no
matter what the source, you're better off writing as thoughtfully
and comprehensively as you can about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some observers think the rivalry between The Union Leader
and the Monitor helped fan the flames of a story that the has not
drawn much public interest. Telegraph editor Geers says the ``two
newspapers created a news event that surpasses what the event was
about.'' Adds Duprey: ``In most of these cat fights, whether you
get 'em between candidates or newspapers, no one comes out smelling
like a rose.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Jurkowitz is media reporter for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 1936EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
