u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELN-VOTERS-BOS &LR;      11-02 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-VOTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS WANT VOTES TO SEND A MESSAGE ON CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (p and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over breakfast Monday at a diner in Santa Monica, Calif.,
Lorraine Hoover expressed the sentiment of many voters who are
poised to send the Republican-controlled Congress a message Tuesday
about the impeachment case against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Republicans are wrong,'' said Hoover, a registered
Republican and retired junior high school English teacher from
Thayne, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover said she weighed the costly investigation into whether
Clinton and the former White House intern, Monica S. Lewinsky,
engaged in ``sex between two consenting adults'' when she recently
cast her absentee ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I normally vote the person,'' Hoover said. ``This time it was
straight ticket, a no-brainer. I thought if Republicans were voting
Democratic, that would send a message.''
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Clinton's impeachment case may hang in the balance
Tuesday, as tens of millions of voters head to the polls amid
varying degrees of disdain for Clinton's sex scandal and disgust
with the congressional response to it.
</P>
<P>
   Impeach the president, censure him, or rebuke an overreaching
Congress. By most accounts, the results of Tuesday's mid-term
congressional elections are likely to be interpreted by leaders on
Capitol Hill as a referendum on the historic impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; If they had their way, scores of prospective voters across the
country said in recent days, they would send Clinton and the
Congress a common message: Stop the wrangling and move on.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews from Boston to San Francisco Bay, a small number
of voters called for Clinton's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I find him a despicable person, and he needs to be put
out,'' said Jack O'Connell, 49, a ``government worker'' and
registered Republican, of Apopka, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said he plans to vote for a straight Republican ticket
in the hope congressional GOP leaders will make Clinton's
impeachment their top priority.
</P>
<P>
   But most shared the sentiments of Keith Howard, 24, of Norwood,
who said he wants Congress to drop the impeachment inquiry ``for
the best interest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard, waiting for a train at South Station after studying
downtown for a job in the travel industry, said he voted for Texas
billionaire Ross Perot in the last presidential election ``because
I didn't think he was a womanizer.''
</P>
<P>
   But he wants no more time wasted examining Clinton's alleged
womanizing. ``I'm not Hillary,'' Howard said, ``so I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Many others said they detest Clinton's personal failures, but
they praised his performance as president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think he was a great president, but this whole thing
with Monica Lewinsky is just too cheap,'' said Mandy Samuels, 23, a
waitress and single mother from Maitland, Fla. ``He reminds me of
too many middle-aged guys who come on to me _ more than just
flirting, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   But Samuels said she is voting Democratic in her House and
Senate races because she wants to send the message that Clinton
should remain in office. ``He's been good for the country. What can
I say? I don't want my little girl to grow up in a country run by
gun nuts and religious fanatics, so Clinton's the man,'' Samuels
said.
</P>
<P>
   The refrain was similar among some voters interviewed in
Chicago. Dylan Lower, 20, a Kansas native and registered
Independent who is studying in Chicago, said he is more likely to
support Democrats because he believes the independent counsel,
Kenneth W. Starr, has searched overzealously for dirt on Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the matter, period,'' Lower said. ``It's been
blown up into something bigger than it needs to have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Both apathy and disillusionment were abundant among eligible
voters across the country, an indication of what many analysts have
predicted will be an abysmal turnout. A large number of eligible
voters said they had not bothered registering to vote and many
others said they were too busy to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Among most of the non-voters, the general attitude was, why
bother, since it doesn't matter anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But many other eligible voters were plenty bothered by the
Republican push for the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I appreciate what Clinton did, but my senator
didn't tell him to go play around with Monica,'' said Martha
Graeber, a Seattle shipping manager who considers herself an
Independent. ``What I don't want is them harping on this. I want
them watching the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wresley Rush, a retired radio broadcaster from the San Francisco
Bay area, is a registered Republican who rarely votes Democratic.
``But I'd vote for Clinton at the drop of a coin because he's done
a great job,'' Rush said. ``I'm in his corner.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's supporting Democrats in part to prove it, including
voting for Senator Barbara Boxer, who is seen by many Republicans
as an extreme liberal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans hurt themselves tremendously by pursuing
this,'' said Rush. ``There's going to be a backlash against them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mary Siler, who said she tends to vote Democratic, said she
is not sure Democrats would run Congress any better than
Republicans have.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a difficult time to decide how to vote,'' said Siler,
55, an administrative assistant for an insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, which is solid Clinton country, the sex
scandal appears to have diminished support for him, and for
Democrats, not a whit. If anything, the Republican appetite for the
scandal has bolstered convictions in this liberal, heavily
Democratic region that the Republicans are preoccupied with
vengeful pettiness and must be defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Leonard, who was arranging a paper turkey display in the
window of his pet shop in the Glen Park neighborhood on Sunday
afternoon, said the scandal indeed had affected the way he would
vote _ but not by provoking the anti-Democratic backlash predicted
by the Republicans. ``It's made me more positive than ever that
I've got to get the Republicans out of there,'' said Leonard, a
registered Democrat in his 50s. ``They're wasting my time and
money.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe correspondents Jane Adams in San Francisco, Brad Liston
in Orlando, Fla., and Stephen J. Siegel in Chicago contributed to
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
