<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: THIS IS A RESEND OF A STORY FILED FOR MONDAY, NOV. 2 
 
SCELZI PUTS PEDAL TO METAL TO BREAK 326-MPH BARRIER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TERRY BLOUNT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Before the rain came Sunday to postpone the last two
rounds of the Matco Tools SuperNationals, Gary Scelzi stormed his
way into drag-racing history. All drag-racing fans have been
waiting and wondering when they would see the first 325-mph run.
</P>
<P>
   They are still waiting to see 325, but they aren't waiting any
longer to see 326 mph after Scelzi became the fastest drag racer
ever with consecutive record-setting runs at Houston Raceway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi was the first person to top 324 mph with a first-round
pass at 324.32 mph and a winning elapsed time of 4.544 seconds in
the Winston Top Fuel dragster. Later, in the second round, he
stunned the crowd again by blowing past 325 and posting an
astonishing 326.44-mph pass with a 4.530 ET.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have got to be kidding me,'' Scelzi said when told about
the 326-mph pass as he got out of the car. ``My God. The thing
popped up the front end, and it was flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi would not get a chance for a third consecutive record
pass. The rain arrived at 1:30 p.m. CST and caused an eight-hour
delay before NHRA officials had some of the Sportsman cars make
passes on the track. However, the cooler air and a slight mist made
conditions too hazardous to continue, so the decision was made to
postpone the remainder of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Fans got their money's worth in the first two rounds before it
started raining. Scelzi's two runs easily eclipsed the previous
record of 323.89 mph set by John Force last May in Englishtown,
N.J. But Force still can boast of having the fastest speed in a
Funny Car.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in speed this season has made 320-mph runs almost
commonplace. It was a little more than a year ago when Cory
McClenathan became the first driver to surpass 320 mph when he ran
a 321.77 mph at Ennis in the McDonald's dragster.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the speed record is nice, but Scelzi and McClenathan
have more important things on their minds these days. Scelzi leads
McClenathan by 73 points as the two drivers compete in the
next-to-last event of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting to run out of rounds,'' said McClenathan, who
also advanced to the semifinals before the rain came. ``Gary's team
is so strong right now that it's hard to keep up. I would love to
be able to put that No. 1 on the car, but if not this year, we will
come back next year and try to do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi virtually clinched his first championship here last
season (needing only to make a qualifying attempt in the last
event) as a Top Fuel rookie when he won the inaugural Matco Tools
SuperNationals. McClenathan finished No. 2 in the points for the
third time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for McClenathan for now is that he has won the
last two events this season _ Atlanta and Topeka _ that were
postponed because of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Force moved two steps closer to his eighth Funny Car title by
winning his first two rounds Sunday, including a second-round
victory over teammate Tony Pedregon in the Selena-themed Syntec
Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   Force has a 90-point lead over Ron Capps, who also advanced to
the semifinals. If Force wins the event and sets a national record,
he can clinch the championship. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
