<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9869 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELN-ISSUES-BOS &LR;      11-02 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-ISSUES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESULTS WILL HAVE LITTLE IMPACT ON ISSUES, MANY FEEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (p and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By this time Wednesday, nearly all the winners will
be known in 34 Senate races, 435 House contests and elections for
governor in 36 states. What will not be clear is this: What should
all those politicians do with their new power?
</P>
<P>
   From Social Security to education and tax policy, advocates for
some of the most heated issues of the day say the 1998 election
will produce few clues, and certainly little consensus, about the
direction that voters want their elected leaders to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a missed opportunity, and I don't think the election
results will tell us anything,'' said Robert Bixby, policy director
for the Concord Coalition, which is trying to foster a national
discussion about the financially troubled Social Security program.
</P>
<P>
   Pundits are calling it ``the Seinfeld election,'' an election
that, like the TV show, is essentially about nothing. ``There are
just no prevailing national issues this time,'' said Jennifer Duffy
of the Cook Political Report, who popularized the Seinfeld line.
</P>
<P>
   How should we fix Social Security? Should we raise the
retirement age? Give workers their own stock accounts? Use our
first-in-a-generation surplus to shore up the program? Few
candidates waded into these details, analysts say, so the election
will likely give little insight about solutions.
</P>
<P>
   With one-quarter of the world in recession, candidates might
have debated ways to make sure the US economy does not falter. But
few candidates talked about whether we can boost growth by changing
the tax code, or by spending our way out of a future slowdown, or
about other solutions. A proposal to give President Clinton ``fast
track'' powers to sign new trade treaties became a contentious
issue in Congress this session, but it barely registered with
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had some honest policy discourse on those
issues...Neither party wants to discuss an economic slowdown when
everyone is trying to take credit for the surplus and our economic
success story so far,'' said Bruce Josten, executive vice president
at the US Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   With the single-rate ``flat tax'' a hot issue in the last
presidential race, candidates might have given a clue about whether
they would scrap the current tax code for something new. ``I
haven't heard of a single case where it's surfaced as an issue in
any race,'' said Dale Jorgenson, a Harvard University economist who
promotes taxing consumption instead of income.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of responding to a national theme, voters will head to
the polls Tuesday because of local personalities, local issues and,
in many cases, to register their opinion about whether to punish
President Clinton for lying about an extramarital affair. ``The
public isn't clamoring for Washington to embark on some big new
program or for the government to stop doing something,'' Josten
said. ``We are literally into the Tip O'Neil `All politics is
local' debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of candidates, for example, are talking about education.
But the issue in Massachusetts turns on expanded teacher testing,
as promoted in different forms by both major candidates for
governor, while in South Carolina the debate is whether to create a
state lottery to finance public education.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to education, Democrats are talking about the need
to shore up Social Security and to give patients new powers when
fighting their health maintenance organizations for medical
coverage. But so are Republicans. ``Candidates will say they all
agree that something has to be done about HMOs, but we have
different ways of getting there. And no one really gets to the
details of what the different ways are,'' said Duffy of the Cook
report.
</P>
<P>
   That means that no matter which party comes out ahead Tuesday,
it will be hard to find a mandate for any policy changes, said
Frank Newport, editor in chief of the Gallup Poll. Teasing out a
mandate will be far harder than in 1994, when Republicans laid out
their platform in the Contract with America, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reading the results will be particularly hard, Newport said,
because a strong Democratic showing may have less to do with the
party's policy ideas than with the voters' distaste for how
Republicans have handled the impeachment process. Similarly, it
will be hard to know if voters chose Republicans in order to
support GOP programs or to help remove Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a national theme may have to do with the fact that
Americans are fairly happy these days. When the Gallup Organization
surveyed people this year on various aspects of their lives, such
as their income, safety from physical harm and prospects for the
future, people reported levels of satisfaction as high as any since
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, politicians are now polling so relentlessly that they
can form positions that conform to the public's view, Newport said.
``You look at all this -- that we are basically a happy nation,
that politicians are sensitive to our positions, and that the
public is not looking for dramatic change right now -- and it will
be hard to tease out an urgent message from whatever happens in the
election,'' Newport said.
</P>
<P>
   Some policy advocates say that a mid-term election is the wrong
forum for debating the details of national policy. ``A presidential
election is more appropriate,'' said Jorgenson, the Harvard
economist. ``Congressional elections are local in character.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Pollack, executive director of Families USA, a health
consumer advocacy group, said that elections tend to turn on broad
themes, rather than on details. He said he was satisfied that a
large number of candidates backed the ``Patients Bill of Rights,''
which would give patients more powers when fighting HMOs for
medical care. It did not trouble him that in few races did the
candidates debate individual provisions, such as when HMOs must
cover emergency care or whether patients should have new rights to
sue insurers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it would be better if we had those details, but you
often can't get to that level of specificity in a campaign. I think
it's asking a little bit too much,'' Pollack said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some advocates hoped that the elections this year would
have produced a greater number of nuanced, substantive debates.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats rallied behind President Clinton's call to hire
100,000 new teachers, and Republicans also talked about reducing
class sizes. But some critics complained that few candidates talked
about how to train all those teachers, or about how to retain the
good teachers who commonly leave the profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to have heard a candidate say, `Ladies and
gentlemen, no teacher in (Massachusetts) should ever have to teach
more than 80 children in a semester. How are we going to rearrange
the money now spent so that teachers have a class load that is at
least close to what is required for serious work?' '' said Ted
Sizer, a former Brown University guru on high school excellence who
now leads a charter school, with his wife, at what used to be Fort
Devens in Ayer, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But these questions get into the ``painful substance'' of
setting spending priorities. It is easier to lean instead on the
call for 100,000 new teachers, Sizer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
