<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-FILINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAPPENS SEEK `SEVERAL MILLIONS' FROM AU PAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Deborah Eappen's lawyers could not put a price tag on
her son's life, though they tried, asking for ``several million
dollars'' from the au pair who killed him and listing cases where
juries had compensated parents for the deaths of their children.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a mother's aching words, included in court papers
filed in federal court Monday, that made it clear why the loss of
eight-month-old Matthew could not be quantified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mattie will have no resume, no diploma, no trophies, no wife
and children, no science fair project,'' his mother wrote in a
five-page statement to US District Judge William G. Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw him take his first steps, have his first day of
school. I miss what should have been. ... I miss that I never heard
Mattie say, `I love you, Mom.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sunil and Deborah Eappen have already won their wrongful death
suit against British au pair Louise Woodward by default, after
Woodward said she could not afford a lawyer to the fight the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In a filing Monday in US District Court, the attorneys for the
Eappens _ Fredric L. Ellis, Edward D. Rapacki and Edward A.
Broderick of Boston and Edward C. Bassett Jr. of Worcester _ were
supposed to suggest how much money they believe Young should award
the couple. He is expected to rule by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   While Monday's court filing does not seek a specific amount in
damages, it does estimate what Matthew could have been expected to
earn in his lifetime: between $1.18 million and $1.67 million. The
lower figure is based on his choosing a profession such as law,
engineering or accounting, the higher on joining his parents and
paternal grandfather in medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, whatever damages Young ultimately awards the Eappens may
prove to be a hollow victory, since the judge has already noted
that Woodward appears to have no assets ``of any significant
size.''
</P>
<P>
   Young has already issued an order prohibiting Woodward from
spending any money she receives for selling her story, which she
and her family have insisted she does not intend to do. Meanwhile,
investigators here and abroad are probing expenditures from the
$500,000 legal defense fund set up in England to pay Woodward's
legal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Eappens have said they filed the wrongful death suit to
prevent Woodward from profiting from the death of Matthew. The
couple plans to donate any money they may get to a foundation
they've established to prevent child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   In the court filing, the Eappens' lawyers also point to a
half-dozen jury verdicts this decade in wrongful death suits
involving children 10 or younger. In four of the cases, the
plaintiffs were awarded $2 million or more in compensatory damages.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a Superior Court jury in October 1990 awarded $2.75
million in compensatory damages to the parents of an 8-month-old
baby who was killed in a fall from a walker.
</P>
<P>
   The Eappens' lawyers are seeking an equal amount in compensatory
and punitive damages, requesting ``several million dollars'' in
each category.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis has said that it is unclear whether any award would be
collectible in England but having a judge, rather than a jury,
determine damages may improve the chances because British judges
may view a judge's award more favorably.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1997 Woodward was convicted of second-degree
murder and sentenced to life in prison. Superior Court Judge Hiller
Zobel later reduced the charge to manslaughter and sentenced
Woodward to time already served, 279 days. She returned home to
England in June after the state Supreme Judicial Court upheld
Zobel's actions.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post reported Monday that the number of British
au pairs in the United States has fallen drastically in the wake of
Woodward's trial and conviction.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures provided by the newspaper from au pair
agencies here and in Britain, about 400 British au pairs will be
placed in homes in the United States this year, down from 1,500 in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Agencies told the newspaper that many young British women are
fearful of applying for US positions because of the way Woodward
was treated by the American legal system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
