<SLUG> BC-GLENN-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN TURNS SOMERSAULTS DURING TIME OFF IN SPACE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Glenn, the world's oldest active astronaut, turned
somersaults and played with floating globs of water on Monday as he
shared time off in space with his younger colleagues aboard the
shuttle Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   As Discovery's planned nine-day mission neared the half-way
point, NASA offered the six-man, one-woman crew about five hours to
gaze from the windows of the shuttle and try the things a child
might enjoy in weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``What comprises relaxation here is really standing on your
head, looking at things a different way, Glenn explained while
attempting to demonstrate the maneuver for a network news anchor.
``We did some things like make balls of water that float out in
front that you can inject with air bubbles that are very, very
unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   The elderly astronaut became the first American in orbit in
1962. But his flight was so brief, less then five hours, and his
Mercury capsule so small that there was no time for such
shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   Even on his longer encore visit to space, Glenn seemed reluctant
to characterize the break as a dereliction of duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a 100 percent day off, it's a little bit more relaxed
up here. All the research and the experiments are still going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The respite permitted all of the astronauts 15-minutes to visit
with family members using camera-equipped laptop computers aboard
the shuttle and in mission control to transmit pictures as well as
sound to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn visited with his wife, Annie, son, David, and daughter,
Lyn, who are monitoring the flight from Houston. Glenn's two
teen-age grandsons, Zachary and Daniel, participated by telephone
from their California home.
</P>
<P>
   He told his family that ``everything could not be going
better,'' said Jack Sparks, Glenn's U.S. Senate office spokesman.
Glenn's family was pleased the 77-year-old has fared well
physically on the flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average 77-year-old person in good health could certainly
come up here and experience this,'' said Glenn, who had to satisfy
NASA's medical experts that he was up to the flight and the
training that led up to it.
</P>
<P>
   The mission has captured the attention of young and old
worldwide since Discovery blasted off last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very nice to see all the folks around the world and
certainly the United States interested in the space program,'' said
Curt Brown, Discovery's commander. ``Maybe this flight will get the
word out and help people understand what we actually do on these
missions.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Discovery crew plans to retrieve the
satellite-based solar observatory called Spartan that was deployed
on Sunday with the shuttle's robot arm.
</P>
<P>
   The retrieval is set for midafternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The $9 million satellite trailed the shuttle crew on Monday,
recording observations of the sun's outer atmosphere and the solar
wind with a pair of telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and pilot Steve Lindsey plan to maneuver the shuttle
behind and then beneath Spartan so that astronaut Steve Robinson
can use the shuttle's robot arm to recapture the boxy, 3,000 pound
observatory.
</P>
<P>
   The observatory should collect about 1,200 images.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we could be any happier with the results this
far,'' said Craig Tooley, NASA's mission manager for Spartan. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
