<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTIONS-COX     11-02 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich may become 'stuck in middle' despite GOP election gains
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving on (a) general news and (w) Washington categories.)
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He's campaigned in every state save Hawaii and raised
millions of dollars to widen the Republican majority in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens to Speaker Newt Gingrich if his Republicans do
not make solid gains in today's election?
</P>
<P>
   ``It obviously doesn't help him,'' said Randall Strahan, an
Emory University political scientist who is writing a book about
the speakership.
</P>
<P>
   Strahan said anything less than 10 seats would not be a
significant addition to the GOP majority in the House. The
Republicans currently hold 228 seats. There are 206 Democrats and
an independent who generally votes with them.
</P>
<P>
   The party's second-guessers will be out in full force, on the
one hand assailing Gingrich's compromise with President Clinton on
last month's $520 billion spending deal and on the other hand
chiding him for an aggressive pursuit of impeachment in the face of
polls that indicate impeachment lacks public support.
</P>
<P>
   In the event Republicans pick up fewer than 10 seats _ and there
is a growing view among analysts that GOP gains will be limited _
Gingrich's first headache may be how to handle the ongoing
impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will find a division in the House Republican party between
more conservative members who will want to proceed aggressively and
more moderate members who will see the election as a signal to
proceeed cautiously,'' Strahan said. ``And Gingrich will be stuck
in the middle of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Palazzolo, a University of Richmond political scientist who
has written extensively about Gingrich, said that even if
Republicans add 20 seats to their majority, Gingrich still would
have to deal with a fractious membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be enough to get him out of the woods, although it
could make Clinton's situation more tenuous,'' Palazzolo said. ``He
won't be able to push the most strident issues the right wing of
the party wants to deal with. That's the problem with this
election. It's not going to shake things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich Galen, a close Gingrich adviser, disagreed with the
assessment of the academics.
</P>
<P>
   He said the speaker will not allow election returns affect the
impeachment process. ``I don't care what happens tomorrow,'' Galen
said. ``If I had to bet right now, I'd bet you that sometime in
late January or early February, there will be a vote on the House
floor to impeach and the matter will be sent to the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Galen acknowledged that Gingrich would have to manage the
competing interests of the GOP's various factions, but he took
issue with the claim that the party, and the speaker, would not be
strengthened if more Republicans, even as few as eight, serve in
the next Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be the first time since 1946 with fewer than 200
members on their side of the aisle,'' Galen said. ``No matter what
the White House says about it being a great victory, Democrats in
the House (are not) going to see it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent grumbling among conservatives who were upset
with the budget compromise with Clinton, the prospect of ousting
Gingrich as speaker appears remote.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative and moderate wings of the GOP would have
enormous difficulty agreeing on a successor, Palazzolo said.
</P>
<P>
   And many Republicans in the House believe that Gingrich may step
down sometime in 1999 to run for president, making an unpleasant
internecine battle unnecessary, Palazzolo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has weathered the storms,'' he said. ``I think the
fight is going to be over the succession after he leaves, rather
than an attempt to overturn him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
