<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNES-NOBLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Books to remain on Georgia shelves
 &HT;    By Doug Payne
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two books that protesters sought to have condemned as
child pornography do not meet the legal definition of obscene
material, and Cobb County, Ga. authorities will not seek their
removal from bookstore shelves, Solicitor Barry Morgan said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor said he reviewed case law on pornography and
showed copies of the two volumes to grand jury members,
professional photographers and members of civic groups to try to
gauge the community's standards on pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you that no one condoned or approved of the
material,'' he said. However, he said, most of the people he showed
the books to felt they were not in violation of state obscenity
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the anti-abortion group Operation Rescue and local
anti-abortion activists staged demonstrations last month outside
two Barnes &AMP; Noble bookstores to bring attention to ``The Age of
Innocence'' by David Hamilton and ``Radiant Identities'' by Jock
Sturges, two photographic collections that show pre-adolescent and
teenage girls and boys in various poses and degrees of nudity.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters expressed disappointment and even shock after
Morgan announced his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next child that is taken into the woods and raped, this
man (Morgan) is going to bear that innocent blood on his hands,''
said the Rev. Phillip Benham, national director of Operation
Rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Michael and Michelle Wolven, two Atlanta-area anti-abortion
activists who took part in the Oct. 19 protest, said they were
disappointed by Morgan's decision but believe he was hamstrung by
state law. Michael Wolven said he and his wife may take the issue
up with the state attorney general's office after today's election.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Morgan said the books ``taken as a whole'' must
appeal to the average person's prurient interest and be lacking in
artistic value. ``I don't think anyone was pleased with the
stuff,'' he said. But ``there is no doubt that it's quality work. .
. . I don't think, taken as a whole, one can say they lack serious
artistic value.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble senior vice president Mary Ellen Keating
applauded the decision, noting that it is in line with the course
of action taken by prosecutors in Texas, Maryland, Kansas and
Wisconsin. Steven Maklansky, curator of photographs at the New
Orleans Museum of Art, has produced museum shows incorporating
Sturges photographs. He said both Sturges and Hamilton are
internationally respected artists whose photographs ``become
metaphors for childhood innocence or adolescence or immaturity or
life transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Sexual deviants and ``hard-core right-wingers'' take the
photographic image too literally, he said. ``Both those sorts of
people see only the naked person. They do not have either the
imagination or the inclination to understand that a photo image,
though apparently real, also can have significant metaphorical
qualities.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Payne writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
