<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nude sign law deemed unconstitutional by Supreme CourtBy Bill
Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A state law prohibiting highway billboards that
advertise nude clubs is unconstitutional because it violates the
rights to freedom of speech, the Georgia Supreme Court ruled
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cafe Erotica, the Peach County, Ga. restaurant featuring nude
dancers, and a billboard company, Sunshine Outdoors Inc.,
challenged the law. The restaurant near I-75 is well-known to
Georgia motorists because it relies heavily on its brightly colored
billboards along interstate highways to draw customers.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimous ruling written by Justice Hugh Thompson, the
court found that the outdoor advertising ban for adult
entertainment ``impedes the free flow of information and far
exceeds the state's legitimate interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling allows all adult entertainment establishments to
continue advertising on highway billboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``My clients are happy with the result,'' Tucker lawyer Thomas
E. Maddox Jr., who represents Cafe Erotica, said.
</P>
<P>
   The state law said such advertising could mislead the public,
hurt property values near the billboards and ``divert the attention
of drivers and thus cause traffic hazards.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
