<SLUG> BC-PIRACY-SOFTWARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT ACCUSES FIVE COMPUTER SELLERS OF PIRACY  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Microsoft Corp. is suing seven Texas computer
resellers, including five in Houston, accusing them of infringing
on the company's copyrights and trademarks.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits, filed in federal courts in Dallas and Houston on
Oct. 27, also allege that all but one of the companies distributed
counterfeit versions of Windows 95 and Office Professional 97.
</P>
<P>
   The five Houston companies are ACS Technology, Biway
International Technology, CPU Distributing, Essex Computers and
Megadyne Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas companies are AR Technologies and SMI Liquidiation.
</P>
<P>
   Megadyne, which does business in Houston as Precision Computers,
is the one company not hit with counterfeit software charges.
</P>
<P>
   AR Technologies is accused of putting unauthorized copies of
Windows 95 and Office Professional 97 on the hard disks of
computers it sold, a practice known as ``hard disk loading.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said hard disk loading, counterfeit distribution by
resellers and unauthorized multiple installations of software in
businesses are the three most prevalent forms of software piracy.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammad Issa, president of Essex Computers of Houston, told
Reuters News Service he was seeking legal advice and intended to
fight the Microsoft lawsuit. He said his company had not intended
to sell counterfeit Microsoft products and had purchased equipment
in good faith from distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a spokesman for Biway in Houston said there had been
no intent to sell counterfeit Microsoft products. He said Biway had
been cooperating with Microsoft sales representatives to identify
counterfeits.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Lain, an attorney for ACS, said he was in discussions
with Microsoft's lawyers about the suit and could not comment
further.
</P>
<P>
   The other Houston companies either had no comment, or did not
return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The suits were spurred by tips to an anti-software-piracy hot
line operated by Microsoft. The software giant gets approximately
2,000 calls and e-mail messages a month about potentially pirated
products. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 1956EST &QL; 
