<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BMC-BOOLE-MERGER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BMC ACQUIRES BOOLE &AMP; BABBAGE AND ANOTHER SILICON VALLEY FOOTHOLD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ BMC Software's $877 million acquisition of Boole &AMP;
Babbage financially combines two companies, but their customers
have been putting them together for years.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, formally announced Monday, creates a software
company with approximately $1.1 billion in combined revenues. BMC's
global workforce will swell from 3,200 to 4,400, and Boole's San
Jose, Calif., offices will give BMC another recruiting foothold in
Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The all-stock transaction has Houston-based BMC giving .675
shares of its stock for every share of Boole &AMP; Babbage. The deal is
expected to close by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   When it does, company executives said it will place BMC in the
``next tier'' of competition, where it will face down such giants
as Computer Associates and IBM.
</P>
<P>
   It's a marriage that's been in the works for about two months,
said Max P. Watson Jr., BMC's chief executive, when BMC first
approached Boole about a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an attractive combination, and shame on me, we should
have done it earlier,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   BMC's stock closed Monday at 46 1/16, down 2 on volume of 7.9
million shares. Boole &AMP; Babbage closed at 30 [, up 3 {, a 52-week
high, on volume of 5.3 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies make software designed to be used on big computer
mainframes, as well as on sprawling corporate networks.
</P>
<P>
   BMC's products are used to monitor, enhance and maintain large
applications, such as databases and workflow management software.
</P>
<P>
   Boole's products, on the other hand, do the same thing for the
computer systems themselves, making sure that networks and
computers are functioning properly and automatically fixing them if
need be.
</P>
<P>
   Watson said the goal is to create products that mesh seamlessly.
For example, the companies might combine their various monitoring
products so that technicians can track nearly every aspect of a
mainframe running a sophisticated database from a single
software-based control panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers need a more integrated system,'' Watson said.
``Boole &AMP; Babbage operates in the same general area as BMC, but
there is no product or revenue overlap. We can extend our reach to
reach to areas that are complementary.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer network managers have been figuring out ways to make
the two companies' products work together, usually by cobbling
together an on-screen display that presents the programs side by
side.
</P>
<P>
   But customers like Bert Cooley, a technical leader in the
information services division of New York State Electric and Gas,
said he hopes the merger will result in a more integrated product
line.
</P>
<P>
   Cooley said he uses BMC software designed to speed up and
maintain his operation's databases, and a Boole program called
Command Post that lets him monitor his network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've put together an interface (that joins the programs), but
it's very minimal,'' said Cooley. ``That is one of the things I
would be looking for in this merger. It would make it much easier
to monitor everything that's going on from one location.''
</P>
<P>
   Boole, a relatively old company in the high-tech world, was
founded in 1967 and bears the names of two early legends of
computing. George Boole (1815-1864) is considered the father of
computer science. Charles Babbage (1791-1871) is credited with the
design of the modern computer, which he called a ``difference and
analytical engine.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paul E. Newton, Boole's president and chief executive, said
the company will drop its name and become a part of BMC, though it
will maintain its San Jose headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Newton said he will stay on until some time next year to help
with the integration of the two companies. He also said only a
handful of jobs will be lost, most likely in the combining of
regional offices.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies were born in an era when the mainframe computer
was king. And both have successfully weathered the transition in
corporations to what's known as distributed computing, in which
different kinds of machines are linked by complex networks.
</P>
<P>
   Software companies who design programs for use on mainframes and
networks have found their stock battered in recent weeks as several
bellwethers _ most notably PeopleSoft and Baan Systems _ have
reported poor earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But Melissa Eisenstat, an analyst with CIBC Oppenheimer in New
York, said that while information systems managers may be buying
fewer products from those companies, the outlook for BMC and Boole
&AMP; Babbage is better.
</P>
<P>
   ``People today are trying to digest all the software they have
bought, and they are having problems doing so,'' Eisenstat said.
``BMC and Boole make software that makes all the other software you
bought work.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenstat said the acquisition bumps up her estimate of BMC's
one-year profits by nickel to 1.95 a share. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
