<SLUG> BC-ELN-NY-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. SENATOR RACE IN DEAD HEAT, POLLS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (p and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton came to New York again Monday,
making her fourth appearance in the past month to rally Democrats
behind Charles Schumer's campaign to oust three-term incumbent
Republican Alfonse D'Amato from the US Senate.
</P>
<P>
   On the final day before the vote in the closest, bitterest, and
most expensive contest in the country, both candidates scrambled to
solidify their bases _ Schumer and Mrs. Clinton speaking to a labor
union in Manhattan, and D'Amato joining Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and
former mayor Edward Koch on a stroll through the Russian-immigrant
enclave of Brighton Beach in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Every poll paints the contest as a statistical dead heat, with
Schumer way ahead in the city, D'Amato somewhat ahead upstate, and
the two neck-and-neck in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons, who are very popular here, have involved
themselves in this race with unusual intensity. Besides the first
lady's weekly visits, President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore
have each come to Schumer's side twice.
</P>
<P>
   In a year when five Democratic senators are in danger of losing
elections, Schumer, a congressman from Brooklyn for the past 18
years, is one of the few candidates who could unseat a Republican _
and the kingpin of New York's Republican Party, at that.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton made only a veiled reference to her husband's
political scandals, saying that Republican victories in this
election would mean ``another year of partisanship'' instead of
dealing with social problems.
</P>
<P>
   The main mission of this trip _ and of the most recent trips by
the president and Gore _ appeared to be a get-out-the-vote cry
aimed mainly at the city's blacks, almost all of whom are Democrats
but few of whom vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we vote, we win,'' Schumer told more than 500 members of
the largely black local of the Service Employees International
Union, leading them in a chant of the phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who was wildly applauded, exhorted the workers to
tell all their friends to vote. She acknowledged that often the
differences between candidates seem small, but added, ``You sure
can't say that this time,'' noting the gulf between the two on gun
control, public education, Medicare, and abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   She also played on the gospel-like atmosphere of the rally,
saying, ``There are only two places where you are equal _ in church
before God, and in the voting booth.'' The crowd cheered.
</P>
<P>
   New York Democrats have recently lost key races because minority
and working-class city dwellers turned out in low numbers. In the
1994 governor's race, residents of New York City, who made up 40
percent of the state's voting-age population, supplied just 28
percent of the vote. As a result, Democrat Mario Cuomo lost to
small-town upstate Republican George W. Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Schumer flew to Albany and Buffalo, the upstate
cities with the largest pockets of Democratic support. D'Amato also
plowed through Long Island, the suburban area where the Republican
organization is strongest.
</P>
<P>
   In Brighton Beach, Koch and Giuliani, speaking on the street to
a few dozen people, mainly Russian Jews, pushed all the right
buttons, noting D'Amato's record in helping Israel, Soviet
immigrants, and the Jews who were attacked in the 1991 Crown
Heights race riot.
</P>
<P>
   The three politicians were joined by the mother of Yankel
Rosenbaum, the Talmudic scholar who was killed in that riot. She
said she flew all the way from Australia, where she now lives, to
help get out the vote for D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   Jews, who make up 15 percent of New York's voters, could be a
deciding force in this election. D'Amato, who is Catholic but long
active in Jewish causes, won 40 percent of the Jewish vote in his
last election, a startlingly high number for a Republican. Schumer,
who is Jewish, has taken back much of that group, slicing its
support for D'Amato in half, according to one poll.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, who also campaigned with Giuliani in the heavily Jewish
neighborhood of Borough Park on Sunday, must know that boosting his
share by a mere percentage point or two could put him over the top.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato has taken a slight slide in the past couple weeks, first
after calling Schumer a ``putzhead,'' a Yiddish vulgarism, then
giving a shrill performance in two televised debates.
</P>
<P>
   He has scored most points in attacking Schumer's failure to show
up for many votes in the House this past year while out
campaigning. This tactic seemed to have some effect in Brighton
Beach. Simon Komissar, a neighborhood leader who came out to greet
D'Amato, said of the Democratic challenger, ``He's done little.''
Joseph Kruglach agreed: ``Sure, Schumer's Jewish, but that doesn't
mean anything. What matters is, he doesn't vote.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
