<SLUG> BC-LONDON-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONDON FUTURES EXCHANGE TO REORGANIZE
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Under pressure to make its trading system faster and
cheaper, the London International Financial Futures and Options
Exchange on Monday announced a sweeping reorganization intended to
cut its operating costs in half by the end of next year. The
changes will mean a loss of 600 of its 1,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was the latest indication that the exchange,
known as Liffe, is under growing pressure _ predominantly from the
new German-Swiss Eurex futures exchange _ to accelerate its move
toward screen-based trading and away from its slower and more
costly open-outcry system.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Williamson, the new chairman of the London exchange, said
it ``needs to act decisively and quickly'' against sharp
competition. The London derivatives market _ once unchallenged as
the biggest of its kind in Europe _ has been under increasing
pressure since the Deutsche Terminborse, Frankfurt's futures
market, seized control of the benchmark 10-year German bond market
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   With the creation of a German-Swiss electronic futures exchange,
Liffe has been caught up in such competition between European
exchanges in advance of the January introduction of the euro, the
single European currency, which will change European trading by
creating huge bond and stock markets denominated in the new
currency.
</P>
<P>
   Liffe executives said at a news conference Monday that the
reorganization would be carried out on three levels: cost savings,
including a reduction in the number of employees to 400 by the end
1999; a quest for new partners in different time zones, and changes
in regulations now modeled on the practices at Chicago trading-pit
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that nothing remotely like our current cost base
is sustainable and that we shall have to cut jobs to remain
competitive,'' Williamson said. The cuts are supposed to reduce the
exchange's operating budget to about $100 million by the end of
next year from more than $200 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to deliver an efficient trading platform and products
that our customers want at a price they are prepared to pay,'' he
said. ``It is clear we shall have to cut jobs to remain
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Liffe executives declined to comment on potential new partners.
In the past, traders have spoken of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
as a possible partner, mirroring negotiations reportedly under way
between Frankfurt-based futures traders and the Chicago Board of
Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Liffe and the London Clearing House have also discussed closer
cooperation. Williamson also said that ``one of the strategies is
to talk to Chicago and Frankfurt.''
</P>
<P>
   He is scheduled to travel to Chicago this week, but ruled out an
announcement there. ``We have a program starting quite soon where
we will take up offers of interest and we will initiate talks,''
Williamson said.
</P>
<P>
   The third aspect of the changes involves drawing up regulations
for automated trading, Liffe executives said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement showed how much the introduction of the euro is
pushing markets into alliances beyond their traditional boundaries.
Frankfurt and London have become the main rivals for derivatives
trading, while some smaller futures exchanges, such as the Matif in
Paris, have thus far been squeezed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 2002EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0351 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9917 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELN-MASS-TWO-PARTY-BO     11-02 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-MASS-TWO-PARTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENEWAL OF TWO-PARTY POLITICS AT STAKE IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (p and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH AND FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Massachusetts citizens head to the polls Tuesday,
they may decide an issue that has scarcely been talked about:
Whether the state will take a small step toward a competitive
two-party system or slip further toward Democratic dominance.
</P>
<P>
   That question has been shrouded by the gubernatorial race, where
the Republican incumbent, Acting Governor Paul Cellucci, appears to
be holding an election-eve lead, according to polls. But further
down the ballot, GOP prospects are not so sanguine, despite a
ticket as good as any the party has fielded in years.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Brad Bailey, the party's nominee for attorney
general, and Michael Duffy, its choice for auditor, are bright,
articulate, experienced candidates who have run impressive _ albeit
underfunded _ campaigns against opponents who have chosen to lie
low.
</P>
<P>
   In 6th District congressional candidate Peter Torkildsen, the
GOP boasts a candidate who has actually held the seat before. And
in the 3d District, state Senator Matthew J. Amorello of Grafton,
an experienced legislator, is making a run at US Representative
James P. McGovern, who as a first-termer is in an incumbent's most
vulnerable period.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in a state where late-focusing voters tend to have an
underlying Democratic reflex, polls show all but Cellucci are
running uphill.
</P>
<P>
   On the legislative front, some party activists hope for a gain
of three to five seats. ``We're optimistic,'' said Marc DeCourcy,
executive director of the state Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But over the weekend, other Republicans said it would be a
victory if their small band is not diminished even further. They
now hold 28 of the 160 House seats. On the Senate side, GOP leaders
hope to pick up one or two seats to add to their current seven in
the 40-member body, still far short of their numbers in 1991-92,
when they had 16 senators, two more than the 14 needed to uphold a
gubernatorial veto.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the GOP's biggest worry, that Democratic nominee
Scott Harshbarger will upset Cellucci. If so, Beacon Hill would be
run by the Democrats, and the Republican Party might well be
reduced to the political impotence it experienced in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   So why does a party whose leaders argue they have governed well
for almost a decade find itself in such a situation?
</P>
<P>
   In part, it's because a rising economic tide tends to buoy all
incumbents, and most incumbents are currently Democratic. In part,
it's because in low-attention years voters' reflex voting habits
kick in.
</P>
<P>
   Still, political specialists say there's real benefit from
strong two-party competition in government.
</P>
<P>
   ``A vigorous two-party system works better in a lot of ways,''
said Bob Woodbury, director of the McCormack Institute at the
University of Massachusetts at Boston. ``It tends to bring new
people into the political system, and it tends to lead to a better
debate on issues.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a point the Republicans think they proved in 1991, when,
at Governor William Weld's insistence, the state's fiscal problems
were solved by slashing spending rather than hiking taxes.
</P>
<P>
   On a swing through the state a few weeks ago, former Senate
Majority Leader Robert Dole, the Republican Party's 1996 candidate
for president, urged voters to think about sending a Republican or
two to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have a Republican Congress _ nobody argues
that _ for the next foreseeable future,'' Dole said. ``Obviously,
it is very helpful to have a conduit to Republican majorities in
the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as former congressman Mickey Edwards, now a public-policy
lecturer at the Kennedy School, puts it: ``When you elect only
Democrats and you have a Republican Congress, people in
Massachusetts are basically cut out of the decision-making. A state
that has people only in one party just loses half of its influence
automatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hess, a senior fellow in government studies at the
Brookings Institution, says that states can maximize their clout by
having a senator of each party, but he is unsure whether adding one
Republican will pay much of a dividend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is terribly useful for a state to have one Republican
senator and one Democratic senator,'' Hess said. ``But one freshman
House member? I think that is a little marginal. I don't know how
much they would be able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Massachusetts is widely considered a longtime
Democratic bastion, that's only true if one has a short-term
historical perspective.
</P>
<P>
   From the end of the Civil War until 1940, Massachusetts was
fertile ground for progressive Republicans, who regularly beat more
conservative Democrats. In that period, the GOP won 49 governor's
races, with the Democrats prevailing in only 15.
</P>
<P>
   The next quarter-century was a period of growing Democratic
strength. With Tip O'Neill leading, Democrats won control of the
state House of Representatives in the election of 1948. The state
Senate fell to the Democrats a decade later, in 1958, and the 1960s
saw precipitous dropoffs in GOP strength in both bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Republican Party remained highly competitive for
statewide offices. From 1940 through 1974, the GOP won nine
contests, while the Democrats took six of those elections.
</P>
<P>
   It was only with the elections of 1974 and 1978 that the
Democrats drove the GOP into near extinction, seizing control of
all the constitutional offices and the second US Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   That era also saw a transformation of party philosophy and base.
The Republicans, once a progressive party, became Reaganized. The
Democrats, once the party of ethnic city dwellers, increasingly
came to represent the lifestyle liberalism of suburban voters.
</P>
<P>
   Running for reelection in 1986, Governor Michael S. Dukakis
declared that Massachusetts didn't need any Republicans, and voters
seemed to agree. With the state GOP having taken a right turn, the
state had only one elected Republican of any consequence, US
Representative Silvio Conte of Pittsfield.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP really came back to life in the fiscal crisis of the
late 1980s. It was that upheaval, and the two large tax hikes it
took to staunch the red ink, that helped Weld and Cellucci squeak
into office as governor and lieutenant governor in the election of
1990.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans claim credit for fixing the fiscal mess, and
polls show that voters agree with them. Meanwhile, Weld and
Cellucci built an eclectic coalition by making inroads into groups
that had usually voted Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start with 15 percent (of registered voters) and you
have to get to 50 percent, you have to stretch a lot more than if
you start at 40 percent and you have to get to 50 percent,'' said
long-time political observer Ralph Whitehead, a journalism
professor at the University of Massachusetts. ``Frankly, Weld and
Cellucci have been fairly resourceful and flexible in getting to
50.''
</P>
<P>
   But Weld didn't put much effort into party-building. Feeling
that the Republican State Committee was a welter of feuds and
infighting, he preferred to keep it at arm's length. That meant
that even though Weld was successful, the party itself was not.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci may have other plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul Cellucci is going to put his stamp on the party,'' said
Senate Minority Leader Brian Lees of East Longmeadow. ``He is
committed to building the party. He believes in grassroots
politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
