<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAKHID WAIVED BECAUSE HE CHALLENGED SYSTEM, AGENT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ David Nakhid's agent said Monday his client is the
victim of a Major League Soccer policy of waiving players who
``challenge the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Nakhid and defenders Janusz Michallik and Dahir Mohammed were
waived by the Revolution Sunday. Nakhid, the only foreign player on
the Revolution without a guaranteed contract, was involved in a
fight with teammate Edwin Gorter during the Revolution's final
postseason practice last month. Gorter was accused of making a
racial remark and fined $20,000 and suspended for two games by MLS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed, because David is a pretty good player, and
other players can vouch for that,'' said Nakhid's agent, Cory
Clemetson. ``I'm not surprised about David being waived. Only in
the MLS are top players who challenge the system put out to pasture
earlier than their time. David is captain of the Trinidad and
Tobago national team and he was a starter in most of the games
until he spoke up against racism within the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you find it disturbing that after the recent violent
altercation in which Edwin Gorter made unprovoked, unwarranted, and
racially inflammatory insult to David, that the powers at MLS
summarily fined him $20,000, suspended him for two games, and
ordered him to take sensitivity training for his racist attitudes,
that he, too, was not waived off the team?
</P>
<P>
   ``David will be speaking with counsel and I'm sure he will have
something to say at the appropriate moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Nakhid were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the statistics this year, these are players
that weren't contributing to the team at a high level,'' said
Revolution general manager Brian O'Donovan. ``We have to make
certain moves because of the four-player limit of international
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``These moves were made based on the perception of the coaching
staff of how players will contribute to the team, their playing
ability, and how they contribute to the team situation under the
strictures of the MLS, including roster limits and international
player limits. Our hands are tied by those strictures of the MLS,
which cause us to make certain decisions. After those cuts, we are
still one player over the foreign player limit.''
</P>
<P>
   If players with guaranteed salaries are waived, their salaries
continue to count against the salary cap. The Revolution have five
foreign players _ Damian Alvarez, Raul Diaz Arce, Richard Goulooze,
player-coach Walter Zenga, and Gorter _ and must comply with the
MLS maximum of four.
</P>
<P>
   Nakhid has been selected to play for the Caribbean All-Stars in
a two-game tour of South Korea. He performed for Grasshoppers
Zurich, PAOK Salonika, and Waregem in Europe and Al Ansar in
Lebanon before joining the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution selected former D.C. United players Kris
Kelderman and Shawn Medved in the waiver draft Monday. Kelderman, a
playmaking midfielder, played 21 games for the Miami Fusion after
being chosen in the expansion draft last year. Medved, who scored
the tying goal in United's 3-2 overtime win over Los Angeles in the
1996 MLS Cup, played 19 games for the San Jose Clash last season
... Jamar Beasley, who played two games at striker for the
Revolution, will train with AC Milan starting this week. Brian
Dunseth, who started 17 games in central defense, will train with
Bayer Leverkusen in Germany ... Defender Ted Chronopoulos, whose 84
career appearances are a Revolution record, is awaiting a transfer
from his Greek team, Panionios. The MLS must pay a fee of $70,000
for Chronopoulos's rights. ``We are assured by the league that he
will be with us next year,'' O'Donovan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
