<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Tuesday, Nov. 3 and thereafter. The stories will carry the ``f''
financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For questions
about stories, contact Stewart Slavin at the Daily News, (818)
713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-SPENDING (Los Angeles) _ For the first time in 40
years, consumers in September spent more than they earned, pushing
the national savings rate to the lowest point on record. But in the
real world of grocery bills, mortgage payments and a looming
holiday season, the change was so slight few consumers seemed aware
that they'd played a part in history. By Ben Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   IDENTITY-THEFT (Los Angeles) _ Sandy Darby was the victim of
identity theft. Last week, a couple posing as employees for her
company passed phony corporate checks with the right account number
and a printed signature at two major retailers. Their total take?
$4,000. This infuriates Darby, who has to clean up her credit
record and restore her company's reputation. Identity theft is a
growing problem, as crooks use the latest technology to pull off
cons, according to consumer group CalPIRG. By Deborah Adamson.
</P>
<P>
   LLOYD-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ Let the hire beware. Daily News
columnist Ken Lloyd, Ph.D., a specialist in organizational
behavior, answers readers' questions on workplace ethics and
relationships.
</P>
