<SLUG> BC-BANKBOS-LAYOFFS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKBOSTON TO CUT 37 JOBS IN INVESTMENT UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Calif.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Citing a downturn in global capital markets, BankBoston
Corp. said Monday it would slash 37 positions in its recently
acquired investment bank, Robertson Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   While the layoffs represent a fraction of the investment bank's
925 employees, they reflect the degree to which global economic
uncertainty has brought initial public offerings, foreign bond
trading, and equity underwriting to a near standstill.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs, which affect junior and midlevel executives in
research, operations, investment banking, and stock brokering, are
primarily at Robertson Stephens' San Francisco headquarters,
according to industry sources.
</P>
<P>
   The cutbacks come on the heels of similar layoffs at other
financial institutions, and show that BankBoston ``has taken quick
action to lower costs in a business that has fallen on hard
times,'' said Gerard S. Cassidy, an industry analyst at Tucker
Anthony Inc., a Boston investment bank and brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   The cutbacks also come barely two weeks after BankBoston said it
would close many of its Asian branches and cut 111 jobs worldwide
in response to a global economic downturn. In July, the bank, New
England's second largest, said it would lay off 114 staffers,
mostly in domestic retail branches, and said more would follow.
</P>
<P>
   A BankBoston statement issued Monday said Robertson Stephens
retained its core research, investment banking, and brokerage
capabilities but gave no further details.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, a major player in Latin America, joins a growing
list of banks and brokerages are scaling back operations after a
miserable third quarter. The bank lost $45 million last quarter,
primarily by trading emerging market debt that fell through the
floor after Russia defaulted.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston eventually hopes to derive up to 30 percent of its
income from capital markets work, up from 7 percent before it
acquired Robertson Stephens in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9935 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELN-MASS-ROUNDUP-BOS &LR;      11-02 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-MASS-ROUNDUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR RIVALS PUT IN FULL LAST DAY ON CAMPAIGN TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (p and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN AND ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROCKTON, Mass. _ From Worcester to Springfield and from
Brockton to Boston, Scott Harshbarger and Paul Cellucci barnstormed
the Commonwealth Monday in their final day of campaigning for the
governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, registered voters can cast their ballots for local,
congressional, and statewide offices. Polling places are open from
7 a.m. to 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates for governor hauled out the big guns from their
respective parties, hoping for voter approval by association.
Senator Edward M. Kennedy and US Representative Barney Frank
accompanied Harshbarger to North Dartmouth, while New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani and former Governor William F. Weld visited the
North End for a rally with Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, Weld, Giuliani, and Andrew Card _ Cellucci's former
colleague in the Massachusetts Senate _ were at the center of a
spirited parade down Hanover Street. Led by a brass band cranking
out John Philip Sousa marches, Cellucci was greeted as a favorite
son by many in the heavily Italian-American neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Chants of ``we want Paul'' and ``four more years'' rang out, and
employees and a few patrons of the street's legendary cafes
scrambled to doorways to wave at the passing parade. One man even
rushed to the front of the parade to plant a big kiss on Cellucci's
cheek.
</P>
<P>
   A giddy Cellucci clapped to the music and played the cymbals for
a couple of blocks. He did not hesitate to predict victory Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling pretty good,'' Cellucci said. ``I think people are
focusing on their pocketbooks. I think that's good news for me and
for Jane Swift, but we're not going to rest until 8 o'clock
tomorrow night.''
</P>
<P>
   About two-dozen supporters greeted Harshbarger, the Democratic
nominee, on the front steps of the Brockton Public Library for a
tour of Main Street with Mayor Jack Yunits. Their chants of ``Scott
'98'' quickly petered out as their candidate alighted from his
black sedan.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be a little more enthusiastic than that,'' urged
Troy Garron, the Democrat running for Plymouth County sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   As the leaves blew to the sidewalk and a few passing drivers
honked in support, Harshbarger had his photograph snapped on the
steps of the library, pointing out that Cellucci had vetoed $3
million to renovate the old building, which has steep steps and no
access for the physically disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger charged that Cellucci had vetoed many important
community projects around the state, including $300,000 for public
housing repairs in Lynn and $11 million for an Advanced Technology
Center at the University of Massachusetts-Dartmouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the best economy of our lifetime, and this is an
example of leadership focusing on the politics of it. It's not
what's right to do,'' Harshbarger said. Cellucci has been ``playing
politics'' in order to get elected, the Democratic candidate
complained.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger's reception was more enthusiastic at the
construction site for the new Superior Courthouse. Laborers called
Harshbarger over to shake his hand and waved his green-and-white
banners with fervor from each deck of the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to pull a Doug Flutie. We're going to win one for
the little guy,'' Harshbarger said. ``We've always been
underestimated.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the street in Sol's Cafe, Robert Haynes, the president of
the Massachusetts AFL-CIO, predicted a Harshbarger victory today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're organized. We're ready to get the party out,'' Haynes
said. ``We've identified a couple hundred thousand votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Harshbarger left Brockton, he said he wants voters to
know that the state can do better, particularly when it comes to
expanding health care, providing child care, and helping senior
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has a trail of broken promises and no
leadership,'' he said. ``Over the next 24 hours we're going to keep
going around and reminding people.''
</P>
<P>
   In the North End, Weld and Giuliani echoed Cellucci's campaign
slogan that Massachusetts voters should not go backward. Weld said
voters support Cellucci because he will be a strong force on
economic issues. ``I truly know that he's going to hold the line on
taxes and the economy and he's going to be a great governor,'' Weld
said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, the Republican--Libertarian New York City mayor who
endorsed Democrat Mario Cuomo in the last governor's race in his
own state, credited Weld and Cellucci with turning around
Massachusetts and reminded Cellucci supporters to show up at the
polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polls can be very deceiving,'' Giuliani said. ``Elections
happen on election day. He and Bill Weld have turned this state
around, and it's now an example to the rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he looks forward to governing as an elected chief
executive, rather than an accidental governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to continue to work hard for the people of this
state,'' Cellucci said. ``I think winning an election probably
gives you a little bit more of a mandate. I think it will give me
more of a mandate to keep moving forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
