<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9940 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FDA-RENAGEL-BOS &LR;      11-02 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FDA-RENAGEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA OKS ORAL DRUG TO TREAT KIDNEY WOES IN ELDERLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a dismal year for biopharmaceuticals, GelTex Pharmaceuticals
Inc. said Monday it received some good news: The US Food and Drug
Administration approved Renagel, an oral drug to help the esimated
220,000 Americans receiving kidney dialysis treatment.
</P>
<P>
   GelTex, a Waltham, Mass. company, said Renagel will be jointly
marketed with Genzyme Corp. of Cambridge, Mass. and manufactured by
a division of Dow Chemical Corp. of Midland, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   The drug is one of only a few from New England biopharmaceutical
companies to gain FDA approval this year. Some other promising
therapeutics either failed to gain government regulatory approval
or proved lackluster in pivotal human clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Last month The Medicines Co. of Cambridge failed to gain an FDA
advisory panel approval for Hirulog, a blood thinner, and earlier
this summer Ergo Science Corp. of Charlestown, Mass. was
unsuccessful in gaining regulatory permission to market its
diabetes drug, ErgoSet, after signing a joint-marketing agreement
with Johnson &AMP; Johnson. And Interneuron Pharmaceuticals Inc. of
Lexington, Mass. postponed further development of CerAxon, a stroke
medication, after disappointing phase 3 clinical trial results.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, several Wall Street biotech analysts said they expect
Renagel to generate about $30 million in revenues next year,
climbing to between $100 million and $200 million in annual sales
in three to four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a nice niche product, one where there is a great need
to control the dietary phosphorus in late-stage kidney dialysis
patients with few side effects,'' said Meg Malloy, a biotechnology
analyst at Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike healthy patients whose kidneys remove waste products from
blood through urine, patients with late-stage kidney disease,
predominantly older people, retain phosphorus, which, if untreated,
can lead to bone disease and soft-tissue calcifications. Renagel
was granted FDA approval because it neutralizes and removes harmful
dietary phosphorus in the gastrointestinal tract and helps lower
cholesterol levels, according to Mark Skaletsky, GelTex chief
executive, who said the drug is not absorbed into the blood stream.
</P>
<P>
   Two to three Renagel capsules are taken each day with every
meal. The drug will cost $1,100 to $1,400 annually per patient,
Skaletsky said, with Medicaid covering about half of patients
requiring it. He said the company hopes private medical insurance
will reimburse the remaining Renagel users.
</P>
<P>
   Renagel is GelTex's first drug and took almost four years and
$50 million to develop, said Skaletsky. The first shipments should
reach patients next month.
</P>
<P>
   GelTex shares closed Mondayat 23 7/8, down 1 1/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 2020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
