<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9973 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELN-ROUNDUP-BOS &LR;      11-02 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-ROUNDUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CLOSE RACES APPEAR CLOSER, CLINTON COURTS BLACK VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (p and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the latest polls suggesting that many key races are tighter
than expected, the last day of campaigning for Tuesday's election
was marked by a fusillade of ads and suggestions by President
Clinton that Republicans are trying to suppress black voter
turnout. GOP officials denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   A final round of polling showed that Democrats had moved ahead
in the ``generic'' congressional poll, in which voters indicate
which party's candidates, in general, they are more favorably
inclined toward.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum shifts rumbled through many campaigns. Senator
Carol Moseley-Braun of Illinois, long considered one of the most
endangered Democrats, moved ahead of Peter Fitzgerald, the
Republican, by 45 percent to 42 percent, still within the 4-point
margin of error. In California, meanwhile, Matt Fong, the
Republican, pulled within striking distance of Democratic Senator
Barbara Boxer, who led 45 to 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts cautioned that races for the House and Senate are
decided on so many unique local issues that the surveys might be
misleading. Most predicted slight Republican gains in the Senate
and governorships, with varying views about which party might pick
up a small number of House seats. A heavy turnout could alter the
outcome of the three dozen or so closest contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans clearly have history and money on their side,''
the Democratic National Committee cochairman, Steve Grossman, said
in an interview. ``But the momentum we seem to have in the last few
days certainly is evidenced by the polling.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, whose impeachment fate could be determined by
the makeup of the new Congress, spent his second straight day
courting black voters, suggesting that a few thousand votes in each
of 35 races could determine the victor. The president, citing
reports that police planned a heavy presence at some polling places
with many black voters, asked Republicans to ``renounce'' such
activities.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said Clinton's charges were false and that the
president was making a last-minute ploy to boost black voter
turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States Tuesday falsely and
improperly suggested that the Republican Party is responsible for
voter intimidation in an effort to keep black Americans from
voting,'' said the Republican Party chairman, Jim Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson then asked Clinton to call upon the Missouri
Democratic Party to withdraw radio commercials ``suggesting that a
vote for Republicans would lead to church bombings and burnings.''
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute charges and countercharges about voter
intimidation resulted from a handful of incidents. Democrats, for
example, noted that Republicans in North Carolina have made plans
to videotape voters as they go to the polls, while Republicans
cited the Missouri Democrats' ad that said: ``When you don't vote,
you let another church explode.''
</P>
<P>
   While there was no evidence of widespread intimidation, the
pre-election rhetoric among party leaders underscored that many
races have tightened in the final days and could turn on a few
thousand votes.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing days of the campaign, Republicans spent $10
million on an ad campaign that highlighted the Clinton sex scandal.
Democrats, nearly broke as a party, responded by releasing an ad
that questioned whether Republicans care about ordinary people.
Democrats said they gained momentum from a backlash against the GOP
ads, which ran in 68 key districts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged a high turnout, especially among black voters, and
suggesting that Republicans would act irresponsibly if given more
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody stays home and we have people in here who would
be irresponsible, then things could get worse in a hurry,'' Clinton
said. ``That's a big risk that that's not worth taking.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to the election, according to leaders of both parties,
is turnout. Curtis Gans, director for the Committee for the Study
of the American Electorate, said in an interview that he expected
turnout to be between 36 to 38 percent, ``but I am less sure of
that than at any time in my lifetime because of the subtext of the
impeachment issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gans said turnout might be slightly higher among the
``upper-income, better-educated, and older people. The first two
are lightly in the Republican direction, and the last is in the
Democratic direction.'' The impact of older voters could spell the
difference in many races, which explains why Democrats have spent a
lot of advertising dollars on promoting the idea that the party
will be more effective in protecting Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   As for black turnout, Gans foresees only a ``slight uptick.''
Republicans normally would be expected to pick up about 35 House
seats in a mid-term election when Democrats control the White
House. But with the GOP having picked up 52 seats in the 1994
election and already controlling the House 228 to 206, Republican
leaders predicted the party would do well to pick up 10 seats
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who for months have been playing down expectations in
the wake of Clinton's sex scandal, expressed confidence that they
are pulling ahead in key races and predicted strong showings in
Republican-leaning areas of the South and border states.
</P>
<P>
   In good news for Democrats, the Gallup Poll found that likely
voters prefer Democrats over Republicans by 49 percent to 45
percent in a generic congressional ballot. But the House races are
decided on many local issues, making it difficult to predict
whether Democrats will be ahead by such a margin in the actual
election.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, of 435 House races, 402 feature incumbents, nearly all
of whom are likely to be reelected. Most political analysts said
there are about three dozen highly competitive House contests and
perhaps six tight Senate contests out of 34 up for election.
</P>
<P>
   But among those tight races, many became even tighter in the
closing days of the campaign, making the election results tough to
call. A major swing even in the small number of competitive races
could determine which party controls Congress and affect the
outcome of a possible House impeachment vote and Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Boxer and Moseley-Braun races, the closest
Senate contests include those between Republican Senator Alfonse M.
D'Amato and Democratic Representative Charles E. Schumer of New
York, and between Republican Representative Jim Bunning and
Democratic Representative Scotty Baesler of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expected Republicans to pick up one to three seats in
the Senate, which is controlled 55-45 by the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were expected to pick several more governorships,
adding to their total of 32. Another 17 governors are Democratic
and one is an Independent. The most closely watched governor's race
is in California, where Lieutenant Governor Gray Davis is leading
Attorney General Dan Lungren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
