</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICARAGUA-MITCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH TOLL IN CENTRAL AMERICA FROM MITCH COULD HIT 7,000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA PAZ CENTRO, Nicaragua _ After nearly a week of torrential
winds and rains from Hurricane Mitch, government and rescue
officials across Central America Monday began taking toll of the
storm's chaos and destruction, estimating that as many as 7,000
people have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   From the hardest hit areas of Honduras and Nicaragua, where the
sun finally shone Monday, further northward to El Salvador,
Guatemala and Mexico, which were shrouded in rain for most of the
day, it became clear that the floods and mudslides triggered by the
storm inflicted some of the worst damage ever produced by a natural
disaster in this region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've ever seen this kind of damage before,''
said Nicaraguan Defense Minister Pedro Joaquin Chamorro Barrios
said after visiting some of the most severely affected areas north
and west of the capital city of Managua. ``These places look like
the lunar landscape with large craters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe it unless you see it with your own eyes,
there are bodies everywhere'' Chamorro added. ``The images are
really horrifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicaraguan officials believe up to 1,500 residents were buried
alive late last week when a slope of the Casitas Volcano collapsed,
spilling a rapidly moving wall of mud on nearby villages. Another
700 people are believed to have died in floods in other parts of
the country, Chamorro said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch proved to be equally devastating for other countries, too.
</P>
<P>
   Honduran President Carlos Flores Facusse, who suspended civil
rights and called out the military to prevent looting, said the
death toll in that country was ``in the thousands, not hundreds,''
because of Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   Honduran officials said the exact number of dead would never be
known. Several parts of the country remained cut off from
communication. The storm dropped up to 25 inches of rain in a
six-hour period last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Floodwaters in Tegucigalpa, the Honduran capital of 800,000
residents, appear to have receded. But all four bridges across the
Rio Choluteca were still out of service. The city's popular
49-year-old mayor, Cesar Castellanos, was killed in a helicopter
crash on Sunday while surveying the storm's damage.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven people died and seven US citizens, all apparently part of
a missionary organization, were injured when their small plane
crashed into a Guatemalan hillside on Sunday in heavy fog and rain.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring El Salvador, the National Emergency Committee
officially listed 74 dead and 106 missing. Another 27,000 were
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Guatemala, where the storm was centered Monday, reported nearly
three dozen deaths related to Mitch. And Mexico noted one death,
but officials there cautioned that number could rise as the rains
move into its rural and poorer southern states.
</P>
<P>
   The International Red Cross tripled its appeal for aid to those
affected to $7.4 million. And President Clinton pledged $2 million
in US assistance in food and medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago Tuesday, Mitch was elevated to a rare Category 5
hurricane on the Saffir-Simpson scale, with winds clocked at about
180 m.p.h., making it the fourth most powerful recorded hurricane
in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of pushing northeastward toward the Mexican Yucatan
Peninsula, as most forecasters predicted, the storm lodged near the
Honduran coast, leveling port communities and small islands popular
with tourists.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, the storm's center, although weaker, began moving
southwest, moving inland over the rest of Honduras and into
Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:20 that morning, according to government officials, who
Monday recounted stories told by survivors of the Casitas Volcano
mudslides, a large blast shook the earth. Just two minutes after
residents received official warnings, an avalanche of mud and
debris swept over entire villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw the hurricane going away from Nicaragua,'' Chamorro
said. ``We didn't expect that it would come back and stay so
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Persistent rains and extensive damage to bridges and roads
around the volcano made it impossible for rescue workers to reach
most of the injured. Many reportedly died from their wounds while
waiting for help to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, Chamorro added, about 70-80 bodies could be
spotted on the ground, often with only limbs or faces sticking up
from the mud. Another 450 bodies had been recovered. In the
afternoon, the government began mass cremations to reduce the risk
of disease from decomposing bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Arturo Harding, executive director of Nicaragua's National
Emergency Committee, said plans were being made to create a large
``national cemetery,'' at the site where the mudslide hit the
hardest.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,600 people are still missing, he added, and the further
would probably rise as rescue workers and the military reached
areas that are still cut off from communication and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout much of the coffee-growing countryside outside
Managua, meanwhile, schools, churches and government buildings were
turned into makeshift shelters for those who were evacuated from
flooded areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no home, no animals and no food,'' said Jose Rios, 66,
who was evacuated from the nearby village of La Paz Vieja and took
refuge in a classroom with 43 other men. ``All I have is these
clothes and the pain of the memory of what this storm has done.''
</P>
<P>
   A damp soccer field in the town of La Paz Centro, about 50 miles
west of the capital, was used as a staging area for three
helicopters which transported doctors, civil engineers and food and
medicine to isolated areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our priority right now is to help the living,'' said one
government official at the landing site. ``And to restablish ground
access to these communities because using helicopters for
everything is too expensive for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the harrowing tales of destruction that seemed to hover
over most Central American countries Monday, on a religious holiday
known as Day of the Dead, there were also stories of survival.
</P>
<P>
   There was the man, rescue workers said, who slid nearly five
miles along the current of the mudslide near the volcano but
managed to keep his head up and his body balanced and come away
with only minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-year-old girl who was nearly paralyzed managed to stay alive
for days because a neighbor gave her drinks of water from his
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Many survivors in the rural areas were taken to a hospital in
Chinendaga, where supplies were reportedly running desperately low.
Government officials said many children were left orphaned by the
storm.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of families in the hardest-hit areas, like the village of
Rolando Rodriguez, had gone days without eating. Doctors noted that
many residents were suffering from weather-related illnesses,
especially ear infections.
</P>
<P>
   At times Monday, the massive scale of the cleanup and rescue
project needed for Nicaragua, the hemisphere's second-poorest
country after Haiti, seemed to overwhelm workers. Not since a
devastating earthquake hit Managua in 1972, killing 5,000 people,
has the country seen such widespread death and devastation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference this time is that the hurricane has destroyed
much of this country's infrastructure,'' whereas the earthquake was
centered in one area, Chamorro said. ``It's like the rains have cut
our country into several small pieces.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
