</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LABOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's no show tonight
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No Game Tonight.
</P>
<P>
   They don't need that sign at the Georgia Dome today. The NBA let
fans know it was coming when the players were locked out July 1 and
made it official weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Pistons at Hawks is canceled, as well as the rest of the 13-game
November schedule and perhaps all of December.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, on the eve of what would have been, union executive
director Billy Hunter used a telephone conference call to dampen
any enthusiasm for a quick settlement. ``I don't see any
possibility for us to reach an agreement this week and I don't know
when we will,'' he said. Asked to predict a possible start date for
the season, he said, ``My gut tells me January.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said Wednesday's meeting of lawyers on technical issues
made so little progress that a full negotiating session scheduled
for Wednesday has been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are much further apart on the economic issues,'' Hunter
said, citing ``fundamental differences on positions in regard to
policy on how a system would work'' and ``a general lack of
understanding and communication in regard to a framework of how
this thing would be structured.''
</P>
<P>
   That contradicted remarks last week by NBA commissioner David
Stern, who reported a ``skeleton'' around which to build.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said he thought the issue of dollars would be easier to
resolve, but said, ``They have one concept we have another.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Hunter mentioned the issue of cost certainties.
``We have one view. They have another,'' he said. ``The NBA elected
today to actually take a step back and there is a question on
whether we will agree in the future. Hard cap isn't an issue. They
know we would never accept one. The question is the structure of
what can actually work.''
</P>
<P>
   One apparent barrier is the apparent collapse of any luxury tax
proposal. ``The entire framework of tax, credit, how you set it up.
We didn't agree on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter also said the players want to move away from the
traditional concept of BRI (basketball related income) as a source
for the division of revenues, to ``reduce our need to do these
exhaustive audits and we would have a fixed pool of revenues from
which our percentage would be derived. We're still working on it.
We won't have to worry about people under-reporting income.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a genuine concern. The most serious issue involved the
Chicago Bulls, who several years ago did not declare income from
200 luxury suites. This was uncovered only when the team and the
NBA battled over the team's desire to show a significant number of
games over Chicago's super station, WGN. As a result the NBA had to
increase the salary cap number for each team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   There is some agreement on such issues as retaining guaranteed
salaries, a form of the Larry Bird rule and the growth of the
middle class. There is sentiment toward extending rights over
rookies for longer than three years and of a tougher drug policy.
But the players have rejected a 50-50 split, although Hunter said
they have come down from 63 percent to 60.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said he has always taken the stance that ``when the
owners want to reach an agreement we will reach one.'' He said he
does not believe that time has come.
</P>
<P>
   He indicated that might happen when the TV networks, sponsors
and some owners may call a halt to this. ``When it comes to a
boiling point,'' he said. ``When people decide that the asset _ the
game of basketball _ is about to take a significant hit, something
will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
