<HEADER>
A9976 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES-COX     11-02 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson's rushing has Reeves gushing
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons coach Dan Reeves was effusive in his
praise Monday when talking about Sunday's 37-15 win over the Rams,
which left the Falcons 6-2 for the first time in the 33-year
history of the franchise. Reeves made it clear he thinks running
back Jamal Anderson is playing at a Pro Bowl level.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-year player from Utah, the 24th running back selected
in the 1994 draft, rushed 22 times for a career-high 172 yards and
two touchdowns, and caught two passes for 31 yards, including a
9-yard TD.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta even split Anderson out wide a few times for the second
week in a row to make it tougher for the Rams to disguise blitzes.
It was as a wideout that he made a one-handed 22-yard catch that
was critical on the team's lone second-half TD drive.
</P>
<P>
   He has rushed for 862 yards this season, putting him on pace for
1,624 yards (the team record is 1,719 by Gerald Riggs in 1985).
Anderson has rushed for six TDs, and caught 16 passes for 215 yards
and a TD.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy that was the catylast was Jamal,'' Reeves said. ``He
was awesome. I've never seen him run any better. He's been more
aggressive than he was; he broke an awful lot of tackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's dangerous as a receiver outside because he's got very
good quickness. He has great hands. He is a complete football
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Bouquets for the O-line
</P>
<P>
   Reeves also was ecstatic over the play of the offensive line,
which allowed just one sack after entering the game surrendering
one every 7.7 passing plays, the worst ratio in the NFL
</P>
<P>
   In particular, left tackle Bob Whitfield had perhaps his best
game as the Falcons totaled a season-high 434 yards against a St.
Louis defense that had allowed an average of just 251.5 yards a
game in the previous four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are likely to continue playing undrafted rookie Jose
Portilla part-time at right tackle in rotation with rookie Ephraim
Salaam, and second-round draft choice Bob Hallen will continue
spelling second-year left guard Calvin Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``After an off week against the Jets, they really played well in
both run and pass,'' Reeves said, referring to a week earlier, when
the Falcons allowed five sacks and managed just 55 yards rushing in
a 28-3 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The two new guys did have breakdowns, however. Portilla gave up
the lone St. Louis sack, when Rams DE Kevin Carter ran past him.
Hallen, while spelling slightly injured RG Gene Williams, let Rams
DT Ray Agnew blow past him and strip QB Chris Chandler of the
football on the St. Louis 6-yard line. Center Robbie Tobeck
recovered, and the Falcons had to settle for a field goal. And in
the fourth quarter, Rams DT D'Marco Farr beat Hallen up the middle
to block Morten Andersen's 29-yard field goal attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Big year for Bennett
</P>
<P>
   On defense, weakside LB Cornelius Bennett is having a year
comparable to what Anderson is doing on offense.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he had eight tackles and batted down a pass while
playing every snap. Because Bennett is on the field during nickel
and dime defenses, he rarely comes off the field. He leads Atlanta
with 67 tackles, ahead of MLB Jessie Tuggle (53 tackles).
</P>
<P>
   Right DE Chuck Smith continues to play especially well against
the run, totaling six tackles Sunday. He added a sack, and is tied
for the team lead with DE/DT Lester Archambeau with 4.5.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie LB Keith Brooking, the team's first-round draft choice,
has had a hard time getting on the field because of Bennett's
outstanding play, but he was in on 46 snaps against the Rams
because Atlanta spent so much time in nickel and dime defenses.
Brooking responded with a season-high seven tackles and broke up
two passes. He did not have a sack, though, as postgame statistics
orginally indicated. He has 15 tackles for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   WR/PR Todd Kinchen, who suffered a concussion on a third-quarter
punt return, was observed Sunday night at Piedmont Hospital for a
couple hours, and underwent a battery of neuro-physchological tests
Monday that gauge memory recall and fine-motor skills. The results
of those tests will be compared with results from preseason tests
and his status for Sunday's game against the New England Patriots
(5-3) will be determined later in the week. If he can't play, CB
Ray Buchanan and/or WR Terance Mathis would return punts. . . . DT
Travis Hall, whose nagging knee injury was originally diagnosed as
a bruised tendon two weeks ago, wasn't recovering as anticipated,
so Friday night team physician Andrew Bishop suggested he undergo a
bone scan. It showed a ``hot'' reading, indicating something was
wrong. Hall had arthroscopic surgery Saturday morning, and a piece
of debris that was catching the back of his kneecap was discovered
and removed. He missed the Rams game and isn't likely to play
against the Patriots. . . . Tuggle hyperextended a knee, but wasn't
limping Monday, and his status for Sunday's game looks good.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling in the red zone
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have scored on 21 of 23 ``red zone'' possessions
this season _ possessions that include at least one first down
inside the 20-yard line. Atlanta has 12 TDs and nine field goals;
the two unsuccessful trips into the red zone ended with a blocked
field goal and QB Steve DeBerg kneeling down in the waning minutes
of a win over the Saints. In the last two seasons, QB Chris
Chandler has thrown 17 TD passes in the red zone and no
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said he has never seen a fullback block better than Bob
Christian did Sunday. . . . From the middle of last season to now,
only two teams, Green Bay and Denver (13-3), have a better record
that the Falcons' mark of 12-4, same as San Francisco and
Jacksonville. . . . Atlanta's six wins have come against teams with
a combined record of 12-35 prior to Monday night's game between
Philadelphia and Dallas. Reeves is irritated that that keeps
getting mentioned in the media. ``People see (what's sometimes
written) and take it as gospel,'' he said. ``That can influence
(potential ticket buyers).'' . . . In their first six games, the
Falcons gave up 12 plays of 30 or more yards, and six of 56 or more
yards. But in the last two games, they haven't given up a play
longer than 26 yards. The Rams' longest play Sunday was a 22-yard
pass to Az-Zahir Hakim, and in the 28-3 loss a week earlier, the
longest play was a 26-yard pass to TE Kyle Brady. . . . The 212
points scored by the Falcons is a team record for the first half of
a season, topping the 208 scored in 1990. Atlanta is fifth in the
NFL with a scoring average of 26.5 points. . . . The Falcons'
six-game home winning streak is their longest ever in the Georgia
Dome. The franchise record for longest home winning streak is seven
games, in 1978 and '80-81. . . . Atlanta is No. 7 in the NFL in
defense on third downs, allowing a conversion rate of 34.3 percent.
. . . Falcons coaches are pleased with the progress of second-year
TE O.J. Santiago, who after going without a catch in the opener,
has 13 receptions for 188 yards and a TD. The 6-foot-7, 267-pounder
also is developing qas a blocker.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
