<HEADER>
A9977 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS03-COX     11-02 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Half-empty Dome shows Falcons still have doubters
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons are off to the best start in
franchise history, but their reward Sunday was a half-empty Georgia
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   There were 37,996 tickets distributed for the game against St.
Louis. With almost 7,000 no-shows, about 31,000 watched a 37-15
victory that left Atlanta 6-2 for the first time. The Dome, which
has a capacity of 71,228, was less than half full.
</P>
<P>
   In one regard, the low turnout was not surprising. The Rams game
has been the toughest sell of all Falcons home games three years in
a row and four times in the 1990s. Three of the five smallest
crowds in the Dome's eight-year history have come against the Rams.
The 26,519 that showed up for the final home game in 1996 remains
the all-time low.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a few Falcons weren't in the mood for excuses, especially
since the previous game, Oct. 18 against New Orleans, was played
before the biggest crowd _ 61,638 tickets distributed _ in nearly
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point the excitement of a team tied for first place
(with the 49ers in the NFC West) in November ... should be enough
(to draw a bigger crowd),'' running back Jamal Anderson said. ``But
a few of us have been here a few years, and ... we know what's
happened in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, history haunts a team that has just seven winning
seasons in 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people out there in disbelief the Falcons are
6-2,'' reserve running back Harold Green said. ``It's imperative
for us to stay focused. If we do that, we can turn some of the
doubters into believers.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the opponent has something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons already have distributed more tickets for all four
remaining home games than they did for the Rams game. And the next
home game, Nov. 15 against San Francisco (6-2), could be the first
sellout since Oct. 29, 1995, a 28-13 loss to Dallas. Already, some
62,500 tickets have been sold for the 49ers game.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's average of 49,832 tickets distributed is way behind
the NFL attendance average of 63,676, but it is ahead of Tennessee
(37,280) and Oakland (44,920).
</P>
<P>
   ``To have 20-some thousand less than we had at the last home
game is disappointing,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``I think (the
Falcons) would be a fun team to watch, but I can't make people see
the same things I do.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
