<SLUG> BC-TRIPLE-EXTRADITE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suspect should have been jailed at time of slayings
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook and Jay Croft
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The man suspected in five Atlanta-area slayings in
October _ including the triple killings at a Hilton hotel in
downtown Atlanta _ should have been in prison at the time instead
of on the streets, according to state and county records.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Fulton County Superior Court Judge William Daniel
sentenced Timothy Dawson to 10 years probation for aggravated
sodomy and aggravated assault on his girlfriend. Georgia law
requires a minimum of a decade in prison with no chance of parole.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson, also known as Harry Lee Johnson, is suspected of killing
three men in the Atlanta Hilton &AMP; Towers, one in the Days Inn in
College Park, Ga. and another in a DeKalb Co. home invasion. He was
arrested Saturday near Memphis, Tenn., on a traffic offense,
charged with murder and returned to Atlanta in custody Monday. The
Georgia Department of Corrections, which supervises felons
sentenced to probation, several times had asked the Fulton County
court to revoke Dawson's probation because he was not reporting to
his probation officer, paying his probation fees or notifying the
state each time he moved.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Fulton County indictment, Dawson forced his
former girlfriend to perform oral sex on him and then he beat her.
In exchange for a guilty plea to aggravated assault and aggravated
sodomy other charges were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something that we worked out with the district
attorney's office and the judge went along with it,'' said Thomas
West, Dawson's defense attorney in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the recent shooting victims were stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he'd have been in prison, Gerrold would be alive,'' said
Maple Bronner, girlfriend of Gerrold Shropshire, one of the men
slain at the Atlanta Hilton. ``The justice system just leaves a lot
to be desired.'' Dawson was also on probation at the time he was
charged with attacking his former girlfriend. He had been sentenced
to five years in prison to be followed by five years probation for
a 1989 Baldwin County theft by receiving conviction.
</P>
<P>
   While free on $20,000 bond on the assault charges, Dawson was
again arrested on a felony charge, for stalking his girlfriend to
keep her from testifying against him. He was shot in the stomach
when police came to arrest him because, the officer said, he
thought Dawson may have had a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Daniel said he did not remember the case, but the
prosecutor, Charles Smegal, said the deal was struck, despite the
dictates of the law, because ``the victim didn't want to
prosecute.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Cook and Jay Croft write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
