r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     11-02 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAT ROOM JERRY-RIGGED FOR LOVEBIRDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've ever hung out in an Internet chat room, you're
probably familiar with this kind of ``conversation,'' quoted
verbatim from a Phoenix-themed room:
</P>
<P>
   SGu6247690: MUSTANG SURE HE FINE HUH
</P>
<P>
   DaNcInAmB2: OH I DON'T CARE
</P>
<P>
   MustangPMP: hell yeah
</P>
<P>
   RTallant: I want to get lucky with a gorgeous woman
</P>
<P>
   DMBalicia: i dont know, some chick on cross country
</P>
<P>
   BlndAzQt: MUSTANG is pretty hot but not my type
</P>
<P>
   MustangPMP: shut up heather -)
</P>
<P>
   Not quite Jefferson's letters to Madison. But stimulating for
those who consider ``Us'' magazine too intellectually challenging,
I suppose.
</P>
<P>
   For everyone else, though, why bother?
</P>
<P>
   But before you write off all chat rooms as places for the
immature and shallow, you should know about Sharon and Jerry
France.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon was an office manager for an animal clinic in Dyer, Ind.,
three years ago when she bought a computer. She didn't know the
first thing about it, so she tried a little bit of this and that. &QL; 
Beginners' luck &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to learn everything right away,'' she said. So she
experimented with all her computer had to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, she eventually gave chat rooms a try, and her first
few forays yielded results like the chatter above. But she stuck
with it, looked around a little more and eventually found a chat
room frequented by people with similar interests.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all she found.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the first times I was ever there,'' she said, ``I met
my future husband.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Jerry, who co-owns an insurance agency in Lake
Havasu City. His side of the story is even better: He met Sharon
the ``first time'' he entered a chat room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody told me about it,'' he said. ``They said give it a
try, so I did. It was just luck.''
</P>
<P>
   No. Three bars on a slot machine are luck. This was something
different, something better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I have the feeling that it was ordained,'' Jerry
allowed. ``It was sort of like destiny, I guess. Or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Something indeed. It wasn't long before the electronic lovebirds
were swapping e-mail and phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was calling me every single day,'' Sharon said. ``He was
supporting Ma Bell for a while there.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after almost a year of e-mails and long-distance
conversations, Jerry flew to Indiana to meet Sharon in person. If
you are at all familiar with nightmarish chat-room lore, you know
that it was quite a relief to Jerry to find that Sharon wasn't
really a 14-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he wasn't worried about that sort of prank. They had
exchanged photos. And he wasn't worried whether she would live up
to all he had come to expect of her from the e-mails and talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worried whether I would live up to her expectations,'' he
said. &QL; 
They're a hit! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He did, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit it off in person as well as we did on the computer and
telephone,'' Sharon said. ``It was sort of like getting to know
someone from the inside out.''
</P>
<P>
   They hit it off so well, in fact, that Sharon moved to Lake
Havasu last year, and in January, they got married.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, well, you're thinking, cute story _ a couple of crazy kids
who probably didn't know any better.
</P>
<P>
   Except that they're both 53.
</P>
<P>
   Young at heart, though.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon still visits the fateful chat room, but Jerry doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I want to chat with her, she's right here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean the cyberspace aspect of their relationship
has crashed. Both of them have computers in their house and use
them frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sends me e-mails all the time,'' Sharon said. ``We sit 3
feet away, and still e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? It's worked from the start. No reason to log off now. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
