A9989 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRTRAN-MISHAP03-COX     11-02 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-MISHAP03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Close call: Plane missed long drop-off
 &HT;    By Gary Hendricks and Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The AirTran plane that ran off a runway at Hartsfield
International Airport Sunday came close to an estimated 60-foot
embankment before it ploughed into an earthen berm, a federal
safety official said Monday. The accident resulted in at least 10
of the plane's 100 passengers sustaining sprains, cuts, bruises and
minor injuries, but the embankment posed a greater threat, said
John Goglia, a member of the National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   Goglia described the drop-off as severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outcome would have been different if (the plane) had
missed the berm,'' Goglia said at a midday news conference at
Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   The dirt berm was created by nearby taxiway construction,
airport spokesman Robert Kennedy said. But if it hadn't been there,
the plane's front landing gear could just as easily have mired in
the ground before reaching the embankment, Kennedy added.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB sent 30 investigators to Hartsfield and divided them
into seven teams to look into the incident. The investigation will
focus on the plane's hydraulic system to determine if its failure
is the reason the pilot couldn't steer the plane after he made an
emergency landing shortly after takeoff for Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB responded with a large number of investigators because
``loss of hydraulics is a very serious problem,'' Goglia said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Boeing 737-200 instruments flashed a problem with the
hydraulics, the plane returned to Hartsfield at 5:30 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It could take days to dislodge the plane from the berm with
either cranes or air bags, Goglia said. The aircraft is out of the
way and not interfering with airport operations on one of the
southern runways east of Concourse E, an airport spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old jet is leased to the carrier by GE Capital
Aviation Services, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration records reflect two safety
incidents and 72 ``service difficulty reports'' involving the
Boeing 737-200 since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   One of the incidents, in February 1996, involved hydraulic
failure upon takeoff from Omaha, Neb., forcing the plane to return
to the airport. No one was injured.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether the hydraulic problem in that incident was
similar to the one that caused the plane to return to Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   The other past incident involved a cooling fan that shorted out
while the plane was on the ground, creating smoke in the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   The service difficulty reports, which log routine maintenance
issues serious enough to be reported to the FAA, include a variety
of problems that were corrected. Most involve corrosion on various
internal metal parts, a common problem in older planes. The airline
said the plane had two regular maintenance checks in October and
one in September.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hendricks and Scott Thurston write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
