A9990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELN-ATTACK-ADS-NYT &LR;      11-02 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-ATTACK-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS HOPE ADS TURN OUT VOTE FOR AN UNDERDOG
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ELN-RDP, ELN-CLINTON, ELN-NONVOTERS, ELN-REAPPORTION,
ELN-ILLINOIS, ELN-GORE) 
 (nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCK HILL, S.C. _ Over a steaming plate of baked beans and
Southern-style barbecue, Mark Penny, a Republican precinct chairman
here, was shaking his head Monday over new Republican attack ads
that aim to exploit President Clinton's sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a waste of money,'' Penny, a 63-year-old retired real
estate dealer, said of one television spot that asked if Clinton
should be rewarded for ``not telling the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever turnout we have will be from people voting their
convictions,'' not from negative ads, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But national Republican campaign strategists are betting
otherwise. Here in South Carolina's 5th Congressional District, one
of 30 targeted in a $10 million nationwide campaign, Republicans
hope the ads will stir up their base and help their underdog
challenger, Mike Burkhold, oust eight-term Democratic incumbent
John M. Spratt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans have long coveted this Democratic
outpost in one of the nation's most conservative states, especially
since the last three Republican presidential candidates _ Ronald
Reagan, George Bush and Bob Dole _ prevailed here. Indeed,
Republican luminaries Newt Gingrich, Oliver North and Marilyn
Quayle have campaigned in recent weeks for Burkhold, a 29-year-old
former town administrator and specialty-foods company executive.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, the National Republican Congressional Committee
flooded the district with mailings that contended ``there's not a
dime's worth of difference'' between Spratt and Clinton. The
leaflets sought to tar Spratt as a supporter of Clinton's ``liberal
social'' and ``pro-abortion'' agendas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our base is not happy with Bill Clinton,'' said Burkhold, who
joined Spratt in donning an apron and serving up coleslaw and iced
tea at a charity barbecue Monday at Sullivan Middle School. ``We
need to get our base out to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkhold, who acknowledged that he had not seen any of the ads
and learned of them last week from a reporter, discounted any
backlash from voters sick of impeachment talk. He said Democrats
here were too disgusted to defend Clinton or his surrogates. But
the district is about one-third black, so the potential for
energizing the other party's voters is there.
</P>
<P>
   None of this seems to worry Spratt, 56, whose district runs from
this Republican-leaning suburb of Charlotte, N.C., to the dusty old
Democratic textile towns to the east. ``If the effects of this ad
campaign are out there, I don't sense it,'' he said after
traversing his district.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do many Republicans who plan to vote for Burkhold, but not
because of some last-minute prodding. ``I don't put much stock in
that,'' said Matt England, a 49-year-old contractor. ``I don't pay
much attention to those negative ads.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican voters here say the ads will be just the tonic
to turn the tide against Spratt. ``They'll agitate a good many
people,'' said Mary Rawls, a retired elementary school teacher who
has lived here for 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthie Helms, a 36-year-old building inspector, and her two
children, Trey, 12, and Taylor, 5, wore ``I Like Mike'' buttons.
``Democrats are in trouble this year, and this will hurt the whole
Democratic ticket,'' Ms. Helms said.
</P>
<P>
   It will be difficult to stick a label of ``tax-and-spend
liberal'' on Spratt, a centrist and one of only 31 Democrats who
voted last month to begin formal impeachment proceedings against
Clinton. Spratt also played an important role in last year's
balanced-budget compromise, is hawkish on defense, and serves on a
special House panel investigating whether China improperly obtained
sensitive American technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans would like to tie Spratt close to Clinton, but
that'll be hard to do,'' said Marty Mobley, a 46-year-old
electrical engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Burkhold has run hard on a theme of ``new energy, new
leadership,'' borrowing a page from Rep. Bob Inglis, the Republican
who is challenging Democratic Sen. Ernest F. Hollings in a titanic
battle for his Senate seat here.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few weeks ago, Burkhold favored an upbeat campaign that
focused on lower taxes, prayer in public schools and less federal
government. Even Spratt's campaign manager, Matt Kuhn, complimented
the challenger's serious tone.
</P>
<P>
   But things have turned nasty. Republicans last week broadcast a
spot challenging Spratt's record on school prayer. Spratt said the
ads were false and demanded that they be pulled. Burkhold at first
distanced himself from the spots, noting that they were paid for by
his party, but after viewing them said he did not find them
inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   To be effective, the new television ads dwelling on Clinton must
attract attention, but this area is saturated with spots for
contested gubernatorial and Senate races in North and South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's deadening the message,'' said Glen Broach, chairman of
the political science department at Winthrop University here. ``The
effects of these ads will be marginal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
