<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9991 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-GOVWRAP-COX     11-02 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-GOVWRAP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Candidates make final pitches
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy and Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With one day left to subvert a Republican takeover of
Georgia government, seven Democratic candidates for statewide
office and the popular outgoing Democratic governor boarded three
planes after sunrise Monday for a seven-city tarmac tour to show
ticket diversity and solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   Gubernatorial candidate Roy Barnes called the ``Victory '98 Fly
Around'' a ``message of continuity of Gov. Zell Miller.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Miller were accompanied by lieutenant governor candidate
Mark Taylor; state school superintendent candidate Joe Martin;
secretary of state candidate Cathy Cox; Attorney General Thurbert
Baker; labor commission candidate Mike Thurmond; and U.S. Senate
candidate Michael Coles.
</P>
<P>
   Interspersed with complaints about the Republicans, candidates
joked amoung themselves to ease last day jitters.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond, who is black, was ribbed about being related to
Republican icon, U.S. Sen Strom Thurmond of South Carolina, who is
white. ``Maybe they ought to do a DNA test,'' quipped Mike
Thurmond, referring to the recent tests that show Thomas Jefferson
had an African-American branch to his family tree.
</P>
<P>
   In Chattanooga, which has about 150,000 Georgian suburbanites,
Barnes pointed out the get-out-the-vote urgency by saying there are
2,200 precincts statewide and ``several of these elections can be
determined by four or five votes difference in each precinct.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were also out in search of the precious votes in
those precincts.
</P>
<P>
   As the Democratic caravan reached Augusta, they were greeted by
placard-toting supporters of Republican U.S. Sen. Paul Coverdell
who had just left the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic operatives plaster the terminal with posters where
Coverdell placards hung 10 minutes earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Republican governor's candidate Guy Millner was also making one
last whirlwind tour of the state Monday, trying to drum up the
votes to make him Georgia's first GOP governor in more than 130
years.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the Democrats finished their tour at
Peachtree-DeKalb Airport, Millner rallied about 150 supporters
there during a stopover on his own seven-city fly-around.
</P>
<P>
   A sea of blue and white Millner '98 signs, chants of ``Go Guy,
go'' and an eight-foot elephant greeted Millner and his traveling
companion for the day, Secretary of State nominee John McCallum.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Democrats, who have campaigned together as a ticket,
Millner has rarely been seen with GOP lieutenant governor candidate
Mitch Skandalakis, who has been roundly criticized recently for
negative campaigning and ads that Democrats call race-baiting.
Skandalakis campaigned elsewhere Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that several polls show the race a dead-heat, or give him
a tenuous edge, Millner told supporters the race now depends on
turnout.
</P>
<P>
   In Augusta, Patricia McCracken, an activist who started a
newsletter focusing on energy issues said she wanted to see Barnes,
an old Marietta, Ga. friend, to try to get some support for her
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they say the same thing at every stop?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election could be determined by four or five votes in
each precinct,'' said Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   In Savannah, the Dems again arrive in the wake of Coverdell. And
Miller again tells the crowd of about 60 supporters that his
travelling candidate companions, four white men, two black men and
one white woman ``look like Georgia, not like charter members of a
country club.''
</P>
<P>
   After finishing his stump speech, Miller unsuccessfully tries to
get his cell phone to work and pauses momentarily when asked about
thoughts on his last campaign as an elected official. ``I'm not
nostalgic,'' he contends. The concrete issue of getting out votes
to continue his legacy keep him from pondering too much.
</P>
<P>
   At lunch, Barnes says his supporters tell him to smile more
while debating Millner. ``But it's hard to smile when I'm around
him,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   On the flight to Albany, Baker reflects on the ego-driven grind
that is political campaigning. ``All this would be fun if you
didn't have to worry about the winning and losing,'' he chuckles.
The other passengers tell him he's been on the road too long.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, Miller says, ``Folks, I'll tell you like it is. This
is a tough, tough, close, close race. I think it can be won in
South Georgia,'' he says, giving the crowd ownership of the race.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later in Clumbus, Baker lets the locals know ``as
Columbus goes, so goes the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   In politics, no locality is an important as the one you're in.
</P>
<P>
   In Macon, former Democratic Ocmulgee County District Attorney
Joe Briley, winces at the feeling that Republicans are breathing
down his party's neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's close, but I don't think the Republicans will take over
this year,'' he said confidently. He then adds, ``I'm thinking it's
four years away.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Torpy and Kathey Pruitt write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
