<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9996 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOPAIN-AZR &LR;      11-02 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOPAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORPHINE-BASED PASTE IS FOUND TO GET RID OF BACK-SURGERY PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JODIE SNYDER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Nurses noticed it almost immediately: The
morphine-based paste tested in Phoenix wiped out pain caused by
back surgery. Patients awoke with relief on their faces instead of
grimaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something to go in a patient's room and ask, `Do you
need anything?' And they would say, `No, I don't think so,' '' said
Dr. Volker Sonntag, vice president of the Barrow Neurological
Institute's department of neurosurgery.
</P>
<P>
   Barrow researchers on Friday presented the results of a yearlong
study that suggests they have found an effective way to reduce the
pain of back surgery. The institute's research could affect many
Americans who suffer from back pain, but who believe surgery would
make their lives even more miserable. An estimated 30 percent of
Americans experience some sort of back pain.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers offered their findings in San Francisco at a
meeting of the North American Spine Society. A presentation earlier
in October to the National Congress of Neurosurgeons generated
about 60 phone calls from colleagues around the country. Barrow has
won two national awards for the research.
</P>
<P>
   The paste, the consistency of thick cake batter, also may be
used to ease pain caused by assorted other surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, researchers have developed many types of
painkillers. But there has been little help for back surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Morphine has been squirted directly into the nerves exposed
during surgery, but it has offered only short-term relief.
Painkillers have been funneled in via catheters but that increased
infection rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing that was 100 percent effective. We couldn't
give people a lot of choices,'' Sonntag said.
</P>
<P>
   But after hearing of a patient who went biking one day after
back surgery, Sonntag and other surgeons are more optimistic. The
reason came after Sonntag accepted an offer from a doctor he had
worked with almost 25 years ago at the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   While riding on a bus to a conference, Sonntag was approached by
Dr. Charles Needham, professor of neurosurgery at the Yale
University College of Medicine. Needham had created a paste. Would
Sonntag test it on his patients?
</P>
<P>
   Sonntag, an internationally recognized surgeon, agreed, and
Barrow decided to test the paste on 60 patients from January 1996
to August 1997. Only patients who had never previously had back
surgery participated in the study. Most patients signed
enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   Some did have concerns about getting hooked on morphine. Sonntag
assured them a one-time dose of the potent painkiller wouldn't
cause addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Sonntag nor the patients knew who got the paste and who
got a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   One of the roles of Dr. Nicholas Theodore, one of the study's
researchers, was to mix and apply the paste to the epidural, which
was inserted into the spine in the same place women in labor get
anesthesia. One part of the paste acts as a reservoir, slowing the
release of the morphine and anti-inflammatories.
</P>
<P>
   Although only Theodore knew for sure which patients got the
paste, nurses quickly caught on as patients awoke in the recovery
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The nurses) would know that this guy got the juice,'' said
Sonntag.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Sutton was one who got the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept trying to get them to tell me if I would get it. The
nurses told me that if I got it, I would know it,'' said Sutton,
who went in for surgery because her nerves and spinal cord were
being squeezed.
</P>
<P>
   After surgery, the 75-year-old Glendale woman didn't have to
take any pain pills. She went home the next day. Although she had a
6-inch scar along her spine, she soon hit the shopping malls.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton's story was typical. The Barrow study showed:
</P>
<P>
   Patients who took the paste consumed three times less pain
medication than those who had the placebo.
</P>
<P>
   Patients' relief from pain came within 24 hours and lasted for
up to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Patients who received the placebo took up to 12 weeks to feel
better.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore said they could not detect any patients having side
effects from the paste. Sometimes, using morphine can cause
respiratory problems but there was no complication like that,
probably because it was used in such a small dose, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore and Janine Drabier, a research nurse at Barrow,
conducted a follow-up study of the patients a year later and found
none reported side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Needham now will use the Barrow studies to convince the Food and
Drug Administration to approve his paste.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, surgeons can concoct their own version of the paste.
Its ingredients already have been approved for other uses such as
blood clotting and reducing inflammation. But to use drugs
``off-label'' like that, doctors must get the consent of their
patients.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easier if the paste could be packaged and come into
the operating room pre-made, Sonntag said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mitchell Gropper, assistant professor of surgery at UA, said
the study offers welcome news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always coach my patients on how bad it is going to be. I
don't want them to have any false expectations but I tell them that
it's an investment in the future. This could be very promising,''
he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
