<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-NATO-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH MAJOR ARRESTED ON SUSPICION OF SPYING FOR SERBIA
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A French military officer at NATO headquarters in
Brussels has been arrested on suspicion of telling Serbia about
targets that the alliance was planning to bomb if Serbian forces
did not stop attacking civilians in Kosovo last month, French
officials said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Maj. Pierre Bunel, 46, is suspected of having
passed top-secret documents to Serbian agents, officials said. He
is assigned to the alliance's military committee, a liaison panel
between the NATO military commands and the civilian political
authorities that they report to.
</P>
<P>
   The documents related information about military targets that
NATO forces would hit if President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia
failed to meet a deadline of Oct. 27 to stop an offensive against
civilians in Kosovo, the mainly ethnic Albanian province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The allies had given their top military commander, Gen. Wesley
Clark, authority to begin bombing throughout Yugoslavia that
evening if Milosevic did not comply. But they postponed the start
of the attacks indefinitely after Milosevic began pulling back his
forces.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials in Brussels had no comment tonight on the arrest,
which French officials said was made on Saturday morning in Paris.
Bunel admitted passing documents to the Serbs but said he had acted
out of sympathy for the Serbian cause, not for money, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   France, though not part of the integrated command structure of
NATO, is a member of the alliance and has deployed thousands of
troops under American command to the peacekeeping operations in
Bosnia.
</P>
</TEXT>
