<HEADER>
A0008 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLF-LOOK-BACK-TE     11-02 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-LOOK-BACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YEAR IN GOLF: MAJORS BETTER THAN MONEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In honor of John Daly, whose 12-step approach to battling
alcoholism apparently will result in the PGA Tour's biggest victory
of the 1998 season, here are a dozen lessons professional golf fans
should have learned in the past calendar year.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, none of them involve ways to improve your game to the
point you could challenge the season-earnings record of $2,591,031
set yesterday by David Duval at the Tour Championship. But here is
what the savvy spectator should carry forward to the 1999 season
for a greater understanding of professional golf and professional
golfers.
</P>
<P>
   Money is good; majors are better.
</P>
<P>
   Duval led the PGA Tour in victories (four) and earnings. But he
expects to finish second to Mark O'Meara, winner of the Masters and
British Open, when peers cast ballots for player-of-the-year honors
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any other year, I've had a player of the year-type
season,'' Duval said. ``But I still believe the majors are the four
most important weeks of the year. I don't even know if I have a
chance to win it, to be honest. You have to look at Mark because of
the two majors.''
</P>
<P>
   Amateurs cannot be discounted.
</P>
<P>
   Those who play for something other than pay cast an imposing
shadow in major championships. Jenny Chuasiriporn, a senior at
Duke, lost in a 20-hole playoff at the Women's U.S. Open. Justin
Rose, a 17-year-old from England, finished fourth at the British
Open. Matt Kuchar, a senior at Georgia Tech, finished 14th at the
U.S. Open and 21st at the Masters. Overall, six amateurs posted
top-25 finishes on the PGA or LPGA tours.
</P>
<P>
   Current purses are chump change.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Duval's PGA Tour earnings record to survive next
season, when television exposure for tour events will increase 20
percent. In addition, the advent of the World Golf Championships _
a series of four high-profile events limited to the game's
top-ranked players _ will boost the total purse for PGA Tour events
to $130 million, up from $96 million this season.
</P>
<P>
   A season of $3 million in earnings for one player suddenly is a
realistic goal.
</P>
<P>
   Player dissension is brewing.
</P>
<P>
   With purses skyrocketing, it seems an ill-advised time for
players to complain and expect much public support. But a group of
players, led by journeyman Danny Edwards, have formed an
organization called the Tour Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   The TPA takes issue with the World Golf Championships being
limited-field events that still count in the official money list, a
move they claim will widen the disparity between the haves and
have-nots on the PGA Tour. TPA members also seek a more public
accounting of tour revenues from commissioner Tim Finchem and a
greater voice for rank-and-file players in formation of Tour
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Formed in August, TPA membership has peaked at 53, well below a
majority of players. How much clout the organization will have
remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods is not slumping. He's human.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he won only one PGA Tour event in 1998. But Woods entered
the Tour Championship with the same scoring average (69.10) he had
during his 1997 season, which included four victories and rampant
Tigermania.
</P>
<P>
   Woods also finished second to Duval in the race for the Vardon
Trophy, given to the player with the lowest scoring average for the
season. In Woods' estimation, the dropoff in victories is offset
over the long haul by a swing change that eliminated his tendency
toward boom or bust rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased with the strides I've made,'' Woods said.
``Expectations \Rfrom outsiders\S obviously have diminished, but
that's all good. To me, this has been a great year.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors have rediscovered Texas golf fans.
</P>
<P>
   After abandoning the Fort Worth-Dallas market in 1995, the
Senior Tour returns next season with the Bank One Championship on
Sept. 17-19 at Las Colinas Country Club in Irving.
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA Tour, which last held a full-field event in Texas in
1991, also returns. The Philips Invitational Honoring Harvey
Penick, a 72-hole event, is scheduled for May 20-23 at Onion Creek
Golf Club in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   This is not just a young man's game.
</P>
<P>
   Three 20-something players won major championships on the PGA
Tour in 1997. This season, the average age of the four major
champions was 37.5. In addition, Tom Watson and John Cook became
the first over-40 players to sweep the Fort Worth-Dallas tour
events since 1958. Watson, 48, won the MasterCard Colonial and
Cook, 40, prevailed at the GTE Byron Nelson Classic.
</P>
<P>
   The wheels of progress keep spinning.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Martin rolled into our consciousness with a golf cart and
a court order, forever altering the way people view handicapped
golfers. Martin, who struggles to walk because of a circulatory
disorder in his leg, won once on the Nike Tour and qualified for
the U.S. Open. He also won in court, gaining the right to ride in a
cart during competition. But he must go through the PGA Tour
qualifying tournament in December to regain playing privileges in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Players walk softer while swinging big sticks.
</P>
<P>
   The clickety-clack of metal spikes is becoming a distant memory
at professional golf tournaments, especially those on the LPGA
Tour. A survey of players showed 78 percent of competitors used
nonmetal spikes last season. The figure was 60 percent on the
Senior Tour, 41 percent on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring records are an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Huston finished 28 under at the Hawaiian Open, wiping out
the PGA Tour's 72-hole scoring record that had been held for 43
years by the late Ben Hogan. On the LPGA Tour, Se Ri Pak lapped the
field at the Jamie Farr Classic, setting records for single-round
(61) and 72-hole (261) totals. Notah Begay posted the first 59 in
Nike Tour history, tying the lowest score ever in professional
golf.
</P>
<P>
   Golf is not life.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most poignant moments of the season came while
watching Daly, a recovering alcoholic, suffer through involuntary
shakes while finishing a round of 74 in Vancouver, British
Columbia. Another came at the PGA Championship, where Stuart
Appleby received a standing ovation after completing his first
tournament following the death of his wife, Renay, in an automobile
accident the previous month.
</P>
<P>
   Even the best-laid plans can still fall through.
</P>
<P>
   Colonial Country Club representatives, who spent 32 months and
$225,000 in a high-profile pursuit of the 2003 Ryder Cup, were
reminded of this last month when PGA of America executives opted to
award the event to another course that spent far less time and
money in organizing its bid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 2117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
