<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     11-02 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FLUTIE AND TESTAVERDE TEST FATES
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
BY HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Do not ask Vinny Testaverde to expound on the
symbolism of Doug Flutie, the Orange Bowl and 1984, other than to
refer to a game he watched from the sideline as ``one of the
greatest'' he ever saw and that, during the third quarter, he
turned to one of his teammates to say, ``The team with the ball
last is going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde was a redshirt quarterback for Jimmy Johnson's Miami
Hurricanes that day, Nov. 23, almost 14 years ago. Down to his
final fling, Flutie somehow found Gerard Phelan in an end zone
crowd for 64 yards, a touchdown, a 47-45 victory for Boston College
and one career-defining moment.
</P>
<P>
   All these years later, Testaverde, who was supposedly destined
for his own snapshots of indelible brilliance, pursues the perfect
astrological alignment of the stars, the moon and the Meadowlands.
At 34, he plays on for what Flutie extraordinarily achieved with
that one desperation pass at 22. Testaverde plays on to be
remembered as a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kept his poise and he's not making a lot of bad
decisions,'' Bill Parcells said, in the manner of a neutral
observer more than a biased coach, referring to Testaverde's latest
episodic rewriting of his reputation. The Jets' tough-to-please
coach was thrilled with his team's 20-17 rain-soaked victory on
Sunday at Kansas City, tempered in what statement, if any, the
Testaverde-led Jets had made in terms of establishing themselves as
a post-New Year's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you last week, it's too early for that,'' Parcells
said. ``There's not enough on the line. That has to be further down
the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Pragmatically spoken, but even the coach knows that this week,
he cannot hold back the forces of hyperbole. Flutie and the Buffalo
Bills come to New Jersey on Sunday, matching two of four deadlocked
division rivals and the two top-rated quarterbacks in the American
Football Conference. They are also former Heisman Trophy winners,
one whose career drifted south of mediocrity, the other's north of
the border, before they rose this season from the benches of their
new teams to pitch 5-0 shutouts as the starters in relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know both of them won the Heisman, to tell you
the truth,'' Parcells said. ``But I think this is interesting.
Flutie is a good story, with all he's accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Part by perception, part by performance, Flutie, 36, has
actually lived with little of the underachiever's rap that
Testaverde has. Testaverde, at 6 feet 5 inches, showed up with the
classic quarterback's body, and the right collegiate breeding. Few
believed Flutie, at 5-9, from pesky B.C., would be more than a
marginal pro. Those who ridicule the National Football League for
ignoring him for years while he won championships in Canada
conveniently forget the uninspiring years Flutie had in Chicago and
New England, from 1986 to 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie, in all likelihood, became a better quarterback in
Canada, by the recurrence of personal and collective success.
``These guys were both good players,'' Parcells said. ``They've got
some God-given talent. Flutie's is different from Vinny's, but
they've been playing a long time. So then a situation comes along
that allows them to flourish a little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   In so many words, Parcells was saying, hold on, don't get
carried away by part of one half-season. Quarterbacks may improve
with advancing age, but not quite like wine. Testaverde and Flutie
haven't exactly reinvented themselves. They have stepped into
better circumstances. They have, to date, made the most of them.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Testaverde, it is not as if he has no track
record. After escaping Tampa Bay, he drove Cleveland two rounds
into the playoffs in 1994. Two years later, he was a Pro Bowl
performer on a bad Baltimore team. Long since forgotten is his 21-1
record as a two-year college starter, but he may never live down
five interceptions against Penn State in the 1987 Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've continued to work at this, and it feels good to know it
pays off,'' Testaverde said. ``The more experience you have, the
better knowledge you have.''
</P>
<P>
   He did sound like a winner when he stepped into the Jets' huddle
on Sunday before their game-winning drive. ``This is what great
teams do,'' he said. ``Finish teams off on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are not a great team, not yet, any more than Testaverde
is a great quarterback. But together they went down the field,
making several crucial plays, and scored. Testaverde was one step
closer to the playoffs, to giving himself a chance to step into the
kind of Flutie moment he witnessed from the sideline 14 years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
