<HEADLINE>
RANGERS STILL WANT CLAYTON, BUT WON'T WAIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Jose Vizcaino and Jeff Blauser are two
shortstops the Rangers might have to consider if they can't re-sign
free agent Royce Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin said re-signing Clayton is still a
top priority. But Melvin said if Clayton starts shopping himself to
other teams, then the Rangers will have to start talking trade
about a shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a guy goes into free agency and files and they want to
hear what other clubs are offering, then they're telling us we're
free to pursue other options,'' Melvin said. ``We can't wait for
guys to talk to other clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton is the only front-line shortstop eligible for free
agency, but Melvin said other teams have called about shortstops
available for trade.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin declined to reveal names, but major-league officials said
the Los Angeles Dodgers, after acquiring Mark Grudzielanek during
the season, are shopping Vizcaino and the Chicago Cubs are offering
Blauser, who lost his job to Jose Hernandez late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is San Francisco Giants shortstop Rey
Sanchez, who split time with Rich Aurilia this year. Before
acquiring Clayton in a July 31 trade with St. Louis, Melvin had
interest in Sanchez. The Florida Marlins might trade Edgar
Renteria, but first they want to make sure that Triple-A prospect
Alex Gonzalez is ready to take over.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people out there we're going to have to take a
look at,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Clubs have exclusive negotiating rights with their own free
agents until Friday. Melvin said he'll continue to talk with
Clayton's agent, Arn Tellem, and will know better by the end of the
week if a deal can get done quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not optimistic,'' Melvin said. ``There's nothing
imminent. I get a sense these guys have been instructed \Rby the
Players Association\S to test the market unless you overwhelm
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tellem could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin is also talking with Jeff Moorad, Will Clark's attorney,
but said re-signing Clayton and the Rangers' quest for pitching
help remain his top priorities. Clark is eligible for free agency,
but has yet to file.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to see what Clayton costs and what pitching costs
and then go from there,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Moorad said, ``Will's first clear choice is to re-sign with the
Rangers. In that regard we've been purposely dragging our feet on
filing for free agency in hoping to give the process with the
Rangers a chance to reach a conclusion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
