<HEADLINE>
COURT AGREES TO RESOLVE DISPUTE OVER LAW ON GIFTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The law that prohibits giving ``anything of value''
to a federal official, known as the unlawful gratuity statute,
criminalizes conduct that falls somewhere in the zone between
outright bribery and the innocent exchange of gifts between
friends, one of whom happens to be a public official.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, in a case growing out of an independent counsel's
investigation of Mike Espy, the former secretary of agriculture in
the Clinton administration who is being tried on criminal charges
here, the Supreme Court agreed to resolve a dispute among the lower
federal courts over just what it is that the gratuity statute makes
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The case is an appeal by the independent counsel, Donald Smaltz,
who two years ago obtained a conviction of an agricultural
cooperative, Sun-Diamond Growers of California, for giving Espy
tennis tickets, luggage and other gifts worth $5,900. In a ruling
last March that troubled federal prosecutors, the federal appeals
court here overturned the conviction and defined the offense of
giving an illegal gratuity in a way that will make it difficult for
any prosecutor, not just an independent counsel, to win cases
against those who seek illegitimate influence over federal decision
makers.
</P>
<P>
   The law at issue, which dates to 1961, is inherently ambiguous.
It is a crime to give, offer or promise ``anything of value'' to a
public official ``because of any official act performed or to be
performed by such public official.'' Under the independent
counsel's interpretation, as reflected in the instructions to the
jury that convicted Sun-Diamond, the law's reference to an
``official act'' simply meant that the gift had to have been
motivated by the recipient's official position, without regard to
any expected or hoped-for response by the official.
</P>
<P>
   But in overturning the conviction, a three-judge panel of the
U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit said the
law required proof that the gift was motivated not simply by the
recipient's position, but by an official act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The giver must intend either to reward some past concrete
official act or acts, or to enhance the likelihood of some future
act or acts,'' the court said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have refused to allow the official act requirement to be
satisfied by some vague hope of inducing warm feelings toward the
donor,'' the appeals court continued, adding that ``the terms of
the statute require a finding that the gifts were motivated by more
than merely the giver's desire to ingratiate himself with the
official generally, or to celebrate the latter's status.''
</P>
<P>
   The line between that definition _ which has been rejected by
most federal appeals courts but accepted by some _ and the legal
definition of bribery is a fine one. Bribery requires a quid pro
quo, an explicit agreement linking the gift to the desired action.
Federal law punishes bribery more harshly than an illegal gratuity,
with up to 15 years imprisonment compared to a maximum of two
years. Sun-Diamond received a $1.5 million fine after its
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   But the appeals court's treatment of the gratuity law ``may make
an unlawful gratuity virtually indistinguishable from a bribe,''
Smaltz complained in his Supreme Court appeal, United States vs.
Sun-Diamond Growers of California, No. 98-131. Asserting that
Sun-Diamond's conviction would have been upheld in many other
federal appellate circuits, he said it was unfortunate that ``the
most important circuit for the enforcement of the unlawful gratuity
prohibition has interpreted the statute differently and more
leniently than virtually every other circuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Espy himself is on trial in U.S. District Court here, on charges
brought by the independent counsel for accepting various gifts from
companies regulated by the department he ran. His contact at
Sun-Diamond, and the donor of that company's gifts, was Richard
Douglas, Sun-Diamond's vice president for corporate affairs, who
was Espy's college classmate and longtime friend. In trying to
persuade the Supreme Court not to hear the independent counsel's
appeal, Espy's lawyer, Richard Hibey, told the court that the case
was atypical, involving ``an uncontested, legitimate friendship
that spanned more than 25 years.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Among the other new cases the court granted Monday were these:
</P>
<P>
   Discrimination Damages:
</P>
<P>
   The court agreed to resolve another dispute among the lower
federal courts and define the circumstances under which a
successful plaintiff in an employment discrimination case can win
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, Congress revised the Civil Rights Act of 1964,
which had provided only limited remedies, and made punitive damages
available for the first time. The revised law made punitive damages
of up to $300,000 available to plaintiffs who could prove that the
employer ``engaged in a discriminatory practice with malice or with
reckless indifference to the federally protected rights of an
aggrieved individual.'' The question for the court in this case,
Kolstad vs. American Dental Association, No. 98-208, is essentially
how bad the defendant's conduct had to be.
</P>
<P>
   In a 6-5 decision last May, overturning an earlier ruling by a
three-judge panel, the District of Columbia Circuit set a very high
threshold and ruled that punitive damages could be awarded only on
proof of ``egregious discriminatory conduct.'' Other courts have
held that plaintiffs need show only that the discrimination was
conscious, deliberate, or engaged in by management.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiff in this case, Carole Kolstad, sued the American
Dental Association after a high-level position she sought in the
organization's Washington office went to a man with less seniority.
A jury agreed that the selection was the result of sex
discrimination and awarded Ms. Kolstad more than $52,000 in back
pay. After the appellate panel ruled that she was entitled to a
trial on her request for punitive damages, the full court
reconsidered the case and ruled that the defendant's behavior was
not ``egregious'' enough to merit punitive damages. The Supreme
Court's decision in this case could also determine the standard for
punitive damages under other federal civil rights laws.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Military Double Jeopardy:
</P>
<P>
   The justices agreed to hear an appeal by the Clinton
administration from a decision by the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
Armed Forces, a civilian court that serves as the highest court in
the military justice system. The appeals court barred the president
from dismissing an Air Force major from the service after the
officer's conviction by a court-martial for willfully disobeying a
``safe sex'' order.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping an officer from the rolls, as such a dismissal is
known, is an action authorized by Congress following certain types
of convictions. Two years after Maj. James Goldsmith's conviction,
Congress expanded the president's authority to include cases like
his. The military appeals court, rejecting the government's view
that the action was an administrative personnel matter, found that
it amounted to extra punishment in violation of the constitutional
prohibition against double jeopardy. An additional issue in this
case, Clinton vs. Goldsmith, No. 98-347, is whether the military
court had jurisdiction to hear the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
