<SLUG> BC-RUBY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX ZOO PLANS C-SECTION TO REMOVE DEAD BABY FROM PAINTING
ELEPHANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB PETRIE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ It's risky. Never before has a Caesarian section been
done successfully on an Asian elephant. Only four such procedures
have been documented.
</P>
<P>
   All four of the elephants died.
</P>
<P>
   But Phoenix Zoo officials said a C-section is the best chance
they have to save Ruby, the popular artistic elephant, who's
fighting for her own life after losing the calf she had nurtured in
her womb the past 22 months.
</P>
<P>
   The zoo will bring in a team of top doctors and experts late
this week to perform the operation to remove the dead, decomposing
fetus that remains inside Ruby and threatens the 25-year-old
elephant with fatal infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try our best to recover this elephant,'' said
Jeff Williamson, executive director of the Phoenix Zoo, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Veterinarians, who discovered the dead calf during a surgical
procedure Saturday, could not remove the fetus via the birth canal.
</P>
<P>
   The C-section would not take place before Friday, so zoo
veterinarians can put Ruby on a fast to clear her intestines and
give her a better chance to survive. Her home, a brown brick
building near the children's zoo, also has to be cleaned and
prepped for the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get the doctors assembled and equipped, and get
Ruby as strong as possible,'' Williamson said.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials would not disclose Monday the doctors involved or
the possible cost and scope of the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to put the pieces together, but there's a lot of
pieces,'' said Bruce Bohmke, general curator, adding the zoo _ the
country's largest not supported by tax dollars _ can afford the
best care possible.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy, either. Ruby weighs 9,000 pounds. Her baby
weighed 250.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take the human condition, and exaggerate it by a
hundredfold,'' Williamson said.
</P>
<P>
   A healthy calf would have been the first born in captivity at
the Phoenix Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   In the other C-section cases involving Asian elephants,
Williamson said the animals all had to be operated on under
emergency circumstances, during the delivery, when they went into
shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The animals were already under severe stress,'' he said,
adding Ruby is in relatively good health. Asian elephants have a
life expectancy of up to 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby's baby apparently was not compatible with her mother,
veterinarians discovered Saturday. If she survives, Ruby will
likely never be mated again, Williamson said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby became pregnant in 1996, during a two-year loan to the
Tulsa Zoo, where she was mated with an elephant named Sneezy,
considered a good match.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were really excited when she got pregnant, and we were
looking forward to a healthy calf,'' Williamson said.
</P>
<P>
   She returned to the Phoenix Zoo in November 1997 when she was 11
months pregnant. In recent days, reaching full term, she showed
signs of going into labor, and veterinarians last week began
administering oxytocin to induce labor.
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, Ruby's water broke. Saturday morning, zoo
veterinarians took video of the elephant and transmitted it to
several national experts, who recommended a surgical procedure to
determine the position of the calf.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m. Saturday, doctors discovered the dead calf in the
birth canal, but could not remove it.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby, born in Thailand, arrived at the Phoenix Zoo in 1974, a
baby herself at just 7 months.
</P>
<P>
   She became famous for painting in 1987, after zoo keepers saw
doodles she left in the sand with a stick.
</P>
<P>
   The keepers then gave Ruby a brush and canvas, and she went to
work, dazzling zoo patrons with her deft strokes of pastels on
canvas. Her lithographs sold for $40 in the gift shop, and raised
about $500,000 for the zoo over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of tears today,'' said Lisa Hodak, a zoo
gift-shop employee who owns three Rubys. ``I grew up with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruby gave up the palette in 1995, as zoo keepers helped her
focus on preparing to raise a calf.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo patrons looking for Ruby on Monday said they were pulling
for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever is best for the mother,'' said Tammie Anders of
Phoenix, visiting with her 4-year-old daughter, Ashley. ``I know
there's not a lot of Asian elephants in captivity. I hope she pulls
through.'' &QL; 
Bob Petrie can be reached at 444-7941 or at bob.petrie(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
