<HEADER>
A0020 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NLF-NOTES-COX     11-02 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NLF-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Season's 2nd half is for salvaging jobs
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The middle portion of the season traditionally marks
the beginning of decision time in the league, and this year is no
different. In some precincts, coaching staffs today are debating
the short- and long-term futures of quarterbacks. In front offices
around the NFL, owners are beginning to consider coaching changes.
</P>
<P>
   One coach, Kevin Gilbride of San Diego, already has been fired,
after an Oct. 11 loss to Oakland. Look for Baltimore's Ted
Marchibroda to be the next coach let go if he loses Sunday to
Oakland. Despite the denials from owner Art Modell and personnel
director Ozzie Newsome, the fate of Marchibroda already is decided.
There is no way he'll be back in '99, and rumor is he'll be
relieved if the Ravens lose Sunday. The best bet is he would be
replaced by defensive coordinator Marvin Lewis on an interim basis
and that Modell will pursue George Seifert in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis team president John Shaw wouldn't throw himself in
front of the door if Dick Vermeil offered to resign, but the Rams
owe the coach $5.7 million in salary for three more seasons and
will have a tough time firing him. Norv Turner is as good as gone
in Washington, and Seattle's Dennis Erickson is shaky after
Sunday's night's loss.
</P>
<P>
   Some other coaches who need strong second-half finishes to save
their jobs are Vince Tobin (Arizona), Jeff Fisher (Tennessee),
Bruce Coslet (Cincinnati) and Pete Carroll (New England).
</P>
<P>
   On the quarterback front, Pittsburgh will stick with Kordell
Stewart as its starter but must re-evaluate him at the end of the
season. Chiefs coach Marty Schottenheimer might be close to
replacing Elvis Grbac with Rich Gannon. And there are difficult
decisions on when to bring back Rob Johnson (Buffalo), Brad Johnson
(Minnesota) and Jeff George (Oakland), because their replacements
are a combined 11-1.
</P>
<P>
   Collins' woes continue
</P>
<P>
   When Kerry Collins asked Mike Ditka if he could stay behind in
Carolina after Sunday's game there, the coach reluctantly granted
the request. Given Collins' history in Charlotte, the results were
predictable. Collins was arrested early Monday morning for alleged
drunken driving and faces a Nov. 12 hearing. Ditka and Saints
president Bill Kuharich have presented Collins the opportunity to
start over and promised he will start ahead of Billy Joe Tolliver
by Nov. 15. The four-year veteran, though, continues to exhibit a
lack of maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Rypien report
</P>
<P>
   Veteran quarterback Mark Rypien, who couldn't fulfill his
Falcons contract this year because of the death of son Andrew from
a brain tumor, hopes to get himself back into shape to resume his
NFL career. Rypien, 38, was in Pullman, Wash., over the weekend to
thank Ryan Leaf for donating a $100,000 scholarship to Washington
State in Andrew's name. Rypien's wife, Annette, will have her final
treatment for cervical cancer next Tuesday. ``We're hoping this is
over,'' Rypien said. The Dolphins, who are seeking veteran backup
help for Dan Marino, are said to be interested in Rypien for the
stretch run. But agent Ken Staninger said Tuesday he hasn't heard
from any teams recently.
</P>
<P>
   Champ chatter
</P>
<P>
   Two of five NFL scouts surveyed at the Florida-Georgia game said
Bulldogs cornerback Champ Bailey actually has a bigger long-term
upside as a wide receiver. Because Bailey is a junior, and the
scouts would be subject to a fine by the NFL for any comments about
an underclassman, their assessments were not for attribution.
</P>
<P>
   Tee time
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta chapter of the NFL Alumni will stage its annual
charity golf tournament today at the Golf Club of Georgia. Former
Falcons center Mike Ruether, the president of the group, has
focused the local chapter on a ``Caring for Kids'' initiative.
Ruether has recruited Andrew Young and Newt Gingrich, among others,
to help raise visibility. An auction will follow today's
tournament, and information on it and other chapter ventures is
available at 770-850-8881.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tops
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has had only four rushing performances in its history _
two each by Gerald Riggs and Erric Pegram _ better than Jamal
Anderson's 172-yard effort Sunday. His 203 total yards from
scrimmage were the 13th-best in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive best
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Brooks of Tampa Bay might be the best weakside
linebacker in the NFL right now, and he demonstrated his all-around
abilities in the Buccaneers' win over Minnesota. The former Florida
State star had 10 tackles, two passes defensed, an interception and
two quarterback pressures. Brooks helped to cover Vikings slot
receiver Cris Carter and his deeper-than-normal pass drops aided
young cornerbacks Ronde Barber and Brian Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Truly special
</P>
<P>
   Denver return specialist Vaughn Hebron got plenty of chances
Sunday, returning six kickoffs for 161 yards against Cincinnati.
But the six-year journeyman saved the best for last. With the
Broncos and Bengals tied 26-26, be broke two tackles on a 38-yard
return that set up Davis' 5-yard touchdown run to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing . . .
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Jay Riemersma was cut by the Bills two years ago, but
he has blossomed into a go-to guy for Buffalo, especially in the
red zone. Riemersma has just 11 catches, but four have been for
touchdowns, including two Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Stat stuff
</P>
<P>
   Marchibroda thought he had discovered a tailback from heaven on
Sept. 27 when little-used Priest Holmes rushed for 173 yards on 23
carries against the Bengals. Since then, however, Holmes hasn't had
a prayer. In the four subsequent games, he has just 156 yards on 50
attempts and only once has gained more than 41 yards in a game. The
Ravens might go back to Errict Rhett or Jay Graham this week.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes isn't the only back slumping in Baltimore. The coaches
are disenchanted with fullback Roosevelt Potts, and he could be
replaced as the starter by Kenyon Cotton. . . . Buffalo wide
receiver Andre Reed had five catches in a victory over Miami, four
of them third-down conversions. . . . Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson
went for it and failed on fourth-and-1 from his own 34-yard line in
the first half. . . . The best offensive tackles on a team going
nowhere continue to be the Ravens' tandem of Jonathan Ogden and
Orlando Brown. The latter is a free agent next spring and will be
sought heavily by teams looking for a right-side power blocker. . .
. Oakland cornerbacks Eric Allen and Charles Woodson limited
Seattle wide receiver Joey Galloway to no catches of more than 8
yards.
</P>
<P>
   The last word(s)
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay defensive end Reggie White, who despite three sacks
Sunday and 11 for the season still insists he won't be back in
1999: ``This time the (retirement) is going to stick. It's fun on
game day, but getting from Monday and back to Sunday again is so
much harder than anyone can imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
