<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ENDS CAMPAIGN URGING DEMOCRATS TO TURN OUT BIG VOTE
</HEADLINE>
   (See also ELN-RDP, ELN-CLINTON, ELN-NONVOTERS, ELN-REAPPORTION,
ELN-ILLINOIS, ELN-ATTACK-ADS) 
(sw) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TACOMA, Wash. _ Vice President Al Gore ended his long and
labored campaign season on Monday with a long and laboring day on
the West Coast, joining major Democratic candidates for a rally in
Sacramento, Calif., and along a four-stop, 130-mile bus tour
through western Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In the final hours before the elections, Gore delivered a fiery
speech at every event, each generally focused on urging Democrats
to vote on Tuesday. To an assemblage of 800 noisy, card-waving
partisans in Sacramento to start the day, he raised his voice to
say: ``The enthusiasm level in this room is very high. You have to
translate that into a very high turnout tomorrow. I know you are
determined to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats across the country, the stakes are unusually high,
measured against predicted losses for the party in the House, the
Senate and governors' mansions, in part because of the
eleventh-hour Republican strategy to make President Clinton's
involvement in a sex scandal a major campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and the candidates who accompanied him on Monday countered
by stressing issues that Democrats have made the hallmarks of their
fall campaigning _ education, health care, economic progress and
environmental protections _ while taking steady swipes at House
Speaker Newt Gingrich and the right wing of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   After his remarks at a park in Olympia, the Washington state
capital, Gore took the additional step of calling aside Jay Inslee,
a former House Democrat who is trying to regain a seat this year,
to acknowledge his efforts as the first Democrat anywhere to air a
television commercial criticizing Republicans who made the sex
scandal a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told reporters that Inslee was the first ``to sound the
trumpet and say, `Hey, wait a minute, this election ought to be
about the future of the American people and not about investigating
President Clinton.' He's taken that message to the people, and the
people have responded by saying, `That is right.'''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Gore reprised a favorite laugh-line when he told
the crowd of several thousand: ``The Republican party in 1998 is in
such disarray that the right hand doesn't know what the far right
hand is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the University of Washington-Tacoma, he seemed to
contradict his own joke by saying Republicans are ``united in their
hatred for President Clinton and their fondness for personal
attacks and negative advertisements.'' He repeated the disarray
joke, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, as well, the stakes in the elections are elevated, in
that all his recent campaign appearances _ more than 100 events in
26 states since late August _ have also been designed to help
solidify his political base for a presidential run in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from a smattering of ``Gore 2000'' signs along the way
on Monday and a reference to him by Art Torres, the state party
chairman, as ``the next president of the United States,'' most
references to the future were limited to the next 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gore said that part of the political calculation for
ending the campaign with a two-day trip that began on Sunday in New
York and Wisconsin was to provide a final boost for four candidates
caught in Senate races that remained too close to call: Rep.
Charles Schumer of New York, Sen. Russell Feingold of Wisconsin,
Sen. Barbara Boxer of California and Sen. Patty Murray of
Washington. Ms. Murray accompanied the vice president on each stop
on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
