<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0022 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITIGROUP-ART-2TAKES-     11-02 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIGROUP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES DIMON, CITIGROUP'S PRESIDENT AND HEIR APPARENT, IS FIRED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: W.Va., N.Y.)  (Eds: Please note subslug for CITICORP) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN and PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Thursday, Oct. 22, about 150 top executives of
Citigroup, the financial services titan created by the recent
merger of Citicorp and Travelers Group, set out with their spouses
for what was billed as four days of golf, corporate planning and
managerial bonding at the tony Greenbriar resort in West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the surface of this ostensibly amiable event,
serious trouble was brewing. The day before, Citigroup had posted a
huge and disappointing plunge in third-quarter profits, and those
ensconced at Greenbriar were soon complaining loudly about the
trouble the company was having knitting together disparate
businesses as lending to big companies and bond and stock
underwriting.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, said executives at the meeting, Steven Black, a
senior Citigroup executive, quarreled loudly with Deryck Maughan,
Citigroup's vice chairman, over how best to manage the company's
disparate corporate and investment banking businesses. And the man
who finally stepped between them was James Dimon, Citigroup's
president, who had been charged with smoothing out such
differences.
</P>
<P>
   But a week after the meeting, at 2 p.m. Sunday at a conference
center in Armonk, Citigroup's co-chief executives, Sanford Weill
and John Reed, responded to the turmoil in an even more direct and
surprising way: they asked for Dimon's resignation. Dimon was
widely considered to be their heir apparent and had once seemed
more like a son to Weill than an employee. But Dimon's bosses had
evidently decided that he was not succeeding in melding the
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Shakespearean overtones of familial betrayal and
internecine battles lies a larger issue: a merger announced only
eight months ago and heralded as ushering in a new era in global
capitalism and supermarket-style financial services is already
showing signs of severe, potentially disastrous, strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a loss of quality management,'' said Joan
Solotar, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. ``Jamie played
a significant role in executing the overall strategy. I think
you'll see more departures and further turmoil.''
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation Monday that Black and other executives
close to Dimon were considering quitting Citigroup. Black declined
to comment, and Maughan did not respond to a telephone message. On
the New York Stock Exchange, Citigroup's shares fell 87.5 cents, to
$46.125.
</P>
<P>
   Reed and Weill declined to comment Monday, though in an
interview on Sunday both spoke fondly of Dimon and optimistically
of Citigroup's prospects. Dimon was equally cheery on Sunday,
though few on Wall Street accept this friendly chatter as a true
indicator of the state of affairs at Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever regrets Reed expressed on Sunday about Dimon's
departure, Monday morning, in comments to Citigroup employees over
the internal ``squawk box,'' Reed offered a rather bloodless
account of Dimon's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt that given the circumstances the best thing to do was
for him to leave,'' Reed said. ``It probably was the right business
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Dimon's departure leaves a gaping hole at the top of
Citigroup, and many analysts and Citigroup employees are
questioning the wisdom of the decision to ask him to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found it shocking,'' one top Citigroup executive said
Monday, insisting on anonymity. ``He was basically fired, and a lot
of it had to do with corporate politics. Jamie had a lot of fans
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was the 42-year-old Dimon's popularity that when he walked
onto the trading floor of the brokerage unit, Salomon Smith Barney,
Monday morning he was greeted with a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Weill and Dimon have come a long way together, becoming a
favorite double act both for Wall Street and for investors around
the world. Their presentations to the investment community
routinely impressed analysts, with Dimon the quiet and trusted
right hand and analyst for Weill, the personable Wall Street baron.
</P>
<P>
   The two executives who have been tapped to run corporate and
investment banking businesses, once considered part of Dimon's
bailiwick, are not seen as credible candidates for Citigroup's
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Menezes, Citicorp's former president, is regarded as a
competent, though not stellar, manager. Michael Carpenter, former
head of the Travelers life insurance and annuities business, has a
notable blemish on his resume: He ran General Electric's Kidder
Peabody unit during a financial scandal involving the onetime bond
trading star Joseph Jett.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup declined to make Menezes and Carpenter available for
comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Dimon's popularity, he has had a rocky tenure over the
last year jointly supervising Salomon Smith Barney's investment
banking activities with Maughan. The unit incurred hundreds of
millions of dollars in trading losses in the third quarter, largely
because of errant bets on overseas markets and other risky bond
investments.
</P>
<P>
   In the executive shake-up announced on Sunday, Citigroup
stripped Maughan of any real management duties and appointed him to
a largely ceremonial role as a vice-chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Weill, who recently acknowledged that he had failed to
scrutinize his firm's relationship with the risky hedge-fund giant
Long-Term Capital Management, also failed to take account of
Salomon Brothers' explosive bond positions when he acquired that
company last year.
</P>
<P>
   The recent trading losses, though, only added to what has become
an increasingly distant relationship between him and Dimon. And
people close to both men said this rift was not apparent to Reed
when the merger was engineered earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There were two main reasons for that rift, people close to both
Dimon and Weill said.
</P>
<P>
   One was Dimon's treatment of Jessica Bibliowicz, Weill's
daughter, when a mutual fund division she managed did not do as
well as expected. Although Dimon and Ms. Bibliowicz had been
friends and vacationed together as teen-agers, Ms. Bibliowicz left
Travelers last year after a series of run-ins with Dimon.
</P>
<P>
   Another divisive issue was what some Travelers executives
believed to be the 65-year-old Weill's growing resentment of
Dimon's spot in the limelight and generally stellar reputation on
Wall Street. Meanwhile, Dimon was beginning to chafe under his
mentor.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Salomon Inc. in the fall of 1997, which Weill
strongly favored, but which Dimon voiced reservations about, was
but one of the latest frictions in their increasingly troubled
working relationship.
</P>
<P>
   All these problems reached a crucial stage with the highly
ballyhooed creation of Citigroup, which aspires to combine consumer
businesses like credit cards, savings accounts and mortgages with
corporate businesses like underwriting and mergers and acquisitions
advice. Once the new machine is up and running, the thinking goes,
Citigroup will be able to sell all of these products worldwide as
Wall Street's answer to Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   While Citigroup has had a relatively easy time putting its
consumer businesses together, it has had a far rockier time
rearranging its corporate activities. And the debate about whether
to integrate Travelers' investment banking business with Citibank's
corporate banking was the final blow in the troubled relationship
between Dimon and his mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Dimon, colleagues said, expressed concern about the wisdom of
hastily combining the two businesses into one operating unit _ the
path Citigroup chose when it announced the executive shake-up on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts noted when the merger was announced in April that both
companies had enjoyed buoyant profits in their respective corporate
businesses and could allow them to coexist without damaging that
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Integrating the corporate businesses raises the stakes for Reed,
59, and Weill because sound management will be required to make
such a potentially unwieldy structure perform effectively. Already,
there have been hard-fought turf wars between Citicorp and
Travelers executives over how to manage the new company's bond
business.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Dimon, who lost a board seat when the merger occurred,
made it clear the last week that he wanted to be the person who
presided over the integrated corporate businesses. But Weill and
Reed had no intention of giving him that plum and made the decision
to ask for his resignation after consulting with Citigroup's board
last week.
</P>
<P>
   When Dimon was summoned to Armonk, he was not expecting to be
asked for his resignation, people who attended that meeting said.
Nor, as some at Citigroup believe, was he offered a ceremonial job
like that given to Maughan.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a partnership with Weill that had lasted more than 15
years was over. Dimon waited in Armonk until 4 p.m. on Sunday to
briefly tell other senior executives of his resignation. Then he
left.
</P>
<P>
   Dimon's resignation, the latest in a series of high-level
departures in a commercial and investment banking business roiled
by global economic turmoil, is likely to lead to the departure of
several of his close subordinates from Salomon Smith Barney,
colleagues said Monday. Several top managers at Salomon Smith
Barney have been closely identified with Dimon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real sense of shock among the investment community.
Investors have the highest regard for him,'' said Sallie Krawcheck,
an analyst at Sanford Bernstein &AMP; Co. ``There's a little bit of a
kick in the stomach that you feel from having one of the best-known
and most visible talents leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimon is leaving Citigroup with a full wallet. He was paid $23.1
million last year and exercised stock options in 1997 worth almost
$37 million. He is also likely to garner a number of job offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is and has been one of the best executives in the financial
services industry,'' said Gerard Roche, chairman of Heidrick &AMP;
Struggles, an executive search firm. ``Any broad-gage financial
services company _ and that includes brokerage and investment and
commercial banking, and insurance, any credit card company _ should
be at least looking at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Weill and Reed still have their work cut out for them
delivering on the promises of the Citigroup merger. Shrinking
profits have caused Citigroup's shares to plunge 38 percent since
reaching a high of $72.625 on July 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure there's a definitive amount of time for Weill and
Reed to prove themselves, but there's not an unlimited amount of
time either,'' said Diane Glossman, an analyst with Lehman
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
