<SLUG> BC-ARTHRITIS-DRUG-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA APPROVES IMMUNEX ARTHRITIS DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enbrel, a genetically engineered rheumatoid arthritis drug from
Immunex Corp., was approved by the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle biotechnology company's stock jumped 1 9/17 to close
at 70 5/8. The approval ended six months of nail-biting at
Seattle-based Immunex Corp., which submitted its data for
fast-track approval last May. It could also give Seattle's largest
biotechnology company its first blockbuster drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major event for Immunex. This product is likely to
transform them,'' analyst Carol Werther, of Adams, Harkness &AMP; Hill,
told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have estimated the market for Enbrel could be worth
between $500 million and $1 billion in sales per year. Immunex has
spent about $150 million developing the drug.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 2.5 million people with rheumatoid arthritis in
the United States, of which about 500,000 have advanced disease
that no longer responds to drugs. There is no known cure for the
disease, which causes painful inflammation and destruction of
joints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most important advance since methotrexate was
introduced into our practice in about 1980,'' said Dr. Philip
Mease, director of the division of rheumatology at the Minor &AMP;
James Clinic in Seattle and an associate professor of medicine at
the University of Washington School of Medicine. ``This is the most
important new treatment since that time.'' Methotrexate, a
chemotherapeutic agent, is widely used to treat severe cases of
rheumatoid arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Enbel is the first of a new class of drugs called biological
response modifiers for treating rheumatoid arthritis. Based on a
molecule that occurs naturally in the body, it reduces symptoms by
interrupting the body's inflammatory response.
</P>
<P>
   In clinical studies, the drug reduced pain and the duration of
morning stiffness for patients with moderate to severe disease. It
also improved the number of swollen and tender joints, allowing
patients to resume or more fully participate in daily activities.
</P>
<P>
   For Laura Sagen-Hughes, 49, the drug let her resume her normal
life pain-free for the first time since she began suffering
symptoms of arthritis 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable,'' said Sagen-Hughes, who was part of the
last stage of clinical testing for the drug in Seattle. ``Within
two days of my first injection, all my pain, swelling and
discomfort disappeared. I thought, `Whoa, whose body am I in?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The drug is given by injection using a needle similar to the one
diabetic patients use, she said. The twice-a-week shots are
painless, and the only side effects she experienced were
occasional, mild redness around the injection site.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies said they would examine the clinical data
before making decisions about coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Enbrel, which is expected to cost between $10,000 and $12,000 a
year, is more expensive than methotrexate, which costs about $2,500
a year, said Mease. But that comparison doesn't take into account
the costs of hospitalizing patients for side-effects and
complications of taking methotrexate, a chemotherapeutic agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you simply compare the two, it's an unfair comparison,'' he
said. The costs of the two drugs are actually ``a lot closer than
you might anticipate.''
</P>
<P>
   Some insurance companies have already indicated to Mease that
they will cover it, he said. ``Coverage is likely to depend upon a
rheumatologist's opinion on whether (the patient) is deemed an
Enbrel candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   The most likely candidates are those who have moderate to severe
disease and who have tried but not been helped by at least one
other drug, such as methotrexate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sagen-Hughes, for example, had tried methotrexate but couldn't
take the side effects, which can include nausea, mouth sores and
other complications.
</P>
<P>
   Immunex and its partner Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories will market
Enbrel in North America. The drug is only available by
prescription.
</P>
</TEXT>
