<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS WOULD FIT THE BILL AS VAUGHN REPLACEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ How to replace Mo Vaughn if he leaves?
</P>
<P>
   Well, while playing for the New York Yankees the last four
years, Bernie Williams has averaged .319, 24 home runs, and 95
RBIs, numbers that would have been even better if he hadn't missed
31 games with a leg injury this past season.
</P>
<P>
   He is a two-time All-Star, an American League batting champion,
and a Gold Glove center fielder, he passes with flying colors the
Friendly Fenway Family Values test, and he is an accomplished jazz
guitarist on the side, for those off-nights in which he might want
to do a gig in Harvard Square.
</P>
<P>
   At 30, he's also nine months younger than Vaughn (who turns 31
Dec. 15), he hits in Vaughn's No. 3 slot in the order, and he bats
from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   He does not have Vaughn's commanding presence in the clubhouse,
but he has always been liked and respected by his teammates, and,
like Vaughn, is noted for his candor, even if he delivers his
message in a much quieter fashion.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't throw the same fear into pitchers that a Vaughn does,
but his ability to deliver in the clutch is not to be dismissed: He
hit .335 with runners in scoring position last season, a number
better than any Red Sox regular, including Nomar Garciaparra (.329)
or Vaughn (.318).
</P>
<P>
   His agent, Scott Boras, offers another argument why Red Sox fans
should find Williams appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a double reason for signing a guy like Bernie,'' said
Boras. Monday ``You create a grand problem for your archenemy (the
Yankees) while improving yourself substantially.''
</P>
<P>
   So, where's the rub?
</P>
<P>
   Glad you asked. According to Boras, at least 10 teams so far
have expressed interest in Williams. Are the Red Sox on that list?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been asked not to say anything,'' said Boras.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is seeking a deal for a ``minimum'' of seven years,
according to Boras, and doesn't expect to be signing for an average
annual value south of Mike Piazza's number ($13 million a year).
</P>
<P>
   What this all means, of course, is that the Red Sox in all
likelihood would have to pay Williams more than it would take to
re-sign Vaughn. That's a pattern with which they're not unfamiliar.
This is the team, remember, that could not sign Roger Clemens
because the bidding became too rich for their tastes, then turned
around and signed Pedro Martinez a year later to the fattest
contract ever for a player until the (itals)piece de
Piazza.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo Vaughn will get a good contract,'' Boras said, ``but I
don't think anyone will give him seven years because of his body
type. Maybe he'll get five from somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   From Boras's perspective, what separates Williams from Vaughn is
that, outside of Ken Griffey and perhaps Andruw Jones, it's rare to
find a center fielder who is a run producer in Williams's class.
Put Vaughn among the slugger types who play first base, left field,
or DH, Boras said, and there are a number of players who can point
to similar production.
</P>
<P>
   Agent talk? Sure, to a degree. But the man makes a point, too,
which is why Williams may be in a position to name his price. Maybe
the only player better positioned in this free agent class is
pitcher Kevin Brown, who happens to be another Boras client. He's
looking for a six-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Boras expects that the Yankees will not give up Williams without
a fight, though published reports in New York say otherwise. Boras
expects the Orioles to be in the bidding, too. The Colorado Rockies
are said to be making a big push for both Williams and Brown, while
the Dodgers, who have targeted Vaughn as their top priority, could
be in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Boras does not expect Williams to make any snap decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still got a lot of work to do,'' said the agent.
</P>
<P>
   Boras said the Red Sox also have interest in another of his
clients, pitcher Tim Belcher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
