<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA: IF PRIMARY PLAN LOSES, STATE MAY, TOO  
 ALASKA: TWO CANDIDATES FOR THE PRICE OF ONE 
NEVADA: HAPPY APPALACHIAN BIDS A WARM HELLO
</HEADLINE>
   (See also ELN-RDP, ELN-CLINTON, ELN-NONVOTERS, ELN-REAPPORTION,
ELN-ILLINOIS, ELN-ATTACK-ADS, ELN-GORE) 
(nk) 
 By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Political contests, by definition, typically have a winner and a
loser. But in California, if final polls have it right, one of
Tuesday's contests is going to produce two losers: the Democratic
and Republican parties and, beyond that, maybe the whole state.
</P>
<P>
   On the ballot is an obscure proposal, labeled Proposition 3,
that calls for the state to revert to ``closed'' primaries, as
opposed to ``open'' primaries, when choosing presidential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The open system, which allows Republicans to vote for Democrats,
and vice versa, was adopted by the state two years ago, and is a
relative rarity in presidential politics. Both national parties
refuse to seat delegates chosen in open primaries, arguing that the
practice skews the political system.
</P>
<P>
   So if Proposition 3 fails, and it was behind by a margin of
roughly 2-to-1 in the final polls, California's Democratic and
Republican parties will have to come up with alternative voting
systems, like caucuses or conventions, for Election 2000.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not the half of it.
</P>
<P>
   If Proposition 3 fails, the state might as well junk its new
plan to become a bigger player in the presidential nominating game
by holding its primaries in early March, rather than in early June.
The date was advanced because the national primary system has
become so heavily front-loaded these days that any primary held
after May is essentially moot.
</P>
<P>
   But if the proposition fails, even a March primary would be
moot. The political parties may then go to court.
</P>
<P>
   Two Candidates For the Price of One
</P>
<P>
   No election contest in the country has been more topsy-turvy
than the Alaska governor's race. And the confusion seems likely to
continue through Election Day _ and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   It began on Day 1, when John Lindauer, a retired newspaper
publisher, jumped into the Republican primary and questions were
raised about whether he was a full-time resident of the state. He
convinced election officials that he was and won the August
primary.
</P>
<P>
   But then in early September, questions were raised about whether
Lindauer was violating state law by hiding the source of the money
he was using to go after Gov. Tony Knowles, the Democratic
incumbent. Again he persuaded officials, including party leaders,
who were threatening to withdraw support, that all was above board.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out in early October, however, that Lindauer was
bankrupt, and that his wife was funding his race. A citizen filed
suit to have him thrown off the ballot, and the Republican Party
withdrew its support, calling for a write-in campaign for state
Sen. Robin Taylor, the runner-up in the August primary.
</P>
<P>
   Then last Thursday, with polls showing Taylor splitting the GOP
vote with Lindauer, Republican officials had second thoughts. They
asked a state court to delay the election, arguing that if it was
held before all the confusion could be cleared up, Knowles would
win almost by default.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, the court ruled that the election should
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Happy Appalachian Bids a Warm Hello
</P>
<P>
   Good humor has not been one of the hallmarks of this fall's
politicking, and in the final hours of the campaign, there has been
some downright mean television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   But Nevada voters, even some Democrats, are getting a yuk from a
spot the state's Republican Party is running against Sen. Harry
Reid, a Democrat who is locked in a dead heat with his Republican
challenger, Rep. John Ensign.
</P>
<P>
   The ad says that Nevada sends $2 billion more to Washington in
taxes each year than the state gets back in federal expenditures or
programs. It blames the shortfall on the senator, asserting that he
votes to help the hard-pressed people of West Virginia, but not
those in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Whereupon a red-bearded hillbilly appears on screen, sitting in
front of a tin-roofed shack, exuberantly tossing fistfuls of
dollars into the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeeee-haaahh!'' he shouts. And across the screen flashes:
``Thank you from West Virginia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
