r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEAFSCHOOL-AZR &LR;      11-02 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAFSCHOOL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX SCHOOL USES TECHNOLOGY TO HELP DEAF STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LORI BAKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Candice Carlton lives in a world where her eyes must
do what her ears can't.
</P>
<P>
   Deaf since birth, the 11-year-old has to communicate by writing
and reading notes, using American Sign Language, or typing on a
special telephone text device.
</P>
<P>
   But Candice recently has been able to use her eyes in new ways
to help her excel at Phoenix Day School for the Deaf.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old school is among the first in the nation to
install technological tools for deaf and hard-of-hearing students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is an equalizer for students with special needs
because it opens up the world through various types of
communication,'' said Lori Elliott, media and technology specialist
for the school.
</P>
<P>
   To practice math skills, Candice uses the Bowling for Numbers
computer program, which flashes a message saying whether her
answers to questions are correct. She soon will be practicing her
typing skills by exchanging e-mail messages with students around
the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of asking the teacher what's for lunch, Candice can
glance up at the television monitor in her classroom and see a text
message.
</P>
<P>
   Similar technology is being installed at the Tucson School for
the Deaf and Blind. Both schools are part of the Arizona State
Schools for the Deaf and the Blind.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Day, at 1935 W. Hayward Ave., serves about 300 preschool
to high school students who come from all over the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   During the past couple of years, about $500,000 worth of
state-funded equipment has been installed in the school's 60
classrooms, including a television monitor, a special phone system
and computers. Digital cameras and video cameras are shared among
classes.
</P>
<P>
   Some rooms also have FM listening systems to help
hard-of-hearing students more clearly hear their teachers through
their hearing aids.
</P>
<P>
   Internet access will be expanded to every classroom by December,
allowing students and teachers to e-mail one another at their
school and others worldwide. The school plans to have its own Web
site later in the school year.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Curry, who teaches fourth- and fifth-graders at the school,
is excited about the opportunities that the technologies provide
for students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do education without technology but it's motivating for
kids to use it,'' Curry said.
</P>
<P>
   She works on a statewide team of educators who train others in
using technology in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Second-grade teacher Kris Trainor, who is on the technology team
with Curry, brags about how her students were able to produce a
slide show with captioning for parents using a digital camera.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is technology helping students learn, it's giving
Phoenix Day a sense of unity.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, each classroom was isolated because there was no
way to communicate between rooms or from the classroom to outside
the campus.
</P>
<P>
   Now each classroom has phones equipped with voice and text
voice-mail systems. Text voice mail allows written messages to be
accessed or left at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has made life easier for students, teachers and
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 30 percent of our teachers being deaf or hard of hearing,
this makes it easier to communicate,'' said Gaby Sorenson, Phoenix
Day's principal. ``Before, if two deaf people wanted to communicate
they had to do it face to face or through notes.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many deaf schools use television sets to show videos
with closed captioning, Phoenix Day does much more with its
monitors.
</P>
<P>
   The monitors are the school's answer to the loudspeaker system
that regular schools use to make daily announcements or sound the
bell when it's time to change classes.
</P>
<P>
   On the television screen, text messages featuring the lunch
menu, school happenings and photos of students are shown throughout
the day. The universal clock on the screen allows students to know
when it's time to change classes. If there were an emergency, a
message would flash on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Day is one of a few deaf schools nationally that have
text messaging voice mail and television monitors in each
classroom, said Judy Harkins, director of Technology Assessment
Program at Gallaudet University in Washington, D.C., a university
designed for deaf students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unusual for schools for the deaf to have TTYs (phone
text systems) in every classroom,'' Harkins said. ``Most classrooms
don't have phones at all. The monitors also are rare and I would
think they would be preferable in hearing schools as well.'' &QL; 
Lori Baker can be reached at 444-7120 or at lori.baker(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
