<HEADER>
A0087 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-OHIOSTATE-COX     11-02 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OHIOSTATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BCS complicates bowl picture, but not for top team
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Most Ohio State players still do not fully
understand how the new Bowl Championship Series rankings are
determined but they do understand this: The Buckeyes are No. 1 this
week and in their eyes, that means all is right again in college
football.
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of scrunched noses and perplexed looks last
week when the Buckeyes were told they were No. 1 in the Associated
Press and USA Today /ESPN coaches' polls but No. 2 in the BCS
standings behind UCLA. Monday, when they were told they had jumped
to No. 1 in this week's BCS ratings, all of the number-crunching
seemed to make more sense to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were definitely disappointed we were No. 2 (last week),''
OSU quarterback Joe Germaine said. ``We definitely think of
ourselves as being a No. 1 team.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, so do the voters and the computers. OSU is first in the BCS
with 3.71 points, a lower total than last week. (The lower the
point total, the higher the rank.)
</P>
<P>
   Poll rankings, computer ratings, strength of schedule and
won-loss records each count 25 percent in determining the BCS
standings. The top two teams at the end of the season will be
invited to play in the national championship Fiesta Bowl Jan. 4 in
Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   A lackluster performance against a weak Stanford (1-7) team last
Saturday dropped UCLA in the polls and as a result in the BCS, from
No. 1 to No. 3 with 6.62 points. Tennessee, which features
Meadowdale High graduate Peerless Price at wide receiver, moved
into the No. 2 spot in the BCS (5.70 points) after its eighth
straight victory Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   OSU coach John Cooper said it's nice to be No. 1 across the
board. ``I'd rather be No. 1 than No. 2, 3 or 4,'' he said. ``But
I'm not going to worry about it like I didn't worry abut it last
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper still maintains that if OSU finishes the season
undefeated, the Buckeyes will play for a national championship. But
if UCLA, Tennessee and Ohio State each win the remainder of their
games, at least one undefeated team will be left out of the title
game. Kansas State, Wisconsin, Arkansas and Tulane also still have
shots at undefeated seasons. OSU offensive lineman Rob Murphy said
he just wants to make sure the Buckeyes stay on top of the heap.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we're there, I'm a happy kid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Germaine, too, said getting to the Fiesta Bowl is his main
focus. An emerging Heisman candidate and Arizona native, Germaine
said he thinks more about playing for a national title in his home
state than accepting the Heisman at the Downtown Athletic Club,
where the award is presented.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really all I think about in the back of my mind: Go to
Tempe and finish out the season there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If OSU and the rest of the teams vying for the top two spots
learned one thing about the complicated BCS this week it was this:
Squeezing out a victory against a weak opponent, as UCLA did
against Stanford, will cost you.
</P>
<P>
   Two of OSU's remaining three opponents are unranked: Michigan
State (4-4) on Saturday and Iowa (3-6) next week.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
