<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAPED GATES TESTIMONY SHOWN AT MICROSOFT TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   In two hours of videotaped questioning shown at the Microsoft
antitrust trial, chairman Bill Gates professed ignorance of several
key charges in the Government's suit, including allegations that he
was involved in plans to bully competitors like Apple Computer and
Netscape Communications to step back from Internet software markets
that Microsoft sought to dominate. When presented with e-mail
messages he had written, he often said he did not recognize the
messages or recall the discussions surrounding them, prompting, at
times, even the presiding judge to chuckle and shake his head.
</P>
<P>
   IMPASSE AT FEDERAL EXPRESS
</P>
<P>
   A top executive at Federal Express warned that the company was
on the verge of losing several large customers during the peak
holiday season because of a threatened strike by its pilots. The
disclosure came after the latest round of negotiations between the
company and the Fedex Pilots Association broke down late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   FDA APPROVES SANGSTAT DRUG
</P>
<P>
   Sangstat Medical Corp. said the Food and Drug Administration had
approved its immune-suppressant drug, Sangcya, for preventing organ
rejection in transplant patients, and for the treatment of
rheumatoid arthritis and psoriasis. Sangstat said it would
introduce the drug within a month and would be priced 20 percent
below an equivalent drug, Neoral, made by Novartis.
</P>
<P>
   DANONE BUYS U.S. BOTTLER
</P>
<P>
   Groupe Danone announced that it was buying Aqua Penn Spring
Water for $112 million, or $13 a share, which sent Aqua Penn's
shares up 30 percent. The move gives Groupe Danone of Paris access
to three spring-water sources in Florida, California and
Pennsylvania in addition to the Utah and Quebec springs it now uses
for its Dannon brand of bottled water, which is distributed
nationwide. It also links Danone for the first time to big
customers like McDonald's, where Aqua Penn sells bottled water in
some areas, and doubles the company's production capacity in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   NEW SIGNS OF ECONOMIC WEAKNESS
</P>
<P>
   The latest evidence of slower economic growth showed that United
States manufacturing was weaker last month than at any time in more
than two and a half years and that consumer income weakened in
September as the savings rate turned negative for the first time in
40 years.
</P>
<P>
   TOWER REALTY SALE COLLAPSES
</P>
<P>
   Crescent Real Estate Equities, an investment trust controlled by
the billionaire Richard Rainwater, and Reckson Associates Realty
have called off their $734 million joint purchase of the New York
office developer Tower Realty Trust, Tower said.
</P>
<P>
   UPDATE AT LONDON EXCHANGE
</P>
<P>
   The London International Financial Futures and Options Exchange,
under pressure to make its trading system faster and cheaper,
announced a sweeping reorganization intended to cut its operating
costs in half by the end of next year. The changes will mean a loss
of 600 of its 1,000 jobs. The announcement was the latest
indication that the exchange is under growing pressure _
predominantly from the new German-Swiss Eurex futures exchange _ to
accelerate its move toward screen-based trading and away from the
slower and more costly open-outcry system.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPS TO CLOSE FACTORIES
</P>
<P>
   Royal Philips Electronics, the Dutch manufacturing giant, said
it would close up to one-third of its plants by 2002 to create a
leaner company and adapt to a difficult world economy. The
announcement, while troubling for the Philips work force of
256,000, seemed to be welcomed by investors. Shares of Philips rose
9 percent in Amsterdam. On the New York Stock Exchange, shares of
Philips jumped $4.5625, to $59.8125.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
