A0097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-COLUMN03-COX     11-02 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Today's vote a bellwether for blacks
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's hard to think of an election of greater import to
African-American voters in Georgia _ one in which they've been able
to vote, at least _ than the one being held today.
</P>
<P>
   This is true only in part because three black Democratic
candidates are on the statewide ticket for the first time _ and
none of them appear to have their races locked up going into
Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   The presence on the ballot of Thurbert Baker, Michael Thurmond
and Henrietta Canty represents progress, but of an uncharismatic
sort. There hasn't seemed to be a great wellspring of enthusiasm
among black voters for the attorney general who's prosecuting Ralph
David Abernathy III, the labor commissioner candidate who
spearheaded welfare changes and the insurance commissioner
candidate who's been serving in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the defeat of all three, if that happens, will in
all likelihood be taken as a stunning setback to black political
ambitions and prompt sober reassessments of how much political
progress has really been made in the state.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this year's election even more critical is that
whoever is elected governor will hold veto power over the next
redistricting map, which will set the course of state politics well
into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   That veto will be particularly important to African-American
voters because the ground rules for how political power is to be
apportioned are much less clear heading into the 2000 census than
they were a decade ago, when the U.S. Justice Department mandated
the creation of new black-majority districts at the congressional
and legislative levels.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has the U.S. Supreme Court rejected some of the
principles on which the redistricting of the early 1990s was based,
but an unprecedented partisan battle is already raging over how the
next census is to be conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Every redistricting session comes down to hard choices, but
that's especially so for the next governor. He will have the final
say on a plan that is supposed to dole out political power fairly
to all groups, with fewer guidelines about what it means to be
fair.
</P>
<P>
   Summing up, it's an election in which black people have more to
lose than to gain, in races that don't spark very emotional chords.
But the way in which this year's campaign has been conducted may
provide some of that spark.
</P>
<P>
   However white voters perceive the breathless Guy Millner ad
calling Roy Barnes a ``liar'' about affirmative action, or Mitch
Skandalakis's characterization of Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell as an
incompetent boob, or the polls that indicate a little-known,
75-year-old candidate could beat Thurmond, they are likely to be
enough to affront many black voters who might not otherwise have
seen much reason to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlanta Mayor Maynard Jackson, appearing on WCLK radio's
``Morning Jazz'' show Monday to urge listeners to turn out,
compared black voters to the kid who's tormented by the schoolyard
bully until he or she fights back _ which in his exhortation meant
to show up at the polls today.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they vote the way he advises or not, Jackson is
essentially correct. A low turnout in predominantly black
precincts, on a day when so much is at stake, sends a message to
both parties that diminishes respect for African-American votes.
What's most important for black Georgians today, who they vote for
is not as important as whether they show up.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution political editor Tom Baxter
provides opinion, analysis and commentary in his column.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
