<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Tuesday, Nov. 3, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Marcus Chan at 415-777-8443 or
Catherine Laidlaw at 415-777-6057.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WELLS _  &LR; Wells Fargo &AMP; Co.'s $32 billion merger with Minneapolis'
Norwest Corp took effect yesterday, as the second of San
Francisco's two historic financial institutions was swept away in
the merger wave rolling through the banking industry. By Sam
Zuckerman
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GAP _  &LR; Just in time for the holidays, San Francisco's Gap Inc.
is upping its investment in the World Wide Web by adding two new
digital stores and launching its first television commercials
devoted to online sales. By Carol Emert
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WINDRIVER _ &LR;  As microchips become ubiquitous, so too does the
computer software that tells the chips what to do. That presents a
tremendous opportunity for fast-growing Wind River Systems of
Alameda, which makes the software that runs the chips in cars,
cameras, telephones and dozens of other everyday devices.
</P>
<P>
   Yet where there's opportunity in the software market, Microsoft
Corp. usually looms _ and that presents the biggest risk for Wind
River. By Dan Fost
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SYQUEST _  &LR; Syquest Technology, a disk drive-maker that has
wallowed in red ink for three years, suspended operations
yesterday, throwing as many as 900 people out of work. By David
Einstein
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIO _ &LR;  A Menlo Park biotech firm has received permission to
start selling the first generic form of cyclosporine, the drug that
kidney, lung and heart transplant patients must take twice a day to
live with their donated organs. SangStat Medical Corp. said
yesterday the Food and Drug Administration has rated its
cyclosporine drug, called SangCya, as the functional equivalent of
Neoral, the drug now used by most of the 140,000 transplant
patients in the United States. By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIGITAL _ &LR;  When the votes are counted tonight, some of the most
anxious spectators will be the Harris pollsters who hope to make
election history by predicting 32 races based on surveys of
Internet users. By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; MAPS _  &LR; Once in a while, a piece of software comes along that
really underscores the power of the personal computer in a
refreshing way. National Geographic Maps is such a program.
</P>
<P>
   It's a collection of eight CD-ROMs containing every foldout map
in the 109-year history of National Geographic magazine _ more than
500 of them. By David Einstein
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OVEN _ &LR;  Silicon Valley technology has put hundreds of millions
of transistors on a microchip and connected the world through the
Internet. Now it's roasting chickens and baking biscuits. By Carol
Emert
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A _ &LR;  What's the true status with online security
these days? Is it good enough so I don't have to worry about giving
my credit card number online? By computer columnist David Einstein
</P>
</TEXT>
