speaking at a campaign stop at a Polish Senior Center in Yonkers on
Monday. New York Gov. George Pataki looks on in the background.
D'Amato is in the midst of a hotly contested battle to keep his job
against Democratic opponent Rep. Charles Schumer. (Andrea Mohin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) OTTAWA, Ill. -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- ELN-NONVOTERS, 11-2 --
Dedra Phillips, right, who works as a quality analyst for a cookie
company, and Jerry Hanck, a 60-year-old liquor salesman, both say
they will not vote on Tuesday. For all the handicapping about the
races between Democrats and Republicans, there is little doubt what
a majority of Americans will effectively choose: none of the above.
(Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) BOSTON -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- BOSTON-BOOM-2, 11-2 --
Tourists and residents alike can now see Boston by land and by
water on the amphibious vehicles operated by Duck Tours, a new city
attraction. Boston's resurgence is seen by many urban experts as
spearheading a hopeful trend among aging northern cities emerging
from decades of decay. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) CHICAGO -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- ELN-ILLINOIS, 11-2 -- Sen.
Carol Mosely-Braun greeted commuters at the Northwestern Train
station in Chicago on Monday. Moseley-Braun stuck close to her
hometown on Monday, playing to her Democratic political base in an
eleventh-hour attempt to keep her job. (Todd Buchanan/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BOSTON -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- BOSTON-BOOM, 11-2 -- Boston's
resurgence is seen by many urban experts as spearheading a hopeful
trend among aging northern cities emerging from decades of decay.
Several cranes are seen at work at the Millenium Construction
Project near Boston's Chinatown which includes an office building,
stores and a hotel.(Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ALBANY, N.Y.-- Nov. 2, 1998 -- ELN-NY-SENATE, 11-2 --
Rep. Charles Schumer, right, the Democratic Party candidate for
Senate, smiles as first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton waves to
supporters during a campaign rally in Albany on Monday. The hotly
contested U.S. Senate election between Sen. Alphonse D'Amato and
Schumer drew to its final hours Monday. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BEIJING -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- BEIJING-BICYCLES, 11-2 --
Although sturdy bicycles remain the primary transportation for the
vast majority of Beijingers, their powerful gas-guzzling cousins
have been multiplying rapidly, literally edging cyclists off the
road. China's Xisidong Avenue was the first street in Beijing to
ban bicycles. A government worker with a megaphone turned away
cyclists from the avenue, instructing them to take other routes.
(Elisabeth Rosenthal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WALDFORD, Md. -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- MILITARY-RECRUITER,
11-2 -- Navy Recruiter Joseph A. Willis Jr. discusses enlisting in
the Navy with 18-year-old William Waldron in Waldford. Recruiting
young men and women into the nation's all-volunteer military has
never been easy, but the military now faces a crisis in recruiting
that has been building for some time and, many commanders fear,
could very well get worse. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) HOBOKEN, N.J. -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- MACYS-PARADE-BALLOONS,
11-2 -- With Clifford, the Big Red Dog hovering above, nearly 100
volunteers for Macy's Thanksgiving Day parade honed their
ballooning skills Monday in a soccerfield in Hoboken. After last
year's disastrous parade, when high winds played havoc with the
balloons and a spectator was seriously hurt after an out-of-control
Cat in the Hat sent part of a lamppost plunging to the street,
Macy's, under strong pressure from the city, has revamped its
procedures. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- NY-FASHION-3, 11-02 --
William Calvert's show had a roped off an area where the models
mingled and chatted. With this red dress, Calvert uses masterly
seaming that allowed the dresses to flow gracefully over the body,
outlining the figure without constricting it. Robert Danes kept the
lines of his dresses simple but relied on tasteful decoration, like
this lacy openwork over the neckline. (Corina Lecca/New York Times
Photos) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- NY-FASHION-2, 11-02 -- David
Rodriguez pairs well-cut tailored jackets with layered sheer skirts
for a play of hard against soft. Rodriguez uses these so-called
``shadowfold'' designs on the front of this jacket. Unlike much of
the origami pleating other designers have been using, these
shadowfolds are flat, like appliques, not bulky or awkward.
(Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- NY-FASHION-1, 11-02 -- From
Russell Bennett, right, an apron of different sizes and materials
over shirts and long full skirts, layered black tulle over voile,
and decorated white cotton with delicate threadwork. (Corina
Lecca/New York Times Photo) Anait Bian, left, shows panels of
pleats on the side of skirts with a sleveless jacket on an angle.
(Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- ELN-CLINTON, 11-2 -- After
a campaign season distinguished more by President Clinton's
tribulations than by any raging national issues, Americans will
head to the polls on Tuesday in a mid-term election that will
inevitably be interpreted as a referendum on the fate of the
president. At a White House event Monday, President Clinton urged
voters to elect congressional candidates sympathetic to his
``Patient's Bill of Rights'' that calls for tougher restrictions on
managed-care organizations. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- OPERA-REVIEW-VIXEN, 11-2
--Robin Blitch Wiper performs in the title role of ``The Cunning
Little Vixen'' at the New York City Opera. Janacek's operas, once
the province of curiosity seekers, are gradually finding the place
in the repertory that they deserve. This one is the tale of a young
vixen and her encounters in both the village and the forest, the
characters and situations defined by a magnificent score. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PORTLAND, Ore. -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- HEALTH-EYE-LASER, 11-2
-- Authorities now expect laser surgery to be available for the
farsighted next year, adding to the more than 400,000 who annually
have the procedure for nearsightedness. The proposal is pending
before the FDA. Dr. Scott MacRae, associate professor of
ophthalmology at the Casey Eye Institute at the Oregon Health
Sciences University in Portland, holds part of the laser equipment
he uses to correct his patients vision. (John Gress/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- SCI-ZOO-NATURE-2, 11-2 --
Sometime in mid-December, Timmy and Dan, two silverback male
gorillas, and their respective troops will move into new quarters
at New York's Bronx Zoo, in an environment designed by scientists
and animal experts to resemble a central African rain forest, the
animals' natural habitat. In the new Congo Gorilla Forest, the
public will enter through a hollow tree. (Norman Y. Lono/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Nov. 2, 1998 -- SCI-ZOO-NATURE-1, 11-2 --
Sometime in mid-December, Timmy and Dan, two silverback male
gorillas, and their respective troops will move into new quarters
at New York's Bronx Zoo, in an environment designed by scientists
and animal experts to resemble a central African rain forest, the
animals' natural habitat. Lee Emkhe, the project manager, shows a
