</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 New Browsers Offer Excellent Online Security  &HT;       
 By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &LR; What's the true status with online security these days? Is it &LR; 
 &LR; good enough so I don't have to worry about giving my credit &LR;   &LR; card
number online? &LR;
<P>
   A: Shopping on the Internet has always been at least as safe as
giving your credit card number over the phone to somebody you don't
know. And the latest encryption technology makes it extremely safe.
</P>
<P>
   Most shopping sites alert you with a warning box when you enter
a secure area to order a product. In addition, you'll see a closed
padlock on the status bar in newer versions of the Netscape and
Microsoft browsers, assuring you that your connection is secure.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean, however, that you can't get fleeced on the
Web. The wisest course is to shop with companies that have solid
reputations for reliability.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, if you're on America Online, you can shop with total
peace of mind, because AOL guarantees security when you buy from
its certified merchants.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Q: Help. My dad was fooling around on my computer and
accidentally reduced Windows Explorer from two viewing panes to
one. Now when I open the Explorer in Windows 98, I can only see the
file tree. When I double-click a folder to open it, I hear the
opening sound but nothing is displayed. Any suggestions for a
solution?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's what you get for letting dad mess with your PC. He
probably shrank the Windows Explorer window by using the mouse to
drag a side border of the window inward. When you do that (whether
you drag the left or right border), the window shrinks from its
right side, hiding the pane that shows the contents of folders. And
as you've discovered, once the window is shrunk, it stays that way
even if you reboot the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I've scared you, here's an easy way to restore Windows
Explorer to its original size, and restore harmony to your family.
Just drag either the left or right border outward until you can
view both panes again.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Your dad may have inadvertently shrunk the window while
trying to drag it out of the way of something else on the screen.
Tell him that to move a window, you should drag it from the blue
border on the top.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a way to print out a sample of all the fonts
available to me on my computer? I'm running Windows 98 with
Microsoft Word.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: A number of programs available on the Internet do exactly
what you're talking about. Two that I like are ListFonts, which is
free, and Win32 Font Lister, which you can try for free, and buy
for $5 if you like it. Both programs can easily print out a list of
all your fonts in any type size you wish. You can find them in
ZDNet's software library at  &LR; www.hotfiles.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've pretty much cleansed Windows 95 of Internet Explorer so
I can use Netscape Communicator unimpeded. My son recently acquired
a new computer with Windows 98 pre-installed. We wonder if it is
safe to attempt the same procedure with Win98, or is Internet
Explorer so intricate and deeply embedded that it would disable
Win98 to remove it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sorry, Charlie. Internet Explorer is sunk into Windows 98
like Excalibur into the stone. According to Microsoft's own online
support library, ``Explorer is an integrated part of the operating
system and cannot be removed from Windows 98.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMAC UPDATE: &LR;  A couple of weeks ago, I gave some
recommendations for ways to transfer files from Macintoshes to the
new iMac _ which for some reason known only to Steve Jobs doesn't
have a floppy disk drive. Alternatives I suggested including using
an Ethernet connection, or transferring between modems. I also gave
the address for a Web site called FreeDrive ( &LR; www.freedrive.com &LR; )
that lets you upload files from your Mac to the Web, then download
them to your iMac _ sort of like a virtual disk drive.
</P>
<P>
   A reader alerted me to another site, iMacFloppy.com
( &LR; www.imacfloppy.com &LR; ) that does the same thing. Both sites are
free and can be used to store data as well as transfer it.
</P>
<P>
   And here's yet another option. Send files to yourself as e-mail
attachments using your Mac, then use your iMac to read the mail and
download the files.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Searching the Intranet can be frustrating, because simple search
words can turn up millions of results. For more precision, use the
advanced searching options that most of the major search engines
offer. Some engines have special forms for advanced searching, and
they all support Boolean logic, which lets you use words like
``and'' and ``not'' to narrow a search.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to  &LR; computers(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
