<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OVEN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Silicon Valley's Take on the Easy-Bake Oven  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Silicon Valley technology has put hundreds of millions of
transistors on a microchip and connected the world through the
Internet. Now it's roasting chickens and baking biscuits.
<P>
   The Flashbake oven, developed by a former Stanford Research
Institute scientist, is the first real oven to cook mostly with
light _ specifically, eight tungsten halogen lamps.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind this microprocessor-controlled high-tech wonder,
the product of $20 million in development funding, is similar to
that of the old Easy-Bake _ a toy oven powered by a lightbulb.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only real difference between the Easy-Bake and the
Flashbake is the spectral shift,'' said Bill Minnear, chief
technology officer of Fremont's Quadlux Inc., which makes the
Flashbake.
</P>
<P>
   The Flashbake's lightbulbs are much more powerful than the
Easy-Bake's, and they use more deep-penetrating, infrared rays,
Minnear said.
</P>
<P>
   The Flashbake, which is about the size of a microwave, does not
require preheating, and its flickering bulbs _ four on the top and
four on the bottom _ cook many foods in half the time of a
conventional oven.
</P>
<P>
   The oven can do some things a microwave can't do, such as brown
meat and baked goods, and warm bread without making it chewy. It
defrosts more slowly than a microwave, however, and it cannot cook
in plastic because its temperatures get too high. It does work with
metal and Pyrex cookware.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than setting a temperature, the Flashbake user chooses
from cook modes such as bake, grill and reheat, which have been
programmed to send different amounts of power to the food during
the cook cycle.
</P>
<P>
   In bake mode, for example, the oven delivers a lot of energy at
the beginning, when dough is wet, and less as it cooks. At the end,
the oven sends a spurt of rays to the surface for browning, unless
the user tells it not to.
</P>
<P>
   Power levels are determined in part by an electronic eye on the
bottom of the oven, which tells the oven's microprocessor whether
the pan's finish is shiny or dull. The oven sends more energy to a
light and shiny surface, which will deflect many rays, than to a
dark, opaque pan, which absorbs energy efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   The Flashbake uses less energy than a conventional oven because
it does not require preheating and it cooks more quickly, said
Clifford Adams, president and CEO of Quadlux. Microwaves use 5 to
10 percent less energy than the Flashbake, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Flashbake goes on sale at premium appliance dealers such as
the Contra Costa Appliance Center in Walnut Creek in mid-November
for a hefty $1,595 _ $1,695 for a built-in version.
</P>
<P>
   A small commercial Flashbake has been used by bars, restaurants
and convenience stores for five years, mostly for the quick baking
of pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think our penetration will be 4 percent to 5 percent of
households with more than $120,000 or so in annual income, which is
about 5.5 million households,'' said Adams, the former chief
operating officer of the Mondavi wine empire.
</P>
<P>
   The company intends to release a downscaled model in 2000 for
about half the price of today's Flashbake, Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   The current model, Flashbake/Wolf 120, is expected to appeal
mostly to well-to-do, two-income families who would like to be able
to cook a full meal quickly after work, Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   In focus groups, some consumers see the Flashbake as a microwave
replacement while others see it as an add-on to their existing set
of appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Flashbake's market would be bigger if it could make a
product to replace conventional ovens rather than microwaves. But
that is not technologically feasible, said Adams.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that halogen lights cannot withstand the
900-degree temperatures necessary for self-cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Another is that people prefer multirack ovens that can cook
several dishes at once. But although the hot air of a conventional
oven can circulate among different levels, the Flashbake's light
cannot. Installing multiple layers of lights would make the oven
prohibitively large, Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   The Flashbake was invented by Silicon Valley computer scientist
Gene Westerberg, who began developing it in 1985. He now is
Quadlux's vice president of technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
