<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYQUEST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Syquest Halts Operations, May File Chapter 11  &HT;       
 By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Syquest Technology, a disk drive-maker that has wallowed in red ink
for three years, suspended operations yesterday, throwing as many
as 900 people out of work.
<P>
   The company did not answer telephone calls to its Fremont
headquarters, limiting its communication to a brief press release
in which it said it may seek to reorganize under Chapter 11
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Syquest has asked Nasdaq to halt trading its stock, which was
valued at just 34 cents _ down from $4 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The capitulation came as no surprise, given the steady erosion
of Syquest's finances. In July, the company enlisted CIBC
Oppenheimer to try to find a partner or suitor. In August, it fired
950 workers _ half its workforce _ and halted manufacturing in
Fremont. The current number and location of Syquest's employees
could not be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Syquest was caught between falling prices for its
products, intensive competition from rival Iomega, and softness in
the personal computer market earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised at all,'' said analyst Howard Rosencrans of
HD Brouse &AMP; Co. ``The handwriting's been on the wall for several
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosencrans said the management of Chairman Ed Marinaro and CEO
Edwin Harper never had a chance to turn around Syquest after
inheriting ``unfixable problems'' from previous CEO Syed Iftikar
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extremely capital-intensive business, and their
financial situation didn't allow them to be viable,'' Rosencrans
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, Syquest put its money on removable disk drives
that let users transfer about 100 megabytes of information from one
computer to another. But the company's products quickly fell behind
similar Zip drives marketed by Iomega.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Syquest attempted a comeback with a removable drive
that held more data, but it, too, failed to catch on.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the company lost $68.7 million on sales of $122.72
million, which was down from a peak of nearly $300 million in 1995.
In its latest quarter, Syquest reported a loss of $42 million on
earnings of $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   Syquest said it plans to maintain limited support for its
customers but did not offer details. The company also did not say
whether it will retain any employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
