<SLUG> BC-WELLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Wells, Norwest Deal Done  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Wells Fargo &AMP; Co.'s $32 billion merger with Minneapolis' Norwest
Corp took effect yesterday, as the second of San Francisco's two
historic financial institutions was swept away in the merger wave
rolling through the banking industry.
<P>
   The combined institution, the nation's seventh-largest bank, is
keeping the Wells Fargo name and maintaining its headquarters in
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hazen, Wells Fargo's top executive, remains chairman. But
he ceded the chief executive post, and effective control of the
bank, to Norwest Chief Executive Richard Kovacevich.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction took the form of a Norwest acquisition of Wells
Fargo, with stockholders of the California bank receiving 10
Norwest shares for each share they hold. The bank uses Wells
Fargo's WFC stock symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Finalization of this latest merger marks a sea change in
California's banking scene.
</P>
<P>
   Within the space of a few weeks, Wells Fargo and its larger
rival BankAmerica Corp. have disappeared as independent
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation's largest banks raced to set up sprawling
multistate operations, bigger in scale than all but a handful of
existing banks, both Wells Fargo and BofA feared they would be left
behind. To remain competitive, they chose to merge with powerful
out-of-state institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite proclaiming their transactions ``mergers of equals,''
both banks agreed to be junior partners in what in fact were
corporate takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the new owner took the name of its California
partner, but the similarities end there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the headquarters remains in our city really
changes the dynamic,'' said San Francisco Supervisor Michael Yaki,
a critic of the BofA merger. ``We have a much higher comfort level
with Wells.''
</P>
<P>
   The differences in large measure reflect the buyers' sharply
different styles.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts describe BofA's new owner, North Carolina's NationsBank
Corp., and its CEO Hugh McColl as brutally effective acquirers.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank quickly flexed its muscle, appropriating key jobs,
including the top California retail banking position, for its own
people. It blamed the old BofA for investment and trading losses,
and sacked the bank's CEO David Coulter days after the merger took
effect.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Norwest is viewed as a more benevolent owner that
is trying to win over _ and not run over _ its new people. Analysts
described Kovacevich as a motivator who sees his prime task as
keeping the salesmanship and enthusiasm of employees at a high
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first acts of the combined bank was to announce
awards of 200 stock options to all of its more than 100,000
full-and part-time employees. Holders can exercise the options
withing five years if the combined bank's stock rises above $70 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   The new bank's stock closed yesterday unchanged at $37.19.
Still, there's no doubt who's in charge, as evidenced by
announcements of the departures last month of three of Wells
Fargo's top executives, including chief credit officer Michael
Gillfillan.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, many employees will lose their jobs. Analysts
estimated the new bank would cut several thousand jobs, including
roughly 1,300 in San Francisco and 800 in Minneapolis as duplicate
headquarters functions are closed.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest veteran Larry Haeg, top spokesman for the combined bank,
said he didn't know how many jobs would disappear. Cuts would take
place over two years, he said, during which time the bank will
carry out a ``retain and retrain'' program to find new positions
for displaced workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a slash-and-burn merger,'' Haeg said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the thorniest issue at the new Wells Fargo is how to
combine the two banks' distinct cultures and business strategies.
</P>
<P>
   The old Wells Fargo thrived by being leaner and meaner than
rivals. It cut back traditional branches and personal service in
favor of cheaper, automated ways of handling customers, such as
ATMs, telephone and Internet banking.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Norwest emphasizes sales and service more than
efficiency on the principle that adding revenue is more profitable
than slashing overhead. It views its traditional branches, which it
prefers to call ``stores,'' as its main outlet for reaching
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Norwest ``runs a people-driven business where the focus is on
revenue,'' said Jay Tejera, a Minneapolis-based analyst with the
brokerage Dain Rauscher.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo employees may benefit as the bank shifts to the
Norwest business model, Tejera said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of having to do more with less, they may find they
have more resources to do their job,'' he said.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
