<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAPS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Century of National Geographic maps unfold on the PC  &HT;       
 By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Once in a while, a piece of software comes along that really
underscores the power of the personal computer in a refreshing way.
National Geographic Maps is such a program.
<P>
   It's a collection of eight CD-ROMs containing every foldout map
in the 109-year history of National Geographic magazine _ more than
500 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Published by Mindscape, the Novato division of the Learning Co.,
it carries a list price of $79.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the significance of National Geographic Maps, it
helps to know a little history. The National Geographic Society
probably has done more to further the science ( &LR; and art) &LR;  of
mapmaking than anyone this century.
</P>
<P>
   Maps accompanying National Geographic magazines have played
significant roles far beyond the pleasure they have given readers.
A 1944 map, Germany and Its Approaches, served as a key reference
for Allied troops on their march to Berlin, and Winston Churchill
used it as his official briefing map. Today, a copy hangs on the
wall of the historic War Rooms below Whitehall in London.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1969, at the height of the space race, National
Geographic brought out the first map showing the entire lunar
surface on a single piece of paper, including the dark side, which
had been viewed for the first time only recently by astronauts
circling the moon.
</P>
<P>
   A map appearing in November 1988 was touted as the most accurate
and detailed relief rendering ever made of Mount Everest. A
multinational team created the map using satellite images and
photographs taken from a special jet that flew over the towering
mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Many National Geographic maps, depicting geography, history and
natural science, have become standard teaching tools in schools
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Creating National Geographic Maps posed both technological and
practical problems. Many of the older maps _ the oldest, depicting
the Ashville, N.C., area, dates from 1889 _ were in poor shape. Yet
they had to be transported from the National Geographic Society's
archives in Washington, D.C., to Kansas, where they were digitized
using large flatbed scanners. To ensure their safety, they were
carried in special wooden crates.
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge was in creating a search engine so users could
look for specific maps by keywords, geographic location or theme.
To accomplish this, the Society's cartographers created a system of
coordinates known as a bingo grid. They then identified major
locations on maps, assigned number and letter coordinates to them
and indexed them so they could be searched. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The result is a product that preserves the beauty of the
original maps while going beyond them, bringing the power of the PC
to bear on what once were just pieces of paper. With National
Geographic Maps you can zoom in through a number of levels of
magnification and pan around a map to pinpoint an area of interest.
</P>
<P>
   The only major drawback is the size of the average PC monitor,
which cannot encompass most of the original maps. But you can print
out any map at its normal size using a technique that divides the
map into sections, each one taking up a standard piece of printer
paper. You have to put the sections together to get a complete map.
If you have a printer capable of photographic quality, your printed
map will rival the original.
</P>
<P>
   Also frustrating is the large number of CDs. They are divided
according to type of map _ history, geography, environment. But you
can't browse the contents of each disc. You're stuck using the
search engine, which tells you which disc contains the maps you're
looking for. Fortunately, you can use the search engine without
changing discs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Even more discs would have been required but for some clever
compression technology that shrinks a 200-megabyte map down to just
7 MB.
</P>
<P>
   Mindscape officials said that if the program is a financial
success, the company will put it on DVD, just as it has done with
its collection of National Geographic magazines. That would shrink
the number of discs to just two.
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic Maps includes multimedia tours of nine
topics, including space and peoples of the past. And there are
features about milestones in mapping history, as well as milestones
for National Geographic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
