<SLUG> BC-GAP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Gap Fills In Web Presence, Plans 2 New Online Shops  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Just in time for the holidays, San Francisco's Gap Inc. is upping
its investment in the World Wide Web by adding two new digital
stores and launching its first television commercials devoted to
online sales.
<P>
   The ventures _ sales and information sites for babyGap
 &LR; (www.babygap.com &LR; ) and GapKids ( &LR; www.gapkids.com &LR; ) _ represent a
bigger commitment to Web commerce by the country's largest
specialty retailer even as Web analysts predict a doubling of
online sales this holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released yesterday, Jupiter Communications forecast
sales of $2.3 billion on the Web this November and December, up
from an estimated $1.1 billion in 1997's holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Apparel, once thought to be the least-popular commodity to be
sold via the Web, is one of the top growth areas this year, along
with toys and consumer electronics, said Nicole Vanderbilt, a
Jupiter analyst who expects apparel sales to more than triple this
year to about $70 million from $18 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Gap, which already operates a sales and information site for its
main chain of adult stores ( &LR; www.gap.com &LR; ) is ``making a real
commitment to (Web retailing),'' said Marcia Aaron, an analyst in
the San Francisco office of Bankers Trust New York.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, Gap's Web sales, which it refuses to disclose,
are certainly a tiny percentage of the company's total. But ``if we
didn't think it was a viable part of our future, we wouldn't do
it,'' said Michael McCadden, executive vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Gap launched Gap.com in December 1996 and started taking orders
last November. GapKids.com went up in March 1997 but was not
``commerce-enabled'' until yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``What we really wanted to do was find out the tricks of
navigation for one online store and find out what (our customers)
want before we went full tilt'' with multiple sites, McCadden said.
</P>
<P>
   Also yesterday, Gap launched its first Web-oriented TV ads, in
San Francisco and Chicago, which carry the tag line
``surf.shop.ship.'' Signs bearing the same tag line were posted in
the windows of Gap's 1,500 domestic stores.
</P>
<P>
   The company will monitor its Web visits from the two test cities
during the next month to determine whether the ads are effective in
driving people to its sites, McCadden said. He declined to release
the cost of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gap has been laying groundwork for its Web business with outdoor
ads featuring made-up words like ``Webology'' and ``Geektronica''
that have appeared on billboards since September.
</P>
<P>
   The company's goal on the Web is to facilitate spending by
making the process as easy as possible, said McCadden.
</P>
<P>
   Surfers can order merchandise on all three sites and pay for it
in one order. Unlike most Web businesses, which cannot ship
merchandise bought in a single transaction to multiple addresses,
orders can be sent to as many as three different addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Gap will evaluate the performance of its Web sites through
Christmas before deciding whether to put its Old Navy and Banana
Republic stores online, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The next logical step _ Web sales to customers outside the
United States _ is still down the road, said McCadden. ``You have
to have a system set up to mail and track packages around the
world. We want to get the first steps of the process really solid
before we take on the rest of the world,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
