r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON &LR;      11-02 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 This Election Night, the Internet Could Turn Out to Be a
Big  Winner  By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
When the votes are counted tonight, some of the most anxious
spectators will be the Harris pollsters who hope to make election
history by predicting 32 races based on surveys of Internet users.
<P>
   Currently, the vast majority of scientific polls are done by
phone. The whole polling industry will be waiting to see whether a
Harris poll released yesterday can accurately call Senate and
gubernatorial elections in 16 states, including California, based
on responses to surveys done by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been skeptical because we're not sure Internet users are
representative of the general populace,'' said Mark DiCamillo, who
runs California's Field Poll. ``But if their methods are
successful, it would open up a new frontier.''
</P>
<P>
   Modern polling began in 1936. The key character, said University
of Rochester political scientist Richard Niemi, was a social
scientist by the name of George Gallup.
</P>
<P>
   Gallup then was a young maverick who believed that a few hundred
people, sampled at random, could predict election outcomes more
accurately than the millions of people who responded to the mass
surveys of the day.
</P>
<P>
   In that era, newspapers and magazines asked their readers to
mail in survey forms. The most prestigious mass survey was
conducted by a magazine called Literary Digest. In 1936, 2 million
Digest readers picked Alf Landon as the next president of the
United States. When Gallup's sample picked Franklin Delano
Roosevelt, it put scientific polling on the map.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 40 years, scientific polling was a door-to-door
affair. Pollsters choose neighborhoods that represented the income,
racial and age characteristics of voters. Then they knocked on,
say, every other door in a neighborhood and asked questions.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s and '70s, social scientists began experimenting
with phone surveys. In retrospect, phone surveys seem like a
no-brainer because they were cheaper and faster than face-to-face
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the conservative nature of pollsters, it took more
than a decade for the phone to replace face-to-face surveys. ``When
I first came to work for Merv Field in 1978, he sent me door to
door in the Marina district,'' DiCamillo recalled.
</P>
<P>
   University of California at Santa Barbara political scientist
Bruce Bimber said phone surveys ultimately triumphed because they
provide pollsters with a universe in which almost everyone from the
Archie Bunkers to the Murphy Browns stand an equal chance of being
selected in a random sample.
</P>
<P>
   Forget picking numbers from a phone book. Pollsters generate
numbers using computer programs that contain every area code and
prefix. The programs add the last four digits randomly, so people
with unlisted numbers can get called.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central problem with Internet surveys is that there is no
way to randomly identify people,'' Bimber said.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the fact that only 40 percent of U.S. adults have
Internet access. By comparison, more than 90 percent of U.S.
households have phones.
</P>
<P>
   George Terhanian, director of Internet research at Harris, said
his company thinks that it can work around these shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Terhanian believes that Internet users are more like the U.S.
populace than generally is understood. Since 1995, he's tracked
Internet use through the Harris Poll. Each month, Harris phones a
random sample of Americans to ask questions about everyday life.
These polls show that women are online almost as much as men and
that 11 percent of blacks have Internet access, close to their 13
percent share of the U.S. population.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Internet users represent all Americans, Terhanian knows
he can't get a random sample because there is no central directory
of Net users.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he's built a database of 1.3 million Internet users.
Most are people who entered online sweepstakes sponsored by
Matchlogic, an Internet startup recently acquired by Excite.
</P>
<P>
   These people have agreed to answer political surveys by e-mail
and have provided information about their age, income, state of
residence.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 80,000 Net users in California volunteered to
participate in the Harris Poll. Terhanian selected 5,375 of them,
chosen to reflect the state's populace, as his survey group. His
theory is that if his Internet sample is weighted to represent the
state's populace, his predictions will be as accurate as phone
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Based on his Internet sample, Harris predicted yesterday that
Gray Davis will trounce Dan Lungren in the governor's race by a
ration of 53 percent to 42 percent, while incumbent Barbara Boxer
will squeak past challenger Matt Fong, 48 to 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   You can see his predictions for the other 30 races at
 &LR; www.harrisblackintl.com/electionpollresults/ &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   After the election, Harris will turn its data over to the
Unversity of Rochester so that social scientists can dissect the
results. ``We're trying to advance the state of the science,''
Terhanian said.
</P>
<P>
   Given how long it took for phones to replace face-to-face
polling, no one expects Internet surveys to become standard
overnight, even if Harris scores 100 percent with its Internet
picks.
</P>
<P>
   But cost and speed favor the Net. It takes six days and $50,000
for Field to do a telephone poll. E-mail surveys could be done
overnight and for a fraction of the cost, DiCamillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Terhanian is confident that the question is when,
not if, the Internet will replace the phone as the pollster's tool
of choice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail ( &LR; abate(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR; ). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
