<SLUG> BC-BIO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FDA OKs Transplant Drug From Menlo Park's SangStat  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A Menlo Park biotech firm has received permission to start selling
the first generic form of cyclosporine, the drug that kidney, lung
and heart transplant patients must take twice a day to live with
their donated organs.
<P>
   SangStat Medical Corp. said yesterday the Food and Drug
Administration has rated its cyclosporine drug, called SangCya, as
the functional equivalent of Neoral, the drug now used by most of
the 140,000 transplant patients in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That FDA approval means SangStat can attack the
$500-million-a-year market for Neoral, which is made by the Swiss
firm Novartis. SangStat said it plans to start shipping SangCya
within the month.
</P>
<P>
   SangStat CEO Philippe Pouletty said his firm will price SangCya
about 20 percent below Neoral to take advantage of the fact that
insurers favor lower-cost generic drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients can be switched from Neoral to SangCya with no new
prescription,'' Pouletty said.
</P>
<P>
   Transplant patients must take up to nine different drugs a day,
every day, for the rest of their lives to prevent their own immune
systems from attacking the transplant. Cyclosporine is the most
important _ and costly _ of these drugs, currently running above
$6,000 per patient, per year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its price advantage, SangStat hopes to win over
transplant physicians by giving patients a handheld device that
will tell them when to take their twice-daily doses of SangCya and
record it if they do.
</P>
<P>
   Pouletty said 15 to 25 percent of all patients fail to keep
their drug regime, leading their bodies to reject the transplant.
He said Novartis does not have a similar dispensing and recording
device for Neoral.
</P>
<P>
   David Buck, a financial analyst with Sands Brothers &AMP; Co. in New
York, said the FDA approval of SangCya was expected and somewhat
overdue. It represents the first big revenue opportunity for
SangStat, which was founded in 1989 and went public in 1993 on the
promise of future remedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The approval is a positive catalyst for the company and its
stock,'' said Buck, who had a buy rating out on SangStat,
anticipating FDA approval.
</P>
<P>
   SangStat closed yesterday at $21.63, up 88 cents before the FDA
news was released. The stock hit a 52-week high of $41.38 in
December.
</P>
<P>
   In February, SangStat applied for approval to sell SangCya in
Europe, where Novartis currently sells the only approved form of
cyclosporine. That application is pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
