<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-SPENDING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT: SEPTEMBER BUYING SURPASSES EARNINGS; SAVINGS AT RECORD LOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the first time in nearly 40 years, consumers
in September spent more than they earned, pushing the national
savings rate to its lowest level on record.
</P>
<P>
   But in the real world of grocery bills, mortgage payments and a
looming holiday season, the change was so slight few consumers
seemed aware that they'd played a part in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I had to renew my homeowners' insurance,'' said Gregg
Zuckerman, owner of Anna-Bella Designs, a women's clothing
manufacturer and boutique chain based in suburban Northridge. ``But
business wasn't especially bad or especially good. It was just one
of those months.''
</P>
<P>
   According to figures compiled by the U.S. Commerce Department,
personal incomes before taxes rose 0.2 percent in September, for a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $7.17 trillion. That's the
smallest increase since November 1994. After-tax, disposable income
also rose 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, spending grew a hearty 0.5 percent. The
combination made for a savings rate, or savings as a percentage of
disposable income, of negative 0.2 percent, the lowest since the
Commerce Department began tracking monthly rates in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Economists say that while the low figure reflects an economy on
the edge, it's better that consumers spent in September than if
they had socked their money away. After all, they note, U.S.
consumers generate two-thirds of the nation's gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need the consumer to be spending,'' said Don Hilber, an
economist at Norwest Corp. in Minneapolis. ``They're pulling the
economy forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, if income and job growth continue to fall, eventually
that likely could spook consumers away from purchases of big-ticket
items such as cars, washing machines and computers, further slowing
the economy. Indeed, sales of durable goods led the recent spending
increase, rising 2 percent, compared to September gains of 0.1
percent and 0.5 percent for nondurable goods and services,
respectively. How long such a confidence-eroding process would take
is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no precedent for what we're into now. We've never had
an extended period of time where we'd gotten to this low a level
and managed to stay there,'' Hilber said.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists argue that an anomaly related to the delayed
opening of thousands of schools in September skewed Monday's jobs
figures, and that the real savings rate was likely higher than what
was reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were clearly special factors in September that
suppressed the hours worked and the hourly earnings in the payroll
report,'' said David Orr, an economist at First Union in Charlotte,
N.C., told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   But even at a 0 percent rate, consumers are at best treading
water, Hilber said. ``It doesn't leave much room for out-of-savings
spending, which has been fueling the economy for the last couple of
years. There's no buffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to Monday's grim spending news was word from the National
Association of Purchasing Managers that manufacturing activity in
October slowed for the fifth month in a row. The group's monthly
index dropped to 48.3 percent from 49.4 percent in September. A
reading under 50 percent reflects industrial contraction.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the weakness that Monday's reports reflect, stocks rose
sharply, with the Dow Jones industrial average gaining 114 points
to close at 8,706.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
