<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-CHANGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR CHANGE AIMS FOR SIDE-BY-SIDE RACING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASCAR officials yesterday implemented aerodynamic modifications
that effectively eliminate the ``5-and-5 Rule'' for all makes of
Winston Cup cars competing in Sunday's season-ending NAPA 500.
</P>
<P>
   Modifications to the rear spoiler and front air dams will be in
effect when qualifying at the 1.5-mile Atlanta Motor Speedway in
Hampton, Ga., begins Friday.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR implemented the ``5-and-5 Rule'' at the start of the
season to make cars less stable through the corners and
theoretically force drivers to slow. The rule was expected to
promote side-by-side racing, but it has had the opposite effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will make the cars more stable,'' said Larry McClure,
owner of the No. 4 Kodak Chevy driven by Bobby Hamilton. ``It will
bring side-by-side racing back into the sport. It will get rid of
some of these boring races. NASCAR needed to do this, and I'm sure
glad they did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chevrolet Monte Carlo will run with a rear spoiler height of
6.50 inches (up from 5 inches) and a 57-inch width. Rear spoilers
on the Pontiac Grand Prix will be 6.875-inches high (up from 5.375
inches) and 57-inches wide. The Ford Taurus will maintain a rear
spoiler of 6.25-inches (up from 4.75 inches) and 55-inch width. Any
team running a Ford Thunderbird will do so with a rear spoiler
height of 6 inches (up from 4.50) and 55 inches wide.
</P>
<P>
   All models must run with a minimum spoiler angle of 65 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Front air dams on all cars will have a 3.50-inch ground
clearance, a reduction of 1.50 inches on Chevys and Fords and a
1.125-inch reduction for Pontiacs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 2258EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
