<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING PRIORITIES STRAIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Bruins should be more concerned with their own
mess than the BCS. Bowl Championship Series rankings and Fiesta
Bowl invitations won't matter unless UCLA corrects its egregious
plays from Saturday's narrow victory over Stanford. There were
simply too many:
</P>
<P>
   __ Missed field goals. Chris Sailer's attempts from 53 and 50
yards were blocked, although protection was not the only problem.
Sailer, recovering from a strained right groin, had low trajectory
on both kicks. He has made 3 of 10 field goals this season, none
longer than 41 yards.
</P>
<P>
   __ Red-zone interceptions. Quarterback Cade McNown threw two
interceptions in a four-play sequence; both came deep in Stanford
territory. In the last three games, McNown has thrown four
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   __ Third-down deficiency. The Bruins converted only 4 of 12
third down chances, while Stanford succeeded on 11 of 18 attempts.
Several were longer than 15 yards.
</P>
<P>
   __ Penalties, penalties, penalties. The Bruins committed 12 for
125 yards, many stalling or squashing scoring drives. They had a
touchdown called back because of a holding call on guard Jim
Ghezzi. Guard Andy Meyers received an unsportsmanlike penalty. Even
mild-mannered freshman DeShaun Foster lost his cool, throwing the
ball at a Cardinal defender after scoring the go-ahead touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The penalties are killing us, and if we don't straighten it
out, it'll be catastrophic,'' offensive coordinator Al Borges said.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Left out:!off! Left guard is another problem, although
not as easily corrected as a penalty. Ghezzi, a transfer from
Glendale College, and sophomore Oscar Cabrera have shared playing
time since Cabrera's return last month from a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our Achilles' heel,'' coach Bob Toledo said. ``Oscar's
our best physically, but he's a sophomore.''
</P>
<P>
   Reserve Josh Webb did not play because of a sprained shoulder
and is doubtful for Saturday's game at Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   __ Lewis update: X-rays on starting tailback Jermaine Lewis'
bruised right calf were negative. He is questionable for Saturday's
game at Oregon State on the Pac-10's worst AstroTurf.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was injured on the second series of the Stanford game.
Keith Brown played the rest of the first half and most of the third
quarter. When he grew fatigued, the Bruins inserted Foster, who had
not played in two weeks because of a sprained left knee.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's medical staff cleared Foster for action, but the knee is
not 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still unstable,'' Toledo said. ``I don't know if it'll be
100 percent the rest of the year because he'll get banged up.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Best in the West?: After facing UCLA and Arizona in the past
three weeks, Oregon coach Mike Bellotti favors the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think right now, obviously, (Arizona is) the better team,''
Bellotti told reporters after a 38-3 loss to the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   __ Short stuff: Tight end Mike Grieb, safety Larry Atkins and
Tod McBride (special teams) were named UCLA's players of the game.
McBride blocked a punt, his second of the season; Atkins forced one
fumble and recovered two and Grieb had two catches. Joining McNown
and Atkins as captains this week are Meyers and fullback Craig
Walendy.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game at Oregon State will be shown on Fox Sports
West.
</P>
<P>
   Kickoffs for the Washington and USC games, Nov.14 and 21,
respectively, are set for 12:30 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
