<HEADER>
A0253 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RYMKUS-OBIT-HNS &LR;      11-02 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYMKUS-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the first head coach of the Houston Oilers, Lou Rymkus won
the inaugural American Football League championship. He was the
first AFL Coach of the Year. His .625 winning percentage is still
the best in the 39-year history of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   But like a lot of Oilers coaches who followed him, Rymkus found
out that Bud Adams wasn't the easiest owner to please. Five games
into his second season, Rymkus was fired and replaced by assistant
Wally Lemm, who helped the Oilers win a second AFL title.
</P>
<P>
   Rymkus, who died Saturday at age 78 after a lengthy illness,
will be buried Wednesday. When his friends swap stories about his
legendary career as a player and coach, they will remember him as a
throwback to a time when players went both ways and played as long
as they could walk. They will use words like pride, toughness and
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never known anyone who loved football as much as my
dad,'' Mike Rymkus said Monday. ``His heart was shaped like a
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad was tough but fair. He got the best out of his players. At
every level, guys who played and coached with him always told him
he was the best, and he took so much pride in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rymkus, the son of a coal miner, grew up in Chicago and became
an All-America offensive tackle at Notre Dame under Frank Leahy.
Drafted by Washington in 1943, Rymkus played one season until he
joined the Marines in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Rymkus played for the Cleveland Browns. In his
six seasons with the Browns, the 6-4, 245-pound Rymkus played both
ways, but he excelled at offensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Browns coach Paul Brown called Rymkus the ``best pass protector
I've ever seen.'' Even though he went on to found the Cincinnati
Bengals, Brown never wavered in his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   As the offensive line coach in Green Bay (1954-57) under Lisle
Blackbourn, Rymkus helped develop such linemen as Forrest Gregg and
Jim Ringo for Blackbourn's replacement, Vince Lombardi.
</P>
<P>
   Rymkus was coaching the Rams' offensive line when Adams hired
him on Jan. 3, 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lou had an impressive record as a player and coach, and he was
just the kind of guy I was looking for,'' Adams said Monday. ``Lou
was hard-nosed and outgoing. He demanded a lot from his players,
but he demanded a lot from himself, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lou will always be an important part of our history. Our
thoughts and prayers go out to his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Rymkus' first Oilers team included such players as George
Blanda, Billy Cannon, Charlie Hennigan, Bill Groman, Bob Talamini,
Charlie Milstead, Al Jamison, Orville Trask and Jim Norton. They
helped the Oilers win the first two AFL championship games and play
in a third in a row.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, Rymkus returned to the Oilers as offensive line coach
at the request of Sammy Baugh. Baugh had been the head coach in
1964, and he stepped aside for Bones Taylor in 1965. Baugh stayed
on to help Taylor and asked Rymkus to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad returned to the Oilers because of Sammy,'' Mike Rymkus
said. ``He told Sammy, `You know what you're asking me to do?'
Sammy told him yes, but he needed him. That's the kind of guy Dad
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football was his heart and soul right up until he died.''
</P>
<P>
   Rymkus won a Super Bowl ring in 1971 when he coached the
Baltimore Colts' offensive line when they defeated the Dallas
Cowboys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
