<HEADER>
A0254 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-APPLEWHITE-     11-02 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-APPLEWHITE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
AUSTIN _ Major Applewhite says he misses the way his Saturdays once
were. Sort of.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He used to do one thing and one thing only on Saturdays _ watch
college football. He would watch the quarterbacks to see how they
did what they did and read the defenses to see what they were
trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   The allegiance of the Baton Rouge, La., native was to LSU (and
still is), although he always appreciated good play from good
players.
</P>
<P>
   But Applewhite doesn't get to watch much college football on
television these days. Lately, he has been going to work on
Saturdays, putting together one of the best freshman seasons ever
by a University of Texas quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a dream,'' said Applewhite, who apparently has no
plans to wake up. ``But you can't have good games unless you have
good players (around you). We've got an outstanding offensive line,
great receivers and an unbelievable running back. They make
everything happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It is just like the unassuming Applewhite to let others share in
the glory of his dream. But though he may try hard to fade into the
background, this 20-year-old has been a rather bright star in this
season's burnt-orange rhapsody.
</P>
<P>
   How good has he been?
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite has thrown at least one touchdown pass in every
start, has participated in the longest play from scrimmage in
school history (a 97-yard TD pass to Wane McGarity against
Oklahoma) and is one game shy of matching the school record for
consecutive 200-yard passing games (seven).
</P>
<P>
   He has thrown for 1,571 yards, averaging 252 yards per start,
and is a threat to break UT's freshman record of 2,341 set in 1993
by Shea Morenz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many people would have given us a chance to win with a
freshman quarterback who's never played a game in his college
career,'' said McGarity, a senior receiver. ``To come out and play
the way he's played _ with a lot of confidence, staying in there
and taking those shots, and making plays for this offense _ he's
emerged as one of the leaders on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite is 5-1 as a starter, with the loss coming in his
first start at Kansas State against quite possibly the country's
best defense. That game was the only one in which he completed less
than 50 percent of his passes, and he has been simply superb since.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a quarterback, he won a lot in high school, and I think
that's important because he expects to win when he walks out
there,'' Texas coach Mack Brown said. ``He has always been a real
football fan. He was always an Alabama fan. He was named after
Major Ogilvie, the running back at Alabama. He was raised around
LSU football, so he's seen full stadiums before. So I don't think
any of that stuff bothers him. I think it excites him.''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite may get excited about playing before a full house and
throwing for more yards than any player previously in the
Texas-Oklahoma game, one of college football's most storied
rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   He may get a charge out of leading the Longhorns to a
come-from-behind win over Baylor in front of UT's largest home
crowd of the season.
</P>
<P>
   And he may even get a little pumped up about tossing a touchdown
pass to McGarity with less than three minutes remaining to give
Texas a win over Nebraska, snapping the Cornhuskers' 47-game home
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   But if he does, he doesn't show it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never see him change his expression,'' Brown said. ``The
guys have bought into it; they have confidence in him. With that
many seniors on offense, it's really difficult for a freshman to
lead those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns, who have seven senior starters on offense, said
all the right things when Applewhite was given the starting nod
after starter Richard Walton was hurt in the second game of the
season. But they had to have questions about their new
signal-caller.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the back of their minds, I'm sure they were kind of like,
`Oh, boy.' But I think as things have moved along (that changed),''
Applewhite said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has scored on 40 percent of its drives with Applewhite at
the helm, logging almost as many touchdowns (28) as punts (31).
More important, he has refused to be rattled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shows a lot of maturity for a guy that's a freshman when he
messes something up,'' Brown said. ``Usually, guys pout. When he
walks off the field if he throws an interception, he doesn't look
like he just threw an interception. He'll jog off like he just hit
another pass.''
</P>
<P>
   This has not escaped his teammates' notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes a lot of mistakes, but he never gets in the tank, and
he always keeps on coming back,'' said Ricky Williams, the
Longhorns' Heisman Trophy candidate. ``So you can't really tell
when he makes a mistake. He's a winner. He's done a lot of the
right things and made a lot of big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   With three regular-season games remaining for the 6-2 Longhorns,
there could be more big plays to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect a whole lot more out of myself each and every week,''
Applewhite said. ``There's some mistakes you're going to make every
week, and the thing I try to do is eliminate those week in and week
out.''
</P>
<P>
   While letting the ``freshman-as-star'' dream continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
