<HEADER>
A0256 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     11-02 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
JOHN Elway could very easily have quit when he was on top, and I
for one believed he should have. Since it took him 15 seasons'
worth of muggings to win a Super Bowl, the odds were rather poor
that he could go claim another title just like that.
</P>
<P>
   Elway had everything _ his health, considerable wealth, a lock
on the Hall of Fame and, finally, The Ring. Yet two words must have
kept resonating in John's head before he chose to tempt fate and
rebuckle his chin strap in the pursuit of a Roman-numeral repeat.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell. Davis.
</P>
<P>
   How do you retire when you can keep handing the football to
Terrell Davis?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, when you look around and see Warren Moon, a starter
closing in on 42, and Steve DeBerg, a backup at 44, in uniform, you
suddenly feel more like a colt than a Bronco. So, no sir, there
would be no Kerry Collins in John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   Now look. There Elway sits at the season's midpoint, no worse
for wear other than a pesky hamstring, holding the reins of an
undefeated thoroughbred. After a shaky preseason, during which
Elway took a brief leave of absence to visit a motorcycle rally in
South Dakota to try to lure retired offensive tackle Gary Zimmerman
back into the fold, the Broncos are busting loose like never
before.
</P>
<P>
   Another first for Elway: Denver is 8-0 _ and clearly the class
of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Davis? He has 1,150 yards and 14 touchdowns, both historic
paces. Elway is quick to say that these days the Broncos are
Terrell's team, not his anymore, but most Denver folks would
disagree _ Davis among them _ voting for a co-stewardship instead.
</P>
<P>
   It's especially fitting that the Broncos are halfway to
perfection on the wings of an Elway-patented rally. Although he was
out of sorts for three quarters against a bad Bengals defense
Sunday, the fourth quarter almost always represents a clean slate
for Captain Comeback.
</P>
<P>
   For the 46th time in his career, Elway ambushed a hapless
opponent at the finish. Denver scored three touchdowns in the last
15 minutes, with Davis' five-yard game-winner, in reply to
Cincinnati's tying points at 2:54, coming inside the final minute.
Had anyone else been taking the snaps, we might call it a miracle
finish. For John, we smile and we shrug. Business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, and somewhat ironically given the one-two entry
punch of celebrated freshmen Peyton Manning and Ryan Leaf, 1998 has
to date been the year of the old-codger quarterback _ all the more
reason to be thankful Elway opted to stay for the party.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen falls ago, he was the exalted rookie, the No. 1 choice
in a draft arguably the best ever for QBs. His many travails should
serve as inspiration for Manning and Leaf, although it might
depress them a little if they knew of everything Elway endured to
get where he is today.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Young, an Elway contemporary with a tale of his own to
tell, is also doggedly acting his name, rather than his age, having
turned the season's corner with a remarkable 21 touchdown passes
against six interceptions. OK, so he can't beat the Packers.
Nobody's perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Great _ and in the case of Collins' continuing sad saga, notably
un-great _ stories abound among the NFL's signal-callers, leaving
Elway a bit lost in the shuffle. A slew of them are having showier
seasons _ some with surprising names such as Flutie, Testaverde and
Cunningham _ but Elway remains conspicuous by virtue of that zero
following the hyphen in the Broncos' record.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Flutie, still too little at 36 and still too stubborn to
admit it, beat the Dolphins on Sunday with a fourth-quarter
uprising of his own on Buffalo's behalf. That's four victories for
Flutie in relief of the banged-up Rob Johnson in this, his second
incarnation as an NFL quarterback after what once figured to be
permanent exile in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Testaverde, another Heisman Trophy owner presumed bound
for the NFL's refuse bin, is running a Jets machine that has five
wins in six starts. As was obviously the order of the day Sunday,
Vinny knocked off the Chiefs with two late scoring drives of his
own. One of them ended with his 12th touchdown pass, against only
two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Randall Cunningham, two seasons removed from an aborted
retirement to the real world of laying marble tile for a living, is
the lone quarterback ahead of Testaverde in the passer ratings and
until Sunday had kept the Vikings unbeaten. Cunningham's own
salient stats: 16 touchdowns with just three picks.
</P>
<P>
   Then, down Dixie way, we have Chris Chandler, another
has-been-in-waiting who won't go away, either. Behind Chandler, the
Falcons are a best-ever 6-2 at the midpoint. Also, they are 12-4 of
late in games he manages to finish, always a problem for the
oft-injured former Oiler, Ram, Cardinal, Colt and Buc.
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Manning and Leaf: Pay attention. At your job, patience
is a virtue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
