</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Schroeder's Presidential Candidate
</P>
<P>
   BONN, Germany _ The Social Democratic Party of Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder nominated Johannes Rau, 67, as its presidential
candidate. Rau, a former premier of North Rhine-Westphalia, will be
the prime contender to succeed President Roman Herzog in May in the
largely ceremonial post.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Coalition for Mecklenburg
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ For the first time the successor to the
Communist Party in East Germany reached a formal agreement to form
a governing coalition in Mecklenburg-West Pomerania. The
organization, now called the Party of Democratic Socialism, will be
a junior partner in a coalition with the Social Democrats. The pact
was reached a month after the Communists had won a strong second
place in statewide elections.
</P>
<P>
   France: Report on Diana Crash Transmitted
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ The police turned over to investigating magistrates a
report on the car crash that killed Diana, Princess of Wales, last
year, but did not release it. The police have confirmed that the
report found that the driver, Henri Paul, was drunk and driving at
62 miles per hour, slower than previously reported but still two
times the legal limit, when he lost control and crashed into a
tunnel pillar. There was also no evidence reported of sabotage or
faulty brakes or air bags in the rented Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Tonga: Rupture with Taiwan
</P>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Taiwan said it was breaking ties with Tonga and
canceling aid after the island switched allegiance to mainland
China, which also promised trade and aid. That cuts the number of
countries that officially recognize Taiwan to 26, mainly poor
African and Latin American countries. South Africa, the Central
African Republic and Guinea-Bissau also switched to Beijing this
year.
</P>
<P>
   India: Accusations Over Kashmir Frontier
</P>
<P>
   NEW DELHI _ India and Pakistan accused each other of firing
artillery across the disputed frontier in Kashmir four days before
officials begin high-level meetings in New Delhi. The countries
plan to discuss border disputes, as well as trade, combatting
terrorism and drug trafficking and cultural exchanges. Meetings in
Islamabad last month produced no concrete progress on nuclear
security.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Colombia: Rebels Attack Police Base
</P>
<P>
   BOGOTA _ Leftist rebels battered a police base on Sunday in
Mitu, near the Brazilian border, killing at least 80 officers and
taking 45 prisoner, the Colombian Red Cross said. The Revolutionary
Armed Forces attacked as the government prepared to open talks to
end a war that killed more than 2,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: 200 Aliens Die Crossing U.S. Border in 1998
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican consul in Los Angeles, Jose Angel Pescador Osuna,
said 200 Mexicans had died this year while trying evade capture as
they crossed the border into the United States. He said stepped-up
enforcement by the Border Patrol had led to the growing number of
deaths.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
