</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. DOESN'T NEED NFL; NFL NEEDS L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the two rival Los Angeles groups seeking a pro football
franchise bow like royal servants at the altar of the almighty NFL,
offering its ownership everything except titles to the Getty Museum
and the MGM film library, I privately cringe.
</P>
<P>
   Why should we in L.A., which still holds all the NFL attendance
records from those glorious days when the Rams often had crowds
exceeding 100,000 at the Coliseum, be coerced into losing our
financial dignity like St. Louis and Memphis and Oakland and
Baltimore and Cleveland have been made to do in recent years?
</P>
<P>
   Why should we in L.A., second largest media center in America
behind New York, undisputed movie capital of the planet, have to
endure the obscene spectacle of dropping to our knees like a
desperate street corner cadger and beg those NFL robber barons to
throw us a crumb?
</P>
<P>
   Why should we in L.A., which in my biased view is the greatest
area in the world because of its mild year-round weather and unique
cultural diversity, act as though the very fiber of our existence
here is contingent on us securing an NFL team?
</P>
<P>
   I found the drama that unfolded last week in Kansas City to be a
tawdry exercise in corporate bullying by the NFL, with the
competing groups from L.A. and one from Houston displaying their
wares to their potential suitors in the same toadying manner
courtesans do from their apartment windows in the alleys of
Amsterdam's notorious red light district.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, I miss having an NFL team in our midst, if for no
other selfish reason that I no longer have such local column
staples to write about as Al Davis and Georgia Frontiere.
</P>
<P>
   I think the NFL National Football League has become a laughable
misnomer because how can a league pass itself off as being national
if L.A., which once had two NFL teams and still has two major
league baseball teams, two NBA teams, two NHL teams, isn't a part
of it?
</P>
<P>
   Those greed-driven NFL owners like Jerry Jones and Al Davis and
Pat Bowlen and Georgia Frontiere and all the others will tell you
their monopolistic confederation is progressing healthily without
L.A., which seems to be the case at the moment with each team
earning $32 million in TV revenue before it even opens its summer
training camp gates.
</P>
<P>
   But we in L.A. also seem to be existing nicely without the NFL,
managing our Sundays in a more orderly, if not docile ways,
checking out delightful places like the Huntington Library out
</P>
<P>
   in Pasadena, or even taking in a matinee at the Ahmanson Theatre
rather than duking it out with Raider fans at the Coliseum, or
booing dear Georgia at old Anaheim Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, we have saved millions of dollars shunning NFL hats and
jerseys, much to the dismay of those in the league who have noticed
the precipitous decline of its apparel revenues in Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL claims it doesn't need L.A., to which I counter we don't
need the NFL and shouldn't act as though we do as our
representatives so humiliatingly did last week.
</P>
<P>
   I want an NFL team here as much as anyone, but I don't think a
single dollar should be fleeced from any of us L.A. residents to
subsidize the emergence of a new team and the construction of a new
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   As I watched the Seattle-Oakland gamematch
</P>
<P>
   Sunday evening, I felt a bittersweet sense of nostalgia because
it's become obvious that the team that was once such an integral
part of our existence, the Raiders, no longer is the dysfunctional
weakling of recent years and clearly is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   You find it difficult applauding the eccentric Raider owner, Al
Davis, who in an impulsive fit of pique after the 1994 season
abandoned L.A. when his jilted paramour, Oakland, waved too much
money in front of his gold-rimmed spectacles for him to resist.
</P>
<P>
   But, grudgingly, you must admit Davis seems to have revived his
long-suffering franchise, and put together a fast, strong,
aggressive, smart team reminiscent of glorious predecessors rather
than last season's 4-12 flameouts who so diminished Davis'
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Amid slightly more serious issues rampant gang warfare, the
terrible deterioration of its school system, etc., the L.A. City
Council last week somehow found enough time to pass a resolution
against Al Davis bringing the Raiders back to our celestial
community.
</P>
<P>
   That in itself is a rousing endorsement for Al Davis because the
L.A. City Council just might be the most obtuse, doctrinaire,
divisive, incompetent government body in America, which,
considering the fierce competition in so many sectors, is quite an
ignoble accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not a person who holds grudges, unlike many of my friends
and former friends. Anger quickly abates in me. Amnesia clouds old
feuds. I shook hands with John Robinson after we had engaged in a
long jihad and now consider him a friend again. I speak to all
former lady companions. I hold no bitter feelings toward a former
radio station general manager who fired me over finances when Joe
McDonnell and I had the highest ratings at the station. I find it
incomprehensible that Tom Lasorda no longer talks to me because I
did something so appalling as to write the truth about what Bill
Russell thought about him.
</P>
<P>
   As much as I detest Al Davis for departing L.A., I would gladly
forgive old grievances if he decided to lam it out of Oakland again
for L.A. This life is far too short to maintain vengeful hatreds.
I'd rather have the Raiders here than go through the growing pains
endemic to an expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   But, please, no taxpayer handouts, not to Al Davis, not to those
L.A. supplicants who last Tuesday so shamelessly threw themselves
at the mercy of those haughty NFL owners who must be made to
understand we can live quite tranquilly without them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
