<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAMBRANO DECISION WEEK OR TWO AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Los Angeles Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano
will have the first of several meetings with the team's new
ownership this morning, but club president Tim Leiweke says he
shouldn't expect a answer on whether he will remain in charge for
another week or two.
</P>
<P>
   There is much talk in soccer circles that Zambrano, a Major
League Soccer coach of the year finalist who guided the Galaxy to a
24-8 regular-season record and into the Western Conference finals,
won't be returning next season, but Leiweke insists no decisions
have been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the next two weeks we owe Octavio a decision,''
said Leiweke, who took charge of the Galaxy when Philip F. Anschutz
purchased the club nearly two weeks ago. ``(Right now) what we know
is that we don't know the answers yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiweke, also president of the Anschutz-owned Los Angeles Kings
and Staples Center, said he has been talking to players, staff and
figures within the soccer community about Zambrano. He and Anschutz
plan to meet with the coach several times through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you've got new ownership, some changes are made,''
said Leiweke, who earlier indicated there had been feedback that
suggested looking deeper at the coaching position. ``It's not
unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These people, this isn't the first company they've acquired,
and I think they have a blueprint of how to go about doing things,
and that process includes a thorough review of everyone,'' said
Zambrano, who has posted a 37-15 record in a little more than a
season and a half in charge. ``I have full confidence that once
they've reviewed everything that everything will be fine and I
fully expect to be back. It would surprise me if I'm not.
</P>
<P>
   ``My record stands on its own merits, and I think that the job
that was done was quality work. ... But as a coach, you must always
be aware that your tenure in a team can change.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano's chances could be hurt by his relationship with some
of his players. Several have been unhappy with how he communicates
decisions -- ``I think Octavio has burned a lot of bridges with his
players,'' said one -- and Leiweke said that chemistry between the
coach and players would play a role in whether Zambrano remains
with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a professional relationship (with the players),''
Zambrano says. ``When you have 20 players that could start for any
team, it's obvious there are going to be some unhappy guys when it
comes to playing time. My job as coach is to maximize their output,
and I think I did that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great relationship with the guys. I can't think of
any guy I have a bad relationship with.''
</P>
<P>
   GALAXY NOTES: Leiweke said he'd like to hire a general manager
with the next week or two, before a decision on Zambrano is made,
if possible. ... Paul Caligiuri, waived Saturday, wasn't taken in
Monday's MLS Waiver Draft and will be available in the supplemental
draft next spring if he signs a new contract. Zambrano said
salary-cap issues forced him to drop the 34-year-old defender, who
needs to renegotiate his pact with MLS after league officials
failed to exercize their option on his current contract. ``It was
very sad, but we hope he can come back to out team,'' Zambrano
said. ``It all depends on his salary.'' MLS doesn't release salary
figures, but Caligiuri was believed to be making $105,000 a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
