<SLUG> BC-NJ-FAMILY-CAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH NEW JERSEY FAMILY CAP, BIRTHS FALL AND ABORTIONS RISE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ New Jersey's so-called family-cap policy, which
cuts off extra cash benefits to welfare recipients who have more
children, has led to an overall decline in birth rates among
welfare recipients and has also contributed to a temporary increase
in abortions, according to the final version of a Rutgers
University study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A draft version of the report, released earlier this year,
reached similar conclusions. Researchers re-examined their
methodology at the request of the Whitman administration and found
larger numbers of abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 million, 1,000-page study, which was commissioned by the
state and federal governments, found a significant decline in the
number of births among welfare recipients after New Jersey became
the first state to impose a family-cap law in 1992. The researchers
estimated that there were 14,000 fewer births between 1992 and 1996
than would have been expected because of trend and population
changes.
</P>
<P>
   The team of researchers also concluded that the law contributed
to an increase of 1,400 abortions among welfare recipients over and
above what would have been expected during the same period. The
researchers said the abortion rate increased sharply after the new
law took effect, but then leveled off to about the same rate as
before the family-cap law took effect. The study also found an
increase in the number of women who used family planning and
contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman, who has been under pressure from some
legislators, women's groups and abortion rights opponents to repeal
the law, said Monday that the study's findings had persuaded her to
maintain the state's family-cap policy because of the decline in
the number of births.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about abortion,'' Whitman said, calling the law a
success. ``It's about accepting responsibility for your actions and
personal responsibility and planning.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey first adopted its law in 1992 under a federal waiver
that allowed states to try alternative policies and programs.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty other states have adopted similar family-cap laws since
the federal government cleared the way two years ago for states to
design their own welfare programs.
</P>
<P>
   Some welfare policy experts contend that family-cap laws help
promote individual responsibility and discourage welfare recipients
from having more children than they can support.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates for the poor, conservative Christian groups, the
Roman Catholic Church and women's organizations say the laws lead
to more abortions and plunge children even deeper into poverty.
They have tried to repeal the laws.
</P>
<P>
   The National Organization for Women Legal Defense and Education
Fund and other groups filed a lawsuit challenging New Jersey's
family-cap law. In September, legislation was introduced seeking to
repeal the law.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Diane Allen, a Republican who is sponsoring the bill,
said the Rutgers study would bolster the legislation's chances for
passage.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said 28,000 children have been born into
families who were dependent on welfare benefits and were denied
extra cash assistance. Officials said the families did, however,
continue to receive extra food stamp benefits and state Medicaid
coverage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 2332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981102.0475 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
