<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-COMMISSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE VACANT COMMISSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Nov. 3:
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Sentencing Commission is a small, independent federal
agency with a big job _ setting sentencing guidelines for federal
crimes. Right now, the agency has one other distinction. It has no
members, the absurd result of months of partisan bickering in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-member commission had been limping along with three
vacancies for more than a year. In August the chairman, Richard
Conaboy, announced that he was leaving as of Oct. 31, and the terms
of the three other commissioners automatically expired when
Congress adjourned last month. By statute, the commission is meant
to be nonpolitical, its members appointed by the president and
confirmed by the Senate. At least three of the members must be
federal judges, and no more than four may belong to the same
political party.
</P>
<P>
   These requirements are supposed to keep the commission free of
politics. But Senate Republicans have had a hard time agreeing on
the three Republican slots, and the individuals they have offered
have been rejected by the White House as too rigidly conservative.
In retaliation, the Republicans have balked at names proposed by
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is crucial to the federal criminal justice
system. Congress routinely creates new crimes or stiffens penalties
on existing crimes. The commission sets the guidelines used by
federal judges to determine sentencing. Often Congress will set a
maximum penalty but let the commission determine when that maximum
would apply and under what circumstances a lesser sentence might be
justified. Congress recently asked the commission for new
sentencing guidelines for crimes involving telemarketing fraud,
identity fraud, child sexual abuse, the theft of cellular phone
services and methamphetamine sales.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's staff will continue its research, but no new
guidelines will be issued until there are some new members. That
should shame both sides into finally producing a slate of qualified
individuals who are above partisanship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 2333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
