<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-RED-WINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED WINGS' REMARKS IRK STARS COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said yesterday he took
exception to comments from the Detroit Red Wings that the Stars had
used ``illegal picks'' on two goal-scoring plays en route to a 3-2
victory Saturday night. He added that the Red Wings could have been
penalized on either play.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at the issues they bring to focus, those issues
are wrong,'' said Hitchcock, stirring up a war of words in the
budding rivalry. ``The right call was made in a no-call. If
anything, it could even be a dive the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings claimed that Mike Modano knocked down Detroit
center Steve Yzerman on one play, opening a path for Jere Lehtinen
to take a shot deflected in by Brett Hull. They also complained
that Modano knocked down winger Brendan Shanahan in the neutral
zone, creating the open ice for Hull to score the game-winner with
six minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two goals came because of interference and picks,'' Red
Wings goalie Chris Osgood said. ``Those are called 95 percent of
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano said he and Yzerman got tangled on the first play and
Shanahan was grabbing his stick on the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``He grabbed my stick and then dropped like I was grabbing
his,'' Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   NHL rules state a player can be called for embellishing a
penalty or ``diving.'' The Stars already have been whistled twice
this season for dives. If Modano's account is accurate, Shanahan
could have been called for a dive as easily as Modano could have
been called for interference.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Hitchcock said, the no-call was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the Red Wings have become experts at the diving
ploy and that was one reason they were given nine power-play
opportunities during Saturday's game. He pointed specifically to
penalties called on Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig against Martin
Lapointe and defenseman Shawn Chambers against Yzerman ``that were
in our view no-calls and ended up being two-minute penalties,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit has become a very good hockey club in the little areas
of getting away with things, so you have to learn from them,''
Hitchcock said. ``They're smart. They have people who know when to
go down, and smart players do that. We've just got to become
smarter than them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hitchcock isn't above a pre-emptive strike to counteract all
the posturing the Red Wings are doing _ posturing, he said, he
believes is aimed at getting a competitive advantage for Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking for the competitive edge. They're trying to
get the referee to look in some areas and I'm trying to get the
referee to look in some areas. It's about competition,'' Hitchcock
said. ``But in the end, the players have to decide the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hitchcock wasn't above getting in his two cents before
the next game against Detroit, scheduled Nov. 13 at Joe Louis
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any team that's focused on winning hockey, they're looking for
an edge,'' Hitchcock said. ``What's important is things the next
time we play are called on the upfront and called fairly, and then
we'll deal with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
