<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0284 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-AARON-HOME-RUNS-T     11-02 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-AARON-HOME-RUNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AARON CAN LOOK BACK WITH PRIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Baseball's all-time home-run king saw how
much the New York Mets are going to pay Mike Piazza. He didn't say
he would be worth that much today.
</P>
<P>
   But Hank Aaron did say if he was still playing, he would go have
a talk with the Atlanta Braves owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go up to Ted Turner and say, `Hello partner,''' Aaron
said. ``If Piazza can get $91 million, then I might be able to own
one of \RTurner's\S television stations.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron retired from baseball 22 years ago, before the escalation
of salaries, and had to settle for _ among many other post-career
honors _ the Lifetime Achievement Award presented to him by the
Bobby Bragan Youth Foundation at a banquet last night at the
Worthington Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The award honors Aaron for his achievements off and on the
field, both as an ambassador to the game and one of its greatest
players. Bragan, a longtime Fort Worth-area baseball figure,
managed Aaron with the Braves in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron finished his career with a record 755 home runs, but there
was much more to his career. So much that Aaron said last night,
``I wish people would think of me for more than home runs ... but
that's never going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   With this year's home-run record chase, national attention was
focused once more on Aaron's accomplishment and on baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The home-run chase kept baseball on people's minds and talking
about baseball,'' Aaron said. ``Whether they were fans of \RSammy\S
Sosa or fans of \RMark\S McGwire, it was good for baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said his goal each year was not to hit home runs, but to
bat .300, drive in 100 runs and score 100 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember what the late Jackie Robinson told me,'' Aaron
said. ``We were sitting around a room in Chattanooga, \RTenn.\S
four or five of us, just talking. He said the only way you're going
to be any good to your team is if you touch each base and you touch
home base. If you pop out or strike out, you don't help your team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I remember something my late manager Chuck Dressen once
said. We were at a banquet and he was just kidding, but I thought
he was serious. He said, `Here's Hank Aaron, he batted .292 (in
1960) and he drove in 100-something runs ... and if he had hit
.300, we would have won the pennant.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuck with me. I was embarrassed if I didn't hit .300 or
drive in 100 runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron did do that most of the time, finishing his 23-year with a
lifetime average of .305, along with 2,297 runs batted in, which
falls just short of an average of 100 RBI per season.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everybody knows Aaron is the all-time home run leader.
Not quite as many know he's the all-time RBI leader as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I'm most proud of is finishing with a .300 batting
average for my career,'' Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Aaron said, would be his consistency. He was the National
League's most valuable player in 1957, when the Milwaukee Braves
won the pennant, but he never had one signature year. Instead he
hit 40 or more homers eight times and 30 or more another seven. His
career best was 47 homers in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even fantasize about hitting 70,'' said Aaron who,
like all other baseball fans, watched with great interest as
McGwire and Sosa shattered Roger Maris' single-season home-run
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, the pennant races were over with early so people
weren't interested in them, and people weren't interested in the
wild-card race because they didn't know anything about it. Plus, we
didn't have a commissioner for much of the season, so those things
were working against us.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a year that nobody will ever forget, one that was
really remarkable,'' Aaron said. ``It was one, I think, looking
back, if it had not been for the home-run chase, baseball would
probably have some severe problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron was in the spotlight in 1974 when he broke Babe Ruth's
career home-run record, first tying it with his 714th off Reds
pitcher Jack Billingham and then passing it with his 715th on April
8 against Dodgers left-hander Al Downing.
</P>
<P>
   He went through some of the same things _ and more _ that Maris
encountered when he broke Ruth's single-season record in 1961. The
worst was the racial hatred of a few people who didn't want a black
man to break a hallowed white man's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed some of it,'' Aaron said. ``I had some ups and
downs. The hard part was seeing my kids unable to enjoy it because
they were isolated in some ways. But my chase was different from
what happened this year. My chase took years and years, this thing
just happened. Mine took 21 years to accumulate.''
</P>
<P>
   The honor will remain with him for years and years to come, even
if he doesn't get paid $91 million for doing it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
