r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-LINEBACKER-     11-02 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-LINEBACKER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINEBACKER HICKS EMERGING AS VITAL COG IN UT'S RESURGENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A role player to his core, Texas linebacker
Anthony Hicks laughed yesterday when asked about a correlation
between his emergence in the starting lineup and the start of the
Longhorns' five-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Both events trace their roots to Sept. 26, when Hicks made 10
tackles during a 59-21 rout of Rice.
</P>
<P>
   The junior from Richardson is so unassuming, he even joked about
being surprised no one handed him a specimen bottle when he came
off the field after making a career-high 13 tackles in last week's
20-16 upset of then-No. 7 Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I came from nowhere, I thought they might drug-test
me,'' said Hicks, who recorded more sacks (2) and tackles for
losses (5) against the Cornhuskers than during the first 25 games
of his college career. ``They can test me all they want. I'm clean.
There's nothing in me but water and Gatorade.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks neglected to mention heart and desire. But those are the
two attributes coach Mack Brown cited as vital to the success of an
undersized player, scheduled to make his sixth consecutive start
when No. 20 Texas (6-2, 4-1 Big 12) meets Oklahoma State (3-5, 2-4)
at 2:30 p.m. Saturday at Royal-Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Brown acknowledged Hicks, who missed spring drills with an ankle
injury suffered last season, hardly wowed coaches during fall
two-a-days with his size (6-foot, 232 pounds) or speed (4.6 in the
40-yard dash).
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't make any of our recruiting lists right now,''
Brown said. ``But he's smart and he plays hard every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks also happened to be an available, fresh face at a time
when Texas defensive coordinator Carl Reese was searching for
answers to correct a unit that allowed 44.3 points and 490.6 yards
per game in its first three outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know much about Anthony,'' Brown said. ``We just
knew we weren't stopping anybody, so we were looking for anyone to
give us some relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Relief eventually came in the form of a player who expected 1998
to be ``a long season for me.'' Unable to showcase his talents to
first-year coaches during spring drills, Hicks watched Brown switch
several players from other positions to outside linebacker. All
were faster than Hicks. All moved ahead of him on the depth chart
while he rehabilitated his ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this year started, it was like I was a freshman again,''
said Hicks, who started the final five games of the 1997 season.
``I was way behind. I knew the coaches wanted fast guys and I'm
thinking, `Where do I fit in?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, as of Sept. 26, proved to be strong-side linebacker.
Hicks has made 37 tackles since becoming a starter (7.4 per game).
None proved more pivotal than against Nebraska, where both of
Hicks' sacks stopped potential scoring drives that reached Texas
territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You visualize days like that, but you never expect to have
them,'' Hicks said. ``Every time something started to unfold, I was
there. Wherever I ran, the ball kept coming at me. I was in a zone
out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
