<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHEF-CHARGED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMINENT CHEF ACCUSED OF CREDIT THEFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A former boxer who rose from the streets of Brooklyn
to become one of New York City's most flamboyant celebrity chefs _
with his own restaurant, cookbook and cable television show _ was
charged Monday with stealing $190,000 from a credit card company by
falsifying credit card receipts for payment, in one case by as much
as $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   The chef, David Ruggerio, 36, whose television program
``Ruggerio to Go'' premiered on the Food Channel only three weeks
ago, was arraigned on felony grand larceny charges in Manhattan
Criminal Court Monday night. He faces up to 15 years in prison if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Ruggerio falsified credit card payments by inflating the
gratuities left by 26 customers at his restaurant, then known as Le
Chantilly, in May and June by amounts ranging from $5,000 to
$30,000, prosecutors said. Last summer, he renamed the restaurant
David Ruggerio.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant's credit card processing company, Paymentech
Merchant Services of Dallas, apparently noticed the large amounts
being charged and contacted law enforcement officials in New York.
</P>
<P>
   At the close of each day, William Bart, the maitre d'hotel, was
to total the day's credit card purchases and submit them by
computer to Paymentech. Beginning on May 9, Ruggiero had Bart
inflate the gratuities, according to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Paymentech then wired money matching the credit card total
directly into the restaurant's bank account. After the money
arrived, checks signed by Desmond Brusch, the bookkeeper, and
Ruggerio were drawn against the account, according to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Ruggerio's lawyer, Charles Carnesi, portrayed the
$190,000 in overcharges as a mistake, not a theft. He said that
Ruggerio, who recently began an episode of ``Ruggerio to Go'' with
a visit to a boxing gym, would repay any money he owed.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors painted a picture Monday that appeared to go far
beyond simple problems of arithmetic. They said Ruggerio ordered
Bart and Brusch to inflate the tips paid by 26 different customers
at his restaurant on East 57th Street and Park Avenue between May 9
and June 22 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Merchan, a prosecutor with the Manhattan district
attorney's office, said at the arraignment Monday that the three
men tried to steal $225,000 from Paymentech, but managed to get
only about $190,000. Judge James Sullivan of Manhattan Criminal
Court released all three men without bail. They are scheduled to
appear in court again on February 14.
</P>
<P>
   John DeLucia, the lawyer representing Brusch, the bookkeeper,
said his client had only followed orders. ``He's just a workman,''
he said. ``He's a bookkeeper. He does what he's told.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for Bart, the maitre d'hotel, could not be reached
for comment Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Carnesi described Ruggiero as a self-made culinary prodigy who
grew up in a working-class family in Sheepshead Bay and
Bensonhurst, Brooklyn. A professional boxer when he was younger,
Ruggerio fought in roughly 10 professional bouts, his lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   As he left the courthouse Monday night, Ruggerio declined to
answer questions from reporters. A woman who answered the phones at
Ruggiero's restaurant said it would remain open.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Carnesi, said: ``He's a terrific chef, an excellent
author. But he's not necessarily a great businessman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
