<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABC-STRIKE-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC WORKERS STAGE 24-HOUR STRIKE; NETWORK RESPONDS BY LOCKING THEM
OUT
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ About 2,000 employees of ABC walked off their jobs
without warning Monday for a 24-hour strike, and the television
network's management responded by saying it would lock out any
striking workers who try to return Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The network said temporary workers would be hired to replace the
employees who took part in the strike, which started at 5 a.m. and
which union officials said was staged over a health care issue.
</P>
<P>
   The strikers included camera operators, technicians and
videotape editors. The union said their absence led to technical
glitches in programs broadcast over the ABC network and to the
suspension of the taping of two soap operas, claims that ABC said
were overstated.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Hoover, a spokeswoman for ABC, said employees hoping to
return to work Tuesday would be turned away because the union
refused to guarantee that workers would not strike without warning
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were locked out because we need to protect our
programming from further unannounced job actions,'' Hoover said.
``This is something we've done reluctantly. We have a perishable
product. It's not like a house that if it's not shown to a
prospective buyer one day, it can be shown the next.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover said she did not know how long the lockout would last.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Donahue, a spokesman for the National Association of
Broadcast Engineers &AMP; Technicians, which represents camera
operators, videotape editors, couriers, technicians, engineers and
some writers, said the ABC strikers were protesting because the
network would not provide details about the costs of out-of-network
care under its Disney Signature health plan.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, which is owned by the Walt Disney Co., is ``breaking the
law by not providing requested information about the health plan,
and by demanding that our 2,200 members enroll in a stealth health
care plan,'' Donahue said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover said that the health care issue was ``a pretext'' and
that the information requested was regarded by insurance companies
as proprietary.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to put pressure on us on the negotiating
table,'' Hoover said. ``For two years we've been negotiating with
NABET. ABC's contract with NABET is the most restrictive and most
expensive in the business. All of our direct competitors have more
flexibility.'' ABC's contract with the union expired on March 31,
1997. The union filed a complaint with the National Labor Relations
Board this summer on the medical dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of technical workers picketed outside the studios and
offices of ABC Monday morning, wearing red sweatshirts with a
silhouette image of Disney's Mickey Mouse that was dubbed ``Mickey
Rat,'' an ABC logo and the words ``Stop Union Busting.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``No one wants a lockout situation,'' said John A. Ahlers, 49, a
supervisor of the company's videotape library, as he walked the
picket line Monday at ABC's studios at 7 Lincoln Square. ``Going on
strike for one day is too long. But this company won't negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Joyce, an executive board representative of Local 16 of
NABET, said there were a series of technical glitches in programs
Monday. ABC broadcasts shows like ``Live With Regis &AMP; Kathie Lee,''
``Monday Night Football,'' ``World News Tonight,'' ``20/20,''
``Nightline'' and the soap operas ``All My Children'' and ``One
Life to Live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On Regis &AMP; Kathie Lee, the camera was zooming in and out
uncontrollably, and you couldn't hear Regis and Kathie Lee,'' Joyce
said. `` `All My Children' and `One Life to Live' were not taped.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoover confirmed that the soap-opera taping was delayed but
described Joyce's report of technical glitches as an overstatement.
``I think they're talking about less-than-exquisite camera shots,''
she said. ``They're trying to create a nonexistent situation.''
</P>
<P>
   NABET staged a one-day strike over contract talks during a PGA
golf tournament in Houston last fall, forcing ABC to broadcast
taped coverage of an old tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
