<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-02 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0296 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-JOHNSON-HN     11-02 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-JOHNSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. and general manager Gerry Hunsicker
made a quick, one-day trip to Arizona on Monday to gauge Randy
Johnson's interest in re-signing with the Astros.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The duo were so convinced, they left the free-agent pitcher with
his first lucrative contract offer to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Astros would not give any contract details, they are
believed to have offered Johnson a three-year deal worth between
$33 million and $36 million. It's possible the third year would be
at the club's option.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who has filed for free agency, intends to test the
market and won't have an answer for the Astros until he has fielded
offers from other clubs.
</P>
<P>
   However, Johnson did tell McLane and Hunsicker that the Astros
were on his short list, and Monday's offer should be competitive
enough to keep the Astros in the thick of the Big Unit sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offer we made was created to send a serious message to
Randy and his family about just how important we feel he is to this
franchise,'' said Hunsicker, who declined to disclose details of
the offer. ``It's more than we've ever offered a player, and it
shows that re-signing Randy is our No. 1 priority. It would allow
Randy to be compensated among the elite pitchers in the game, which
he most certainly is.''
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson accepts the Astros' proposal, he would become the
highest-paid player on the team and the third-highest-paid pitcher
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Jeff Bagwell is the highest-paid Astro, at $8
million a year. Boston's Pedro Martinez, in the second season of a
six-year, $75 million deal, averages $12.5 million a year; Greg
Maddux of Atlanta averages $11.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have exclusive negotiating rights with Johnson
through Thursday. After that time, he may field offers from other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim, Texas, Cleveland, Arizona, Colorado and the New York
Yankees have expressed interest in the 6-10 lefthander, who was
10-1 with a 1.28 ERA after the Astros acquired him in a July 31
trade with Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He was 9-10 with a 4.33 ERA in 23 starts with the Mariners and
led the major leagues with 329 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I stop short of saying we're the
front-runners,'' Hunsicker said. ``I don't feel like we're the
front-runners; we're one of a handful of teams that he is seriously
considering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't leave the meeting confident (the Astros could re-sign
Johnson), but I didn't leave there discouraged, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and his agent, Barry Meister, indicated they intend to
whittle their list of suitors to as few as three teams before the
pitcher and his family begin visiting prospective clubs. Although
Johnson has 10 years of service time, this is his first experience
with the free-agency process.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels obligated to go through the process, so nothing is
going to happen during our exclusive period,'' Hunsicker said.
``It's going to take some time to get through this. He does have a
genuine interest (in the Astros), but at this point it's hard to
tell if we have any advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he appreciates the support he received here, and that
doesn't hurt. But family is very important to Randy, and he wants
to get his family involved in the decision-making process, and we
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's meeting took place at Johnson's home in Glendale,
Ariz., which is near Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks managing partner Jerry Colangelo visited Johnson at
his home over the weekend, and the Big Unit no doubt will do more
entertaining before he decides on an offer.
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros were first to weigh in, and _ by all indications
_ they weighed in heavily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
