<SLUG> BC-CONN-SERIAL-KILLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERIAL KILLER IN CONNECTICUT MAY HAVE TRIED SUICIDE WITH DRUGS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ A convicted serial killer who had asked to be
executed apparently attempted to commit suicide early Monday
morning, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A guard making the twice-hourly patrol of the state's death row
at the Northern Correctional Institution in Somers found the
inmate, Michael Ross, lying on the floor of his cell, said Capt. S.
Scott Semple of the state Department of Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half hours later, Ross was taken to the University of
Connecticut Health Center in Farmington, Semple said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, Ross was removed from a respirator and his
condition was upgraded from serious to fair, according to a
hospital official and one of Ross' lawyers. Prison officials and
state police are investigating if Ross hoarded a prescription
medication he was taking and then ingested several doses at once,
said James Walter, a spokesman for the University of Connecticut
Health Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Corrections instructed the health center not
to release the name of the drug, Walter said.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Butler, one of Ross' lawyers and a public defender, said
his client suffered from mental illness and was on two medications,
only one of which he could have been hoarding. Butler refused to
say what medication Ross was taking or what specific ailments his
client was being treated for.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, a 1981 graduate of Cornell University who worked as a
door-to-door insurance salesman before his arrest, was charged with
killing six young women between 1981 and 1984. He confessed on the
day of his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   After a jury rejected Ross' claim that he was ``emotionally
disturbed,'' he was sentenced to death in 1987. In 1994, the state
Supreme Court upheld the guilty verdict in the case but ordered a
new sentencing hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But Ross entered an agreement with a special prosecutor, C.
Robert Satti, in March in which Ross said his crime had aggravating
factors that warranted the death penalty and no mitigating factors.
That pact would have allowed the state to skip the sentencing
hearing and hasten Ross' execution.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Thomas Miano of Superior Court in New London threw out
the agreement in July. A new trial on the penalty phase is
scheduled for Feb. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Ross had said he was pursuing the pact because he did not want
the families of his victims to have to endure another trial. His
lawyer, Karen Goodnow, acknowledged that Ross' wishes and
motivations were complex. ``He wants to live, and he wants to spare
the victims' families,'' Ms. Goodnow said.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's last execution was on May 17, 1960.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
