A0303 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BOWL-LADN     11-02 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLS ARE HARD TO BEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA learned its first Bowl Championship Series
lesson Monday afternoon: Style counts with the computers, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins fell from No. 1 to No. 3 in the latest BCS poll
because they did not defeat last-place Stanford convincingly
Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   At least that was the message sent by the New York Times and USA
Today/Sagarin computer ratings, each of which dropped the Bruins
four places after a 28-24 victory, their 17th in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Times computer poll, which does not include victory
margin, ranked the Bruins No. 1 for the second consecutive week.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in the Sagarin and New York Times ratings _ combined
with UCLA's expected plunge in the opinion-based top-25 polls _
raised the Bruins' BCS point total from 3.04 to 6.62, behind No. 1
Ohio State and No. 2 Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said. ``What it
tells us is, it doesn't matter if you win, you've got to do it
convincingly. Sometimes, that leads to running up the score. That
sends a bad message.''
</P>
<P>
   Two coaches apparently heard the message Saturday, and both have
scoffed at sportsmanship in the past: Florida's Steve Spurrier
ordered a reverse with 40 seconds left and a 31-7 lead over
Georgia; and Kansas State coach Bill Snyder left star quarterback
Michael Bishop in the game in the fourth quarter despite a 40-6
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it means you've got to run up the score to win the national
championship, we're doing the wrong thing,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins expected to fall in the BCS rankings after dropping
one spot in the Associated Press poll and two spots in the coaches'
poll Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not concerned with style,'' safety Tod McBride said.
``Yeah, it's disappointing to look in the papers and see we've
dropped. But we don't care if we win 2-0. As long as we keeping
winning, at the end of the year the rest will take care of
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   So they hope.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS formula combines a team's average in the top-25 polls,
its average in the computer polls and a strength-of-schedule
quotient, then adds one point for each loss. The teams with the
fewest points in the final poll (Dec. 6) will play for the national
title in the Fiesta Bowl on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   In dropping to third, the Bruins (7-0, 5-0) relinquished control
of their own destiny. There's no guarantee that four convincing
victories, beginning Saturday at Oregon State, will catapult them
past Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's alarming. We've got to get on it,'' Bruins fullback
Durell Price said. ``But we're not where we feel our Fiesta Bowl
shot is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't worry about the bowls. I look at it like if we finish
11-0, we'll be where we should be, and that's the Fiesta Bowl. We
can't worry about playing the computers. We've got to beat Oregon
State.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's greatest advantage is the strength of its schedule, which
will affect the BCS quotient and the three computer ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins finish with Washington, USC and Miami _ a seemingly
tougher path than either Ohio State (Michigan State, Iowa,
Michigan) or Tennessee (Alabama-Birmingham, Arkansas, Kentucky,
Vanderbilt and the SEC title game).
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't concerned when we were up on top and I'm not
concerned that we're a couple notches down,'' UCLA quarterback Cade
McNown said. ``We'll have a chance to prove what sort of team we
are in the next couple weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo believes the No. 1 ranking last week _ and resulting
attention _ was a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard not to (be distracted),'' he said. ``We're picked
No. 1 and everybody starts thinking they're better than they are.
But we've got to put that aside and seize the moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
