</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-NYMARATHON-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LOROUPE, NEW YORK IS 26 MILES OF TROUBLE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The trouble began on Saturday night for Tegla Loroupe
of Kenya, but she shrugged it off as tension. After consecutive
victories, she had finished seventh at the 1996 and 1997 New York
City Marathons. Now she was returning as the world record-holder
and a heavy favorite. Her stomach bothered her, but she was sure it
was just nerves.
</P>
<P>
   Early in Sunday's race, though, she suspected again that this
would not be her day. Suffering from diarrhea, she ran in the lead
at the start, but after only 3.2 miles the cramps began in her
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the midpoint of the 26.2-mile race, Loroupe thought
about dropping out. She hung on, caught back up to the leaders and
tried to slow the pace. But she faded again, dehydrated now, and
finished third in 2 hours 30 minutes 28 seconds, more than five
minutes behind the winner, Franca Fiacconi of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   From seventh a year ago, Loroupe had improved to third on
Sunday. But third is not first. She had set the world record of 2
hours 20 minutes 47 seconds last April in Rotterdam, the
Netherlands. Now she had run nearly 10 minutes slower in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I finished,'' Loroupe said. ``For that I'm happy. I
had my doubts at 20 kilometers, but I was thinking that if I drop
out, it can become a habit. And it is a bad image.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, she owned New York. Now, nothing seems to go right. Two
years ago, she started too fast. Last year she overcompensated and
started too slow. Then this, a stomach virus.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Steinfeld, the race director, said he believed that
Loroupe may be succumbing to internal pressure to do well in New
York, which launched her career. And because she is so popular in
New York, he said, ``I think she gets caught up in the crowd, and I
don't think she stays focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Loroupe disagreed. She limited her public appearances this year
and got plenty of rest, she said. ``This time, I didn't do
anything,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Roberts, the race coordinator, said that a stomach virus
was going around, and that two of the favorites, Madina Biktagirova
of Russia and Irina Kazakova-Gras of France, were so affected that
they dropped out during the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she didn't have bad luck,'' Roberts said of Loroupe,
``she'd have no luck at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Thugwane's Costly Misstep
</P>
<P>
   Josia Thugwane, the 1996 Olympic champion from South Africa,
told his agent, Luis Posso, before Sunday's race that he felt he
was in world-record shape. Thugwane pushed the pace but stepped
awkwardly as the race descended the Queensboro Bridge in the 16th
mile and strained a groin muscle. By Mile 20, he dropped out, while
John Kagwe of Kenya won in 2:08:45.
</P>
<P>
   Abel Anton, the 1997 world champion from Spain, dropped out at
18 miles without explanation and was so disgusted, he caught a
plane home on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   A Record 31,456 Finishers
</P>
<P>
   Some 32,398 runners started Sunday's marathon, and an unofficial
31,456 finished, which is a record, Allan Steinfeld, the race's
director, said. The oldest male finisher was 91-year-old Sam
Gadless of the United States, who clocked in at 8:26:00. The oldest
female finisher was 83-year-old Carolina Bottichio of Italy, who
ran 8:48:15.
</P>
<P>
   Among the finishers was 31-year-old Ketil Moe of Norway, who has
cystic fibrosis, and who ran with two transplanted lungs and a
transplanted liver. Escorted by Grete Waitz of Norway, the
nine-time winner in New York, Moe crossed the finish line in 7
hours 17 minutes 54 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Why the 97 percent finishing rate in New York, where a third of
the field is local, a third national and a third international?
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-thirds of our runners come from far away and spend
thousands of dollars to come here,'' Steinfeld said. ``They'll be
damned if they aren't going to finish the race. If they drop out at
13 miles, they have no clue where they are. They might as well go
to the finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Suspicions Groundless
</P>
<P>
   Suspicions arose Sunday about one runner, Roberto Barbi of
Italy, who did not show up among the leaders during the race, but
finished sixth in 2:10:55. The race's director, Allan Steinfeld,
said Monday that Barbi's time was legitimate, that he had been
trained by Orlando Pizzolato, the 1984 and 1985 winner, and that
Barbi had taken a bus to the start with other runners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
