<HEADER>
A0306 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      11-02 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING ROOM FOR MENSWEAR  
 RANDOLPH DUKE GOES IT ALONE  
 A NEW OUTPOST FOR J.P. TOD'S.
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Menswear designers, too, will now have a chance to
raise their flags above the Bryant Park tents. In February, when
American designers show en masse ahead of the Europeans (this
season the New York shows bracketed the European shows), menswear
will also be on the schedule. The announcement was made Monday by
Fern Mallis, executive director of Seventh on Sixth, organizer of
the Bryant Park shows. The men's shows will run from Feb. 11 to 13;
Feb. 14 is being suggested for designers who want to combine
menswear and women's wear on the same runway, and the women's
collections will be shown from Feb. 15 to 19.
</P>
<P>
   The combined shows answer designers' concerns about having to
present a women's-wear collection two weeks after showing menswear,
a problem that arose when Americans switched from their traditional
March or April presentations. Some retailers and foreign editors
had also complained about the inconvenience of traveling to New
York twice within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to designers of participating in Seventh on Sixth _ now
$7,500 to $32,500, depending on tent size _ is also expected to
fall, because the combined shows are expected to attract more
sponsors, Ms. Mallis said.
</P>
<P>
   Designers who abandoned the tents because of the cost, and those
who bid farewell for esthetic reasons, will be urged to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will bring back some of the bandits who left us,'' said
Stan Herman, the president of Seventh on Sixth. ``I think it will
be beneficial for the menswear industry, which has been so
fractured. We've never been able to offer them the park. The best
thing is, the park is allowing us to take the extra three or four
days. In February, no one is in the park, not even the pigeons.''
</P>
<P>
   Randolph Duke Solos
</P>
<P>
   Not everything intriguing in fashion this week is on the runway.
Randolph Duke, the designer who resuscitated the Halston brand
before departing abruptly last summer, is quietly showing a capsule
collection in his Chelsea loft.
</P>
<P>
   Duke seems to have landed on his feet after leaving his Halston
job, following the label's purchase by new investors. Although his
widest recognition has come from the work he did at Halston, before
that Duke had his own signature label. So far, he is underwriting
his new line himself, but he said Monday that he expects to sign a
deal with an investor shortly.
</P>
<P>
   His new collection for spring consists of about 25 evening-wear
pieces. ``It ranges from what I consider more separates, component
pieces, to gala gowns _ drop-dead entrance makers,'' Duke said.
There are T-shirts of viscose spandex and gowns of stretch silk
crepe or chiffon, in shades of sea foam, gray, white or black.
Retail prices are from $850 to $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Duke said he has learned from the experience of preparing a
collection directly for retailers, rather than for the runway.
``When you're not showing on runways, it's different,'' he said.
``Retailers don't buy groups, they buy singles, so it's almost
about each dress being in a different color.''
</P>
<P>
   Another J.P. Tod's
</P>
<P>
   Diego Della Valle, the Italian shoe designer, is reaping the
rewards of the current interest in shoes and handbags. For many of
fashion's top companies, like Gucci and Prada, accessories are
outselling clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Della Valle, who a few years ago shifted his focus from his
delicate signature footwear to the more functional J.P. Tod's line,
will open a new J.P. Tod's store at 650 Madison Ave. (61st Street)
in February, carrying shoes and a handbag line.
</P>
<P>
   The store is within four blocks of an existing J.P. Tod's
emporium at 41 East 57th St. (Madison Avenue), which will remain
open, selling footwear exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   The Hogan collection, a more youthful athletic-inspired line of
footwear, introduced in the United States last year, will not be
sold in the new store. Plans are to open the first Hogan store in
America in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have enough space to display the entire line, since
the bags have been so successful,'' said Claudio Castiglioni, chief
executive of Diva Inc., Della Valle's U.S. subsidiary. Worldwide
sales for the company reached $400 million this year, Castiglioni
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-02-98 2355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
