</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: PLAYERS HEAVE AIR BALL WITH BOYCOTT THREAT 
 
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
 BY RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC and Turner Sports are not quaking at the prospect of
National Basketball Association players boycotting interview
requests during the lockout and then during the season, whenever it
is to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a serious threat,'' said Craig Sager, a Turner
reporter. ``It came out of uneducated comments. I don't think
they'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as they plan no comment,'' Bob Costas, NBC's lead
play-by-play announcer, said with a barely contained chuckle, ``I
have no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, we see Michael Jordan barring NBC's Ahmad Rashad from a
pajama party where he would exclusively reveal his irksome hangnail
to his faithful Boswell, and Karl Malone shunning Sager after
scoring 45 points. Just envision Malone telling Sager, ``Forget it,
Craig, I don't like your network's contract.''
</P>
<P>
   How many future Bartlett's quotations will be lost to this venal
plot against public discourse? If Bill Wennington doesn't tell
NBC's Jim Gray his innermost thoughts as his perspiration drenches
the microphone, can we survive?
</P>
<P>
   Think of this: Charles Barkley turning down a chance to chat _
about anything. Even about deciding not to talk. As soon as he
heard the boycott threat, Doc Rivers, the TNT analyst, ascribed it
to a small group of agents. ``I just didn't think it would hold
water,'' said the former Knick, who has been working out in San
Antonio with the Spurs' David Robinson and Tim Duncan. ``Tensions
are high, but they won't be once things get settled.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Rivers added, ``As long as Barkley's around, we're
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of a possible boycott came out of a players' meeting in Las
Vegas last month. The players were incensed that NBC and Turner
were paying the NBA in full this season, which is required during a
lockout. If NBC and Turner did not agree to such a payment clause,
the NBA would have found willing customers elsewhere ``and the
players would be talking to CBS and ESPN,'' Rivers said.
</P>
<P>
   For the perfidy of making guaranteed payments _ bankrolling the
lockout and emboldening the league to be resolute, it is alleged _
players talked of denying NBC, TNT and TBS their oratory. In Las
Vegas, Patrick Ewing, the union president, said, ``When all is said
and done, this lockout will have cost the players a lot of money
and NBC's role will not be forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny how Ewing never made public his distaste for the same
lockout payment clause in past NBC and Turner contracts that helped
his salary soar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players who are informed know most of the money we pay
goes to them,'' said Sager, who was at the Las Vegas meeting.
``When I was there, they didn't shun me. Someone kiddingly said to
me, `There's the enemy.' I interviewed 300 players last year. They
know I'm there to publicize their achievements.''
</P>
<P>
   And to provide a forum for future work. On Turner's roster are
former players like Rivers and Reggie Theus. On NBC's roster are
Isiah Thomas, Bill Walton, Steve Jones and Matt Guokas. After last
season, NBC jettisoned John Salley, who had replaced Julius Erving,
as a studio show analyst.
</P>
<P>
   NBC and Turner have each made the first payments on their
contracts, which total $2.6 billion over four years. NBC will be
repaid for missed games (the network's season does not start until
Christmas Day) with rebates on their next three years' fees.
Turner, which started missing games Monday night, will get games
added to its TBS schedules.
</P>
<P>
   The damage of a boycott to NBC and Turner would be small. There
will be holes in the studio shows where relaxed player interviews,
some illuminating, some dull, will have to be filled. But as a
whole, being denied the cavalcade of pre-game and post-game player
talk is like being barred by your mother from playing your CD of
Sebastian Cabot singing ``Blowin' in the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Players not playing during the lockout harms NBC and Turner by
forcing them to insert replacement programs that generate reduced
advertising revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But players not talking? Can you say ``empty, misguided
threat''?
</P>
<P>
   `Monday Night' Strike
</P>
<P>
   If ``Monday Night Football'' looked less technically
sophisticated last night, it was because of the 24-hour strike
called against ABC by the National Association of Broadcast
Employees and Technicians. Since last season, ABC has sent a
backup, nonunion production crew to all ``Monday Night'' sites in
case of a strike. But ``Monday Night Blast,'' the pre-game show
that emanates from Baltimore, was not to be seen because that crew
does not have a backup. Instead the pre-game show was scheduled to
come from Veterans Stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
